<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARBURY AND THE NETS FALL SHORT AT THE BUZZER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIOB _ The defending National Basketball Association
champions got a taste of what the New Jersey Nets look like when
Stephon Marbury and Keith Van Horn are at the height of their games
offensively, and the experience was nearly too much for the San
Antonio Spurs to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, continuing his assault on the league's point guards,
scored a game-high 34 points on 9-of-14 shooting, and Van Horn
scored 23 points in just 24 minutes of play. But the Spurs, behind
David Robinson's 25 points and Tim Duncan's 17, were able to escape
the Alamodome with a thrilling 106-104 victory on Monday night when
a 30-foot 3-point attempt by Marbury fell short at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn and Marbury put the Nets in position to win with
outstanding fourth-quarter play. Van Horn, whose minutes were
limited by foul trouble, scored 9 points and made a steal in a 15-9
run that pulled the Nets within 2, at 102-100, with three minutes
to play. A free throw by Robinson and a 3-pointer by Jaren Jackson
made the score 106-100 and seemed to close the door on the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   But Marbury, who scored more than 30 points for the fifth time
in his last nine games, hit a driving layup, and then Van Horn
followed with a steal and basket with 37 seconds remaining. Twenty
seconds later, Jamie Feick, who led the Nets in rebounding with 11,
made a steal and set up Marbury's final attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The game was reminiscent of the Nets' 96-94 loss to San Antonio
at the Meadowlands in November, when Duncan blocked a last-second
layup attempt by Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Nets to 2-3 on this road trip and to 24-36
heading into Wednesday's home game against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets trailed by just 3 points at the start of the final
period. But a little-known second-year guard out of Eastern
Michigan, Derrick Dial, put them in a hole that was hard to climb
out of. In his first NBA game _ he was on the injured list all of
last season and most of this season with a lower back strain _ Dial
scored 7 straight points early in the fourth period to increase the
Spurs' advantage to 93-85 with eight minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets caught the Spurs at the right time. San Antonio (38-22)
had lost three of its last four home games, including the last two.
And Duncan, who missed four games with a lower abdominal strain,
was a bit rusty in his second game back.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Robinson finished with 13 rebounds each as the Spurs
outrebounded the Nets, 52-31.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio took a 28-27 lead after one quarter behind the
surprising scoring of Avery Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who entered the game with an 11.4-point average, scored
10 and gave out 3 assists in the first 12 minutes. Marbury answered
with 9 points and 3 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury went to the bench with the Nets ahead, 30-29, early in
the second period. His backup, Elliot Perry, scored 6 points, made
3 steals and dished out 2 assists as the Nets increased their lead
to 7 points twice.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, an eighth-year veteran, was so hot that with 4 minutes 31
seconds left, Marbury began heading for the scorer's table only to
reverse his direction when Perry buried a 21-foot shot in front of
the Nets' bench. As the shot fell through, Marbury smiled and told
Coach Don Casey to leave Perry in the game. Perry's jumper put the
Nets up by 47-42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
