<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MITCHELL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS MAKE OFFER TO QB MITCHELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys made a contract offer yesterday to
quarterback Scott Mitchell, and owner Jerry Jones said he expects a
decision today on whether Mitchell would rather play behind Troy
Aikman or Akili Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Jones would not divulge the Cowboys' offer, but said Mitchell's
decision will not be based solely on money because ``the
circumstances are different in Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell reportedly has an $800,000 offer from the Bengals to
back up Smith, a second-year player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is reviewing everything,'' Jones said. ``He wants to know
how playing in Dallas behind Aikman or playing in Cincinnati would
impact his career. Obviously, he wouldn't get as much chance to
play here. He also has to decide where he thinks he has the best
chance to win. He's looking at it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor for Mitchell is the chance to work again with
Cowboys offensive coordinator Jack Reilly, who coached Mitchell in
college at Utah. Their relationship is the reason Mitchell worked
out for the Cowboys after he was reportedly close to an agreement
with the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good workout and good meetings with everybody,''
Reilly said. ``He's going to go back home, think about it and see
where he is with everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, 32, spent the first nine seasons of his career with
the Miami Dolphins and Detroit Lions before joining the Baltimore
Ravens last year, when he came in as the starter before being
benched after two games.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell has 66 starts and 14,688 passing yards, 92 touchdowns
and 70 interceptions over the past decade. However, he has been
plagued by inconsistency and weight problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys believe the 6-foot-6, 245-pound Mitchell has the
size and strength to be a capable replacement for the departed
Jason Garrett (New York Giants) as Aikman's backup. They are also
encouraged by Mitchell's commitment to a conditioning program.
Cowboys head coach Dave Campo said Mitchell has lost a lot of
weight and looked sharp yesterday.
Wilson hired as QB coach
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones has said all along that he wanted a former Troy
Aikman backup to join the team as quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Garrett spurned Jones' offer to join the coaching staff
and signed with the Giants because he wanted to continue playing.
So the Cowboys hired Wade Wilson, the guy Garrett replaced as
Aikman's backup in 1998. Wilson, 41, recently retired as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``His lengthy career will serve him well,'' Jones said. ``He is
an outstanding people person, has great respect from his teammates
and a great relationship with Troy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson played for five teams in 19 seasons, including the past
two with the Oakland Raiders. He was with the Cowboys from 1995-97.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys signed fourth-year tight end Brian Roche to a
contract yesterday. Roche did not play last season after playing
with the Chiefs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys plan to work out four quarterbacks and two receivers
today. Three of the quarterbacks _ Charles Puleri, Todd Hammel and
Arron Garcia _ are Arena League veterans hoping to become the next
Kurt Warner. The other is CFL veteran Cody Ledbetter. The two
receivers scheduled to work out are Anthony Rodgers and Connie
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese, who spent
the past three years running the New England Patriots' offense,
said he expects to join the Cowboys soon as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' off-season program officially began yesterday. A
number of players, including Troy Aikman, guard Larry Allen, safety
Darren Woodson and defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman, dropped by the
team's headquarters to meet with strength and conditioning coach
Joe Juraszek.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
