<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WELLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERNON WELL'S ADVANCEMENT HAS BEEN ANYTHING BUT SLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ A simple bit of subtraction is all it takes to
know how far Vernon Wells has come in such a short time.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in spring training he wore an football offensive
lineman's number, No. 62. This year, he's reduced it by 52, wearing
No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   A little knowledge of baseball etiquette is helpful to
understand the significance.
</P>
<P>
   In spring training, only longshots and no-hopers ticketed for
the minors or the waiver wire get the lineman and receiver numbers.
The players on the team, or the ones with a chance to make the
team, get the baseball-player numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 62 meant that Wells, although he was a top prospect, was
just biding his time before a minor-league assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 10 means that Wells, who was patrolling the outfield for
Arlington Bowie High School only three years ago, has a chance to
break camp as the Toronto Blue Jays' starting center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the job's wide open, and I haven't heard anything
to discourage me from that,'' Wells said. ``That's all you can hope
for, is to get a chance to break with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a theory that because of his youth and inexperience,
the 21-year-old Wells might be better off beginning the year in the
minors. Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi doesn't necessarily subscribe
to that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was working on my fourth year in the big leagues at 21,''
Fregosi said. ``Good athletes have a way of adjusting to things.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that Wells is a good athlete. He was an
All-America baseball player at Bowie and an all-state football
player as a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic ability and skill prompted the Blue Jays to take
him with the fifth overall pick in the 1997 amateur draft. He
quickly signed and reported to St. Catherines, a rookie-league
team, where he hit .307 with 10 homers and 31 runs batted in in 66
games.
</P>
<P>
   Wells spent all of the 1998 season at Class-A Hagerstown, where
he hit .285 with 11 homers and 65 RBI in 134 games.
</P>
<P>
   The high draft position and the skills established Wells as the
Blue Jays' top prospect, and they invited him to spring training as
a nonroster player last year to give him a taste of life at the
top. Wells got to hang around with big-leaguers, but he wasn't yet
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got two at-bats, or something like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the season at Dunedin of the Class-A Florida State
League, as the Blue Jays were prepared to have him climb the ladder
to the majors one step at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Wells did it according to plan. He just drastically accelerated
the process.
</P>
<P>
   He tore up the FSL, batting .343 with 11 homers and 43 RBI in 70
games, and was promoted to Double-A Knoxville He had an even
shorter stint there, earning a promotion to Triple-A Syracuse after
hitting .340 in 26 games. Wells again excelled, batting .310 with
four homers and 21 RBI, stealing five bases in six attempts and
scoring 20 runs in 33 games.
</P>
<P>
   Wells completed his unlikely journey in late August, when he was
promoted to the majors three months before his 21st birthday. It
wasn't a matter of getting the kid a taste of the big leagues. The
Blue Jays were in the wild-card race, but the club thought his bat,
defense, speed and poise could help.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an organizational decision,'' Fregosi said.
``Everybody was involved, all the scouts, and the field
personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells became the starting center fielder, and held his own with
a .261 average in 88 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He struggled a little bit at the beginning, but he adjusted,''
Fregosi said.
</P>
<P>
   The long trip from Class A to the majors in such a short time
was one Wells didn't even dare dream about when the season started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' he said. ``I just hoped I'd end up in Double A. Then
I got to Double A, and I figured I'd be there for the whole year.
Then I got called up to Triple A. And so on and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   The meteoric rise to the majors makes this year's spring
training a lot different than last year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to this one,'' Wells said. ``I had fun
last year and had a chance to see big-league games and see what
it's all about. Now it's an opportunity to hopefully be on a
contending team and have some fun at the big-league level.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells is competing with Jose Cruz Jr. To break camp with the
big-league team, he'll have to clearly win the job. The
organization would rather see him develop by playing full time in
the minors than playing sporadically in the majors as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in here competing for a job,'' Fregosi said. ``The only
difference is, if he makes the major-league club, he'll be the
everyday center fielder. Otherwise, he will play every day in
Syracuse. He's got a wealth of talent, he's got a lot of ability,
he's a great kid, he's got a lot of things going for him. But we
would never do anything to deter his career. We'll try to do what's
best for the young man.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting a taste of the majors, Wells doesn't want to
return to the minors. But he sees the benefit of playing all the
time at Triple-A rather than sitting the bench in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather it not happen, but if it does I'm not going to get
discouraged about it,'' Wells said. ``I'd still be a lot further
ahead than where I thought I'd be at this time last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 10 on his back tells just how far he's come.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
