r s BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     03-07 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAVEY KEEPS BRIGHT OUTLOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A scar snakes down Stars center Aaron Gavey's
face, starting under his right eye and trickling all the way down
to his lip.
</P>
<P>
   He's lucky it isn't worse. The hockey skate opened up a gash
that required 130-plus stitches to close.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, you honestly wouldn't notice it if not for the fact his
Mary Lou Retton-sized smile draws attention there every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an optimist,'' Gavey said, explaining the smile and
reciting his motto in one, short declarative sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He remained optimistic after being sent down to Kalamazoo
despite a strong training camp.
</P>
<P>
   He remained optimistic when sent back to Kalamazoo not once but
twice more during the regular season. Not that he made a bad
impression when the Stars called him up. He didn't make any
impression at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have moments where you wonder,'' Gavey admitted before
quickly adding, ``but things are all done for a reason. I can't
worry about things I can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   What he finally figured out is he can control some of those
things by the way he plays.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey said he didn't consider it his last chance when he was
called up for the third time on Jan. 10, but if his chances were a
marathon he had to be around the 25th mile. He has six goals since,
including three in the Stars last three games against Philadelphia,
Phoenix and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk about the pluses of the week against these intense
competition, he has to be right up there with one of the top
pluses. He and Brenden Morrow,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``I think Aaron is able to carry his own weight right now. I think
Aaron can go and play with anybody and he's got an impact in the
game right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With a week to go before the March 14 trade deadline, Gavey has
put himself and the Stars in the enviable position of having a
really hot commodity.
</P>
<P>
   If they want to make a trade for Carolina's Gary Roberts,
Montreal's Shayne Corson or one of the many other names rumored to
be going just about everywhere before the deadline, they have a
young talent to deal. If they aren't able to get a deal done, they
still have their young talent who could quickly become their
versatile scoring forward they so desire for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Gavey and his wife, Jennifer, are ready for either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on what happens on the 14th, she's going to either
drive our truck back here or follow me wherever I go,'' Gavey said.
``I know I can play at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are the only team in his five-year career where he's
bounced from the minors to the pros.
</P>
<P>
   They drafted what they thought was one player. They got quite
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when you are 24 and you have a 21-year-old that you
want to bring up here you think, `Maybe, this guy may be past
it,''' Hitchcock said. ``He's in the middle of proving he's capable
of playing in this league right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He did in Tampa Bay, playing in 73 games his first year for the
Lightning. The only games he missed were because of the cut to his
face. He jokes that he made his own red line of blood as he skated
from Tampa Bay's bench to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, the stitches were removed and he returned.
</P>
<P>
   The scar remained, and likely always will even if he has
surgery, because the cut went against the grain. The scar used to
bother him. He hated looking at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really talk about it for a while,'' Gavey said.
</P>
<P>
   The morose moment went as quickly as it had come, replaced by
the smile. For it is this you notice not the scar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be that ugly,'' Gavey said with a laugh. ``My wife
married me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
