<SLUG> BC-PROPOSITION-SONG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS JINGLE IS FOR VOTERS, NOT SHOPPERS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN JONES 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   State propositions have inspired many things in the past _
name- &LR;  calling, yawns, endless junk mail. But this election,
they've inspired a catchy, toe-tapping hit single.
</P>
<P>
   A Sacramento-based voter education organization released a
31/2-minute jingle to help voters remember the 20 propositions on
Tuesday's ballot. ``The Proposition Song,'' written and performed
by California Voter Foundation president and founder Kim Alexander,
has gotten air time on dozens of talk and news radio shows around
the state, including KQED-FM in the Bay Area. It has been featured
on CNN and National Public Radio and in the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The song also received 63,000 hits on the group's Web site in
February. It hasn't made the Billboard charts yet, but it might
before the election results are tallied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a fun public service. Anything that gets people
thinking about the election is a good thing,'' said Scott Shafer of
KQED, who featured the song during a one-hour special on the
election, which was sent to the station's affiliates around the
state. ``People seemed to like it. Now, whether they're whistling
it in the voter booth is another thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The melody is sort of a folksy rendition of ``My Baloney Has a
First Name.'' Alexander, a former camp song leader, said she
intended it to sound like a TV commercial jingle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it all started. We all get TV jingles caught in our
head. I thought, `What if we can get the state propositions stuck
in voters' heads?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander and her friends started working on the lyrics in
December, when the ballot was finalized. It was a tremendous
challenge, she said, to cover the complexities of 20 bonds and
initiatives in a cute and nonpartisan way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to think of it as `Schoolhouse Rock,' '' she said.
``Our whole generation learned the Constitution through that
song.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander and a friend, along with a guitar accompanist,
recorded the song in two takes at Capitol Public Radio in
Sacramento. They made 30 compact disc recordings at her husband's
office and mailed them to radio stations around the state. A
Massachusetts company created a Web video for the song almost pro
bono. The video features the lyrics with a bouncing ball for
viewers to sing along.
</P>
<P>
   The whole project cost less than $2,500, Alexander said. ``It's
not perfect, but it's not unbearable to listen to. That was my main
concern,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Proposition Song'' has been such a success, Alexander
would like to record another song for the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to get a band in there,'' she said. ``But I have to
convince my friends to help out first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
