A9015 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-PEDIATRICIAN-A1 &LR;      03-07 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEDIATRICIAN-A1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDIATRICIANS URGE COUNSELING IN VIOLENCE PREVENTION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Confronting an epidemic of youth violence, the nation's leading
pediatricians group said Monday that a child's visit to the doctor
should include screening and counseling for violence prevention.
<P>
   The influential American Academy of Pediatrics said preventing
violence should take a place alongside whooping-cough vaccines and
nutrition counselingin everyday clinical practice _ starting with
counseling parents even before the child is born.
</P>
<P>
   The group outlined a series of subjects for doctors to raise
with parents and youngsters, including exposure to violence in the
home and school, attitudes toward discipline and corporal
punishment and access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations also offer guidance for doctors on how to
deal with problems as they arise. In many cases, the pediatricians
are expected to serve as an early-warning system, referring the
most difficult cases to counselors and other specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence prevention is a major problem affecting the health of
children of all ages, and we feel it should be part of
pediatricians' responsibility to try to prevent it,'' said Dr. Jack
Swanson, a pediatrician in Ames, Iowa, speaking for the
55,000-member national organization.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy follows an academy-sponsored task force study
that began in 1997, even before the Columbine High School shootings
dramatically heightened public concern about youth violence. But
doctors said the latest spate of tragedies _ most recently the
shooting death of a classmate by a Michigan 6-year-old _ added much
more urgency to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The pediatricians group cited a grim array of statistics showing
the United States has some of the highest youth homicide and
suicide rates in the world. American teenagers, experts noted, are
more likely to die of gunshot wounds than of all natural causes
combined.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in popular culture, child abuse at home and easy access
to guns are among the ``many issues relevant to pediatric
practice,'' the doctors group said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many issues are affecting kids now, it often seems that
viruses and bacteria are the least of our concerns these days,''
said Dr. Edward Cox, a Grand Rapids, Mich., pediatrician helping to
implement the new clinical guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The group acknowledged that screening for the warning signs of
violence is a sensitive topic fraught with possibilities for
misunderstanding and invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   But if a family's pediatrician raises the subject in the right
way, the group believes that parents or children will talk about
these sensitive issues for the good of the child. The idea is to
raise the subjects in a nonconfrontational way.
</P>
<P>
   The change announced Monday is part of a periodic update of a
schedule of preventive services and screening practices doctors are
supposed to offer their patients, starting with prenatal screening
and continuing through late adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Besides adding violence prevention to the list of health issues,
the latest revision included for the first time a recommendation
that newborns be screened for hearing difficulties. Recent studies
have found early detection of hearing problems can make a
significant difference in child development and language skills
throughout life.
</P>
<P>
   The violence-prevention guidelines are designed to tackle a much
broader concern. The upshot would be a new role for pediatricians
that would include not only clinical services _ at virtually every
stage of a child's development _ but community advocacy, research
and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a role,'' said Dr. Ann Tipton, a pediatrician and
adolescent health specialist at Kaiser Permanente's Oakland medical
center. She called violence prevention ``a multifaceted problem
that needs many approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it isn't part of the classical medical model,'' she
said, ``we all need to be working together in the home setting, the
school setting and now also in the medical setting.''
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines are being published on the pediatric group's
Web site Tuesday  &UR; (www.aap.org),  &LR; along with the 1999 policy
statement that gave rise to the change. They also appear in this
month's issue of Pediatrics, the organization's journal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hans Steiner, a youth-violence expert at Stanford Medical
Center, said it's clear that a new awareness of violence is needed
in doctor's offices if the epidemic is ever to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems often start very early in life, and so they need to
be identified early in life,'' he said, adding that pediatricians
can be among the first to pick up risk factors such as an
aggressive temperament and exposure to violence in the home.
</P>
</TEXT>
