<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9016 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-DIAMONDS- &LR;      03-07 1503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAMONDS- </SLUG>
  
 DIAMONDS FINANCE AFRICA'S REBEL ARMIES  &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The traditional spring wedding season is approaching, and
diamond engagement rings are sparkling on the hands of brides-to-be
throughout America.
</P>
<P>
   But some of those diamonds have a sordid history. In many parts
of Africa, diamonds don't mean glamour, purity or eternal love.
Instead, they mean slaughter and sadistic brutality.
</P>
<P>
   In civil wars in Angola, Congo and Sierra Leone _ among the
world's bloodiest yet most ignored conflicts _ guerrilla groups
earn hundreds of millions of dollars annually from mining and
exporting diamonds. They use the money to buy huge arsenals and
terrorize enormous expanses of countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, a backlash has begun.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, in Washington and elsewhere, diplomats
and politicians are belatedly admitting that Western businesses and
consumers contribute to the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign is beginning to cut off diamond trading with the
rebel armies. At stake, its backers say, is the fate of a huge
swath of Africa _ and perhaps of the global diamond industry
itself.
</P>
<P>
   `'Diamonds are leaving a trail of misery through a lot of
African countries, and we as Americans have a lot of
responsibility,'' said Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, who notes that an
estimated 5 percent to 15 percent of gem diamonds sold in the
United States come from rebels in Angola, Congo and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   ``At minimum we need to let consumers know that these symbols of
love are causing great hardship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., are sponsoring legislation to
require that all diamonds sold in the United States be labeled
according to country of origin _ the first step, they say, to
forcing the guerrillas' diamonds off the American marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is rising for a crackdown on ``conflict diamonds'' in
the following ways:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Angola. &LR;  Diplomats led by Canada's ambassador to the United
Nations, Robert Fowler, are trying to stop diamond exporting by
Angola's powerful UNITA rebels. Fowler complains that U.N. members
have ignored a 2-year-old U.N. embargo on UNITA's diamonds, which
are believed to earn the rebels nearly $150 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, fighting between the government and the rebels
has killed 10,000 people, caused 75,000 to die of starvation and
has displaced more than 1 million people from their homes. In 25
years of civil war, more than 500,000 Angolans have died, most of
them civilians.
</P>
<P>
   A Security Council panel on Angola, headed by Fowler, is
expected to issue a report March 15 revealing that businesses in
countries such as Ukraine, Belgium and South Africa, as well as
several African governments, are colluding with UNITA to break the
embargo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Sierra Leone.  &LR; A shaky peace is barely holding in this tiny
West African nation's civil war. The Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) guerrillas have harassed and seized weapons from the 6,000
U.N. peacekeepers, and they have refused to disarm or give up their
control of the nation's diamond mines, as they agreed to do in a
peace pact last year.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels spread mayhem throughout the nation and horrified the
world during the eight-year war by hacking off the arms, legs, ears
and lips of thousands of civilians. About 75,000 people died in the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the RUF is using the tens of millions of dollars it earns
annually from diamonds to strengthen its forces. CIA Director
George Tenet told Congress last month that the RUF is ``poised to
break a tenuous cease-fire and resume a campaign of terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Many diplomats and activists say the United Nations must place
an embargo on diamonds from Sierra Leone and neighboring Liberia _
whose ruler, Charles Taylor, acts as the RUF's diamond exporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sierra Leone's diamonds are top quality, and the RUF is
getting them to market one way or another, and it must be stopped
or else the U.N. mission will be a total failure,'' said Ian
Smillie, a researcher for Partnership Africa Canada, a coalition of
development organizations that in January released an influential
expose on the RUF's role in the diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Congo.  &LR; More than 5,000 U.N. peacekeepers are scheduled to
move into this sprawling nation in the coming months to try to stop
what has been called ``Africa's world war'' _ a conflict that has
drawn in tens of thousands of soldiers from neighboring Rwanda,
Uganda, Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola and Chad. But many experts say
the war will continue until the foreign armies are forced out of
the nation's $600-million-per-year diamond trade.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda, whose troops form the backbone of the rebel
forces, pay their way by diamond and gold mining in rebel-held
areas of eastern Congo, and act as conduits for UNITA's diamond and
weapons smuggling. Zimbabwe, which backs the Congolese government,
enjoys a lucrative diamond concession granted by President Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is building on the Security Council to put  &LR; impose a
ban on all Congolese diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- Consumer information.  &LR; In Congress, Hall and Wolf say their
legislation is needed to help build pressure on the diamond
industry to stop dealing with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world looked the other way once, while revenues from
diamond sales were used to butcher innocent civilians,'' Wolf said.
``This time, we should not stand idly by. We should do whatever it
takes to cut off these revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, Hall and other reformers insist that they do not want a
general boycott of the diamond industry, which they say would
damage nations like Botswana, South Africa and Namibia, where it
provides much-needed jobs and generally operates in an ethical
manner.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is running scared, fearing that any bad publicity
could hurt sales. Gem diamonds have no intrinsic value, and their
value depends totally on the upscale image the industry has created
over the years through slick advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., the South African conglomerate
that controls about two-thirds of the wholesale diamond trade
worldwide, announced last Tuesday that starting later this month,
diamonds sold by the company will be accompanied by a certificate
stating that they do ``not include any diamonds which come from any
area in Africa controlled by forces rebelling against the
legitimate and internationally recognized government of the
relevant country.''
</P>
<P>
   That will mean that De Beers will sell only gems from its mines
in Botswana, South Africa, Namibia and other nations, or ones
bought on the open market from places like Russia and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``As industry leader we feel an obligation to take these steps,
not only from a moral standpoint,'' said Andrew Lamont, a spokesman
in London for De Beers. ``We hope this will ensure that the
legitimate diamond trade is not adversely affected by the small
number of diamonds that benefit the rebels.''
</P>
<P>
   Reform advocates hailed the decision. ``De Beers has taken a
lead that the rest of the diamond industry must now follow,'' said
Charmian Gooch, director of Global Witness, a group based in London
that has led the international campaign against African conflict
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   But the diamond trade's secretive nature makes it difficult for
De Beers to fully comply. Experts say diamonds cannot be
distinguished visually by place of origin, and as a result a
suitcase of gems worth tens of millions of dollars can easily be
``laundered'' through several countries to falsify their place of
origin.
</P>
<P>
   In January, U.S. diamond importers and retailers signed a
statement pledging to obey the embargo on UNITA diamonds, and
promising to cooperate with U.N. attempts to strengthen the ban.
</P>
<P>
   But Gooch and other reformers say that U.S. importers buy as
much as one-third of their diamonds from wholesalers in Antwerp,
Tel Aviv and elsewhere that, unlike De Beers, refuse to crack down
on rebel-mined gems or give verifiable information on their origin.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, they say, is a mandatory global diamond labeling
system in which all sales must be accompanied by verifiable
documents declaring the origin of the diamonds and their
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Such systems _ and the proposed Hall-Wolf legislation _ are
opposed by the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible to find a practical or feasible way to
label diamonds,'' said Jeffrey Fischer, vice president of the
Diamond Manufacturers and Importers of America, who was one of the
signers of the January statement. ``The diamond industry is a very
fluid, fast-moving business. (Mandatory controls) would only burden
the industry, and ultimately the consumer, with much higher
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has not yet decided whether to
support a mandatory labeling system. Action has been advocated by
mid-level officials for several years, but was ignored at more
senior levels until very recently because wars in Africa are not
generally seen as affecting America's strategic interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
