A9017 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-GAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-07 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH CAMPAIGN DENIES SHIFT ON GAYS  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK _ A spokeswoman for Texas Gov. George W. Bush insisted
Monday that the candidate's pronouncement that he would meet with
gay Republicans is not a reversal, but a clarification of comments
widely ``misinterpreted'' by the national media.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told NBC's Tim Russert on ``Meet the Press'' last fall that
he would ``probably not'' meet with Log Cabin Republicans, a gay
organization, because it would create a ``huge political ...
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, he defended his comments, saying he did not wish
to ``politicize'' a matter as ``personal and private'' as someone's
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Bush told The Chronicle that he welcomes support from
gays and is willing to meet with the group. Explaining his comments
to reporters on the campaign trail in Southern California
yesterday, Karen Hughes, Bush's communications director, insisted
his initial reluctance had been directed only at two specific
leaders of the gay group, whom he believed had already decided to
support to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor does have many supporters who are members of
local chapters of different Log Cabin organizations,'' she said.
``He welcomes their support and will certainly consider meeting
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The words drew an incredulous response from officials of the Log
Cabin group, which is based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the more she talks, the more bizarre this gets,''
said spokesman Kevin Ivers. ``If you look at the video, it is
pretty clear. Still, we stand by our statement that what the
governor said (Sunday) is a positive development.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Sunday morning show last fall, Russert said to Bush:
``John McCain, your opponent, met with Log Cabin Republicans, gay
Republicans. Would you meet with them?''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BUSH07 (14007 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Bush responded: ``Oh, probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, Bush said, ``I don't believe in group thought,
pitting one group of people against another. And all that does is
create kind of a huge political, you know, nightmare for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's refusal to meet with the gay group was the subject of a
pro-Bush radio ad produced by the Christian Coalition and aired in
South Carolina. The ad questioned McCain's conservative credentials
by noting that he had met with the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, as Bush delivered a speech on tolerance at the Simon
Weisenthal Center in Los Angeles, he was repeatedly interrupted by
a heckler who demanded: ``What about gay people?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about tolerance and inclusion _ but he just can't
open his heart to include gay Americans,'' said the heckler,
Richard Noble, 31, an artist from West Hollywood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 0121EST &QL; 
