<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9019 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     03-07 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A GOOD LOOK AT A BAD BUNCH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's Super Tuesday, when at long last California
and New York rise up and exercise almost as much political clout as
New Hampshire and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know anything about the candidates or the issues, so I
called on my chief political adviser, Dr. Paula Ticks.
</P>
<P>
   She says that when considering the four main presidential
candidates, you should look at the negatives, rather than only at
the so-called upsides.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people, says Dr. Ticks, make important, life-altering
decisions based on a few glittery, superficial qualities. This is
what psychologists refer to as Darva Conger Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the good doctor's notes on candidate negs:
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush. He speaks at Bob Jones University, then weeks
later apologizes lukewarmly for not taking the school to task for
its strident anti-Catholicism and ban on interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   That's one slow thinker, folks, even for a Texan. (Just kidding,
padnuhs!) John McCain. The G word. Suppose things get dicey between
China and Taiwan, the U.S. gets involved in negotiations, world
peace hangs in the balance, and President McCain slips and uses the
G word. Oops!
</P>
<P>
   Besides, McCain is just a garden-variety Republican, except on
campaign finance reform, and that's a bogus issue since people who
champion that cause drop it like a hot cow pie once they get into
office (see: Bill Clinton).
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore. He's being swept into the Democratic nomination on the
strength of his association with Clinton. Either this logic is
flawed, or Gabby Hayes should have won several Academy Awards for
best actor.
</P>
<P>
   And the deal with Gore inventing the Internet and being the
inspiration for ``Love Story''? Just a little bit creepy. Al's
reality/fantasy boundary is wobbly. Actually, Gore  &UR; was  &LR; the
inspiration for ``Robo Cop.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley. Clinically unable to throw tantrums. McCain, Bush,
Gore _ all noted blow-tops, in public and behind the scenes. But
Bradley takes a situation that calls for petulant lash-out and
tries to handle it with calm, boring reason and analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the blustery, cartoonish personality we demand in our
presidents?
</P>
<P>
   Bradley would be OK in summit talks with belligerent world
leaders, sure, but he would be lost if ever called upon to appear
in an infomercial giving an enthusiastic endorsement to the Buns of
Steel video.
</P>
<P>
   SHOCK AND OUTRAGE were the most common reactions to photos of
Sunday's airliner crash in Burbank, where the plane came to rest
under a Chevron gas station sign.
</P>
<P>
   The horror! A buck seventy-nine for super premium! Twenty cents
cheaper than Bay Area gas.
</P>
<P>
   It's not true that the pilot leaned out the cockpit window and
said, ``Fill 'er up!'' But George Hampton points out that since a
jet has a 6,000-gallon fuel tank, a fill-up at the Burbank Chevron
is $1,200 cheaper than a tankful at a service station near SFO.
Plus down there, or so it appears in the photos, firefighters clean
your jet's windshield.
</P>
<P>
   MY FINANCIAL analyst, Suds Shanahan, looked up the portfolios of
the candidates on AOL Personal Finance and unearthed the largest
single stock investment held by each man, to wit:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, Bank of America, $100,000. So would Bradley be OK
with moving the White House to North Carolina and letting Hugh
McColl call the shots?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, Microsoft, $180,000. Amazingly enough, Bush
supports tax breaks for the computer industry, has even floated a
proposal to make Canada a subsidiary of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, lease of a zinc mine, between $100,000 and $250,000.
With ready access to zinc tablets, Al can easily ward off colds and
flu.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, Anheuser Busch, $300,000. Hey, John Sixpack! Here
comes the Slurred Speech Express, and key endorsements from two of
the three Budweiser frogs (one has withheld endorsement due to
McCain's proposal to use all rivers and swamps for storage of
radioactive waste).
</P>
<P>
   FINALLY, Dr. Ticks says she wants to congratulate all the
Democrats who reregistered Republican in order to vote for McCain
and stamp out Bush.
</P>
<P>
   You've not only enlisted in a lost cause, but you've also
energized the once-complacent W.
</P>
<P>
   And as a bonus, you've taken away votes from Bradley that might
have made him a contender. So many Demos shooting themselves in
feet, it's no wonder their party supports gun control.
</P>
<P>
   My own pick on Super Tuesday: The Rams by a touchdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
