<HEADER>
A9028 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-AIRCRASH-HERO-LADN     03-07 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-HERO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESSES TO PLANE CRASH QUICKLY BECOME HEROES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  BURBANK, CALIF. _ In the last harrowing moments before
Southwest Airlines Flight 1455 crashed, passenger Garrett Hamil
said he knew something was very wrong as the jetliner swayed
violently down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to crash at that time,'' Hamil recalled
Monday, a day after the jet slammed through a metal fence, careened
onto Hollywood Way and stopped short of a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you look at death in people's eyes, and you
think these are the last eyes you're going to look into? That's
what happened. Everybody was looking for comfort in each other,''
the 27-year-old Hollywood man said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the plane made a quick right turn and burst through
the fence that divides the airport from Hollywood Way. The
passengers and crew members were jolted upon impact and then again
when the plane hit a car before coming to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Panels from the plane's ceiling tumbled onto passengers,
trapping Hamil and others, as the plane finally stopped about 30
feet away from gas pumps at a Chevron station.
</P>
<P>
   The nose of the plane had dropped down. The cabin lights went
off and smoke filled the plane as passengers exited on inflatable
ramps. Miraculously, no one was seriously hurt in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fortuitous ending to what began as a rough landing. Ten
minutes before landing, the pilot warned of turbulence ahead, Hamil
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said we may have some rough turbulence because of 27 mph
winds. But he said it should be no problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, passengers were jerked to the right and then to
the left as the plane swayed in the wind. ``I knew we were going
too fast,'' Hamil said. ``People are screaming and hysterical.''
</P>
<P>
   When the plane touched down, almost everyone applauded. ``A
couple people yelled out, `Right on!' '' Hamil said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too soon: Hamil and others looked out the window and
saw that the plane had landed too far down the runway. The jet then
crashed through the fence.
</P>
<P>
   The next communication with the passengers came after the plane
stopped and a flight attendant told them to head to the nearest
exit. ``You could totally tell her panic. Her voice was shaking,''
Hamil said.
</P>
<P>
   Some passengers tried to grab their luggage but were ordered to
leave without it.
</P>
<P>
   A few men had to lift the large panel that had fallen before
Hamil and others could exit the rear of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   After making their way through the smoke-filled plane, the crew
told passengers to jump from the plane onto an inflatable slide.
</P>
<P>
   Hamil jumped and was caught by firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started running away from the plane,'' he said. ``I
looked back and saw people walking on the wing. You're just taking
it all in and wondering if everyone's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those helping rescue passengers was Abayomi Omolewu, a
Prime Time shuttle van driver who had been waiting at the Chevron
station. While others ran away, Omolewu, a father of two, ran
toward the plane. He saw a man hanging from the wing who shouted,
``Help! Help!''
</P>
<P>
   Omolewu's co-workers hollered for him to step back. But he
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was just telling me to go and help. I was watching
to see if it was going to blow up,'' said the 46-year-old Nigerian
native who lives in Van Nuys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept yelling, `Sit down and slide,' '' Omolewu said.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-7 and 190 pounds, Omolewu ended up catching about 30
people. ``I believe God gave me that strength yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Two others, including one passenger Omolewu helped down the
slide, also helped catch people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking maybe this plane will blow up. But I'm looking
at the people in the plane who may die ... I didn't want those
people to die. So I did whatever I could,'' Omolewu said. ``It's
hard to see someone drowning. If I know I can swim, I'll go and
help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Martinez, 18, a cashier at the Chevron station, also ran
to help the victims after hitting the emergency button to shut off
gas pumps and calling 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the plane was going to blow up, but I didn't want to
just leave them there,'' Martinez said. ``One old lady was crying
and didn't know where to go. I hugged her and I told her everything
was going to be all right. I told her to get away from the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Omolewu and other shuttle and taxi drivers helped drive the
victims to safe ground at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Still sore in his neck and shoulder, Hamil said he broke down
after realizing he was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so full of emotions and crying. I was asking why
was I so lucky to live, and that I wish I could see my family right
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my problems I had before really are OK,'' Hamil said.
``It's the luckiest thing I've ever been through in my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
