<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9051 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SOCAL-GOP-LADN     03-07 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCAL-GOP-LADN </SLUG>
 
BUSH, McCAIN APPEAL FOR VOTES IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ In final symbolic gestures for Tuesday
primaries, GOP presidential candidates campaigned in the nation's
biggest state Monday with front-runner George W. Bush talking about
tolerance and challenger John McCain attacking establishment power.
</P>
<P>
   With California and 13 other states, including New York, on the
line, the Texas governor offered an upbeat message to moderate
Republicans and denounced racial and religious hatred in a speech
at the Simon Wiesenthal Center and the Museum of Tolerance in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all its flaws, I believe our nation is chosen by God and
commissioned by history to be the model to the world of justice and
inclusion and diversity without division,'' Bush said. ``These are
American convictions. Defending them is America's calling, and they
must be passed intact to America's children.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator, fighting to keep his candidacy alive with
California's 162 delegates among the 613 GOP delegates at stake
Tuesday, attacked Bush's campaign tactics and ``his sleazy Texas
buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   At a UCLA rally, McCain told students he's like fictional movie
hero Luke Skywalker trying to get out of the Death Star with his
crusade to reform campaign financing and government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get out of the Death Star and we're going to
defeat the forces arrayed against us,'' McCain told hundreds of
students gathered in a drizzling rain outside Kerckhoff Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the establishment, all the big money _ the iron triangle
of big money, lobbyists and legislation. We're going to break that
iron triangle and we're going to give government back to you. That
is what this campaign is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Tuesday's'' biggest prize is California's
winner-take-all primary, but McCain could score a damaging upset by
winning the popular vote ``beauty contest'' against Bush by
appealing to independents and Democrats to cross party lines. Only
votes of Republicans will count toward GOP delegation selection,
under rules imposed by the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pledged that if he is elected president, he will give voice
to the need for tolerance in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I must give it force. That is my commitment to the people
of this country. Every American must know they are equally American
_ no matter their culture, race or religion,'' he said. ``And those
who practice intimidation and violence will have a determined enemy
in the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Bush lit the memorial flame at the center in honor of
those killed during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   During his appearance at UCLA, McCain said he hoped his recent
comments criticizing the actions of ministers Jerry Falwell and Pat
Robertson didn't alienate conservative Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my party to be the party of Abraham Lincoln, Theodore
Roosevelt and Ronald Reagan,'' he said. ``A party that says
everybody come on board, even if you have some disagreements.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA junior Neel Punwani, 21, said he liked what McCain had to
say about reforming government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a breath of fresh air in our political system,'' he said.
``I really admire him for speaking out against the Christian right.
It takes a lot of guts to do that. He'll probably pay for it, but I
commend him on his beliefs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
