r f BC-SOCAL-GAS-LADN     03-07 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCAL-GAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LETUP IN SIGHT AT GAS PUMPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ Motorists across the region who are hoping for
relief from rising gasoline prices can look forward instead to more
bad news this summer, federal officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
decides to increase oil production later this month, U.S. gasoline
prices could easily soar an additional 20 cents a gallon by May or
June, according to an analysis released by the Energy Information
Administration, the statistical arm of the Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   That means prices could head into or above the $1.70-a-gallon
range for this summer's busy driving season. In California, where
the average price for unleaded is already at $1.63, prices could
top $2 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gasoline in some spots in California is already $2 a gallon,''
said Philip Verleger Jr., an economist with the Brattle Group, a
Cambridge, Mass.-based economic consulting firm. ``Californians are
going to pay 20 cents more on average than the EIA is saying.''
</P>
<P>
   After last year's uproar over soaring gas prices which included
a one-day boycott of service stations _ California motorists could
be particularly sensitive to further fuel-price hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Gas station owners could bear the brunt of that unrest this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the service station dealers, we catch the front-line wrath
of the consumer,'' said Will Woods, executive director of the
Automotive Trade Organizations of California, an association of
service station dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not happy about it either,'' Woods said. ``In most cases
we don't pass on the full cost increases because we have to compete
with other stations.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Chandler, assistant executive director of the California
Energy Commission, said the government has had little power to
influence oil and gasoline prices since 1981, when President Reagan
deregulated the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a commodity market,'' Chandler said. ``It's very
difficult for the state of California or the federal government to
step in.''
</P>
<P>
   Although consumer complaints are sure to rise with gasoline
prices, Carol Thorp, spokeswoman for the Automobile Club of
Southern California, said prices will probably not affect the
summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, as long as the economy is good and people are
secure about their jobs,'' she said, ``increases in gasoline prices
have little or no effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists blame the current situation on an effort by the OPEC
cartel to shore up prices by curtailing oil production. OPEC and
other oil-producing countries have already cut daily production by
an estimated 4.3 million barrels, or about 181 million gallons,
since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Daily production now stands around 75 million barrels, Verleger
said.
</P>
<P>
   The OPEC cuts lifted crude oil prices from under $11 a barrel to
around $30 a barrel. Each $1 increase in crude oil translates into
an additional 2 cents per gallon of gasoline at the pump, according
to the California Energy Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Although the commission estimates that California gets just 15
percent of its oil from foreign sources, OPEC price levels set the
benchmark for the entire industry. And gasoline refiners are
particularly vulnerable to crude oil price increases now because
U.S. inventories of gasoline are ``alarmingly low,'' according to
the Energy Information Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Even if OPEC decides to increase production at its scheduled
March 27 meeting, it will take weeks before gas prices are
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent increases, inflation-adjusted gas prices are
still nowhere near their 1981 peak, however. In current dollars,
gasoline would cost about $2.70 a gallon, according to Verleger.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will be complaining if prices increase in coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles-based Arco, which draws much of its oil from Alaska,
should see higher profits as a result of higher gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Verches, spokesman for Arco Products Co., said the
high prices and resulting windfall for some oil companies _ is
unlikely to last and is not enough to derail Arco's proposed merger
with BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive period financially for the company,'' he said,
``but it's a little late to save us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
