<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9063 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-HERSHISER     03-07 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-HERSHISER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER IS PITCHER AND PROFESSOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Anyone who knows Orel Hershiser even a little
will tell you his options are limitless when his playing days are
over. Whether he's a pitching coach, a manager, a general manager,
a president or whatever, he'll be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all the things people say about Hershiser, there is one
thing no one can tell you. No one knows when Hershiser will stop
throwing baseballs and pursue that next career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys are like, `How much do you have left?''' said
Hershiser, a 17-year veteran. ``Well, I'm still winning 12, 13, 16
games. ... Even in my last day of my last year, when it comes, I'm
never going to say it is (time to retire) because that'll mean I
quit in the midseason, or spring training, or in September, and
that's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hershiser left the Dodgers after the `94 season, the
consensus among the front office was he no longer possessed the
skills to perform as a starter. Stops in Cleveland and San
Francisco punched holes in that evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hershiser has a one-year, $2 million contract (with a club
option for 2001), and the speculation is his return is nothing more
than a precursor to a front-office job or a spot on the coaching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's lost that much as far as velocity,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He still has good sink, makes
the ball move. He takes real good care of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, 41, is with his fourth team in four years and not
assured of a spot in the starting rotation. He's battling Carlos
Perez for a starting spot. Otherwise, Hershiser will wind up in the
bullpen out to pasture in the role of long relief.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hershiser's run after right shoulder surgery in 1990
suggests anything, it's that he should never be counted out, only
counted on. The last three seasons are insight into his willingness
to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   He won 14 games for playoff-bound Cleveland, won 11 before San
Francisco fell to Chicago in a one-game play-in for the playoffs,
then signed with the Mets during last spring training and tied for
the team lead with 13 wins. The Mets went to the National League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better this year than I did last year,'' Hershiser
said. ``I went into the Cleveland camp on a nonguaranteed,
minor-league deal, having to impress people to get a job. I had to
go into spring training to perform, not to prepare for a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in 15 years I had to go to spring training
trying to win a job. I had to try to execute all my pitches right
from the get-go and I fell behind because I spent a lot of bullets
just making a team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fact that makes many within the organization cringe: The
last time the Dodgers won a playoff game was 1988, when Hershiser
threw the title clincher against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not the same pitcher now as he was in `88. His mental
skills were always an asset, but his physical ability was imposing.
The surgery that cost him nearly all of the '90 season taught him
how to survive without dominating stuff, and now folks around
baseball shake their heads in amazement at how the wiry Hershiser
still wins.
</P>
<P>
   Being the quintessential student of the game, Hershiser honed
his mental skills. Now, his success comes from preying on young and
impatient hitters. Those who exhibit patience are the ones who give
him trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orel has to rely on his mental ability more so than on his
physical ability, which he probably used more when he was a younger
pitcher,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros said. ``The guy finds
a way to win. There's guys with more talent, but he finds a way to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as he began doing years ago, he's imparting that wisdom to
the Dodgers' younger, and inexperienced, pitchers. Before
Grapefruit League games started, he would hold daily rap sessions
to talk with them. But the games didn't put an end to the meetings,
just the number of pupils he talks to at one time.
</P>
<P>
   After rookie Eric Gagne, in the running for a starting spot and
in the spotlight for the first time, allowed seven runs in his
initial spring outing, Hershiser spent time talking to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a professor in the art of pitching,'' 30-year-old rookie
right-hander Matt Herges said. ``I don't know if he ever plans on
being a coach; I imagine he does. He's maybe getting prepared for
that. And I think he'd be great. He doesn't force anything. He
knows everyone has different mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser is being paid by the Dodgers to be a pitcher _ whether
relief or starter has to be decided. But he brings so much more. He
loves to talk about pitching, or hitting, or the offensive aspect
of the game. He's involved with the players' union and he's
interested in the business side of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's not sure whether he wants to remain in uniform or
trade the cleats and support hose for a suit and tie. When his
playing days end, he'll have his pick. Funny thing, even though the
scenarios and opportunities appear limitless, when Hershiser takes
advantage of them is anyone's guess. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
