<HEADLINE>
HASEGAWA GETS TV TIME IN JAPAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa was no different
than many of his teammates during the offseason _ he stayed in
Orange County and worked out in preparation for the 2000 season.
But he also spent six weeks of the winter doing something entirely
different.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa went to his native Japan to be a TV star. Sort of.
Hasegawa signed with an agency that gives him work in television
doing a variety of things. He does commentary on sporting events,
and participates in comedy shows and quiz shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about my future,'' Hasegawa said. ``It's good for
baseball, it's good for my life now and it's good for a little bit
of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa said he did 20 programs and one commercial. One of the
shows was a quiz show, in which Hasegawa was a contestant.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The other contestants) were so talented,'' he said. ``It was
nice of them to ask me, but I don't know. I was a little mixed up.
Everybody answered questions but me, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The comedy shows were fun, Hasegawa said, ``but they were so
serious. Same as our job as baseball players.''
</P>
<P>
   SPRING CUTS: Catcher Bryan Graves was reassigned to minor-league
camp in Mesa. Four others _ outfielders Nathan Haynes, Darren
Blakely and Juan Tolentino, and infielder Brian Oliver will spend
their last day in major-league camp today, then report to
minor-league camp Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
