<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-CLIPPERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER KNOWS HOW CLIPPER FEEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press Telegram  
LOS ANGELES _ One Laker who's familiar with life on the other side
of L.A.'s tracks is veteran guard Ron Harper.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harper spent 4 seasons with the Clippers before hauling away
three championship rings with the Chicago Bulls. He also has some
advice for any young, whiny Clipper looking for the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they don't understand is the grass ain't any greener
someplace else,'' said Harper, who struggled in Chicago as Michael
Jordan's successor until Jordan returned from pro baseball.
``L.A.'s a great place. It's a great city. The one thing they have
to understand is that they have to stick together to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   HORRY SHOW: Aside from providing stellar defense and rebounding,
Lakers sixth man Robert Horry has morphed back into the sniper who
helped the Houston Rockets snag two NBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   Leading into Monday's game with the Clippers, Horry had made 7
of his previous 14 3-point shots over a five-game span.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson said Horry has been something of a
deadeye since retiring the mask used to protect his broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he got out of that Phantom of the Opera thing, he's
looking pretty good as far as shooting-wise,'' Jackson said of
Horry, whose nose was broken courtesy of a Tim Thomas elbow at
Milwaukee on Jan. 12. ``He's starting to come through again.''
</P>
<P>
   THE RIDE STUFF: On his 28th birthday, at least one of Shaquille
O'Neal's presents truly wasn't accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the most expensive Bentley on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   When a TV reporter asked the Lakers center if his teammates had
pitched in for a birthday gift, O'Neal said each of his teammates
coughed up $50,000 toward the aforementioned luxury sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Including those Lakers on the injured list, the Bentley either
would have had a sticker price of $650,000, or O'Neal would now
possess enough cash to load up on CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Some story, but not true, O'Neal admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he did receive a birthday Bentley green. Shaq said it was a
gift from his mother.
</P>
<P>
   OLD CENTER, NEW STAGE: Life on the other side of the tracks
didn't register any vibe of peculiarity for Clippers assistant
coach Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being with the Clippers now really doesn't affect anything,''
said Abdul-Jabbar, who helped sky-hook the Lakers to five NBA
championships in the '80s. But being detached from the Lakers
doesn't mean he's missed what's been going on around the NBA.
``They (Lakers) have about the best team in the league. They
certainly are contenders to win it all.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW CENTER, OLD STAGE: Clippers center Michael Olowokandi still
responds with a nervous chuckle when the subject of any inquiry
leads to his matchup with O'Neal. But at least now he has what
should be Yoda-caliber advice from Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kareem said `keep him out of the paint,''' Olowokandi, still
chuckling, said.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to keep down low and push him off the block,''
Olowokandi added. ``That'll be the game plan for tonight.
Hopefully, when he (O'Neal) gets too deep, you can get some help.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy may need some fine tuning. Olowokandi was assessed
three personal fouls in the first 4:17 of Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN AND OUT: The Clippers, who already have Eric Murdock and
Brian Skinner on the injured list with ankle problems, didn't suit
up Keith Closs and Troy Hudson. Closs continues to have lower-back
problems; Hudson's stomach ailment will be checked out by a doctor
today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
