<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-GONZAGA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA STOPS PEPPERDINE, WINS WCC TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ When Gonzaga called on the Calvary,
Pepperdine turned to its reserves.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Calvary _ Bulldogs forward Casey Calvary _ won
out. As a result, it's Gonzaga who will charge into the NCAA
Tournament after beating the Waves 69-65 in overtime Monday to win
the West Coast Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga's win secures a coveted automatic bid to the NCAA
Tournament, beginning March 16. Pepperdine's fate rests in the
hands of the NCAA Tournament committee. The Waves, who won the
regular-season conference title, felt coming in they'd earn an
at-large berth by reaching the final here.
</P>
<P>
   It's a theory they didn't want to test, but now they can only
hope it bears out. The conference has sent two teams to the
tournament just six times in its 45-year history, the last coming
in 1996 when Portland and Santa Clara advanced.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the final was Calvary, who had 25 points and
seven rebounds. He had two points in overtime and a key offensive
rebound and kickout pass to Richie Frahm, who nailed a 3-pointer to
put Gonzaga ahead 66-58 with 3:52 left.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine got 17 points from reserve guard Craig Lewis, who
pulled the Waves to within 68-65 on a 3-pointer with 2:18 left. But
Pepperdine never scored again, despite three shot attempts,
including Tezale Archie's 3-point try with three seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a transition period, looking over to the coach to get
a play, and not everybody knew what the play was,'' Archie said.
``The clock was running down, I tried to create, but I wasn't able
to get (a good) shot off.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvary started the second half with nine quick points, giving
the Bulldogs a 50-42 lead. But the Waves, who fell behind by 14 in
the first half, got back in it on Lewis' jumper to make it 55-54
with six minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Sheppard tied the game 58-58 with 43 seconds left.
Pepperdine had a chance to win it, but Archie misfired on a wild
jumper to in the closing seconds to send it to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs (24-8) led 38-34 at halftime after leading by as
many as 14 points. Gonzaga opened a 35-21 lead with 5:19 left in
the half when Ryan Floyd shook free for a 3-pointer, his second of
the game. Floyd hurt the Waves throughout the first half, scoring
13 points to lead the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just Floyd. Gonzaga's two big forwards Calvary and
Zach Gourde continually outworked the Waves inside. Calvary
finished the half with 12 points and Gourde, a freshman reserve,
had six.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine got little offense outside of Archie for the first 16
minutes. He kept them in the game with three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was Brandon Armstrong's foul trouble.
Armstrong, the Waves' leading scorer, picked up two less then three
minutes in and wasn't a factor, playing just six minutes and
missing his only field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Waves kept chipping away, using their depth to wear
the Bulldogs down and cut into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Gibbs hit two short jumpers in the paint to make it
36-28. Then Al Minihan hit a 3-pointer to make it 36-31, followed
by a Lewis 3-pointer to pull Pepperdine within 36-34 with 40
seconds left, completing a 15-4 run.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga finished the half shooting 57.4 percent from the field.
Pepperdine, after a slow start, wound up shooting 13 of 29 (44.8)
after it's late spurt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
