<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-CENSUS-$ADV12-COX     03-07 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH MORE AT STAKE THAN EVER, CENSUS BEGINS ITS DIFFICULT TASK
 &HT;    With CENSUS-RACEMIX, CENSUS-HARDTOREACH, CENSUS-NEW and
CENSUS-FACTS. For release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Check the mailbox. Something's coming that could
change your life. Millions of dollars are at stake, not to mention
power and influence.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about the Publishers Clearinghouse
sweepstakes, but the U.S. census.
</P>
<P>
   Every 10 years, as it has since U.S. marshals combed the new
nation on horseback in 1790, the government conducts a head count
of America.
</P>
<P>
   Questionnaires for the 2000 census are going out this month in
advance of April 1, the date known as Census Day.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like a dull exercise, but every question is
mandated by Congress and has a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The results help determine how you are represented in Congress
and the state legislature, how federal and state money is
distributed to your city and school district, and where developers
might build the next subdivision, shopping mall or bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution requires the census as the way to determine how
the 435 seats in the House of Representatives are distributed among
the 50 states. The numbers also are applied to federal grant
programs, roughly $180 billion a year in money that Washington
distributes among the states.
</P>
<P>
   There are some firsts in the 2000 census. Reflecting America's
growing diversity, for the first time people can check more than
one box to indicate their race. Also for the first time, people can
file their census questionnaire via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But in an era of telecommuting and smart-card shopping, the
census remains a labor-intensive task. The Census Bureau is hiring
500,000 full-time and part-time workers to fill nearly 900,000
jobs, with some workers filling several jobs before the task is
finished.
</P>
<P>
   Before it's over, they will have counted about 120 million
households, or 275 million residents. And while much of it will be
accomplished by super-fast computers, they'll have made a lot of
trash _ more than 20 million maps needed for field work and 1.5
billion piece of paper moved in the process.
</P>
<P>
   This temporary army of census workers is up against some
powerful forces: public resentment of the government and people's
concerns over whether their answers are truly confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the bulk-mail factor. ``We worry a lot about the
questionnaire simply not being opened because it gets lost amid the
junk mail,'' said Kenneth Prewitt, director of the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in the census this year will hit a record low, the
government predicts. The Census Bureau expects only 61 percent of
households to return the form mailed or hand-delivered to homes.
Census workers will continue follow-up calls and visits through
early July trying to find those who do not respond initially.
</P>
<P>
   But their job has become more complicated. The rise in the
numbers of two-earner households means that people often are not
home when the census workers come to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that people no longer consider participation in the
census as a patriotic duty and that a growing distrust of
government makes them less likely to want to reply. The rapid
growth of America's immigrant population, for many of whom English
is a second language, means there are millions of residents who are
confused by or scared of the forms.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau detected a significant drop in its count 20
years ago when mail response rates fell to 75 percent, from a 78
percent rate in 1970. In 1990, the slide became steeper, down to
only 65 percent, meaning that roughly one of every three households
failed to respond to the questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem is the fact that the count of minorities
traditionally has been less accurate than that of whites.
Historically, blacks and other minorities have been wary of the
government and less likely to respond to the census. Furthermore,
in low-income areas the distrust of government and census takers'
fear of crime may have reduced the count's accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   The steadily worsening results prompted the Census Bureau this
year to mount its first-ever paid advertising campaign on
prime-time TV and develop an extensive promotional effort involving
clergy, teachers, elected officials and other community leaders in
thousands of neighborhoods across America to inform people of the
stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is critical that people know what this is and that they do
not throw it away,'' said Karen Narasaki, executive director of the
National Asian Pacific American Legal Consortium, an advocacy group
for Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities were undercounted by a rate of more than 2 to 1
compared with whites in the 1990 census. Children made up more than
half of the 4 million people who were missed in the count, meaning
that states and cities that often need the help most were
shortchanged when government aid was distributed over the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What were the consequences to our community? Simple. We lost
out on money and power,'' said Maria Demeo of the Mexican American
Legal Defense and Education Fund.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only minority groups and special-interest
organizations who are pushing their people for a better count.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota, recognizing that many of its citizens head south to
spend the winter in resort homes, is urging them to file their
census forms from their northern address. The state has launched a
public-relations campaign and has distributed pamphlets in Arizona
and Florida urging people to wait and file their forms from their
homes in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Southern and Western states suffered the most in the 1990
census. Because their populations are growing and shifting faster,
they were more difficult to count and thus more likely to be
missed. Had the 1990 been adjusted for the undercount later
detected, Georgia, California and Montana each would have gained an
additional congressional seat at the expense of Oklahoma,
Pennsylvania and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   According to an analysis of 15 federal grant programs by the
U.S. Government Accounting Office, about $384 million more would
have gone to states in the South and West in 1998 that instead went
to states in the North and Midwest. Over the decade, that comes to
more than $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by the U.S. Supreme Court last year also raised the
stakes. The court forbade the Census Bureau from using statistical
models to fill the projected gaps in the undercount for the
purposes of reapportioning congressional districts, making the 2000
count perhaps the most closely watched and politically charged
ever.
</P>
<P>
   By late March, most people will have received their form in the
mail, or by hand delivery in rural areas. About 83 percent of
households receive the ``short'' form of only eight basic
questions: name, sex, age, race, Hispanic origin, relationship to
others living in home, rent or own, and phone number.
</P>
<P>
   One in six households will receive a ``long'' form of 53
questions. The long form is used to find out detailed information
about housing, income, health and other social characteristics.
Scientific sampling techniques are applied to this information to
draw conclusions about the wider population.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall, all field work will be concluded and, under law,
the Census Bureau must report the total U.S. population by state to
president by Dec. 31. States receive more detailed data by April 1,
2001, on which to base the redrawing of legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   While it's just getting under way, the Census Bureau's huge
operation has not been flawless.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a computer error by a private printer doing
work for the Census Bureau resulted in wrong addresses being
affixed to more than 100 million advance letters being sent to
households to inform them that the census form would follow.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a General Accounting Office report raised questions
about whether the sophisticated computers to tabulate the census
data will be ready. The Census Bureau contends that the system will
be fully tested and operational.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt, the census director, said the agency has done all it
can to guarantee a thorough count.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, it is simply up to people to answer the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the form arrives, the responsibility shifts from the
government to the people,'' Prewitt said. ``This is the moment of
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 0935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9170 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-CENSUS-HARDTOREACH-$A     03-07 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-HARDTOREACH-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS MAKING SPECIAL PUSH TO REACH THE HARD-TO-REACH
 &HT;    With CENSUS. For release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ People unlikely to fill out the Census 2000
questionnaire are a diverse group _ ethnic minorities and
anti-government militiamen, native Americans on reservations and
the upper-class residents of gated communities.
</P>
<P>
   Or simply busy working parents who just can't be bothered.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for a better result this year than in the last census in
1990, the Census Bureau has mounted a sophisticated marketing and
advertising campaign intended to reach people who are less likely
to respond to the questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   In planning its ad blitz, the Census Bureau and its ad agency
turned to existing demographic data on civic participation _ the
types of people who do and don't get involved in their local PTA,
those who try to avoid jury duty and those who do it even though
they don't necessarily want to.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they identified three distinct groups:
</P>
<P>
   _ Will mail the questionnaire back. About 40 percent of the
population, these people tend to be older, middle-class,
white-collar homeowners. They are familiar with the census and its
benefits. This group includes all races, but because it is
predominately white, it suffers less of an undercount than
minorities and new-immigrant ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ May get to it or not. The largest group, at 43 percent of the
population, these people tend to be middle-class Americans of all
races who feel no compelling reason to respond to the form. They
have at least a high school education and are primarily blue-collar
and service-industry workers. The Census Bureau hopes to convince
these people that it is in their interest to respond.
</P>
<P>
   _ The disaffected. The third group, at 17 percent, are the
people unlikely to fill out the form at all, including people from
a range of ethnic groups that have been undercounted in the past:
blacks, Hispanics, native Americans and others highly distrustful
of government. These groups are being targeted with print, radio
and TV ads that are tailored to their ethnic market and which
reinforce the message that the answers remain confidential. In
inner cities and high-crime areas, the Census Bureau will send out
``blitz teams'' of counters traveling together. The Census Bureau
also will make special efforts to count homeless people and illegal
aliens.
</P>
<P>
   The questionnaire is being printed in six languages _ English,
Spanish, Chinese, Tagalog, Vietnamese and Korean. Guidebooks to
filling out the form are available in 49 languages other than
English. In neighborhoods across America, the Census Bureau will
operate 60,000 assistance centers.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 0935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-CENSUS-NEW-$ADV12-COX     03-07 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-NEW-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With CENSUS. For release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHAT'S NEW IN THE 2000 CENSUS
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, people can file their census questionnaires
via the Census Bureau's Web site (www.census.gov). To file by the
Web, people use the 22-digit number printed on their census form as
a password.
</P>
<P>
   But census officials are not promoting the fact, mainly because
their operation is geared for the paper forms. So only about 8
million households out of a total 120 million are expected to take
advantage of cyber-census filing this year. In the future, the
Census Bureau plans to expand filing by the Web.
</P>
<P>
   SHORTEST SHORT FORM
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau cut the size of the short form _ which five of
every six households will receive _ to just eight questions, from
13 in 1990. Five questions related to housing were moved to the
long form. It is the shortest short form in history, intended to
make it easier and more likely to be filled out. It should take no
more than 10 minutes to complete the form.
</P>
<P>
   GRANDPARENTS AS CAREGIVERS
</P>
<P>
   A new question posed by the census _ No. 19 on the long form _
seeks to determine how many grandparents provide the bulk of
support and are primary caregivers for their grandchildren. As with
all items on the census questionnaire, it was put there by Congress
and intended to provide government with a better picture of who is
taking care of the nation's children. The question, in three parts,
asks: Are your grandchildren living in your house or apartment? Is
the grandparent responsible for the most basic needs of the
grandchildren? How long has the grandparent been responsible for
the grandchildren? The answers could have a bearing on the
distribution of government aid and legal issues involving child
care and children's rights.
</P>
<P>
   TO ADJUST OR NOT TO ADJUST?
</P>
<P>
   This is the most expensive and complex census in history. One
reason is a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in 1999 that forbids the use
of statistical sampling to compensate for the inevitable undercount
of the population. The Supreme Court said that the apportionment of
seats in Congress, the main reason the government counts people
every 10 years, cannot be based on sampling, which applies
scientific calculations to estimate the number and characteristics
of those people missed by the census.
</P>
<P>
   So the Census Bureau is making extensive efforts to count every
man, woman and child to come up with its unadjusted total. It will
also produce adjusted figures based on sampling _ widely consider
more accurate _ for the use of states who want them.
</P>
<P>
   States may be able to use the adjusted figures to help draw new
state legislative districts and for formulas governing the
distribution of federal and state money. But more lawsuits are
expected to be filed on the issue, which may compel the Supreme
Court to clarify its earlier ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
