<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RACEMIX-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MULTI-RACE CENSUS OPTIONS LEAVE SOME GROUPS WORRIED
 &HT;    With CENSUS. For release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a nation where celebrities such as Tiger Woods
and Mariah Carey represent the increasingly multiracial face of
America, the government is adjusting to diversity.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the 2000 census form arriving at homes
across the country this month allows people to identify themselves
as a combination of races by choosing as many races as they wish
from 12 check boxes and three write-in spaces.
</P>
<P>
   The results will give the Census Bureau data on 63 different
possible racial categories, plus a separate category for those of
Hispanic origin that blurs the potential combinations even further,
to 126.
</P>
<P>
   It is a multiple choice many racial and ethnic groups do not
want their members to make.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing their communities could lose money and clout, groups
representing African Americans, Asian Americans and American
Indians are encouraging people to choose only one box.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we all know from the recent TV movie about Sally Hemings,
most African Americans are a mixture of many things and could check
a number of boxes,'' said William Spriggs, policy director for the
National Urban League. ``This is not a matter of ethnic pride, this
is a matter of accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Spriggs and other black leaders worry that the multi-box options
could reduce the overall number of African Americans and
potentially weaken the enforcement of civil rights laws, fair
employment practices and social service funding distributed on the
basis of census data.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a particular county in Mississippi that was majority
black, these numbers could be 40 percent black and 18 percent
something else. That in turn could mean no more federal oversight
of civil rights laws. That's the kind of concern we have in how
these numbers are tallied,'' said Spriggs.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the fears, the Census Bureau has not yet decided how the
racial data will be tabulated and, more important, the Clinton
administration has not determined how the results will be applied
to federal programs that shape political power and the distribution
of government money.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear. The results of the 2000 census on race will
not be directly comparable to the last census in 1990, which asked
people to check only one box.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials predict that no more than 2 percent of the
population, or about 5 million people, will check more than one
box. The rates will be higher in larger cities, they believe.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 census ``dress rehearsal,'' 5.4 percent of the
residents in Sacramento, Calif., checked more than one box, while
fewer than 1 percent of the people in Columbia, S.C., listed
themselves as more than one race.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's Office of Management and Budget mandated the
change as a way to reflect the growing diversity of America.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to 1990, the number of interracial marriages ballooned
from 100,000 to 1.5 million. In the same period, the number of
children from mixed marriages quadrupled to 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The country's booming immigrant population suggests that the
trend will accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, this census question may become meaningless,'' said
Carl Haub, an expert with the Population Reference Bureau, a
non-profit demographics research organization. ``The definitions
may blur racial lines to the extent that it just doesn't matter
what you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
