A9173 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-CENSUS-FACTS-$ADV12-C     03-07 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-FACTS-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With CENSUS. For release Sunday, March 12.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE 2000 CENSUS, BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   _ People to be counted: more than 275 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Households to be counted: about 120 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Questions on the short form: 8, covering name, sex, age, race,
Hispanic origin, how many people live with you, rent or own, your
telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   _ Questions on the long form: 35, including the basics of the
short form plus details such as how you live, work, commute, the
state of your health, education, what your earn, and the value and
size of your home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Workers hired to conduct the census: about 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maps needed for field work: more than 20 million,
</P>
<P>
   _ Sheets of paper to be processed: 1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cost of the count: about $4.8 billion, more than twice the
cost of the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   _ When the results will be in: The Census Bureau must report the
population totals to the president by Dec. 31 for purposes of
apportioning congressional districts to the states. By April 1,
2001, states will receive their population counts for the purposes
of redrawing state legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   _ The money at stake: census numbers guide the allocation of
about $180 billion in federal spending each year.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
