<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conference on race barely taps people's desire to talk
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If we talked in terms of dinosaur DNA, we might
get people's attention. Except all we're talking about in the case
here is people, and chaos.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable number of Waco residents gave up a part of their
Sunday last weekend to talk about it, to make the choice that
Martin Luther King Jr. said we must, between ``chaos and
community.''
</P>
<P>
   They chose the latter.
</P>
<P>
   The ``chaos theory'' is what caused ``Jurassic Park'' to get
bloody _ the rule that forces left untended manage to go awry even
with the best of designs.
</P>
<P>
   In Waco as in most communities, we think of race relations as
yesterday's news. Discrimination by government or business is
prohibited, right? So all we need to to is make sure the streets
are passable, the police are on call, education and jobs are
available, right? All will be well as we reside in our neutral
corners. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Not even close. Chaos or community. In our indifference and
drift and through our actions we've affirmed that the consensus
choice is anything but community.
</P>
<P>
   That's why some far-seeing people assembled the first Dialogue
on Race Relations last year, and a first-anniversary event last
Sunday. Good news: Though the forces of chaos still have the
numbers, the numbers at this event were up from 150 registrants
last year to 220 this year. Indeed, they approached standing
room-only in the University High School cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing sentiment? Frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration wasn't with the people or subject matter. The
frustration was that with so many participants and so little time,
passionate and rewarding discussions were cut short. People of will
and goodwill were left begging for more. Which is good.
</P>
<P>
   For if they think it's worth pursuing this type of dialogue,
they have the power and opportunity to continue it.
</P>
<P>
   One of many small-group discussions focused on something Waco
public television station KCTF will be coordinating: a set of study
circles to discuss social issues. A study circle is composed of
eight to 12 individuals and meets regularly over a period of weeks.
It progresses from personal issues to broader issues and to
community responses.
</P>
<P>
   Over 100 communities are in various stages of this initiative
with assistance from the Study Circles Resource Center in Pomfret,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the teaspoonful of most-stimulating sharing among a
study-circle discussion group Sunday, this idea can bring out
personal and communal revelations.
</P>
<P>
   Another opportunity, one hopes, for personal and communal
discovery is that more people in Waco see the video, ``The Color of
Fear.'' A handful of people saw an excerpt Sunday, and if there's
one of them who didn't want to see the rest of it, that person has
Crazy Glue instead of ear wax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color of Fear'' is not something for a captive audience. It is
for people who want to be challenged, as a group of eight men does
in an excruciating, real-life encounter of their own fears and
prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   The video is like volatile chemicals best handled by
professionals. It comes with provisos about how best to present it,
along with workshops and training for presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor University social work lecturer Helen Harris said that
groups or businesses interested in the film could contact her or
producers Stir-Fry Productions, (800) 370-STIR. Be advised, this no
$3.50 Blockbuster rental. It is expensive. But for organizations
interested in changing attitudes, is it a worthwhile investment.
</P>
<P>
   So often the adage is right, that talk is cheap. Not in this
case. Talk is of the essence, the essence of community.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
