<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACNE-PATCH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Got a zit? Zappers offer overnight cure
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The uninvited guests at the party of
life, pimples have a way of showing up at the most inopportune
times.
</P>
<P>
   Like when you've scored the big date, landed the important job
interview or scheduled a sitdown for your yearbook photo.
</P>
<P>
   Now skin-care companies are asking the zit-ridden to sleep on
their complexion problems, with the debut of nighttime ``blemish
bombs'' and ``acne patches'' that you stick on trouble spots before
you go to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight Blemish Reducers by Pond's Institute contain
skin-friendly Vitamin E, rosemary and tea tree oil, as well as
salicylic acid, which helps unclog pores. A package of 24 clear
dots costs $5.99.
</P>
<P>
   The Biore Blemish Bomb uses salicylic acid and Panthenol
(pro-vitamin B5), which reduces redness. The Bomb costs $6.99 for
10 single-use packets (each packet can treat up to four blemishes).
</P>
<P>
   Both products promise results overnight, but acne experts aren't
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of salicylic acid have been known for many years,
says Patricia Farris, a New Orleans dermatologist and board member
of the American Academy of Dermatology, but these new products
sound more like ``a marketing gimmick than an actual zit buster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to have little effect overnight,'' Farris says. ``I
don't think they're the magic bullet for cysts.''
</P>
<P>
   There's not much hope for a 24-hour cure at home, she says.
Benzoyl peroxide, available in many over-the-counter acne formulas,
is a good antibacterial agent but doesn't work that quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest way to send a zit packing? An injection of diluted
cortisone from a dermatologist, Farris says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
