r l BC-MESSAGE-BOTTLE08-COX     03-07 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MESSAGE-BOTTLE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Found bottle from afar uncorks youthful enthusiasm
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On Nov. 19, a class of second-graders
from Red Bay Primary School in the Cayman Islands wrote their names
and the titles of their favorite storybooks on slips of paper,
corked them up in an emerald-green bottle, and dropped the bottle
in the ocean, not knowing where the bottle would go, or even if it
would be found.
</P>
<P>
   You'll never guess in a million years were the bottle ended up
three months later.
</P>
<P>
   Give up?
</P>
<P>
   With more second-graders. Last week, when Pam Langford,
second-grade teacher at Meadow Park Elementary School in West Palm
Beach, was fishing 8 miles off Palm Beach with her husband, Mike,
she saw a sparkling green bottle bobbing in the waves and plucked
it out of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   A story like this is simply too exciting to trust to a grown-up,
who can make anything boring, so I went straight to the school and
asked the second-graders to tell me in their own words what was
going on. When I asked questions, the children answered in such
eager, high-pitched voices that when I typed their responses, they
came out in italics.
</P>
<P>
   Where did the bottle come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was from Grand Cayman.''
</P>
<P>
   How far is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 500 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It started Nov. 19.''
</P>
<P>
   Where is Grand Cayman?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's down there by Mexico and the bottle floated all the way
around Cuba and Mrs. Langford picked it up and it had all kinds of
shells and things stuck to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it smelled real bad!''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we couldn't get the messages out so we stuck a piece of
wire inside and twisted it around until they came out.''
</P>
<P>
   What was inside the bottle?
</P>
<P>
   ``Notes about the children's favorite storybooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Whose favorite storybooks?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grand Cayman second -graders. They took a vote on `Wombat
Stew' and `Mr. Grumpy's Outing'.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the best?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wombat Stew! Wombat Stew! Gooey, brewy, yummy, chewy, wombat
stew!''
</P>
<P>
   Is that your final answer?
</P>
<P>
   It was, by a vote of 27 to 1. ``Mr. Grumpy's Outing,'' second
choice of both classes, was about a farmer who went for a boat ride
on his pond, and when all his animals insisted on going along, the
boat capsized, and they ended up swimming ashore and going to the
farmer's house for a cup of tea. ``Wombat Stew'' is about a dingo
in Australia who catches a fat wombat for a stew, but first he
makes the stew using suggestions by all the other animals like mud
by the platypus and bugs by the emu, and when he tastes it, he
spits it out because he thinks he's poisoned, and the fat wombat
runs away.
</P>
<P>
   Their teacher explained: ``We hadn't read those books, but they
were in the library. So we read them, and now we have written
letters to the Grand Cayman students, and we are mailing them
today.''
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't mail them before I got a peek at some of the
letters, each addressed to a Grand Cayman child in Mrs. Rankine's
Red Bay Primary School. And although all the letters were
interesting, the chattiest was by Holly of West Palm Beach, writing
to her new pen pal, Holly Ann of Grand Cayman:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Holly Ann,
</P>
<P>
   Our teacher found the bottle while she was fishing.
</P>
<P>
   I have some queshtons.
</P>
<P>
   What color is your hair? What color is your skin? And what color
is your eyes? Do you wear glases? What is your favorite food? I
have blond hair, blue eyes and peach skin. May be we cold be pen
pals. I am in 2nd grade. My favorite color is blue. What is your's?
Pleas write back.
</P>
<P>
   from Holly.
</P>
<P>
   I also liked Kevin's note to Wesley: What kind of video gamed do
you play? Well if you have Pokemon careds please wright back to me.
If you can get some pitjchers of you so I can see what you look
like and I'll get some pitcher of my self so you can see what I
look like.
</P>
<P>
   The address of the second-graders is Red Bay Primary School, Box
380 SAV, Grand Cayman, Cayman Islands, B.W.I., and I'm betting that
the West Indian students from first through sixth grades would
enjoy hearing from any South Florida students who would like a
foreign pen pal. And now, in case anybody is wondering what
happened to the emerald-green bottle, I was wondering that, too,
when I asked to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Langford threw it away!'' a chorus of Meadow Park
second-graders cheerfully informed me.
</P>
<P>
   Why on earth? I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too stinky!
</P>
<P>
   ``It smelled!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was yucky!''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, I thought, but I would have been quite happy to put a
clothespin on my nose if I could hold a bottle and think that it
had drifted all the way across the Gulf of Mexico, around Cuba and
up into the Gulf Stream with messages from children in another
country.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
