<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9203 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HEALTH-HYSTERIA08-COX     03-07 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-HYSTERIA08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Irradiating solid foods safe, but there are
still naysayers
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If the news media had transmitted hysteria as
effectively in the mid-1800s as they do now, 19th century crusaders
might have saved the world from the evils of pasteurized milk.
</P>
<P>
   There was opposition then to the process of heating liquid foods
to kill the micro-organisms responsible for spreading many
diseases, just as there is opposition now to the use of ionizing
energy for the same purpose on solid foods.
</P>
<P>
   This opposition is based largely on unfortunate terminology.
``Food irradiation'' conjures up images of glowing green stomachs
and mushroom-cloud explosions that might have been avoided by
``food ionization.'' But whatever irradiation's detractors lack in
clarity, they make up in volume.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration approved
irradiating raw beef, pork and lamb to prevent foodborne illnesses.
Last week, the U.S. Department of Agriculture determined E. coli
0157 is more prevalent in cattle than previously believed, calling
attention to inadequacies in the inspection process.
</P>
<P>
   Irradiation eradicates E. coli and eliminates virtually all
listeria, salmonella and other pathogens responsible for food
poisoning. Foodborne illnesses strike as many as 80 million
Americans a year with unpleasant symptoms commonly known as
``stomach flu.'' They kill about 9,000, mostly the very young, very
old and those with weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Food that's irradiated passes through a low-dose radioactive
field of cobalt-60 gamma rays without touching anything
radioactive, similar to dental X-rays. The process disrupts cell
function of bacteria so they cannot reproduce to harmful levels, as
its proponents describe it.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat and white potatoes have been irradiated since the
mid-1960s, spices and dry vegetable seasoning since 1983 and fresh
fruits since 1986. In fruits, irradiation has helped extend shelf
life and reduce the use of pest-killing chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   It does not make food radioactive. It does not use elements that
can explode or be used in making a nuclear weapon. All the nuclear
waste from used cobalt-60 would fit in an office desk, says the
American Dietetic Association's position paper.
</P>
<P>
   Medical equipment is routinely irradiated for sterile surgery.
Astronauts and hospital patients with depleted immune systems have
eaten irradiated food for years. Food irradiation is used in 27
other countries, including Canada, Japan, France and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irradiation has been studied more extensively than any other
food-preservation process, including canning, freezing, dehydration
and chemical additives,'' says the American Council on Science and
Health. Warning labels are required on all irradiated food, but the
ACSH encourages food companies to advertise the labels, the way
they alert consumers that something is ``calcium fortified.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Public Health Association, ADA, American Medical
Association and university-based Food Safety Consortium also
endorse irradiation. Most favor expanding irradiation to precooked
meat products.
</P>
<P>
   Its organized opponents tend to be those against everything
nuclear or governmental and those who bow to everything natural,
forgetting, for example, that the reason farmers use pesticides is
that with all their drawbacks, they're usually preferable to the
bugs they kill.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern for nuclear safety hazards might make sense if
trucks routinely spilled radioactive waste and ``The Simpsons''
were a documentary. They complain that chemical changes in
irradiated food haven't been adequately researched, but also that
there's no sure method to tell if food has been irradiated, so
slight are the chemical changes.
</P>
<P>
   If irradiated food is harmful, it's a wonder that mankind has
survived all these centuries of eating cooked food.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical changes produced by irradiation are identical to
the ones from cooking, steaming, roasting and pasteurization, the
ADA says. Nutrient losses are small and ``often substantially
less'' than from canning, drying and pasteurizing.
</P>
<P>
   Irradiation isn't a cure-all for foodborne illness. It can't
reverse spoilage that has begun. Healthy animals, sanitary
processing and handling of food and adequate cooking still are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   As research continues, better methods might turn up. Cal Poly
Pomona scientists announced a promising technique last week for
using a natural protein in cows' milk to starve bacteria in meat.
After years of research, maybe some day experts will consider it as
safe as irradiation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
