<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BALDNESS08-COX     03-07 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALDNESS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hair loss a question of timing and amount
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ A little black cloud hangs over the head of
just about every man imaginable. It evokes worry, panic and even
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Most men try not to think about it. Few talk about it. But
ignoring it won't make it go away.
</P>
<P>
   Hair loss. It causes no known medical complications, but it can
cause emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 96 percent of men demonstrate some natural progression of
hair loss after puberty, according to Dr. Valerie Laing, a
dermatologist with Boice-Willis Clinic in Rocky Mount. Some men
don't notice it until 30 years later. Others see visible signs of
hair loss in their early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier hair loss begins, the greater the eventual loss,
Laing said. It's most common for men to lose the hair on the top of
their head and around the temples.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic and hormonal factors play a role in hair loss. While it
can't be prevented, in most cases, hair loss can be controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Few men refuse to sit quietly and watch their hair thin. Many
men wage war against hair loss. Their first mode of attack -
Rogaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most men will try an over-the-counter product, such as
Rogaine, first,'' said Dr. Fiona Cook, an endocrinologist with
Physicians East in Greenville. ``If that doesn't work as well as
they would have liked, they'll visit their family physician. Not
for hair loss, per se, but for some other reason. The hair loss
often comes up as a 'by the way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rogaine is a topical application that can be bought at any
pharmacy. It's effective, but not as effective as the prescription
drug Propecia, according to Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Propecia has been known to slow down hair loss, prevent further
hair loss and in some cases help regrow hair. It usually takes
three to 12 months before men start to see results. Its most common
side effect is decreased sexual drive.
</P>
<P>
   Other hair loss treatments include scalp reductions, weaves and
hair transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Most times, though, surgery is the last resort. People will
often experiment with wigs and hairpieces first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safer than popping a pill or going under the knife,''
said Dennis Cobb, co-owner of Downtown Wig Mart in Wilson with his
wife, So Young. ``They may be costly, but wigs and hairpieces are
still cheaper than a prescription or an operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wigs and hairpieces at Downtown Wig Mart cost between $24 and
$200. Of the two, wigs are more popular, Cobb said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just slip them on and go. Hairpieces, on the other hand,
have to match the color of one's hair exactly. Otherwise, they'll
look funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Men aren't the only ones afflicted with hair loss. Up to 79
percent of women demonstrate some natural progression of hair loss
after puberty, according to Laing. Visible signs of female hair
loss rarely begin before menopause or age 50.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors view female hair loss as more serious than male hair
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Male pattern baldness in women isn't normal. Actually, it's
pretty rare,'' Cook said. ``When we see it, we often worry about an
abnormal male hormone level in women.''
</P>
<P>
   In women, hair loss usually occurs on the top of the head. While
Propecia is effective in treating hair loss in men, it isn't
appropriate for women, especially women of child-bearing age. The
drug is potentially harmful to a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Cook advises women suffering from hair loss to visit their
family physician for an evaluation, so an appropriate method of
treatment can be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hair loss is painless. But it does can cause emotional
distress,'' Cook said. ``The earlier it's caught, the earlier you
can begin treatment and get on with your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
