<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The poet William Wordsworth had it that ``The
child is father of the man.'' What sort of man, then, will that
6-year-old in Michigan rear _ the boy who shot a first-grade
classmate dead? (Teepen, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ Coincidentally (I presume), two
stories in major newspapers last Sunday disclosed how our
four-decades-old economic boycott of Cuba _ including the
Helms-Burton Act _ is little more than a mere annoyance en route to
doing business with Fidel Castro. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE _ I grew up in
Sudan, a small West Texas town where farmers still crawl into their
weather-beaten pickup trucks and putter snail-like into town down
narrow, two-lane blacktop. My grandpa was one of those farmers, and
like the others, he was bound to the rich, dry ground through a
type of marriage whispered between him and God _ a marriage of pure
determination, wit and perseverance pitted against the forces of
nature. (Barker, Cox News Service). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Times have changed, but not
that much. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ In Waco as in most communities, we
think of race relations as yesterday's news. Discrimination by
government or business is prohibited, right? So all we need to to
is make sure the streets are passable, the police are on call,
education and jobs are available, right? All will be well as we
reside in our neutral corners. Right? Not even close. Chaos or
community. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
