<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SECURITY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home security doesn't have to be expensive
 &HT;    By Christine Moran
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ People pay thousands of dollars to have
alarm systems installed in their homes. But, while alarm systems
deter crime, not everyone can afford them.
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't, Yvette Jones, Rocky Mount Police
Department's crime prevention technician, cites several inexpensive
steps people can take to protect their homes against invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have a deadbolt lock, buy one,'' Jones said.
``Otherwise, burglars won't think twice about kicking your door in.
You might invest in additional locks for your windows, too. Some
people buy what's called a drill and pin packet. This lock actually
secures the two window panes together so an intruder can't break
the glass, unlatch the lock and lift up the bottom pane. It can
present a fire hazard, however, so if you have small children, it's
probably better that you don't use this method.''
</P>
<P>
   Burglars look for poorly lit areas to hide themselves so they
can sneak into a home. Exterior lighting around the perimeter of a
house helps prevent break-ins, as does trimming nearby bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Burglars hide themselves in tall bushes and climb into homes
through windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overgrown areas send direct messages to burglars,'' Jones
said. ``It tells them that the people who own the house probably
don't spend a great deal of time at home. It also tells them that
they'll probably be able to find some easy points of entry.''
</P>
<P>
   The most common point of entry is the front door, said Detective
Robert Williams with the Rocky Mount Police Department's criminal
investigation division. Most times, he said, burglars walk right up
to the front door, kick it in and make their way into the house.
</P>
<P>
   Since most burglars aren't looking for a confrontation, Williams
encourages homeowners to lead burglars to believe they're home even
when they're not. Do such things as leave the TV or radio on and
keep several lights lit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burglars want to get in and get out as fast as they can,
without ever coming face to face with a homeowner. Most often
they're stealing to help support a drug habit. They take what they
can carry - TVs, VCRs, stereos, jewelry, loose change, clothes.
They either sell these items for cash or trade them for drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   It's important to engrave your valuables with your driver's
license number and state abbreviation. By doing so, if the items
are ever stolen, they can be returned to their correct owner once
they're retrieved by the police.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Jones encourages people to write down the make, model
and serial number of the items for their own records.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocky Mount Police Department will send patrol officers free
of charge to people's homes to conduct home security surveys.
Officers circle the perimeter of the house, looking for danger
areas, such as poor lighting or unkept shrubbery. They then make
their way inside the house, examining locks, door frames and
windows.
</P>
<P>
   The officers offer the homeowners advice on how not to become
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
