<HEADER>
A9209 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN08-COX     03-07 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is a trip to Hooters practical? It is for the father of the year
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The practical man met the father of the
year last week.
</P>
<P>
   At Hooters.
</P>
<P>
   Now before you sensitive types sling more scorching screeds his
way, let the practical man get one thing straight. Hooters is
practical. Or so he told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old buddy's in town,'' he said. ``We're taking him to
Hooters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``O for Pete's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bah! It'll keep us out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big pervs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's brilliant! We'll be distracted by the babes, won't drink
too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing cackle was bloodcurdling, but the practical man
doesn't scare easy. Minutes later he was perched on a stool and
surrounded by pals _ three similarly washed-up married men.
</P>
<P>
   They ate wings, which were hot, fattening and expensive. They
drank beer _ cold, fattening and expensive. They talked,
pointlessly, of the past, which made their lives seem empty. And
they gawked, pointlessly, at the girls, who made them ache for
their youth. It was, in short, not just a shameful but a painful
waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   Until the father of the year appeared.
</P>
<P>
   This gent's enormous girth at first disguised his true identity,
for when he lumbered into the joint, he obliterated all perception
of what trailed behind. But soon the fat man's charge wanted to see
what all the hooting was about, and he poked his nose around Pop's
billowy belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet mother of heaven!'' exclaimed the practical man. ``It's
a Cub Scout!''
</P>
<P>
   Appalled, his crew looked on as father and son made their way to
a table, sat and studied menus. Within seconds, the Scout began
bobbing above his bill of fare like a determined dog over a
backyard fence. The practical man and friends discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid's game,'' said one. ``But one rib doesn't make a
barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One bat doesn't make a ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One stick of wood doesn't make a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   And then they sent a waitress to the table with a gift: Hooters
T-shirts. For by this time, the father of the year's genius had
begun to dawn on them. Why let a boy muddle through puberty,
nibbling at nuance and sipping at secrets, when he can gorge on
whole truth for the price of a chicken wing?
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S LEFT FOR OLDER, DISCARDED WORKER?
</P>
<P>
   A reader from West Palm Beach sent an interesting e-mail. It's
much too long to publish, but the practical man will summarize as
best as he can:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: Everyone says the economy is booming, but
it's not booming for older workers who have been discarded in favor
of younger, cheaper employees. I'm 57, with vast corporate
experience and proven management skills, but ``I've been relegated
to the garbage heap and at this rate, I'll soon be one of those
living with relatives or in my car. What a country! Give your all _
only to lose it when you get older.... Where does one go from
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Tough break, and tough question. The practical man can't pretend
to have the answer, but he does have some thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   First, you are not your work.
</P>
<P>
   Careerists inevitably get this wrong, only to suffer
disillusionment after retirement, or after realizing their kids
have been raised almost entirely by strangers, or, like you, after
being laid off. Only then do they pause to take in the tragic
truth: 99 percent of all white-collar jobs exist only to make the
smart feel important or to swindle the stupid out of their cash.
</P>
<P>
   Humanity would not only survive happily, it would likely be
better off without advertisers and stockbrokers and the
military-industrial complex, without the media and celebrities and
politicians, without zillions of companies trying to sell us
trinkets we don't need, without cell phones and pagers and the
Internet, and yeah, without a Practical Man column.
</P>
<P>
   Because it doesn't matter how well you can write, how
effortlessly you can manage, how quickly you can calculate the
square root of 317. What matters is the stuff you don't get paid
for: your family and friends, being kind to people, improving your
mind so you can live in the world without hurting it and enjoy it
without buying bogus toys.
</P>
<P>
   So, to the practical man, where you go from here is obvious: Get
a job. It doesn't have to be a job you're ``qualified for'' or one
that puts your massive but meaningless corporate talents to good
use. Take any job that pays enough to keep you from living in your
car. Then forget about your career and start concentrating on your
life.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: U are my favorite reading these days. ...
Are you a local? Are you really a man?
</P>
<P>
   _ Doesn't Vote Either, Deborah
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Forgive the stationery. Trying to save a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the practical man not a woman, he's also not Ron
Wiggins. He's 38 and he's lived in Palm Beach County 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   But those are the only clues you'll get, Deborah, for the
practical man has discovered that nothing _ not even a toolbox
stuffed with Snap-On wrenches and a pocket edition of ``The Way
Things Work'' _ is as practical as anonymity, especially when your
specialty is ticking people off.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about the stationery: For the love of God, never do that
again! You may have saved a tree _ or more like a twig _ but you
dang near killed the practical man. Nothing strikes fear in his
heart like the second coming of Christmas cards.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: This note is to comment on your column of
Feb. 20 (''the secret of lasting love'').
</P>
<P>
   Your answer to that person was RIGHT ON!
</P>
<P>
   I am in my late 60s. Married 48 years. For the many stories of
true and everlasting love there are probably as many like mine.
Whatever aspirations we had in our youth we have had to submerge,
DEEPLY, and carry on.
</P>
<P>
   My spouse brags about 48 years of bliss, and it has been _ FOR
HIM!
</P>
<P>
   The Peggy Lee song ``Is That All There Is?'' tells it all for
me. Thank you!
</P>
<P>
   _ For obvious reasons, I cannot sign this
</P>
<P>
   Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, Fla. 33416. Or
e-mail PracticalMan (at)pbpost.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
