<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WILL-TOLIVE08-COX     03-07 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILL-TOLIVE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meeting a final deadline
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Peanuts'' cartoonist Charles M. Schulz never
missed a deadline, his former editors have said.
</P>
<P>
   His death then, on the night of Feb. 12 _ while the ink of his
final cartoon strip was still wet on newspapers around the country
_ came as if he had sketched it out himself.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz's timing may have seemed eerily perfect.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts on death and dying say living to meet a final
deadline is a common phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal experience is that when there's somebody who
really wants to be alive (to mark a milestone), somehow they
struggle to do it, and afterwards they really quickly die,'' said
Dr. Carlos Encarnacion, a medical oncologist at Texas Oncology
Cancer Care and Research Center. ``I certainly believe there is
something a person does or an inner strength that helps them last
until certain events happen. It's not very scientific, but who can
be scientific under those circumstances?''
</P>
<P>
   Terminally ill people may postpone death to celebrate the events
they have cherished throughout life _ birthdays, anniversaries,
family weddings, babies' births, holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of deaths around the Thanksgiving and Christmas
and New Year's holidays,'' said Hatch Bailey, president of
Wilkirson-Hatch-Bailey Funeral Home. ``And we see a lot of people
make it just past a birthday, especially if a birthday is a
milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   A loved one's will to live became a personal experience for
Tillman Rodabough, a sociology professor who teaches a class on
death and dying at Baylor University. His brother, a quadriplegic,
fell critically ill around Thanksgiving last year, but he didn't
die until late January. Rodabough said he believes his brother
willed himself to live that long so he could ring in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can, to some degree, determine when we die,''
Rodabough said. ``Some people have very little to live for, and
physically they are dying, but they can slow the process just by
will. We can control our body to a pretty fair extent, and I think
that's what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   No scientific explanation exists as to how people can will
themselves to live. But many researchers have been interested in
the mind's power over the body, and recent studies have shown that
optimistic people tend to live longer.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are born optimists. But shaping thought processes
and striving to meet optimistic goals can be learned at any stage
in life, according to Norman Fluet, director of psychological
services for the Scott &AMP; White Clinic in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, those who have had an important part of their lives
taken away may not feel as motivated to live because part of
themselves has already died, Fluet said. That is why spouses often
die within a short time of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Fluet said Schulz may have felt this way about ending his
``Peanuts'' strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had a love affair with his comic strip
characters,'' Fluet said. ``All that was coming to an end as his
own mortality was coming to an end. I think his timing was
absolutely incredible. It was like saying goodbye to all his
characters was like saying goodbye to his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people may feel ready to die but will themselves to hang on
for family and friends, said Rodney Kruse, chaplain and bereavement
coordinator for Scott &AMP; White Hospice in Temple. He has served
patients who want to ensure financial and emotional support for
their spouses and children before they die.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realize they're trying to live until they die, and part
of living until you die is taking care of business,'' Kruse said.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to survive to meet a milestone can be emotionally
taxing on a terminally ill patient's family, especially when the
patient's quality of life is gone. If dying people feel they can't
die for fear of abandoning other people, families must give them
permission to die, Rodabough said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A family member that says we've had great times, we're glad
you are here and we'll remember you forever says it's OK to die,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Encarnacion said doctors' first responsibility is to be honest
with families about their loved ones' chances for survival. But in
most cases, he would also encourage people to survive to meet a
personal milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to take away hope, but you don't want to be
unrealistic,'' he said. ``No one knows how long anyone has to
live.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if a person doesn't live long enough to pass an important
milestone, the fact that he or she tried can ease the family's
grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the idea of realizing the dying person wants to
accomplish this gives comfort to the bereaved,'' Kruse said.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to wave goodbye is one of the first things children
learn, and it's one of the last symbolic gestures people make in
life. Some people who die quickly don't get that last chance. But
for those who are able to mark a final salient point in life, the
last wave goodbye can be a peaceful, if not joyful, gesture, Kruse
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the idea of saying goodbye or accomplishing something
is the idea that as people look forward, they see a future,'' Kruse
said. ``And the future is not on this earth, and at some point,
people realize that they let go and they trust in God. So instead
of saying people give up, that they dread the future, I think
people let go because they see the future. Instead of living out of
fear, they live out of trust and grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
