products sold as dietary supplements. It's as easy to buy as
aspirin, and looks safer, because no warning labels are required.
Yet the Food and Drug Administration has collected more than 800
reports of users suffering adverse reactions, and is launching a
new push to address public safety issues posed by ephedra. By ERIN
McCORMICK.
