<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9248 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-ARROYO-ART-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     03-07 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ARROYO-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 JAMAICA, N.Y.: ... a jockey.' ''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1998, Arroyo was working as a groom at Rockingham Park for
trainer Jonathan John, and then he went to work on a horse farm in
Virginia. By last summer, he was ready to begin his riding career
when Rockingham opened for its summer meet in Salem, N.H. Trainer
Nick Cicerone had taken the youth under his wing ``and I've got to
thank Nick Cicerone for getting me going,'' said Arroyo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hall was tending to his business as agent for veteran
jockeys Joe Hampshire and Jose Caraballo, two of the leading
jockeys in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one day,'' Hall recalled, ``Joe came up to me and said he
was really impressed by this bug boy (apprentice) and he told me
his name was Arroyo. Joe said he was very good at getting a horse
out of the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampshire could have told Hall this apprentice's name was Willie
Shoemaker and Hall still wouldn't have been impressed. Hall, much
like football's Bill Parcells, does not like rookies ``because they
make so many mistakes and you have to wait so long for them to get
good,'' said the agent. In all his years, Hall had been an agent
for only three apprentices, and that was back in the 1970s and
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hall stuck to veteran jockeys because they were reliable. An
apprentice, by definition, was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take so much time and effort,'' said Hall, ``but so many
of them never make it. They lose races because of mistakes, and an
old veteran rider doesn't make those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hall, with the prodding of his meal ticket, Hampshire, took
a look at Arroyo, and he came away impressed. Arroyo's first ride,
Mia's Gold, finished fourth, but on the fifth ride of his career,
he brought home Iron Lady, a 49-1 shot, last June at Rockingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed,'' said Hall. ``It was a blanket finish.
There were three or four horses at the wire, but what I liked was
that he was dead last at the top of the stretch but (Arroyo) was
able to get him home.''
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo was even more excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if I had won,'' he said. ``I remember when I was
pulling up after the race, I said to (jockey) Harry Vega, `I think
you won,' and Harry said he didn't know. And when I got back and I
saw my number was up, I was so excited. The horse paid $99. It was
my first win. It was so exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Other trainers noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started getting calls from some of the top outfits,''
recalled Hall, ``but the kid was as green as a pea. He made a few
mistakes, and the horses didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was not all bad. Hall knew it was important for a
youngster to gain experience before he won too many races, for
practical as well as psychological reasons. The psychological
reasons are obvious: too many wins too soon and all the success
might go to a youngster's head.
</P>
<P>
   But the practical reasons are perhaps just as important. An
apprentice jockey begins by carrying 10 pounds less than a veteran
jockey on a horse. After a set number of wins, that weight
allowance drops to 7 pounds and finally to 5. The apprentice is
then allowed an entire year to ride with that 5-pound allowance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous when I got started,'' Arroyo said,
``but I am very competitive, and I knew I would do good. I used to
box and the other fighters would see how small I was and they would
think they could do anything with me; but I would beat them. I had
that same mentality when I started riding.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the Rockingham meet in September, when, in fact,
Arroyo was still ``green as a pea,'' Hall had his master plan.
Knowing that this youth had exceptional talent, Hall thought Arroyo
should start out fast when the Suffolk Downs meet opened in
September, win race after race, and then head down to New York at
the first of the year. Traditionally, the top New York jockeys
leave for Gulfstream Park in Florida in the winter, and
opportunities for a skillful apprentice abound in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then, right when Suffolk opened, Norberto had a spill and
he hurt his shoulder,'' said Hall. ``He was out for a while, and
that set us back.''
</P>
<P>
   By October, Arroyo was back on horses, and by November and
December, he was the sensation of Suffolk Downs, winning races at a
25 percent clip. Michael Gill, the leading owner at Suffolk, had
noticed the youth, put him on horse after horse, and Arroyo won
race after race. Other top trainers also put him on their better
horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then, I knew I could do it,'' said Arroyo. ``I was very
confident. I wanted to go to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Hall, the unthinkable for him now was inevitable. Hall
knew he had to leave New England and see how far Arroyo could go
with his apprenticeship (which will last until August). Beyond the
talent, beyond Arroyo's likability as a person, said Hall, the
youngster had a rare trait for an apprentice: ``He'd do what he was
told; he'd listen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   New York, said Hall, was the place to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The color brown _ dull brown _ permeates winter racing in New
York. The outer track at Aqueduct, unused in the winter, is brown,
just as dusty brown is the color of the inner track, where the
horses run nine times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Further inside, the grass on the turf course _ also unused _ is
winter brown, just as the bushes surrounding the infield lakes seem
tinted brownish green by winter's cold. Even the clouds and air
between Aqueduct and nearby JFK airport seem dully brownish, just
as are the parkas and winter coats of so many of the men who gather
for the day's races at New York's winter racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Brown. Dull. The color of racing for the sake of racing. Winter
racing. Neither the sport of kings nor the sport of flings, but
merely a day's work for both horse and man.
</P>
<P>
   But heat, sparks, flashes, and a warm glow soon warmed Aqueduct.
Instead of dull brown, Aqueduct was white hot because of Arroyo
virtually from the day he arrived in New York two months ago.
Arroyo now is the 10th leading jockey in the US _ winning more
races than such stalwarts as Mike Smith, John Velasquez, and Jerry
Bailey _ and is 12th in money earned with more than $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, jockeys get 10 percent of winning purses and agents
collect 25 percent of what the jockey earns. Thus, Arroyo has
already earned more than $150,000 in 2000 and Hall receives a
quarter of that. Arroyo has won 22 percent of his races in New
York, a superlative record.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall had a huge hurdle to climb once he got to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had to win right away so we could make a good
impression and get off to a fast start,'' said the agent, ``but I
didn't know the New York trainers.'' And racing, like all walks of
life, is dependent on contacts.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one thing about New Englanders who have raced at
Suffolk or Rockingham, it is their loyalty. Hall knew his only hope
for a fast start was to contact former New Englanders now racing in
New York _ ``guys such as Bobby and Steve Klesaris and Russell
Derderian'' _ and throw himself at their mercy.
</P>
<P>
   So Hall went to Bobby Klesaris, who began his career at Suffolk,
and told him, ``I need a live one _ fast.'' And Klesaris came
through with a live horse the next day, put Arroyo aboard, and the
apprentice won. After a few more wins, Arroyo caught the eye of
veteran New York trainers such as Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Some New Yorkers, of course, are grizzled cynics who say Arroyo
is no better than other bug boys who have shown up in the winter
only to disappear once the top jockeys return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at his competition,'' said one of the cynics. ``Aaron
Gryder (the leading rider in New York) and Mike Luzzi _ that's
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Arroyo can't praise Gryder often enough (``Aaron
Gryder is a true friend; he's done so much for me''), a few other
jockeys have not been happy about Arroyo's aggressive riding style,
which already has been the cause of two suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't hide it,'' said Arroyo of a few New York jockeys
not happy with his appearance on the scene. ``They've got to show
it. No class. Once a jockey tried to put me over the rail. They
were on the lead and I was laying second and I was on the inside,
and down the backstretch they tried to put me over the rail if I
didn't take my horse back. I got my boot all scuffed (from the
paint on the rail). They weren't even trying to win the race. They
were just trying to make sure I wasn't going to win. A lot of them
go out there riding so you won't win while not even caring if they
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The boxer's spirit, the athlete's competitiveness, ooze from
every word.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think because I'm a bug boy I'll be intimidated,'' said
Arroyo. ``But I'm not intimidated by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as he says he will do well once the top jockeys return in
April _ Bailey, Smith, Velasquez, Jorge Chavez, Jose Santos, and
Edgar Prado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they are the best,'' said Arroyo, ``but I am confident
I will do well if I am given a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo has already won a stakes race in New York (``That is now
my biggest thrill, when winning my first race at Rockingham had
been'') and is in constant demand. On last Saturday's card at
Aqueduct, for instance, he had a ride in all nine races.
</P>
<P>
   The two men from the Boston area, one 22 years old and the other
a grandfather, use similar words to describe their experiences.
``This is a dream for me,'' said Arroyo, ``to ride in New York and
win.'' And Hall, his agent who never thought there was anyone or
anything that could yank him out of New England, says, ``Norberto
is definitely fulfilling a dream for me.''
</P>
<P>
   And each morning at dawn, the two are at the Aqueduct stables,
Arroyo working out horses and Hall checking to see which horses his
jockey should ride. Then comes the afternoon of racing and, at
night, back to the apartment in Queens, the two studying the tapes
of the day's races.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a son to me,'' said Hall, and Arroyo, so close to
his father that he calls him ``my best friend,'' said his agent is
``like a father to me. I listen to what he says, just as I love to
listen to P.G. (Phil) Johnson. These men have seen everything in
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Including dreams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
