<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9249 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-KAROLYI-BOS &LR;      03-07 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KAROLYI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAROLY RETURNS TO STEADY US GYMNASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bela Karolyi wears grown-up, 9-to-5 clothes now. Checked jacket,
crimson tie, real shoes. ``My wife said I'm looking more human,''
he said. ``I wish I was back in my old warmup suit, jumping
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this Olympic year. The greatest coach in gymnastics history,
mentor to Nadia and Mary Lou and Kimbo and Dominique, has nobody in
the chase this time. Or, more accurately, he has everybody in the
chase, the whole US women's team for this summer's Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi is the national team coordinator, the man with a plan to
pull the deflated Americans off the floor and get them back on the
medal stand where they belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had a so-called coordinating or advisory position
in my life,'' said Karolyi. ``I'm not a very political person. I am
pretty vocal in my opinions. I enjoy having the freedom to say
whatever I want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Karolyi has to play the diplomat. He has to convince more
than two dozen coaches that he has nothing up his sleeve. That he's
not going to spirit away their gymnasts before the trials. That
he's not going to be prowling the floor at Olympus and grabbing the
credit when the medals are handed out. That he will keep the warmup
suit in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi retired from elite coaching after the Magnificent Seven
won the team gold medal in Atlanta four years ago. After three
decades, after producing nine Olympic and 15 world champions in two
countries, he had nothing more to prove.
</P>
<P>
   So he went back to his Houston ranch and his summer camps.
``When I stepped out, I considered it over,'' said the 57-year-old
Karolyi. ``With me, it's all in or all out. Halfway, I don't
enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   He figured that some younger coach, someone with personality and
leadership, would step up and take over the reins. ``But somehow,
it never came around,'' Karolyi said.
</P>
<P>
   After just one year, the US women tumbled from first to sixth on
the global stage. ``It's unreal,'' he said. ``You cannot accept it.
There is something deeply wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the usual post-Olympic transition, the coaches and
federation people insisted. Next time, we'll be back up there. But
when the Americans finished a dispirited sixth again at last year's
world championships in China, behind even the Australians, it was
crisis time. ``Now we're going to do it my way,'' declared USA
Gymnastics president Bob Colarossi, who had pushed for a shake-up
when he arrived from the Mass. Sports Partnership in summer 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His way meant Karolyi, the man whose golden touch had produced
Nadia Comaneci, Mary Lou Retton, Kim Zmeskal, and Dominique
Moceanu. The man who never, ever does sixth place. ``Winning
medals,'' said Colarossi, ``drives everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi's wife, Martha, told him he was out of his mind. ``When
I came back in 1992, she told me I was crazy,'' he shrugged. ``When
I came back in 1994, she told me I was really crazy. When I came
back in 1996, she told me I was really, really crazy. Now she
thinks I'm completely crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   What else could he do? Karolyi enjoyed the summer camps, ``the
little kiddos hanging on me, saying, `Bela, Bela.' '' But he missed
the competitive excitement, ``running around the floor like a crazy
rooster, eating my fingers.'' And he was undeniably frustrated at
seeing American kids getting their heads handed to them at world
meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years of my life I was working so hard growing the
sport of gymnastics in this country,'' Karolyi said. ``Now
everything is going down. I said, is not fair, damn it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, last November, he agreed to come back and ``coordinate'' the
national team. That means visiting clubs from Pennsylvania to Ohio
to Nevada to California to check on the elite gymnasts. That means
helping decide on the selection process (more intricate than a
quadratic equation) and helping choose the team. (Back in Romania,
he merely pointed: you, you, you, you, you, you.) That means
holding monthly boot camps at his ranch. That means organizing,
prodding, cajoling, hugging, growling, inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   It does not mean coaching individual gymnasts, and that was
spelled out in his deal. ``There would be a revolution,'' Karolyi
realized. ``It would be called biasedness. It would be called
everything in the world. And I understand, because I would probably
react in the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when the federation had ``the meeting of all meetings'' in
Tulsa in December, skeptical coaching eyebrows were everywhere.
``Still was suspicion out there, still they thought I want to take
it over and not give them their well-deserved recognition,''
Karolyi said.
</P>
<P>
   Videos from Olympics past rolled in their heads. Bela stopping
the show for 40 minutes in Moscow, claiming that Comaneci was
robbed. Bela giving Retton a victory bear hug in Los Angeles. Bela
carrying wounded Kerri Strug onto the medal stand in Atlanta.
Always Bela.
</P>
<P>
   Their gymnasts, though, have seen the same videotapes _ which is
why they were agog when Karolyi walked into the gym. ``I couldn't
stop smiling the whole time,'' said Vanessa Atler. ``I was
awestruck.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the familiar walrus mustache, the piercing glare, the
guttural growl, the 10,000 volts of energy, the boundless optimism:
``Sure, we gonna do it. We gotta do it. Now or never.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also the unyielding standard, the disdain for mediocrity,
for sloppiness, for halfheartedness. The women discovered that at
Karolyi's first boot camp. ``It's work,'' Karolyi said. ``It's
intensity. It's repetition. Not wasting time, not hanging around.
No talk. What to talk? Do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi was stunned when he dropped by Atler's gym in a Dallas
suburb to check on her and watched her casually abandon a bars
routine halfway through. ``Hey, hey, what the hell is this?'' he
snapped at her. ``You call this a routine? That's crap, that's
nothing. Go back and do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Atler did a half-dozen routines, then moved to the balance beam
and did another half-dozen there. ``I said this is the difference,
honey, between training and training,'' Karolyi said. ``They need
to understand, this is the standard. But someone has to push them
to it. They need that strong voice, that support, to pull them
through what they think are difficulties. To perform all the time
their routines without falling, without walking away.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no other way to climb up from sixth place, to win a
medal, Karolyi tells them. You think the Russians and the Romanians
and the Chinese are jumping down from the bars? ``He makes us
realize that there are other gymnasts working every second,'' Atler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Why let them and their coaches kid themselves, Karolyi believes.
The competition in Sydney will be fierce, and there are only a few
months to prepare. His job is to get everyone moving in
triple-time, with a boot up the butt (``more efficient guidance'')
if necessary. ``No hocus-pocus, but reality,'' Karolyi said. ``Tell
them the truth. That's the most important.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the elite group is fitter and more focused
since Karolyi has been around. ``He makes all the girls want to do
more,'' said Kristen Maloney, the two-time national champion. But
if the Games were held now, the Americans still would not be
anywhere near the podium.
</P>
<P>
   None of their top people _ Maloney, Atler, Jennie Thompson,
Elise Ray _ were ready to compete at the American Cup two weekends
ago. Karolyi needs a star to emerge, like Retton or Zmeskal or
Shannon Miller, and a team to build beneath her. ``You need a star,
period,'' he said. ``But you need a team to create the star.''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi will mold and motivate that team, but this time he will
not be the running-around rooster. ``I will not be on the floor,''
said the so-called coordinator. ``But I'm gonna be around the
floor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
