<SLUG> BC-SOC-ATLETICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLETICA IS NEW PRO SOCCER SPONSOR AS REEBOK EXITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It's a long way from Foxborough, Mass. to San Miguel el Alta,
Mexico, but the distance was no obstacle for the New England
Revolution and Major League Soccer in their off-season search for
corporate sponsorships to help finance the still-fledgling league.
</P>
<P>
   When Reebok International Ltd. of Stoughton signalled last year
that it would not renew its four-year sponsorship of the
professional soccer franchise in its own backyard _ in one of the
most robust soccer markets in the country _ the Revolution and MLS
realized they needed a new, aggressive corporate partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at the sales figures and the return that we were
producing on our investment over the four years, and it just wasn't
making sense,'' said John McCluskey, director of international
soccer promotions for Reebok.
</P>
<P>
   Exit Reebok, the troubled manufacturer of athletic shoes and
apparel that has spent three years revamping its approach to sports
marketing by shedding both athletes and teams as marketing
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Atletica, a new kid on the block in the United States. It
is establishing a beachhead in the lucrative American sporting
goods and apparel market by spending $800,000 to $1.2 million to
sponsor the Revolution and MLS for four years, according to league
officials and industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the idea of working with a new and aggressive company
that has really expanded dramatically into Latin American
markets,'' said Brian O'Donovan, chief operating officer of the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are about more than just bringing the MLS to Foxborough,
obviously. The Krafts have purposefully fashioned a role in soccer
internationally, and it makes sense for us to forge relationships
in these new markets, as well. It strengthens that role,''
O'Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Atletica, a 15-year-old Mexican company that employs about 2,500
people, signed a deal that allows it to feature the Atletica name
on Revolution jerseys and fieldboard signs, stadium announcements,
and radio, as well as a rotating spot for national commercial time
on ABC and ESPN broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to go to the American market because we find that
our products sell very well with those people in the US who follow
Latin American teams,'' said Diego Aceves, Atletica's director of
product development. The company supplies uniforms and equipment
for several national teams in Latin America and several teams in
the first division of the Mexican professional league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reputation throughout Latin America is that we really
cater to the needs of the players,'' Aceves said. ``We get many
inquiries for supporting new teams, but this is a first for us in
the US.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer was structured in 1995 to have three of the
major sports shoe and apparel companies, Nike, Adidas, and Reebok,
participating as sponsors of the league and individual teams. Under
the league's ``single-entity structure,'' MLS receives most of the
money, parceling some of it out to the individual franchises to
cover operating costs, although each of the sponsorships also
included smaller, ancillary deals with franchises.
</P>
<P>
   In the first four years of MLS's existence, Reebok's stock has
tumbled and sales of athletic shoes in the US market have declined
almost across the board. Last year, the sale of athletic shoes
dropped 3.8 percent in the United States, according to the Sporting
Goods Manufacturers Association, a trade group in North Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   However, the sale of soccer shoes last year actually increased
by 6 percent, to $155 million. Meanwhile, New England has long been
one of the hotter spots for soccer in the United States, driven by
the longstanding competition at the collegiate and high school
levels, as well as the wealth of interest in the internationally
popular game among immigrants from Europe, Latin America, and
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But Reebok failed to find enough support for its sponsorship of
Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reebok actually sold more Revolution merchandise than our
competitors who had other teams,'' McCluskey said. ``New England
was in first place because, obviously, they have a very high
attendance, considering the other teams. But, like all of our
competitors, we realized our loss in the first year was to be
expected. But when it continued into the second, third, and fourth
years, we just decided to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   McCluskey asserted that Reebok's commitment to soccer remains
strong, with its sponsorship of an international competition known
as the Reebok Cup. He also said the company would reconsider
sponsoring MLS if attendance and television viewership improves.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Phipps, MLS's executive vice president for corporate
sponsorships, said that despite Reebok's decision the league has
done well renewing sponsorships in what has been a crucial
off-season. Honda, Budweiser and Pepsi-Cola have all renewed,
Phipps said, and Aquafina, the New York Life Insurance Co., and
Lego have become new sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's been a good off-season for MLS,'' Phipps said.
``In the next 30 days, we'll be making announcements about several
new companies joining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
