<HEADER>
A9255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-ARROYO-2TAKES-ART     03-07 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ARROYO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ARROYO ON THE RIDE OF HIS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMAICA, N.Y. _ Max Hall is old school. Hard work. Attention to
detail. Even more hard work. Pull out the binoculars and watch
close-up every horse's step, to spot the lame, the improving, the
horse on the down cycle, the ones coming up to a peak. Then even
more work. Watch the tapes at night, slow-motion and rewind, to
spot what the binoculars missed.
</P>
<P>
   But Max Hall can adjust to the times. The new way. Cell phone in
pocket. Keeping in touch. Missing not a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream come true,'' Max Hall was saying the other
day. ``I mean, in so many ways, the boy is such a good rider, but
he is such a good person, too. I feel for him like he's my son.''
</P>
<P>
   The cell phone rings. ``Yes,'' Max Hall can be heard saying.
``Right . . . sure.'' Another trainer eager for Max Hall's ear,
another trainer desperate for Max Hall to say, ``Yes.'' Max's
``boy'' will ride that trainer's horse.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Max Hall was sitting in the racing secretary's office at
Aqueduct when all this was happening, the entries for races two
days away just having been drawn, Max Hall fending off this trainer
and that, all wanting Hall to put his ``boy'' on their horse.
Donald Trump could be handing out $10 bills on the apron at
Aqueduct and he might not be as popular as Max Hall is at this
moment.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the hottest apprentice jockey in America is his.
Norberto Arroyo Jr. is his name, he is 22 years old, and he is from
Medford and Somerville. Two years ago, Arroyo was selling sneakers
at the Foot Locker store at a mall in Cambridge, Mass. A few years
before that, ``I wanted to get into Suffolk Downs,'' said Arroyo,
``but they wouldn't let me in.''
</P>
<P>
   The cell phone rings again. Another trainer. Max Hall once again
listens politely, saying ``yes'' and ``sure'' but withholding the
final approval. Max Hall might know every racehorse in New England
but he still isn't sure about many of New York's horses. Old
school. Hard work. The tried-and-true way he has practiced for 30
years. Max Hall will go back that night to the apartment he and his
``boy'' share near Belmont Park, not far from here, and study more
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him on good horses,'' Max Hall said. ``He's such a good
rider that's all he deserves to be on _ good horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Without being asked, the man next to Hall volunteers his
opinion. ``He's a natural,'' Phil Johnson offered. ``He has that
natural instinct of a good rider. He can go a long way.'' Phil
Johnson? A great New York trainer for decades. In the racing Hall
of Fame at Saratoga. A man who knows his horses and his riders. ``I
put him on my horses right away,'' Johnson said, ``and I'll do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cell phone rings again. Yet another trainer. More polite talk
from Hall, and then this jockey's agent bares his soul, that he is
reborn, that his wife and children and two grandchildren with two
more grandchildren due April 15 are up in Boston, with Max taking
the shuttle back every Sunday to be with his family, but coming
back down to New York on Tuesday to follow the dream and his
``boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's best of all?'' said Hall, a grandfather as
excited as any 20-year-old about life's prospects. ``How this is so
good for New England. This just doesn't happen in New England, a
jockey like this coming out of New England and causing such a
storm. I just think it's great how this reflects back on New
England and how much attention it'll bring to New England racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Hall, after all, is as Boston as the Old North Church,
``Cheers,'' and the Freedom Trail. He has paid his dues at Suffolk
Downs and Rockingham Park. He never would have thought this could
happen. But it has.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Chris McCarron started his rise nearly three decades
ago has a Boston area jockey created such a fuss as Arroyo. And his
goal, and the goal of Hall's, is as simple as it is profound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win the Eclipse,'' said Arroyo. ``That's what I want
most of all. I want to win the Eclipse badly.''
</P>
<P>
   And Arroyo just may be capable of doing it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The protocol for meeting a jockey at Aqueduct is to go to the
jockey's room, ask the man in charge to page the jockey, then wait.
At Aqueduct, the man in charge of the room is Braulio Baeza,
himself in the Hall of Fame, a top jockey of the 1960s, the rider
of such great steeds as Buckpasser and Arts and Letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boy has a future,'' Baeza said. ``He is a very good
apprentice, but it seems he may have a future beyond that. He has
natural instincts and he is fearless. And he is aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for Arroyo to arrive, Baeza spoke of how he gives
pointers to the youth, of how he may spot something that Arroyo did
wrong in a race and then quietly point out the mistake to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is very good about him,'' said the Hall of Famer, ``is
that he doesn't make the same mistake twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo arrived wearing a New York Yankees hat, and when told
this was very bizarre garb for a Bostonian, he blurted out with a
wide smile, ``I have a whole bunch of Red Sox hats in my locker,
too.'' And he makes the point even sharper when he talks about
arguments in the jockeys' room over who is a better shortstop, the
Red Sox' Nomar Garciaparra or the Yankees' Derek Jeter, ``I shout
out, `Nomar! Nomar! Nomar is the best.' '' His personality is
bright and open.
</P>
<P>
   The first time on a horse?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 6,'' said Arroyo. ``We used to go out and ride
horses and the man told me to be careful. And when I got out away
from the man, we were riding under a tree and I reached up and
grabbed a branch and ripped it off and I whacked the horse. But I
stayed on the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   This was outside San Juan, but in 1989, when Arroyo was 11, his
father brought the family to the United States. His father,
Norberto Sr., had been a boxer in Puerto Rico (``My father sparred
with Roberto Duran, and my father was undefeated as a
professional'') and the youth followed his father's athletic
instincts, playing virtually every sport. Baseball was his love,
and he said he was the starting shortstop for three years for
Somerville (Mass.) High School, leading the team in hitting.
</P>
<P>
   But the young Arroyo still recalled how much he'd loved riding
horses back in Puerto Rico ``and I wanted to get on a horse here,''
he recalled. ``When I was about 15, I went to the track (Suffolk
Downs) but they wouldn't even let me in the track.'' His cousin,
Enrique Arroyo, was riding at Suffolk, ``and I told them I was
Enrique's cousin, but they still wouldn't let me in.''
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo kept on at Somerville High, and he would box and play
soccer as well as baseball, but the lure of the horses just
wouldn't leave him. In time, Suffolk trainer Al Borosh took to the
youth, ``and Mr. Borosh put me on a horse and I'd work in the barn
and walk the horses and do those things,'' said Arroyo.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing high school, Arroyo found himself managing the
Foot Locker outlet, but the company transferred him to a store in
Florida. ``And when I was in Florida,'' said Arroyo, ``I kept
thinking, `I really want to be a jockey; I really, really want to
be a jockey.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
