<HEADLINE>
NASD'S ZARB PLANNING FOR GLOBAL TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank Zarb is a busy guy.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the National Association of Securities Dealers
has to hustle just to keep up with the hyper pace of expansion of
its Nasdaq Stock Market, a system that now handles a mind-boggling
2 billion shares in a typical trading day.
</P>
<P>
   But Zarb also spends a lot of time fending off people who want a
piece of the action or others seeking to restructure the entire
market.
</P>
<P>
   The US Securities and Exchange Commission seems to want the NASD
to merge with the New York Stock Exchange and create one giant,
centralized market that is easier to police. Meanwhile, big
customers like Fidelity Investments are trying to chew into his
business with their own private electronic communications networks,
or ECNs, that trade stock ultraefficiently on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb, speaking on a panel at the Boston College economic
conference Monday, was asked point-blank about what happens to the
Nasdaq Stock Market amid all that uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the marketplace and regulators will insist on a
configuration of stock exchanges which do the best job for
investors and the marketplace,'' he said. ``I think we'll just have
to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   As you can imagine, no one is really waiting around for a memo
about their future.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD needs to make a compelling case why it should not be
merged and push a strategy to compete successfully against anyone,
including its customers. The point of attack: globalized stock
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb has launched joint ventures that will establish new Nasdaq
markets in Tokyo and London, known as Nasdaq Japan and Nasdaq
Europe. He said two other international Nasadaq markets were ``on
the drawing board.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea: create global, around-the-clock stock trading
platforms for investors and stocks anywhere. For starters, the 100
largest Nasdaq stocks will be available for 24-hour trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means more companies can invest in Microsoft and Intel
throughout the world,'' Zarb said. ``We're using pools of liquidity
outside the US to invest in our companies and that's got to be
good. We're also allowing our investors, you, to invest in that
Japanese company, that new IPO, when we're open and they're
closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The point about liquidity _ the ability to execute trades at any
time _ was no casual reference. As trading hours are extended into
America's evening and more ECNs get in the act, the ability to
endlessly match buyers with sellers to maintain an orderly market
and keep stock prices from jumbling around has emerged as a big
issue. Stretch markets too thin and that coveted liquidity could
begin to evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   By moving the trading platform around the world as it works
around the clock, Zarb argues, the Nasdaq markets are actually
improving liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion, however, has come with strings attached. The NASD has
needed partners to move into new parts of the world and share their
ownership. It teamed with Masayoshi Son's Softbank Corp. in Japan.
Nasdaq Europe counts Softbank, News Corp. and Vivendi SA as
partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means we have to share some of our revenues and we'll
only own a piece of those facilities,'' said Zarb.
</P>
<P>
   The NASD has been able to move into other parts of the world in
part by trading on its brand name. There isn't anything stopping
one of those private trading networks from doing the same thing,
but how many could really pull it off?
</P>
<P>
   So what about a push to merge the NASD with the NYSE?
</P>
<P>
   Though the plan appeals to regulators and some big market
players like Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
there are lots of details that make it a difficult deal.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zarb and NYSE president Richard Grasso must deal with
brokerage and specialist companies that don't want anything to do
with a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Goldman Sachs promote a merger of exchanges
because it would cut costs. But Zarb will tell you competition in
the stock exchange business is international and driven by
technology. He believes that plays to his NASD's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do it right we're going to continue to be a dominant
stock market in the US and the world,'' Zarb said. ``If we don't,
we'll lose and we'll deserve to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chalk up still another victory for the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week we told you that Sycamore Networks had moved past
Gillette Co. to become the Massachusetts company with the second
greatest market value. Sycamore, in case you don't know, is a
red-hot, but very small optical networking company that boasts a
market cap of $40.6 billion. Gillette's market cap is $37.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's stay in third place didn't last long. By the end of
Monday, CMGI, the Andover, Mass. Internet company, had also moved
past Gillette. CMGI's market cap is $41.1 billion. It goes without
saying that neither Sycamore nor CMGI were profitable in the most
recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
