u a BC-ECOM-WIRELESS-BOS &LR;      03-07 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-WIRELESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEZOS SEES HUGE FUTURE FOR WIRELESS E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ So you're sitting in the doctor's office leafing
through a magazine when finally you see the gift you have been
wanting to give your father-in-law for his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   You pull out your wireless phone _ but instead of calling
someone to place an order, you scroll down the little screen to
Amazon.com, and with a few keystrokes on the number pad find the
book you think he'll love, use your Amazon account to order it, and
have an e-mail sent to him to arrange delivery.
</P>
<P>
   As futuristic as that scenario may sound, some wireless
subscribers can already do that today. And Amazon.com founder and
chief executive Jeff Bezos, among many top industry executives who
met here this week for the Wireless 2000 convention, thinks cell
phones, or wireless devices including Palm Pilots and enhanced
digital pagers, could become a major way for people to do business
with his company and other e-commerce firms.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association officials cite
estimates that within five years 830 million wireless devices
around the world will be capable of connecting to the Internet _
not just phones and handheld devices but laptop computers equipped
with wireless modems.
</P>
<P>
   Said Michael Capellas, chief executive of Compaq: ``That's a
good number, but I suspect it's (actually) low.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the advantages for wireless e-commerce is that by
definition, the network can tell where people are _ if not just
which metropolitan area, potentially what city street they are on,
through emerging location technologies that chart a wireless
phone's distance from several towers to pinpoint where the user is
and chart it on a computerized map.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see that many people might find it a little creepy
to have a marketing-minded Big Brother following their every step
down the street, figuring out which store or restaurant to try to
steer them toward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine walking by a restaurant and getting a message
(translate ``advertisement'') offering you a lunch special, and it
just happens to be your favorite food at an irresistible price,''
said Jeffrey Kagan, an Atlanta telecommunications analyst. For
Net-enabled wireless devices: ``Push advertising is going to be a
hot trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. Zander, president of Sun Microsystems, which is making
a big push into wireless Net services, said he envisions a day when
``my device will know where I am, what I like to eat, and when I
last ate'' and send advertising messages accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos acknowledged that there will be a potentially steep
learning curve for all but the hardiest technology freaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cell phone is a device that people are in such a strong
habit of using one way, for voice. They have to have sufficient
value'' to persuade people to learn how to toggle around a
cell-phone screen to make purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, virtually all of the optimistic forecasts for wireless
e-commerce assume that the obvious drawbacks to cell phones _
spotty coverage in some areas, dropped calls, exorbitant airtime
charges _ will either go away or prove to be no serious obstacle to
attracting people to mobile e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   It also seems likely that some things will prove much easier to
sell over the phone. Books, CDs, airplane and Amtrak tickets, and
hotel reservations may be considerably easier to pitch wirelessly,
for example, than clothing or jewelry, for which seeing the product
first can be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   A poll taken for the cellular telecommunications group by Peter
D. Hart Research Associates of 812 US wireless subscribers found
that they seem considerably less interested in using the phone for
e-commerce than in getting reliable voice service.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the most important feature they would look for in a new
phone, 46 percent of respondents cited nationwide coverage and 31
percent a long-life battery, compared to only 9 percent citing
e-mail and Internet access. Twenty-five percent said they have a
great deal or quite a bit of interest in wireless data services,
compared to 44 percent expressing very little interest. Overall, 13
percent of wireless users said they want to use the phone to shop
over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers, however, do not discourage many industry
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the revenues we get from wireless are minimal,'' Bezos
said, adding: ``If you look far enough into the future I think
we'll be 100 percent'' wireless sales.
</P>
<P>
   If carriers successfully push to get a commission on sales
transacted over their units, ``that's a whole new revenue source
that will be a boon for the wireless industry,'' said Steven
Guggenheimer, Microsoft's director of consumer wireless products.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gent, chief executive of Vodafone Air Touch PLC, which
accounts for more than 10 percent of the world's wireless phone
subscribers, said his company sees large opportunities controlling
that revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be very happy to do deals with Yahoo and AOL,'' Gent
said, but ``we want to make sure we have control of the customer
interface. We have a high ground we don't want to give up'' and
will insist that ``the first icons people will see'' on their
wireless unit screens ``will be associated with our Internet
branding, not someone else's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-07 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... at Sorenga.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting around Europe is better than ever. This year Denmark and
Sweden will open a 10-mile Oresund crossing between Copenhagen and
Malmo on July 1, completing new rail and auto connections between
the Scandinavian peninsula and the bulk of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's high-speed ICE rail station is open at Frankfurt
Airport. Norway will begin operating high-speed trains from Oslo to
Stockholm and from Oslo to Bergen and Stavanger this year; a new
4.2-mile auto tunnel is open to the island of Mageroya and North
Cape. Athens' new subway lines began operating in late January and
work continues on a new airport.
</P>
<P>
   Europe remains the fastest-growing destination for Americans who
cruise, and these include many making their first trip to Europe.
Scandinavia, and the Mediterranean, Adriatic, and Aegean welcome
new ships this year. River cruises on the Rhine, Danube, Elbe, and
Rhone remain very popular, as do barge cruises through the canals
of France, England, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Most cruise passengers fly to Europe to board ships and usually
can choose from a variety of pre- and post-cruise land packages.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Elizabeth II will again offer regular trans-Atlantic
service and gives passengers a choice of flying one way and sailing
(six days) the other. Some sailings will be from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, Europe designates one city to be its Cultural
Capital. But this year, the 15-nation European Union is designating
nine cities as Cultural Capitals for 2000. It is both the first
time more than one city and cities beyond the EU have been named.
They are:
</P>
<P>
   --Avignon, France: famous for its Mozart-loving summer festival.
In April, an exhibition called ``Beauty'' will be at the Palace of
the Popes.
</P>
<P>
   --Bologna, Italy: among Europe's oldest university cities and
famous for its food. A ``Masters at the End of the Millennium''
dance festival will be held yearlong.
</P>
<P>
   --Brussels: capital of Belgium and the EU, and rich in art and
cuisine. A ``Grand Carrousel'' equestrian spectacle will be in
June; Grand'Place will be carpeted in flowers in August.
</P>
<P>
   --Helsinki, Finland: leader in design, architecture, and music.
Culinary concerts will be held throughout the summer, and designer
shows will be held throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   --Santiago de Compostela: city of Spain's patron saint and a
historic pilgrimage site. Exhibitions include ``Faces of Earth''
and ``Faces of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Non-ECU cities participating are:
</P>
<P>
   --Bergen: gateway to Norway's fiord country. An International
Dance Festival will be held this month, and the Bergen Music
Festival in May.
</P>
<P>
   --Krakow: city of Polish kings and bishops. Avant-Garde Theater
will take place in March; ``Ballet Spring'' and Wawel Castle
exhibit in May.
</P>
<P>
   --Reykjavik: marking the 1,000th anniversary of Iceland's
Christianization and celebrating artists of every description.
</P>
<P>
   And if that's not enough, consider too that Cyprus will host the
Miss Universe pageant May 12-13; European Cup finals are June
10-July 12 in Belgium and Holland; the Tall Ships will race from
Britain to Italy, Spain, and across the Atlantic from April to May,
and in the Baltic, July to August.
</P>
<P>
   It's definitely no year to miss Europe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IF YOU GO &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The European Travel Commission offers a number of ways to save
on a trip to Europe:
</P>
<P>
   The commission suggests planning ahead and using a knowledgeable
travel agent to help find the best deals on air fares,
accommodations, and packages.
</P>
<P>
   Internet research is helpful, the ETC says, but agents speed the
shopping process with their access to reservation systems and
industry contacts, and can quickly explain the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   Other tips:
</P>
<P>
   --Buy as much of the trip as possible before leaving the United
States. Consider vacation packages, which can save time and money,
and which offer a great variety of destinations. Packages range
from basic fly-drive-hotel combinations for independent travelers
to fully escorted group tours to cruises.
</P>
<P>
   --Stop at a city's tourist offices for the latest information on
events, discounts, and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   --Use public transportation. Subways and buses are generally
clean, safe, and reliable. Paris, London, Berlin, Munich, Vienna,
Budapest, Lisbon, Helsinki, Oslo, Stockholm, and other cities offer
discount travel cards that also often include admission to museums
and other attractions as well as discounts for dining and shopping.
</P>
<P>
   --Take trains between cities: Rail Europe offers many varieties
of the 17-country Eurailpass, as well as five-country Europasses,
regional passes, and national passes (including BritRail passes).
These can all provide savings. Call 1-800-324-RAIL. Rail Europe
also takes reservations for high-speed premier trains, including
the Eurostar trains through the Channel Tunnel. Call 800-EUROSTAR.
</P>
<P>
   --Car rentals are always less costly if reserved in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   --Consider traveling beyond major capitals where prices are
always lower.
</P>
<P>
   --Use charge cards instead of cash whenever possible to obtain
good exchange rates (be aware, however, that some cards are now
charging a 2 to 3 percent surcharge on purchase overseas). Also use
automatic teller machines for cash; they can be found almost
everywhere. Before leaving home, check with your issuer to ensure
that your PIN will work in Europe (most machines only accept
four-digit numbers). When exchanging dollars and traveler's checks
go to banks or exchange bureaus rather than hotels.
</P>
<P>
   --When calling home, use a service such as the AT&AMP;T Direct
Service in Europe. There is a local AT&AMP;T access number for
virtually every country in Europe. Also beware of hotel surcharges
to call home, even with the AT&AMP;T service. Check with the hotel as
to its telephone policy.
</P>
<P>
   --Eat where the locals eat, and look for fixed-price tourist
menus when dining out.
</P>
<P>
   -- Look for VAT (Value Added Tax) forms when shopping. Foreign
visitors can usually get refunds on VAT, which can run as high as
25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: The euro came into effect in 1999. But, although it is
legal tender in 11 European Union nations, local currency _ francs,
marks, lira, etc. _ will continue to be used for all paper money
transactions until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The European Travel Commission has annually produced an
informative booklet on travel overseas. This year, however, this
information is available only on the Internet at
www.visitEurope.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
