<HEADLINE>
SOME STORES ARE WEB HOLDOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus, Macy's, Bloomingdale's, Nordstrom. These are just
a few of the department stores that have rushed online to sell wine
glasses, chenille blankets, and designer clothing.
</P>
<P>
   So where are Lord &AMP; Taylor, Filene's, Hecht's, and the other
chains owned by May Department Stores Co., the nation's number two
department store operator?
</P>
<P>
   Firmly on the ground, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its rivals, May dares to go Internet-free. But it is not
the only Web holdout. Many big businesses retailers have avoided or
delayed chasing after online shoppers for a hodgepodge of reasons,
including the following:
</P>
<P>
   --There's no big rush. Although Internet-only retailers
disagree, big chains such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc. believe they can
catch up and dominate Web sales after late starts.
</P>
<P>
   --Shoppers aren't ready. Some categories, such as luxury goods
and hardware, are still maturing online. That's why home
improvement retailers and jewelers have been slower to move online.
</P>
<P>
   --Channel conflicts continue. Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. tried to claim
the Web for itself, barring retailers like J.C. Penney Co. Inc.
from selling its denims. It didn't work. Home Depot Inc.'s warning
letters to manufacturers have been more effective.
</P>
<P>
   --The Net does not work for everyone. Rolex and other makers of
expensive jewelry like to tightly control retail channels to keep
their prices high and their products exclusive. It's more difficult
to micromanage the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As for May, its motive for avoiding the Web is unclear. Some
industry observers speculate that its individual chains are too
regional to make online forays worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   May spokeswoman Rhonda West said the retailer was indeed selling
products on the Internet: electronic gift cards. As for offering
other merchandise online, she said: ``I'm not sure I can respond to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other old-line businesses are beginning to make compromises. In
a customer survey, Michaels Stores Inc. discovered its consumers
weren't overwhelmingly interested in buying arts and crafts
materials on the Web. So the retailer announced last week that it
will strike a balance, offering mainly an informational site that
will gradually add items for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crafting community is not seriously interested in
purchasing online,'' said Cynthia Gould, a company spokeswoman.
``They want how-to's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
