<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-AMERICAN-BEAUTY-EURO-     03-07 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-BEAUTY-EURO-LATAM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY `AMERICAN BEAUTY' IS SO FASCINATING OUTSIDE THE USA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, N.J. _ Millions of people outside the USA suppose
that life in the suburbs is similar to the portrayal in ``American
Beauty'' _ in other words, a paradise of spacious homes surrounded
by green gardens, whatever the season, and indoors a hell of
domestic hatred and frustrated dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's something like that. At times reality is worse than
fiction; at times, better. I've lived for 10 years in an East Coast
suburb and still don't understand a lot of the lifestyle. Once in a
while, on weekends, I meet with ``friends'' from Rutgers
University, and it's rare that we agree on anything.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, one of them mentioned ``Picture Windows,'' a book by
Rosalyn Baxandall and Elizabeth Even, two American culture teachers
in Connecticut. In its preface, the authors confess an initial
bias: ``... We didn't think we could unearth a story in the
suburbs. We thought the suburbs produced an anaesthetized mindset;
they were a non-place ruled by conformity and consumerism.''
</P>
<P>
   The suburbs are much more than that, but human beings do tend to
simplify reality and give too much credence to first impressions.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago an Italian journalist visited me in Highland
Park. We strolled through this town of 1,200 residents which has 10
synagogues, six churches of various denominations and a Catholic
temple.
</P>
<P>
   She was surprised that on Main Street, among the travel
agencies, drugstores and pizzerias were nine luxury salons whose
only business was manicures, not to mention six or seven
barbershops, each with its own manicurist. And how busy they all
were. Some customers were willing to wait several hours.
</P>
<P>
   At noon we stopped for a hamburger in a fast-food restaurant.
The girl who waited on us had outrageous nails, two inches long and
decorated with arabesques in three different colors. She moved her
fingers with the dexterity of a spider. More than once, when she
was wrapping the hamburgers, I expected those nails to drop off.
</P>
<P>
   At the tables, several fat couples devoured deep-fried onion
rings and sizzling chicken wings coated with flour and grease. Most
of the diners were overweight, and that was also true of many
people in the street when we took a walk after lunch.
</P>
<P>
   I saw several neighbors, some of whom greeted me politely. My
friend asked how we had met and I told her their children went to
the same school as my daughter, and many friendships in the town
were born in meetings at school or church.
</P>
<P>
   Some days later when I read her story, I was surprised that
those few bare facts had been enough to create a full scenography:
``The suburb of the United States,'' she wrote, ``is similar to
those in the Hollywood movies. Sedentary life and fast food are
creating an overweight population of lonely people who spend their
time letting their nails grow and painting them extravagantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was a kernel of truth in this oversimplification, but
actually any half truth tends to create more false impressions than
an outright lie. If the Italian journalist had stayed longer, we'd
have strolled through the town's two parks, where people run or jog
or power-walk from 7 a.m., till nightfall, year-'round. It's almost
impossible to see an overweight person there.
</P>
<P>
   In big cities, sports are often done for an aesthetic goal: The
body is something that is shown to others. In the suburbs, exercise
is done for health reasons: The body must be kept in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Another essential difference is the meeting places. The city,
all of it, is a place of encounters, a virtual square. In the
suburbs, people have to search for each other because residential
neighborhoods have no social center and people drive cars wherever
they go. Moviehouses with 20 theaters or shopping malls or churches
or even bank drive-in lanes are the substitute places for life in
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   This, in turn, sets limits to human relations: to meet, people
make dates. Chance is almost absolutely excluded from day-to-day
life.
</P>
<P>
   The American suburb was born around 1908, when pockets of
affluent families moved from Manhattan to Long Island because they
felt their original neighborhoods were being overrun by poor
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But, as it turned out, life in the suburbs was cheaper and less
socially demanding than in the cities, so the immigrants and the
poor also ended up there. Today almost no suburb lacks a belt of
African-Americans or Hispanics living and growing by its side _ and
providing services to the great houses of the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Life in the suburbs is cheaper and safer, but infinitely more
monotonous. By 10 p.m., there's nothing to do. Not even a
restaurant is open; maybe a few bars close as late as 1 a.m. This
monotony leaves gaps in the imagination. Couples devoured by
boredom dream of a better life, and of an unconventional love life.
Any breakdown of the routine becomes an attractive alternative to
trivial reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' the movie, does have an edge in that it
discovers so many truths hidden by outward appearance.
</P>
<P>
   An even more pathetic byproduct of this lifestyle is the fate of
the old men and women who decide to seek shelter in the many
suburban residential clinics and care centers for the aged. At 9
a.m. they are picked up by a municipal bus. It drives a few blocks
to any of several supermarkets, where the old people walk the
aisles in search of an apple, a box of cookies, maybe a tomato _
not because of hunger or lack of money, but because it's something
to do. At 11 a.m., after stops at the post office and the
drugstore, they return to their rocking chairs and bingo games.
</P>
<P>
   Happiness is hard to find anywhere, but in the American suburb
it's a daily miracle. ``American Beauty'' shows that such a miracle
is, almost always, a mirage, an impossible goal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
