neighborhoods have no social center and people drive cars wherever
they go. Moviehouses with 20 theaters or shopping malls or churches
or even bank drive-in lanes are the substitute places for life in
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   This, in turn, sets limits to human relations: to meet, people
make dates. Chance is almost absolutely excluded from day-to-day
life.
</P>
<P>
   The American suburb was born around 1908, when pockets of
affluent families moved from Manhattan to Long Island because they
felt their original neighborhoods were being overrun by poor
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But, as it turned out, life in the suburbs was cheaper and less
socially demanding than in the cities, so the immigrants and the
poor also ended up there. Today almost no suburb lacks a belt of
African-Americans or Hispanics living and growing by its side _ and
providing services to the great houses of the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Life in the suburbs is cheaper and safer, but infinitely more
monotonous. By 10 p.m., there's nothing to do. Not even a
restaurant is open; maybe a few bars close as late as 1 a.m. This
monotony leaves gaps in the imagination. Couples devoured by
boredom dream of a better life, and of an unconventional love life.
Any breakdown of the routine becomes an attractive alternative to
trivial reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' the movie, does have an edge in that it
discovers so many truths hidden by outward appearance.
</P>
<P>
   An even more pathetic byproduct of this lifestyle is the fate of
the old men and women who decide to seek shelter in the many
suburban residential clinics and care centers for the aged. At 9
a.m. they are picked up by a municipal bus. It drives a few blocks
to any of several supermarkets, where the old people walk the
aisles in search of an apple, a box of cookies, maybe a tomato _
not because of hunger or lack of money, but because it's something
to do. At 11 a.m., after stops at the post office and the
drugstore, they return to their rocking chairs and bingo games.
</P>
<P>
   Happiness is hard to find anywhere, but in the American suburb
it's a daily miracle. ``American Beauty'' shows that such a miracle
is, almost always, a mirage, an impossible goal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
