u f BC-VALLEY-MECEDA-BOS &LR;      03-07 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-MECEDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-THE-EDGE ENTREPRENEUR THRIVES ON RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WOODSIDE, Calif. _ In Silicon Valley, where failure is worn
like a badge of courage, Ann Meceda is a shining example of
success.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, she is already on her third start-up, having been chief
executive of one, executive vice president of new media for
another, and now executive vice president of business development
at a third Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no signs of fatigue, Meceda agreed to sit down for
dinner recently to discuss what it feels like to be part of a new
generation of hard-charging, risk-defying, and nomadic
entrepreneurs flooding the Valley with wave after wave of Internet
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like the concept of starting with nothing and creating
something out of it,'' said Meceda, looking relaxed and composed in
her gray sweater and indigo jeans as she nibbled on a chicken
sandwich at Buck's, an eclectic diner that over the years has
become the de facto breakfast hangout for Silicon Valley venture
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   The rugged journey for Meceda began in 1997, six months before
she was to graduate from the Haas School of Business at the
University of California at Berkeley. Meceda and a group of fellow
classmates launched a start-up called Private Communications Corp.
as a project for a class on entrepreneurship. PCC was built around
the concept of an ``anonymous, disposable telephone number'' that
could be used by online dating services to let people extend their
online chats over the phone without having to disclose their real
phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In May, just weeks before graduating, Meceda became the
company's CEO, knowing that the business could just as easily burst
into flames as catch on like wildfire. Her decision to forgo a job
in Paris with a global entertainment company to head a risky
start-up became the subject of a 1998 Harvard Business School case
study.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months after she took the job, PCC ran out of money, despite
having raised $324,000 in capital, and Meceda moved on. She jumped
to another start-up, HLH Entertainment, a music production company
in San Francisco, as chief financial officer and then executive
vice president of new media. Folks at HLH didn't bat an eyelash
over her experience at a failed start-up.
</P>
<P>
   The high-tech start-up business is like baseball, according to
Randy Komisar, a veteran Silicon Valley entrepreneur who helped
found Claris Corp. among other companies. One can ``fail 70 percent
of the time and still be considered a success,'' Komisar wrote in
his upcoming book, ``The Monk and the Riddle,'' which is being
published in May by the Harvard Business School Press. ``The Valley
recognizes that failure is an unavoidable part of the search for
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Meceda, the daughter of two entrepreneurs, seems unfazed by past
adversity or the possibility of sudden failure in the future. She
is now involved in an Internet start-up that is currently in
``stealth mode,'' a Silicon Valley tactic that calls for absolute
secrecy about the company's business plan in order to prevent
copycats during the crucial ramp-up phase. The wraps come off in
April. By then, her company would have created a comfortable head
start over its rivals, Meceda says. Until then, she is not even
allowed to reveal her company's name.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she is a millionaire yet, Meceda laughed and said
no. After a moment's thought, however, she changed her answer.
``Maybe,'' said Meceda, who explained that her equity in HLH might
be worth $1 million, depending on how well the company did in its
last round of financing. ``I'm just not sure,'' she said with a
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Meceda noted that some of her peers talk about ``being done,''
accumulating enough wealth to be able to pursue other interests.
``It's about achieving a sense of financial freedom, to have a
choice as opposed to having money for money's sake,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   But Meceda doesn't look forward to ``being done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have an endpoint,'' Meceda said. ``As long as
people keep coming up with ideas, I've got a job.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
