<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES ASK FOR HELP TO END STUDENT BIDDING WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid an escalating bargaining war that has colleges wooing
students with financial aid packages that include summer jobs and
trips to Europe, a growing number of college administrators want
the federal government to reverse a decade-old ban on tuition
``price fixing.''
</P>
<P>
   The colleges want the federal government to allow them to return
to a system under which they could all agree on how much financial
aid to offer needy students, preventing the current free-for-all in
which colleges try to outbid one another. In 1991, the Justice
Department charged 11 trend-setting colleges that shared this
information with violating antitrust laws, ultimately forcing them
to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current free market, schools now use more and more aid
to attract top-notch, wealthier students with merit awards or
tuition discounts, leaving less aid available for needier students.
And colleges are paying for the discounts they offer the more
attractive students by targeting other groups of applicants to pay
full fare, which now reaches beyond $30,000 a year at many schools.
Those who get hurt, administrators say, are the poorer or
middle-income students who don't have some special talent to set
them apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone agrees that there's got to be a better way; this
unbridled, winner-take-all effort is extremely expensive, not only
for the institutions, but for the consumer, whose interest the
federal government was supposedly aiming at,'' said Joseph Russo,
director of financial aid at Notre Dame. ``Where do these price
discounts get funded? They get funded by tuition. Who pays tuition?
People pay tuition, and they're borrowing like never before.''
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting last month in Dallas, several prominent college
administrators called for the federal government to come up with a
new policy that would allow cooperation on financial aid packages _
exempting the schools from antitrust laws. They later repeated that
call in Washington before a Senate hearing on the increasing cost
of tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Those watching the debate say it will heat up in the next year,
as two things happen. First, the consent decree under which the
schools agreed to stop conferring on aid will expire. Second, the
legislation that currently limits cooperation is up for renewal,
which opens it to tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried about the corruption of the essential
charitable mission,'' said Gordon Winston, director of the Williams
College Project on the Economics of Higher Education, who spoke at
the session in Dallas. ``These guys with their car dealership
mentality _ slash and burn, give them a year-end discount and sink
them _ they're forgetting entirely what we're about.''
</P>
<P>
   Many colleges warned a decade ago that this would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1950s, about two dozen colleges known as the
Overlap Group had met at the Wellesley Club each spring to agree on
how much financial aid to offer the students they had accepted in
common. That way, when it came time to choose which college to go
to, each student would get the same package from all schools.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed that aid would be based on need, and everyone
used the same definition of need. The general idea, the schools
argued, was that there was only so much money to go around, and
that schools should use it wisely and charitably.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, however, didn't see it as charity, but
as price fixing, and in 1991, entered a consent decree with the Ivy
League colleges under which they agreed to stop sharing any
information. Only the Massachusetts Institute of Technology fought
the government, and, after winning one round on appeal, also
settled with a similar agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, the federal government changed its
definition of financial need, so that, for instance, a family did
not have to include home equity above $150,000 when figuring how
much it could afford to contribute to the cost of tuition.
</P>
<P>
   With this and the end of Overlap, there was no common definition
of need. Schools began using aid packages as a way to go after
students they really wanted. Duke, for example, famously lured a
significant number of top-ranked black students away from Harvard
in 1994 with the prospect of travel and summer jobs. Such perks are
no longer rare, and it is even more common for students to try to
use one school's offer to entice another school into giving a
better discount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overlap served the very real purpose of letting us behave as
charities in a way that made sense,'' Winston said. ``We were not
squandering our charitable resources on people who were haggling
and bidding for the best deal they could get. And we are making
haggling more successful by allowing them to do it. The next-door
neighbor of the family that just got $10,000 knocked off the price
sees that and says, `But I make less money than he does. What about
me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wary of looking like they are buying students, many schools
insist that they offer ``need-based financial aid.'' But the
different definitions of need mean that the students they offer aid
to aren't always those who might generally be thought of as
``needy.'' As one college president said, ``Need is, if I need a
quarterback, I give financial aid to a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of directors of financial aid, many schools now
employ ``enrollment managers'' to decide what percentage of
wealthy, full-price students they need to enroll to allow them to
give aid to top-notch students, who may or may not be needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle isn't between the schools and the applicants,
it's between the poor applicants and the wealthy applicants and the
deserving but non-needy applicants,'' said Thane Scott, a lawyer at
Palmer and Dodge who represented MIT in its case against the
Justice Department. ``If I were not a spectacular cellist, but a
pretty good student and poor, these would not be good times. The
very wealthy will always have a place to go, the very talented poor
will always have a place to go. But the middle is facing increasing
problems. We're not just talking the middle quartile, it's by far
most people going to most schools.''
</P>
<P>
   College officials say they doubt anyone would want to return to
the Overlap system the way it existed. Once it was exposed and
called ``price fixing,'' colleges were shamed by it.
</P>
<P>
   What they suggest is that colleges could agree to certain
principles and practices. That would begin with a recommitment to
award financial aid according to need, but also include agreement
on how to determine need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, the federal government would make clear that schools
could enter into enforceable agreements on how they measure the
ability of families to pay for college,'' said Michael McPherson,
the president of Macalester College, who has written extensively on
financial aid and testified at the Senate hearing. ``The system
would become more transparent, it would be clearer when schools
were trying to attract students with particular qualities, and
provide an easier playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   But for schools to be willing to share information, officials
said, Congress would have to pass a law explicitly exempting the
practice from antitrust laws. A statute passed in 1997 allows
schools that are entirely need-blind in their admissions _ meaning
they do not consider a student's ability to pay in deciding whom to
accept _ to share information with other institutions. Only a very
few schools, Harvard and MIT among them, are completely need-blind.
</P>
<P>
   That law is set to expire at the end of September 2001, which
has many administrators calling for Congress to revise and extend
it to include schools that are mostly need-blind in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   But that presumes that colleges would agree to the limits. And
not everyone agrees the old system was best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trustees as well as anyone who understands the free market
says, `Hey, lookit, if we put our money down, we get to set the
rules,' '' said William Elliott, vice president for enrollment at
Carnegie Mellon University, which spends between 75 and 80 percent
of its aid budget on merit aid, up from 25 or 30 percent 10 years
ago. ``In the long run, people ought to be spending their money to
improve their academic position. In the past 10 years, we
absolutely have gotten better quality of students.''
</P>
<P>
   And to some small schools, it's simply self-serving that the
bigger and richer schools would be asking to stop the competition,
a point some at the larger schools concede.
</P>
<P>
   Still, David Breneman, dean of the School of Education at the
University of Virginia, who spoke in Dallas, said that even
agreement among the top schools to limit their competition would
restore some fairness to the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are perfectly understandable economic reasons why we're
never going to recapture some notion of everyone doing this on pure
need,'' he said. ``But when the very top group is not able to keep
the competition in check, there's no hope for the rest of us. The
30 or 40 top schools have a symbolic stance. What they do filters
down so dramatically in public perception. And people do feel
there's something that's been lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
