<HEADLINE>
THE SELF-DESTRUCTION OF BILL BRADLEY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors...NOTE 200-word trim)   (UPDATED, RESENT from March 3)  
  
 (This excellent 850-word article is from the current (week
beginning 4 March 2000) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 650 WORDS; TOTAL UNCUT IS 850.)  
  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE AND SPOKANE _ A month ago Bill Bradley came within four
percentage points of beating a sitting vice president in the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 29 he trailed behind Al Gore in another stronghold of
independent voting and campaign-finance reform, Washington state,
by a humiliating 37 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington primary is an eccentric affair: a ``nonbinding
beauty contest'' that does not do anything so pedestrian as
allocate delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's decision to spend six consecutive days campaigning
there _ against the advice of his staff and leading supporters,
such as New York's retiring senator, Daniel Patrick Moynihan _ not
only reduced the amount of time he could spend campaigning in the
bigger states that went to the polls on March 7. It turned what
should have been a minor contest into a major test of virility.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of Democratic Party elders are urging Bradley
to end his agony and pull out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to broadcast a five-minute-long appeal to voters on
CBS last Thursday night (appropriately at the same time that most
viewers tune into ``ER'' on NBC) suggested that he would remain in
the race, albeit as a spent force, until Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Why did this former basketball star and Senate veteran turn out
to be such a dismal candidate?
</P>
<P>
   Not because of lack of money. Bradley, a darling of Wall Street,
had more cash on hand than Al Gore after the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Not because of lack of infrastructure. The Bradley campaign
spent a small fortune in Washington state on television advertising
(including ads questioning Gore's environmental record). Every day
it sends a torrent of e-mails and faxes to anyone who has ever
expressed a polite interest in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And not because of a lack of ideas. Bradley courageously tried
to make health care an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Many people think that Bradley was simply mugged. A less
honorable man might have been quicker to respond to Gore's
truth-twisting attacks on his health-care policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was also partly a victim of his party's electoral
timetable, which left a month between New Hampshire and the next
Democratic primary. That period has given the vice president a
chance to armor-plate his lead, while the media have focused
exclusively on the helter-skelter of Republican races.
</P>
<P>
   But an even bigger problem for Bradley is the fact that his
style is so boring.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Whitelaw, a British Tory grandee, once accused Labor
activists of going around the country ``stirring up apathy.'' That
has often seemed to be the essence of Bradley's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He is such a laconic speaker that one wonders whether the
candidate or the audience will fall asleep first. And he is such a
self-involved figure that he is incapable of connecting with his
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The omens were bad last year when he gave a speech in Los
Angeles lamenting the growing divide between blacks and whites. The
audience, many of whom were Hispanic or Asian, looked on in
bemusement.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago he attended one of those churches where everybody
claps their hands and sways their bodies. The impassive Bradley
could have been attending a Senate hearing on U.S.-Icelandic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck with a group of sympathetic reporters in New Hampshire, he
would not even say what book he was reading, for fear of opening
up.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's failings have been rendered all the more transparent
by John McCain's successes.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley mumbles that Al Gore is not entirely honest,
McCain promises to beat the vice president like a drum on the
campaign-finance question; while Bradley bows the knee to Al
Sharpton in New York, McCain taunts the religious right for being a
bunch of bigots.
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly surprising that floating voters should flock to the
charismatic arsonist rather than the dithering professor. Bradley
is an insurgent who failed to insurge. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 650, OR CONTINUE TO 850) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   In general, Bradley's failing campaign has left Gore in a
remarkably strong position. Gore has proved that he can survive a
challenge by a well-funded and well-respected rival.
</P>
<P>
   He has survived it without leaving too many hostages to fortune
(forcing senior army officers to support gays serving openly in the
armed forces being an exception). And the Democratic machine is
solidly behind Bill Clinton's protege.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a few doubts remain. The fact that Bradley, a man whose ear
for politics now seems so tinny, could come so close to toppling
the vice president in New Hampshire suggests considerable
discontent about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And, whatever else, the two Republicans have both been through a
ruthless examination.
</P>
<P>
   Under fire from McCain, Bush distanced himself from the bigotry
of Bob Jones University; Gore has failed to condemn the bigotry of
his campaign manager, Donna Brazile, who denounced ``white-boy
attitudes'' as a synonym for ``I must exclude, denigrate and leave
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore may yet come to regret Bradley's disdain for street
fighting almost as much as Dollar Bill's supporters currently do. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
