<HEADER>
A9346 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-2TAKES-     03-07 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAZZLING ARRAY OF EVENTS IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there was a year to visit Europe, this is it! Europe is
welcoming the 21st century with some great happenings _ a world's
fair with a vision of the future, a mammoth picnic, a towering
Ferris wheel over London, a once-in-a-decade Passion play, and
more.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is still the number one destination for Americans seeking
heritage, culture, architecture, museums, grand sights from ancient
castles to soaring mountains, and glorious food. This year's
celebrations, from the Jubilee Year in Rome to thousand-year
anniversaries, only add to the reasons to pack your bags and head
across the Atlantic for, perhaps, some once-in-a-lifetime memories.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with such a festive menu is deciding when to go
to join in the celebrations Europe has planned. All this means the
Europeans are expecting more Americans than ever. The number of
Americans with the means to go (adults in households with incomes
of $60,000 plus, according to the ETC) has doubled over the past 10
years to more than 60 million, and at least 25 percent of the
projected 12 million-plus US citizens heading to Europe will be
going for the first time, according to Einar Gustavsson of Iceland,
US chairman of the 29-nation European Travel Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Making the journey a bit easier is that the dollar is strong and
air fares are attractive, according to the European Travel
Commission. The ETC says the dollar is buying 19 percent more in
euros and other European currencies than it did when the euro was
inaugurated in January 1999, and with airlines adding more
trans-Atlantic flights and seats, competitive pressures are there
to fill seats and hold down fares.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve, London unveiled a vast Millennium Dome filled
with 14 stunning exhibitions ranging from an enormous see-through
human body to millennial looks at communications, recreation,
spirituality, etc. Artist David Hockney and designer Sir Cameron
Mackintosh are among those who developed the projects. Performances
are held in the dome and the nearby Baby Dome.
</P>
<P>
   A little farther up the Thames is the London Eye, a
450-foot-tall Ferris wheel that at any one time will carry nearly
1,000 passengers high above the river and the Houses of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Also for the Millennium, London has opened a new Tate Gallery of
Modern Art and a new Millennium Bridge. Other projects include
major new science and environmental centers elsewhere in England
and in Scotland and Wales.
</P>
<P>
   France plans two unique Millennium Year events open to all: On
June 21, the first day of summer will be greeted by PeripheRock, a
grand music fest set up on the wide peripherique highway circling
Paris. The road will be closed to traffic, transformed into a huge
nightclub with wired stages, and taken over by scores of rock
bands, music groups, and the public. There will be additional
performances in the capital's major squares and in cities
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Bastille Day, July 14, more than 3 million people are
expected to take part in The Incredible Picnic, to take place on
scores of sites stretching 620 miles along the Meridieine Verte
between Dunkirk and the Pyrenees. In Paris alone, mile-long picnic
tables will be set up at the Louvre, in Montmartre and on an Orly
Airport runway. Open to all, each site will offer local
specialties. Baton relays will meet at the meridian midpoint and an
armada of aircraft will buzz the entire line between 2 and 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Emperor Charles V, was the man of the 16th century, and now on
the 500th anniversary of his birth, four of the countries he ruled
will hold special exhibits and celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Ghent's Prinzenhof in 1500 and brought up in Belgium,
Charles V inherited vast empires, including those of Spain,
Austria, and the Low Countries. A central figure of the 16th
century, he led the opposition to Martin Luther in Germany, fought
France for control of Italy, halted the relentless Ottoman advance
at Lepanto, and expanded Spain's new world holdings before
abdicating in Brussels in 1555 and retiring to a monastery in
Spain's Sierra de Gredos.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, Ghent will exhibit 19th-century renderings of
Charles's career; in Mechelen there will be an exhibit of
tapestries of Charles (May 26-Oct. 8) and other exhibits will be
held in Leuven, Antwerp, and Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Spain will hold the ``Art and the Kings of Spain'' exhibition in
Barcelona through May, and related exhibitions will be held in
LaCoruna and Granada April through June.
</P>
<P>
   On July 4 and 6, Brussels holds its annual Ommegang pageant in
the Grand'Place, re-creating Charles's spectacular procession of
1549. Madrid will follow suit with its own Ommegang procession on
July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Germany will certainly be taking center stage for many events
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hannover 2000, the first World Expo of the new millennium and
the first ever in Germany, runs July 1 through October. Planned as
a celebration of ``Humankind-Nature-Technology,'' it will provide a
395-acre platform for nearly 200 nations and international
organizations to explore global solutions to 21st-century
challenges. Thematic areas will delve into the past and future of
humankind, work, health, communications, the environment, and more.
A Planet of Vision will take visitors into utopian worlds. A
nonstop performing arts schedule _ from Faust to the Scorpions _ is
planned, as are nightly fireworks and laser shows.
</P>
<P>
   If you miss the Passion play in Oberammergau, Germany, this
year, you'll have to wait 10 years for the next performances. After
a 17th-century plague, the villagers of the Bavarian town of
Oberammergau vowed that if saved they would perform the ``Passion
of Christ'' every 10 years. The villagers have kept their promise
and this year present a millennium version of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Another significant event will be the celebration of
Guttenberg's 600th birthday in Mainz, where he introduced printing
with movable type, which led directly to huge advances in
communications and education.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, Pope John Paul II has inaugurated the Golden Jubilee
Year, inviting Christians everywhere to make a pilgrimage to the
Eternal City and to the dazzlingly refurbished St. Peter's
Basilica. Jubilee events are planned for every week of the year,
peaking with World Youth Day (Aug. 15-20), which could draw more
than 2 million young people.
</P>
<P>
   The city has responded by restoring monuments from the Colosseum
to Nero's Golden Palace and creating a great archeological park to
link the ancient Roman forums. A number of museums have opened,
including the Palazzo Massimo, the Palazzo Barberini, and the
galleries of the Villa Borghese. Brand new are the minimalist
Church of the New Millennium and the monumental, horseshoe-shaped
Citta della Musica, an amphitheater and series of concert halls.
</P>
<P>
   Other important anniversaries:
</P>
<P>
   --One thousand years of the Hungarian Crown (March 15-31).
Exhibitions in Budapest and other cities celebrate the Crown of St.
Stephen, who introduced Christianity as king of the new Magyar
state.
</P>
<P>
   --The 1,000th anniversary of Leif Ericsson's ``discovery'' of
North America on a voyage from Iceland: A replica Viking ship will
retrace his probable route this summer.
</P>
<P>
   --The 200th anniversary of the Rijksmuseum, founded by Louis
Napoleon Bonaparte. Amsterdam celebrates this great collection,
which includes Rembrandt's ``Night Watch,'' with a year of special
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   --The 250th anniversary of the death of Johann Sebastian Bach in
Leipzig, Germany (March 8-April 15 and July 21-30).
</P>
<P>
   The 500th anniversary of the discovery of Brazil. Lisbon and all
Portugal celebrate the navigator Pedro Alvares Cabral and the
country's unique relationship with the sprawling South American
nation.
</P>
<P>
   --Oslo's 1,000th year. The Norwegian capital celebrates with a
special edition of the famous Holenkollen Ski Festival (now through
March 12) and with St. Hallvard's Day parades (May 13-17) followed
by a special sound-and-light show at the ruins of the original
settlement at Sorenga.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRISH-PUBS-BOS &LR;      03-07 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-PUBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH TRADITIONALISTS WON'T BUTT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ As sure of it as anything in this world, Liam Craven
crossed his arms, closed his eyes and announced, as if it was a
solemn oath, ``It'll never happen in Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not talking about Ireland becoming a rich country. That's
happened, its economy the fastest-growing in Europe for a decade.
He was not talking about the Roman Catholic Church losing its
dominant role in Irish life. That's happened, too. And he was not
talking about Ireland having a female president. It's already had
two.
</P>
<P>
   What Craven insists will never happen is a ban on smoking in
Irish pubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people would revolt,'' said Craven, a bartender at
O'Neill's pub near Trinity College.
</P>
<P>
   But a government committee recommended just such a ban last
November, and the Irish government is considering it.
</P>
<P>
   And while Craven is convinced that the Irish people will never
tolerate a world in which they are not allowed to enjoy a smoke at
their local, his boss is not so sure. Declan Mannion thinks it is
only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   No-smoking sections are already common in restaurants, and
smoking was banned on buses a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people, especially, are much more health conscious than
my parents' generation,'' said Mannion, 30, who manages O'Neill's.
</P>
<P>
   He sees a smoking ban as part of the inexorable change in
Ireland, and Dublin in particular, over the last 10 years. Fueled
by an economy that has made this nation of just 3.6 million second
only to the United States in producing computer software, Ireland
has grown prosperous and more European.
</P>
<P>
   Tall cranes dot Dublin's skyline, and jobs are so plentiful that
for the first time in history the English are coming here for jobs,
not the other way around. In a country that since the potato blight
of 1845 sent a diaspora of 70 million abroad, tens of thousands of
economic refugees from everywhere now want to come here. Mannion
bought his house less than two years ago for about $100,000; it has
almost doubled in value since.
</P>
<P>
   But the traditional Irish pub is something ingrained deeply in
the Celtic consciousness, a place where pints of beer and
cigarettes seemed inextricably linked to conversation. It was in a
smoky pub in Dublin that Flann O'Brien once told Patrick Kavanagh
he was merely a minor poet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Homer, we all are,'' Kavanagh replied through the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   But the traditional pubs are being gradually pushed aside by
super-pubs, two or three times the size of older ones, and
European-style cafes that are adorned with polished marble instead
of dark wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pubs are the last bastion of what Ireland used to be,'' said
Mannion, pulling a pint of Guinness. ``A cigarette and pint go hand
in hand. People have always accepted that when you went to a pub;
smoke was part of the scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not for much longer.
</P>
<P>
   While Mannion and others think a smoking ban is inevitable,
others say it would be disastrous. Tadg O'Sullivan, chief executive
of the Vintners Federation of Ireland, said many pubs would go out
of business.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a pub in Galway became the first to try a ban.
The owner reversed his decision in less than a month after business
dropped precipitously.
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan's group wants to introduce a voluntary system like in
Britain. Under the plan, publicans would display a notice outside
indicating if they had air conditioning or a no-smoking section.
</P>
<P>
   Some pubs like O'Neill's are big enough and architecturally
designed so that they could create non-smoking sections. But at the
Dawson Lounge, a single-room basement pub just off St. Stephen's
Green, they don't have the luxury. Nor do many smaller pubs in the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the Dawson, a foursome of friends all laughed when
asked if they thought a smoking ban was feasible. All four were
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Mullingar, and a pub there tried a non-smoking
section,'' said John Reilly, 23. ``It lasted two weeks. Nobody took
it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smyth, 32, from Galway, nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as a group of Irish people going to the
pub that doesn't include a smoker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure they eat at restaurants that ban smoking, said Suzanne
Stewart, 26. ``Not a bother.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``A pub's different.''
</P>
<P>
   While smokers think a ban is unthinkable and downright un-Irish,
a growing number of people say they would not lament the demise of
smoky pubs, however cozy the images they conjure up.
</P>
<P>
   Dermot Brangan, an Irish diplomat, sheepishly confesses that he
does not spend much time in pubs because of the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get in and out quick,'' he said. ``I'm seldom in a pub
after 8 o'clock, because it just gets too smoky for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In Limerick, Ireland's third-largest city, taxi driver Pat
O'Connor said he cannot imagine a ban on smoking, and believes it
would be unenforceable. He sees a ban as an unfair curb on personal
liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a social smoker,'' he said. ``I'll have one with a pint.
Watching the races at the pub, I might have 10 or 20. I detest
smoking in a restaurant. In a pub it's different. It's a
traditional way to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   But traditions are falling hard and fast in modern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   In McDaid's, on Dublin's Harry Street, where the playwright
Brendan Behan once held court, Martin Bourke pulled hard on a
filterless cigarette, which he called an indispensible
accompaniment to his pint of Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary thing altogether that they're even
talking about banning smoking in pubs,'' Bourke said. ``I mean, for
Jayzuz sake, this is Ireland still.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Behan, a great raconteur and smoker who drank himself
to death in 1964 at the age of 41, would say if he were alive
today, Bourke exhaled a long plume of smoke, took a quick lash of
the black stuff, and, after some thought, said, ``Brendan would
say, `How the (expletive) did I live this long?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
