<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9350 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CALIF-POLL-VAULT-ECON     03-07 1625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLL-VAULT-ECONOMIST-RESEND-625&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA DREAMIN': WHO'LL WIN ELECTORAL GOLD RUSH TUESDAY?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for March 7...NOTE 2 trims, totaling 600; 1,325 uncut)   (UPDATED, RESENT from March 3)  
  
 (This excellent article is from the current (week beginning 4 March
2000) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS 2 HELPFUL OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 600 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS
1,325.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As goes California, so goes the nation. Or so
Californians like to claim. Only three times in the past century
has a candidate won the presidential election without winning in
California.
</P>
<P>
   In November, with Florida and Texas likely to be solidly
Republican, California seems a particularly crucial piece of the
electoral map.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republican nominee can win it, he will be practically
home and dry. Unless the Democrat holds on to it, he will have
little hope. For the Democrats, the Californian primary on March 7
looks likely to be Al Gore's coronation.
</P>
<P>
   A few months back, Bill Bradley's prospects in the state had
looked promising. In financial terms, he raised more than Gore in
Silicon Valley; Hollywood also seemed to be leaning in the former
senator's direction.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore now has both organization and momentum on his side. The
vice president has visited the state more than 60 times while in
office and he is supported by nearly all the state's leading
Democrats, including the governor, both senators, and the mayors of
San Francisco and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   His environmental enthusiasm and his interest in technology are
popular with Northern Californians, and the attention he gives to
education scores him points with Southern Californians fed up with
the Los Angeles Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times poll on March 1 showed him beating Bill
Bradley by 54 percent to 11 percent among registered Democrats in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   For California's Republicans, the choice between George W. Bush
and John McCain looks much more trickier. That is partly because of
the state of the national race.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush once again regained the initiative when he
trounced McCain not only in Virginia, where he was expected to win,
but also in Washington state. Even a few hours before the polls
closed in Washington, McCain's camp was claiming that Bush was a
purely Southern candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The McCainites seemed to have the wind behind them. Nobody who
went to McCain's rally at Bremerton, just outside Seattle, where
thousands of people chanted his name over the strains of the
``Rocky'' soundtrack, believed he could ever lose. But he did, by
20 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   However, even if the national race were not so fratricidal,
California's Republicans would still find the choice between Bush
and McCain peculiarly awkward. They see themselves as the
intellectual arsenal of their party's conservative battalions.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan and the tax-cutting proposition movement both
emerged from Southern California. Around 40 percent of the state's
Republicans consider themselves to be part of the Christian right.
Even the so-called ``Southern strategy,'' focusing on white
conservatives, was, some say, concocted in the paleo-conservative
swamps of Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Californian Republicans are now more
aware than most that this strategy has run its course. In 1998, Dan
Lungren lost the race to succeed his fellow Republican, Pete
Wilson, in the governorship to a Democrat, Gray Davis, by 20
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos, once a promising constituency for the Republicans, are
still furious about Wilson's own version of the Southern strategy,
embracing the anti-immigrant Proposition 187 in 1994.
Asian-Americans also seem to have defected.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley types who would otherwise be natural Republicans
fume about the party's position on some moral issues, notably
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   California's Republicans have discovered the danger of looking
old, white and intolerant in a state that is getting younger and
browner by the day. Non-Latino whites will soon become a minority
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans account for only 35 percent of the registered
Californian electorate _ around ten percentage points less than the
Democrats _ which makes them even more dependent on the growing
number of independent voters. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 125 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 625) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush at first seemed the dream candidate for the Californian
Republicans: a conservative with new ideas. In early 1999, a
delegation of Sacramento Republicans wrote to the Texan governor
asking him to stand for the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was a conservative who had won the trust of Latino voters
in Texas; he had tackled education, the top Californian issue, so
successfully that the state had sent several delegations to Texas
to study its approach to schools; and he looked a winner.
</P>
<P>
   That reasoning has been thrown into turmoil by two things. The
first is Bush's drift to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a South Carolina university that forbids interracial
dating was hardly likely to win Bush broad popularity in
California, where miscegenation is something of a state sport. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The opinion polls now suggest that Gore would beat Bush in
California; but he would lose to McCain. The other thing is that
McCain has made the Republicans seem hip again. After falling for a
decade, the party's membership has surged.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bernd Schwieren of the Republican Assembly Caucus
in Sacramento, 21,000 new Republicans registered in the month
ending on Feb. 7. The party had lost 600,000 since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Even more pleasingly, the Democratic registration tally fell by
93,000. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 850, OR CONTINUE TO 1,325 WORDS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   The way in which the primary will be conducted on March 7 seems
almost designed to play on the strains within the state's
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   All voters will be able to vote for any candidate, regardless of
party, by marking a single card on which they all appear. The two
main parties, however, will allocate their delegates on the basis
of only the votes of their registered members.
</P>
<P>
   There will thus be two results: an internal party one, and a
beauty contest that ranks all the candidates by their total number
of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush looks likely to win the internal race (he leads by 20
percentage points in the polls). In the absolute count, however, he
is only slightly in front of McCain (with a lead of two to six
points) and still around six points behind Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Bush might win all his party's delegates
but finish third in the popular vote may increase if many of the
independents and Democrats who had been leaning towards Bradley
defect to McCain, as they have done in other primaries.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that McCain, particularly in his strident remarks about
the party's fundamentalist wing, is already concentrating on coming
top in the everybody-can-vote count.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of both candidates claiming that they ``won
California'' has the makings of a Republican nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   But there could be yet another agony in store. The current
two-count system is an awkward compromise between California's
voters, who have twice voted for propositions requiring open
primaries, and the parties, which have passed rules trying to close
them.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tony Quinn, a Republican demographic analyst, the
legal stitching on this piece of political patchwork is weak: you
can amend an initiative only with another initiative.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain wins the beauty contest, he might take his challenge
to the courts. Such a clash would do little for the bid by
California's Republicans to reclaim a position at the front of
their party.
</P>
<P>
   That, coupled with the fact that California is already far more
multi-ethnic than most states will be in even 50 years' time, is
starting to make some people say that the state can no longer hope
to march at the head of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   That still seems wrong. First, the sheer weight of numbers
(California's population of 34 million today is projected to grow
to 50 million by 2030) is bound to make this a state with clout.
</P>
<P>
   And, second, the basic political question in California _ how to
attract suburbanite voters who are mostly conservative on fiscal
issues but liberal on issues like abortion _ is the same question
that politicians everywhere in America are facing.
</P>
<P>
   Alas for them, it is a question to which the Republicans have
yet to come up with a clear answer. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: This material from The New York Times Syndicate is
for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, call
1-888-269-8796.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
