u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-07 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG YEAR WITHOUT BIG PRICE HIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Steves, who has been writing guidebooks to Europe and
providing lively television programs on his visits there via public
television, has found that visiting in this millennium year will
not be costly.
</P>
<P>
   Steves, in updating his guidebooks, found that prices in hotels
are essentially the same as last year. ``Hoteliers are worried that
all the hype about crowds will scare away many travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheap air fares are now commonplace as travelers are flying
between major European cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe has never been more prepared for tourists. The sights
are spiffed up and the scaffolding is down; Europe is a can-can of
architectural treats. Extra tourist information kiosks are
scattered throughout the most popular towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no better time to explore Europe's back roads and
hidden towns. As EU regulations take hold, some of Europe's
old-time character will end up in the folk museums _ the victim of
modern building codes.''
</P>
<P>
   Steves is also offering a free guide to European railpasses. For
a copy, write to Rick Steves, Box 2009, Edmonds, WA 98020; call
425-771-8303, fax 425-771-0833, or visit www.ricksteves.com/rail.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the government has set up a toll-free cultural
information line to help tourists during the 2000 Jubilee
celebration. The number, 800.99.11.99 (not reachable in the United
States), will be available through 2001. Also available is
www.coinsociale, a Web site with information on handicap-accessible
museums, hotels, restaurants, and sites. For those seeking
information on the Jubilee, the Web site www.piuitalia2000 has a
wide range of information in seven languages.
</P>
<P>
   For those thinking of visiting Italy, Central Holidays
(800-935-5000) is offering five nights in first-class hotels
throughout Italy with breakfasts and, in most cases, dinner,
beginning at $350 a person. The deal is good July 1-Aug. 26.
Between March 27-June 30 and Aug. 27-Oct. 3, the rate is $465.
</P>
<P>
   Alitalia is offering a package to Rome or Florence beginning at
$869 from Boston for April 7 through May 31. The package includes
air fare, hotels, breakfasts, and a tour.
</P>
<P>
   Select Italy makes touring some historic places easy. The firm
provides advance reservations to visit museums and to the first
showing of the Shroud of Turin in two years Aug. 26-Oct. 22. For
information, call 847-853-1661 or visit www.selectitaly.com.
</P>
<P>
   Westin Hotels have not only a greater presence in Europe this
year but also have added some very historic properties. Now
carrying the Westin brand are Hotel Bristol in Vienna, the
Excelsior in Florence, the Palace in Milan, Excelsior in Rome,
Europa &AMP; Regina and the Excelsior in Venice, the Palace in Madrid,
and the Hotel Maria Cristina in San Sebastian. These hotels join
some already famous Westin hotels in Europe such as the Turnbury
Golf Course and Spa in Scotland and the Trianon Palace in
Versailles, France.
</P>
<P>
   The London White Card, a discount admission pass to many of the
city's attractions, offers an inexpensive way to tour the city. The
card, now called GoSee/The London White Card, is available at $25
for three days; family and longer passes are also available. The
card can be purchased at information centers in London. Its Web
site, www.london-gosee.com, offers upcoming events.
</P>
<P>
   An inexpensive and interesting way to visit Europe is through
Untours, a Pennsylvania travel company that places travelers in
private homes or apartments in villages and cities on the
continent. From there, visits both nearby and by rail can easily be
arranged. Untours has a representative in the area where visitors
stay to help with arrangements. For information, call 888-868-6871.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 10 years since Avis launched Know Before You Go, a
service that provides lots of information to car renters before
leaving home, as well as toll-free telephone information for 38
nations while in Europe. And now the service has been retooled with
even more help. Know Before You Go callers can also request a
Michelin map for Italy, France, Britain, or Germany. Those
interested in the program should first reserve a car by calling
800-331-1084, then with the Avis confirmation number handy, call
800-297-4447. Travel agents have details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATA to Chicago
</P>
<P>
   ATA (American Trans Air) will begin nonstop service between
Boston and Chicago's Midway Airport May 7. Three flights daily
(except Saturday) will be offered. Direct, same-plane service will
also be offered between Boston and Dallas/ Fort Worth, Denver, and
Seattle. To introduce the service, ATA will offer fares to Midway
beginning at $79 each way for travel May 7-June 30. Tickets must be
purchased by March 31. From Boston, other introductory fares
include Dallas, $99/$109; Denver, Las Vegas, Seattle, and San
Francisco, $119/$149. Fares are one-way and are for off-peak and
peak periods. For information, call 800-1 FLY ATA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
