<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9355 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      03-07 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OASIS' FEE FI HUM-DRUM OR, THEY MIGHT HAVE BEEN GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Oasis released their fourth album of new material,
``Standing on the Shoulder of Giants.'' It dropped in stores rather
quietly, free of the fanfare garnered by the latest Smashing
Pumpkins effort, ``Machina/The Machines of God,'' or ``Two Against
Nature,'' the first album in more than a decade from '70s stalwarts
Steely Dan.
</P>
<P>
   Is that any way to treat the greatest rock band in the world?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago when Noel Gallagher _ songwriter and
lead guitarist who, along with his lead-singer brother Liam, form
Oasis's heart and soul _ proclaimed, ``If it was 1965, we'd
absolutely be pop kings of the world. It would've been the Beatles,
the Stones, Oasis, and then the Who.''
</P>
<P>
   Never one for false modesty (or, for that matter, any other
kind), Gallagher had been heralding his band's greatness since
1994's ``Definitely Maybe'' became the best-selling debut album in
their native England. Although the reception here was more maybe
than definitely, there was something so cocksure about Noel's
melodies and Liam's snarly singing that one had to prick up their
ears. Just to hear Liam spit out the line, ``I was looking for some
ack-she-UN'' like a curse and a challenge on ``Cigarettes and
Alcohol'' was worth the CD's price.
</P>
<P>
   Their sophomore release, ``(What's the Story) Morning Glory?''
had the kind of stateside success that gave Gallagher's
straight-faced pronouncements of world domination some real juice.
It was one of the best albums of 1995 (and arguably, the decade,)
with hit singles ``Wonderwall,'' ``Don't Look Back in Anger,'' and
``Champagne Supernova.''
</P>
<P>
   Their critics called them as derivative as a Beatles cover band,
but there were millions who fell for their accessible and at times
gorgeous melodies and punchy guitars. At a time when the rock-star
lament of ``We hate it when we become successful'' had become
tiresome, there was something refreshing in the Gallagher brothers'
dedication to excess. They fought like Cain and Abel (or Ray and
Dave Davies of the Kinks), drank too much, and did too many drugs.
They kept the British tabloids fat and happy, traumatized hotel
managers and flight attendants, and gave the kind of candid
interviews that give publicists ulcers. (Liam calling George
Harrison a ``(bleepin') nipple'' _ the Queen's slang for an idiot _
after the former Beatle referred to him as ``silly'' was classic.)
They completely understood that rock stars might be a lot of
things, but whiny malcontents all bollixed up about fame wasn't one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ripe moment when Oasis could have owned the world. It
was before the boy bands, pop tarts, and rock-rap mooks came in and
started running things. Kurt Cobain was a year dead, Eddie Vedder
had ridden his self-righteousness into irrelevance, and grunge was
fading as fast as an old flannel shirt. The door was open just wide
enough for someone to slip in, grab the spolight, and shake things
up.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened to Oasis on their way to rock
immortality. They started to believe their own hype. Believing they
were already the best, they stopped striving for something
incredible and indelible. They forgot that a big part of being the
greatest band in the world is making great records.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, their hotly anticipated third outing, ``Be Here Now''
tripped commercially and critically. They kept making headlines _
marriages, drunken stupidity, babies _ but they stopped making
interesting music. More recently, group turmoil led to the
departure of two original members, guitarist Paul Arthurs and
bassist Paul McGuigan, and Oasis, never a rock of stability, almost
broke up.
</P>
<P>
   So now comes their latest, ``Standing on the Shoulder of
Giants'' _ not exactly greeted with a ho-hum, but far from the
hosannas one might have expected from a group that believed it was
the '90s answer to the Fab Four. It's not as good as ``Morning
Glory,'' but not as misguided as ``Be Here Now.'' All the Beatles
references are there, and the melodies are pleasantly catchy, even
if Noel still can't write lyrics as smart and engaging as
Morrissey, Bono, or his hero, John Lennon.
</P>
<P>
   Already a hit in England, the CD, led by the single, ``Go Let It
Out!'' will probably do OK here, but it won't set the world on
fire. Sadder but wiser, perhaps the brothers Gallagher will have to
be content with standing on the shoulder of giants, although they
should have been giants themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
