<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY-ANALYSIS (Austin, Texas) _ Presidential frontrunners
George W. Bush and Al Gore look beyond today's Super Tuesday
primaries while underdogs John McCain and Bill Bradley look for
upsets. We check exit polls to see what they portend for the
candidates in the general election. By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-JUDGES (Washington) _ The Senate begins debate on the
controversial nomination of U.S. District Judge Richard Paez to the
U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals, ending a record-breaking
four-year wait by the California jurist. Conservative Republicans
had blocked a vote on Paez since 1996, contenting he was too
liberal. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ While the nation is preoccupied with
choosing the next president, the current one is keeping busy. Bill
Clinton hasn't turned out to be a liability after all and is even
making some legislative progress with the Republican Congress,
which does not want to be labeled do-nothing. On Wednesday Clinton
makes a major speech touting expanded trade with China, which will
be one of the biggest fights this year on Capitol Hill. He may not
win it, but it won't be for lack of trying. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
