</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE UNFATHOMABLE TRAGEDY OF MOZAMBIQUE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the worst floods in living memory continue to swirl, parts of
South Africa, Zimbabwe and especially Mozambique desperately need
help to prevent the death toll from escalating. The floods have
pushed back into poverty large numbers of Mozambicans who had
recently begun to lift themselves out of it. And just as bad, the
flooding has almost certainly dislodged thousands of landmines and
carried them into places previously considered safe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 100-word optional trim; 1,000 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MISERY-MOZAMBIQUE-ECONOMIST-750&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SAD GYPSIES OF SLOVAKIA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mikulas Dzurkinda, the Slovak prime minister, winces when asked
what he thinks of Austrian right-winger Joerg Haider. ``I'm certain
Austria will stay democratic. But demagogues are frightening.
Imagine the trouble they could cause if they got hold of our Gypsy
question.'' Indeed, if the politics of hate were to make a comeback
in lands to the east of the present EU, Gypsies would be prime
targets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-GYPSIES-HAIDERISM-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLICK OPERATOR: PHOTO MOGUL GETTY TOPS GATES'S CORBIS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's the clash of the titans. Both young moguls, both cornering
the world market in photo archives, both now based in Seattle: Mark
Getty, grandson of oil magnate J.P. Getty, and Bill Gates, who
needs no introduction whatsoever. This week, with its 14th large
acquisition in five years, Getty Images increased its photo library
holdings to around 70 million images. That tops its main
competitor, Gates's Corbis, which has 65 million images. As Getty
says, ``Intellectual property is the oil of the 21st century.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 300-word trim at 600; 1,025 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MOGUL-MARK-GETTY-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE INTERNET IS RUNNING OUT OF ADDRESSES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, naming your start-up can be more arduous than
financing it. This is because most Internet addresses, known as
domain names, have been taken already. In the .com domain, the most
desirable online real estate, almost every recognizable name has
been claimed. Much is at state. If the name space of the Internet
cannot grow, e-commerce will suffer. &QL;
</P>
