<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9364 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS &LR;      03-07 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER DRUG SHOWS PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No test of a cancer drug has been so closely watched, and seldom
has one been shrouded in such secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are indications that endostatin, the
tumor-starving substance discovered in the lab of Dr. Judah Folkman
in Boston, appears to be safe _ at least so far _ and may be
halting cancers in some of the desperately sick patients enrolled
in its first human trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone takes it as encouraging that there hasn't been much
progressive disease'' among the cancer patients who are the first
humans to receive treatment with endostatin, said Dr. James Thomas
of the University of Wisconsin in Madison, one of three centers
testing the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very well tolerated,'' Thomas said in an interview.
``There's been no drug-related toxicity. People are doing fairly
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas spoke last week during a meeting at the National Cancer
Institute in Bethesda, Md., where researchers from the three
centers conducting the endostatin trials, which began late last
year, exchanged information.
</P>
<P>
   One topic under discussion was whether, and when, to enroll more
patients to further test the dose that the current trials are
showing to be the most effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not accrue any more patients at this time, but will
wait for the other two centers to catch up'' and complete their
quota of 15 patients each before adding more volunteers, said Dr.
Donald Kufe, who heads the trial at Dana-Farber Cancer Care.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin, viewed as a potential breakthrough in cancer
treatment, is being given to volunteers in Boston at the
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and three Boston hospitals, and at the
M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston, as well as at the
University of Wisconsin. About 100 patients are scheduled to
receive endostatin in the Phase 1, or safety phase, of the clinical
trial, which is required in bringing any new drug to market. It is
intended to reveal any toxic effects of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Endostatin is a protein discovered in Folkman's laboratory at
Children's Hospital. It is one of the strongest of dozens of
``angiogenesis inhibitors'' _ compounds that block the growth of
new blood vessels _ whose existence was proposed by Folkman decades
ago. Endostatin has dramatically shrunk many kinds of cancers in
mice with no side effects, but hasn't been tried in humans until
now.
</P>
<P>
   EntreMed Inc. in Rockville, Md., is developing endostatin as a
drug, with the trade name simply Endostatin with a capital ``E.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last October, about 33 patients have received daily
infusions of endostatin: 15 of them in Boston, 9 in Wisconsin and 9
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The first public reports on the Phase I trials may come at a May
meeting of the American Society for Clinical Oncology.
</P>
<P>
   The positive buzz is one element cited in the soaring stock
price of EntreMed Inc., the company that developed Endostatin.
Shares rose to over $100 last week, up from 25 5/8 on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer patients and relatives, the medical community, and
biotech investors are eager for any tidbits about the trial's
progress that can be gleaned, but there has been precious little.
``We've really worked hard to quiet'' any unauthorized reports
about the trial ``to give the poor drug a chance,'' said Folkman in
a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   At least two on-line services have electronic bulletin boards
where investors share tips and speculate and argue about the
EntreMed trials. The participants scrutinize every public
appearance by Folkman, every word written in the press about
Endostatin, and every rumor in hopes of divining something about
what's going on behind the closed doors of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   One patient involved in the trials has spoken publicly. Chuck
Killian, who has metastatic colon cancer drives every day from his
home outside Chicago to the University of Wisconsin to receive an
infusion of Endostatin into a tube in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Killian, an insurance executive diagnosed with colon cancer in
1998, said in a telephone interview that he feels better and more
energetic, and that pain in his liver, where the cancer had spread,
has almost disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers emphasize that such anecdotal reports are
meaningless by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One way of gauging the trial's progress is noting how many
patients drop out: the rules require them to discontinue endostatin
if their tumors grow by more than 50 percent. The patients are
going through the trials in groups of three, each group getting an
increased dose of endostatin.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune reported last week that at as the doses have
increased in the Boston trial, fewer patients have been dropping
out. Dr. James Pluda, a National Cancer Institute official, said
that the report was essentially accurate. This could be interpreted
to mean that higher doses of endostatin are having greater
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   However, a spokesman at Dana-Farber declined to confirm or deny
the report, and a spokeswoman at EntreMed had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of endostatin in the trials is viewed as a
crucial test of Folkman's belief that the non-toxic, angiogenesis
inhibitors, used in combination with other treatments, could open a
new era of cancer control and even prevention. Folkman, however,
emphasizes that the best role for endostatin and other inhibitors
may take years to determine, and that probably most will be used in
combination with more conventional therapies, like chemotherapy and
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   He also believes that angiogenesis inhibitors in the body, like
endostatin, are perpetually keeping many tumors small by not
allowing them to switch on the growth of blood vessels from nearby
tissues. So the inhibitors may eventually serve as long-term cancer
preventives, he says.
</P>
<P>
   EntreMed has licensed the endostatin rights from Children's
Hospital, and also is developing another potent anti-angiogenesis
drug, angiostatin, that was found in Folkman's lab. The Food and
Drug Administration recently gave EntreMed the go-ahead to begin
human tests of angiostatin and also of yet another angiogenesis
drug, known as 2ME2.
</P>
<P>
   Children's receives licensing fees from the company but Folkman
does not benefit personally, nor does he own EntreMed stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
