</P>
<P>
   RAIL-MERGERS (Washington) _ Surface Transportation Board begins
four days of hearings on railroad mergers and the future structure
of the industry in light of the proposed combination of Burlington
Northern Santa Fe and Canadian National. By Anthony De Palma.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Dow was sharply lower in mid-afternoon.
At 1:30 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was down more than
300 points, led by Procter &AMP; Gamble, which accounts for more than
half of the Dow's decline. The Nasdaq composite index, in contrast,
was up 41 points.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-GERMANY (Frankfurt) _ Horst Kohler, president of the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, is the German
government's new candidate to run the International Monetary Fund.
By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ECOMMERCE (London) _ Looking at Britain's new push into
the e-economy, as competition to offer cheaper Internet service
heats up, the government auctions the next generation of wireless
licenses and Tony Blair urges further deregulation of European
telecommunications markets to encourage Internet use. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-MARKET (Singapore) _ A crisis paralyzes the Manila
Stock Exchange as the entire compliance department quits to protest
what it calls lax prosecution of trading irregularities. Securities
regulators suspend trading on the exchange, but its president vows
to reopen as usual Wednesday. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   RENAULT-SAMSUNG (Seoul) _ Renault's offer to buy 70 percent of
Samsung Group's bankrupt car-making unit for $50 million in cash at
first and $400 million out of the venture's future earnings gets a
chilly reception from Samsung creditors. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties'' and Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings.''
</P>
