<P>
   (th)
</P>
<P>
   THIS ADVISORY WAS TRANSMITTED TUESDAY, MARCH 7
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Here are the week's top offerings from The New York
Times Syndicate. To publish any of these ``separate-buy'' feature
articles, they must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-798-0970; fax,
310-798-7338.)
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------- ------ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (moved in ``e'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   A QUIZ FOR THE ALSO-RANS ON OSCAR NIGHT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-NIGHT-MOVIE-QUIZ-STARBEAT _ For every Oscar winner there
are four nominees who go home empty-handed, four people who come in
as winners and go out as losers. Just in time for Oscar night on
March 26, Greenfield, Ind.-based free-lance writer S. Burelison
delivers an engaging quiz on the Oscar also-rans. By S. Burelison.
</P>
<P>
   THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING ERIN: ROBERTS TAKES A DRAMATIC TURN
</P>
<P>
   JULIA-ROBERTS-IN-ERIN-BROCKOVICH-STARBEAT _ Her last three
movies were romantic comedies, and they collectively grossed nearly
$400 million at the box office. But Julia Roberts goes for
something different in ``Erin Brockovich,'' her latest film:
Opening nationwide on March 17, it's a strong, based-on-fact legal
drama about a community's struggle against toxic pollution. By
Cindy Pearlman. (With color photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CROSSOVER KING: THE UNLIKELY TRIUMPH OF RICKY MARTIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-RICKY-MARTIN-STARBEAT _ Ricky Martin has come a long way
in a short time _ only a few years back, he was best known as the
singing bartender Miguel on ``General Hospital.'' But since his
memorable rendition of ``The Cup of Life'' at the 1998 Grammy
Awards, Martin has been the world's most popular male singer. By
Kevin Dickson. (With color photo.)
</P>
<P>
   DEVON SAWA, THE LAST BIG THING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEVON-SAWA-IN-FINAL-DESTINATION-STARBEAT _ Devon Sawa knows all
about the Hollywood star-making machine. Only three years ago, as
his film ``Wild America'' was in the works, Sawa was touted far and
wide as the Next Big Thing. But then the movie flopped, and he
found himself on the edge of oblivion. Now he's back, however, with
the lead role in ``Final Destination,'' a highly praised, eerie
thriller opening March 17. By Ian Spelling. (With color photo.)
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-BEAUTY-EURO-LATAM-NYTSF _ Millions of people outside
the USA suppose that life in the suburbs is similar to the
portrayal in ``American Beauty'' _ in other words, a paradise of
spacious homes surrounded by green gardens, whatever the season,
and indoors a hell of domestic hatred and frustrated dreams.
Happiness is hard to find anywhere, and maybe it's true that in the
American suburb it's a daily miracle. ``American Beauty'' sets out
to show that such a miracle is, almost always, a mirage, an
impossible goal. By Tomas Eloy Martinez. (Also moved in ``k'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (moved in the ``k'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WE CAN THANK PINOCHET FOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-ETHICS-CASE-NYTSF _ For many in Chile, Pinochet is the
personification of evil: The man with the dark glasses is as bad as
they come. Yet for a large minority of the population, he remains
the savior of a nation threatened by heathen communism and
inflationary socialism. It is good for Chileans to have realized
this split of opinion, and for others to grasp that dealing with
the past is a very complicated matter, and that easy solutions, as
brisk and painless as they may seem, generally do not work. We can
thank Pinochet for this, but for nothing else. By JORGE G.
CASTANEDA.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET'S VICTIMS WILL NEVER STOP SEEING HIM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-MENTAL-LESSONS-NYTSF _ So Pinochet has had his last
glimpse of London, but his victims will keep on seeing him,
endlessly. For Pinochet, the world was still divided into the
Marxists and the Christians, a notion that presupposed the
inevitability of a war between them. For Pinochet, this was a
matter of life and death, and anything goes. You don't merely
defeat the enemy: You destroy him. The only way to deal with an
enemy of such magnitude is extermination: concentration camps,
slavery, torture. By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET WITHOUT HATRED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALLENDE-ON-PINOCHET-NYTSF _ I feel no hatred for Pinochet.
Hatred is a very heavy burden, one I shook off many years ago, when
I started writing. Writing has allowed me to exorcise most of my
demons and transform my pain into strength. I would like to see
Pinochet face a trial, so that the truth about his crimes is fully
exposed. But I wouldn't want the general to rot in prison, as so
many of his victims did. I merely wish that in the winter of his
life the general would ask forgiveness of all those whose lives he
destroyed, the families of the dead and disappeared, the exiled and
tortured; that he would reveal where the bodies of his victims can
be found. By ISABEL ALLENDE.
</P>
<P>
   WHY DOES THE MEDIA TREAT THIS POLLSTER LIKE A GOD?
</P>
<P>
   CULT-OF-ZOGBY-SLATE _ A little-known independent pollster based
in Utica, N.Y., John Zogby rocketed to fame by correctly predicting
the results of the 1996 presidential election. Like all religions,
the cult of Zogby relies on myths about his feats and denial about
his failures. Meanwhile, pundits, reporters and chat show hosts now
routinely genuflect to him.
</P>
<P>
   SUPREME COURT GUIDE TO DRUG-SMUGGLING AND BAG-SQUEEZING
</P>
<P>
   GREYHOUND-BUS-PRIVACY-SLATE _ The Supreme Court ponders whether
you have a reasonable expectation of privacy when you place your
illegal drug stash in the overhead compartment of a Greyhound bus.
Here's a tip from Justice Antonin Scalia: Buy hard luggage.
</P>
<P>
   TIME TO CLOSE THE `APPRECIATED PROPERTY' LOOPHOLE
</P>
<P>
   KINSLEY-GIFT-LOOPHOLE-SLATE _ Is there any reason the government
should care whether you give a charity $10,000 of stock or $10,000
in cash _ care enough to reduce your tax bill by two or three
thousand dollars for choosing to give the stock? None that I have
ever heard. But it's the kind of ridiculous ``arrangement'' that
gets into the tax code unintentionally and then can't be gotten rid
of.
</P>
<P>
   MUDDLE IN THE JUNGLE: U.S. NARCS VS. COLOMBIA'S FARC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   US-COCA-WAR-ECONOMIST _ It is not Vietnam, nor will it become
so. But once again the United States is preparing to commit lots of
cash, military hardware and advisers to a battle in a foreign
jungle. This one is in southern Colombia, where an embattled
president faces daunting problems, including left-wing guerrillas,
right-wing paramilitaries and the world's largest source of coca,
the raw material for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   DEMONIZING HEZBOLLAH WON'T SAVE YOUR SOLDIERS, ISRAEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BACK-OFF-HEZBOLLAH-ECONOMIST _ To bomb the Hezbollah guerrillas
fighting Israeli occupation or just to threaten to bomb? That seems
to be the only question the Israeli government asks itself about
Lebanon these days. As a result, Lebanese civilians suffer much
more at Israeli hands than vice versa. True, Hezbollah used to be
an alarmingly active terrorist group. But nowadays, things are not
quite so simple. Indeed, for all the talk of Lebanese terrorism, it
is Hezbollah that has looked the more disciplined force of late,
and Israel that has been making innocents suffer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA'S RIGHT. STANLEY FISCHER IS BEST BOSS FOR THE IMF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IMF-HEADACHE-ECONOMIST _ Doubtless, Caio Koch-Weser is a jolly
decent fellow. Germany's finance state secretary could probably do
all sorts of jobs, perfectly competently or even brilliantly. The
trouble is that running the International Monetary Fund is not one
of them. What a pity that the best man for the job _ Stanley
Fischer, the IMF's deputy managing director and, since Michel
Camdessus stepped down a few weeks ago, it's acting head _ probably
won't get it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN'S GRANDDADDY OF A `SISTER SOULJAH' MOMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-WRATH-ECONOMIST _ John McCain's behavior bears the
hallmarks of reckless political courage. Denouncing the Reverend
Pat Robertson, founder of the Christian Coalition, in his own
Virginia hometown, was a remarkable moment in recent Republican
history. Never before has a presidential candidate nominee
castigated the religious right like that. It was not just a Sister
Souljah moment, mimicking Bill Clinton's 1992 attack on black
extremism, it was a brother, grandmother and indeed entire Souljah
family moment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST _ (This week's droll ``Primary
Color'' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `POSTER BOY' ELIAN BACKFIRES ON CUBAN-AMERICAN HARD-LINERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-CURSE-ECONOMIST _ Three months after Elian Gonzalez, a
six-year-old Cuban boy, was rescued from the sea off Miami, his
story resembles the fanciful tele-novelas that Latinos love to
watch. Call it ``The Curse of Elian.'' But there is also a growing
sense that the story is not playing out in the way that Miami's
hard-line Cuban-American leaders had intended. Ironically, they may
in fact be helping the very man they detest: Fidel Castro. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO'S CERTIFIABLY MAD WAR ON DRUGS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS-ECONOMIST _ It is known as the ``February
surprise.'' Every year, shortly before the U.S. government
announces on March 1 which countries it ``certifies'' as willing
allies in the war on illegal drugs, Mexico unveils a new and bold
anti-drugs initiative. This year, though, the surprise was on
Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AS FLOODWATERS ROSE, THE WORLD JUST WATCHED. WHY? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `PATHETIC'-FLOOD-AID-INDEPENDENT _ Finally, a major if still
barely coordinated relief effort is under way for Mozambique. But
the flurry of action has not been nearly enough to mollify the
anger of international aid agencies at what they condemn as yet
another ``pathetic'' failure of the rich and self-centered West to
respond with sufficient speed to a crisis in a Third World country.
``If this had happened in the West, the response would have been
entirely different,'' said an angry relief worker. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHN-LENNON-FBI-FILE-NYTSF _ Did John Lennon provide financial
support to the IRA? Was his song ``Working Class Hero'' subversive?
Read all about it in ``Lennon's M15-FBI Files,'' a commentary by
Jon Weiner, the author of ``Gimme Some Truth: The John Lennon FBI
Files.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET SURFING HARMS YOUR SOCIAL LIFE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOG-OFF-AND-LIVE!-INDEPENDENT _ People who use the Internet for
as little as five hours a week are less likely to talk to or visit
their family and friends and are in danger of shutting themselves
off from society, according to new research. Is it time to log off
and live? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHY MUST WE WAIT TO ENJOY OUR LEISURE TIME WHEN WE'RE OLD? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT-LEISURE?-INDEPENDENT _ Why on earth do we have a tax and
benefit system that encourages workers to take all of their leisure
time when they are older, and none when it would be most desirable
to them _ in the prime of life? When will governments have the
vision to lift their eyes above the problem pensions pose for their
budgets and tackle the crazy structure of lifetime work
incentives? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WE CAN LIVE WITHOUT THE NET, BUT WE'LL ALWAYS NEED SHAMPOO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-SHAMPOO-INDEPENDENT _ It is, as someone once said, a funny
old world. Two global corporate titans, Ford and Unilever,
announced recently that they are getting rid of thousands of their
workers. But we are undoubtedly going to go on needing Unilever's
detergent powder, shampoo and frozen peas. And we will certainly be
driving around in Ford cars for another generation. The old economy
may be out of fashion in the cyber-new world, but we still need the
things it produces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (moved in ``i'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   ARE WARS ALL ABOUT MONEY? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WAR'N'MONEY-ECONOMIST _ Making money and making war have long
been related activities. That soldiers loot and arms manufacturers
turn a profit is hardly news. But is competition for wealth and
resources becoming the major cause of new wars around the world? A
look at the lucrative business of war. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE UNFATHOMABLE TRAGEDY OF MOZAMBIQUE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MISERY-MOZAMBIQUE-ECONOMIST _ As the worst floods in living
memory continue to swirl, parts of South Africa, Zimbabwe and
especially Mozambique desperately need help to prevent the death
toll from escalating. The floods have pushed back into poverty
large numbers of Mozambicans who had recently begun to lift
themselves out of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SAD GYPSIES OF SLOVAKIA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GYPSIES-HAIDERISM-ECONOMIST _ Mikulas Dzurkinda, the Slovak
prime minister, winces when asked what he thinks of Austrian
right-winger Joerg Haider. ``I'm certain Austria will stay
democratic. But demagogues are frightening. Imagine the trouble
they could cause if they got hold of our Gypsy question.'' Indeed,
if the politics of hate were to make a comeback in lands to the
east of the present EU, Gypsies would be prime targets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS (moved in ``f'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   SLICK OPERATOR: PHOTO MOGUL GETTY TOPS GATES' CORBIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOGUL-MARK-GETTY-ECONOMIST _ It's the clash of the titans. Both
young moguls, both cornering the world market in photo archives,
both now based in Seattle: Mark Getty, grandson of oil magnate J.P.
Getty, and Bill Gates, who needs no introduction whatsoever. With
its 14th large acquisition in five years, Getty Images increased
its photo library holdings to around 70 million images. That tops
its main competitor, Gates' Corbis, which has 65 million images. As
Getty says, ``Intellectual property is the oil of the 21st
century.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE INTERNET IS RUNNING OUT OF ADDRESSES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE-ADDRESSES-ECONOMIST _ On the Internet, naming your
start-up can be more arduous than financing it. This is because
most Internet addresses, known as domain names, have been taken
already. In the .com domain, the most desirable online real estate,
almost every recognizable name has been claimed. Much is at state.
If the name space of the Internet cannot grow, e-commerce will
suffer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE REASONS BEHIND THE HIGH COST OF TOILET PAPER IN BRITAIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOILET-PAPER-UK-ECONOMIST _ Why does it cost more to wipe your
bottom in Britain than in any other country in the European Union?
It is because British consumers are extremely discriminating when
it comes to toilet paper. British bums, in short, demand and get
the best. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL (moved in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   `SMELLS AND BELLS' OF LENT CAN'T BE FOUND ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   LENT-WITHOUT-INTERNET-NYTSF _ It seems almost deviant to say so,
but traditional church appears to be making a comeback among
computer-savvy baby-boomers and Generation Xers. In contrast to the
disembodied spirituality of cyberspace, people seem eager for
sensual religious experience _ kneeling, incense, bread and wine,
congregational singing. The more ``smells and bells'' the better.
Thus, the Internet actually creates a need for human connection to
the divine.
</P>
<P>
   DR. WEIL'S WISDOM: SIZING UP FAD DIETS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DR-WEIL-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF _ Three new studies on Americans
and weight gain were released last fall, and the news wasn't good.
The verdict: Not only is obesity on the rise _ from 12 percent of
the population in 1991 to almost 18 percent in 1998, according to
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention _ but more than half
of the adults in this country are now considered at least
moderately overweight. All this, despite the fact that total fat
consumption in the United States has decreased over the past
decade. What's going on here? And what to do about it? By Dr.
Andrew Weil, written with Joseph V. Amodio. With photo. (Also moved
in ``l'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   STURDY YELLOWWARE HAS SERVED AMERICANS WELL FOR 200 YEARS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-YELLOWWARE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF _ When shipments of English
yellowware crossed the Atlantic early in the 19th century,
Americans eagerly made room in their cupboards. More durable than
redware and less cumbersome than stoneware, the newfangled goods
were handsome to behold and inexpensive to buy. Today, yellowware
remains functional, but it's also fun to collect. By Debra Muller
Price. With photos. (Also moved in ``l'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HONEY, I'M HOME ... FOR TWO DAYS ANYWAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELING-PARENT-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF _ Not very long ago, my
5-year-old daughter, Willa, held a birthday party for her doll
Lucy. Willa played Lucy's mom, while I played Lucy's grandmother,
and my 3-year-old son, Devin, was her uncle. Someone, however, was
missing. ``My husband is away on a trip,'' Willa explained, as she
blew out Lucy's candles. ``He travels a lot for work.'' This hit
suspiciously close to home. My husband, Austin, travels for his job
_ a lot. By Laura Hilgers. (Also moved in ``l'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOR DOGS WHO CAN'T PLAY SOLITAIRE, INTERACTIVE PLAYTIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOG-DAYCARE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF _ Dogs are social beings. They need
company. Well-socialized pets _ dogs that respect and interact
comfortably with people as well as other dogs _ are happy and
responsive. But because today's families tend to spend less and
less time at home, their gregarious canine companions sometimes
miss out on the socializing they crave. In order to develop into
friendly companions, young animals need extended interactive
playtime. Thus the ultimate in surrogate pet parenthood _ day-care
facilities for dogs _ is quickly becoming a solution. By Toni
Gardner. (Also moved in ``l'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOR DAMP DAYS, PERFECT PARTNERS FOR A SOUL-WARMING CUP OF TEA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRISH-TREATS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF _ The music of tea splashing into a
porcelain cup has been known to soothe an Irish soul long before
the amber liquid even touches the lips. But as a new generation of
innovative Irish chefs have come into their own, teatime sweets
just may upstage the ritualistic afternoon cuppa. Comes with three
recipes that are just right for St. Patrick's Day pages. (Also
moved in ``l'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
