<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-FOR-SALE-575&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERTUESDAY' AND AMERICA'S WARPED POLITICS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Provocative Commentary...TIMELY for `SUPERTUESDAY' March 7!)   (This pithy, TIMELY ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 225-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 575. TOTAL UNCUT IS 900
WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By JOHN O'FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first Europeans to reach the Pacific coast of North America
observed a bizarre custom practiced by the Kwakuitl Indians, in
which tribal chiefs would challenge each other to what was called a
``potlatch.''
</P>
<P>
   It involved the two chiefs going to the cliff edge and throwing
items of immense value into the sea to demonstrate their village's
enormous wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Blankets, copper pots, weapons: they took turns to chuck away
everything that they needed to survive as their two tribes looked
on and gasped at their leaders' courage.
</P>
<P>
   The first one to run out of valuables was the loser. And the
explorers watched all that and thought, ``Great _ that's how we'll
choose our president!''
</P>
<P>
   Today is Super Tuesday in the United States of America. The only
accurate part of that description is that it is indeed a Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiresome waste of money Tuesday'' might be a better name, or
``Let's bore everyone to tears Tuesday,'' because it is the day
when American democracy reaches its inane anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   Call me a skeptic, but it cannot be a good thing that the leader
of the free world is chosen on the basis of who has the most
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   The race to become president has now become a permanent cycle of
massive fund-raising and profligate spending and, as George W. Bush
has demonstrated yet again, the candidate who accumulates the most
dollars wins the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Why can they not just be honest about it? Instead of spending
months flying around the country, accusing each other of being soft
on crime or dithering on abortion, why does Bush not take out his
wallet and say to John McCain, ``OK, let's get this over with _ how
much have you got?''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush could take the stand and shout: ``God bless money!''
as everyone whooped, clapped and held up banners saying,
``Whoever's richest for the White House!''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore seems to have already wrapped up the Democratic
nomination on the basis that while Bill Clinton was president, Gore
was right by his side. I only hope he averted his eyes on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   But he, too, has spent tens of millions of dollars and will
spend as much again when the election proper gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   When Lincoln dedicated the cemetery at Gettysburg, his speech
was only slightly wrong: ``These dead shall not have died in vain _
that this nation under God shall have a new birth of freedom and
that government of the billionaires by the billionaires for the
billionaires shall not perish from this Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain in effect lost his battle to become the Republican
candidate last October, when a bill he had co-sponsored to limit
spending in U.S. presidential elections was defeated in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Amid accusations of dirty tricks, a filibuster to prevent proper
debate on the bill was passed by just five votes, and so the 20th
attempt in the last 12 years to reform the financing of elections
was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet again, America's super-rich are free to throw money at the
candidate they think least likely to take any serious money off
them once in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the majority of poor Americans, who are offered
nothing by either party, take no part in the whole process, and an
apathetic apartheid is created. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (225-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 575) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if the same system were used to appoint the British head
of state. The Queen's fortune would be used up in a couple of
months, buying television prime time to persuade us that the
Windsors really were one big happy family and that the Duke of
Edinburgh was not going to go all liberal on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Once the cash had run out, she would need to have fund-raising
dinners with various showbiz millionaires, pretending to be amused
when Gazza put a whoopee cushion under her throne.
</P>
<P>
   And worst of all, I would find myself mailing a small donation
to her campaign as she emerged as the only candidate with an
outside chance of beating mogul Richard Branson.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, in this country we have far fewer elections and
manage to be slightly more democratic than America. At least most
British citizens actually take part in a British general election.
But as ever, the trend is toward the American way.
</P>
<P>
   At the last election, the Conservatives spent (or arguably threw
away) (pounds sterling)20 million ($32 million) without shifting
their poll position one iota.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Labor Party cannot pretend that relying on donations
from the likes of Bernie Ecclestone has helped their credibility. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 900) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is an inevitable equation which states that the more money
political parties require, the less democratic the political system
will become.
</P>
<P>
   It is because today's American presidential hopefuls are so
beholden to their financial backers that there could never be a
candidate with a real program to tackle America's huge
inequalities.
</P>
<P>
   The people who need representing the most will not be voting
this supine Tuesday. And because of the narrowness of the remaining
constituency, none of the candidates can suggest any vaguely
sensible policies, such as introducing gun control or abolishing
capital punishment for crimes committed by juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is that the United States is lumbered with politicians
who would not only be prepared to sell their grandmothers but, in
George W. Bush's case, to electrocute them as well. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
