<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9399 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-07 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIF. HAS ITS MONSTER BALLOT ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In every election the California ballot is
filled with monsters of the Id, to borrow a concept from the
science fiction movie ``Forbidden Planet.''
</P>
<P>
   We live in a great and prosperous state filled with good and
generous people. California is the original land of live and let
live. Yet each election presents us with one or more ballot
measures which pander to the meanness, resentment and dread
festering deep in the California psyche.
</P>
<P>
   In recent elections we've had ballot measures picking on illegal
immigrants, mandating three-strike life sentences and attacking
affirmative action. Those all passed, but what did they do? Nothing
but stir up trouble and heartache.
</P>
<P>
   None of them advanced the career of Pete Wilson, the former
governor who had hoped to be carried to the White House on the
backs of his Id monsters. Good times, and bad timing, ruined
Wilson's politics of fear and resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Wilson is still with us. In this election we face
Proposition 21, another Wilson brain monster, one that asks us to
punish children as adults. We also have Prop. 22, Pete Knight's
gratuitous rebuke to gays and lesbians who wish to be married, and
apparently Knight's way of communicating with his gay son.
</P>
<P>
   This election day, Californians should ask themselves what kind
of petty fools their politicians take them for.
</P>
<P>
   Before Prop. 22, did you ever hear people saying their marriages
are shaky
</P>
<P>
   because California might recognize the union of a couple of
lesbians?
</P>
<P>
   Heterosexual marriages are usually threatened by heterosexual
relationships _ extra-marital ones. If you want to defend marriage,
why not ban those?
</P>
<P>
   Before Prop. 21, did you believe it would be worth spending a
billion dollars on new prisons so 14-year-olds could be
incarcerated with hardened adults, and perhaps coerced into
homosexual acts? Think about that inconsistency between Props 21
and 22.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think Prop. 21 is the way to stop all the car-jackings on
the news, the only place most people see jacked cars?
</P>
<P>
   If Prop. 21 passes, we'll live in a brave new California where
14-year-old vandals who do more than $400 worth of damage will be
felons, and could do a year of hard time in the big house with
adult murderers and rapists who can turn them into truly
professional criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any wrecked school locker that costs less than $400 to
repair?
</P>
<P>
   The idea of Prop. 21 is to play upon fears of young
``predators,`` a term that has fallen from use as the crime rate
has fallen. Still, we're stuck with Wilson's Prop. 21, even though
he and his hopes of becoming the fear president have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, Prop. 21 would make felons of any teenager found
guilty of any activity loosely defined as ``gang recruitment.'' Any
kid defined by the
</P>
<P>
   cops as engaging in ``active participation'' in gangs would have
to register
</P>
<P>
   with the state or face prison.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile suspects' names could be released to the public even
before the kids are charged with crimes. The Justice Department
would be required to report juveniles' records, thus kids' felony
vandalism would follow them the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Rights and rehabilitation are being wiped out so kids can be
locked away. Given the emphasis on gangs, you know the main targets
are kids who are black or Latino.
</P>
<P>
   Kids under 18 already can be prosecuted as adults by means of
judicial waiver. Prop. 21 would take this power from judges and
give it to prosecutors, who generally aren't known for
underzealousness.
</P>
<P>
   All this is an expression of pure meanness on the part of a man
who is no longer governor and has no hope of being president. For
that, at least, we should be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that Americans wildly overestimate the prevalence
of juvenile crime. It's no wonder given the school shooting stories
overplayed in the news. But most adults have no idea the trouble
the judicial system can make for kids.
</P>
<P>
   A young guy I know (who lives in another state) got arrested for
stealing money from the fine drawer of a public library. He's a kid
with an attention deficit disorder and a history of running with a
bad crowd in a small town. He's the kid who always got caught, and
he got caught right after his 18th birthday so he was charged with
an adult felony.
</P>
<P>
   The cops in the small town (the virtues of small towns are
highly overrated) told him they'd pin a bunch of petty crimes on
him and put him away forever under three strikes. So he confessed
to stealing the library's money. He escaped prison with probation
only because his grandparents paid for a good lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   After moving in with relatives in another state, and working
hard in a supermarket, he's made good, paying reparations for his
crime, and getting an even better job.
</P>
<P>
   If this young man had taken the library's coins under a Prop. 21
type of law, he'd be in a state prison learning the wrong kind of
career with some very hard men, and a major national company
wouldn't have a particularly energetic young salesman.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the sort of story we think about when we go into a
polling place to vote our fears. But these are the kind of kids we
can ruin with a hole punched in a ballot card.
</P>
<P>
   There are monsters on the streets, but there are many more
monsters in our minds. Unscrupulous politicians know how to call
them forth.
</P>
<P>
   What will it be next election? Six-year-olds tried for murder as
adults?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1504EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
