<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORONATION-DAY-US-650&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPER TUESDAY' PRIMARIES SET TO CROWN GORE AND BUSH  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for `Super Tuesday,' March 7)   (This timely 825-word (untrimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is from
THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
CAN STAND IN 650 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 825.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Voters across America, from the small states of New
England in the east to the broad sweep of California in the west,
went to the polls Tuesday in ``Super Tuesday'' primaries that
looked set to crown Vice President Al Gore and George W. Bush as
the two contenders for the White House in November.
</P>
<P>
   Their challengers, whose rebel crusades had unexpectedly
enlivened the long weeks of campaigning, and at times even
threatened a lasting upset, appeared down, but _ in the case of the
Republican, Senator John McCain _ not yet out of contention
completely.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, whose final rally in the Southern California city of San
Diego was described by one participant as ``so sad, it was almost a
wake,'' spent the day quietly in Los Angeles, before a planned
``victory'' celebration in Hollywood after the polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   He and his campaign team still hoped for the sort of surprise
sprung by Michigan's voters, which brought him back into the race
after his double-figure defeat in South Carolina just three days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Latest opinion polls suggested that he had a good chance of
victory in the New England states and could still overtake Bush in
New York, but that Ohio and Georgia were lost, as _ more
distressingly _ was California.
</P>
<P>
   The best that McCain could hope for there was a narrow victory
in the so-called ``popular vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was well ahead among registered Republicans, the only vote
that counted in terms of delegates to the Republican National
Convention this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But there was still a chance that McCain could prevail in the
overall tally.
</P>
<P>
   California, like Washington state, has a two-tier system that
allows all registered voters to vote for whomever they like, but
only the votes of registered Republicans count in the contest for
convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly close results in the other states voting Tuesday
could yet postpone McCain's departure from the presidential race,
but next week's primaries across the South are expected to seal his
fate.
</P>
<P>
   The future for Bill Bradley, Gore's sole challenger for the
Democratic Party's nomination looked even less bright.
</P>
<P>
   The former New Jersey senator and former player for the New York
Knicks professional basketball team, was up early, meeting and
greeting commuters at a Manhattan subway station, from where he
went on to a local school to hobnob with voters as they emerged
from the voting hall.
</P>
<P>
   And while he, too, had a ``victory'' party planned for New York
City Tuesday night, he was said to have set aside Wednesday for
consultations with his staff _ consultations likely to leave Gore
the de facto Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The confidence of both front-runners could be gauged by the
elaborate arrangements each had made for their victory parties last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Both were at their national headquarters in their home states:
Gore in Nashville, Tenn., and Bush _ who is Governor of Texas _ in
the state capital, Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign was reported to have ``four buckets of
confetti'' ready for release in anticipation of a countrywide
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee and Texas both hold their primaries next week, but the
presence of the two front-runners at their headquarters was a clear
signal to the country that as of last night they, and only they,
were duelling to succeed President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 16 states voted Tuesday; 15 held Democratic primaries or
caucuses, and 13 held Republican ballots (i.e., 12 held both).
</P>
<P>
   And while the only close results were expected in New York and
the popular vote in California, America's usually voluble political
pundits were cautious, having seen their forecasts confounded in
New Hampshire, South Carolina and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   As in these states, one of the biggest imponderables was the
turnout, which was expected to be the highest in primaries for
years, perhaps ever, reflecting the extent to which the energetic
insurgency of McCain had galvanized a new generation of voters. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 650, OR CONTINUE TO 825) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   With voting brisk, a minor spat erupted on the sidelines about
the use of ``exit polls.''
</P>
<P>
   These polls, which estimate the final outcome on the basis of
asking voters how they have voted as they emerge from the polling
station, have increasingly enabled broadcasters and others to
pronounce the result, often with uncanny accuracy, within seconds
of the polls closing.
</P>
<P>
   Exit pollsters, however, also make running tallies and release
to subscribers, under strict embargo, periodic ``results'' through
the day. The leaking of these interim ``results'' on the Internet
prompted first complaints, and then legal action, from the polling
company.
</P>
<P>
   The company complained that it was abuse of its information (and
could influence the outcome). The Internet magazine, Slate, among
others, however, defended its decision to publish as being in the
interests of free speech and noted that the electoral world stood
to be transformed by the Internet and the clock could not be turned
back. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 825-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
