<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9452 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-REAGAN-WANNABES-INDEP     03-07 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAGAN-WANNABES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES SORELY LACK REAGAN `CHARISMA'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This timely 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, CALIF. _ At the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library,
in the rolling foothills of Ventura County, some 40 miles northwest
of Los Angeles, the legacy of America's most popular _ if divisive
_ recent president is enshrined in the so-called Four Pillars of
Freedom: individual liberty, economic opportunity, global democracy
and national pride.
</P>
<P>
   Those are political slogans that the two front-runners for this
year's Republican presidential nomination, George W. Bush and John
McCain, have no trouble embracing.
</P>
<P>
   For all the acrimony dividing them, both have invoked the Reagan
era as their inspiration. Indeed, they have tussled over which of
them deserves to be called Reagan's true successor.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for the Reagan mantle is not simply a matter of
point-scoring in debates; it is a serious issue.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans want to win back the White House, they are
going to have to field a candidate with at least some of Reagan's
crossover appeal to Democrats and independents, as well as some of
the ideological zeal that galvanized the Gipper's closest
followers.
</P>
<P>
   So which of the two candidates best fits the bill? In what may
be an ominous sign for the party's chances come November, the
overwhelming consensus among Ronald Reagan devotees ambling through
the library and museum this week was that neither does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is too dependent on the powerful people who put him where
he is to be a real leader,'' opined Terry Erskine, a retired
businessman from Orange County, one of the most conservative areas
in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for McCain, he's a feisty little guy, but he doesn't have
Reagan's charisma. Reagan was a great orator. He had stature. I
don't see that in either of these two.''
</P>
<P>
   The charisma issue surfaced, unprompted, in interview after
interview with library visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Charisma was indeed Reagan's strongest political asset and a
shield that protected him from the consequences of his
administration's more outrageous acts of foreign policy adventurism
and domestic hostility to unionized workers and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   As a couple of visitors reluctantly admitted, a similar ability
to connect with people helped Bill Clinton reach the White House
and stay there for two terms.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was variously described as ``wooden,'' ``unconvincing''
and ``too much a product of his privileged background.''
</P>
<P>
   As for McCain, he scored points with some people for his ability
to reach out to a broad electorate _ the so-called ``Reagan
Democrats'' who proved so decisive in the 1980s in states like
California and Michigan _ but fell down with others because he was
perceived as being more about bluster and rebellious energy than
true charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reagan's quality was that he was infinitely likeable, and
that's important in U.S. politics,'' said Jan Smithers, a Canadian
sociologist living in California. ``I don't think Bush and McCain
have that.''
</P>
<P>
   If such views are representative of the electorate as a whole,
they spell trouble for both Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of his campaign, Bush sold himself as the voice of
inclusion, the ``compassionate conservative'' who could appeal to
both the right and the center. His sharp turn to the right,
provoked by McCain's challenge, appears to have done considerable
damage to that platform.
</P>
<P>
   As for McCain, he has been counting on his brash populism to
override the misgivings about him within the Republican Party
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   If the sort of voter who visits the Reagan Library _ who might
be anything from a hard-line right-winger to a soft independent
centrist _ can't get excited about him, then his chances of winning
a plurality of registered Republicans seem dim indeed.
</P>
<P>
   A big propaganda coup for either candidate would be to receive
the endorsement of the Reagans themselves. Ronald, ill with
Alzheimer's disease, is presumably past making a rational choice,
and his wife Nancy has so far stayed above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The best indication of the family's preferences came this week
on a radio show hosted by Michael Reagan, the ex-president's son,
who argued with McCain about the religious right and then, after
his guest's mobile phone signal broke up, said: ``I don't want to
talk to him if he calls back.''
</P>
<P>
   Was that a tacit endorsement of Bush? If so, it is not
necessarily shared by rank-and-file Reaganites.
</P>
<P>
   One library visitor describing himself as a centrist, retired
university administrator Eugene Johnson from New York, said he
would rather vote for Al Gore than for George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans will choose Bush as their candidate, and they
will go down to defeat,'' he predicted.
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1543EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9456 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     03-07 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK UNHITCHES ROUTE FROM LOCAL ECONOMIES OF ALPINE, SANDERSON,
DEL RIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abilene and Odessa are going to be passenger rail stops again;
Fort Worth will be a major hub.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is making these suggestions and if no one interferes, the
new plan could be running by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The new path of the Sunset Limited between San Antonio and El
Paso has been hailed all along the Interstate 20 corridor. The
train, which begins in Orlando, Fla., and ends in Los Angeles, will
turn north at San Antonio, travel to Fort Worth, then west
shadowing the interstate. It brings new opportunities for commerce,
and additional chances for tourism dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the move isn't so celebrated in Alpine,
Sanderson and Del Rio, the cities along the old route that have
been summarily abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular route change is shortsighted when considering
the big picture of tourism and the picturesque Sunset Limited
itinerary,'' said David Busey, director of community development in
Alpine.
</P>
<P>
   To be a bit more succinct, Busey added, ``With the changes
proposed, the Sunset Limited will be scenically and culturally
challenged by being diverted northerly through monotonous plains,
oil fields and nondescript urban sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he's right. The charm of rails curling along the Rio
Grande, passing over the massive Lake Amistad, and winding through
the Glass and Del Norte Mountains is definitely greater than
chugging along the predominantly flat lands between Abilene and El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that this has been an historic route,'' Busey said.
``The train has been coming through here since 1883. And it is just
one more of those things that ends up being a blow to a rural
community. It's one thing after another.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sanderson, the blows have been relentless. First, the city
lost important traffic when Interstate 10 supplanted U.S. 90 as the
major East-West route across the southern portion of the state.
Then, the railroad began its withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson was founded on the railroad. It was a major Southern
Pacific overhaul center with a round house and full crews. Over the
years, the work left; eventually, in 1994, the entire service
center closed, costing the city 50 jobs and $5 million in payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The newest decision, to bypass Sanderson on the Sunset Limited
line, cuts deeply into the town's emotional base. ``It's going to
hurt us,'' County Judge Dudley Harrison said. ``Anything you do to
us like that hurts. We have been working very hard to make a
comeback and a lot of that work will go by the wayside now.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Del Rio have recently joined in a ``Rails and
Trails'' program in which Del Rio visitors take the train to
Sanderson _ across the Amistad reservoir and through Seminole
Canyon State Park, with a stop at Judge Roy Bean's in Langtry. They
eat lunch at local restaurants, then return by van to Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a popular program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be gone now,'' Harrison said. ``We sure don't like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak, of course, won't be dissuaded by a van full of local
tourists. The national rail line needs volume, the kind that comes
from servicing larger metropolitan markets. It needs the freight
those markets generate. It has to be off the government dole by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   It can't worry over historical concerns in Alpine, or whether
the train passengers get to see a mountain range or a West Texas
oil patch. Amtrak needs the new business.
</P>
<P>
   But so do the cities it is leaving behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amtrak's decision to eliminate the El Paso-San Antonio sector
of the Sunset Limited route is a great disservice to the people of
the Big Bend region,'' Alpine Mayor Paul Weyerts said. ``It is also
a disservice to the thousands of future Amtrak passengers who will
be deprived of seeing one of the most scenic parts of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1544EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
