   As for McCain, he has been counting on his brash populism to
override the misgivings about him within the Republican Party
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   If the sort of voter who visits the Reagan Library _ who might
be anything from a hard-line right-winger to a soft independent
centrist _ can't get excited about him, then his chances of winning
a plurality of registered Republicans seem dim indeed.
</P>
<P>
   A big propaganda coup for either candidate would be to receive
the endorsement of the Reagans themselves. Ronald, ill with
Alzheimer's disease, is presumably past making a rational choice,
and his wife Nancy has so far stayed above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The best indication of the family's preferences came this week
on a radio show hosted by Michael Reagan, the ex-president's son,
who argued with McCain about the religious right and then, after
his guest's mobile phone signal broke up, said: ``I don't want to
talk to him if he calls back.''
</P>
<P>
   Was that a tacit endorsement of Bush? If so, it is not
necessarily shared by rank-and-file Reaganites.
</P>
<P>
   One library visitor describing himself as a centrist, retired
university administrator Eugene Johnson from New York, said he
would rather vote for Al Gore than for George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans will choose Bush as their candidate, and they
will go down to defeat,'' he predicted.
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
