<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAD-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S SUGAR AND SPICE AND CONTRADICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A serious question for you, dear reader, one that I have no
answer to and that currently keeps the Post Toasties in my belly
all aflutter: Is there any way to keep my 5-year-old daughter from
becoming a female?
</P>
<P>
   The background: It had been a glorious Sunday morning. I woke up
early, ate some oatmeal, engaged in some quality time with a
well-known Western deity, jogged to the gym, swam a thousand
meters, walked back, lunched on a shrimp po-boy and a few adult
beverages to counteract any good the workout did for me, then
headed home. The wife and daughter were in the middle of _ I am not
making this up _ a Tae-Bo workout. I said to myself, ``Hey, the
women are busy. House is clean. Chores done. Beverage effect
kicking in. Time to kick it old-school: I'm going to break off
about a two-hour afternoon nap for the first time in years.''
</P>
<P>
   How stupid am I? Ten minutes later I was snug and cozy, fading
to sleep, my last thoughts of the restful bliss that defines a fine
lazy Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``JUST WHAT DO YOU THINK YOU'RE DOING?'' came the war cry.
</P>
<P>
   The wife was in the room. My heart leaped out of my chest, ran
and hid.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know ... sleeping ... dear.''
</P>
<P>
   With no heart, therefore no steady blood supply, my brain was
shutting down. I didn't realize it was a trick question. Of course
she didn't want a literal answer. She wanted to know what all women
want to know in that situation: ``What makes you think I'll let you
do something solitary and enjoyable on a weekend?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, this didn't really surprise me. It's part of the ``joyous
compromise'' of marriage. I had just lost my mind for a minute.
Still, I wasn't ready for what came next.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, all sinewy and lean after her Tae-Bo session,
leaped onto my stomach. ``YEAH DADDY! GET UP RIGHT NOW BECAUSE
YOU'RE ALWAYS SLEEPING AND WE HAVE THINGS ... FOR ... YOU ... TO
DO!''
</P>
<P>
   A large cartoonish question mark formed over my head, complete
with a ``boing'' sound. Always sleeping? I haven't slept since she
was born. Things to do? What, watch ``Blues Clues''?
</P>
<P>
   As I settled back into my everyday dadlike, sleep-deprived
state, I realized that my daughter _ formerly ``pumpkin'' and ``my
little girl'' _ had been acting more and more like her mother in
recent weeks. I had just passed it off as my imagination, but
looking back at specific incidents _ e.g., saying she needed new
Powerpuff Girl sneakers because ``all the kids had seen her in
those a hundred times'' _ a pattern emerged. My daughter was
becoming a female.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, my fears were confirmed. As Mom was getting
ready for work, the munchkin turned on the TV in my room, then
hopped into bed to watch cartoons. I gave her a good-morning hug
and cheek-smooch.
</P>
<P>
   ``GROSS DADDY YOU STINK!'' she announced to the neighborhood.
``GO GET IN THE SHOWER! I'M TRYING TO WATCH CARTOON NETWORK!''
</P>
<P>
   Shunned, I did as I was told. A few minutes later, the wife and
I heard the daughter crying and ran back in the room. ``What's the
matter, honey?'' we asked.
</P>
<P>
   (Sniffling quietly, in a doe-eyed manner) ``Daddy won't watch
cartoons with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom looked accusingly at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But ... she kicked me out ... said I stunk ... I tried to
watch ...''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. At once repulsed by me and yet always wanting me by her
side. At once forceful and emotionally needy. At once assured and
teary. The transformation was complete. My daughter was, is, my
wife. She is a female.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I want her to be more masculine, piggish,
self-centered, like her daddy. But I was hoping there was something
in between, a state where my daughter would exhibit all the
glorious warmth and intelligence and caring of her mother without
all the stuff that I jes dunt unnerstan.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, I did my best. Crawled into bed so she'd have
someone with whom she could watch cartoons. I hugged her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, did you shower yet?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
