<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-RELIGION-DEBATE-TEX     03-07 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-DEBATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE WE LOSING OUR ABILITY TO DEBATE ABOUT RELIGION?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALAN COCHRUM 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hmmm. How can I put this?
</P>
<P>
   I have serious problems with Roman Catholic theology. (Which is
not a surprising thing, given a lifelong background among the
Churches of Christ.)
</P>
<P>
   I do not believe in the veneration of Mary. I do not believe in
the invocation of saints. I do not believe in the use of icons. I
do not believe in mandatory singleness for church leaders. I do not
believe in the infallibility of the church or the pope.
</P>
<P>
   I find the doctrine of indulgences baffling. I find the church's
use of annulments tragicomic. I find its practice of baptizing
infants biblically suspect, at the very least.
</P>
<P>
   So if I say all those things, am I an anti-Catholic bigot?
</P>
<P>
   Until last month, George W. Bush probably hadn't given
Catholicism too much thought recently. But thanks to GOP primary
opponent John McCain, the reaction to Bush's campaign visit to Bob
Jones University _ where Vatican City is not seen as a light among
the nations _ left the Texas governor nursing a bloody political
nose and writing an apology to a New York cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   However, a larger issue lurks behind this episode, which
actually had far more to do with the politics of religion (and the
religion of politics) than faith itself. For a moment, set aside
Bush, McCain and the specific attitudes at one South Carolina
campus. The question here is whether America is losing the ability
to debate religious claims with anything like the conviction that
they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   America's founders were intimately acquainted with the perils of
marrying civil and ecclesiastical power. So what man had joined
together, the Constitution put asunder. The church _ or, one could
add these days, the synagogue or the mosque _ was not going to be
running the state, and the state was not going to be running the
church.
</P>
<P>
   It is one divorce that has actually worked. For two centuries,
adherents of various faiths have been able to go about their
business without worrying that the next transfer of political power
could mean disenfranchisement, exile or the latest version of the
stake. But recently the divorce has birthed an illegitimate child.
</P>
<P>
   The old saying was that one didn't discuss religion or politics
in polite society. The public square was a different matter. Creeds
as well as candidates were fair game. One can log onto eBay and
find sellers offering old books and pamphlets with titles like
``The Smith-Lovelady Debate'' _ the texts of public arguments about
everything from marriage to church music.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, it seems that religion is being elbowed rudely out
of the public square as well as the dining room. It's not a matter
of the truth or falsity of the faith claims _ the problem is the
proclamation itself.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that this religion is truer than that one, or seeking
to convert members of one faith to another, is ... crass. It is
gauche. It is Not Done. It encounters the kind of disapproval that
once greeted promiscuity. Better to suggest that someone's mother
wears army boots with round heels.
</P>
<P>
   What a tragedy. We are selling our birthright _ the freedom to
discuss and contend for the truth as we understand it _ for a mess
of insipid pottage, a stew of hollow tolerance that in the end
nourishes no one.
</P>
<P>
   Does religious bigotry exist? Of course _ as surely as all
prejudices exist. Many a mother can probably tell of the rejection
suffered by children when their playmates, or their playmates'
parents, discovered their religious background. The Know-Nothings,
the political activists of the mid-1800s who saw those alien Irish
Catholics as such a threat, are an old American story.
</P>
<P>
   But ``bigotry'' is a word to be handled with care, a rhetorical
diagnosis to be pronounced only when truly warranted. It is not a
muzzle to be snapped over the mouths of those who simply call our
beliefs into question.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th-century thinkers behind the Bill of Rights knew that
government could not be trusted to act as an arbiter and dispenser
of moral truth. The virtue of the First Amendment is that it
provides a civic space where ideas can freely fight for survival.
(Whether the truest ideas will indeed thrive is another question
altogether.)
</P>
<P>
   But when we turn this freedom into a rationale that objective
truth is undiscoverable or nonexistent _ a feeling that what is
``true'' for you need not be ``true'' for me, a sort of
Get-Out-of-Moral-Responsibility-Free card _ then we have wasted our
inheritance as Americans, and indeed as human beings. Like the
prodigal son, we will find ourselves in the fields, feeding swine
and perishing with hunger.
</P>
<P>
   If we argue that our particular religious views are somehow
sacrosanct simply because they are ``ours,'' we are not dealing
from a position of strength. We may be dealing from a position of
insecurity (from an inability to defend our dogmas) or arrogance
(from the conviction that we have ``everything'' nailed down to the
last jot and tittle), but not strength.
</P>
<P>
   America does not need more religious bigotry. What we need is a
society that understands that our religions purport to tell us the
truth about humanity and divinity, and that those faith systems are
not telling us the same thing. What we need are people who can
discuss their beliefs intelligently and vigorously and still be
good neighbors, classmates, colleagues and citizens. But that is
impossible if we turn ourselves into spiritual porcupines,
bristling at the very idea that someone might have a morsel of
truth that we do not.
</P>
<P>
   I have more than a few quarrels with the Roman Catholic Church,
and with many another religious group besides. But I have more
respect for those who assert that God is therefore unhappy with me,
and that I need to repent, than for those who argue that no one has
a moral right to try to change my mind.
</P>
<P>
   (Alan Cochrum is a writer and editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram Editorial Board. You can reach him at
amcochrum(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7753. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
