<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MORDECHAI-392&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI CABINET OFFICIAL INVOLVED IN SEX HARASSMENT CASE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the latest of a series of scandals involving top
Israeli officials, Transportation Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
announced on Tuesday that he was taking a leave of absence after
police began investigating a complaint that he had sexually
assaulted a woman who works in his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, 55, a member of Prime Minister Ehud Barak's security
cabinet and the leader of the Center Party, emphatically denied the
woman's accusation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never happened,'' he said in remarks broadcast live on
radio and television. ``I say it wholeheartedly: it never
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, a former defense minister and candidate for prime
minister, said that the acts attributed to him ``contradict my
moral universe, my personal values, everything I believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I have decided to take a leave of absence so that
the police can carry out a quiet and effective investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint to the police, the woman, whose name was not
disclosed, said that Mordechai had assaulted her in his Tel Aviv
office on February 25. Television reports said that in a detailed
account supported by a lie-detector test, the 23-year-old woman
accused Mordechai of touching her and forcing her down on a couch
before backing off when she burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman said that the complaint received on Monday
was of ``an indecent act and sexual harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   The accusation emerged a day before International Women's Day,
which was marked on Tuesday in a special session of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the legislators, Barak urged women ``not to be afraid
to complain and to report any harm to them, regardless of who the
assailant is.'' He added that ``there must be no leniency
whatsoever'' toward such assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking later to reporters, Barak said that he respected
Mordechai's decision to take a leave of absence and expected it to
clear the way for a speedy investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai, a former army general, has been through public trials
before. In 1984, the Shin Bet security service tried to frame him
for the killing of two Palestinian bus hijackers who had been
beaten to death by its agents.
</P>
<P>
   On television on Tuesday night, Mordechai said that he and his
family were going through ``difficult days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A person wakes up in the morning and finds his reality turned
upside down,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The investigation of Mordechai is the latest of a series of
high-level scandals that have emerged here in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Barak's election campaign are under investigation
for suspected illegal fund-raising activities. President Ezer
Weizman is being investigated for receiving large and undisclosed
sums of money from a French-born businessman. And former Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has been questioned by police on
suspicion of failing to return gifts he had received while in
office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
