</P>
<P>
   Visa opponents also say many older workers want high-tech jobs,
but young executives at high-tech companies won't offer them
training. Are there really enough older tech workers to supply
fast-growing companies with the labor they need? That question has
never been answered conclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, visa opponents insist the job market is changing enough
to relieve labor shortages without more foreign help. O'Neill, of
the electrical engineers group, admits hiring has been difficult
for some companies in the past year, but attributes much of the
employment surge to the effort to repair Y2K computer bugs. Now
that those problems have been fixed, computer-related job openings
are declining and ``salaries are leveling off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Hatch-sponsored legislation, Dan Stein, a
lobbyist for the anti-immigration movement, says: ``There isn't a
single study that shows that kind of bill is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Tech employers vigorously disagree. They note that the Bureau of
Labor Statistics' employment projections through 2008 show the No.
1 industry for job growth will be computer and data processing
services, which will need 3.47 million workers in 2008, compared to
1.6 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000 and 2001, the Labor Department says the five
fastest-growing occupations are computer engineers; computer
support specialists, systems analysts, database administrators and
desktop publishing specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Department of Education reports that college
degrees granted in engineering are declining, while computer
science degrees are down sharply from the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Thom Stohler, a spokesman for the American Electronics
Association, a Washington-based trade group representing high-tech
companies, says U.S. colleges can't possibly produce enough
engineers to fill the labor market in coming years because very few
students are taking the math courses needed to get those degrees.
``The pipeline from K through 12 is not looking good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But given that the National Science Foundation's study on the
job market won't be completed for months, Smith and Goodlatte say
the most appropriate thing for Congress to do now is boost the visa
cap only for this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that the expansion is of a temporary
nature, so that our long-term goal is to make sure these
opportunities exist for American citizens,'' Goodlatte said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
