<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S HOT AT THE MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., March 12) 
(jt) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The millennial fireworks are long since over, but this spring
and summer art in Europe sparkles on.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a year for the sort of festival _ the Venice
Biennale, Documenta _ that turns the international art community
into one big traveling chat room for a week or two. (The biennial
in Lyon provides the requisite expense-account item this summer.)
Yet a cultural gala of major proportions is already under way: the
Roman Catholic Jubilee year that is transforming the Eternal City
into a vast museum-without-walls. Go, see, and be overwhelmed by
sights and crowds alike. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Institutional expansions and overhauls are also important
attractions in the months ahead. The Pompidou Center in Paris is up
and running again after a renovation. And late spring and early
summer in London are likely to feel like one long ribbon-cutting
ceremony. The fast-paced schedule is as follows.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the high-profile events of the season will be the opening
on May 12 in Southwark of the new Tate Modern, devoted to
international art of the 20th century. The museum will be housed in
a revamped power station, a massive central-chimney building
designed by Sir Giles Gilbert Scott, who also designed Britain's
signal contribution to the communications age, the nearly extinct
red telephone booth. As for the existing Tate, it reopens as the
Tate Britain on May 24, with British art from the 16th century to
the present. The Wallace Gallery introduces new galleries on June
22, and the venerable Dulwich Picture Gallery opens new buildings
on June 25. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of these museums will do something a little special to
celebrate the occasions. The Tate Britain has organized ``Ruskin,
Turner and the Pre-Raphaelites'' (through May 28), which marks the
centenary of the death of the aesthetician John Ruskin (1819-1900).
Hugely influential, he was the first British artist-critic to give
his contemporaries a big promotional push, and in this survey of
his polymath output he will be surrounded by grateful peers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year of Ruskin's demise provides the title for an ambitious
exhibition at the Royal Academy of Arts, ``1900: Art at the
Crossroads'' (through April 3). It focuses on a threshold moment
when Winslow Homer was an eminence grise and Pablo Picasso a Young
Turk. All kinds of artists long forgotten (until now, anyway) are
folded in here, and they will all travel to the Guggenheim in New
York in May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Victoria and Albert picks up the turn-of-the-century thread
in ``Art Nouveau 1890-1914'' (April 6 to July 30), which will
examine a period style through the lens of fine and applied arts.
Any show that counts Antoni Gaudi, Emile Galle and Aubrey Beardsley
among its participants is an extravaganza by definition. This one
is sure to be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To all the above add ``The House Beautiful: Oscar Wilde and the
Aesthetic Interior'' at the little known Geffrye Museum (July 18 to
Jan. 21, 2001). Wilde, who died in 1900, considered himself the
founder of the Ruskin-inspired Aesthetic Movement, which he
envisioned as a revolutionary break from the stifling middle-class
tastes of the day. He would be amused to learn that a century later
``middle brow'' is enjoying a high-brow art world vogue.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given Ruskin's enthusiasm for up-to-date art, it makes sense
that his Tate Britain survey will be followed by ``New British Art
2000'' (July 6 to Sept. 24), the first in a new series of triennial
temperature-taking exhibitions designed to find out what's hot
(meaning what's cool) in art. This year's version, with 20 artists,
will be the largest showcase of contemporary work ever held at the
museum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the National Gallery is trying to spiff up its patinated
image with ``Encounters: New Art From Old'' (June 14 to Sept. 17).
Two dozen ``contemporary masters'' have been invited to respond to
a piece from the collection with work of their own. Truth to tell,
most of the matches sound snoozy, but sparks may fly in a few of
the face-offs: Lucien Freud's with Chardin, say, or Louise
Bourgeois' with J.M.W. Turner.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, it's ``1900'' all over again. That's the title of a
show at the Grand Palais (March 17 to June 26) that rustles up 400
works made between 1895 and 1905 to address such slippery issues as
national movements versus pan-European styles, and the
post-Romantic relationship of man to nature. As at the Royal
Academy, there will be familiar delights and things that no one has
taken a squint at in years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paris is also honoring the 100th birthday of the photographer
Brassai with two exhibitions. The larger one is the retrospective
at the Pompidou (April 19 to June 26), which ranges from his famous
``Paris de Nuit'' series to his covers for Harper's Bazaar. The
other is at the Picasso Museum and considers collaborations between
two modern art colossi (Feb. 2 to May 1). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Picasso's homeland of Spain, many roads lead to the
Guggenheim Museum Bilbao. Thanks to Frank Gehry's architecture, the
museum doesn't need a stitch of art to be a tourist magnet, but it
has exhibitions anyway. Through May 7, one can catch the last stop
of a traveling retrospective of work by David Salle, organized by
the Stedelijk Museum in Amsterdam. Salle is paired with another
artist closely identified with the 1980s, Francesco Clemente, in
the retrospective that recently closed in New York (through June
4).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They are followed by ``Amazons of the Avant-Garde: Alexandra
Exter, Natalia Goncharova, Liubov Popova, Olga Rozanova, Varvara
Stepanova and Nadezhda Udaltsova,'' a showcase of wonderfully
inventive women who were crucial, though undervalued, players in
early Russian modernism. The show will come to New York in
September. Early birds can catch it at the Peggy Guggenheim
Collection in Venice until May 28. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any excuse to stay a spell in Venice is the right excuse. But
Rome is where the action is this summer, even for non-Jubilee
activity. There will be a Goya show at the Palazzo Barberini from
March 18 to June 18. And two historical exhibitions that focus on
the city itself sound especially appealing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Idea of Beautiful: A Visit to Rome in the 17th Century
With Giovanni Pietro Bellori,'' at the Palazzo delle Esposizioni
(March 29 to June 26), is centered on the figure of the Italian art
critic and historian who formulated the cult of Classical antiquity
in the Baroque period. A staggering array of 800 works, from
paintings by Annibale Carracci and Nicolas Poussin to antique
sculptures, will give a sense of his sources and influences. It
will be complemented by a concurrent show, ``Rome-Paris, 1640:
Classical Ideal and Baroque Epic in the Time of Poussin,'' at the
Villa Medici.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the merging of aesthetic and spiritual ideals is the
very essence of art from Asia, and no exhibition this season will
demonstrate that dynamic more exquisitely than ``Korea: The Old
Kingdom,'' covering the history of Korean art from the bronze age
into the 20th century, which ends its European tour at the Rietberg
Museum in Zurich (March 19 to July 9). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It boasts first-rank treasures from the National Museum in
Seoul, including ink paintings, Buddhist icons and celadon bowls.
And when light flickers across the surface of a centuries-old
ceremonial crown of openwork gold encrusted with jade, fireworks
are in the air again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
