<HEADLINE>
BARAK AND ARAFAT ARE REPORTED TO BE MEETING ON PEACE EFFORT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak was to meet on Tuesday
with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, in an attempt to
restart formal peace negotiations after a break of more than one
month, according to Israeli and Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting place and time were kept secret. The last time the
two leaders met was on Feb. 3.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's special envoy to the Middle East, Dennis B.
Ross, also was supposed to attend the meeting, the officials said.
Ross arrived for a two-day visit in Israel and the Palestinian
territories Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Radio reported before the meeting that Barak was prepared
to offer the Palestinians a number of inducements to reestablish an
atmosphere of trust _ or at least hope _ in the fitful
negotiations. Among them, the radio report said, were the release
of Palestinian prisoners and the payment of taxes owed by Israel to
the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The talks on formalizing a framework for a final treaty broke
down last month. Palestinian officials have complained that Barak
has not adhered to earlier agreements that call for the
step-by-step transfer of pieces of West Bank land to Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides disagree over which parts of the West Bank should
be placed under Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Tuesday, Arafat addressed his Palestinian parliament
and repeated his vow to declare an independent state by the end of
the year, even if the final status of relations between Israel and
the Palestinians remains unresolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
