<HEADLINE>
A ROBUST RABBIT WITH TOUCHES OF SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the second of eight columns by Christian Delouvrier, the
executive chef of Lespinasse in Manhattan. They are being written
with Melissa Clark.)  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By CHRISTIAN DELOUVRIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In France, one of the most traditional ways to serve
rabbit is hunter's style, a robust stew made with mushrooms, onions
and herbs _ the sorts of foods a hunter might come upon on his way
home through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hearty dish that was popular when I was growing up; my
mother and grandmother often made it, and I still do. But at the
restaurant I treat this rustic dish with an elegant touch.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of stewing pieces of the meat in a sauce, I roast the
rabbit quickly at a high temperature so the skin becomes crisp and
brown while the meat remains succulent. My sauce is enriched by the
rabbit trimmings, tomato, garlic, carrot, and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   And I serve it on a particularly creamy polenta made with milk
and Parmesan. It's as rich and soft as a buttery potato puree, an
extravagant partner for the lean rabbit meat. Polenta is, of
course, not so typical in France; mashed potatoes or rice would be
served instead, and you could do that, too.
</P>
<P>
   As the weather begins to warm, I look forward to bringing
touches of spring to the plate with vegetables like blanched
asparagus tips sauteed in butter until the ends crisp, and morels,
gently stewed with olive oil and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   But even with all those embellishments, at heart this is still a
simple dish. Its success depends on having a fresh, young rabbit;
frozen ones tend to toughen during cooking. And because the meat is
extremely lean, it's important not to overcook.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbit can even be taken off the heat a little early, when
it's still slightly pink near the bone. Then it can finish cooking
as it rests under a sheet of foil. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED RABBIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours, plus 1 hour's simmering &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 rabbits, hind legs and forelegs separated from loins, hind
legs cut in two at joints, trimmings reserved
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 white button mushrooms, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, sliced
</P>
<P>
   12 cloves garlic, smashed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   } cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes, cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch thyme
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, sliced &QL; 
For the polenta:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup quick-cooking polenta
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   { cup grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large, deep skillet over high heat, heat 1 tablespoon
oil and 1 tablespoon butter. Add rabbit forelegs, trimmings (except
liver) and salt to taste. Cook over high heat, stirring, until
golden brown on all sides. Add mushrooms, onion, carrots, 4 cloves
garlic and tomato paste, and cook, stirring, until vegetables are
tender, about 10 minutes. Add { cup wine and simmer until it
evaporates. Add tomatoes, { bunch tarragon and { bunch thyme and
water to just cover. Simmer until reduced by half, about 1 hour.
Strain, pressing on solids. Discard solids.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place loins on a work surface with cavities facing up. Lay
remaining thyme and tarragon and remaining garlic on centers of
each of loin. Roll up loins so that filling is enclosed and tie
with kitchen twine.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. In a large, oven-proof skillet
over high heat, heat remaining oil and butter. Add loins and hind
legs and sear until golden brown, adding salt to taste. Place
skillet in oven and roast 5 minutes. Turn rabbit pieces, reduce
temperature to 425, and roast until meat is slightly pink at bone,
15 to 20 minutes. Transfer rabbit to a platter (reserving skillet
and its drippings) and cover with foil to keep warm. Let rabbit
rest 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. To finish sauce, place skillet with drippings over medium
heat. Add shallots and saute until tender, about 5 minutes. Add
remaining wine and cook until it evaporates. Add sauce and simmer
10 minutes. Strain sauce, pressing hard on shallots.
</P>
<P>
   5. While sauce simmers, prepare polenta. In a medium saucepan,
simmer milk. Add polenta and salt, whisking well, until polenta
absorbs milk but is still soft, 5 to 7 minutes. Stir in cheese and
butter. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   6. Cut twine off loins and remove garlic and herbs. Carve loin
meat off bones. Arrange loin and leg meat over polenta. Pour sauce
around meat and serve. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1624EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9501 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TEACHER-TESTS08-COX     03-07 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-TESTS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEACHER TESTS DON'T MEASURE COMPETENCE, PANEL SAYS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Today's teacher-licensing tests don't predict
whether a teacher will do well in the classroom, the prestigious
National Research Council reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The tests ``are not designed to predict who will become
effective teachers,'' concluded a panel of academic experts headed
by chemical physicist David Z. Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The educators and researchers on the panel were chosen by the
council, which is administered by the national academies of
science, engineering and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The number of states that test people seeking licenses to teach
in public schools rose from three in 1977 to 44 in 1987, and has
remained steady at 41 in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A federal law designed to shame bad teacher colleges into doing
a better job will go into effect next year. Passed unanimously by
Congress in 1998, it will require states and colleges to report how
many of their education students pass their own state's
teacher-licensing tests.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel's findings raise doubts about the law's
usefulness:
</P>
<P>
   _ There is ``little evidence'' that the cut-off scores between
those who pass and those who fail such tests distinguish fairly
between those who are ``minimally competent to teach'' and those
who are not. In fact, most states cope with teacher shortages by
waiving the tests or lowering the passing scores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comparisons of passing rates among states ``are not useful for
policy purposes because of the diversity of testing and licensure
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Because teacher colleges differ in aims and student bodies,
differences in the passing rates of their graduates are ``difficult
to interpret as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tests find out whether someone is literate, can do simple
math, knows a particular subject or knows about ways to teach that
subject, said Robinson. But they don't show which practitioners
``will be successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly surprising, commented Penelope Earley, chief
lobbyist at the American Association of Colleges for Teacher
Education, which includes 735 public and private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, does the lawyer who had the highest score on a
state bar exam automatically become the state's best litigator?''
she said. ``Tests measure what an individual knows, not how an
individual applies the knowledge in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the panel's findings support schools of education that
oppose being judged solely by how many of their graduates can pass
state exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have the National Research Council _ a group
that might be perceived by those in the policy world as being more
neutral than we are _ saying that,'' Earley said.
</P>
<P>
   The council said that its full report would be posted on the
Internet shortly after 5 p.m. EST Tuesday at
http://national-academies.org.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
