<HEADER>
A9503 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     03-07 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FLIER'S GUIDE TO COMPLAINING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., March 12) 
(jt) 
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Complaints to the Department of Transportation about air travel
doubled from 1998 to 1999, rising to 20,495 from 9,608. The major
factor in the rise was the opening of electronic portals, including
those run by private companies that pursue passenger complaints.
Instead of having to write, copy an address and find a stamp,
disaffected consumers can send their grievances by clicking a
mouse.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Norman A. Strickman, assistant director for aviation consumer
protection in the Department of Transportation, said that
one-quarter of the complaints to his department were now arriving
electronically, either directly to the department's e-mail address,
airconsumer(at)ost.dot .gov, or through links provided by private
Web companies. Whatever level the numbers reach, the department
says, the content is steady, with flight delays and cancellations
ranking at the top, followed by service issues and luggage
problems.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., co-sponsor of the passenger-rights
legislation that was set aside in the face of airline pledges of
new policies, said in an interview that passengers ``have had a
bellyful.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are treated like cargo,'' he said. ``They have heard how
the industry was going to adopt voluntary programs, and they find
it is business as usual.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation does not adjudicate or mediate
the individual complaints it receives, although it can fine an
airline when it finds violations of the few remaining regulations:
deceptive advertising on fares, for example, or failure to
compensate travelers whose flights are overbooked and who are not
taken to their destinations within a specified time. The complaints
that come into the department are watched for patterns that might
lead to penalties, but verified civil rights violations tend to
bring immediate action against an airline.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right now, as a result of Wyden's amendments to a Department of
Transportation bill, the inspector general in the department is
monitoring the flow of complaints in two areas: finding the lowest
fare and overbooking.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress has asked for a report by the end of this year on the
impact of consumer-satisfaction programs established by the big
U.S. airlines on Dec. 15. There will be an interim report in June,
according to Scott Macey, the inspector general's project director
for the review of the airlines' customer-service commitments.
Complaints to the department are one yardstick for whether
travelers consider they are being badly informed, maltreated or
cheated. Government auditors have visited the airlines'
headquarters to learn how they do business, Macey said, and will
also visit major airports to see for themselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation's electronic mail basket had
been in service almost 22 months when the airlines presented their
consumer programs; it was set up late in February 1998. Of the
9,608 complaints and inquiries it got that year, just 626 arrived
by e-mail, the rest on paper or by telephone. In 1999, 5,650 of the
20,495 complaints came by e-mail. And almost half of these were
relayed by a site called passengerrights.com, a no-fee enterprise
set up by a travel agency in Florida. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is one of several Web sites harvesting complaints. At least
two new Web entrepreneurs will process consumer complaints for a
fee and seek compensation for their clients. There is usually no
reason travelers should not do this themselves, saving a $19.95 or
$25 fee. But if the choleric complaints sent as copies to this
department are any indication, the discipline of filling in blanks
and confining an account to one page is in short supply; a concise
account by a professional probably speeds the problem to the
cashier's window.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief tour of the electronic grievance gallery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Passengerrights.com is an offshoot of Global Travel
International, a travel agency with its telephone center in
Maitland, Fla. The costs of the Web site, according to Randall J.
Warren, who owns the agency with Michael A. Gross, are sustained by
subscriptions to the travel agency's monthly newsletter, Travel
Confidential, which costs $59 a year.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Complaints are forwarded to the airline involved, Warren said,
and to the Department of Transportation. ``We find out a lot from
the complaints,'' he said. ``For instance, a traveler told us she
learned after buying a ticket that Southwest Airlines does not take
pets, in the cabin or as cargo. So if a pet-owner wants to travel,
she needs to make other plans.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most complaints received through the Web site have to do with
misinformation. ``The gate people don't know anything,'' Warren
said. ``Passengers are told a ticket is not refundable, and it
is.'' The newsletter can be reached by writing to Post Office Box
940103, Maitland, Fla. 32794; (888) 802-8878; its separate Web site
is www.travelconfidential .com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1travel.com is another travel agency with complaint channels on
its Web site. These are an adjunct to its consumer-affairs
material, prepared by Terry Trippler, a travel writer and
publisher. The ``rules of the road'' link on the home page at
1travel.com leads to addresses of airlines' complaint offices and
to a hyperlink at the Department of Transportation. The site gives
advice on writing a complaint letter and emphasizes the importance
of sending a compliment when something goes right.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelproblems.com and complain.com are new enterprises that
will handle complaints for a fee. These organization do not handle
complaints that seem trivial; their work is based on the assumption
that the problem is serious enough to merit recompense from the
company _ cash, a voucher or frequent-flier miles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travelproblems.com was begun Nov. 17 by David Jarashow, a lawyer
in West Orange, N.J.. He charges $25 to process a complaint that
may yield up to $200; beyond that the fee is $50 plus a 20 percent
commission. When a traveler gets a response in frequent-flier
miles, Jarashow values them at $25 for a thousand miles _ ``what
the airline charges if it sells them,'' and sets his fee
accordingly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jarashow said that so far he had handled 80 complaints, with
about half resulting in a settlement for the consumer, and that he
had decided against pursuing many cases, some because they were
frivolous.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jarashow's experience is in mediation and arbitration and he has
also worked for an insurance company. The major complaint category
he encounters is canceled flights, ``long delays, with employee
rudeness.'' Runway confinements are the next category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He cites two cases. James Daly of Bensalem, Pa., returning from
London through Kennedy Airport last November, reported that the New
York-Philadelphia flight was canceled by American Airlines and he
ended up being bused to Philadelphia, a trip that took three hours.
American Airlines provided a $200 voucher in response to his
complaint. On the other hand, a Texas woman who ordered a ticket on
priceline.com was booked to Denver instead of Aspen last July.
After Jarashow took up her case, she was told that a credit would
be put through in two billing cycles. Three cycles later, it had
not yet been put through. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Complain.com is based in Mountain View, Calif., and charges
$19.95 to handle a complaint, regardless of the outcome. The
company takes complaints only after a traveler's first effort has
failed, according to Steven Ericsson-Zenith, the founder. It gets
payment by credit card before the complaint is acted on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since it started in June 1999, the company has handled about 100
complaints. Priscilla Harriman, who learns the details and packs
them into a one-page complaint, said that about half had produced
results. But since the responses go directly to the consumers, she
does not always know the outcome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most complaints are directed to airlines, Harriman said, but
hotels and car companies are also high on the list. Complain.com
handles any complaints involving a product or service. ``We do not
get into legal questions,'' she said. ``We are quite experimental.
A lot of companies are springing onto the Web.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Better Business Bureau of New York has gone on the Web, too,
at www.newyork.bbb.org. There is no charge for using this. Jennifer
Dikes, an information and investigation specialist, said that the
bureau relays complaints to the Department of Transportation when
it sees patterns _ particular companies, particular types of scams.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Department of Transportation, Macey said, there has been
an increase in complaints about airlines direct to the inspector
general's office. On Feb. 1, it set up an electronic in-basket for
complaints about two particular topics, pricing and overbooking,
called www.oig.dot.gov.
</P>
<P>
   The entry ``airline overbooking/air fares'' provides forms to
use. The airlines understand, Macey said, that these particular
complaints made direct to the inspector general in this period will
be followed up with the airline within 60 days. Forms are also
available by phone: (800) 884-9190. Complaints can be mailed to
Department of Transportation, Office of the Inspector General,
JA-2, 400 Seventh St. SW, Washington, D.C. 20590.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
