<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, March 8. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PAKISTAN (Washington) _ President Clinton will stop in
Pakistan on his trip to South Asia this month, the White House said
Tuesday in a terse statement that gave no hint of the decision's
difficulty. The White House said details of the visit are still
being worked out with Pakistan's government, which is run by the
military leaders who seized power in a coup last fall. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MEDIA (Johannesburg) _ The South African Human Rights
Commission holds a hearing on racism in the media; some see this as
part of a government effort to pressure the press into more
favorable coverage. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-UNREST (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Dozens of people were
injured in shootings and grenade attacks in the divided town of
Mitrovica on Tuesday, among them up to 20 French peacekeepers and
both ethnic Albanian and Serb civilians. What began as a street
brawl escalated rapidly into a number of retaliatory attacks
between ethnic Serbs and Albanians, catching the peacekeepers in
the middle. The violence comes on the back of a whole month of
serious disturbances, which have caused at least nine deaths in the
town, and dashed hopes of the international community that the
worst was over. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ELN-REPUBS (Undated) _ A ledeall on the Republican race. By
Richard L. Berke. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Bush and McCain, NYT10-11.
</P>
<P>
   ELN-DEMS (Los Angeles) _ A ledeall on the Democratic race. By
Adam Clymer. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos of Gore, NYT1, and Bradley, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   ELN-ASSESS (Undated) _ A news analysis on the state of the
presidential race. By R.W. Apple Jr. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   ELN-GORE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ With Al Gore in his home state;
the scene at his headquarters and a look at how he got where he
finds himself now. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Blue-chips extended their slide as worries
about the earnings outlook for consumer companies pushed market
indicators down. Shares of Procter &AMP; Gamble, the culprit in the
earnings fears, declined 28 1/8, to 59 5/16, and the selloff
extended to blue-chip issues in related areas. The Dow industrials
closed off 347 points. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-DRESDNER (Frankfurt, Germany) _ In the most radical
example yet of corporate restructuring in Europe, Deutsche Bank of
Germany plans to acquire Dresdner Bank in a deal worth more than
$30 billion. Deutsche Bank, already the world's biggest bank, would
become a powerhouse with more than $1.2 trillion in assets, twice
the volume of Citigroup. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
</TEXT>
