   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 5 p.m., Fri., March 10) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS 2000: Check the mailbox. There's a form in your future _
and it could change your life. Every 10 years, the government
conducts a head count of America. It may sound like a dull
exercise, but the results help determine how you are represented in
Congress and the state legislature and how federal and state money
is distributed to your city and school district.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CENSUS: RACEMIX: For the first time, the census is
allowing people to identify themselves as more than one race. The
expanded choices raise questions about how the data will be used.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CENSUS: UNDERCOUNT: In 1990, an estimated 8 million people
were missed while 4 million were counted twice. What were the
ramifications of the deficient count?
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CENSUS: FACTS: Facts about the 2000 Census.
</P>
