<HEADER>
A9511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      03-07 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THERE's A LITTLE SPOT I KNOW IN PARIS ...  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ One of the best wine lists in Paris is at a little place
up an alley near the Bastille. Not a blind alley, because it has
entrances at both ends, but what's called a passage. Specifically,
the Passage de la Bonne-Graine, and the place with the great wine
list is called _ inevitably, perhaps _ Le Passage.
</P>
<P>
   About to celebrate its 10th anniversary next month, Le Passage
was for most of its early years a secret among Paris wine lovers.
Never advertised, and hidden behind two of the busiest streets in
the east end of the city, the Rue du Faubourg St.-Antoine and the
Avenue Ledru-Rollin, it could never attract walk-in business. There
are locals and visitors who report looking for it in vain.
</P>
<P>
   And that is just the way Soizik de Lorgeril, the owner, likes it
(Soizik is a Breton name). With no previous restaurant experience,
she opened the tiny wine-oriented restaurant because she was tired
of the public relations business.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, with the new Opera de la Bastille under
construction, the area was beginning to change. Clubs, restaurants
and galleries began to move into empty storefronts and
long-abandoned lofts and ateliers. She and her husband, Gerard
Pantanacce, a decorator, lived in the neighborhood and were caught
up in the creative ferment.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our friends were urging us to do something different, and
this is what we chose,'' she said simply.
</P>
<P>
   Pantanacce kept his day job, doing apartments and lofts for the
writers, media and advertising people who are making the area the
SoHo and the TriBeCa of Paris. Four years ago, with Le Passage
doing well, he abandoned his swatches and sketches and opened a
little restaurant and nightclub around the corner from Le Passage,
called Le Cafe du Passage. It has a smaller menu, lots of wine by
the glass, an exceptional list of single malt whiskies and a lively
retail wine business.
</P>
<P>
   Le Passage has a longer wine list, but in fact the two are
interchangeable. At Le Passage, many of the wines are listed on two
big blackboards _ the place is too small for any more _ and in a
formidable printed list enhanced with articles on some of the
restaurant's favorite producers. The current list features a long
article, in English, about Alain Graillot, a relatively new
winemaker in Crozes-Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the wine expert,'' Ms. de Lorgeril said of her husband.
``I run the restaurant.'' Perhaps, but she is more than ready to
discuss the differences between, say, a Cote-Rotie from Pierre
Gaillard and one from Jean-Michel Gerin. Or to explain how Auguste
Clape makes his Cornas and how Robert Michel makes his.
</P>
<P>
   Pantanacce, when he isn't conducting Saturday morning tastings
at the cafe, may be giving a wine lecture in Denmark or visiting
winemakers in the Loire or Burgundy or in the Rhone Valley.
</P>
<P>
   When I stopped in to the cafe the other afternoon, Pantanacce
was getting ready for the 5 o'clock opening. Spread before him on a
table was a group of large, striking photo portraits of some of his
friends in the Rhone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down there last month for the annual fair of producers
in the Cote-Rotie area,'' he said, ``and I hired a photographer
with an old-fashioned portrait camera to get these pictures.''
Among the subjects were Graillot, Gerin, Gaillard, Francois Villard
and the brothers Jean-Luc and Jean-Paul Jamet. Soon the cafe's back
room will be a gallery of winemaker portraits. Pantanacce has not
completely abandoned his decorating skills.
</P>
<P>
   While Rhone wines predominate at both Le Passage and the cafe,
there is no lack of alternatives. The Burgundy list includes
Jayer-Gilles, Armand Rousseau, Denis Mortet, Comtes Lafon and Louis
Jadot. The Bordeaux list is short but distinguished, and there are
wines from every important area in France. Italy, Spain, South
Africa, Austria and Portugal are also represented.
</P>
<P>
   Should you find yourself in Paris this Saturday with nothing to
do, Patanacce will be staging a tasting of wines from California,
Italy, the Loire Valley and Beaujolais. On March 18, he will be
focusing on Jadot Burgundies.
</P>
<P>
   Le Passage is at 18 Passage de la Bonne-Graine. Le Cafe du
Passage is at 12 Rue de Charonne, both in the 11th arrondissement,
both a short walk from the Place de la Bastille.
</P>
<P>
   Even if wine were not the principal attraction at Le Passage, de
Lorgeril's food would be worth noting. She specializes in, of all
things, andouillette. For the uninitiated, andouillette is a
pungent sausage made mostly from pig's intestine. Central though it
may be to traditional French bistro cooking, andouillette is, as
they say, an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   Le Passage is probably unique in the world in featuring eight
kinds of andouillette, each from a different part of France. My
favorite comes from a M. Hardouin in Vouvray, a little more intense
in flavor than some of the others.
</P>
<P>
   Served grilled with a bit of mustard and a gratin dauphinois, it
is, well, perhaps not quite fit for a king, but delicious _ once or
twice a year. With what wine? Andouillette needs a strong wine to
tame it. I'd try any one of Le Passage's Cote-Roties, perhaps the
1995 from Mathilde and Yves Gangloff. Le Passage's better wines are
not inexpensive: this is about $80.
</P>
<P>
   For clients on a budget, de Lorgeril offers a delightful young
red from Auguste Clape for about $18. It's called Le Pas Sage,
which means, loosely, the smart move. Little French joke there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
