<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING ENTRY-LEVEL PORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Only two things stand in the way of regularly
enjoying the glories of vintage port: time and money.
</P>
<P>
   Time, because if you buy a vintage widely available now, like
1994 or 1997, the bottle will usually need a lot more aging, maybe
as much as 15 years from the vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Money, because if you can find an older bottle that's ready to
drink, say a 1977 or a 1983, it could cost $100 or more. Not a bad
value, perhaps, compared with a fine aged Bordeaux, but still not
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an excellent alternative to vintage port: aged
tawny port, which not only can be wonderful in its own right, but
is less expensive than vintage and is finished aging by the time
you buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage port is made only every few years, when makers consider
a single harvest to be exceptional. After a couple of years in
barrels, it is bottled and ready for years of aging. Tawnies are
blends of wines from years that were not declared vintages. They do
their aging in barrels or vats so that when they are finally
bottled they are ready for drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Don't confuse aged tawny, which is 10, 20, 30 and sometimes 40
years old (and labeled as such), with simple tawny, a wine that
achieves its tawny color not from aging, but by the mixing of pale
and dark wines.
</P>
<P>
   A well-aged tawny can be complex and delicious, offering
balanced sweet and spicy flavors from caramel and chocolate to
cinnamon, cloves, figs and mint. For my list, I concentrated on
10-year-olds, which, at $20 to $30 a bottle, are the entry-level
aged tawnies, but I also added a couple of 20-year-olds for
comparison's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Even tasted blind, the older tawnies easily stood out as
smoother and rounder with a wider spectrum of flavors. The younger
ones were sweeter and more concentrated but less wily, giving you
everything they have immediately instead of allowing flavors to
unfold over time.
</P>
<P>
   The six tawnies in the accompanying table are listed in order of
preference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAYLOR FLADGATE 20-YEAR-OLD $50 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pale reddish brown with chocolate and cinnamon flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COCKBURN 20-YEAR-OLD $38 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellow-orange hues; spicy, herbal, caramel and anise flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FONSECA GUIMARAENS 10-YEAR-OLD $28 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rich and seductive, with aromas of chocolate, caramel and figs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUINTA DO NOVAL 10-YEAR-OLD $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More red than brown; sweet caramel aroma. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROZES INFANTA ISABEL 10-YEAR-OLD $28 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brownish red; sweet mint aromas, rich, thick fruit flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COCKBURN 10-YEAR-OLD $30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruddy brown; spice and chocolate flavors with a hot alcohol
finish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices are those paid in various Manhattan wine shops. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
