r e BC-OSCAR-BALLOTS-SNAFU-L     03-07 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-BALLOTS-SNAFU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HED GOES HERE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If someone out there stole about 4,200 Oscar ballots in hopes of
stuffing the ballot box and creating a surprise outcome at the
March 26 ceremony, the motion picture academy says forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences and
its accounting firm, PricewaterhouseCoopers, were preparing to mail
new ballots to its California members to replace the batch
apparently lost by or stolen from the Beverly Hills post office
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The original ballots were delivered by PricewaterhouseCoopers on
March 1 during one of several pre-Oscar photo opportunities.
Academy spokesman John Pavlik said their disappearance came to
light Saturday during the Scientific and Technical Awards event
when some members asked why they hadn't received them. (Ballots to
out-of-state and foreign addresses were mailed a week earlier with
no problem.)
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, Pavlik has been checking with various California
academy voters, and none had received a ballot. Meanwhile, postal
employees have been searching as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what happened either,'' Pavlik said. ``This
has gone all the way to Washington, as I understand it. Somebody
told me they have inspectors opening every bag of mail in the
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the search continued Tuesday, the academy was pressing
forward with a new mailing that was to go out late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reprinting new envelopes with new numbers,'' Pavlik
said. He said the revised return envelopes will be yellow, while
the originals were white, making it easier for the accountants to
sort out any bad ballots that may come back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``PricewaterhouseCoopers keeps track of each ballot,'' he said.
``They know who they went to and who should be sending them back.
If somebody thought they could grab a handful of ballots and start
stuffing the box, it won't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ballots we get back will be actual ballots from voting
members, and we'll be back on track by tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the current schedule, voters have until March 21 to
return their ballots. He said it's possible the accounting firm
will extend the deadline by a day or two if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess that we'll get together after this and see how
we can keep it from happening again,'' Pavlik said. ``If it turns
out that someone stole them, and we find out about it, yeah, we'll
prosecute them, you betcha.''
</P>
<P>
   However, unless there is evidence of theft or deliberate
destruction, he said, the academy will dismiss it as ``a simple
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the academy had a ballot mailing snafu was in 1982
with nomination mailers. When the post office found them, officials
there agreed to send them special delivery. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
