<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9519 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-GOD-THE-DEVIL-FEAT     03-07 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOD-THE-DEVIL-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOD, THE DEVIL' AND THE JOURNALIST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give the people at NBC credit _ in their efforts to draw
audiences, they've pulled in some pretty heavy hitters this past
season. First, they hired the President of the United States to
star in their hit drama ``The West Wing.'' And now, they've
recruited both God and the devil to grace the new animated comedy
``God, the Devil and Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God et al.'' concerns Bob (voiced by French Stewart), a
Detroit Everyshlub who becomes the battleground for a bet between
God (James Garner, naturally) and the devil (Alan Cumming). If Bob
can go against his instincts and bring a modest good to the world,
God wins the wager; if not, the devil wins. More importantly,
mankind loses.
</P>
<P>
   The show, premiering Thursday before taking up residence on
Tuesday nights, was created by Matthew Carlson, a former seminary
student who more recently busied himself with the devil's work _ or
whatever you want to call the failed sitcom ``Men Behaving Badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cumming, who describes his character as a ``snarling brat,''
says of the show, ``I just couldn't believe it was getting made _
it walks a fine line between shocking and hilarious.'' He adds of
co-star Garner, ``He's so funny. His parking space at the studio
reads, `James Garner: God.' So if we do another season, I'm
demanding my parking space read, `Alan Cumming: devil.'''
</P>
<P>
   We secured the ultimate interviews _ with God and the devil _
through their earthly intermediaries, Cumming _ a Tony winner for
``Cabaret,'' who has also played oily types in ``Titus'' and the
remake of ``Annie,'' and stole Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut''
by flirting madly with Tom Cruise _ and Carlson, the series'
Creator's creator.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What drew you to the project?
</P>
<P>
   GOD: I could tell you how much I wanted to try my hand at
comedy, but the truth is, I needed the money.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: I have so many friends already in television that it
seemed a logical progression to star in my own show. I think of
this as a fly-on-the-wall documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you consider your finest accomplishment and,
conversely, your biggest disappointment?
</P>
<P>
   GOD: My finest accomplishment is microwave popcorn. My biggest
disappointment would have to be Buckner missing that ground ball in
the `86 World Series. He asked for an easy grounder, I gave it to
him _ did he want me to catch it for him, too? Now you got me
started again ...
</P>
<P>
   The devil (discretely interrupting): I think my finest
accomplishment would be American television, and, in a funny way,
my biggest disappointment would be American television, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Q (to the devil): Do you feel that you're the victim of bad
press? Does God just have better publicists?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: God's always got the higher moral ground, obviously,
because he invented it. I don't think God's got publicists. I have
a slew of publicists, I have many friends in that world.
</P>
<P>
   Q What can you point to as absolute proof that you exist?
</P>
<P>
   GOD: My mailbox. Hey, I'm getting the Pottery Barn catalog _ you
tell me.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: The success of the Backstreet Boys. McDonald's.
Pokemon. Things like that _ get `em while they're young.
</P>
<P>
   Q What's your favorite part of L.A.?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: Well, L.A.'s my pride and glory, it's my finest work.
Geographically, it's an earthquake waiting to happen, and of
course, Hollywood was my idea _ and it's working very well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your idea of a perfect date?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: There's a scene in an upcoming episode where there
are nuns fighting, and I say, `Nuns kicking nun butt _ it doesn't
get any better than this.' So watching nuns fight would be a good
date.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Turn-ons?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: In everyone, there's a little bit of a mirror that I
see myself in, so that's a turn-on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Turn-offs?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: Marie Osmond. It switches off pretty quick there.
(Note: God, being God, had the good sense not to participate in
this part of the interview.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do you see yourself in five years?
</P>
<P>
   GOD: Running a string of yogurt shops. My friends tell me I
should aim higher.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: At the top. God will have retired by that time, and
I'll have taken over. I think I'd mature into the position but
never lose my inner child.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Favorite TV show?
</P>
<P>
   GOD: ``Maverick,'' for some reason. I couldn't tell you why.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' was a
stroke of genius, and I didn't have to do anything for that to
happen. All the things I think about people came out there. The
rise of the American game show, that occupies my time. I think
Regis was thrown out of heaven about the same time as me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Favorite music?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: Dolly Parton. She's a surprising, yet willing,
disciple. She sends subliminal messages in her music.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You two meet at an auto show at the beginning of the series _
what kind of car do you prefer?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: DeLoreans were one of my ideas that didn't quite go
through. I don't like SUVs; anything that's safe I'm not for. But,
of course, they kill other people. That's a really good thing. You
have fewer accidents if you're driving one, but more people die
when they're hit by one. So basically, you have to get one of those
or you're screwed.
</P>
<P>
   Q (to the devil): What did you think about ``Eyes Wide Shut''?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: It was a brave attempt, but obviously it only
scratched the surface. A brave attempt. Good try.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the biggest misperception about you?
</P>
<P>
   THE DEVIL: The biggest is that heaven is where all the good
people go. All the boring people go to heaven. All the cool people
go to hell.
</P>
<P>
   GOD: I've actually got tiny hands. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
