<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HAZZARD-MEMOIR-ART-2T     03-07 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAZZARD-MEMOIR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVELISTS' FRIENDSHIP DISTILLED INTO PROSE BEGINNING ON CAPRI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT12, is being sent. Nonsubscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was like a scene out of a Graham Greene novel. On
a rain-swept December morning in the late 1960s, the novelist
Shirley Hazzard was sitting by herself at a table in a cafe on
Capri. While working on a crossword puzzle, she overheard a
conversation at the next table. A man she recognized as Greene was
quoting the Robert Browning poem ``The Lost Mistress'' to a friend.
He reached the penultimate line, ``I will hold your hand but as
long as all may ... '' and was unable to remember the end of the
poem. After Hazzard had finished her coffee and the puzzle, had
paid her bill and put on her raincoat, she said, as if passing on a
coded message, ``The line is `Or so very little longer.''' Without
waiting for a response, she walked out of the cafe.
</P>
<P>
   That evening Hazzard and her husband, the biographer Francis
Steegmuller, were at their favorite Capri restaurant, as were
Greene and his friend. Years before, Greene had met Steegmuller in
New York. Now at last he knew the identity of the mysterious woman,
and he invited the couple to join him for dinner. Many dinners and
meetings followed. Before leaving the island that winter, Greene
paid Hazzard the ultimate compliment. He said, ``I'm glad I forgot
that line of Browning.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly the two novelists would have eventually met, but for
Greene, the manner of the meeting was tantalizing, and it opened
the door to what became a remarkable personal and literary
friendship that lasted for more than 20 years _ until his death in
1991. That friendship is the subject of Hazzard's new memoir,
``Greene on Capri.'' Meeting Greene, she said in a recent
interview, was one of those ``sheer strokes of destiny,'' chance
encounters that have defined her life.
</P>
<P>
   In most respects the two were opposites. Greene, a British
novelist of moral and psychological complexity, was known as a
difficult, often cantankerous figure. A former spy for British
Intelligence, he lived life on the edge of danger, and that became
the subject of many of his books.
</P>
<P>
   Hazzard, an Australian transplanted to the United States, is
marked by decorum in her private life and in her fiction. ``The
Transit of Venus,'' winner of a National Book Critics Circle Award
in 1981, and her other novels and stories shimmer with lapidary
language.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their disparities, the two writers shared common ground,
a love _ and a comprehensive knowledge _ of literature. They would
quote freely from favorite texts, as Hazzard continues to do in the
normal course of conversation. ``We will not see someone like
Graham again,'' she said. ``He belongs to a great past in our
literature, which is not past, which will go on forever. How
exciting it was to be with him because of the unexpected
illuminations, the lightning that was always striking.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene has been the subject of harshly critical books as well as
Norman Sherry's authorized biography. In her memoir, Hazzard
catches him off guard in moments of conviviality as well as
animosity, and offers an intimate, understanding view of what she
calls ``a labyrinthine man'' and ``an octagon'' of a personality.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait is filled with apparent contradictions. Greene
could be rude to friends or, conversely, polite to strangers,
although sometimes, she said, he would lash out at an interviewer
or a photographer. Everything had to be ``on his terms.'' Hazzard
explained that Greene exercised a certain discipline over his life
in order ``to live very simply and to dictate how he would dish out
his time.''
</P>
<P>
   His home on Capri was a sanctuary for work, whereas Hazzard was
there also because of the splendor of the environment. Greene, she
said, was not interested in having a visual experience and had no
patience with pleasure. ``It cloyed very quickly,'' she said. ``He
was born to want to suffer. I've quoted him on that: `I feel
discomfort, therefore I am alive.' There was a vein of a suicidal
feeling for all his life. Yet he lived to be 86 and very
productive, but if he had not been productive he could not have
lived.'' Asked why Greene wrote, she quoted Trollope: ``To deliver
my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she switched to Shakespeare: ``Hamlet says, there was a
kind of fighting in my heart that would not let me rest. There was
a kind of fighting in Graham's heart. You respected that, and as he
got older, he was still engage.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of his anger and his willfulness, he sometimes
seemed to be testing the limits of friendship. ``People withdrew
and then they would make up or perhaps he would make the
rapprochement.'' At least once Steegmuller said to his wife, ``We
are not here to indulge him.'' But their friendship endured.
</P>
<P>
   Greene had a blind spot when it came to most female writers,
firmly declaring that he had not read _ and obviously had no
intention of reading _ ``Pride and Prejudice.'' Hazzard said that
he had a greater interest in writers like Beryl Bainbridge and
Muriel Spark, who were distinguished by their astringency and
asexuality.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she met Greene, Hazzard had written several books.
In the course of their friendship he commented on her work. She
said that he liked ``People in Glass Houses,'' her sardonic stories
drawn from her days working at the United Nations, and her novel
``The Bay of Noon,'' but something bothered him about ``The Transit
of Venus.'' She recalled, ``He said repeatedly that it had
wonderful reviews, which is like saying it had a beautiful cover.
There are a couple of remarks of his in the book that he might have
recognized, and that wouldn't have pleased him.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in their relationship, Greene talked about academic
theorists as ``wounded people'' who needed special attention. ``One
has to be specially nice to them,'' he said, adding, ``as one is to
Indians and women.'' That, she said, ``was a sign of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   His reaction to Indians remains obscure, but his attitude to
women was clear though double-edged. She said he was resentful ``of
their hold on his life'' at the same time ``he needed their
adoration.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a long marriage, he had a series of infidelities,
including his affair with Catherine Walston, the inspiration for
the character of Sarah Miles in his novel ``The End of the Affair''
(played by Julianne Moore in the current film). In life as in
fiction, the romance continued with the knowledge of the woman's
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Hazzard never met Walston, but in the years before she knew
Greene she would see the two of them together on Capri. ``By that
time she was not young anymore, but she was very good-looking,''
she said. ``I don't know how to say this, but she was the
incarnation of Woman, like some mature Venus _ so pleasing,
intelligent, delightful company and yet always the sensual
vibration.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene wanted to divorce his wife and marry Walston, but she
refused to leave her husband, which caused Greene to threaten
suicide. Subsequently he had a long liaison with Yvonne Cloetta,
who for years accompanied him to Capri.
</P>
<P>
   After her meetings with Greene, Hazzard made no notes, except to
mark the dates in her appointments book, but she and her husband
would talk about what was said and the words and images would be
firmly recorded in her mind. Asked if she had a photographic
memory, she said: ``It's extremely selective. I remember what
interests me and what I like, and, unfortunately, things I'm
ashamed of.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Then she traced the genesis of her memoir. After Greene's death,
she received a letter from his friend Michael Richey recounting
their first meeting on Capri and asking the name of the poem that
brought them together. About the same time, Sherry, working on his
biography, asked her for her memories of Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recollections came pouring back,'' she said. She put aside her
novel in progress and began writing the memoir. As she talked about
it, she went on about Capri and about her husband, then suddenly
wondered how she had come to this point in the conversation.
Reminded that she had been asked about her memory, she laughed and
said, ``I forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she recalled a scene in a Laurel and Hardy movie about the
Foreign Legion, in which each soldier is asked why he joined and
what he wanted to forget. When the question finally arrives at the
two clowns, they look at each other blankly: they had already
forgotten what it was they wanted to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hazzard has known many other celebrated literary
figures, she said, ``Greene on Capri'' will be the only book of its
kind for her. Besides being about Greene, it is her celebration of
Capri and, she said, ``a love letter to the life I had with my
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Since her husband died in 1994, she has continued to return to
Capri and to Naples every year, splitting her time between Italy
and Manhattan, where she lives in an apartment filled with art,
mementos of her earlier travels and books. In her study are several
shelves of works by her friend Graham Greene.
</P>
<P>
   She is eager to finish her next novel, which she has been
working on for years. Asked what it was about, she said, ``As
always, it's about life, love, death, God.'' As with ``The Transit
of Venus,'' it is set around the world, including a section on the
Far East, where she lived with her parents after they left
Australia. When finished, it will be her first novel since ``The
Transit of Venus.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about her husband and about her friendship with Greene,
she remembered a line from her last novel: ``Past, past, past, that
can turn even the happiest memories to griefs.'' ``When I wrote
that,'' she said, ``I thought I understood it, but I understand it
much better now.'' As she has found, a flood of memories can lead
to ``a great sadness of mortality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
