<HEADER>
A9527 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BOOKS-STAGGERING-GENI     03-07 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-STAGGERING-GENIUS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB BUZZ BOOSTS `STAGGERING GENIUS' AUTHOR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In much the same way that ``The Blair Witch Project'' became a
huge hit due to its Internet component, author Dave Eggers is
successfully exploiting the Web to hawk his book, ``A Breathtaking
Work of Staggering Genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Eggers' critically acclaimed book offers a most ambivalent,
ironic take on the memoir genre: The author spends a lot of time
fretting over and making fun of how he's exploiting his own pain
for financial gain. Eggers writes of the death of his parents, who
both succumbed to cancer within weeks of one another, and how he,
as a fresh college graduate, took it upon himself to bring up his
7-year-old brother.
</P>
<P>
   Much to his apparent dismay, Eggers has become a media darling _
though the title of his book is jokey, intentional bravado, it has
clearly done its work and focused a lot of attention upon him.
Since early profiles depicted the writer as reticent and laconic in
interviews _ one even suggested readers would be doing him a favor
by not buying his book _ Eggers has been canceling press interviews
right and left. No matter: The Internet, which doesn't require face
time with actual people, is doing his promotional work for him.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers is also the editor of McSweeneys, a quirky literary
magazine (like its editor, it's nearly impossible to get ahold of)
whose Internet component (mcsweeneys.net) has been charting the
progress of his book-signing tour, which passed through Los Angeles
and Pasadena last week. His book signings have taken on the patina
of performance art: At one stop, he recruited an Auto Club
representative to lecture the assemblage on road rage, and he
sometimes takes requests _ fans call out numbers, and he'll read
from that page in his book.
</P>
<P>
   More ingeniously, McSweeneys has initiated a contest for fans:
Whoever submits the best fake ``review'' of ``Breathtaking Work''
to Amazon.com wins a free subscription to the magazine.
Participants must adhere to a couple of rules: They must give the
book five stars, and their review must be utterly confused and have
nothing to do with the actual book. Since the contest began, the
overworked editors at Amazon.com have caught on and have begun
deleting the most bizarre reviews, but they're still receiving a
deluge of contest entries.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers' travails have also been turning up with regularity in
the Obscure Store and Reading Room (obscure.com), a daily
compendium of oddball and media-related news. And Modern Humorist
(modernhumorist.com) has concocted an inspired parody blending the
season's biggest literary phenomena, ``Harry Potter and the
Breathtaking Work of Staggering Genius,'' which describes, for
example, a game of Quidditch in the same luxuriantly florid
language Eggers reserves for playing with his Frisbee.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers' book is climbing the New York Times best-seller list,
currently at No. 12 in the non-fiction category; it's also put time
in in the top 10 of Amazon.com's updated-hourly compendium of top
sellers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9531 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-THEATER     03-07 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-THEATER-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITCHES OF UPDIKE FLYING TO LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., March 12) 
(jt) 
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is to replace ``Miss Saigon,'' which has just ended a
10-year run at Drury Lane? Since this is London's oldest, grandest
theater _ once owned by the dramatist Sheridan, who sat drinking
nearby as it burned down and famously remarked, ``Surely a man may
take a glass at his own fireside'' _ the answer is as important as
it is surprising. The impresario Cameron Mackintosh is presenting a
new musical by two Americans, John Dempsey and Dana P. Rowe, based
on John Updike's novel about New England witches who use martinis
and peanut-butter brownies to conjure up a demonic Lothario to be
played by Ian McShane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Witches of Eastwick'' arrives on July 18, and is the
climax of a more-than-usually busy period for musicals in the West
End. After ``Lautrec,'' a celebration of the artist that boasts
music and lyrics by Charles Aznavour, opens at the Shaftesbury on
April 6 we get another large-scale show on a French theme, ``Notre
Dame de Paris,'' at the Dominion May 23. In between there is more
familiar stuff: Elaine Paige in a revival of ``The King and I'' at
the London Palladium on May 3 and an adaptation of the movie
``Singin' in the Rain,'' which comes to the National Theater on
June 8 from one of Britain's leading repertory theaters, the West
Yorkshire Playhouse in Leeds.
</P>
<P>
   The two big drama openings announced so far for the West End
this spring are Terry Johnson's version of the movie ``The
Graduate,'' which brings Kathleen Turner to the Gielgud as the
formidable Mrs. Robinson on April 5, and Nicholas Wright's
``Cressida,'' with Michael Gambon in the role of an actor and
talent scout. However, the setting isn't modern Shaftesbury Avenue
but the seedy, troubled London of 1630, when the Puritans were
readying themselves to close Britain's theaters and the Juliets,
Violas and Cressidas were still played by boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cressida'' is being staged at the Albery on April 4 by the
Almeida, the tiny north London theater that took Diana Rigg's Medea
to the West End and Broadway and followed the same route with Ralph
Fiennes' Tony-winning Hamlet. Indeed, Fiennes is again at the
forefront of the company's thinking. Starting April 12 and June 14
respectively, he plays Shakespeare's Richard II and Coriolanus for
the Almeida, this time at the Gainsborough, which is a large
disused film studio in Shoreditch, in the heartland of the Cockney
East End.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Almeida is so active and enterprising at the
moment you could almost call it the National Theater of the Fringe.
Among the productions it is scheduling for the summer are Richard
Eyre's staging of his own adaptation of Sartre's ``Dirty Hands''
and the British premiere of Arthur Miller's ``Mr. Peter's
Connections.'' But March 22 sees a still more notable opening at
the company's Islington headquarters, a double-bill comprising
Harold Pinter's first play, ``The Room,'' and his latest, the
yet-unseen ``Celebration.'' Since the dramatist, in my view still
Britain's most original, seldom produces new work these days, this
is sure to receive plenty of attention.
</P>
<P>
   But then so will the National Theater of New Writing, as the
Royal Court likes to call itself. How will this company, which has
just returned from a three-year exile in the West End, fare in the
Chelsea theater it has rebuilt at a cost of $43 million? We critics
are feeling quietly optimistic after sitting, like swells in a
vintage Bentley, in its comfy leather seats for Conor McPherson's
portrait of an alcoholic mortician, ``Dublin Carol''; but firmer
judgment must await Jim Cartwright's tough, brash ``Hard Fruit,''
which opens April 6, and the premiere in the Court's studio theater
a week later of ``The Force of Change'' by Gary Mitchell, who
specializes in even tougher, brasher plays set in his native
Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there's the real National Theater, which
has recently opened a fine adaptation of Tennessee Williams' ``Baby
Doll.'' That is to be followed by an updated version of Gay's
``Beggar's Opera'' on April 11; David Edgar's new play about
Hitler's favorite architect, ``Albert Speer,'' May 25; Alan Howard
in ``The Heiress,'' a well-tried adaptation of Henry James'
``Washington Square,'' June 13; and Alan Ayckbourn's new comedy,
``House and Garden,'' Aug. 9. Comedy, do I say? With his customary
display of dramatic bravura, Sir Alan is giving us twin comedies
about a village fete and staging them simultaneously in each of the
National's big, adjacent auditoriums. You and I spend one
performance in the Olivier and another in the Lyttelton while the
actors move between them, depending on whether their interlocking
scenes are occurring in a house or a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who enjoyed Sir Alan's ``Norman Conquests,'' which
consisted of three self-sufficient plays involving the events of
the same weekend as they occur in living room, dining room and
garden, will know that this outre idea can work well. It's not the
only oddity the National is offering this summer. Late in August
the theater starts previews of a ``Hamlet'' I myself am
particularly eager to see, since the prince will be played by Simon
Russell Beale, a brilliantly gifted actor but short, podgy and not
at all the ``glass of fashion and the mould of form'' described by
Ophelia. The other day, a fellow critic rather rudely said he
resembled Gertrude Stein.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a slimmer, taller Hamlet, he can be found from June
9 onward at the Globe, the replica of Shakespeare's original
theater that stands 300 yards farther along the Thames. Yet Mark
Rylance, who takes the part, is not the most conventional of
theater people either, since he played Cleopatra at the same
address last year and, as the Globe's artistic director, is
continuing a policy of gender-bending in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has seen many distinguished actors, from John Gielgud to
Ian McKellen, play Prospero in ``The Tempest'' in recent years, but
never, I think, an actress assay the Milanese magician. On May 26,
though, the beauteous Miranda will find she has a mother, not a
father _ and the lady will be the actress whom Tennessee Williams
once described as the finest in the world, Vanessa Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   But where's the Royal Shakespeare Company, Britain's prime
guardian of the dramatist's reputation? Out of London for much of
the summer. Nonetheless, early-season visitors to the capital will
still get the chance to see the bold and vigorous Antony Sher in a
fast-paced revival of ``Macbeth,'' which arrives at the Young Vic
from Stratford-on-Avon on April 27, as well as Adrian Noble's even
better received production of Chekhov's ``Seagull'' at the Barbican
from April 25. And anyone who ventures north to Stratford itself
will find some interesting, ambitious Shakespeare on offer.
</P>
<P>
   True, several of the more popular plays are being staged there:
``As You Like It'' on March 23; ``The Comedy of Errors,'' April 20;
``Romeo and Juliet,'' July 5. But the prime event in the RSC's
three Stratford theaters is ``This England,'' a millennial season
that starts March 29 and will eventually include all Shakespeare's
histories except ``King John.'' ``Richard II'' will be followed
April 19 by ``Henry IV Part One'' and June 29 by ``Henry IV Part
Two,'' each with the gloriously funny Desmond Barrit as Falstaff.
``Henry V'' comes into the repertory Aug. 31, with the three
``Henry VI'' plays joining it at some unspecified date afterward.
</P>
<P>
   And if you feel like venturing farther north, you'll find
another millennial event, a June-and-July staging in York's
cathedral, York Minster, of the city's medieval miracle plays,
among them the most powerfully realistic, painfully graphic
pre-Shakespeare drama of all, the ``York Crucifixion Play.''
</P>
<P>
   Go a bit farther, and, starting Aug. 13, there's the Edinburgh
Festival, whose most notable theatrical event this year promises to
be Calixto Bieito's production of Ramon del Valle-Inclan's
``Barbaric Comedies.'' Myth, superstition, sex and violence: the
setting is turn-of-the-century Galicia but could, I fear, be
turn-of-the-millennium anywhere at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
