<P>
   &UR; New Palm Island Resort Opens in the Grenadines &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tiny, remote Palm Island, in the Grenadines chain of islands
between St. Vincent and Grenada in the Caribbean, has a new upscale
beach resort, an all-inclusive cottage hotel named Palm Island.
</P>
<P>
   The previous resort on the island, the more rustic Palm Island
Beach Club, was bought and leveled by the developer of the new
property. Palm Island, open since Jan. 18, has a cluster of 40
units in 22 cottages, two open-air restaurants, a 90-foot long
free-form pool, and a private launch to whisk guests back and forth
from the small airport on Union Island, a 10-minute boat ride
through turquoise water.
</P>
<P>
   The 135-acre island has five beaches, coral reefs on three
sides, and three small mountains but has neither airport nor
automobiles and no other hotels. Transport is by golf cart or
bicycle. It is within sight of the Tobago Cays, a group of islets
with beautiful beaches protected by a snorkeling reef.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the cottages were built with local off-white coral
stone; the other five are on stilts. The decor is Indonesian with
dark hardwood from an Amazon forest and bamboo furniture. Fabrics
are Egyptian cotton in pastels and earth tones. The accommodations
have air-conditioning, ceiling fans and mini-refrigerators but no
telephones or television.
</P>
<P>
   Cuisine at the two restaurants is a combination of continental
and Caribbean. There are three walking trails and a tennis court
surfaced with artificial grass. High-season double rates at Palm
Island, (800) 345-0356 or (784) 458-8824, fax (784) 458-8804, start
at $670; from April 1, they begin at $550. That includes meals,
beverages, afternoon tea, the use of non-motorized water-sports
equipment and bicycles, one boat trip to the Tobago Cays, taxes and
service.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2002 Olympics Tickets To Be Sold on the Web &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Just about anything can be ordered on the Web, and beginning in
the fall, tickets for the next Olympic Games in the United States
join the list. Tickets.com, a Costa Mesa, Calif., company, has been
selected as the ticket-selling service for the 2002 Olympic Winter
Games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded in 1996, sells tickets to sports and
entertainment events, as well as airline and cruise tickets, at
www.tickets.com. It will also accept telephone and mail orders for
Olympic tickets; the phone number and address will be announced
later.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 tickets _ the total supply so far for United
States residents _ will be put on sale in October; on the Internet,
at www.saltlake2002.com. All orders received by Internet, phone and
mail will be included in a lottery-type selection, and the winners
will be notified no later than April 2001. A deadline for orders
for this first wave of ticket sales has not been set, nor have
details on payments for ticket orders.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining individual tickets will go on sale by Internet and
telephone in June 2001, with consumers able to choose specific
seats and receive immediate confirmation, and box-office sales
should start by January 2002. The Games are scheduled for Feb. 8 to
24, 2002. The Salt Lake Organizing Committee says that ticket
prices will range from $20 to $425, with 78 percent of the tickets
less than $100, and the average sport ticket $82.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dirty Tricks, Circa 1828, In a Nashville Exhibit &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Elect Jackson,'' an exhibition recounting the campaign in 1828
that led to Andrew Jackson's becoming the seventh president, opens
March 15 and runs through Nov. 10 at the Hermitage, Jackson's Greek
Revival mansion in Nashville. The campaign between Jackson and John
Quincy Adams made history as one of the dirtiest in American
politics and is credited with reviving the two-party system and
giving rise to the Democratic Party. It is also significant for the
fact that Jackson directed the campaign himself from the Hermitage
instead of deferring to party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As a major general in the War of 1812, Jackson, who was born on
March 15, 1767, became the hero of the Battle of New Orleans. His
admirers also called him Old Hickory; during the campaign hickory
leaves turned up everywhere, and hickory poles were raised in towns
throughout the country to show support for the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   On display are campaign artifacts like newspaper articles that
accused the Jacksons of adultery and a handbill that said Jackson
had soldiers executed without due process during his military
career. Also exhibited are campaign coins (a first for an
election), portraits of Jackson, song sheets, cartoons, lithographs
and excerpts from Jackson's writings.
</P>
<P>
   The Hermitage, accessible from Exit 221 of Interstate 40, is
open daily except Thanksgiving and Christmas from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
and attracts about 250,000 visitors a year. Admission, including a
two-hour tour, is $9.50 (reduced to $3 on March 15 in honor of
Jackson's birthday). The visit includes a 15-minute film, a stop in
the museum on the former cotton plantation, a self-guided
archaeology walk, Jackson's tomb, some of the original log cabins
on the property (one built to house slaves and another that was
home to the Jacksons before the mansion was finished), the Old
Hermitage Church and a tour of the mansion.
</P>
<P>
</P>
