<P>
   &UR; `Luisa Miller' to Open Spoleto Festival &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A new production of ``Luisa Miller'' will open the Spoleto
Festival U.S.A. in Charleston, S.C., on May 26. The Spoleto
Festival Orchestra's performance of the 1849 opera by Verdi will be
conducted by Yves Abel, the founder of the Opera Francais de New
York, and directed by Christopher Alden.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto, founded in 1977 by the composer Gian-Carlo Menotti, is
the American companion to the Festival of Two Worlds in Spoleto,
Italy. This year's U.S. festival is being affected by the
controversy over the Confederate flag, which flies over the State
Capitol in South Carolina. The state branch of the NAACP has
organized an economic boycott to protest the flag's continued
presence, and as a result Bill T. Jones and his dance company have
withdrawn from the festival. Nigel Redden, the general director of
Spoleto, said that although he personally opposes the flying of the
flag, the festival will go on.
</P>
<P>
   Major presentations in Charleston will include Gluck's
``Iphigenie en Tauride''; ``The Silver River,'' a new version of
the music-theater work by Bright Sheng with libretto by David Henry
Hwang, based on Chinese folklore; and ``Running Man,'' a
collaboration by the poet Cornelius Eady and the jazz composer
Diedre Murray. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Wachovia jazz series with Kurt Elling, Fred Hersch and Bill
Frisell; choral and orchestral concerts, and the annual chamber
music series led by Charles Wadsworth are also part of the
festival, which runs through June 11. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Courage and Her Children,'' Brecht's drama of war and
survival, will be presented by the Shared Experience Theater of
London. Nancy Meckler will direct the play and Kathryn Hunter, who
made a mark in the festival's 1991 presentation of ``The Visit,''
by Friedrich Duerrenmatt, will star. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the dance schedule, Les Grands Ballets Canadiens will perform
a program of ``Great Europeans'' (the choreographers Jiri Kylian,
Nacho Duato, William Forsythe). Susan Marshall and Co. pay tribute
to the new millennium, and Mats Ek's radically reconfigured ``Swan
Lake'' will be performed by the Cullberg Ballet troupe of Sweden.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, ranging from $17 to $60, can be ordered at (877)
386-7765. On the Internet: www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bauhaus Home Of Klee, Kandinsky Opens in Dessau &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Bauhaus, the progressive school of art, architecture and
design established in 1919 in Weimar, grew to its greatest fame
after moving to the industrial city of Dessau in 1925. In Dessau,
the architect and school founder Walter Gropius (1883-1969) created
the avant-garde, glass-and-concrete Bauhaus studio building in
addition to four smaller ``master houses,'' fashioned from
interlocking cubes, that served as residences for professors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the master houses, the restored two-family dwelling
occupied by the artists Paul Klee (1879-1940) and Wassily Kandinsky
(1866-1944) during their tenure as Bauhaus instructors, reopened to
the public last month. The interior walls have been repainted with
the 170 rainbow colors that Kandinsky and Klee used for its
original decor. Through May 7, the two-story house, at 69-71
Ebertallee, welcomes an exhibition of works by Klee and Kandinsky
from their Dessau period.
</P>
<P>
   While Bauhaus principles strongly influenced architecture in the
United States, where Gropius and his fellow Bauhaus luminaries
Ludwig Mies van der Rohe and Laszlo Moholy-Nagy emigrated after
Nazi persecution of the school, the Dessau campus was neglected
under the East German Communist regime. Its inclusion on the Unesco
World Heritage List in 1996 helped reinvigorate interest in the
site.
</P>
<P>
   The Klee-Kandinsky house can be visited in conjunction with the
restored Bauhaus studio building at 38 Gropiusallee, which is
presenting an exhibition called ``1929'' through April 24, with
photographs and documents exploring the development of the movement
and events of the period. The Klee-Kandinsky house is open Tuesday
to Sunday 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $4, at 2 marks to $1.
Contact (49-340) 6508 251 or www.bauhaus-dessau.de.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
