<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVELATION-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BOOK OF REVELATION': A PRISONER OF SEXUALITY, OUTWARDLY AND
INWARDLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A warning: ``The Book of Revelation,'' Rupert Thomson's new
novel, may produce a powerful disquiet in you. It may keep you up.
It may give you nightmares. In a quiet, straightforward,
unspectacular way, Thomson stirs emotions we usually try to keep at
bay, telling the story of an unnamed man who is kidnapped by three
women and used as a sex slave for 18 days. They release him, and he
then spends the five years of the novel's span trying to pick his
way through the psychic desolation his experience has caused.
</P>
<P>
   This might make ``The Book of Revelation'' _ or at least its
first half _ sound like a pornographic fantasy, and indeed it is
prurient in its raw, torture-chamber physicality. Thomson, an
English novelist who seems likely to become better known in the
United States than he has been until now, has produced an erotic
horror story, but there is nothing banal or sensationalist about
it. ``The Book of Revelation'' (whose mock-biblical title is itself
a satirical master stroke) delves uncompromisingly and with
lucidity into the mysteries of power and sexuality. His book
subverts the standard sexual classifications, forcing the reader to
experience his or her own fantastical, confused and forbidden
stirrings.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson begins with a narrative archetype: the man who goes out
for a bottle of milk and never returns. In the case of ``The Book
of Revelation,'' the man is an English dancer who works in
Amsterdam choreographing and performing for a successful company.
He lives with his girlfriend, a slender beauty named Brigitte, a
dancer in the same company. Life, in other words, is good, until
one day during rehearsals Brigitte runs out of cigarettes and the
dancer, while disapproving of her smoking, goes out to buy her some
more.
</P>
<P>
   On his errand, he sees three cloaked and hooded figures approach
him. Thinking that they are street-theater actors and harmless, he
stops to talk them. Suddenly he is stabbed by a hypodermic needle
and goes unconscious. When he awakens his wrists and ankles have
been chained to railings on the floor of a bare room with a
skylight. One of the three women stands over him. ``You belong to
us,'' she says. ``You're ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The archetype has always been powerful because it projects the
common terror represented when we dream about being naked in a
public place; it reminds us that what we normally experience as the
solidity of ordinary life is actually an abyss. To that generalized
dread, Thomson adds a fantasy of imprisonment, of balls and chains,
of the dungeon, but what is so clever about his particular
nightmare is its psychoanalytical sophistication. ``We don't want
you to suffer,'' a woman says to a man the three have chained to a
floor. They subject him to a creative series of erotic enticements
and punishments. In his utter powerlessness, he desperately strives
to avoid additional cruelty by ingratiating himself with his
captors and obeying their kinky demands.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously there is a reversal of the standard male-female sexual
pathology here and also a version of the Stockholm syndrome, in
which a captive person begins to identify with his captors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had reached a point where he had begun to feel as if his
fate was no more or less than he deserved,'' Thomson narrator
intones. ``There was nothing random or accidental about what had
happened to him. There was nothing unlucky about it. All those
years of performing on stage _ exhibiting himself ... What was
dance if it was not exposure of the body? It was as though he had
advertised himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the dancer is released and Thomson's story turns into
a kind of thriller, full of unexpected twists and turns and a sense
of danger lurking in the shadows. After a long period during which
he avoids anything having to do with his earlier life, the dancer
embarks on a campaign to find the women who imprisoned him. But he
acts entirely alone. His story is too fantastical to be believed,
but there is a deeper reason he does not tell it.
</P>
<P>
   During his imprisonment he was sexually abused by one of the
women, who whispered into his ear the dehumanizing obscenities that
male rapists are said to use on their female victims. Like many
female victims of rape, the dancer feels ashamed and vaguely
guilty. This is in part because of the humiliation and the
suffering itself. Even more so it is because the dancer knows that
in some secret and troubled part of himself, he took a measure of
unwanted and unexpected pleasure in the experience, and that
pleasure completed and perfected his powerlessness and subjugation.
</P>
<P>
   When the nightmare is over, silence is his principal response to
it, but not his only one. He also takes on some attributes of his
abductors. Sex for a time becomes dissociated from pleasure or
affection; it becomes a means to establish his power. Even when
that phase seems to reach a conclusion and he begins to regain a
healthier sexual persona, he remains caught between contradictory
impulses: to put what happened behind him and to get revenge.
</P>
<P>
   As these themes intertwine, Thomson's story becomes almost
unbearably suspenseful. It is impossible to know until literally
the last page whether the novel will turn on a piece of private
detective work or whether it will reach a more purely psychological
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson's spare narrative, not minimalist exactly but far from
Dostoyevskian, carries the story with deceptive ease, making its
psychological complexity almost imperceptible. But despite its
smooth, uncluttered form, ``The Book of Revelation'' casts a jagged
chill.
</P>
<P>
   It belongs to the Sadean and Freudian genre that plumbs the
darker and more perverse connections in the human mind. What makes
it extraordinary is Thomson's ability to draw the reader into the
dancer's emotional world, to actually experience the disturbing
connections between subjugation and guilt, cruelty and pleasure
that we normally like to keep, like sleeping dogs, undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BOOK OF REVELATION'
</P>
<P>
   By Rupert Thomson
</P>
<P>
   260 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
