<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-DANCE-$     03-07 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-DANCE-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPS OF AMBITION AND INNOVATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., March 12) 
(jt) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the European summer for those intrigued by Asian dance.
Homegrown dance will also be easy to find. There will be new work
by Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker and Lucinda Childs, the latter with a
text by Susan Sontag. Americans will be able to catch up on the
work of Maurice Bejart, rarely seen these days in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The award for sheer ambition should go this summer to the
Montpellier and Lyon festivals and to Julidans in Amsterdam. A
fitting start to the European summer dance season might be the
International Dance Day in Sweden on April 29, with more than 100
events around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions in Stockholm include the Royal Swedish Ballet in
Kenneth Kvarnstrom's offbeat ``Carmen?!'' at the Royal Opera House
and ``Exit'' by Petter Jacobsson, the company's director, along
with a new work by Ohad Naharin, open dance rehearsals, all-day
dance for children and dance by students in open squares and
subways. Also in Stockholm, ongoing programming in May at Dansens
Hus will include performances by the companies of Saburo
Teshigawara and Paul Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Montpellier Danse Festival International (June 20 to July 9)
celebrates its 20th anniversary with ``Modernism and the South,''
an exploration of Mediterranean and African modern dance alongside
companies from countries more traditionally known for the form.
Participants include Childs, Nacho Duato's Compania Nacional de
Danza, Jan Fabre of Belgium, Salia ni Seydou from Burkina Faso and
William Forsythe's Ballett Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   In Lyon, more than 20 modern-dance companies from China, India,
Taiwan, Korea and Japan will perform with their French counterparts
in the Ninth Biennale de la Danse (Sept. 8 to 30), commemorating
``The Silk Road,'' the 2,000-year-old commercial route between
China and Europe. Other French stops might include Le
Chore-graphique 2000 festival in Tours (May 17 to 21), a showcase
for the newest in French modern-dance choreography, and the
Festival d'Avignon (July 6 to 30), which will feature international
avant-garde dance.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a rich selection of folk dance in France at two
events in Brittany: the Festival de Cornouaille in Quimper (July 17
to 23) and the Festival Interceltique in Lorient (Aug. 4 to 13).
And homage will be paid to that loveliest and most austere of
Spanish folk dances, the sardanas, in the French Festival de la
Sardane in the streets of Ceret in Languedoc (July 28 and 29).
</P>
<P>
   Saburo Teshigawara opens the adventurous Julidans festival (July
3 to 22), now in its 10th year in formal and funky theater spaces
in Amsterdam. One triple bill explores the different ways that
Dutch and Japanese cultures work with senior dancers. The Dutch
Dansgroep Krisztina de Chatel will collaborate with the Japanese
multimedia collective Nest. Other companies and choreographers
include Dumb Type from Japan and Felix Ruckert from Germany, with
more dance from Italy, Spain and America.
</P>
<P>
   Serious experimentalists should head for Austria and
tanz2000.at-ReMembering the Body (July 12 to Aug. 13), co-presented
by the Vienna Festival and ImPuls Tanz, which aims to explore no
less than radical 20th-century concepts of movement from Vaslav
Nijinsky, George Balanchine and the Bauhaus on to American
postmodernism of the 1960s and '70s. From early May to mid-August,
the months surrounding the festival proper bring performances,
workshops and film and video screenings. There will be an
exhibition on Merce Cunningham and his work (May 5 to June 11),
open rehearsals and a video-based installation called ``Stress''
(May 17 to Aug. 27) that focuses on ``the complex choreography of
everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballet attractions promise a little light relief this summer,
starting with the Royal Ballet at the newly restored Royal Opera
House in London. Highlights include a ``New World'' program, with
Jerome Robbins' ``Concert,'' William Tuckett's new ``Crucible,''
based on the Arthur Miller play and set to music by Charles Ives,
and George Balanchine's ``Serenade'' (April 12 to May 4). ``The
Diaghilev Legacy'' (May 6 to 20) includes Bronislava Nijinska's
perfumed ``Biches,'' Nijinsky's ``Jeux'' and ``L'Apres-midi d'un
Faune,'' and Michel Fokine's ``Firebird.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in England, the Brighton Festival (May 6 to 28) will
present performers including the Chinese Guangdong Modern Dance
Company, Teshigawara, Jin Xing from Beijing, the Bill T.
Jones/Arnie Zane Dance Company from America and, from England,
Wendy Houstoun, the sharply perceptive performance artist, and
Wayne McGregor's Random Dance Company.
</P>
<P>
   Don't try to walk in London in June, when everyone promises to
be sashaying through the salsa, lindy and Javanese dancing. Those
are among the 30 styles in the free Feet First festival beginning
June 10 and running for five weeks at 15 theaters and studios
around the city. Organized by Arts Worldwide, Feet First will end
on July 23 with a giant outdoor dance party in Finsbury Park, North
London. And at the venerable Edinburgh Festival in Scotland (Aug.
13 to Sept. 2), there will be performances by the Nederlands Dans
Theater and the modern-dance troupe of Mathilde Monnier of France.
</P>
<P>
   Spain will play host to the Bolshoi Ballet in performances of
``The Sleeping Beauty'' at the Gran Teatre del Liceu in Barcelona
(June 27 to July 2) and in late August, at the Festival
Internacional de Santander (Aug. 1 to 31), where the Russian troupe
will also perform ``Giselle.'' Modern dance will also be well
represented in Spain, however, in the Summer Festival of Barcelona
Grec 00 throughout the city, with the Merce Cunningham Dance
Company opening the festival's dance component with outdoor
performances at the Teatre Grec (July 19 to 21). Work by Cesc
Gelabert, Mar Gomez and Catherin Allard will be seen in the hallway
and women's garden of the Centre de Cultura Contemporania de
Barcelona (July 3 to 19), and by Tomas Aragay and Sonia Gomez at
the gaudily enticing La Paloma grand ballroom (July 6 to 16).
</P>
<P>
   In Denmark, the ballet choreographer Peter Schaufuss and his
company will present an unlikely-sounding program at the Ostre
Gasvaerk in Copenhagen that includes dances based on the film
``Midnight Express'' (May 23 to 26), on ``Hamlet'' (May 27) and on
the life of Elvis Presley (May 29 to June 4). Also in Copenhagen,
the Danscenen theater will present new modern dance by emerging
Danish, English and American choreographers (through June 15).
</P>
<P>
   The Icelandic dance hero Helgi Tomasson will return home with
his San Francisco Ballet to present ``Swan Lake'' at the Reykjavik
Arts Festival (May 26 to 28), followed by that clattering revue
``Stomp'' (June 27 to July 2), which is one of Reykjavik's Cultural
City 2000 events. And in early September, everyone will be invited
to participate in a dance choreographed for the Wind Festival 2000,
which celebrates the important role that the wind plays in nature
and culture in Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   In Finland, a dizzying variety of dance will be packed into the
weeklong Kuopio Dance Festival in pretty Kuopio (June 28 to July
4). The headliners include the ballet stars Irek Mukhamedov and
Carlos Acosta and the tap stylist Herbin ``Tamango'' Van Cayseele.
There will also be folk dance from Ireland, hip hop from America
and modern dance from England, Ireland, Scotland and Scandinavia.
</P>
<P>
   Modern dance will be imaginatively represented in Norway in the
48th Bergen International Festival (May 24 to June 4), opening with
Carte Blanche of Norway and continuing with Philippe Decoufle's
Compagnie DCA from France, the ubiquitous Teshigawara and the Paul
Taylor company.
</P>
<P>
   A new work from De Keersmaeker, known for the fierce
intelligence and theatricality of her dance, is always an occasion.
The premiere performances of her new work ``In Real Time'' at
Studio de Rosas in Brussels, co-produced by the Theatre de la
Monnaie, should warrant a stop on any dance itinerary.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
