<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9547 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BOOK-ILLUSTRATOR-HNS &LR;      03-07 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ILLUSTRATOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WORDS, DRAWINGS BRING ILLUSTRATOR MONSTEROUS SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPENCERTOWN, N.Y. _ Jacqueline Rogers lives in a cluttered
farmhouse with a couple of cats, a dog and an army of monsters,
critters and funny, saucy children. While some of these creatures
are three-dimensional (her two daughters, for example), many are
painted extensions of Rogers' deeply inventive, childlike
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers has illustrated more than 50 children's books, including
lively preschool stories such as ``Monkey See, Monkey Do,'' jackets
for chapter books, including the Amber Brown series, and picture
books filled with magical detail. She's worked with Jacqueline
Onassis and Sarah Ferguson, the Dutchess of York, as well as Boomer
Esiason and Danielle Steel.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest book, ``Fairies, Trolls and Goblins Galore,'' is her
third poetry picture book on the subject of scary beasts and the
children who love them. The short poems are beautifully illustrated
in rich, vivid watercolors, each picture packed with details like
tiny green fairies hidden in the grass or a scolding mother wearing
furry bear slippers, complete with claws. The children here are
dreamy and wise and capable of telling goblins from elves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play games in my books,'' said Rogers, sitting in
her home studio, a room off the kitchen with wide plank wood floors
and walls covered with watercolor paintings and charcoal drawings.
``I like to give kids lots of things to look at, because I remember
that from my childhood. I loved the books that every time I picked
them up, I found something new. And also, I remember feeling
overwhelmed by the feelings I would get from the pictures I looked
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Her enthusiasm for children's books has not diminished since her
own childhood. When she launches into a loving description of
several scenes from ``Go Dog Go,'' you want to run out and read the
1960s children's classic immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' work ranges from the folksy to the fanciful. ``I have a
real love for animals, so I have an animal direction,'' she
explained, offering as an example her book ``Best Friends Sleep
Over,'' which is the story of a young gorilla who spends the night
at the house of his friend the elephant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I have the saucy, feisty kid with the socks falling off.
You know, like my children. I get a lot of work for the kids' faces
and children's character pieces because I do them well. Then
there's the monster avenue, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, those pesky monsters.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what else Rogers was working on, somehow pages of her
sketchbook would be filled with drawings of trolls and dinosaurs
and other assorted beasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept appearing,'' said Dilys Evans, who has been Rogers'
agent for about 15 years. ``I finally said to Jackie, `We've got to
find a home for these guys. They're auditioning all the time for
parts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Dilys, knowing that I needed a vehicle for my monsters,
went desperately out to try and find a way to get my monsters
published,'' said Rogers, who talks about ``her monsters'' as if
they were some kind of furry and feathered cousins. ``They're
real,'' Rogers said, laughing. ``Those are soul creatures for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans began compiling children's poems, which Rogers then
illustrated with rich watercolor paintings. And thus her first book
for her creatures, ``Monster Soup and Other Spooky Poems,'' was
hatched in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love poetry books because every page is like a new story, so
you don't have the burn out of doing 32 pages about the same
situation,'' Rogers said. ``Everything is fresh and new. It's
always a challenge to tie them all together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Weird Pet Poems'' followed in 1997, about which The New York
Times Book Review wrote: ``From the collection's cover, in which
the letters of the title are decorated with snakeskin, animal fur,
even the face of a bulldog, Rogers' beasts exude personality.
Twinkling of eye, exuberant of pose, they manage charm without
cuteness.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, 41, grew up in Westport, Conn., the youngest of six
children, all of whom are artists. Her mother was a portrait
painter and her father was a gifted craftsman who owned a marketing
research company in New York City and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art was really promoted in my family. A lot of materials were
always around for me to use, and my imagination was just really
rich,'' Rogers said. ``I loved sci-fi growing up. Some of the first
things I drew were dinosaurs and bugs and monsters. I just loved
aliens and making up my own creatures. I couldn't just draw a
horse, I had to draw a horse that was in the army or was going to
camp or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went with my imagination. Of course, my imagination can
get me in a lot of trouble in my personal life too, but it sure
worked well in the art world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rogers always knew she wanted to be an artist. ``There was never
any doubt in my mind. I think in third grade I wanted to be a nurse
for about a week and that was it. It was art all the way without
question. And it was really the only thing I was really good at, so
it kind of made it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who is close to all her siblings, was especially
attached to her older brother Martin when they were growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I were joined at the hip. He was two years older,''
Rogers said. ``He had an incredible imagination. Every time I do a
picture book, he's in there. Something we played or some way he
dressed; his influence on me is always in there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of the tail end of the litter,'' said Martin
Rogers, now a sign painter in Westport. ``So we pretty much fended
for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair spent lots of time drawing together, even illustrating
their dreams. But by the time his sister was 5 or 6, Martin Rogers
said, her drawing ability had progressed well beyond his own. She
was producing pictures ``with excellent proportion and
perspective,'' he said proudly. ``I couldn't keep up with her in
that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave up drawing for fishing, but luckily for children and
fish everywhere, Rogers did not.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she studied art at Arizona State University, then the
Rhode Island School of Design. After graduating in 1981, Rogers
started illustrating immediately, ``but never with the intent of
going into children's books,'' she said. ``Being the youngest of
six, I had no experience with children. I didn't like them. I was
scared of them, actually. I would baby-sit and I'd be like'' _ here
she makes a praying motion _ ``Please be asleep, please asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a terrible baby-sitter. I just didn't relate to
children. Until my older brothers and sisters started to have their
own kids. Then I could play with them and give them back.''
</P>
<P>
   She began shooting photographs of all her nieces and nephews,
creating pictures for her portfolio of 4-year-olds (based on them)
feeding porridge to monsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became clear to me that I was leaning toward children's
books because that's what I liked to do for samples,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her ideas about children began to change, too. In 1986, Rogers
got married and had her first daughter about a year later. She and
her now ex-husband moved to Spencertown so he could be closer to
his job in Troy. ``We drove through it and fell in love with it,''
Rogers said of her adopted hometown, where she lives with her
daughters Martha, 12, and Emma, 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe what a change that was from being afraid
of children to absolutely loving them,'' said Rogers, shaking her
head. Now she volunteers at schools, teaching youngsters how to
paint, in addition to staying busy splashing her inner child on the
page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it. It's always a challenge to me. I know that I'm in
the right place when I'm scared to death to start a new book
because that's where I get my fire. That place of being afraid,''
she said. ``Then I know it's a challenge and there are obstacles to
overcome. Because if I'm too confident or too complacent, then it's
not going to have any zest to it. So I like to keep that nervous
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy in this field. I absolutely love my job.''
</P>
<P>
   And her children, pets and monsters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
