<SLUG> BC-VOTING-IN-CYBERSPACE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET TO REPLACE VOTING MACHINES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Arizona _ 16th graf)   (This 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD GREENWICH, CONN. _ About 6-ft. tall and almost as wide, they
look like a cross between a Wurlitzer, an old-fashioned telephone
board and some kind of end-of-the-pier one armed bandit.
</P>
<P>
   Pull the big red lever at the front, from left to right, and a
curtain will draw behind you. (When they are fully closed, a little
bell will ring.) It is the curtain that gives them away. These
contraptions, made of metal and mounted on wheels, are nothing more
mysterious than voting machines.
</P>
<P>
   Beloved for their creakiness and eccentric design, they have for
decades done their bit for American democracy. When ballots need to
be cast, out they come.
</P>
<P>
   There they were, for example, in the gym of Old Greenwich
Elementary School Tuesday, designated as Polling Station for
District 6 in Connecticut, one of 16 states that participated in
the ``Super Tuesday'' presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Although six had been installed, only three were in use. There
was one for Democrats, on the left of the gym, and, two to the
right, for the Republicans, who are more numerous.
</P>
<P>
   The person responsible for the station is 70-year-old Tony
Hayden. His title is ``moderator'' and his first task at 5 a.m. _
the polls opened one hour later _ was to remove the little steel
seals from the machines and then take the four keys necessary to
get each one ready.
</P>
<P>
   The keys themselves are sealed in little manila envelopes. He
then checked that every machine was in good order and set at zero.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for Hayden, the choices Tuesday were entirely
straightforward. Once installed behind their curtain, Democrats had
only to press one of three little buttons on a large board. They
read Al Gore, Bill Bradley and ``Uncommitted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans had McCain and Bush to choose between, although
there were buttons also for candidates who have actually withdrawn,
like Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the choices can be much more numerous and that is when
the queues can begin.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, like New York, voters Tuesday had to choose
between slates of delegates representing the different candidates.
In others, such as California, there were also ballot issues before
the electorate, for instance on gay rights. Then the voting machine
boards can be crammed with dozens of buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the close of the polls _ 8 p.m., in Connecticut _ do the
machines reveal their secrets. Moderators take a fifth key and open
a panel at the back. Wherever there is a button, there is a counter
behind it, like an odometer on a car.
</P>
<P>
   They will record the total for each button _ candidate, delegate
or ballot question. These will then be phoned in to state election
offices where final results are tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden, a teacher, cannot say how long the voting machines have
been around, but it is surely a long time. He has been working the
polling stations in Greenwich since 1960 and they were here when he
started and they have never been modernized.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do they seem to help much with reducing labor. Ten people
were on hand to help Hayden Tuesday, each one paid $100 for a
15-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   Voting in America may not be quite so Dickensian for long. Far
away on the other side of the country Tuesday, Arizona was the
first state to make a leap from the age of the voting Wurlitzer to
voting in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, when the state will hold its Democratic primary,
voters in Arizona will be able to cast their ballots on the
Internet via their home computers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if things seemed less than frantic at Connecticut's
District 6 Tuesday, Hayden was unconcerned. (By 9:15 a.m. only 280
voters had passed by, of which 180 were Republicans and 100 were
Democrats.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know, for a primary, this is unusually active,'' he
commented contentedly. &QL; 
