the queues can begin.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, like New York, voters Tuesday had to choose
between slates of delegates representing the different candidates.
In others, such as California, there were also ballot issues before
the electorate, for instance on gay rights. Then the voting machine
boards can be crammed with dozens of buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the close of the polls _ 8 p.m., in Connecticut _ do the
machines reveal their secrets. Moderators take a fifth key and open
a panel at the back. Wherever there is a button, there is a counter
behind it, like an odometer on a car.
</P>
<P>
   They will record the total for each button _ candidate, delegate
or ballot question. These will then be phoned in to state election
offices where final results are tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden, a teacher, cannot say how long the voting machines have
been around, but it is surely a long time. He has been working the
polling stations in Greenwich since 1960 and they were here when he
started and they have never been modernized.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do they seem to help much with reducing labor. Ten people
were on hand to help Hayden Tuesday, each one paid $100 for a
15-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   Voting in America may not be quite so Dickensian for long. Far
away on the other side of the country Tuesday, Arizona was the
first state to make a leap from the age of the voting Wurlitzer to
voting in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, when the state will hold its Democratic primary,
voters in Arizona will be able to cast their ballots on the
Internet via their home computers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if things seemed less than frantic at Connecticut's
District 6 Tuesday, Hayden was unconcerned. (By 9:15 a.m. only 280
voters had passed by, of which 180 were Republicans and 100 were
Democrats.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know, for a primary, this is unusually active,'' he
commented contentedly. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
