<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERCRESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRESS: GREEN WITH AN ICY BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With food as with people, passion can lead to unintended
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Take watercress, for example. English cooks of the early
Victorian era were so mad about this spicy green that they even
pressed it into service as a sandwich filling.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the sandwiches in question were dainty, crustless
affairs featured at overly refined formal teas. As a result,
watercress became fixed in the public mind as a somewhat silly
food, the epitome of effete eating.
</P>
<P>
   But this typecasting is actually quite misleading. Watercress is
a green with real character, capable of standing up to a multitude
of culinary roles.
</P>
<P>
   To restore the more muscular reputation that watercress enjoyed
before it was caught in a web of Victorian manners, think of the
generals of ancient Greece, who commanded their troops to eat it as
a source of courage.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for a more modern source of inspiration, look to the cooks
of China and Southeast Asia. Although watercress originated in the
Mediterranean region and was not introduced to Asia until the 19th
century, cooks in those regions took to it with a passion,
stir-frying it with intense flavor accents and tossing it into
soups by the handful.
</P>
<P>
   You might also consider watercress as an alternative to those
Italian darlings of the produce market, radicchio and arugula, with
which it shares a characteristic boldness.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, watercress' generic Latin name, nasturtium, translates
roughly as ``twisted nose,'' a testament to the grimaces caused by
its pungent bite. But unlike many other members of the far-flung
mustard family (not to be confused with the garden nasturtium),
watercress also has a surprisingly cooling effect in the mouth that
makes it refreshing. Because its leaves are paper thin and tender
while its fleshy stalks have some real crunch, this green also
incorporates a pleasant textural contrast.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its purely sensual virtues, watercress is a
prototypically healthful food, rich in potassium, iron, folic acid
and vitamins A and C.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for growers, watercress spreads easily and requires
little care. The original hydroponic vegetable, it grows with its
roots in cold, fresh-running water. If you look carefully along the
shady bank of a spring or stream in early spring, you are likely to
catch sight of its bright green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The watercress found in produce markets is a cultivated variety,
grown in special watery beds. Today, good-quality watercress is
available at a reasonable price 12 months a year. During the
summer, wild watercress can be found at the Union Square
Greenmarket in Manhattan..
</P>
<P>
   Although there are many varieties of watercress, the differences
are subtle, said Andy Brown of B&AMP;W Quality Growers, a family-owned
business based in Fellsmere, Fla., that describes itself as the
world's largest producer of watercress.
</P>
<P>
   All varieties, he said, belong to one of two strains. The type
most common in the United States has the thick, juicy stems and
ovoid leaves preferred by Chinese-American cooks, who he estimates
buy 35 percent of all watercress sold in this country. The second
strain, most of which is sent to Europe, has thinner, more delicate
stems and more consistently round leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Both kinds are versatile in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   When raw, watercress makes an excellent lettuce substitute in
salads of all kinds. Because it brings a more substantial flavor to
the mix, it encourages the use of more intensely flavored
ingredients _ like ham or horseradish dressing _ than lettuce does.
</P>
<P>
   But our favorite way to use raw watercress is as a bed for meat
or fish. The freshness and gentle bite of the greens provide an
ideal balance to the richness of pork, for example, and somehow
make even a richly sauced meat dish seem rather light. We found
this to be true even when pork tenderloin is teamed up with other
rich ingredients like Madeira, olive oil, walnuts and blue cheese.
</P>
<P>
   As a cooked green, watercress is particularly well suited to
soups. The point at which you add it depends on the texture you
want.
</P>
<P>
   As with classic Chinese watercress soup, the cress can be added
several minutes before the end of cooking so that it becomes very
soft and tender. But we prefer the Southeast Asian approach, mixing
the watercress with other greens or herbs in a bowl, then dousing
them with hot stock just before serving. That way, the leaves
become wilted while the stems retain some vestigial crispness.
</P>
<P>
   Those strong stems are one reason watercress also responds well
to quick, high-heat cooking methods like stir-frying. Quickly
wilted by intense heat, watercress has a pleasant crisp-tender
texture, and its potent taste makes it a good match for strong
Asian flavorings like ginger, garlic and chilies.
</P>
<P>
   However you are going to use the cress, it should be washed
thoroughly but quickly and only when you are just about ready to
use it, since the leaves become soggy if soaked for very long.
</P>
<P>
   When choosing watercress, look for vibrant green color in the
leaves and a little crispness in the stems; if you bend a stem back
on itself, Brown said, it should snap just before it touches. The
flavor of both stems and leaves should be pungent but not bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Since the pungency of individual bunches of watercress varies
quite a bit, it is' also a good idea to sample a leaf or two before
buying the whole bunch. Obviously, avoid wilted or yellowish
leaves, which are signs of age.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clean watercress like other greens. Place it in a large bowl of
cold water and swish it around for 30 seconds or so. The grit will
drift to the bottom. Gently lift out the greens, empty the dirty
water, and repeat until the water is clear.
</P>
<P>
   Watercress is quite perishable and will keep only a couple of
days in the refrigerator. To store it, place its stalks in a bowl
of water, which should be changed daily, and cover its leaves with
damp paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   If you must, you can even use it in a sandwich. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHEAST ASIAN BROTH WITH WATERCRESS AND FRESH HERBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 cups low-salt chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped ginger
</P>
<P>
   6 scallions, thinly sliced at an angle
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fish sauce (nam pla)
</P>
<P>
   Stems from 1 bunch cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch watercress (about 2 cups), bottom inch of stems trimmed,
well washed
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup Thai or regular basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 jalapenos, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 lime, quartered &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan, combine broth, ginger, 2 scallions,
fish sauce and cilantro. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and
simmer 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, combine watercress, mint, basil and remaining
scallions in a large bowl and toss gently to mix. Divide among 4
soup bowls. In a small bowl, combine jalapeno and soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   3. Strain solids from broth mixture and divide broth among
bowls. Serve accompanied by jalapenos, soy and lime wedges for
squeezing.
</P>
<P>
   Yield:: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STIR-FRIED WATERCRESS WITH GINGER, GARLIC AND CHILIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches watercress, bottom inch of stems trimmed, washed and
dried
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place a large saute pan over high heat for 30 seconds. Add
both oils, and heat, swirling, until very hot but not smoking,
about 15 seconds. Add watercress and cook, stirring constantly and
vigorously, until just wilted, about 90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the minced ginger, garlic and pepper flakes, and cook,
still stirring vigorously, for 30 seconds. Remove the pan from the
heat and add the remaining ingredients. Stir and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEARED PORK TENDERLOINS OVER WATERCRESS WITH WALNUTS AND BLUE
CHEESE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 pork tenderloins, 10 to 12 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { red onion, peeled and diced small
</P>
<P>
   { cup Madeira (or substitute red wine)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   \ cup crumbled blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches watercress (about 4 cups), trimmed, washed and well
dried
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped walnuts, toasted in a dry skillet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Dry tenderloins with paper
towels, and sprinkle generously with salt and pepper. In a saute
pan large enough to comfortably hold both tenderloins, heat 2
tablespoons oil over medium-high heat until hot but not smoking.
Add tenderloins, and brown well on both sides, about 10 minutes
total. Transfer meat to a small roasting pan, place in preheated
oven, and roast to an internal temperature of 130 for medium rare,
about 12 to 15 minutes. Remove from pan, cover loosely with foil,
and allow to rest for 10 minutes before slicing.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, return saute pan to medium-high heat, add
remaining tablespoon of oil and heat until hot but not smoking. Add
onion and saute, stirring occasionally, until transparent, 7 to 9
minutes. Add Madeira and cook, stirring, for 1 minute. Add stock,
bring to a simmer, and cook until it is reduced by about half,
about 10 to 15 minutes. Remove sauce from heat, skim any film off
surface, then stir in the blue cheese, parsley, and salt and
pepper, and set aside, covering pan to keep sauce warm.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a small bowl, whisk together the extra virgin olive oil,
lemon juice, and salt and pepper to taste. Toss watercress and
walnuts with dressing, and divide salad among 4 plates. Slice pork
at an angle into slices about 1 inch thick, place a few slices on
top of each serving of watercress, drizzle generously with sauce,
and serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
