<SLUG> BC-GOOSE-COMEBACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ALEUTIAN GOOSE COMEBACK WILL BE CELEBRATED IN CALIF. 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRESCENT CITY, Calif. _ In 1967, when the species population
fell to 800, the Aleutian goose's goose was just about cooked.
</P>
<P>
   But in a remarkable, human-assisted comeback, these geese are
flourishing anew. And on March 24-26, their arrival will be
celebrated in Crescent City at the second annual Aleutian Goose
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   All the world's Aleutian geese, numbering about 35,000, are
resting up on tiny Castle Island off the Crescent City headlands
for their 2,000-mile flight to the rocky, wind-blasted islands in
the Gulf of Alaska where they breed.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is unusual in that it shuns fireworks, music,
floats, pageantry and booze and emphasizes the natural beauty of
the flora and fauna of Del Norte County in California's far
northwest corner.
</P>
<P>
   If guided trips by kayak and redwood forest walks, watching a
sky full of rare geese, are your thing, the Aleutian Goose Festival
is for you. It is billed as ``A Celebration of Wildness.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleutian geese, a smaller version of Canada geese, with a more
abrupt forehead, shorter bill and a white neck ring, were hunted to
the verge of extermination by arctic and red foxes, which were
introduced to the Aleutian Islands for fur breeding. When the fur
breeders quit in the 1930s, the abandoned foxes made the gooses'
breeding grounds their dining commons.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Aleutian goose was recognized as an endangered
species long before the Endangered Species Act became law, the 1973
act was the tool that empowered U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
rangers to terminate the foxes with prejudice to protect the geese.
</P>
<P>
   Result: the goose population has recovered so well that its
de-listing as an endangered species is in the works, even though it
is far from occupying its original range, which extended from
Japan's Kurile Islands to southern Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn, the entire flock rises and wings off Castle Island for
a day of feeding on the grasslands of the Smith River Delta _ an
event of breathtaking beauty that becomes a bit of a problem for
the mainland dairy farmers on whose grasslands they feed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we bought the ranch eight years ago, the (goose)
population was seven or eight thousand birds, and what we did was
let 'em eat,'' said Blake Alexandre, a dairyman who milks a herd of
1,400 Holsteins south of the Smith River. ``It was kind of fun when
the population was small, but now it's more than doubled in size.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleutian geese are grazers, and ``if the grass grows a quarter
of an inch a day, they'll eat it,'' Alexandre said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Ferguson, a dairyman and president of the Del Norte County
Farm Bureau, said the geese ``spend about 55 to 60 percent of their
time on private land.''
</P>
<P>
   To mitigate the goose problem, Alexandre has received permission
from the state to manage 500 acres of state land on the adjoining
Lake Earl Wildlife Project Area for goose grazing. ``It gives us a
place to chase the geese,'' said Alexandre. But he added that ``now
it's not enough land.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said that farmers in the area, who employ 3-wheelers to
chase the geese, have calculated that the birds are costing them
$225,000 to $250,000 a year in lost grass and labor.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, they are in the process of forming a Resource
Conservation District and working with the California Coastal
Conservancy on a plan by which they might receive some compensation
for the grass the geese are eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a win-win situation so far,'' Alexandre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
