<HEADER>
A9560 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-MARINO-COX     03-07 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sudden interest in Marino leaves Dolphins on the hook
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan Marino let the Miami Dolphins off the hook in February. By
voiding the final two years of his contract, he solved a salary-cap
problem that otherwise would have resulted in the unthinkable, a
pink slip for the franchise's signature player.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, though, with the news that another team wants Marino,
the hook has been reset, and deeper than before.
</P>
<P>
   Pity new head coach Dave Wannstedt. He's the guy who got stuck
with this no-win quarterback quandary as Jimmy Johnson skipped out
the door. Marino's retirement, at least, would have represented a
draw. You know, the Dolphins take some heat for judging Marino
irrelevant, but get some vindication when the rest of the league
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Green's offer to lead the Minnesota Vikings puts Marino
back in circulation. Here's a coach who not only believes a
39-year-old quarterback can be an effective NFL starter, he has the
proof of former Viking Warren Moon making the Pro Bowl at that age
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Green has run out of time for Randall Cunningham, 36,
and is prepared to release him to help make room for Marino, but
that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   We have more than enough to talk about right here with Danny and
the Dolphins. It's a relationship that can never end, even if
Marino joins the Vikings. For instance, if Minnesota makes the
playoffs in 2000 with No. 13 in the huddle, woe unto Wannstedt if
he falls short without him. And what if Marino's wearing purple
when the Dolphins and Vikings play at the Metrodome this season?
That's a loyalty test no Miami fan can take without some serious
guilt pangs.
</P>
<P>
   Who would you rather see take a blind-side sack from a blitzing
safety? Dan Marino, who played 258 games for the Dolphins, or Jay
Fiedler, who's played zero?
</P>
<P>
   Who would you rather see celebrating a touchdown pass? Dan
Marino, who threw 48 of them in 1984, or Damon Huard, who's thrown
eight in his career?
</P>
<P>
   These are questions Wayne Huizenga never wants asked. No doubt
he has a golden parachute all ready for Marino, a reward for
spectacular services rendered over 17 seasons. Monday was but a
taste of the afterlife for an NFL superstar, a sun-splashed round
of golf for Marino on Huizenga's private course in Palm City.
Huizenga was vilified for selling off the best of the 1997 World
Series champion Florida Marlins, an affront to baseball's
credibility, but he can be extraordinarily generous toward causes
that are nearer to his heart. A year ago Wayne opened his wallet
for the United Way, donating $1million to be divided evenly between
member charities in Martin and St. Lucie counties. There is good in
the man, and an appreciation for success that consistently places
Marino in the path of his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the distinct possibility that Marino will be getting
his warm hugs from Minnesotans next fall. Longtime Miami fans are
willing to share him for a season, given the alternative of Dan's
Super Bowl dream being extinguished once and for all. The Dolphins,
however, desperately need the clean break that comes with Marino
calling it quits.
</P>
<P>
   It still could go that way. This Vikings offer, supposedly
everything Marino could want, is no slam dunk or he'd already be
signed. To leave Claire and the kids for six months at a stretch is
an agonizing decision. Marino's never had to do it and never
dreamed it would be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the uncertainty over Marino's arm strength. Only he
knows what's really left, measured against decades of experience
with off-season soreness and fatigue. What's more, a little
homework will show Marino that Minnesota's offensive line allowed
43 sacks last year, six more than Miami, and that was before
Randall McDaniel was released as a salary-cap casualty.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there's no reason to pile on the Dolphins for ending it
with Marino. The time had come. There is something fascinating,
however, about watching him make the team twist a bit, and so
unexpectedly. I, too, was convinced that no one else would want him
as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between me and the Dolphins, in this very unusual
case, is that I rather enjoy being proven wrong.
</P>
<P>
   davegeorge(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
