<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Wednesday, March 8, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ The split between new economy and old economy stocks
widened when a classic old economy company P&AMP;G reported that
earnings for the two quarters will be lower than expected.
Meanwhile the tech-loaded Nasdaq composite pushed closer to the
psychologically important 5,000 level-the equivalent of the dow
crossing 10,000. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COKE-LAWSUIT _ Coca-Cola Chairman Douglas Daft has now indicated
to employees that he wants to settle a racial discrimination
lawsuit against the company and get the matter behind it. (Unger,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-SBC _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth's potential deal with SBC to
create a national wireless network has the potential to steer the
stodgy phone company in a whole new direction. Most of its business
overseas is in wireless and its wireless unit here is so valuable,
the company has been aiming to create a tracking stock out of it.
Why is wireless the next new thing for BellSouth? (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-ADS _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth on Wednesday will announce a
major ad campaign ($35 million to $50 million) that is meant to
''re-position'' the company. The company is looking to nudge its
name recognition higher among younger, more tech-savvy customers.
The television spots will start running on NBC Thursday and then
during the NCAA playoffs. They are a far cry from the Chatsford,
home town campaign, although they are also radically different from
the in-your-face Internet dotcom gerbils-out-of-cannon ad. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-ADS _ We get an advance look at Delta's new tv spots, the
first by its new ad agency, Leo Burnett Co. of ``Friendly Skies''
fame. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBALSPEAK _ ATLANTA _ Frank Baia, CEO of Atlanta-based
Globalspeak, is an old-time advertising man and business publisher,
but his business is cutting edge _ a multimedia platform for
staying in business touch and doing transactions worldwide. Among
the features of the company's powerful website is the cability to
conduct international trade missions, with a recent example
allowing Nigerian businessmen to do business with Atlantans,
without stirring from their offices in Lagos. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OT-ABUSE _ The nation's factories and offices are running
full-tilt. So, too are workers. And many aren't taking the extra
work load lightly. Instead, they're taking their employer to court
for overtime abuse. On the other side of the argument: the
workplace is changing thus creating a grey area: who should get
paid overtime? And who's exempt? A look at this issue. (Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL-SUPPLIES _ ATLANTA _ An Atlanta-based Internet site for
buying and selling hotel and restaurant supplies is expanding its
service to reach customers on the move. Hsupply.com, which brings
together procurement specialists and producers of consumable
supplies like tissue and soaps, is now making its service reachable
by hand-held mobile devices. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REALTORS-HIGHTECH _ If a Realtor doesn't have an interactive
website, use e-mail, autoresponders, virtual home tours, etc., they
can forget it in today's market. We'll look at how technology is
changing the way Realtors do their work as demonstrated by a
``high-tech'' Realtor. (MariaMallory, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0307: 2000 LAND ROVER DISCOVERY II -- For anyone
who's about to venture into real unpaved territory and wants a
vehicle that's thoroughly tough, there's nothing quite like the
Land Rover Discovery II. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
Art includes 4-column color photo of the 2000 Land Rover Discovery
II.
</P>
