<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-LIGTENBERG _ It's been more than a year since Kerry
Ligtenberg pitched for the Atlanta Braves, missing the entire 1999
season following elbow surgery. The reliever is expected to make
his return to the mound today in an exhibition game against
Detroit. A look at Ligtenberg's performance as he pitches for the
first time since the 1998 season. (CRogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL/NBA
</P>
<P>
   BKC-TURNED-PRO _ ATLANTA _ Former Georgia Tech player Dion
Glover and former Georgia player Jumaine Jones could be two major
players leading their college teams into conference tournaments
this week. Both instead are sitting on NBA benches after deciding
last spring to leave college early. Neither have played much this
season. But both contend the million-dollar salary has tempered any
thoughts about the mistake of coming out early. (Bunn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR
</P>
<P>
   CAR-NASCAR-LABONTE _ It is rumored that Bobby Labonte is such a
Weather Channel freak that NASCAR officials have asked him during
weather-plagued race days to check out the radar and give his
opinion. Labonte certainly has had a lot of success at AMS . . . on
the track and on the radar. (Carvell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/NFL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MARINO _ Dan Marino let the Miami Dolphins off the hook in
February. By voiding the final two years of his contract, he solved
a salary-cap problem that otherwise would have resulted in the
unthinkable, a pink slip for the franchise's signature player.
Suddenly, though, with the news that another team wants Marino, the
hook has been reset, and deeper than before. Pity new head coach
Dave Wannstedt. He's the guy who got stuck with this no-win
quarterback quandary as Jimmy Johnson skipped out the door.
Marino's retirement, at least, would have represented a draw. You
know, the Dolphins take some heat for judging Marino irrelevant,
but get some vindication when the rest of the league agrees.
(George, Palm Beach Post). 20.
</P>
