<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASH-WEDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christians may be missing the point of Lent
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Today is Ash Wednesday, the first day of the 40
days of Lent that lead up to Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, it's a time of prayer, discipline and penitence
that culminates with the celebration of Christ's resurrection and a
sense of spiritual renewal.
</P>
<P>
   But the faithful who think of Lent as a time to give up
something _ say, chocolate or television _ may be missing the point
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Bible, 'sacrifice' does not mean to give up, but to
make holy,'' says the Rev. James Manning of St. Albert the Great
Church in Kettering. ``If you use the hour you usually spend on TV
to read the Bible, the focus should be on what you get, not on what
you give up.''
</P>
<P>
   This Lenten season is a special one for the Catholic Church, a
Jubilee year in which Pope John Paul II has asked Catholics to take
stock of the sins committed by the Catholic Church through history.
</P>
<P>
   In an apostolic letter, John Paul wrote, ``The church rejoices,
gives thanks and asks forgiveness, presenting her petitions to the
Lord of history and of human consciences.''
</P>
<P>
   As the church is conscious of its own sins, Lent can be a time
for individual Catholics to focus on their own shortcomings, says
Dan Andriacco, spokesman for the Cincinnati Archdiocese, which
includes the Miami Valley area.
</P>
<P>
   The Jubilee _ which occurs every 50th year _ is a Jewish
tradition, mentioned in the book of Leviticus, a period that is a
special opportunity for grace, Manning says. It is a time for rest,
for fair dealings with neighbors and business associates, and for
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cincinnati Archdiocese, Catholics can observe Lent during
this Jubilee year by making a pilgrimage to churches that have an
artistic or historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   The seven churches in the Dayton area are: Our Lady of the
Immaculate Conception, 2300 S. Smithville Road, in Kettering; Holy
Family Church, 140 S. Findlay St., in Dayton; Emmanuel Church, 149
Franklin St., in Dayton; Holy Trinity Church, 272 Bainbridge Ave.
in Dayton; St. Joseph Church, 411 E. Second St., in Dayton; St.
Mary Church, 310 Allen St., in Dayton, and Holy Angels Church,
Brown and L streets, in Dayton. For more information about the
pilgrimage, visit the archdiocese Web site at www.archdiocese
cinti.org., or pick up a brochure at any of these churches.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christian denominations observe Ash Wednesday with a
ceremony in which a priest or pastor uses ashes burned during the
previous year's Palm Sunday (the Sunday before Easter) to mark a
cross on the foreheads of worshipers. This blessing is based on the
passage from Genesis: ``... for dust thou art, and unto dust shalt
thou return.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40 days of Lent symbolize the 40 days that the Bible says
Jesus spent in the desert before beginning his public ministry.
It's a powerful number throughout the Old and New Testaments,
Manning says, considered to be an ideal time needed to prepare for
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``But whether it's 40 or 39 or 41 is not the issue,'' he says.
``The point is to prepare for the new life of Easter.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kathy Whyde Jesse atkathywhydejesse(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
