A9568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOILETS-WORKPLACE-NYT     03-07 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOILETS-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEBODY HAS TO DO IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Pedro Gomez is assistant manager of A Royal Flush, a provider of
portable toilets.) 
(DW) 
 By PEDRO GOMEZ with PATRICIA R. OLSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm responsible for setting up portable toilets at special
events in the city such as street fairs, road races, concerts. Once
a driver drove over the Great Lawn in Central Park _ where Diana
Ross sang _ and left tire tracks. Now I'm the only one the Parks
Department will trust to set up toilets there.
</P>
<P>
   I work seven days a week. Many times, I start at 2 or 3 a.m.
People are just coming out of the clubs, and I see a lot of
interesting things at that hour. I enjoy it. I do all the planning
for the jobs, drop off the toilets and pick them up after the
events. Another guy pumps out the toilets into a truck after the
event and then puts locks on the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Once I was picking up some toilets from a construction site. I
had one of them ready to load when someone inside started
screaming. He had been locked in. The toilet flushed up, and when
he came out, his whole back was blue. It wasn't funny for the guy
who put the lock on. He was fired.
</P>
<P>
   When a water main breaks, we're one of the first services the
city calls. After the World Trade Center bombing, we set up units
for the disaster relief people. When President Clinton comes to
town, we set up two toilets on the tarmac for the Secret Service
men who stay with the plane. We've also got handicapped-accessible
units.
</P>
<P>
   Customers don't always know what they want. We use a tool like a
slide rule to figure the number of toilets they need, according to
the crowd they're going to have. It also depends on whether people
are going to be eating and drinking. The true test of whether
enough were ordered is how full the units are when we pick them up.
If they're full to the top, the customer didn't order enough.
</P>
<P>
   At the St. Patrick's Day parade. there's no drinking allowed on
the route, but people go into bars and drink. It took over a week
to pump the toilets out after the New Year's Eve celebration in the
city. A lot of the time we find empty bottles in the units.
</P>
<P>
   I've been on a lot of movie sets. I met Bruce Willis during the
filming of ``The Siege,'' and I met Richard Gere when the Dalai
Lama held a service in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   After I've loaded all these toilets in the back of my truck, the
odor can be overpowering. When I stop at a light, I know what's
going to happen. Once I pulled up next to a group of girls with the
car windows down and the radio blasting. After a minute they looked
over at me, started yelling, rolled the windows up and ran the red
light. I laughed so hard I had tears in my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   For occasions like lawn weddings, I have larger, V.I.P units
with sinks, paper towels and soap, and flush toilets. Once an
actress said she'd like to take one on the road, and someone
whispered: ``Do you know who that is? You should ask for her
autograph.'' But I'm a professional; I don't do that.
</P>
<P>
   I'm always immaculately dressed, and my truck is always clean.
Still, some people ask, ``How can you do this?'' I tell them: ``If
you saw my check, you'd understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
