<HEADER>
A9569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES     03-07 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `FEMALE GRISHAM' CREATES A LIE WORTH TELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ People magazine has called Lisa Scottoline ``the
female John Grisham.'' Grisham is fun, but Scottoline is more
creative.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest legal thriller ``Moment of Truth'' (HarperCollins,
$25, 355 pages) is a fresh addition to the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Newlin had no choice but to frame himself for murder.
Once he set his course, his only fear was that he wouldn't get away
with it. That he wasn't a good enough liar, even for a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer with Philadelphia's top firm, Newlin arrives home late
for dinner and finds his heiress wife stabbed to death. Believing
his 16-year-old daughter Paige was the killer, he rigs the murder
scene to make it look like only he could be the murderer. He calls
911 and says he has just killed his wife. Taken into custody, he
waives his rights and confesses. Then he hires an inexperienced
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   His only problem is that everyone knows he is lying, but nobody
agrees what the lie is. The district attorney is ecstatic because
he is sure he has an open and shut capital murder case. The lead
homicide detective knows something is wrong and starts looking for
other suspects. And Newlin's lawyer, Mary DiNunzio, believes a
loving father would do anything to protect his daughter, even die
for her.
</P>
<P>
   So DiNunzio sets out to prove that Paige, a model living away
from home, killed her mom. She learns that Paige's mom had abused
her for years and tries to get the girl to confess.
</P>
<P>
   This is a book you pick up and find you can't go to bed until
it's finished because of a realistic plot driven by likable and
highly believable characters who talk like people you know.
``Moment of Truth'' truly is a thriller that delivers.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Void Moon.'' By Michael Connelly. Little, Brown and Co.
$24.95. 391 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly's latest thriller has a sassy female protagonist who
moves the plot along at a rapid-fire pace.
</P>
<P>
   Six years before, Cassie Black was on top of the world. She and
her lover Max had planned one last robbery of a Las Vegas casino
gambler before retiring from crime life. But something went
horribly wrong, Max fell to his death and she was sent to prison.
Now on parole, Cassie works at a Porsche dealership in Los Angeles.
Suddenly, she decides she needs a great deal of money and calls
Max's half-brother Leo and asks him to set up one more heist.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen days later Leo calls her back and says there is contract
job in Las Vegas and that she can net $150,000. The mark is a
big-time gambler and all she needs to do is wait until he goes to
sleep, slip in, grab the money and get back to Los Angeles with it.
But Leo warns her not to do the job between 3:22 a.m. and 3:38 a.m.
Thursday _ the time of a void moon, a time of very bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Cassie goes to Vegas, sets up the heist, slips into the mark's
room and gets the money _ but oops, she's still in the room at
3:30. She also grabs his briefcase and takes off. When she
discovers that there is $2.5 million in the briefcase, she knows
she's in big trouble. Turns out that mark was a courier for the
mob. Now Cassie is on the run being trailed by the man who set Max
up.
</P>
<P>
   None of Connelly's thrillers has been made into a movie, but
``Void Moon'' should be. The main character is likable, smart and
resilient. Her nemesis has no conscience and has no qualms about
killing anyone who gets in his way. There are some unexpected plot
twists, interesting minor characters, good dialogue and a pace that
just keeps on building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1743EST &QL; 
