A9572 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DREAM-KITCHEN09-COX     03-07 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAM-KITCHEN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upscale touches create cook-friendly Atlanta interior _ and
you're invited
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 9.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jackie Cottrill's kitchen may look like it's straight out of a
decorating magazine, but, being an avid cook, she insists it's used
every day.
</P>
<P>
   The secret is in her own design. ``A kitchen is a necessity, but
I didn't want mine to look like one,'' the Atlantan said. ``I
wanted it to look like a room with nice furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   The cabinetry she chose not only hides her appliances but was
designed with varying depths, heights and surface materials to
avoid a static line around the room. And by nixing wall cabinets in
favor of floor ones, Cottrill further enhanced the idea of a
decorated room.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen is definitely high-end, yet it's jammed with
cost-saving ideas. That makes it one highlight on the Tour of
Kitchens on March 18 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Cottrill knew exactly what she wanted in a kitchen when she and
her husband, Richard, built their Atlanta home last year. After
all, it was their 18th house in 25 years, and she has designed or
decorated every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The couple not only love to cook but to entertain _ not big
formal parties but casual dinners for small groups. For that
reason, Cottrill, aware that guests always end up in the kitchen,
wanted hers to put on its best face.
</P>
<P>
   French doors separate the kitchen from adjoining rooms, and two
short islands, instead of one long one, make the room less
predictable. They are working islands. But at the end of one is an
eating area, designated by a pair of rattan bar chairs on either
side, not your typical row of stools.
</P>
<P>
   The neoclassical French design began with a couple of monkey
chandeliers Cottrill found in an antique store. She painted the
monkeys' blue coats in a leopard pattern, adding tones of black and
beige that inspired the room's color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley McFarlane of Kitchensmith of Atlanta designed the
cabinetry Cottrill wanted, warm Heritage pieces with an aged maple
finish that contrasts with countertops mixing matte black enamel
and limestone.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of banking the cabinets in a uniform row, the are
staggered in different depths to make them look like furniture.
``Things don't have to be on the same plane all around a room,''
Cottrill said.
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of wooden, nickel and black-accented hardware also
makes the cabinets look like fine individual pieces. The metal
accents yet another surface, the appliances' stainless steel _ a
feature that helped the kitchen recently win a regional Sub Zero
design award.
</P>
<P>
   On one end of the room is an electric stove with gas cooktop,
above which Cottrill used mosaic tile to create a backsplash with a
fish design.
</P>
<P>
   On the other is a wall oven surrounded by cabinetry that houses
a hidden TV above it and art and other collectibles on glass-front
shelves on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Although at $150,000 the kitchen was pricey, Cottrill put the
money into features that make a difference, such as a few
lattice-front cabinets in the butler's pantry _ the area through
which guests pass on their way to the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's somethng you want to do and it's too expensive,
just use it as an accent,'' she said. ``That makes more of a
statement anyway than if you used a lot of one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   COTTRILL'S COST SAVERS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When you can't afford custom cabinets, buy stock cabinets and
arrange them in varying depths to create the look of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choose a less expensive door or drawer style on cabinets and
use the savings to upgrade the cabinets with the finish or design
you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dress up cabinetry by adding accents, such as stair ballusters
to the end of islands or a mix of interesting hardware on doors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use granite tiles on countertops to give the look of more
expensive solid granite.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choose inexpensive shelving for less visible areas, such as
butler's pantries, instead of kitchen cabinetry.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
