<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9573 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GEORGIA-GUIDES08-COX     03-07 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-GUIDES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia guides head down roads less traveled
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture it: A busload of Dutch tourists disembarking at Andrew's
Oyster Bar in Bainbridge to slurp the house special _ swamp gravy.
Or how about a band of beret-wearing bohemians oohing and aahing
over folk art at the Frogbottom Grist Mill in Hazelhurst? Or a
gaggle of big-city bon vivants gossiping over cocktails in the
lobby of the Windsor Hotel in Americus?
</P>
<P>
   OK, stop laughing. True, these off-the-beaten-path Georgia sites
may not be major tourist meccas yet. But recent efforts to showcase
the state as a whole _ including two new travel guides and a state
government push to make rural areas more peachy to tourists _ may
mean more vacationers heading down Georgia roads less traveled.
</P>
<P>
   Call up Amazon.com on the Web, and you'll find plenty of travel
guides on Atlanta, Savannah and the mountains, but guides to
getting around Vidalia, Fitzgerald and Brunswick have been mighty
rare. But two first-edition guides _ ``Hidden Georgia'' from
Ulysses Press and ``Compass American Guides: Georgia'' from Fodor's
_ join a handful of others, including Moon Travel's comprehensive
``Georgia Handbook,'' in its third edition, in exploring the entire
state.
</P>
<P>
   The books arrive in the wake of Georgia's post-Olympic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at tourism numbers for destinations across the
country, and Georgia's numbers are very strong,'' says Ulysses'
marketing manager Bryce Willett. The publishing company was
impressed by the fact that visitors kept coming after the Olympics
were over: The Georgia Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism
reports the state racked up $18.19 billion in tourist dollars in
1998, the latest year for which there are figures. That's up about
21 percent from 1996, the year of the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   Fodor's publisher Kris Klieman thinks we can also thank a
certain best seller. ``Interest in Southern culture has grown in
part because of `Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,''' she
says. ``Think about it _ that book was published all around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``the Book,'' as Savannahians call it, the two new travel
guides burrow beneath Georgia's smiling surface to find its
eclectic, eccentric soul. ``Hidden Georgia,'' published in
February, highlights obscure attractions, from Jack Wingate's
Lunker Lodge in Bainbridge to the gator-rich Colemans Lake Resort
near Midville.
</P>
<P>
   Author Marty Olmstead, a Savannah native, spent months exploring
the state and found it ``satisfyingly quirky.'' She raves about
stops such as the Frogbottom Grist Mill, where visitors can buy a
batch of homemade cane syrup, peruse local folk art and perhaps
encounter some indigenous fauna.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner killed a snake while we were there!'' Olmstead says.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlantan John T. Edge found himself having to downshift a
bit while doing research for ``Compass American Guides: Georgia,''
published in December. ``People talk about the pace of life being
slower in South Georgia, and I really did feel that. I could feel
my grip on the steering wheel loosen as I drove South.''
</P>
<P>
   Edge, who was born in Clinton and lives in Oxford, Miss., took a
shine to recently rejuvenated Augusta. ``The renaissance of the
downtown area is really wonderful. Broad Street has all these great
little restaurants and shops.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorites: the Soul Bar, a watering hole with a James
Brown theme, and Luigi's, an Italian eatery that boasts a plethora
of Masters memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   The evenhanded approach that both guides take to covering
Georgia should please officials who are trying to give the state's
rural areas a boost. Last month, the Georgia Senate voted to
approve a proposal by Gov. Roy Barnes to create the OneGeorgia
Authority, which will promote business in the state's rural
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-the-way attractions are a top priority at the Georgia
Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism, which is mounting a
promotional campaign focusing heavily on ecotourism adventures in
the Okefenokee Swamp and coastal areas. There are also plans to
have a virtual tour of Georgia, including Civil War trails in every
county in the state, online by fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really trying to get people interested in places other
than the big cities,'' says spokeswoman Heather Potts.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's Oyster Bar better start cooking up more of that swamp
gravy _ a tasty stew made from fried fish leavings, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Georgia Department of Industry, Trade and
Tourism, 1-800-847-4842 or www.georgia.org.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
