<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-KITCHEN-FLOOR09-COX     03-07 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-FLOOR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Know what's afoot with surfaces for the kitchen
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, March 9.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you walk in the kitchen, take a good look at your
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Do spills dot your vinyl like a trail of blood in a scene from a
suspense thriller?
</P>
<P>
   Does your tile show more skids than the Downtown Connector?
</P>
<P>
   Are your hardwoods so scratched by Rover that they've formed a
new pattern?
</P>
<P>
   Could be time to pamper your floor _ or to simply buy a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Just be prepared. The array of options in materials, designs and
finishes may floor you. Competing with hardwoods and stone are
laminates, vinyls and ceramics designed to resemble those natural
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it all goes way beyond the superficial appearance.
Choosing a flooring is all about lifestyle,'' said Steve Cambas,
assistant manager of Expo Design Center in Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Installing a kitchen floor has come a long way from the old days
of rolling out a sheet of Congoleum. Costs alone can be major _
especially when you consider that surface materials are just one
expense in furnishing a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, you can drop $100,000 on a kitchen just like that,''
Cambas said. ``A few years ago, that was a house.''
</P>
<P>
   These days consumers are far more savvy about products than they
were 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so value conscious _ not so much interested in what
the flooring costs per square foot but in knowing it will last for
a long, long time,'' said Jere Bowden of Rutt, a kitchen design
firm in Atlanta. ``They're investing in something that's an
integral part of their home, something that's attached and won't
have to be replaced like other surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   When choosing a floor for the room where family and friends most
often congregate, consider aesthetics, durability, comfort and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Then factor in your lifestyle. ``We always ask people, `Do you
have children? Do you have pets?''' said Paulette Rewis of Just
Floors, an Atlanta flooring company. ``If they don't, they have a
lot less to be concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they cook and entertain often, that's also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   It almost becomes a sensory thing, Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to think of the whole room, with its ceiling
treatment, the sound the floor creates and how loud it will be when
the whole family's in the room or when the dishwasher's running,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the visual flow of floor materials from room to
room, and how the kitchen surface feels to stand on for long
periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is people want something that is unique to them
in their home, and with large areas of floor, pattern is
important,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   In high-end kitchens, many people are opting for floors that
combine natural stone and wood, she said. They're choosing woods
such as cherry, hickory and mesquite in 12-inch widths, often using
``reclaimed'' lumber salvaged from old buildings.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't afford the real thing, take heart: Man-made
materials, such as vinyls and laminates, are supplying the look for
less cost.
</P>
<P>
   So which floor's for you? Here are some pointers from flooring
experts about each of the five major groups:
</P>
<P>
   VINYL
</P>
<P>
   The look: Vinyl has advanced tremendously in recent years.
Although sheet vinyl remains the backbone of kitchens, vinyl tiles
provide versatility when it comes to creating different looks that
use wood, stone or other natural materials.
</P>
<P>
   One brand, Amtico, can be mixed and matched to include borders,
medallions and other details because it's sold in rectangles,
strips and other shapes. ``You can get the 3-D effect of slate, add
a strip to look like the grout lines of ceramic tile, put borders
around a room. It's custom all the way,'' Cambas said.
</P>
<P>
   The strength: All vinyl is extremely durable, but one advantage
of vinyl tile is that if damage occurs, you need only replace a
square or two, as opposed to removing a section of sheet vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   The feel: Vinyl by far is the softest of kitchen surfaces, so it
is a natural choice for diehard cooks.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup: It's also among the easiest to clean, though
manufacturers sell their own products for maintaining the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The cost: Sheet vinyl ranges from $9 to $60 per square yard.
Vinyl tiles start at about $3 per square foot and can go up to $15
per square foot installed. ``Tiles generally cost about twice as
much as sheet vinyl installed, but dollar for dollar with tile
you're paying only for what you use, not for the waste of the
sheet,'' Cambas said.
</P>
<P>
   HARDWOOD
</P>
<P>
   The look: Wood has become extremely popular in kitchens for two
reasons: Homeowners want to blend the room with great rooms that
contain hardwoods and are increasingly drawn to natural materials.
</P>
<P>
   The strength: Hardwoods are a practical choice for kitchens
because manufacturers are using aluminum oxides to create harder
finishes. ``We have three dogs, and hardwoods have been no problem
in our own kitchen,'' Rewis said. ``But nothing is impervious to
living.''
</P>
<P>
   The key is the wood's thickness and polyurethane finish. ``If
you drop a pot, you could get a dent, and with heavy traffic it
will scuff,'' Cambas said. ``But the floor itself isn't what takes
the abuse _ it's the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical 3/4-inch-thick flooring contains three to seven
layers of wood, and the top should be at least 1/8 inch. That's so
the floor can be lightly buffed after losing its luster, typically
in seven to 10 years, Cambas said.
</P>
<P>
   The feel: Wood is middle of the road _ softer than stone or
ceramic tile, harder than vinyl and laminate.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup: Easy. Grain hides spills and some scuffs.
</P>
<P>
   The cost: Prefinished wood sells for about $3 to $10 per square
foot, or about $10 to $15 per square foot installed.
</P>
<P>
   LAMINATE
</P>
<P>
   The look: Commonly called by the trade name Formica, laminate is
a hard synthetic material affixed to a layer of wood or
particleboard. One hot seller is Pergo, which provides the look of
hardwood or stone but at less cost.
</P>
<P>
   The strength: The material is extremely durable, Cambas said,
but proper installation is crucial. It's sold in 4-foot-by-7
1/2-inch planks laid tongue-and-groove in order to appear solid.
Joints must be properly glued to prevent moisture penetration and
buckling. If a section is damaged, the whole surface usually must
be replaced, Cambas said, unlike vinyl tiles.
</P>
<P>
   The feel: A real softie.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup: Like hardwoods, the finish hides a lot, and
laminate cleaning products are available.
</P>
<P>
   The cost: It starts at about $4 per square foot, or $7 to $10
per square foot installed.
</P>
<P>
   CERAMIC TILE
</P>
<P>
   The look: Natural stone is the craze, but at about one-third the
cost, ceramic tile can provide a similar look. Large tiles _
18-by-18s and 12-by-12s _ are more popular than smaller ones. In
addition to smooth glazed tiles, there are ones that simulate
stone. ``There are so many innovations in ceramics these days that
you can even get fossil-looking images in the tiles,'' Cambas said.
A variety of grout colors also provides different looks.
</P>
<P>
   The strength: In kitchens and baths, ceramic is more practical
than stone because advances in fired-on finishes have made ceramic
inpenetrable. And while chipping does occur, the grout makes tile
more forgiving of wear and tear than stone.
</P>
<P>
   The feel: A hard surface.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup: Damp mopping is best. (Make sure grout is sealed to
prevent stains.)
</P>
<P>
   The cost: At $2 to $7 per square foot, it's worth attempting by
the do-it-yourselfer; $10 to $20 per square foot installed.
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL STONE
</P>
<P>
   The look: Natural materials have never been hotter, and
manufacturers are dressing up stone tiles with borders and accents
so homeowners can customize their designs. Any stone _ travertine,
granite, porcelain, Jerusalem stone _ is suitable for kitchens
except marble, Cambas said, because it's so porous.
</P>
<P>
   The strength: Because most prefer to abut the stones rather than
grout them, proper installation (over a level concrete surface) is
critical. A move as minor as dragging a bar stool across the floor
can chip the stone if its surface isn't level.
</P>
<P>
   The feel: Tough on the feet for extended periods.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup: Easy. Special products also available.
</P>
<P>
   The cost: $15 to $25 per square foot installed.
</P>
<P>
   THE LOOK HARDWOOD
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Gigliotti: My dream kitchen will have it.
</P>
<P>
   Nan Niyomkul: We have this at home. I like the naturalness.
</P>
<P>
   LAMINATE
</P>
<P>
   LG: Pretty good look, though not as pretty as hardwoods.
</P>
<P>
   NN: It doesn't look finished enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   VINYL TILE
</P>
