<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Exceptional warmth will reach its peak Wednesday from the Ohio
Valley to the interior Middle Atlantic States. Plentiful sunshine
will boost afternoon temperatures to record-setting levels from the
middle 70s to lower 80s across these regions. Farther to the north
and east, the flow of wind around expanding high pressure will draw
cooler ocean air and patchy clouds into New England and parts of
Middle Atlantic Coast keeping temperatures 15 to 30 degrees cooler
than areas to the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous storm will produce a band of rain from central
Dakotas to the western Great Lakes. The windswept rain will change
to wet snow across the northern and western Dakotas as colder air
is drawn into the system. The rain and snow will end overnight as
wintry air envelops the region. Meanwhile, broken bands of showers
and potent thunderstorms will develop Wednesday afternoon as an
advancing cool, dry air mass lifts the unusually warm air over the
northern and central Mississippi Valleys. Strong winds shifting
with altitude will impart rotation to some of the storms
heightening the risk of isolated tornadoes. Farther west, a surge
of dry air will promote sunny skies over Texas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will persist in the West. Intermittent snow
will occur near the east slopes of the northern Rockies as moist
winds ascend the sloping terrain. The latest in a series of Pacific
fronts will produce showery rain from central California to the
Pacific Northwest Coast. Mountain snow and valley showers will
develop in Nevada and western Utah.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: When It Rains, It Pours &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It does not rain very often in the desert, but when it does, it
often rains hard. From Saturday through Tuesday afternoon, 2.77
inches of rain fell in Phoenix as a series of potent storms passed
through the Southwest. This total produced over one-third of the
typical yearly rainfall of 7.66 inches in Phoenix. On average, when
it rains in Phoenix, about 0.2 inches falls, which is nearly 3
percent of the normal annual rainfall. By comparison, a typical
rainstorm in New York City produces 0.4 inches, or less than one
percent of the normal rainfall for a year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
