<P>
   &UR; SUPER TUESDAY' AND AMERICA'S WARPED POLITICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Today is Super Tuesday in the United States of
America. The only accurate part of that description is that it is
indeed a Tuesday. ``Tiresome waste of money Tuesday'' might be a
better name, or ``Let's bore everyone to tears Tuesday,'' because
it is the day when American democracy reaches its inane anticlimax.
Call me a skeptic, but it cannot be a good thing that the leader of
the free world is chosen on the basis of who has the most
balloons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Provocative Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By John O'Farrell, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 225-word optional trim; total uncut is 900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WHITEHOUSE-FOR-SALE-575&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `SUPER TUESDAY' PRIMARIES SET TO CROWN GORE AND BUSH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Voters across America, from the small states of New
England in the east to the broad sweep of California in the west,
went to the polls Tuesday in ``Super Tuesday'' primaries that
looked set to crown Vice President Al Gore and George W. Bush as
the two contenders for the White House in November. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 650 words; 825 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CORONATION-DAY-US-650&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANDIDATES SORELY LACK REAGAN `CHARISMA' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, CALIF. _ If the Republicans want to win back the
White House in November, they are going to have to field a
candidate with at least some of Ronald Reagan's crossover appeal to
Democrats and independents, as well as some of the ideological zeal
that galvanized the Gipper's closest followers. So which of the two
GOP candidates best fits the bill? A consensus among Reagan
devotees ambling through his presidential library this week
presents an ominous sign for the party's chances: neither one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Gumbel, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-REAGAN-WANNABES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET TO REPLACE VOTING MACHINES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLD GREENWICH, CONN. _ About 6-ft. tall and almost as wide, they
look like a curious cross between a Wurlitzer, an old-fashioned
telephone board and some kind of end-of-the-pier one-armed bandit.
These contraptions are nothing more mysterious than voting
machines. Beloved for their creakiness and eccentric design, they
have for decades done their bit for American democracy. When
ballots are needed, out they roll. But not for much longer... On
Tuesday, Arizona was the first state to make a leap from the age of
the voting Wurlitzer to voting in cyberspace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Arizona _ 16th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By David Usborne, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
