<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-RAILROADS08-COX     03-07 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILROADS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OFFICIALS URGE CAUTION IN CONSIDERING RAILROAD MEGA-MERGER
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several witnesses warned the Surface Transportation
Board on Tuesday that allowing new mergers of railroad companies
would lead to less competition and poorer customer service.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day hearing, which began Tuesday, is board's first
comprehensive review of rail consolidation. It was triggered by the
announcement that Burlington Northern Santa Fe Corp. and Canadian
National Railway Co. plan to merge. If approved, the merger would
form North America's largest railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told the board that recent railroad mergers, which
have left only a handful of lines operating in North America, have
caused rail car shortages and shipping delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger, if approved, will lead to other mergers, and the
last thing the industry needs is concentration,'' said Sen. Byron
L. Dorgan, D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dunn, an assistant agriculture secretary, described service
troubles arising from past mergers that he said caused farmers to
lose money. Citing what he called ``merger fatigue,'' Dunn said
there are serious concerns about whether further consolidation
should take place.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of railroad customers, the Alliance for Rail
Competition, said that in some regions ``service has been so bad
that customers have been forced to shift production to other
regions,'' said spokesman Diane Duff.
</P>
<P>
   Even the board's chairman, Linda Morgan, noted widespread
feelings that it's time to take a ``breather'' on mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the two railroads said the merger is necessary
because the industry is suffering from a lack of growth. ``Truckers
are beating us,'' said Canadian National Railway Co. CEO Paul
Tellier.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers can contribute positively to the railroad industry and
have done so in the past, said Chairman Robert Krebs of Burlington
Northern Santa Fe Corp. He said the number of carriers is less
important than the quality of the carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transaction is not an ego trip,'' Tellier said. ``I don't
dream of being the CEO of the largest railroad company. We are
doing this to serve customers better.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the companies are expected to file a merger
application by March 20. They are looking to form a railroad system
with 50,000 miles of track that would generate about $12.5 billion
in revenue a year.
</P>
<P>
   This week's hearings are not expected to resolve the question of
whether the new merger should be allowed to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, the board is to hear from more customers and
rivals of the proposed merged railroad, as well as labor leaders
and financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 160 witnesses that are expected to testify, more than
half are customers such as General Motors Corp., duPont Co. and the
Department of Defense, all of which are expected to tell of
merger-related delays.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailm(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
