<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9595 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-SUB-BOS &LR;      03-07 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRIMER ON THE THE MIXED ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrections, edits, thruout; PLEASE SUB)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So much ideological guff has been floated during the last 20
years about the kind of world we live in: ``a private enterprise
system,'' ``an opportunity society,'' ``market capitalism,'' and so
on _ all of it partly true.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who harbors the slightest doubt, however, that we live
more than ever in a ``mixed economy'' should have stopped by Boston
College Monday. There a parade of financial celebrities turned out
at the invitation of US Representative Edward Markey for a daylong
conference on The New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan said the economy was
growing too fast for its own good and the market went down,
anticipating further increases in short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Gerstner of IBM Corp. speculated on the impact of the
Internet on large firms. Arthur Levitt of the Securities and
Exchange Commission described the changing missions of his agency,
as did Frank Zarb of the National Association of Securities
Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs including CMGI's David Wetherell, Gururaj ``Desh''
Deshpande of Sycamore Networks, Mario Gabelli of Gabelli Asset
Management, and Kay Koplovitz of Working Woman Network participated
in panels.
</P>
<P>
   And opening the conference, Boston College president William P.
Leahy SJ underscored the politically charged theme that underlay it
when he spoke of ``the justice and fairness issues that have been
at the core of religious concern since the days of the prophets.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowed Markey to an audience of more than 1,000 people, most of
them BC graduates like him (class of 1968, law school 1972), it was
``one of the all-time all-star lineups ever assembled anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   What brings Markey such drawing power? He's the ranking Democrat
on the House subcommittee on telecommunications, trade and consumer
protection.
</P>
<P>
   And it is through the committee that virtually all legislation
concerning the Internet, communications satellites, and telephone
services and cable television must pass.
</P>
<P>
   Markey's district bristles with companies that manufacture the
next generation of switching equipment and software for the
Internet. Low rent and a ready-made work force are part of the
story about bustling I-495 _ but so is the direct access that a
factory in the district affords to the world's ultimate
standard-setting body, the US Congress.
</P>
<P>
   BC understands this nexus of markets and politics better than
most. Monday's meeting took place in the Silvio O. Conte Forum, a
basketball and hockey palace named for the former Western
Massachusetts representative. On the hill above sits the Thomas P.
``Tip'' O'Neill Library. Like Conte, the late US House speaker was
a BC alumnus.
</P>
<P>
   An only-slightly-different ethic prevails at the Massacusetts
Institute of Technology, where the strictly personal is so frowned
upon that, until recently, the buildings were numbered instead of
named for great or generous men and women. Nevertheless, most of
MIT's growth has derived from federal spending on R&AMP;D.
</P>
<P>
   So when US Representative Michael Capuano recently found $600
million in ostensibly new money headed for the Department of Energy
in the Networking and Information Technology Research and
Development Act, he filed an amendment shifting half of it to the
National Science Foundation, where it would be doled out to
universities _ perhaps even MIT _ rather than government labs.
</P>
<P>
   At the last moment, a letter from the Energy Department arrived
over the House fax claiming that the measure would close the
nation's largest unclassified computer facility at California's
Lawrence Livermore Laboratory. The amemdment sailed through on a
voice vote nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked about it; they never answered until it was too late,''
Capuano said. The funding may be restored. But what better way to
serve notice that the congressman who represents Harvard and MIT
now has a seat on the science committee?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David warsh is a Boston Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
