u e BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-07 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BILL CARTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NBC Quits the Club &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NBC continued to go its own way in the broadcasting industry
Tuesday, announcing that it had quit the National Association of
Broadcasters, the Washington-based organization charged with
representing the industry's interests with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   NBC thus joins Fox in a move that illustrates how their
interests have diverged from those of other networks. Fox left the
association in June, but ABC and CBS have announced their
intentions to stay, at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The crux is a decision by the group not to push for further
relaxation of rules in areas like station ownership and the
networks' relationship with their affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cotton, general counsel for NBC, said Tuesday that the
network could no longer take part in an organization that was
sticking with ``archaic, anachronistic rules'' in a ``marketplace
that is turning upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC had sought backing for an effort to change rules that limit
the number of stations one company can own. One organization cannot
own television stations that reach more than 35 percent of the
country. NBC argued that the association had been extremely
aggressive in pushing to relax regulations that had limited station
ownership in radio but had held back in television.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the association, the NBC president, Bob Wright,
said the network had no alternative but to leave the organization
because of its ``continued unwillingness to embrace a
forward-looking strategy.'' He said the association treated
broadcasters as if they ``still lived in a world where Americans
gathered around their black-and-white televisions to watch Milton
Berle and `Bonanza.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fox quit the association for similar reasons. But many of the
corporate owners of television station groups _ which make up the
majority of the membership and dominate the association's board _
have opposed lifting the cap on station ownership. Dennis Wharton,
an association spokesman, said, ``Our board has told us they think
the 35 percent cap in appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Networks and other station owners have been on a collision
course in recent years, especially over the issue of the networks'
payments to stations that carry their shows. The networks have been
trying to end that practice, which goes back to the days of network
radio; stations have been fighting to keep it in place.
</P>
<P>
   Stations fear that if the networks gain too much power it will
be easier for them to force their affiliates to hew to their
wishes. Station owners are also concerned about networks' having
the ability to buy more stations, fearing they might bid up the
prices of stations that come up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton said the 35 percent coverage limit was absurd because it
was applied geographically, not in terms of actual audience
reached. He said that NBC had calculated that, given the growth of
competition from cable and other outlets like satellite television,
its stations reached only about 6 percent of the national audience.
He compared that figure to individual cable companies, some of
which reach 20 percent of the national audience.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's departure means the loss of $400,000 in annual dues for
the association. Wharton said the organization was still strong,
though NBC's decision to abandon it ``certainly hurts us on a
perception level.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Those Strong `Walls' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HBO had its biggest Sunday night in three years on the strength
of ``If These Walls Could Talk 2,'' also its highest-rated original
movie in three years.
</P>
<P>
   But the other big part of the story was ``The Sopranos,'' which
proved that its popularity can even survive an unusual scheduling
move. Despite being moved up an hour to 8 p.m. on Sunday night, a
change that went unnoticed by many fans of the series, Sunday's
``Sopranos'' episode scored a lofty 13.8 rating in homes that
subscribe to HBO. That is among the higher ratings the series has
received.
</P>
<P>
   It was also enough to boost ``If These Walls Could Talk 2'' to
an 11.5 rating, the highest rating for any HBO movie since January
1997, when it ran a film called ``Dead Silent.'' (Each rating point
for HBO represents approximately 260,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   The score for the movie, while good, did not come close to the
rating for the original ``Walls,'' which played in 1996. That movie
got the highest rating for any movie ever on HBO, an 18.7. Of
course there was one difference: this time HBO was up against some
different programming on Sunday night at 9, ABC's ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   That powerhouse game show proved impervious even to steamy sex
scenes starring Sharon Stone and Chloe Sevigny in separate
vignettes. Even in HBO homes ``Millionaire'' was the No. 1 show on
Sunday night at 9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; That's the News &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Nightly News'' with Tom Brokaw has been the leading
network news broadcast for much of the last three years and
continued its dominance in the February sweeps, beating ABC and CBS
across the board.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings for the evening news on both NBC and ABC stayed
relatively constant with their performances last February, but the
CBS news broadcast continued to show signs of falling off. For
February CBS' program was down 9 percent from a year ago in
household ratings and 12 percent in total viewers.
</P>
<P>
   NBC meanwhile was off only 3 percent in households and 2 percent
in total viewers. ABC was off just 1 percent in households and 2
percent in total viewers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
