<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-ART-460     03-07 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-ART-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH PEACEKEEPERS AND KOSOVAR CIVILIANS HURT IN ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Dozens of people were injured in
shootings and grenade attacks in the divided town of Kosovska
Mitrovica on Tuesday, among them French peacekeepers and both
Albanian and Serbian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a brawl quickly escalated into a number of
retaliatory attacks between the ethnic groups, catching the
peacekeepers in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The violence comes on the back of a whole month of serious
disturbances, which have caused at least nine deaths in the town,
and dashed hopes of the international community that the worst was
over.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 17 French soldiers were wounded, all from shrapnel
from hand grenades thrown in their midst, a spokesman for the
peacekeepers said. Television pictures showed some of them being
carried on stretchers, in scenes of burning cars and further
explosions. None of the soldiers were in serious danger, the
spokesman said, and only three were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 20 Serbian civilians and 5 Albanians were reported
injured, although figures were not precise, and even spokesmen from
KFOR, the Kosovo peacekeeping force, were giving out different
numbers. Several strong explosions were heard later in or around
three apartment buildings inhabited mostly by Albanians. It was not
clear if there were further injuries.
</P>
<P>
   With the violence, some 50 Albanians fled their homes in the
north, making their way to the Albanian district south of the
river, The Associated Press reported. One of them, Aida Kadriu,
said her uncle had been injured in a grenade blast, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 800 Albanians live among the Serbs in the north of
the city but their lives are increasingly precarious. Most of the
violence of the last month has been centered in the north part.
Peacekeepers had only just persuaded some 40 Albanians to return to
their homes after an outburst of Serbian violence Feb. 3 that
killed eight Albanians and caused 1,000 more to flee.
</P>
<P>
   The city, which is patrolled by over 1,000 troops, came under
curfew at 8 p.m. Tuesday night. Four suspects were arrested in
connection with the grenade attacks, the French military spokesman,
Lt. Matthieu Mabin, told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   The violence broke out in the middle of the day in an Albanian
area that borders the Serbian-dominated sector of the city. An
argument broke out between a Serb and an Albanian, when a second
Albanian pulled a gun and shot the Serb, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   An angry crowd of Serbs gathered and French troops moved in to
break up the confrontation, when Albanians suddenly lobbed several
grenades into the crowd. The French soldiers do not appear to have
been the target, but they bore much of the damage. Two cars began
to burn as troops carried away the wounded and reinforcements
arrived.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The area where most of the violence occurred Tuesday is known as
the Bosnian quarter and is especially volatile. Mostly inhabited by
Albanians, it was the scene of fierce fighting Feb. 13 when two
French soldiers and a number of Serbs were wounded, and an Albanian
gunman was shot dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians say they are under threat from the Serbs who want
to push them out from their homes on the northern bank of the River
Ibar. The Serbs say the Bosnian quarter is home to Albanian armed
extremists, who are seeking to push the Serbs out of Mitrovica
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The French troops, who have command of Mitrovica as part of
their northern sector, are trying to keep the two apart, but have
failed to calm the local communities. The Albanians complain that
Serbs are trying to attack them from behind the shadow of the
French troops. That may be an exaggeration, but television pictures
of Tuesday's violence showed Serb civilians milling around the
French troops, taking shelter behind armored vehicles, and
essentially sharing the same front line.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians say those throwing the grenades are aiming at Serbs
who are attacking them, but the more radical of the Albanians say
they now consider the French troops to be on the same side as the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme commander, canceled a visit to
Mitrovica Tuesday, NATO officials said after the attacks. They did
not say if the violence was the reason.
</P>
</TEXT>
