<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCHRANE-CONSTRUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING ON A NORTH CAROLINA BACKGROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Luther Cochrane is chief executive of Bovis Lend Lease, a New
York-based construction and project manager owned by the Lend Lease
Corp. of Australia.) 
(DW) 
 By LUTHER COCHRANE with DEIDRE LEIPZIGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I come from a town in North Carolina called Weldon. It had about
2,000 people when I was born and has about 2,000 today. Not much
else has changed there, either. Though I've lived in a lot of
places since, I'm a dyed-in-the-wool North Carolinian.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 12, with a little help from a lot of people, I worked
on a renovation project for the home of this lady in Weldon, using
ideas I'd seen in magazines. A builder actually used my ideas. The
lady paid me $200, and I won an honorable mention in a Good
Housekeeping contest. Then a friend of my mother's wanted to build
a house for the family who worked her farm. She asked me _ I think
mostly to humor my family _ to give her some design sketches. That
was built, too. So by the time I was 13{, I had two construction
projects under my belt.
</P>
<P>
   I was hooked. I wanted to be an architect. But when I was in
high school, I was a reasonably good football player. North
Carolina State University in Raleigh, which had a good architecture
school, didn't recruit me, though; they told me I wasn't a very
good football player. The University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill, which had liberal arts, did, so I went there. Turns out
Raleigh was right: I wasn't very good at football, and I soon quit
playing.
</P>
<P>
   I finally got my undergraduate degree from Chapel Hill, then
decided I would study law because I wasn't ready to work yet.
</P>
<P>
   While scrambling for a summer clerkship, I met Buck Griffin, who
is one of the great influences of my life. He worked with an
Atlanta firm that did construction law. I liked this guy so much
that despite my intention to stay in North Carolina I accepted an
internship there. Then, I liked that Atlanta firm so much that I
accepted a job offer with them after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   One week on the job, McDevitt &AMP; Street Co., which evolved into
Bovis, became my first client. I was still wet behind the ears, but
because McDevitt was North Carolina-based, the firm sent me.
</P>
<P>
   When Buck and I started our own firm in 1980, McDevitt came with
us as a client. While I was outside counsel, McDevitt asked me to
sit on the board. Bob Street, who was the owner, named me his
successor _ you know, just to have one.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1989, Bob suddenly took ill. He had just run a marathon.
He said: ``Luke, I've got to go to the Mayo Clinic. How about
dropping everything to run the year-end executive meeting? I'll be
back in a week or so.''
</P>
<P>
   He died in early April of 1990, of Lou Gehrig's disease. What we
had both thought would never occur had occurred. I moved full time
to McDevitt.
</P>
<P>
   One of the neat things about my business is that you create
something tangible _ something that people enjoy. It makes you feel
good to do that _ though you remember, of course, here's a floor
slab that didn't go right, there's a building that came in four
months late.
</P>
<P>
   When my son, Robert, was around 2{, we drove past a big building
in Charlotte that my company had worked on. I said, ``Robert, did
you know that Daddy built this building?'' then amended that to,
``I didn't actually build it, I did the contract.'' I thought he
understood.
</P>
<P>
   Later, while driving around with my wife, Robert pointed out the
building. ``Daddy built it all by himself,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
