<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Friday March, 10) 
 
By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   March 10, 2000 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The annual American Crossword Puzzle Tournament starts today in
Stamford, Conn. When and where was the crossword puzzle invented? &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To get the point ACROSS, this week's featured wine should go
DOWN well with those who like a well-made chardonnay. It's also the
finest chardonnay I've ever had from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   I tasted the wine ``blind'' and wrote down that it was obviously
from California and probably from the Russian River Valley, because
the 1998 Llano Estacado ``Cellar Select'' Chardonnay _ 4 1/2 stars
_ had excellent, spicy apple-pear fruit and just the right amount
of oakiness to complement the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   In short, a crackerjack effort. About $15.99. From Republic
Beverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ According to Famous First Facts, the first crossword was
devised by Arthur Wynne in 1913 for the New York World newspaper.
