<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BALLOON-THEATER-REVIE     03-07 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOON-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE RED BALLOON': BREATHING NEW LIFE INTO OLD `BALLOON' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any solitary child who has ever longed for a pet,
created an imaginary friend or inhabited a fantasy world of high
adventure seems likely to identify with Pascal in ``The Red
Balloon,'' the little charmer that will play through Sunday at the
New Victory Theater in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   If the title of this engaging production by the Visible Fictions
Theater Company of Scotland rings a bell, believe the bong. ``The
Red Balloon'' was adapted by the company from the story by Albert
Lamorisse, whose film of the same title won an Academy Award in
1957 for best original screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   As interpreted by the versatile four-member Visible Fictions
Troupe through dialogue, mime, dance, puppetry and music that
ranges from pop to classical, the 55-minute ``Red Balloon'' proves
once more to be a vehicle that can soar with joy and plumb the
depths of loneliness and despair. At times funny, at times
suspenseful, trenchant and buoyant _ after all, the balloon of the
title packs plenty of mischief _ ``The Red Balloon'' is a fine
fantasy, calculated to entertain children as young as 4 while
holding substantial rewards for their older companions.
</P>
<P>
   So once again the little French boy, played now by Veronica Leer
with the proper mixture of youthful spirit, impudence and
rebelliousness, is refused a pet by his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his fantasy adventures built around his only playmate,
a cloth hand puppet, a quest for a cat proves fruitless. ``Frank
searched for miles and miles,'' Pascal narrates. ``There was no
cat. He will never have a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But one day an enchanted red balloon enters Pascal's life,
touching off a series of adventures and encounters among bus
riders, schoolmates, the school janitor, the overbearing principal
(who gets a few bops from the balloon for her pains) and the
slingshot-toting rowdies who are the villains of this piece.
</P>
<P>
   The balloon, manipulated by Douglas Irvine, who plays a variety
of roles _ as do Kate Brailsford and Yngvil Vatn Guttu _ proves to
be a character filled with more than hot air or helium. The balloon
is a good friend, with a broad red cheek to hug and the good sense
to wake Pascal with a firm bop when he oversleeps. But it is
equally mischievous, occasionally jealous and often disobedient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balloon, you have to come when I call you,'' Pascal warns.
``You'll get us both in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   That trouble is part of the wit and wisdom that makes ``The Red
Balloon'' so durable and beguiling a tale.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE RED BALLOON'
</P>
<P>
   A Visible Fictions Theater Company production, Douglas Irvine,
artistic director; Kate Brailsford, associate director; Lavinia
Landels, administrator. Adapted by the company from the novel by
Albert Lamorisse. Directed by Annie Wood; sets by Karen Tennent;
lighting by Stuart Jenkins; musical director, Yngvil Vatn Guttu;
stage manager, Camilla O'Neill; production assistant, Kirel Samuel.
Presented by the New 42nd Street Inc. At the New Victory Theater,
209 West 42nd St.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Veronica Leer (Pascal), Douglas Irvine (Balloon), Kate
Brailsford (Janitor) and Yngvil Vatn Guttu (Head Teacher).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
