<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9627 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RADIO-FRESH-AIR-ART-2     03-07 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-FRESH-AIR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROSPECTOR PANNING FOR CULTURAL NUGGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT21 and NYT22, have been sent to New York Times
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SAMUEL G. FREEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Moving through the weak winter sunlight early one
morning, Terry Gross reached the threshold of WHYY-FM's offices
here, dragging behind her a portion of American culture, packed
into a salesman's sample case. It was a Thursday, the busiest day
of the week for Gross in her role as host and co-executive producer
of ``Fresh Air,'' the syndicated arts show that reaches nearly
three million listeners daily on National Public Radio and thus is
an increasingly influential taste maker.
</P>
<P>
   Before day's end she would moderate an hourlong live broadcast,
conduct two interviews for future shows and wade into the morass of
books, films and CD's vying for coverage in the coming week. The
sample case, her usual means of transporting material to and from
the radio station, suffices for any evening except a Thursday. That
night she would load her car with crates full of submissions to
take home.
</P>
<P>
   Gross had stayed up until 11:30 the previous night working her
way through the sample case's contents. She watched a documentary
on the theremin, an electronic instrument; made notes on the bond
between Chinese food and culture and played tracks from a few discs
of synthesizer music, trying all the while to catch snatches of the
Grammy Awards broadcast. ``If I'm doing one thing, then I'm missing
another,'' she said of the regimen. ``To keep up with one part of
culture, you ignore the other.''
</P>
<P>
   By 7:30 that morning she had scanned the newspaper obituaries
for any cultural figure worthy of a memorial segment and packed a
bagel, fruit and an egg-white sandwich for the breakfast and lunch
she knew she would eat at her desk. As she entered the WHYY
building at 8:15, she found Daniel Miller, her fellow executive
producer, listening through headphones to one of the interviews
scheduled for broadcast that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fresh Air'' will have its 25th anniversary in September, and
over the years it has done more than grow from a local feature on
WHYY to a programming staple of 290 stations. The program has made
Gross, with her rolling laughter and falsetto leaps of enthusiasm,
a trusted voice and arbiter in the cultural landscape. From Gross'
interviews to commentary by a stable of critics, ``Fresh Air''
guides listeners to choices as considered yet eclectic as the soul
singer Arthur Alexander, the novelist Nadine Gordimer and the
director Roger Corman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't say that we have The List,'' Gross, 49, said of the
show's decisions. ``We don't have the resources to be encyclopedic,
and I don't think we present ourselves as doing that. We're saying,
`Here are current and interesting books and movies and CD's and
issues.' I see our listeners as people who are smart and curious
and like to have a new idea, like to be challenged, don't want to
just go with what they already know.'' Or as one of Gross'
producers, Naomi Person, put it, ``It's that feeling of finding
something great and wanting to tell everybody you know about it.''
As a national show ``Fresh Air'' stands nearly alone in the
broadcast media for its abiding commitment to culture. ``Given the
almost complete cop-out of television in arts and cultural
programming, you have to look to public radio for coverage that
shows curiosity and enterprise as distinct from tracking big names
and celebrity,'' said Michael Janeway, director of the National
Arts Journalism Program at Columbia University. ``Every time I
listen to `Fresh Air' I'm struck by the range of interest, the
originality. They're doing very creative work.''
</P>
<P>
   With such credibility has come marketplace clout. ``It's one of
those shows you want, badly want,'' said George Gibson, the
president of Walker &AMP; Co., a publishing house best known for Dava
Sobel's ``Longitude'' and ``Galileo's Daughter.'' ``It speaks to a
highly intelligent, motivated audience _ people who buy books and
will respond to an intelligent dialogue about them. Terry Gross has
a gift for getting below the surface, for bringing out intriguing
aspects of an author or a book. And she's quirky. It's a mystery to
me, and I suspect even to her producers, what works for her.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One thing that worked on this particular Thursday in February
was ``The Chinese Kitchen,'' a new book by the chef Eileen Yin-Fei
Lo. A few minutes before 10 a.m., Gross settled into the studio for
a taping with the author. Since she originated ``Fresh Air'' in
1975, Gross has conducted some 5,000 interviews, and like the jazz
singers she admires, her neck veins and supple cheeks attest to
years of vocal projection. She gently steered her discussion with
Lo toward the idea of cuisine as culture, lowering her eyebrows in
concentration, rubbing her fingers together as if handling beads.
</P>
<P>
   By the session's end Gross had conjured from Lo stories about
foot-binding, the kitchen god and the ``sweet-birth vinegar''
consumed by pregnant women. Lo had recounted her escape from China
in 1950 and her refusal ever to return to the home village where
her relatives were punished in retaliation. Of her first ambition
outside Communist China, Lo confided to Gross: ``I always wanted to
be a spy. CIA.''
</P>
<P>
   From exactly 58 minutes 59 seconds of tape, Person and an
associate producer, Ann Marie Baldonado, would extract 22 minutes
of dialogue, the length of most interview segments. But the editing
would not occur until the next week. For now production remained
incomplete for the program to be broadcast live at noon. (Many
stations carry the program on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Headphones at his ears, razor in hand, Miller hunched over his
editing machine, listening again and again to a few inches of
Gross' interview with Christopher Lloyd, the executive producer of
the NBC television comedy ``Frasier.'' Gross led into one question
by summarizing the plot of a recent episode, and Miller wanted to
slow down her delivery just a bit for clarity. ``Looking for
breath,'' he muttered as he scrutinized the tape. ``Gaspy breath.''
</P>
<P>
   He was still searching for it when Roberta Shorrock, director of
``Fresh Air,'' entered the control room at 11:55 a.m. to speed-dial
the number of the U.S. Naval Observatory. On the opposite side of
the glass Gross tapped away at a laptop in the studio, finishing
the text for the introduction to the show and the bridges between
its recorded segments. With Shorrock assured by the Navy that
``Fresh Air'' had the correct time down to the second, the show
commenced.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:27 p.m., with an opening segment about medical errors just
about finished, Miller strode into the control room with the first
of three reels of the segment with Lloyd, now enhanced by a
transplanted syllable of gaspy breath. By ``Fresh Air'' standards,
that timing was not even alarming. On one show a few years ago, an
edited tape reached the control room so close to broadcast time
that it could not be threaded onto the takeup reel and instead
unspooled onto the floor as it played. ``Somebody once accused me
of being hypnotically attracted to chaos,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   What allows a certain composure on ``Fresh Air'' is a veteran
production team. Miller, Shorrock and the segment producers _
Person, Phyllis Myers, Amy Salit and Joan Toohey Weisman _ have
variously logged from 11 to 22 years with the show. Their
backgrounds, as diverse as the program they develop, range from
salsa musician to documentary filmmaker to drama student. More than
the rest, Person and Salit act as filters, deciding what fraction
of the tonnage of material submitted to ``Fresh Air'' should be
funneled to Gross.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:15 that Thursday afternoon, Salit was all but barricaded
behind her desk by 21 mail crates of books, CD's, press kits and
Federal Express packages. ``I didn't even get today's mail yet,''
she said. She wouldn't for a few more hours, either, because at 2
p.m. she had to go to the control room to produce Gross' interview
with Robert Moog, inventor of the synthesizer. Salit, who has a
passion for alternative music and club-hopping, was the one who had
suggested Moog as a subject.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Person was wedged into her carrel trying to watch
stretches of Eric Bross' film ``Restaurant'' on a VCR while reading
a press release about National Poetry Month in April. On her desk
was a pad of phone messages in triplicate, the brainstorm of an
efficiency consultant whom WHYY recently hired. Above Person's
computer hung a Buddhist proverb: ``Chaos should be regarded as
extremely good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward 4 p.m. Salit and then Person reported to Gross' office
with one mail crate apiece. A book about the film ``All About
Eve,'' a CD by a Romanian pan-pipe virtuoso, some reviews of
Charles Durning's performance in a revival of ``Glengarry Glen
Ross,'' a videocassette of a James Toback film with Robert Downey,
Jr. _ the women picked and mulled over all that and more. ``I like
the title. ... Here's a band from Nashville getting good reviews.
... I know there's a press kit with this. ...''
</P>
<P>
   A youthful Frank Sinatra gazed dreamily from an enlarged photo
above Gross' desk, a reminder that, in the end, she has her own
tastes and judgments. She grew up in Brooklyn smitten with musical
theater and aspiring to become a lyricist, and her adult love of
jazz is one she shares with her husband, the music critic Francis
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago Salit returned from a screening of Paul Thomas
Anderson's ``Magnolia'' certain that Gross would find it
pretentious. On the contrary, Gross enjoyed the film enough to see
it twice.
</P>
<P>
   With the afternoon sun waning and the WHYY entrance falling into
shadows, Gross lurched toward her car with her crates, her first
step outside in nine hours. She would stay up until midnight trying
to make choices and still give herself a night's sleep before
Friday's interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may lose your energy,'' she said before leaving the
office, ``but you never lose your love for culture. The thing that
burns you out also keeps you going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
