<HEADER>
A9630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CHICKEN-0308-COX     03-07 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-0308-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY FINDS FEW SAFETY PROBLEMS WITH FEDERAL SCHOOL MEAL PROGRAM
 &HT;    500&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a recent rash of incidents raising concerns
about the safety of food purchased by the federal government for
the nation's schoolchildren, a General Accounting Office
investigation has found few problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few outbreaks of food-borne illness have been reported''
involving government-donated food, the GAO said in a report
released Tuesday. In fact, the report said, U.S. Agriculture
Department officials ``may have prevented or mitigated such
outbreaks'' by helping to remove suspect food before it reached
kids.
</P>
<P>
   However, the GAO faulted the Agriculture Department for not
sufficiently documenting problems with food that the federal
government donates through the National School Lunch and School
Breakfast programs, which provide a total of 33 million breakfasts
and lunches at thousands of schools each day.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticized the agency for not giving guidance to
local school districts when they purchase food to supplement that
which is provided by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are unacceptably large gaps in our knowledge about
whether we are doing all we can to ensure the safety of 33 million
meals eaten every day by our nation's children'' Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, said in a statement accompanying release of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin requested the GAO study a year ago following a Cox
Newspapers report on an E. coli outbreak at an elementary school in
Finley, Wash., that health officials linked to government-donated
beef. The GAO is the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   While the report dealt only briefly with the Finley outbreak, it
said the Agriculture Department tested a sample of the ground beef
used in the meal and found nothing wrong. However, the GAO included
that incident among those in which food-borne illnesses were
associated with federally-donated foods.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the GAO said it found 17 outbreaks of food-borne
illness during 1997 and 1998 that could be tied to food served in
schools. However, that number could be larger because the GAO,
lacking any nationwide statistics for 1998, instead said it
surveyed only ten states.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Oleson, the GAO official in charge of preparing the
report, said Tuesday his investigators did not call all 50 states
because it was a ``time issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also said federal procurement officers told
investigators they ``consider the potential suppliers' records for
compliance with food safety regulations in their reviews of bids''
for contracts to provide food. However, the report does not discuss
what federal purchasing officials considered when they bought
ground beef from Northern States Beef, the Nebraska-based company
that supplied the meat suspected in the Finley outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department records show that in the 18 months prior
to its purchase from Northern States Beef, food safety inspectors
cited the company 171 times for ``critical'' food safety
violations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, a plant operated by Hudson Foods, which in 1997
had the largest recall of meat in U.S. history because of E. coli
contamination, amassed 90 critical violations the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Oleson said he never heard of Northern States Beef and could not
explain precisely what the government had considered before
purchasing from the company. He said he would have to talk to his
investigators about the case.
</P>
<P>
   The report also cited the 1999 Supreme Beef case in Texas as an
example of how the Agriculture Department has established policies
to ensure the safety of food bound for school meals. The report
says that the day after the agency began enforcement proceedings
against the Dallas-based company for not complying with food safety
standards, the government ``terminated (the company's) school food
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   According to federal records, Supreme Beef flunked three rounds
of tests for Salmonella contamination over a period of roughly
eight months prior to its action. During that time, the government
continued to buy meat from the company for the school meals
program.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Agriculture Department action against Supreme Beef
late last year, concerned Texas school officials embargoed the
ground beef that the federal government had purchased at the same
it was discovering Salmonella. Eventually, after the agency assured
the state the meat was safe, it was released to local schools.
</P>
<P>
   Oleson acknowledged the government was buying beef at the same
time it was discovering Salmonella, but said the Agriculture
Department was locked into a contract with the company. Oleson said
as long as Supreme Beef was open for business and being inspected
by the federal government, the government was legally obligated to
buy what was being produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food system in the United States is not one hundred
percent safe,'' Oleson said, ``There are not guarantees. You are
going to have outbreaks. You are going to have illnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Jaspin can be reached by e-mail at:
elliotj(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
