<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SLOW TO ALERT TROOPS ABOUT FAULTY SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN M. DONNELLY ASSOCIATED PRESS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although a Pentagon agency warned the Army and Air
Force in early February not to use potentially flawed chemical
suits, the services didn't pass the message on to the field until
weeks later _ the day after the problem was made public, military
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Even now it is unclear how widely the message has spread among
US forces deployed worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 3, the Defense Logistics Agency told all the military
services' logistics offices not to use suits from two suspect lots
in any real emergency. But it was not until Feb. 28, the day after
the Associated Press reported that many of the suits contained
holes and tears and the contractor had been charged with fraud,
that the message went beyond the logistics offices.
</P>
<P>
   Unaware of the problem's scope were troops at Army and Air Force
bases who, the Pentagon inspector general says, could have been
killed wearing faulty suits during a gas or germ attack.
</P>
<P>
   Only last Friday did the Defense Logistics Agency send a memo to
four-star generals and admirals on every continent, the Army and
Air Force chiefs, and others _ as opposed to logistics offices. The
latest memo provides more detailed information on what items to set
aside and who to call with questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 3 warning said 1989 and 1992 lots of ``battle dress
overgarments'' made by Isratex Inc. of New York City should be
removed from the active inventory. An alert in December to the same
logistics offices mentioned only the 1992 lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force didn't tell bases around the world that either lot
was defective until the day after the story broke, said Major Donna
Nicholas, an Air Force spokeswoman. The Army had told its soldiers
about the 1992 lot but not about the 1989 lot, because Army
headquarters didn't get the Feb. 3 memo and first learned about it
in the press, said spokeswoman Nancy Ray. A Navy spokesman,
Lieutenant Matt O'Neal, said sailors and Marines have their own
protective suits and none are made by Isratex.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 1989 lot has not been proven defective, it was
pulled with the 1992 lot and is considered suspect because of the
company that made it, agency and inspector general officials have
said. The company provided 780,000 suits to the military at a cost
of $49 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas said officials at Air Force headquarters never got the
December message. And she said the Feb. 3 warning was sent to the
wrong Air Force location and wasn't received by headquarters until
Feb. 15. Nearly two more weeks passed before the Air Force issued a
warning memo Feb. 28, the day after the AP story.
</P>
<P>
   The belated Feb. 28 memo was sent not to field units, such as
air bases in Korea or the Middle East, but to the supply offices of
major commands and to Air Force centers that store such equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The service telephoned bases in ``high-threat'' areas such as
Korea to notify them of the problem suits, Nicholas said, though
she could not document such contacts or say precisely when they
occurred. She called it ``coincidence'' that the service's warning
came soon after the press report.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Army warned field units about 1992 lots,
headquarters never received the Feb. 3 memo on the 1989 lot, Ray
said. She and others said the news stories alerted officials to the
1989 lot and that on Feb. 28, phone calls were made to warn US and
overseas units about both lots.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Larry Barker, responsible for chemical gear for the
85,000 troops in the 18th Airborne Corps, said the first time he
heard about the 1989 lot being a potential problem was Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have conceded they knew as far back as 1994
that Isratex was being investigated for allegedly selling inferior
products with the intent to defraud the military. Eventually, five
Isratex contracts were included in an indictment against the firm.
Last September, company officials pleaded guilty to various charges
in US District Court in New York. Sentencing is set for April.
</P>
<P>
   After tests last September showed flaws on suits from the 1992
lot were more serious than previously believed, the Defense
Logistics Agency issued the Dec. 2 warning to 18 logistics offices.
The December warning cites only the 1992 deal but says all suits
``that are connected with/manufactured by subject contractor be
used for TRAINING ONLY!''
</P>
<P>
   The Feb. 3 memo was sent to the same recipients. This time it
said the 1989 and 1992 lots ``have been tested and identified as
being unsuitable as chemical protective suits.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no deadline for action in either memo, but both
requested ``widest possible dissemination of this document.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
