<HEADLINE>
MOZAMBIQUE DEBT RELIEF URGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As floodwaters recede in Mozambique, many advocates
for the poor say Washington's reaction should be more than food,
shelter, and rescue teams.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest gift, they say, would be in helping poverty-stricken
countries eliminate their debt.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of clergy, non-profit leaders, and senior Clinton
administration officials Tuesday pressed Congress to help unlock an
international debt-relief plan that would aid Mozambique and other
poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the House Appropriations Committee, which will take up a
$210 million debt relief contribution Thursday as part of a $5.2
billion supplemental bill, has cut funding for the program because
administration officials did not follow proper procedures, said
committee spokeswoman Elizabeth Morra.
</P>
<P>
   Morra said House Republican leaders and Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers had agreed the committee would fund new debt
relief only with authorizing legislation, and no such bill has been
introduced. In addition, she questioned whether debt relief should
part of an emergency spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is whether it's a real emergency,'' Morra
said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said it was, as did several others Tuesday, including
three from Massachusetts: Cardinal Bernard Law; the Reverend M.
Thomas Shaw, bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts; and
Raymond C. Offenheiser, president of Oxfam America, who recently
returned from Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Mozambique, debt relief means flood relief,'' Shaw said at
a news conference. ``. . . We must seize this historic opportunity
to take moral action, grounded in Scripture and our compassion for
those in need.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said erasing much of the African nation's debt ``is a
good investment for the United States.'' He also announced the
administration was forgiving the remainder of Mozambique's debt to
the United States, a largely symbolic gesture amounting to less
than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mozambique owes $6 billion, much of it to Russia, and until
recently had been paying $2 million a week in debt service _ more
than it spends for education and health care combined.
</P>
<P>
   In the world's 33 poorest countries, that is a depressingly
familiar story.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the advocates say, debt service has kept the poorest
countries wedded to misery. In these nations, life expectancy is 25
years less than in developed countries. People are 40 percent less
literate. Women are 30 times more likely to die during pregancy.
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering of the largest industrial nations last year in
Cologne, Germany, leaders created the Heavily Indebted Poor
Countries Trust Fund. The fund aims to collect $28 billion that
will allow those countries to write off about $90 billion in debt,
the difference mostly made up of interest payments. The US share is
$960 million in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   The fund was designed so that all creditor countries contribute.
Several countries have put their share on hold until they see what
Congress does with the $210 million request.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funding is critical not only because of what it will
supply directly but also because of the important inducement it
will provide for other donor countries,'' Law wrote to House
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, an Illinois Republican.
</P>
<P>
   If the trust fund works, the countries still would be $37
billion in debt, but it would free millions of dollars for social
services and infrastructure. In Mozambique, weekly debt payment
would fall from $2 million to $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frees up about $800,000 a week for reconstruction of that
country,'' said James McDonald, a policy analyst at Bread for the
World, a nonprofit citizens' group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam's Offenheiser said debt relief becomes especially critical
in the aftermath of a natural disaster. ``We learned from Hurricane
Mitch in Nicaragua and Honduras that relief aid really helps
short-term needs, but debt relief has real long-term effects,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9639 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HISPANICS-SOUTH-COX     03-07 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-SOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanic population rising faster in the South
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hispanic population is increasing faster in the South than
in the rest of the country, according to a report released today by
the U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The report paints the portrait of a nation undergoing a profound
transformation from a mainly biracial population to one sprinkled
with people of more various racial and ethnic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're experiencing a major demographic change in the United
States,'' said Roberto M. Ramirez, author of the report. ``Across
the board there have been increases in the Hispanic population all
over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, he said, the number of Hispanics in the South
increased 23.6 percent while the number of Hispanics nationwide
went up 18.9 percent. He estimates that the South's Hispanic
population increased 4.6 percent last year, compared with a 2.9
percent national increase.
</P>
<P>
   The census bureau considers the South a 16-state region that
includes the District of Columbia and stretches from Florida to
Delaware to Oklahoma and Texas. It says 10.4 million of the
nation's 31.7 million Hispanics live in the South. About 84 percent
of the South's Hispanic population live in Texas and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   While Census estimates last year said Georgia's Hispanic
population had shot up 100 percent since 1990, Latinos still make
up only 2.9 percent of the state population. By contrast, Hispanics
made up 30 percent of the population in Texas and 15 percent in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Maritza Soto Keen, executive director of metro Atlanta's Latin
American Association, said Latinos will gain more political power
as their numbers increase across the South. Last year, Gov. Roy
Barnes appointed a Latino Forum to recommend changes to state law
to benefit the estimated 220,000 to 480,000 Latinos here. In North
Carolina, Gov. Jim Hunt created an Office of Hispanic/Latino
Affairs in 1998. Georgia ranks fifth nationally in percentage
increase in Hispanic buying power since 1990, according to a
University of Georgia study. Only Arkansas, Nevada, North Carolina
and Vermont had bigger increases in disposable income.
</P>
<P>
   Only three states had higher growth rates in their Hispanic
population in the 1990s than Georgia, and two of them _ Arkansas
and North Carolina _ were in the South. The fourth state was
Nevada; thousands of Latinos have taken jobs in recent years in the
hotels and casinos of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said the largest wave of immigration _ legal and illegal
_ in nearly a century has increased the nation's Hispanic
population, but so have high birth rates. He said Hispanic women
have an average of 3.2 children and that non-Hispanic white women
have an average of 1.5 children. His report says Hispanics are
three times more likely than non-Hispanic whites to live in poverty
and that they generally have lower education levels than
non-Hispanic whites.
</P>
<P>
   It also points out statistical differences among Hispanics
grouped by nationality. While 23 percent of Hispanic families lived
below the poverty level, according to the report, the number is
higher for Mexicans (24 percent) and Puerto Ricans (27 percent)
than for Cubans (11 percent). The report says 6.1 percent of
non-Hispanic white families live below the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Among all Hispanic groups, about 50 percent of Mexicans had a
high school diploma or more, compared with 64 percent for Puerto
Ricans, 64 percent for Central and South Americans and 70 percent
for Cubans (88 percent of non-Hispanic whites had a high school
diploma).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think Hispanics are a homogenous group. They don't
realize there are stark differences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
