u v BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2     03-07 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, March 12,
2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST-WEST-FILM (Paris) _ The end of the cold war was definitely
bad news for those novelists and screenwriters who were counting on
the ``evil empire'' to provide them with plots for life. And yet,
while the KGB may no longer be a credible adversary, the old Soviet
Union has not been exhausted as a font of good stories. In fact,
thanks to the collapse of communism, it is now possible to see many
human dramas long obscured by the glare of the ideological
struggle. Regis Wargnier's new movie, ``East-West,'' nominated for
best foreign language film in this year's Oscars, recounts one such
drama. ``I could have made this movie in any place or any country
where there had been a totalitarian regime,'' the 51-year-old
French director said of ``East-West,'' which opens in New York on
April 14. By Alan Riding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHYAMALAN-FILMS (Philadelphia) _ Ascribe it to a sensitivity
earned from a youth in schools as the only Indian among Americans,
the only Hindu among Catholics. Attribute it to the eye that is
trained when a 10-year-old is given a movie camera, which he uses
to make 45 short films before age 15. Whatever the reason, it
should seem appropriate that M. Night Shyamalan _ M., for Manoj;
Night, a name he adopted at 17 (``romantic, mysterious, poetic'');
Shyamalan (pronounced SHA-ma-lan) _ would come up with ``The Sixth
Sense.'' After all, it's a thriller about a boy, Cole, who sees
things that no one else can see (dead people, as it happens), and
it features an alarming secret, numerous clues to which have been
sitting in plain sight. Shyamalan has a way of seeing things other
people do not see, and recognizing things others are slow to grasp.
By Jamie Malanowski. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMY-AWARDS-FILMS (Undated) _ This year I'm really going to
do it. When Billy Crystal bounds onto the stage of the Los Angeles
Shrine Auditorium on March 26, I will have seen every single film
and performance nominated for an Academy Award in every major
category, so help me God. Even if I have to go to a movie about an
old man driving a lawn mower across Iowa. By Anita Gates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMY-AWARDS-DOCUMENTARIES (Undated) _ In contrast to past
years, when popularity at the box office seemed to disqualify a
documentary from academy consideration, this year's five nominees
include one film that found an unusually large audience for a work
of nonfiction: ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' about a group of
forgotten musicians from prerevolutionary Cuba. The other nominees
include some well-regarded pictures, two of which also focus on
musicians. In the past, academy officials acknowledge, the choice
of nominees in the documentary category was skewed by rules that
required every member of the screening committee to watch every
eligible film in a theater, subjecting them to a marathon of as
many as 65 films in the space of two months. By Terry Pristin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CITY-BALLET _ While waiting for the next Balanchine to fill
the original Balanchine's shoes, the trick is to preserve his
legacy and breathe fresh air into the company he founded. One
solution, as the New York City Ballet demonstrated this winter is
to present an exuberantly danced season, introduce young and gifted
dancers, and realize that there is no second Balanchine. For
starters, it would be helpful to accept the idea, 17 years after
George Balanchine's death, that his kind of genius comes along only
every 100 years and to stop measuring other choreographers in the
company by his standard. By Anna Kisselgoff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUDDY-MEERS-THEATER (New York) _ A student at the Milton Academy
near Boston, David Lindsay-Abaire, who finished fourth in a
national ''speech team'' competition, is appearing in a new comedy,
``Fuddy Meers,'' at the Minetta Lane Theater. As the seemingly
nonsensical title suggests, the play is filled with shards of
broken speech uttered by fractured characters. By Peter Marks. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIVICA-GENAUX-OPERA (Washington) _ Not many rising opera stars
would choose to make their New York recital debuts singing chamber
music, and little-known Baroque chamber music, at that. Yet that is
what Vivica Genaux, 30, an American mezzo-soprano, plans to do
Monday evening at Weill Recital Hall. With Chatham Baroque, a
period-instrument group, she will delve into cantatas and arias by
Bononcini, Handel, Scarlatti, Vivaldi and the obscure 18th-century
Spanish composers Pablo Esteve and Antonio Literes. By Cori
Ellison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-REMAKES (Undated) _ The notion of artists changing their
music to please the prudish and commercial elements of society is
critically odious, but in the case of several recent singles, the
editing has actually improved the song. In a music landscape in
which the crude come-on has replaced the sly innuendo, some remakes
are bringing a touch of subtlety back to urban music. By Neil
Strauss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOB-DYLAN-MUSIC (Undated) _ When Bob Dylan was an acerbic young
folk singer warning that the times were a-changin', one change he
probably did not envision was that he would become a darling of the
high-art world. Yet last fall, nearly 40 years after he made his
first records, Dylan was declared one of the greatest artists of
the 20th century by Andrew Motion, the British poet laureate. And
now the composer John Corigliano, commissioned to write a song
cycle for the soprano Sylvia McNair's Carnegie Hall recital on
Wednesday evening, has produced ``Mr. Tambourine Man: Seven Poems
of Bob Dylan,'' a 35-minute song cycle. By Allan Kozinn. WITH
PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARTISTS-TIME-BOXES (Waltham, Mass.) _ In a stage-worthy scene,
the artists Richard Artschwager, Daniel Buren, Sol LeWitt and
Robert Ryman met here recently to reveal the secret contents of
four steel boxes they individually filled and sealed 25 years ago.
These artists' time boxes, and the dramatic opening held at the
Rose Art Museum at Brandeis University on Feb. 24, are both part of
a quarter-century-long collaborative project initiated by another
artist, Stephen Antonakos. The boxes, their contents and a neon
installation by Antonakos will be displayed here through Sunday as
part of the museum's millennium celebration. By Ann Wilson Lloyd.
WITH PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-MONEY-ART (Washington) _ Over the last 15 years, spurred
by exhibitions of African masks and ceremonial sculpture in
galleries and museums, collectors have been acquiring African
money. A pioneer collector, William Greenspon, a New York
psychiatrist who became an art dealer and painter, assembled a
large holding of African and other tribal money and sold it in 1986
to the Chase Manhattan Bank. These sculptural pieces were then
displayed as art in the bank's executive offices. Now both kinds of
African money, mostly owned by collectors, is going public in two
exhibitions. The smaller but more important show, ``The Artistry of
African Currency,'' opens here Sunday at the Smithsonian's National
Museum of African Art and remains through July 23. The show, the
first of African money in an American museum, includes 50 artifacts
in a variety of metals and humbler materials: cowrie shells, beads
and cloth. The larger exhibition, ``Africa's Iron and Copper
Currencies,'' is on view in Manhattan this month in the Low
Memorial Library at Columbia University. By Rita Reif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-ROBERT-TROUT (New York) _ Robert Trout came out of a cold
drizzle and into a nearly deserted midtown restaurant the other
day, ordered a bowl of risotto and a glass of red wine and began to
chat amiably, almost shyly, about broadcasting, cab driving and
Warren G. Harding. Trout is 90, and while osteoporosis has bent his
back and skewed his sense of balance, he is still the very model of
the suave, modern anchorman. And still very much in demand. By
Charles Strum. WITH PHOTO. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.) &QL;
