<HEADLINE>
ABC REVAMPS ITS EXCLUSIVE OSCAR PRESHOW
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC, which has exclusive rights to air live arrivals coverage in
the half hour before the Academy Awards ceremony, is promising a
preshow that is a lot livelier than last year's critically drubbed
broadcast hosted by actress Geena Davis.
</P>
<P>
   This year there will be three hosts covering the red carpet
outside the Shrine Auditorium, among them Meredith Vieira of ABC's
``The View.''
</P>
<P>
   Given her experience as a broadcast journalist and talk-show
interviewer, it's likely Vieira will be more comfortable working
without the script safety net Davis employed.
</P>
<P>
   ABC spokesman Dan Doran said Vieira's colleagues for the March
26 telecast are expected to be announced later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's first attempt at the exclusive preshow, during which other
broadcasters could tape footage but were forbidden to show it live,
was criticized as boring, relying on too much old footage, canned
segments and Davis' interviews inside the theater, thereby dousing
the spontaneity and you-are-there enthusiasm viewers savored on
several TV channels earlier in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the feeling has been that they wanted it to be more
red-carpet oriented,'' Doran said. ``There will be pretaped
packages _ you can't help that. The idea is to make it very
fast-paced, and it will be a seamless transfer right into the
regular show.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the critical pans prompted the change in the
show's format, Doran said, ``Last year was the first year and it
was an experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC exclusive preshow begins at 5 p.m., with the ceremonies
starting at 5:30. Other broadcasters covering earlier star arrivals
at the Shrine Auditorium include E! Entertainment on cable, KTLA
and KABC. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
