<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9647 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-REALTORS-HIGHTECH08-C     03-07 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALTORS-HIGHTECH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Using Internet to sell homes means door is always open
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the old days of buying and selling real estate, the
process was decidedly low-tech _ and high tedium.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, we had to go around to each real estate office
and pick up a key to the house, then show the house and go back and
take the keys back to that office,'' recalls Jim Bulla of Re/Max
Greater Atlanta's Cobb County office.
</P>
<P>
   In superaccelerated, Information Age time, those days are eons
ago _ back in 1978 _ when Bulla began selling homes in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the real estate industry has gone high tech, and Bulla
has ridden the information technology wave in order to transform
his old business practices to meet the demands of Internet-savvy
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I love it so much is there isn't any competition,''
he says. ``Right now, according to the National Association of
Realtors, 7 percent of the nation's Realtors are doing 93 percent
of annual sales nationwide. I'm in the 7 percent, if you want to
know where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   To compete at that level, Bulla uses the high-tech tools of the
trade, including fax machine, four computers (two at home, two at
the office), scanners, a Palm Pilot, two cell phones, two Web sites
and five printers.
</P>
<P>
   His target: a healthy share of the estimated 62 percent of
buyers who are now beginning their home search on the Internet.
Last week, for example, Bulla sold two houses for about $250,000
apiece. Both buyers were Internet shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can document over $4 million of sales direct from
Internet,'' Bulla says.
</P>
<P>
   Bulla has been competing on the Internet for some time now. ``I
started five years ago with my first Web site, and it wasn't
anything more than a billboard with my name on it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that small offering, he saw results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a hit on it,'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Bulla sold a house to that client, who turned out to be familiar
with Internet technology, and together they upgraded Bulla's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Bulla has created multiple Web sites, some of which
target specific categories of buyers, including a Web page for
senior citizens and one for buyers relocating to the Atlanta metro
area.
</P>
<P>
   Bulla himself moved to Atlanta 18 years ago, and he's been with
Re/Max for 10 years. He's originally from Indiana, where he was
raised on a hog farm and attended a school with a total of 125
students. ``I graduated in the top 10 of my class,'' he laughs.
``There were nine of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he went to the same school from first through 12th
grade, Bulla says he never experienced the anguish of moving from
one school to another. Last year, when a client from Chicago
decided to move to Atlanta, Bulla was struck by the reaction of one
of the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the daughters just started crying. She was leaving all
the friends and kids she'd ever known,'' he says. ``I just never
had that kind of trauma. As obvious as it is, it just never struck
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to that child's reaction, Bulla created a Web site
for kids, to help ease the anxiety of moving and to provide
kid-related information on schools, extracurricular activities and
the like.
</P>
<P>
   To further distinguish himself on the Net, Bulla has
incorporated ``virtual tours'' of many of his home listings. These
Web-based tours allow a potential buyer a 360-degree, full-color
view of key rooms in the home, as well as its exterior features.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his Web activity, Bulla has turned his office
into a miniprint shop. Using desktop publishing technology, he
customizes relocation kits for potential clients with
how-to-buy-a-house information, a personal moving inventory log and
detailed information on the schools in the area of their new home.
</P>
<P>
   Bulla also publishes informational pamphlets for his home
listings, which potential buyers can take with them after visiting
a property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually put a customized book in the house that has
pictures of all the rooms, a copy of the school report,'' Bulla
says. ``It tells the (home's) features, lists property disclosure
where the owner will tell you all he knows about the house, and a
termite disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get to the end of the day and they've looked at 20
houses and they can't remember any of them, they can remember ours
because they've got the book,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
