<HEADLINE>
MOZAMBIQUE DEBT RELIEF URGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As floodwaters recede in Mozambique, many advocates
for the poor say Washington's reaction should be more than food,
shelter, and rescue teams.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest gift, they say, would be in helping poverty-stricken
countries eliminate their debt.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of clergy, non-profit leaders, and senior Clinton
administration officials Tuesday pressed Congress to help unlock an
international debt-relief plan that would aid Mozambique and other
poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the House Appropriations Committee, which will take up a
$210 million debt relief contribution Thursday as part of a $5.2
billion supplemental bill, has cut funding for the program because
administration officials did not follow proper procedures, said
committee spokeswoman Elizabeth Morra.
</P>
<P>
   Morra said House Republican leaders and Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers had agreed the committee would fund new debt
relief only with authorizing legislation, and no such bill has been
introduced. In addition, she questioned whether debt relief should
part of an emergency spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is whether it's a real emergency,'' Morra
said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said it was, as did several others Tuesday, including
three from Massachusetts: Cardinal Bernard Law; the Reverend M.
Thomas Shaw, bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts; and
Raymond C. Offenheiser, president of Oxfam America, who recently
returned from Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Mozambique, debt relief means flood relief,'' Shaw said at
a news conference. ``. . . We must seize this historic opportunity
to take moral action, grounded in Scripture and our compassion for
those in need.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said erasing much of the African nation's debt ``is a
good investment for the United States.'' He also announced the
administration was forgiving the remainder of Mozambique's debt to
the United States, a largely symbolic gesture amounting to less
than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mozambique owes $6 billion, much of it to Russia, and until
recently had been paying $2 million a week in debt service _ more
than it spends for education and health care combined.
</P>
<P>
   In the world's 33 poorest countries, that is a depressingly
familiar story.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the advocates say, debt service has kept the poorest
countries wedded to misery. In these nations, life expectancy is 25
years less than in developed countries. People are 40 percent less
literate. Women are 30 times more likely to die during pregancy.
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering of the largest industrial nations last year in
Cologne, Germany, leaders created the Heavily Indebted Poor
Countries Trust Fund. The fund aims to collect $28 billion that
will allow those countries to write off about $90 billion in debt,
the difference mostly made up of interest payments. The US share is
$960 million in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   The fund was designed so that all creditor countries contribute.
Several countries have put their share on hold until they see what
Congress does with the $210 million request.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funding is critical not only because of what it will
supply directly but also because of the important inducement it
will provide for other donor countries,'' Law wrote to House
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, an Illinois Republican.
</P>
<P>
   If the trust fund works, the countries still would be $37
billion in debt, but it would free millions of dollars for social
services and infrastructure. In Mozambique, weekly debt payment
would fall from $2 million to $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frees up about $800,000 a week for reconstruction of that
country,'' said James McDonald, a policy analyst at Bread for the
World, a nonprofit citizens' group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam's Offenheiser said debt relief becomes especially critical
in the aftermath of a natural disaster. ``We learned from Hurricane
Mitch in Nicaragua and Honduras that relief aid really helps
short-term needs, but debt relief has real long-term effects,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
