<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-07 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE LAME DUCK FLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation may be preoccupied with choosing the
next president, but the current president is busy running his own
sideshow, trying to burnish his legacy in the few months that
remain to him.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't doing too badly, either.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his impeachment by the House, Bill Clinton turns out to
be neither much of a liability for Vice President Al Gore nor
irrelevant on Capitol Hill. He may not get the public attention he
used to attract, but he is still brokering deals with the
Republican Congress, raising money for Democratic candidates,
sounding off on major issues, rallying the troops with partisan
speeches and traveling the globe like an elder statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain have had
a good time arousing Republican audiences by denouncing what they
say are the shabby ethics and dishonesty of the Clinton era. They
have been competing to be the anti-Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not as simple a task as it appeared only a short
time ago. Clinton's job-approval rating remains high, in the 80s in
some polls. The booming economy is keeping voters content with the
status quo. An electoral rebellion does not yet seem in the air,
although cleaning up Washington and tossing out the rascals has a
certain universal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may be old hat these days, but he is still here. And he
still has an overstuffed agenda and a cheerful countenance. To see
him chattering away on television, you'd never guess he was almost
bounced from office only a year ago. His foes ignore him at their
peril; for a has-been, he's still very much present tense.
</P>
<P>
   He was scheduled to make a major speech Wednesday putting forth
the case for expanded trade with China, an issue on which both
parties in Congress are divided. It will be one of the key votes of
the session, and if it passes Clinton will get some of the credit.
If it loses, he will blame the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he met at the White House with congressional leaders
who could, if they would, break the legislative logjam over gun
control. He tried to utilize the outrage over the Feb. 29 killing
in a Michigan school of Kayla Rolland by another 6-year-old by
pressing the lawmakers for a compromise. Although the issue remains
intractable, the president gets an A for persistence.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, Clinton keeps up his international diplomacy
by going to India, a vast, impoverished nation with which we have
often had tense relations. He will also visit Bangladesh and
Pakistan. We will soon see pictures of him posing at the Taj Mahal.
Hopefully, he will not imitate President Lyndon Johnson and yell
``Yahoo'' in the place.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton doesn't deserve credit for the recent House vote to let
more senior citizens earn as much as they can without losing Social
Security benefits, a move so popular it had heavy bipartisan
support. The Senate is expected to follow suit soon. Clinton has
said he will sign the bill, wrapping up the first legislative
achievement of the new century and giving him another forum in
which to act presidential before the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   It does not seem likely there will be many more such
achievements. Some congressional Democrats prefer stalemate, in
hopes it would signal to voters that Republicans are no good at
running the place and that it's time to return Congress to the
Democrats. Some Republicans feel the same way, for other reasons _
they don't like compromising and would rather send Clinton bills
they know he will veto to clarify their differences with him.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP leadership is inclined to feel that a record of some
accomplishment, no matter how marginal, sells best at the ballot
box even if they have to share some of the credit with Clinton. So
there is still hope.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is said to be worried about his legacy and hoping to
make up this year for the rotten year he had in 1999, when the
Senate refused to convict him of obstruction of justice and another
charge in connection with the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   He has the good sense to be solidly behind his vice president's
campaign for president. Gore in the White House could protect
Clinton against further criminal prosecutions by extending a
pardon. Gore in the White House would continue Clinton's favorite
programs and policies, unlike the Republicans who would dismantle
what they could.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a given that a president supports his own party's
nominee to be his successor. Ronald Reagan, who never did care much
for Vice President George Bush, stayed out of Bush's 1988
presidential campaign. Johnson undercut his veep's 1968 campaign,
afraid that Hubert Humphrey would not resolve the Vietnam war but
that Richard Nixon would. LBJ, of course, regretted that decision
when Nixon later ignored him and failed to end the war for several
more years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is musing sadly about life after the White House, and
what to do with it. Until that time comes, Clinton is being his
irrepressible self.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
