<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GLOBALSPEAK08-COX     03-07 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBALSPEAK08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Entrepreneur sees Internet as platform for connecting
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Frank Baia, chief executive officer of Atlanta-based
Globalspeak, is an experienced advertising man and business
publisher, but his newest business is cutting edge _ a multimedia
platform for staying in business touch and doing transactions
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Globalspeak, in existence a year, gained notice several weeks
ago with its Webcasts of the troubled Seattle conference of the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``While so much of the attention was on the demonstrations
around the meetings, we allowed people to focus on the real
business,'' said Baia.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we did not dodge the controversy _ in fact we deliberately
provided a forum also for the
</P>
<P>
   protesters, and for economists who wanted to answer them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the journalist side of him that suggested the controversy
and the proceedings were important, but that neither should cancel
out the other.
</P>
<P>
   Providing a platform is the main business of Globalspeak, says
Baia, anaffable man who believes that the communicating side of the
Internet is one of the keys to growing business-to-business
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at the company's Internet site, Globalspeak.com, shows
directories of business news, heavy on international events, as
well as an offering of Webcasts and similar programs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the proudest moments in Globalspeak's young life took
place last July when the company worked with the Commerce
Department, the Small Business Administration and Commerce's
International Trade division to link American businesses via the
Internet with Nigerians to explore trade opportunities. All this
was done via live Webcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allowed businesspeople to learn and also present
themselves, in a convenient way that will be more common in the
future,'' Baia said.
</P>
<P>
   Arranging these meetings by way of broadband technology will
allow businesspeople and trade specialists to learn and do business
in unique ways, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, evolving technology will allow executives to watch
a trade conference by way of online video, identify a likely
business contact and signal that person to get online for
interactive discussions and transactions, even as the conference
proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING THE SHOW
</P>
<P>
   It is an example, Baia said, of how the technology will soon
move the technology specialists aside and allow businesspeople to
run the show and capitalize on the opportunity the machines and
networks represent.
</P>
<P>
   Doing business the way Globalspeak likes it, he said, consists
of standing back and letting the participants hold forth _ much
like the way C-SPAN covers public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with the very important added ingredient, allowing for
interaction, so it's not just performers and viewers, but
interaction among participants that all belong to the event,'' Baia
said.
</P>
<P>
   Baia dates his earliest business experience to the 1970s when he
ran an advertising business in South Florida with a number of
partners, including Atlantan Dan Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   That gave him experience in formulating business concepts and in
learning the value of communicating, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Baia sold his business and semiretired to the
Rome, Ga., area and the life of a gentleman farmer of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to circumvent wealth and go straight to happiness,''
Baia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived a pleasant life there with my designer cows and
chickens, Rhode Island Reds,'' he said, all the while ignoring the
smirks of his farmer neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   On a more serious side, he was really drawn to the North Georgia
economy, including the old manufacturing base in his area and
related businesses in carpeting, poultry and the like.
</P>
<P>
   He launched a business magazine, the Coosa Valley Review, and
got drawn into trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time we began to appreciate the fact that businesses up
there needed opportunities to expand their markets overseas, and at
the same time, tap into import businesses abroad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The critical importance of the two-way nature of trade relations
led him and his partners eventually to explore the Internet as a
base for international contact.
</P>
<P>
   Farther out, in terms of his online business concept, there will
be free-flowing electronic procurement sites, auctions, in effect,
where supplies and goods can be obtained at optimum prices 24 hours
a day, Baia said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Globalspeak can have roles as communications
platforms, he says, offering live exchanges, or archived or
recorded programs.
</P>
<P>
   With the thought to expanding its reach, Globalspeak, which has
offices here and in Los Angeles, is talking to C-SPAN about access
to public affairs material that can be a part of the business
information mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before long we will have the full business experience
available online,'' Baia said, ``including virtual plant tours,
demonstrations of technology, machines and products of all sizes
and types.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, he said, can be compared to the interstate highway
system, complete with high-speed, nonstop roads and bridges, except
it's global.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now time to let businesses and the business imagination
take over from the highway builders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
