<HEADER>
A9667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RAIL-MERGERS-NYT &LR;      03-07 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BNSF-CN MERGER PLAN HITS SOME SLOW ORDERS  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bold plan to unite two national freight railroads
_ one in the United States and the other in Canada _ to form the
biggest network of tracks and trains in North American history ran
into stiff opposition on Tuesday from shippers, competing railroads
and members of Congress who told regulators that the merger would
cripple service and dampen competition.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual day of hearings before the Surface Transportation
Board, the federal agency that regulates railroads in the United
States, witnesses painted a gloomy picture of how the proposed
merger of the Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railway and the Canadian
National Railway Co. would force the remaining large railroads in
both countries into another round of consolidations.
</P>
<P>
   By the time such mergers ended, several witnesses predicted,
only two national freight railroads would be left to serve the
entire North American market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure my great-grandfather would have liked that, but we in
West Virginia do not,'' said Sen. Jay D. Rockefeller IV, a Democrat
from West Virginia and a critic of the railroads who testified at
Tuesday's hearing. Rockefeller complained that few of the service
improvements or cost efficiencies promised in mergers that occurred
over the last five years had been realized, and he does not expect
much to come of the current proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., did not oppose the merger on its
own merits. ``On paper, the proposed merger looks great,'' he told
the board. ``But I ask you to withhold approval of the merger until
comprehensive plans to deal with the kinds of short-term problems
and the long-term problem of real competition are put forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern and Canadian National announced in December
that they would seek regulatory approval to combine their two
systems into a single 50,000-mile network reaching into most states
and provinces. The executives of the railroads said the combined
system would allow them to improve service because they could ship
bulk goods like coal and manufactured goods like automobiles across
country, and across borders, without having to switch lines.
</P>
<P>
   But many shippers, annoyed by long delays and costly mix-ups
that continue to plague railroads in the United States, have not
embraced the merger proposal, and neither have the competing
railroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers think we're nuts to start a new round of mergers
today,'' said Richard K. Davidson, chief executive of the Union
Pacific Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson and the executives of the four other so-called Class I
North American railroads urged regulators to impose a moratorium on
mergers for up to five years to give the industry and shippers a
chance to digest the last round of consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodney Slater, the secretary of transportation, said he did
not believe a moratorium was ``the right response.'' Instead, he
urged tightening performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings, which are to continue through Friday, focus on the
proposed merger, but they were intended to serve as a review of the
future of the railroad industry. Although the Burlington
Northern-Canadian National proposal was made public last year, a
formal application cannot be filed until at least March 20.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Surface Transportation Board, Linda J.
Morgan, said in an interview that she intended to listen to all the
testimony and then decide whether the board should take any action
before the merger application is filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a message,'' she said, ``about how the board is
going to handle this application and how it is going to handle
further consolidations.'' Morgan had previously refused to rule out
a moratorium. On Tuesday, though she was careful not to tip her
hand, many of her questions touched on the effect that a delay
would have on railroad stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Railroad stocks have been hit hard lately. By one count, the
major rail lines have dropped a total of 25 percent since
mid-December, an equity loss calculated at about $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The executives of the merging railroads argue that it is unfair
for them to be judged on the failures of their competitors to pull
off their own mergers. Paul M. Tellier, president of Canadian
National, told the board that this merger would not inevitably lead
to others unless those mergers also made economic sense.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a moratorium, Tellier invited the board to impose
additional service standards to ensure that the merger does not
cause disruptions. The two railroads have already guaranteed
shippers in writing that they will bear financial responsibility
for any losses that occur because of the merger.
</P>
</TEXT>
