<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-MEDIA-975(2TA     03-07 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MEDIA-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN INQUIRY ON RACISM IN MEDIA STIRS DEBATE ON PRESS
FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The subpoena landed on the editor's
desk on a Friday afternoon in February. It ordered him to appear
before the country's Human Rights Commission, which was
investigating racism in the media. It said he must account for his
newspaper's reporting or face up to six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the commission issued 36 such subpoenas to editors _
white and black _ of newspapers, radio and television stations. And
in a country where freedom of the press was only recently enshrined
in the constitution, where newspapers were frequently closed and
journalists arrested under the apartheid regime, the subpoenas
inevitably sent shivers through the newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `My God,' '' said the editor, Phillip van Niekerk,
who is white and who runs The Mail &AMP; Guardian, a weekly newspaper
in Johannesburg. ``I really didn't expect them to go that far. The
jackboot approach is something we thought we'd got away from.''
</P>
<P>
   In the outcry that ensued, the subpoenas were withdrawn and the
editors agreed to appear voluntarily before the commission. van
Niekerk and other white editors say they're willing to discuss the
issue; they just don't want to be forced to discuss the issue.
Nonetheless, the hearings on racism in the media, which started
this week, have stirred a roiling debate over whether the
commission and the government of President Thabo Mbeki are seeking
to stifle criticism and dissent in the press.
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that Mbeki and his ruling party, the African
National Congress, remain deeply suspicious of the white-dominated
news media. ANC and government officials, who helped write the
country's liberal constitution, say white journalists seem intent
on discrediting the black government and typically disregard issues
important to the black majority.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nation's politically influential newspapers,
including van Niekerk's Mail &AMP; Guardian, are run by white editors.
There are also several popular newspapers directed at black
readers, of which the largest is the daily tabloid Sowetan.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, the ANC and commission members deny that they want to
muzzle the media, but they rarely sugarcoat their critical views.
The ANC, for instance, applauded the commission for issuing the
subpoenas. Last month, in its annual report, the ruling party
described the media as a ``hostile press'' that is ``still
primarily owned and controlled by antagonistic forces with minority
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But those opinions are increasingly shared by black editors. At
Tuesday's hearing, five black editors broke ranks with their white
colleagues to support the commission's investigation, which has
been largely derided by whites. The black editors testified that
the media still portrays blacks as corrupt and incompetent, focuses
almost exclusively on the white minority and drowns out the stories
and concerns of ordinary black people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our contention that in a country like South Africa, it
simply cannot be right that, because of its dominance in the media,
a minority should continue to set the public agenda,'' said Mike
Siluma, editor of Sowetan, the nation's largest daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe very strongly that, in the interest of the country,
a way will have to be found to ensure that this group's dominance
of public debates is reduced and the black majority, especially the
African component in it, has a voice commensurate with its
numbers.'' The black editors said the issue was so important that
they would have willingly testified under subpoena, which stunned
their white counterparts, who had unanimously attacked the
subpoenas as an infringement of press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about a rainbow nation, but we're still living in
different places,'' said van Niekerk. ``We still occupy different
head space.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the editors, both black and white, battled racism and
apartheid in South Africa and suffered for it. In 1988, van
Niekerk, who worked at for what was then The Weekly Mail, saw his
newspaper shuttered for several months because the government
decided the newspaper had portrayed ANC guerrillas favorably.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Peter Sullivan, who is white and is now the editor
of The Star, who then worked for the liberal Rand Daily Mail and
was forced to justify his reporting before a government commission
in the 1970s. And Aggrey Klaaste, the editor-in-chief of Sowetan,
who is black, was jailed for six months in 1977 after the
government closed what was then Sunday World.
</P>
<P>
   All three men run influential newspapers. All agree that the
commission's interim report on racism in the media, which was the
foundation of the investigation, was seriously flawed. The report,
for instance, criticized a photograph of two black birds sitting
near an overflowing garbage can, saying the birds depicted
Johannesburg's black downtown and the garbage can its decay.
</P>
<P>
   All agree that the subtle racism and stereotyping described in
the report continues to surface in newspapers and television and
radio broadcasts. ``We mirror a very racist society,'' Sullivan
said. ``If there was no racism in the media, it would be absolutely
astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the similarities end. The white editors say
they are already working hard to hire blacks and improve coverage,
and that the commission's investigation was, for the most part,
unnecessary. The black editors disagree.
</P>
<P>
   After this week's hearing, the commission will present its
recommendations to Parliament. ``People must not pretend that
things are normal when they are not,'' Klaaste said. ``The country
is run by white people, economy-wise. These newspapers are run by
white people. We know that. There's no point in trying to be coy
about this kind of thing. They say there is racism in the media,
but they say that and do nothing about it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The commission began looking at the issue two years ago when the
Black Lawyers Association and the Association of Black Accountants
called for bias inquiries into two papers, including van Niekerk's
Mail &AMP; Guardian. The groups pointed out that The Mail &AMP; Guardian
had written 14 times about allegedly corrupt blacks but only 4
times about whites.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists counter that that should not be surprising since the
most government officials these days are black.
</P>
<P>
   They also note that the major newspapers have also given Mbeki
some favorable coverage. Mbeki and Trevor Manuel, the finance
minister, both received rave reviews last month for their state of
the nation and budget speeches. The Mail &AMP; Guardian, in its
evaluation of the new government, gave Mbeki an A- for his first
few months in office.
</P>
<P>
   According to the commission's statistics, progress has been made
in the hiring and promotion of blacks, but whites still
overwhelmingly dominate the top tiers of management. Last year, the
commission said, about 76 percent of the country's top media
managers were white as compared to 88 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But whites are not the only ones to voice concerns about Mbeki's
commitment to freewheeling discussion and critique. Earlier this
year, two black professors complained about what they described as
the dampening of dissent within the ruling party in a column in the
recently revived Sunday World newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, Trevor Ngwane, an ANC councilman in Johannesburg,
was suspended from his party positions for publicly criticizing the
ANC-led council's planned privatization of government services.
</P>
<P>
   Parks Mankahlana, a spokesman for President Mbeki, says the
Human Rights Commission, an independent body that reports to
Parliament, is no mouthpiece for Mbeki. Last year, he notes, the
commission sharply criticized the government for seeming to scale
back the rights of accused criminals and initiated an investigation
into the government's policy against the distribution of the
anti-AIDS drug AZT.
</P>
<P>
   Mankahlana emphasizes that it was the black government, not the
white government, that gave this country its first constitutionally
protected rights to free speech.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
