u i BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-NYT     03-07 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, CITING CONCERNS OVER KASHMIR AND TERRORISM, TO VISIT
PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take to follow; See also PAKISTAN-U.S.) 
 (nk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Arguing that important national security interests
would be jeopardized if he stayed away, the White House announced
Tuesday that President Clinton would visit Pakistan ``for a few
hours'' at the end of his lengthier trip to India later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which came after weeks of fierce in-fighting
within the Clinton administration, was based on the need to urge
the Pakistani military government to work toward resolving the
heightened conflict with India over Kashmir and to clamp down on
terrorism, senior officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been described by his aides as confident that he
could personally engage the new Pakistani military leader, Gen.
Pervez Musharraf, and decided that he should go.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani government had made virtually no progress on any
of the three major requests that administration officials laid out
for Musharraf during a visit in January _ to shut down a particular
terrorist group, to agree to a timetable for the restoration of
democracy and to improve its record on nonproliferation, the
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But they asserted that it was most important to ``keep the
channels of communication open'' so that Clinton could develop the
kind of relationship with Musharraf that enabled the president to
persuade the deposed prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, to back down in
Kashmir last year.
</P>
<P>
   A White House statement tried to dismiss the notion that
Clinton's presence in Pakistan would confer legitimacy on the
military government, which came to power in October, an argument
that was made by anti-terrorist experts at the State Department and
elsewhere in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president will go to Pakistan because the Pakistani nation
is a friend, not because he approves of, or acquiesces in, the
government of Gen. Pervez Musharraf,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It also added that Clinton was not going to mediate the Kashmir
dispute, an idea that India vehemently opposes.
</P>
<P>
   In order to differentiate between Musharraf, to whom Clinton
will try to deliver a stern message, and the people of Pakistan,
the administration is exploring the possibility of the president
addressing the nation in a television address, a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1902EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9673 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-VIVICA-GENAUX-OPERA-$     03-07 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIVICA-GENAUX-OPERA-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNUSUAL PATH TO OPERA, WITH ROSSINI AS GUIDE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CORI ELLISON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not many rising opera stars would choose to make
their New York recital debuts singing chamber music, and
little-known Baroque chamber music at that. Yet that is what Vivica
Genaux, an American mezzo-soprano, plans to do Monday evening at
Weill Recital Hall.
</P>
<P>
   With Chatham Baroque, a period-instrument group, she will delve
into cantatas and arias by Bononcini, Handel, Scarlatti, Vivaldi
and the obscure 18th-century Spanish composers Pablo Esteve and
Antonio Literes.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, little about Genaux's career has been conventional.
Now 30, the mezzo has hurtled from her 1994 professional debut at
the Florentine Opera in Milwaukee to a dramatic debut at the
Metropolitan Opera in 1997 and regular appearances in international
musical centers. And although she has performed around the globe,
her career trajectory has been uncommonly focused; the brunt of her
activity has been nearly 100 performances of the same three lead
roles, in Rossini's ``Cenerentola,'' ``Italiana in Algeri'' and
``Barbiere di Siviglia.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few seasons, Genaux has begun judiciously expanding
her repertory to 17 roles, most of them bel canto. She has made a
vivid impression at the Caramoor International Music Festival in
Katonah, N.Y., bringing her winning combination of daredevil
vocalism, keen musicianship and personal magnetism to cherishable
concert performances of Rossini's ``Cenerentola,'' ``Donna del
Lago'' and ``Gazza Ladra'' and Donizetti's ``Lucrezia Borgia,'' all
conducted by Will Crutchfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great asset for Vivica is that the timbre of her voice is so
individual,'' Crutchfield said. ``That's a real plus, because a
distinctive voice lasts in the memory of listeners as part of their
experience of the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Genaux's concentration on bel canto has been so consuming that
her more recent forays into the Baroque and French repertories seem
colossal leaps. Having tested the waters with Handel's
``Ariodante'' in 1998, she added Hasse's ``Solimano'' last year and
is tackling Vivaldi's ``Giustino'' and Handel's ``Arminio'' this
year. In 2001, she is to record Baroque arias with Rene Jacobs and
Concerto Koln, and to take on her first Monteverdi opera, ``Il
Ritorno d'Ulisse in Patria.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say, `When are you going to sing something other
than Rossini?''' the sylphlike Genaux said recently, polishing off
an implausibly hearty stack of French toast in a Georgetown hotel
the morning after a Kennedy Center performance of Handel's ``Giulio
Cesare.'' ``I said, `Rossini is not just ``Barber.''' My recitals
and recordings of his songs and arias are a real statement. Rossini
is very diverse.'' She is scheduled to appear in four more
productions of ``Barbieri'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her Mediterranean looks and her Swedish given name,
Genaux was born in Fairbanks, Alaska, in 1969. Her father, of
Belgian descent, was a biochemistry professor at the University of
Alaska and her mother, of Swiss-German extraction, was a language
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Genaux studied violin, piano and dance, but it was
her stint as Eliza Doolittle at 13 in a summer camp production of
``My Fair Lady'' that sealed her fate.
</P>
<P>
   She started on a practical path, studying genetics at the
University of Rochester. But by her sophomore year, she had
transferred to Indiana University and enrolled in the studio of the
soprano Virginia Zeani and her husband, the bass Nicola
Rossi-Lemeni.
</P>
<P>
   ``I graduated as a soprano in 1991,'' Genaux said. ``But when I
was preparing to start auditioning, I couldn't find five soprano
arias that would work for me. Plus I didn't identify with soprano
characters. They were too woe-is-me.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one of my lessons with Miss Zeani, I was singing `Come
scoglio,' and really laying into those low triplet runs. She said,
`My dear, if you want to sing this way, you must be a
mezzo-soprano.'''
</P>
<P>
   Worried that she would starve awaiting the odd ``Carmen'' or
``Barbiere,'' Genaux scoured the card catalog of Indiana
University's record library for mezzo roles. ``Then I realized the
writing had been on the wall,'' she said. ``When I played violin, I
always wanted to play second violin, and I always loved viola. When
I sang in choir, I always wanted to sing alto because I loved the
inner harmonies. And mezzo characters are so much fun, so clever
and strong.''
</P>
<P>
   She auditioned for the Ezio Pinza Council for American Singers
of Opera, which sponsors an annual summer school in Oderzo, a small
town outside Venice. There, she met Claudia Pinza, the great
basso's daughter and the organization's director. Pinza swiftly
became a vital mentor, and in 1992, after the first of Genaux's
four summers in Oderzo, she moved to Pittsburgh to continue
studying with Pinza.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, on MOnday, Dec. 15, 1997, Genaux's manager phoned,
saying that the Met had inquired about her availability to sing
Rosina in ``Barbiere'' that Wednesday evening and in the Saturday
broadcast. Genaux worked with Pinza for an hour, and at 5 p.m. they
called to accept the offer. Genaux arrived in New York at midnight,
and reported to the Met on Tuesday morning for a rehearsal with a
smattering of cast members and covers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening, after meeting her colleagues Simone
Alaimo, Dwayne Croft and Bruce Ford for the first time, she stepped
on stage to face a sold-out house primed for the Met debut of the
heralded Bulgarian mezzo Vesselina Kasarova. One of those classic
performers' nightmares?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really fun,'' Genaux said. ``We had a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I was in Alaska, I went to the place where we
used to go blueberry picking. You're on this hill and there are
mountains here and there, then a rock outcropping so far down you
think you'll never get there. But you just keep walking, looking at
the flowers and picking blueberries, enjoying every step you're
taking. So that's my philosophy in life, too. Enjoy the steps for
themselves, for what they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
