<HEADER>
A9679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SENATE-BORDER-HNS &LR;      03-07 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-BORDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS QUIZ INS HEAD ABOUT HIRING MORE BORDER PATROL AGENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators criticized the head of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service on Tuesday for her agency's failure to hire
as many Border Patrol agents as mandated by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What gives?'' asked Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C. ``Why can't
we get some people employed?''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism came during a hearing before a Senate
Appropriations subcommittee considering INS's 2001 budget request.
The $4.8 billion proposal, an 11 percent increase from this year's
budget, includes funding for 430 new agents next year instead of
the 1,000 required each year under a 1996 law intended to beef up
the Border Patrol by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Republican who helped push
the law through Congress, called the shortfall ``appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   She reminded INS Commissioner Doris Meissner that half of the
drugs and illegal immigrants coming into the United States from
Mexico passes through Texas, and two of Mexico's four largest drug
cartels, the Gulf and the Juarez cartels, operate along the Texas
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we can't let up. Four hundred and thirty new agents is not
enough. It is not sufficient,'' she said. ``I don't want to
micromanage your agency ... but we are frustrated because we have
been very clear in the mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee's chairman, Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., warned
that he might seek cuts in the Border Patrol's administrative
budget if the agency doesn't hire more agents and purchase new
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee is going to take that very seriously,'' he
said. ``We do have the final say in this exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said hiring remains a high priority for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did fall behind last year,'' she said, ``and we need to
make it up.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the booming economy has made recruiting Border Patrol
agents difficult because of competition from other law enforcement
agencies. However, she assured committee members that if her agency
cannot recruit enough agents by a June 1 deadline, it will make
good on a promise to put the money currently earmarked for new
personnel into efforts to retain veteran agents.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said the INS has almost doubled in size since
1993, and nearly one-third of the new personnel planned for next
year will be Border Patrol agents. Next year's budget request also
sets aside $40.9 million for promotions and pay increases for
existing agents, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison and other committee members acknowledged that Meissner
has requested funding for more agents, only to be thwarted by the
Clinton administration, which they said has ignored congressional
efforts to make controlling the country's borders a priority. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Texas senator also praised Meissner for taking the
subcommittee's suggestion to increase testing and recruiting of new
agents along the border. But she said the agency should also
consider giving hiring bonuses to bilingual agents, rather than
sending non Spanish-speaking recruits to a Spanish school in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we can continue to work together,'' Hutchison told
Meissner, ``because we're not succeeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in opening remarks to the committee, Meissner cited
several Border Patrol accomplishments, including Texas' Operation
Rio Grande and Arizona's Operation Safeguard.
</P>
<P>
   During the first two years of Operation Rio Grande, an effort to
crack down on drug trafficking and illegal immigration in South
Texas, apprehensions in the border city of Brownsville fell by more
than 160 percent, she said. The numbers continue to decline, she
said, falling another 45 percent so far this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she said, the agency has improved services for people
seeking to immigrate legally, cutting in half the average
processing time, from 28 months in 1998 to 12 months in 1999. This
year, she said, the agency is committed to reducing the waiting
time to an average of six months.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also has made progress in detaining and deporting
immigrants who commit serious crimes, Meissner said. Since 1994,
the number of criminals in INS detention has quadrupled to more
than 12,000, while the number of criminal immigrants removed from
the country reached 63,000 last year, more than double the number
deported in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
