u f BC-STOCKS-TUMBLE-BOS &LR;      03-07 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-TUMBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW SUFFERS FOURTH-LARGEST SINGLE-DAY DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A vulnerable Dow Jones industrial average lost nearly 4 percent
of its value Tuesday after a warning of lower profits by Procter &AMP;
Gamble Co. fed into investors' fears that rising oil prices and
interest rates would slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The 374.47-point decline was the Dow's fourth-biggest drop in
one day and pushed the index to its lowest closing since March 31,
1999. The Dow finished the day at 9796.03.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly invulnerable Nasdaq Composite index, which had
soared more than 100 points to just over 5000 in the morning,
eventually gave in to the Dow's downward pull. The Nasdaq began to
fall after nervous investors in technology stocks cashed in some of
their enormous profits. The index fell 57.01 points, closing at
4847.84.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's decline came as investors were reminded of twin
threats to the nation's economic expansion. The down day coincided
with a surge in US crude oil prices, to more than $34 a barrel, and
came a day after Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan restated
his intention of cooling the economy by continuing a policy of
boosting interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Nasdaq's muted reaction to the Dow's plunge
reflected a growing belief among investors _ still unproven _ that,
if the economy slows, the high-tech companies that dominate the
Nasdaq may be insulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in uncharted territory,'' admitted Bruce Addison, branch
manager of the Boston office of First Union Securities. ``The
height of the market, the new psychology of Internet day traders,
online traders, people rolling money out of value funds and buying
growth stocks _ it's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's fall was a dramatic reaction to a surprise
announcement from Procter &AMP; Gamble that profits would be
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer products giant said profits in the March quarter
would fall 10 percent from last year, rather than rise more than 7
percent as the company had earlier forecast. Profits are expected
to rise in the fourth quarter. Procter &AMP; Gamble blamed rising
prices for raw materials, especially paper pulp and oil.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch then downgraded the entire consumer products
sector, depressing stocks such as Colgate-Palmolive and
Kimberly-Clark, triggering a fall in the Dow, an index of big,
blue-chip industrial and financial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Local consumer products stocks also suffered. Gillette Co., the
shaving giant, fell 2 7/16 on the New York Stock Exchange to 32
7/16. Staples Inc., the office supplies retailer, dropped 13/16 to
19 3/8 on the Nasdaq. Overall, the Bloomberg Massachusetts index of
local stocks closed down 7.68 points to 397.14, after hitting a
record Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Procter &AMP; Gamble announcement ``makes everybody think
potentially this could happen to anybody,'' said Manuel Weiss,
portfolio manager for the Putnam Investors fund, which has $14
billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why investors reacted Tuesday to oil prices, which
have been going up for months, Weiss suggested, ``maybe investors
had not quite put into their estimates the impact of $30 oil'' on
company profits. ``Suddenly, today everybody started thinking, `Oh
boy, maybe we have to be more cautious.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Only Exxon Mobil Corp., a beneficiary of higher oil prices, and
Microsoft Corp., which seems immune, kept the Dow from falling
farther. Exxon Mobil gained 8 1/16, to finish at 81; Microsoft rose
2 1/4, to 92 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index fell as investors took profits in a basket of
stocks that had risen by 5 percent in March alone. Despite
Tuesday's decline, the Nasdaq has gained 19 percent this year,
while the Dow is down nearly 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see nervousness with a drop this big,'' said Larry Rice,
chief investment officer at Josephthal Lyon &AMP; Ross, referring to
the Dow's drop. ``But I'm not considering a 60-point drop in Nasdaq
anything to be concerned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the Nasdaq's continued strength despite Tuesday's
swing, Kevin Park, chief equity officer of Massachusetts Financial
Services, said the technology industry is not a ``single industry''
whose stocks will, necessarily, rise or fall together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have so much of the market lumped under one banner
headline,'' Park said. But, ``there are multiple layers and
multiple industries within the sector. Parts are probably
overvalued and parts aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said some technology stocks, including Oracle, LSI
Logic, and Norwood's Analog Devices, are expected to report strong
first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamentals which have been driving this market are still
intact,'' said First Union's Addison, ``But expect more
fluctuations and more wild swings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
