<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY WITHDRAWS ITS CANDIDATE FOR IMF MANAGER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Capitulating to demands from the United
States, Germany on Tuesday withdrew its candidate for managing
director of the International Monetary Fund but proposed someone
who may not be much more popular.
</P>
<P>
   In an embarrassing diplomatic defeat, German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder agreed not to push for Caio Koch-Weser, his deputy
finance minister and a former World Bank official.
</P>
<P>
   Koch-Weser took himself out of the running on Monday, more than
a week after the President Clinton essentially vetoed his candidacy
on the grounds that Koch-Weser lacked the stature to run the
international institution.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to regain some stature himself, as well as make sure that
a German obtains the job, Schroeder is now proposing Horst Koehler,
head of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
</P>
<P>
   Though respected, Koehler is not a particularly well-known or
prestigious figure in international financial circles. It remains
unclear whether he has the support of other countries within the
European Union, and American officials remained aloof when his name
surfaced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over who will lead the International Monetary Fund,
which provides financing to countries in economic difficulties, has
become a prolonged squabble over political entitlements and
national pride.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the IMF director has been a European _ a
Frenchman for 32 of the last 37 years _ while the top post at the
World Bank has been reserved for an American.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a broader effort to project a bolder German profile
on the world stage and move beyond Germany's chronic postwar
shyness, Schroeder has been determined to have a German succeed
Michel Camdessus of France, who retired last month.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Schroeder and other German officials had insisted
that they would not back down from their support for Koch-Weser.
</P>
<P>
   But French leaders were hostile toward Koch-Weser from the start
and wrestled for months with German leaders before finally agreeing
to support him as a the consensus European candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll of IMF members taken last week, Koch-Weser received
support from only 43 percent of IMF members, though he came in
ahead of the other two candidates: Stanley Fischer of the United
States and Eisuke Sakakibara of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, Koehler oversees an institution that provides loans to
the formerly communist nations of central Europe. It is in some
ways a small version of the World Bank, devoted largely to lending
money for public projects.
</P>
<P>
   But that could be a problem: one of the American objections to
Koch-Weser was his background with the World Bank and a suspicion
that he would support development projects rather than
straightforward economic assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1921EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9690 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SENATE-JUDGES-HNS &LR;      03-07 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-JUDGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA JUDGES TO GET THEIR VOTE IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM and JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Conservative Republicans failed in a last-ditch
attempt Tuesday to block a vote on federal judge Richard Paez, who
has waited a record four years for the Senate to decide on his
nomination to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Paez picked up support from a key Republican,
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the powerful Senate Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before debate on Paez's nomination began, Sen. Jeffrey
Sessions, R-Ala., urged Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott to delay
the vote to allow an investigation into Paez's sentencing of former
Democratic fundraiser John Huang.
</P>
<P>
   Huang pleaded guilty last May to raising $7,500 illegally from
U.S. employees of the Lippo Group, an Indonesian company owned by
Mochtar Riady, a friend of President Clinton. Federal law forbids
foreigners to donate money to U.S. political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Paez, a U.S. District Court judge in Los Angeles, sentenced
Huang to one year of probation and allowed him to avoid answering
questions on the origins of more than $1 million in suspect
contributions he brought to the Democratic National Committee. The
DNC later returned the money to Huang.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Sessions' complaint about Huang's light sentence,
Lott refused to call off the Paez vote, saying that unless
``specific evidence'' showed Paez did something illegal, the judge
would get his chance before the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Paez faces a close vote. Although he has won the support of all
45 Democratic senators, most of the 55 Republicans oppose him, and
he needs a majority to win. But in addition to Hatch, five other
GOP senators are said to be leaning toward his confirmation. They
are Robert Bennett of Utah, John Chafee of Rhode Island; James
Jeffords of Vermont; Gordon Smith of Oregon and Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could come down to one or two votes,'' said David
Sandretti, spokesman for Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., who fought
to bring Paez's nomination and that of his fellow Californian,
Marsha Berzon, to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Berzon, a San Francisco lawyer specializing in federal appeals
cases, is also up for a seat on the 9th circuit appeals court,
which covers California and eight other Western states. The vote on
both nominees is scheduled for Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative Republican senators have also objected to
Berzon, a member of the board of the American Civil Liberties
Union, saying she is too liberal. But she is said to have more
support among GOP senators than Paez.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, however, said just before the Senate debate on the pair
that he thinks both ``are bad nominees.'' Lott added, ``The 9th
Circuit is badly out of touch with mainstream America (and) has
been overruled many times because of extremely liberal decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the Senate floor, Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., said
appointing Paez and Berzon to that court would make a ``terrible
situation worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also contended that Paez is a judicial activist,
refusing to fully enforce laws that he disagrees with. ``When you
get a judge who tries to change the law because he doesn't like it,
that's when you have a rogue elephant who wreaks havoc on
society,'' Sessions said during the debate.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch said in a statement that ``Judge Paez has earned a
good deal of bipartisan support within his home state of California
and his native state of Utah and has given me his word that he will
abide by the rule of law and not engage in judicial activism.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator said Berzon is one of the most qualified nominees he
has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer agreed, saying, ``These are two exceptionally qualified
nominees who have had to wait far too long.'' Berzon was nominated
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Paez, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.,
said before the debate, ``It's a travesty of justice that someone
has been asked to put their life on hold for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
