u f BC-DELTA-ADS08-COX     03-07 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ADS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Delta ads highlight simple pleasures
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A passenger wanders into an airport ice cream shop and
idly enjoys a cone. He has the time for such pleasures because he
used an e-ticket and avoided airport lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check in at the curb and go straight to the plane,'' the ad
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or not.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the television spots in Delta Air Lines' new ad
campaign, which debuts this weekend. It's the first by the
Atlanta-based airline's new agency, Leo Burnett Co., which created
United Airlines' old ``Fly the Friendly Skies'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta ads eschew a single slogan or theme in favor of
airport vignettes and fill-in-the-blank bag tags that focus on
simple passenger needs.
</P>
<P>
   Many spots close with personalized bag tags in which passengers
have scribbled in their desires. The accompanying narration or copy
touts Delta's efforts to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly ... understood,'' reads the tag at the end of a TV spot
featuring a cluster of passengers around a baggage carousel, each
of whose priorities are described in a handwritten note
superimposed next to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly ... like an '80s bond trader,'' reads the tag in a print
ad for Delta's BusinessElite international service, with its cushy
seats and lavish legroom.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign debuts this weekend during the NCAA basketball
tournament on CBS, as well as in major magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to highlight the customer and the basic experiences
that affect them,'' said Martin White, vice president of consumer
marketing at Delta, whose ad account is valued at about $100
million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to see airplanes or seats or food,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a slogan, theme song or other easy-to-remember hook
is a departure for Delta, still known by many for its ``We Love to
Fly and It Shows'' campaign from a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's last campaign was 1997's ``On Top of the World'' spots,
with new age theme music and narration by actress Christine Lahti.
It was created by Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi, of New York. Delta switched to
Leo Burnett last year.
</P>
<P>
   White said Delta and the agency have been in a ``listening
mode'' for several months, conducting thousands of passenger
interviews. He hopes the ads will convey Delta's eagerness to
respond to passengers' basic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to brand-building, some spots tout specific
products, such as e-ticketing, the Delta Shuttle or BusinessElite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than just doing a soft brand campaign, we wanted some
to have a very strong tactical message about our products,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign kicks off a company-wide brand update that may even
entail changes to the paint scheme on Delta's planes, according to
a Leo Burnett briefing sheet. But a Delta spokesman said there are
no firm plans to alter the paint scheme. Delta is still at work on
a fleetwide re-painting launched in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
