<HEADER>
A9693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-GUNS-ART-NYT     03-07 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN CONTROL GENERATES TALK BUT LITTLE ACTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the week since another child was shot to death
in an American school, there has been plenty of maneuvering on gun
control in Washington, but little movement.
</P>
<P>
   That was never more clear than Tuesday when President Clinton,
after meeting with lawmakers in a highly publicized Oval Office
session that was billed by the White House as an effort to break a
months-long impasse on gun legislation, met as well with the mother
of the slain 6-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Clinton urged Congress to shatter the
legislative stalemate and pass far-reaching gun-control laws before
the first anniversary next month of the shootings at Columbine High
School in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past eight months, the leaders in Congress have done
virtually nothing to complete a final bill,'' Clinton said after
meeting with four key lawmakers, an event the White House labeled
an effort to broker a compromise. ``Congress has kept the American
people waiting long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, the president met with Veronica McQueen, the
mother of Kayla Renee Rolland, the 6-year-old girl who was fatally
shot last week in her first-grade classroom in Michigan by another
6-year-old who had brought a pistol to class.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they invited McQueen on Monday when
they heard she would be in town for a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, were steaming afterward, accusing Clinton
of wielding them as an election-year prop. ``We were there to be
used,'' fumed one senior House Republican aide.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control promises to be a politically hot issue in both the
presidential and congressional campaigns this year, and both
opponents and supporters are blaming each other for the delay in
resolving the legislative logjam.
</P>
<P>
   The White House cited new Justice Department statistics Tuesday
showing that the number of youths killed with a firearm increased
sharply from 1987 to 1993, while other types of homicides remained
constant.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate approved different gun control bills after
rancorous debates last year. But legislators in the two chambers
are deeply divided on the restrictions, especially on regulating
gun shows, and have yet to reconcile them in conference.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Clinton signaled a willingness to support a modified
version of a compromise proposed by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who
heads the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hyde's plan, vendors at gun shows would have up to 24
hours to conduct mandatory background checks of prospective gun
buyers. If the check turned up a potentially disqualifying arrest
or felony conviction, the vendors would have three days to perform
the checks. The National Rifle Association opposes this plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hyde proposal is a substantial movement away from just the
total, what you might call the complete NRA position,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who heads the Senate Judiciary
Committee, has refused to convene the conference committee of House
and Senate negotiators until gun-control supporters relent on their
demand for a three-day waiting period on all sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put everybody together so people can shout
political epithets at each other,'' Hatch told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Republicans of caving in to NRA demands to
keep the conference bottled up. ``We want to lay our cards on the
table; they do not,'' said Julian Epstein, the Democratic staff
director of the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hyde and Hatch, the two ranking Democrats on the
judiciary panels, Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan and Sen.
Patrick Leahy of Vermont, attended the White House meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said he would
back a less sweeping bill that included provisions that enjoy broad
bipartisan support, like child-safety trigger locks and a ban on
imported large-capacity ammunition clips. ``There are some gun
provisions that make good common sense,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   But White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton would oppose
legislation that failed to close what the president called ``the
gun show loophole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
