<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-SBC08-COX     03-07 1818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-SBC08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth a takeover target to some analysts
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The road to respectability may lead through the air.
</P>
<P>
   With increased pressure on BellSouth to do something, news of
talks between the company and SBC aimed at a combination of the
companies' wireless offerings have set the stage for what could be
a series of major announcements in a critical year.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure on BellSouth does not come from losses or even slowing
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is additional scale, on one hand, and new
technologies on the other that are being rewarded by analysts and
investors. In a kind of tectonic shift, mergers are moving the
world of telecommunications from an archipelago of regional
companies toward a handful of super players spanning the globe.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, say voices from industry and Wall Street, must expand
to compete. The buzz from the company's Campanile building
headquarters in midtown Atlanta is that BellSouth will respond with
announcements in a range of businesses, from entertainment to
international units.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless might be a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   Word that San Antonio-based SBC and BellSouth are talking leaked
out of a recent meeting between SBC and analysts. Together, their
wireless network would reach more than 175 million potential
customers in 31 states. They would be bigger than AT&AMP;T Wireless,
the second-largest network. For BellSouth, long the most
conservatively managed of the seven regional phone companies
created in the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T, the partnership could trigger
a flood of new capital, revamp its image and preserve its
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be the first step to being acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company will talk publicly about it, but industry
analysts find the notion appealing _ even compelling. Andrew Cole,
vice president at Renaissance Worldwide, is emphatic. ``SBC and
BellSouth have absolutely no choice. They should have done this a
year ago. They are at a significant disadvantage, and they must
also join with a significant ally which has a European wireless
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   One European power, Deutsche Telekom, has reportedly been
talking to Qwest Communications, a long-distance and high-speed
lines company in which BellSouth owns a stake. Qwest itself was
about to merge with local phone company U S West, and analysts
wonder whether Deutsche Telekom wants to buy both.
</P>
<P>
   They also assume that the German company will not stop there.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber analysts predicted Tuesday in a report that
``BellSouth would probably become the next major U.S. acquisition
for DT after Qwest/U S West. DT will want to buy BellSouth before
SBC Communications, Bell Atlantic, AT&AMP;T or MCI WorldCom can get to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other possible suitors. For instance, Spain's
Telefonica is aggressive, and _ like BellSouth _ has ambitious
Latin America investments.
</P>
<P>
   A wireless deal with SBC might accelerate things, wrote
PaineWebber. ``We believe that a DT acquisition of Qwest/U S West
and the announcement of a domestic wireless merger between
BellSouth and SBC Communications would cause investors to look at
(BellSouth) as a takeover target, not as a buyer of Qwest.''
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber projects BellSouth reaching $60 a share within a
year and recommends buying the stock.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGE IS IN THE AIR
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is already considering creation of tracking stocks,
nonvoting equities that would be sold separately from the company's
existing stock. The idea is that wireless and international are
valuable properties that would draw tremendous investment if they
were not weighed down by the currently sagging valuations given
local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has precedent _ along with financial allure.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint created a wireless ``tracker'' whose value was about $54
billion at the close of trading Tuesday. AT&AMP;T is about to launch a
wireless tracking stock that could become the biggest public
offering ever. Nextel, a purely wireless company, has a value of
$45 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If other wireless companies are any guide, the market awards
anywhere from $7,000 to $11,000 in value for each subscriber a
company has. By that measure, BellSouth's 5.3 million wireless
customers _ more than Sprint _ should easily be worth more than $40
billion. An SBC-BellSouth wireless combination, with 15.4 million
subscribers, could be worth a staggering $125 billion. Currently,
BellSouth as a whole has a market value of about $82 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest potential for the alliance is among Latinos
_ both within the United States and outside, said Perry Walter,
analyst at Atlanta's Robinson-Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has investments in nine Latin countries, including
Brazil, the region's largest economy. SBC has investments in the
second-biggest market: Mexico. In the United States, the most Latin
cities _ not counting New York _ are on SBC or BellSouth turf.
``SBC and BellSouth could combine their domestic and international
businesses,'' Walter said. ``Think of the power of that.''
</P>
<P>
   As a marriage partner, BellSouth comes with an enticing dowry.
Within its nine-state region, BellSouth is pre-eminent as a
wireless provider. The company believes it has about a 40 percent
share in many of its major markets, despite the crowd of
competition.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's advantage has been twofold.
</P>
<P>
   First, it held one of the first two wireless licenses in most
markets. Second, its wireless business gets an incalculable boost
from BellSouth's long-time dominance in local service through most
of the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   But that still isn't enough by itself.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least so say analysts who, with a steady drumbeat, pound
home the idea that regional players will be marginalized or
absorbed. Despite the current profitability of regional wireless
offerings, customers increasingly will demand far-reaching coverage
that can be provided only by global players, they say.
</P>
<P>
   National carriers will increasingly hurt BellSouth in several
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, they will steal some customers. Perhaps as bad,
national players are more likely to carry a call when their
customers roam into BellSouth turf, depriving it of even a piece of
the payoff. About three of every four wireless users are now on a
handful of national networks, said analyst Mark Lowenstein of the
Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   And while BellSouth may argue it can compete by forging
``roaming'' agreements across the nation, bigger players will need
BellSouth less for their own customers, he said. ``When you see a
BellSouth or SBC subscriber roaming onto other networks, the
national providers will be less willing to give them good roaming
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   An alliance holds out the hope of an attractive roaming deal, at
least on SBC turf.
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently agree. BellSouth stock has languished for a
year while companies that have launched a national wireless
strategy _ Nextel, Sprint _ have scored impressive valuations. News
that SBC and BellSouth might be cooking up a wireless alliance
quickly juiced BellSouth stock into a 25 percent increase.
BellSouth closed Tuesday at $43.68 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   With regional phone companies retaining near-monopolies, the
logic of globalism has not yet reached the bottom line. BellSouth
last year reported $25.2 billion in revenue and $3.4 billion in
profits. But the future seems to be rushing toward BellSouth _
ready or not.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996 sparked a thunderous series
of mergers and acquisitions, and the noise has yet to subside. A
few companies are emerging as behemoths in the game. In the United
States, it is AT&AMP;T, Bell Atlantic, SBC and MCI WorldCom, which has
an agreement to buy Sprint. Each is working toward a national
wireless ``footprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, there is Nextel, strictly a national wireless
player. And there are independents like VoiceStream and Powertel,
which deploy a technology known as GSM for nearly 5 million
customers. In that group there has been consolidation, too, and
analysts expect eventually at least a loose national alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless is also becoming more than just calling home from the
traffic jam to check on the kids.
</P>
<P>
   New generations of phones can send and receive data, and link to
the Internet. Moreover, plenty of other devices _ from Palm Pilots
to refrigerators _ will soon be equipped with wireless links.
Information, more than conversation, could be the most common and
lucrative use of wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Any arrangement between BellSouth and SBC ought to take that
into account, said Joe Laszlo, analyst for Jupiter Communications.
``It would make a lot of sense to include not just roaming for
voice, but roaming for data services as well. First, you are going
to see this targeted at business travelers. Even the consumer
market, I think, can see data services as a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it's not just about talk.
</P>
<P>
   The device in the consumer's and professional's hand will be a
portal to a host of uses, the way desktop computers are now, Cole
said. ``All the electronic-commerce and mobile data will be done
that way. The world is moving away from wireline toward wireless,
and you will see it in substantial numbers within 18 months or
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing new entrants that focus on data, telecom players must
have a wireless gateway, he said. ``The war of the portals is
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Both SBC and BellSouth have kept mum. And certainly any
tentative deal could collapse. After all, the companies several
years ago danced to the edge of a merger only to back away. Yet
even a wireless pact may be just a step toward something more
definitive, said Elliott Hamilton, vice president of the Strategis
Group. ``Ultimately, an alliance won't get either company what it
will need.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see the talks with SBC as prelude to radical
shifts, perhaps even a trisection of the company into wireless,
international and Southeast units.
</P>
<P>
   Any grand deal would have to pass muster with the Justice
Department and FCC _ and regulators might balk, said analyst Marc
Bacurin of J.C. Bradford &AMP; Co. SBC has already swallowed two former
Bells, as well as Southern New England Telephone. Regulators
accepted those mergers, as well other huge deals, but this one
might set off alarms by paring the number of regional Bells to
three. Combined, SBC and BellSouth have lines into customer homes _
and market dominance _ in nearly half the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are almost reconstructing AT&AMP;T,'' Bacurin said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Chairman and Chief Executive F. Duane Ackerman has
been assuring employees that he still believes BellSouth stock is a
great bargain. He is scheduled to speak Friday to the company's
96,000 workers via video hookups, although company officials say he
has no special news to announce.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman is slated to talk about BellSouth's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
