<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9697 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-07 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA'S SIMPLE REQUEST: PLAY HARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; TEMPE, Ariz.  &UR; _ &LR;  He will not hug his players, as one of his old
managers used to do. He will not pick an argument with an umpire
just because the game is on national television. He will not
appoint himself third-base coach during an Angels slump in the
belief that more of Mike Scioscia will make everything better.
</P>
<P>
   He sure hopes the TV camera will never catch him cussing in the
dugout, but he's an emotional guy, and if it happens, it happens,
you know?
</P>
<P>
   He will not spit tobacco juice. Chewing tobacco is one baseball
tradition he has never revered. The occasional bubble gum will be
his only vice on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   He will neither allow the computerized matchup statistics to
dictate his strategy nor scorn the benefits of technology for macho
effect. He'll look at the printouts when appropriate in the late
innings, but they won't stop him from calling for Troy Percival in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   He will not rant and rave in clubhouse meetings  &UR; _ &LR;  though,
again, he's an emotional guy, so we'll see.
</P>
<P>
   He will figure out if he's a bunting, base-stealing, hit-and-run
type of manager or a wait-for-the-three-run-homer type of manager
only after the roster is set and he assesses his weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Scioscia, 41, the old Dodgers All-Star and playoff hero,
begins his rookie season as a major-league manager determined to be
himself, not to worry about matters of image or style or
personality any more than he did as a somewhat bottom-heavy
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be the same manager as I am a person. I think
I'll be an easy read,'' Scioscia said in his spring-training office
at Tempe Diablo Stadium as his green digital-watch dial registered
9:00 Tuesday morning. ``I'm myself. I'm not going to change. I
don't have another side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a real simple philosophy about this game, about having
guys show up on time, about practicing hard, about preparing
yourself to play the game and about playing the game hard. That was
my makeup as a player and in that essence I'm just being myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, you learn from experience, but hopefully the
experience isn't going to change who you are. If it does change who
you are, you might not be as true to your philosophy as you thought
you were.
</P>
<P>
   ``!ital!That,'' he said sharply, summing up, ``is my style.''
</P>
<P>
   He is simple but not simplistic, a product of The Dodgers Way as
taught to him by Roy Campanella and Johnny Roseboro and Del
Crandall. His conversation is 90 percent baseball and 10 percent
food.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia's experience with major-league managers consists of 13
years playing for and observing Tom Lasorda. His own experience is
a year in the Arizona Fall League and a year at Class-AAA
Albuquerque before seeing no future with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   He is not Lasorda, that's for sure. But he learned from Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom was big on creating an atmosphere where you wanted to come
to the ballpark and work as opposed to him having to order you to
work,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   His own psychological ploys are elementary. Such as the way he
has found to inject some fun into the team meetings that are a
necessary evil in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's called on guys to get up and talk about themselves, their
families, their hobbies,'' said Tom Candiotti, the knuckleball
pitcher who has worn the same uniform as Scioscia the Dodgers
player, Scioscia the Dodgers bench coach and now Scioscia the
Angels manager. ``One kid loves to cook; Mike had him make 30
enchiladas for the coaching staff. He had another kid paint new
name signs for the parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now (teammates) know more about each other than what's in the
media guide. We can say, `Hey, those enchiladas were lousy, go back
and try again.' It brings the club together.''
</P>
<P>
   For a team that finished 70-92 under Terry Collins and Joe
Maddon in 1999 amid much clubhouse turmoil, the lighter mood is a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that also has a new general manager and a For Sale
sign in the windshield, a steady personality is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a plus that, for the first time since the end of Buck
Rodgers' reign in 1994, the Angels' manager had a significant
major-league career, giving Scioscia instant credibility with the
players. He doesn't have to put on airs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always been the same, a solid baseball guy (with) no
ego,'' said Kevin Kennedy, the former Texas Rangers and Boston Red
Sox manager who has known Scioscia since 1982, when Kennedy was a
Dodgers farm instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Staying that way will be the key to happiness for Scioscia, win
or lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can live with not being a manager right now because I stayed
true to myself,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose? Scioscia will have plenty of obstacles to think
about on the 70-mile commutes to Edison Field from his Thousand
Oaks home.
</P>
<P>
   A lineup with Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon and Jim Edmonds will be hard
to blow out of any game. But the Angels pitching staff might be up
to the task. The starting rotation has almost as many 1999
victories as Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Staying true to yourself and your philosophy might be easier
when it's the first week of the Cactus League than when it's
August, you're 10 games out and the car radio is wondering why the
Angels didn't hire Don Baylor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
