<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9702 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS &LR;      03-07 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES LAWMAKERS TO PASS TOUGHER GUN LAWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton urged lawmakers Tuesday to ``pass
the strongest possible'' gun-control legislation to help save the
lives of children, who he said are being killed by gun violence
around the country at the rate of 13 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton unveiled the federal statistic after meeting at the
White House with top-ranking Republicans and Democrats on the House
and Senate judiciary committees. He called on them to reach a
compromise on a gun-control bill that has been tied up on Capitol
Hill since last year and have it to him by April 20, the
anniversary of the Columbine High School shootings in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many more people have to get killed before we do
something?'' he asked later at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also met with the mother of a 6-year-old girl killed
last week in a Michigan classroom by a first-grader who brought a
handgun from home.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the tragic death of Kayla Rolland to highlight a
Justice Department study showing that the number of minors killed
in firearm-related incidents increased sharply between 1987 and
1997, while the rate of other types of gun deaths remained
constant. More recent figures are not available. But Clinton said
the federal data, taken in part from a 1999 Justice Department
report on juvenile victims and offenders, indicates that 13 minors,
below the age of 18, are killed with guns every day in the United
States, either in accidents or crime-related incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he wanted Kayla's mother, Veronica McQueen,
to know that ``as a parent, my heart goes out to her and as
president, I'm going to do all that I can do to see that this
doesn't happen to other children.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hoped his meeting with Sens. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, Patrick Leahy, D-Conn., and Reps. Henry Hyde. R-Ill, and
John Conyers, D-Mich., will help break the stalemate on Capitol
Hill over gun-control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   A bill requiring a three-day waiting period on firearms
purchases made at gun shows, mandatory trigger locks on handguns
and a ban on high-capacity ammunition clips passed the Senate last
year, but it was rejected in the House. Republican leaders opposed
to tougher gun laws have so far refused to allow a conference to go
forward between House and Senate members aimed at producing an
acceptable compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the death of Kayla Rolland, Clinton said it was becoming
increasingly ``urgent'' that lawmakers do what they can to help
keep guns out of the hands of children, as well as criminals. He
said Congress ought to at least pass a law requiring trigger locks
on all handguns and a three-day background check at gun shows,
which would be in keeping with the current Brady Law that requires
a similar waiting period for firearms bought at commercial gun
stores and pawn shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the gun lobby is cranking up pressure on Congress
again. But when first-graders shoot first-graders, it's time for
Congress to do what's right for America's families,'' Clinton told
reporters, complaining that lawmakers ``have done virtually nothing
to complete a final bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Washington are always talking about what we can't do
instead of what we can do. I'm not interested in talking about how
little we can do,'' Clinton said. ``I'm interested in how much we
can accomplish to keep guns out of the hands of criminals and
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the White House meeting, Hatch, who chairs the
Senate Judiciary Committee, did not hold out much hope for a
compromise bill. He said lawmakers are divided over the issue of
tougher gun-control laws, especially when it comes to requiring a
three-day waiting period for purchases made at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're polls apart on what can or cannot be done. But we're
certainly going to continue talking,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the senator said in his view neither ``the tragedy in
Michigan'' nor the Columbine incident could have been avoided with
new gun-control laws. In the case of Kayla Rolland, he noted that
the gun used to kill her ``would have never had a trigger lock on
it anyway'' because it was kept in a ``crack house'' and
``improperly allowed to sit out where some kid 6 years old could
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``None of what we're talking about is going to solve that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton disagreed, however. He said if guns can be kept out of
the wrong hands to begin with lives can be saved.
</P>
<P>
   Taking aim at gun shows, Clinton cited federal reports showing
that criminals are more likely to purchase weapons at gun shows,
where no background checks are required, than at commercial gun
stores where the waiting period covers three business days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
