<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-GRANITA-NYT &LR;      03-07 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANITA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICY, TART AND SUCH A NICE CRUNCH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all started with a Champagne sorbet I had at Lutece a few
weeks ago. Compared with the complicated, swooping, architectural
desserts so much in vogue in top restaurants, the sorbet was
elegant and understated. It reminded me of a dessert I like to
order in Paris: a granite des pommes, with Calvados. It, too, is
simple and memorable: three scoops of apple granita flavored
(``baptized,'' some French waiters say) with an ounce or two of
apple brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Was the Champagne sorbet actually a granita? I asked Lutece's
pastry chef, Eric Bedoucha. ``No,'' he said. ``It was sorbet.'' So
how, exactly, are they different?
</P>
<P>
   I asked some people I thought would know. A granita, one told
me, is ``some kind of iced coffee.'' Another said, ``You know, like
the lemon ice you get at the San Gennaro festival.'' In fact, it's
neither.
</P>
<P>
   Invented in Italy, granita is a coarse-textured ice dessert made
from fruit juice or espresso. The liquid is placed in a shallow pan
in a freezer and stirred every 30 minutes or so to prevent it from
becoming a solid block. The result is an ice with relatively large,
slow-melting crystals. (Sorbet, on the other hand, is usually
processed until the ice crystals are tiny and silken.) A granita's
flavor is fresh and long-lasting.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, the locals prefer their espresso-flavored granita
layered with unsweetened whipped cream, and their fruit granita
tart. Other ways to enjoy it: drop lemon granita into iced tea, or,
after dinner, drizzle some grappa on top.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the granite des pommes with Calvados is a specialty of
the brasseries run by the Flo Group, which includes the famous
Brasserie Flo. For sentimental reasons, I like to order it at the
Terminus Nord, the company's brasserie near the Gare du Nord where
I first had it 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor is intense and tart, and the color is pale green,
reminiscent of a ripe Granny Smith apple. The Calvados, or Calva as
everyone in Paris calls it, is good, solid apple brandy from
Normandy. It has an apple flavor and an ethereal apple bouquet that
blends beautifully with the crunchy apple ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Flo brasseries would not part with their recipe, but once
you understand what granita is, it's easy enough to replicate at
home. As for the Calvados, it is not hard to come by in this
country, but I am more than happy to use a good domestic apple
brandy like the one made by Laird &AMP; Co. Call it applejack, call it
Jersey lightning, it would be right at home in the Terminus Nord.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE GRANITA WITH CALVADOS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus 30 minutes' cooling, and 1 hour's
freezing and stirring
</P>
<P>
   4 large Granny Smith apples, cored, quartered and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 cups unsweetened clear apple juice
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   \ cup Calvados, or as desired
</P>
<P>
   1. Place a shallow metal pan in freezer. In a nonreactive
saucepan, combine apples, apple juice, sugar, lemon juice and salt.
Bring to a boil, then simmer uncovered until apples are very
tender, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Strain mixture, pressing as much apple pulp as possible
through strainer. Cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour apple mixture into chilled pan; return to freezer. Stir
every 20 minutes until it thickens into coarse crystals, about 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   4. Stir granita and mound into small cups. Splash with Calvados.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 4 cups (4 to 6 servings).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
