u a BC-MOTHER-MURDERED-BOS &LR;      03-07 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-MURDERED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES CLAIM DOCTOR ALLEGEDLY PUSHED DOWN STAIRS BY DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI AND JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHREWSBURY, Mass. _ A distinguished forensic psychiatrist who
counseled prison inmates died at a hospital Tuesday, two days after
her 16-year-old daughter, whom friends described as emotionally
unstable, allegedly pushed her down a flight of stairs and beat her
with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dr. Kathleen A. Thomsen-Hall, 44, was an assistant
professor of psychiatry at the University of Massachusetts Medical
School and an expert on criminal behavior, she was apparently
unable to protect herself from her own daughter's violent emotional
distress, according to her daughter's friends.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Valerie Hall, a junior at Shrewsbury High School, was
arraigned in juvenile court in Worcester on charges of assault with
intent to murder, use of a dangerous weapon, and drug possession.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester District Attorney John J. Conte said the case against
Hall would be presented to a grand jury next month, and the
teenager could be charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear where Hall is being held.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the teenager's friends noted the bizarre twist of fate
for Thomsen-Hall, who since August had worked as a clinician in the
women's prison at MCI-Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so ironic that Val's mom is a forensic psychiatrist,''
said Raymond DePalo, 18, a friend of Hall's. ``She worked with
murderers every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter had attempted suicide about a month ago by
overdosing on the medication she took to treat manic depression,
said DePalo and another friend of Hall's, 18-year-old Ryan Luby.
They said she had once before hit Thomsen-Hall, but that otherwise
mother and daughter appeared to have a loving relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw this coming,'' Luby said. ``They had their good
moments and bad, like all families, but more good than bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall's fights with her mother were typical adolescent dramas
that erupted over how late she could stay out or whether she could
have boys in her room, her friends said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Val loved her (mother), I know that,'' Luby said. ``That's why
this is the biggest shock in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Luby said he stopped by the family's house Sunday afternoon,
just hours before the alleged attack. Everything seemed fine, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   `The only thing that was different was that Val was a little
mellow,'' Luby said. ``She told me she was on a new prescription
that was supposed to keep her calm and mellow.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday about 8 p.m., police received a call from a distraught
female using a pay phone at a convenience store saying that a woman
had fallen down the stairs in a nearby home and needed an
ambulance. A spokeswoman for Conte said investigators later
determined that the caller was Valerie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Police who responded to the call at the small blue wood-frame
home in a residential neighborhood found the doctor bleeding with a
weak pulse and took her to UMass Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, police in the nearby town of West Boylston
stopped a truck belonging to Hall's boyfriend, Joseph A. Fulginiti,
20, of Shrewsbury. Hall and Fulginiti were arrested and charged
with illegal possession of marijuana and hallucinogenic mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Fulginiti is scheduled to make a court appearance on the drug
charges later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Hall had been dating Fulginiti for about two months, according
to her friends, who added that her mother disapproved because he is
older and unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's father died when she was an infant, DePalo and Luby said.
She and her mother moved to Massachusetts from Little Rock so
Thomsen-Hall could accept a one-year fellowship in forensic
psychiatry at UMass Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   DePalo said that when Hall moved to town he and his friends
``took her under our wing, since she was the new girl.'' Though she
occasionally became depressed about boyfriend problems, she was not
violent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Luby added that police came to the house once a few years
ago when Hall hit her mother, and that the girl had been in trouble
with authorities in the past for marijuana possession.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, Thomsen-Hall operated a private practice and
lobbied legislators to pass proposals on mental illness, said Paul
S. Appelbaum, chairman of the medical school's psychiatry
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kathleen was a good person, and in many ways she was
remarkable,'' Appelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Thomsen-Hall, who had moved to the Bay State from
Arkansas the year before, was one of two Massachusetts
psychiatrists to receive the Exemplary Psychiatrists Award from the
National Alliance for the Mentally Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unusually brave of her to make the decision to leave
private practice and become a student again,'' said Appelbaum,
referring to her fellowship. He said Thomsen-Hall had planned to
return to Little Rock after the fellowship, but decided to stay at
the medical school as a staff psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her death, she was working with Appelbaum on a
paper examining the treatment of substance abuse in the United
States in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exchanged e-mails on Sunday, so you can imagine how shocked
I was to hear what had happened on Monday morning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luby and DePalo said Thomsen-Hall was unusually relaxed and
friendly toward her daughter's friends. She listened to their
troubles and gave them odd jobs around the house so they could earn
spending money, Luby said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like a mom to me. She always tried to help,'' Luby
said. ``We could tell her anything, and her daughter could always
talk to her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
