<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-ADS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth to launch `repositioning' ad campaign
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth today is slated to announce a major
advertising campaign, a nine-month effort costing upwards of $50
million, to reshape the company's image among tech-savvy consumers.
</P>
<P>
   With ads that will run on television, as well as in newspapers,
magazines and on the Internet, BellSouth hopes to ``reposition''
itself for a world in which not only is there more competition, but
rivals from unexpected places, said F. Alan Blount, assistant vice
president for advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is mostly limited to the Southeast, where BellSouth
does nearly all of its domestic business. But with the industry
moving toward consolidation and seemingly all business connecting
to the Internet, BellSouth is competing with everyone from AT&AMP;T to
America Online, from MCI WorldCom to Yahoo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is the work of Merkley Newman Harty, a New York
City agency, whose clients include BMW Motorcycles, Forbes,
M&AMP;M/Mars and Pitney Bowes. Other parts of the campaign will be
produced by different companies but using similar themes and
presentation, Blount said.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are a series of vignettes, snapshots and come-ons based
on a fictional town called ``Chatsford.'' All have a single
tagline: ``Connect and create something.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth considers Chatsford _ and its lead character Tyler
Webb _ tremendously successful in building its image in the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chatsford was created in a very different environment,''
Blount said. ``This is really a repositioning campaign. What do you
want from your relationship with BellSouth? It's all about what do
you do when you connect.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, marked since its creation as a local phone company,
hopes to convince potential customers to think of it for all manner
of communications, from Web access and hosting to wireless service.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has typically been well-known and respected among
older consumers, who matured when there was but one phone company.
BellSouth feels it must shift its emphasis toward younger people
growing up as the Internet was sprouting and the marketplace was
becoming a loud and competitive free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign begins Thursday on NBC, continuing with ads that
run during the NCAA basketball playoffs. Each of the first four ads
are 30-second melodramas ending with a twist:
</P>
<P>
   _ ''Park Bench'' starts with a long shot of an apparently lonely
old man sitting on a bench.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Dinner Time'' catalogues one plugged-in family's many
devices and connections.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Store'' shows a nearly deserted urban outlet, its owner
sweeping an empty sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Skyscraper'' follows an apparently failed entrepreneur on
his way to the office.
</P>
<P>
   There will be ads in metropolitan newspapers, Rolling Stone,
Business Week and Martha Stewart Living. There also will be
billboards. All the ads will use the same kind of printing and the
same tag line. The company also means to revise many other things
that customers see _ packaging, in-store posters, sports marketing,
brochures and bills _ to convey the same feeling, Blount said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chatsford, the new campaign is understated despite its hope
of reaching younger customers. Blount said BellSouth believes the
relatively action-free ads are better than trying to copy the
frenetic ``dot-com'' campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The company steers away from the explosive, in-your-face
approach of many new and hungry Internet players, Blount said.
``When you are shooting gerbils out of a cannon, you are going for
shock value. It's not a sustainable position, so it's not where we
want to be. There is confidence in the understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
