<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWSUIT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING BURNED: FARMERS CONFRONT BIG TOBACCO, FRACTURING UNITED
FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Greg Hyman, a tobacco farmer from Conway, S.C.,
compares his dealings with cigarette manufacturers to a
relationship gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel used and abused,'' said Hyman, who recently joined
4,000 farmers and tobacco quota holders in a suit against the
companies. ``I feel like I've been misled and manipulated for the
past several years.''
</P>
<P>
   The class action alleges that the nation's top four cigarette
manufacturers conspired to reduce farm income by manipulating the
quota system, which determines how much tobacco is grown and sold
in this country. The farmers also charge that the cigarette
manufacturers betrayed them in the $206 billion settlement the
industry reached with 46 states in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco executives for Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Co., Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp., and Lorillard Tobacco Co.
deny the charges and promise to fight them vigorously in court.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of its outcome, the lawsuit, filed last month,
highlights a growing fracture in what once was a solid alliance of
manufacturers and farmers battling tobacco foes. The lawsuit also
signals a shift in the political dynamics of the golden leaf. Both
tobacco foes and supporters say the lawsuit makes it harder for the
industry to defend its interests on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it desirable when the growers and the manufacturers are
pulling the plow in the same direction,'' said U.S. Rep. Howard
Coble, R-N.C., whose district includes both farmers and a Lorillard
plant. ``This certainly would make our position more awkward up
here if we had to choose between growers and manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco executives have long sought to align themselves with
farmers, knowing they remain a sympathetic political symbol on
Capitol Hill. Any time lawmakers talked about higher taxes for
cigarettes or further government regulation, tobacco executives
could be counted on to evoke the plight of the family farmers,
asserting that the hard-working men and women in the fields would
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, tobacco farmers like Hyman contend that the industry itself
is the source of much of their pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's akin to catching your spouse cheating on you,'' Hyman
said. ``That's how I feel.'' The farmers' lawsuit comes on top of
another lawsuit from a group of wholesalers who charge the
manufacturers with fixing prices, a claim the industry denies.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Myers, president of the Coalition for Tobacco-Free Kids,
said the challenge from a cadre of angry farmers may be the most
significant the industry has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 4,000 farmers and quota holders who have signed onto
the lawsuit, however, are only a fraction of the farmers and quota
holders nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The united front between tobacco growers and manufacturers is
crumbling,'' said Myers, who represents health advocates. ``There's
no way around it.'' Myers said the industry had used the farmers to
score political points on Capitol Hill while placing their
livelihood secondary to the industry's profits.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the coalition released a report that documented how
the large cigarette companies are increasingly using foreign
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit points to other disputes. Some farmers contend that
the tobacco corporations discouraged them from supporting
congressional legislation that would have tightened federal control
of tobacco and also established a $28 billion fund to help farmers
develop other crops. Under the subsequent settlement with the
states, farmers won a trust fund of $5.15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   As for the quota system, the farmers charge in the lawsuit that
the tobacco corporations acted as a ``cartel'' to control the
market and drive prices down.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Pires Jr., a Washington-based attorney for the
farmers, said the tobacco companies want to dismantle the
government quota system and exert direct control over the farmers,
a move that would decrease tobacco prices and increase profits. In
fact, Philip Morris is moving ahead to set up direct contracts with
some large tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little guy has no friends anymore,'' Pires said, adding
that more tobacco farmers are joining the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pheil, director of communications for Philip Morris,
disputed that characterization. He said that his company remains
the largest purchaser of American-grown tobacco and continually
invests in research efforts to help farmers. ``We feel the lawsuit
is unfortunate,'' he said, dismissing it as the work of a
``relatively small group of farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of creating additional litigation and uncertainty in
the industry, we believe we should be working constructively to
find solutions to mutual concerns,'' Pheil said.
</P>
<P>
   For political leaders who have long supported the tobacco
industry, this latest lawsuit is troubling because there is no
obvious foe. North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt said he believes tobacco
farmers and cigarette makers have been ``pretty good partners,''
and he said he doesn't believe the lawsuit reflects the thinking of
all farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But he emphasized that tobacco farmers remain the industry's
most powerful political weapon and a valued constituency on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really important that the companies treat the farmers
right and treat them extra right,'' Hunt said. ``The American
tobacco farmers are basically the ones who keep them viable in this
American market. And they should always remember that. And they
should always go the extra mile to treat the farmers right and to
give them a little help whenever they can.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
