r a BC-CONROY-FIRE-COX     03-07 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONROY-FIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ansley Park mourns burned historic home
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis and S.A. Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chunks of Atlanta's past went up in smoke Tuesday in a
pre-dawn fire that destroyed one historic home and damaged two
others in Ansley Park, one of the city's oldest neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The home at 34 Peachtree Circle was once owned by noted author
Pat Conroy, who lived there for about two years while penning ``The
Prince of Tides.'' Now a South Carolina resident, Conroy wrote the
novel in a garage apartment behind the two-story frame house, built
just six years after Ansley Park's founding in 1904.
</P>
<P>
   From his studio windows, Conroy could have seen the high-rise
buildings of Colony Square and the secret garden of his neighbor's
back yard, said Ginny Bales, who sold Conroy the home in 1983 after
she and her former husband spent seven years renovating the place.
The house is currently owned by Kay and Woodrow Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful house,'' said Bales. ``I always thought of
it as a grandmother-style house with that big front porch and just
the prettiest windows you've ever seen, with a star pattern above
them. It's a shame to see a house like that go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ansley Park began at a time when a new invention was beginning
to stretch the boundaries of Atlanta, said resident Eleanor
Edmondson, who edited ``Historic Living in Ansley Park,'' published
by the neighborhood's civic association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with Druid Hills, Ansley Park was one of the first
automobile suburbs of Atlanta,'' she said. Edwin Ansley, one of the
park's developers, built the Westminster Drive home that later
became the governor's mansion. The owners of the ill-fated Winecoff
Hotel were Ansley Park residents, as were the owners of Muse's
Department Store and the Inmans of Inman Park fame.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrow Wells was clearly upset as he worked Tuesday to salvage
what was left from the piles of charred beams, flooring and
furniture on his muddy lawn.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled papers from a centuries-old footlocker in his family
for generations. ``I have no idea how it survived,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife had lived in the four-bedroom home since 1985.
They recently put the house on the market for $989,000.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the Wells home damages the fabric of the whole
neighborhood, said Greg Paxton, a resident who serves as director
of the Georgia Trust for Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The fire also melted residents' sense of security. Some
homeowners are considering updating insurance policies and taking
other precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
