<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW08-COX     03-07 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gap between blue-chip and `new economy' stocks continues to
widen
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investors have chosen sides in the last four and a
half months, during which so-called ``new economy'' technology
stocks have soared in price while ``old economy'' smokestack stocks
have plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   This is reflected in the widening gap between the Dow Jones
industrial average, the blue-chip index that is down 15 percent so
far this year, and the technology-loaded Nasdaq composite index,
which is up 19 percent. Stocks have been divided before, but
analysts say they don't recall a bigger division. Years of concern
about the length of the bull market and warnings of excessive
valuation have made investors nervous and the market volatile.
</P>
<P>
   All it took to send stocks tumbling Tuesday was Procter &AMP;
Gamble's warning that its third quarter profits will fall because
of rising raw material prices. As the biggest U.S. maker of
household goods and a member of the Dow, the 31 percent drop in its
shares gave the index its fourth-worst one-day point loss ever.
</P>
<P>
   Selling also prevented the Nasdaq from closing above 5,000,
where it had traded momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   Two explanations are usually offered for the current split in
stock market sectors.
</P>
<P>
   One is the Federal Reserve's policy of raising interest rates to
slow the pace of an economy it perceives to be growing at an
inflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rates hurt old economy stocks such as banks and other
financial institutions, retailers, producers of consumer products
and growth-related cyclical companies.
</P>
<P>
   But computer, technology and other Internet-related stocks rely
less on debt for financing. Their profits have not suffered as much
from the rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Also, investors are not convinced that the economy is moving in
a direction that will boost the future profits of blue-chip
companies. Slower economic growth means slower profit growth, and
profits drive the market.
</P>
<P>
   A third explanation for the market's behavior is that investors
tend to overreact.
</P>
<P>
   ``As often happens, fear has gone to an extreme,'' said Alfred
Goldman, chief market strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   His advice to investors is to become more greedy ``and buy some
growth stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman also contends that the market's recent sell-off makes it
less likely that the Fed will raise interest rates again when it
meets March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts aren't so sure in light of Chairman Alan
Greenspan's's recent remarks that the economy is still expanding
too rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, analysts regard the Fed's interest rate policy
as the key to the market for the rest of the year, since higher
rates _ or a change in rate policy _ will influence the outlook for
corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Goldman and other strategists recommend that
investors continue to put money in stocks, but to be highly
selective in what they buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stock picker's market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
