u f BC-YANKEENETS-MARKETPLAC     03-07 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEENETS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: HIGH STAKES FOR A SPORTS BOND OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Would you lend money to a sports conglomerate whose
current operations do not generate enough profits to pay interest
on the loans, let alone repay the money being borrowed?
</P>
<P>
   That is the issue buyers of junk bonds are facing as the
YankeeNets LLC _ the new company that controls a winning baseball
team and a losing basketball team _ tries to borrow $250 million.
It is expected that the borrowing will go through Thursday, but at
a very high interest rate of about 12.25 percent. That is half a
percentage point higher than the rate the company had hoped to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The private offering will finance payouts to the owners of the
two teams, enabling the former New Jersey Nets owners to pay back
money they borrowed to finance the payments that enabled them to
become equal owners of YankeeNets with the former owners of the New
York Yankees baseball team. For the owners of the Yankees, led by
George Steinbrenner, the payments will simply add to their wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner realized about $135 million in cash when the
Yankees and Nets combined business operations, and he is likely to
collect $40 million more if the bond offering is completed and a
related plan to sell a minority interest in the company also goes
as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The bond offering is being sold in a private placement open only
to institutional investors, including high-yield mutual funds.
While the offering memorandum is not public, a copy of it was
provided to The New York Times. It gives a detailed look at the
finances of the two teams and the unusual operating arrangement
that will preserve Steinbrenner's ability to run the Yankees as he
sees fit, notwithstanding the fact that he will no longer own a
majority stake in the team.
</P>
<P>
   The offering memorandum warns, in boldface type: ``We may not be
able to service our debt obligations if we do not increase cash
flow.'' Indeed, on a consolidated basis, the two teams showed a net
loss of $98.2 million on revenue of $241 million in the 12 months
ended Sept. 30, 1999. While some of that loss represented noncash
expenses, the combined company would have had a negative cash flow
of $4.2 million even before paying interest on its existing debts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the losses have come from the Nets. The financial
statements in the offering memorandum show that the Yankees are
marginally profitable before post-season revenue is counted _
revenue that would vanish if the team failed to make the playoffs.
For the first nine months of last year _ a period that does not
include the playoffs _ the team reported operating income of just
$556,000, and a net loss, after considering interest expense on its
current debt, of $4.4 million. Figures for the fourth quarter of
1999, including the playoffs and World Series, were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1998, when the team had post-season revenue of $11.5
million, it reported operating income of $20.1 million and net
income of $12.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   This borrowing, if the interest rate is 12.25 percent, will
require annual interest payments of $30.6 million, well above
previous cash flows for the teams. The $250 million would be due in
2007.
</P>
<P>
   The offering memorandum holds out two principal hopes for the
teams' coming up with the money to meet their obligations. The
first is a better local television contract for the two teams. The
Yankees contract with the Madison Square Garden Network expires
after this season, and the Nets have the right to terminate their
contract with Fox Sports New York at the end of the 2000-2001
season. The second is a sale of stock in one or both teams to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations for that contract should be interesting. Both
MSG and Fox Sports New York are now controlled by Cablevision _
which tried to buy control of the Yankees before the deal with the
Nets was made _ and competition between the two has diminished. But
the Yankees and Nets could conceivably put together their own
television operation if MSG and Fox Sports New York do not agree to
pay enough.
</P>
<P>
   The bond offering memorandum mentions the possibility of selling
shares in one or both teams to the public by 2003 but does not
commit itself to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the bond offering nor the planned sale of $75 million in
ownership interests in YankeeNets will do much to provide cash to
operate the teams. Only $15 million of the $325 million being
raised will go to operations. Another $15.7 million will go to pay
expenses connected to the offerings, and about $80 million will be
put into escrow to assure that the company will have the money to
make interest payments for the first three years that the bonds are
outstanding. That leaves about $214.3 million to be distributed to
the owners of the teams.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal company, the board has complete control over the
company's operations, although it delegates much of that control to
management. But the YankeeNets company is different. The board of
the Nets will have control over most aspects of that team,
including the right to set the team's budget within certain
parameters. Steinbrenner, as managing general partner of the
Yankees, will have the right to set that team's budget and to make
all major decisions on issues like personnel and player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   There is, to be sure, a board for the company. But its powers
are limited to certain decisions, including areas like real estate
investments. There is also a board for the Yankees, but the
agreement specifies that if the board and Steinbrenner disagree,
Steinbrenner's opinion will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
