u p BC-REPUBLICAN-PRIMARIES-     03-07 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICAN-PRIMARIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH BLITZES SUPER TUESDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     (EDS: Will be updated throughout the evening)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George Bush effectively silenced the challenge of
Sen. John McCain for the Republican presidential nomination
Tuesday, setting the stage for Bush to court McCain and his
supporters to join in a GOP crusade in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush harnessed hard-hitting campaign ads and a lavishly financed
nationwide campaign organization to roll up victories in at least
eight of the 13 states with GOP contests, according to Voter News
Service exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   Those polls showed Bush beating McCain in New York, Ohio,
Georgia, Maryland and Missouri, as well as in two New England
states that McCain had counted upon _ Rhode Island and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was running ahead of McCain, as well, in the popular vote
contest in California in which non-Republicans cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also swept key winner-take-all delegate contests, including
California, as well as the majority of the GOP delegates in New
York and Ohio, the exit polls showed. The results will give Bush
most of the 613 delegates chosen on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, whose fiery populism sustained an uphill challenge for
the last six weeks, captured only Vermont, Connecticut and
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But the 63-year-old former Navy pilot and Vietnam prisoner of
war failed to make inroads among the bedrock Republican voters that
he needed in order to capture a large numbers of delegates in the
district-by-district duels, particularly in New York and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The successful Republican candidate needs 1,034 delegates to
secure the GOP nomination at the national convention in
Philadelphia in late July.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said last weekend that he would withdraw from a failing
race rather than have his ``megaphone turn into a kazoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, son of former President George H.W. Bush, made it clear
that his most pressing task in the days ahead will be to court
McCain as well as the centrist Republicans, independents and
Democrats who rallied to McCain in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush extended an olive branch to McCain even before the results
were in, keenly aware that continued campaign attacks by McCain
would only jeopardize Bush's campaign against Vice President Al
Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if there's any personal issues between me and my
opponents, we'll sit down and talk,'' Bush said. ``But there's
going to be ample time to heal any wounds and I'm confident we can
heal any wounds that may exist between us.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary schedule moves into Bush territory next Tuesday,
with contests in six key southern and southwestern states,
including Texas, where Bush is governor, and Florida where his
brother, Jeb Bush, is chief executive. The six states offer 341
delegates _ enough to give Bush a mathematical lock on the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would stay in the race only if he believed he
still had a chance to turn things around and win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how proud I am to have sparked this kind of
prairie fire out there that got people involved,'' McCain said told
a radio call-in program Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's hard-hitting populist bid, featuring attacks on Bush,
``the establishment,'' the White House, Congress and special
interests, attracted legions of first-time voters, once-alienated
young voters, independents and Democrats to the GOP banner.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's candidacy ignited historic turnouts in New Hampshire
and Michigan, where he won early momentum, as well as in South
Carolina where he lost.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross Baker, a political science professor at Rutgers
University, said excitement does not translate into nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a credible early favorite _ and you have the
fortitude to stay on in the face of early disappointments _ you're
going to win the nomination,'' Baker said. ``Ultimately the
favorites designated by the party gray beards walk away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster based in Atlanta who is not
working for any presidential campaign, said McCain could not hope
to win the GOP nomination ``without Republican votes,''' adding:
``Establishment matters, and money matters _ especially in a war of
attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, which had the support of Republican leaders _
including 29 governors, 38 senators and 175 House members _ carried
out 2 million get-out-the-vote telephone calls in nine states in
the final two days of the Super Tuesday campaign, mailed 2 million
pieces of campaign literature and distributed 69,000 yard signs,
according to Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Baker and Ayres said Bush had been strengthened for the
fall campaign by being forced to grapple with McCain's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has become ``a far superior candidate, far more aggressive,
far more unscripted, far more willing to take chances,'' Ayres
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920 or at the e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
