<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-SURPLUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $16-BILLION SURPLUS AT FHA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said Tuesday that the Federal Housing
Administration generated a surplus of $16 billion in the fiscal
year that ended Sept. 30. That is $5 billion more than in the year
before, a gain that could make thousands more low-interest
mortgages and rental units available to low- and moderate-income
people.
</P>
<P>
   In a congratulatory memorandum, President Clinton directed
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo and Jack Lew, the White House budget
director, to develop a proposal for the newly available money and
report back in 160 days.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuomo may get a less glowing reception Wednesday at a
hearing of the House Appropriations subcommittee on housing, where
lawmakers will ask him to explain several enduring problems in his
department. Among other things, the subcommittee wants to know why
he believes the supply of affordable housing fell last year when a
General Accounting Office report says the supply has increased in
each of the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee chairman, Rep. James T. Walsh, R-N.Y., says he
generally agrees with Clinton that the Department of Housing and
Urban Development has made great strides under Cuomo, improving
programs and effectiveness. But Walsh says he still had concerns
over apparent discrepancies like those in the tally of affordable
housing.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict coincides with the Clinton administration's effort
to make a case for a budget request of $32 billion for the housing
department in the 2001 fiscal year, $6 billion more than its budget
this year. But Cuomo said the FHA surplus, which could help as many
as 750,000 families, was ample evidence that the department had
made reforms and deserved the increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come full circle with this,'' he said, recalling a
period five years ago when some Republican lawmakers wanted to
eliminate the housing department. ``We had to make changes, and
this is vindication of the entire effort.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
