<HEADER>
A9727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-TOWN-MEETINGS-NYT &LR;      03-07 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-TOWN-MEETINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE VERMONT HAMLET DEBATES SAME-SEX MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Vt. _ After the crock-potted beans and homemade
doughnuts, after the quick votes on culvert repair and the cemetery
committee, the 60-odd souls gathered Tuesday at the annual town
meeting of this Vermont hamlet turned to the tough, heated part.
</P>
<P>
   Did the town's residents support holding a referendum on
same-sex marriage? Yes, by acclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Did they support or oppose same-sex marriage itself?
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief, troubled pause. Then they waded in.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Vermont Supreme Court ruled in December that committed
gay couples should receive the same rights and benefits as straight
spouses, there have been surveys and legislative hearings and
endless radio and general store discussions on how to respond to
the ruling. But Tuesday, in more than 30 spots around Vermont, the
ultrademocratic forum of the traditional New England town meeting
offered citizens a chance to weigh in on an issue that has so far
been controlled by the court and the politicians.
</P>
<P>
   In Athens, a relatively conservative and poor town of about 313
in southern Vermont, the heat of the discussion seemed to indicate
that while the Legislature has agreed to concentrate on a ``civil
union'' bill that stops just short of marriage for gay couples, a
bill that is working its way efficiently through the House of
Representatives, there is no such agreement among many Vermonters.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the question was put, Wayne Ryan, a mechanic in black
garb and cowboy hat, rose and said: ``I believe it's against our
constitutional rights to have government and legislation change the
word `marriage' to mean something as ill and as foul as same-sex
partners. I believe anybody that does so cannot do it in clear
conscience, because it is against our constitutional rights to
change such a sacred word as `marriage.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Perry, a dairy farmer, spoke next. ``I'd like to know our
representatives' opinion on this, and if it comes up, how you
intend on voting,'' because, he said, ``that makes a difference how
we vote in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. David L. Deen, a Democrat who represents Athens and
three other towns, promptly obliged him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, in fact, abhor discrimination,'' Deen told the townspeople.
``It is just antithetical to everything I am or have been.''
</P>
<P>
   He therefore supports the civil union bill, he said. He also
reminded those at the meeting that despite dire warnings before the
state passed a law banning discrimination based on sexual
orientation back in 1992, ``the world as we know it hasn't
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives haven't changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Deen said, if he loses his seat over this issue,
``the world as I know it does not end,'' either.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy questions came from the crowd. Harold Noyes, the local
minister who had pushed to put the marriage questions onto the town
meeting agenda, argued that if, under the bill, same-sex partners
would go before an ``oath-giver'' and get a certificate, that would
be virtually no different from marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Noyes and the town clerk, Darlene Wyman, also expressed concern
about whether they would be forced to participate in a same-sex
union procedure to which their consciences objected.
</P>
<P>
   Deen said that he had ``no problem with people opting out if
they chose,'' but that he believed town clerks would be required to
provide couples with the certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have the right to refuse that document?'' Wyman asked.
</P>
<P>
   Told she likely did not, she responded, ``Then they'll have to
find another town clerk because I will not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   When other townspeople pressured Deen to vote in accordance with
their majority's wishes and against the bill, he refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a matter of conscience for me,'' he said. ``I get to
exercise my conscience, and you all get to vote the first Tuesday
in November every other year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will,'' inserted Walter Ryan, Wayne's father. ``You'll be
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview later, Deen commented that Athens was by far the
most conservative town he represented, and that voters in the
other, bigger and more liberal towns viewed domestic partnership
and gay marriage more favorably.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the town's opinions seemed to reflect the significant
depth and breadth of such opposition in Vermont _ in particular,
because it spoke as a whole town and not merely as a motivated few
who ventured to a Statehouse hearing to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, 35 townspeople voted to express opposition to gay
marriage _ a nonbinding vote that did little more than put their
opinions on record _ and 17 people dissented.
</P>
<P>
   In a second vote, on domestic partnership, 13 said they
supported the idea and 39 opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who supported domestic partnership, Tim Stevenson,
said he was not surprised at how the vote broke down, given the
conservative nature of Athens and its many longtime residents.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson was, however, struck that ``this was obviously the
flash point issue of the meeting, even more than the school issue,
which is really one that affects people much more personally, or
seemingly so, than the issue of gay and lesbian partnerships.''
</P>
<P>
   And though he was in the minority, he said, ``I feel like, yeah,
the people of this state should express themselves, whether they're
for it or against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen L. Fine, the town moderator, remained skeptical,
however, about whether the town's opinion would be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Legislature cares what Athens thinks,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
