u p BC-BRADLEY-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      03-07 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TOO PASSIVE IN PITCHING HIS VIEWS TO PUBLIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ True, a few things that led to Bill Bradley's undoing
in the Democratic presidential race were beyond his control.
</P>
<P>
   Opponent Al Gore &UR;  &LR; evolved into a better campaigner. Republican
John McCain sopped up independent voters and media attention.
Bradley's episodes of an irregular heart beat put him on the front
page when hardly anything else could.
</P>
<P>
   But at the core, Bradley's demise can be called the death of a
non-salesman. His inability or reluctance to be a gut-level
pitchman for his own lofty message prevented him from overriding
the outside factors.
</P>
<P>
   That is the viewpoint of two political experts who follow
Bradley's career.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential campaign ``is not a civil service exam where
you just have to get over the threshold and you get the job,'' said
Gerald Pomper, a political science professor at Rutgers University
in Bradley's home state of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley is a very competent and smart person, but he is not
the kind of person that arouses passion on the part of the
people,'' Pomper added. ``When you are running an insurgent
movement, especially on the left, you have to engender some
personal passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Walters, a University of Maryland political scientist who
wrote a book called ``Black Presidential Politics in America,''
said Bradley failed to translate his ideas from the language of the
lecture room to the language of the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last debates,'' Walters said, ``it looked like he was
`conceptualizing.'``
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Keitel, the actor and pugnacious personality, unwittingly
distilled these ideas at a rally for Bradley last week in New York
City's Greenwich Village. After urging the crowd to vote for
Bradley, the movie star and ex-Marine told Bradley for all to hear
that he should fire his political advisers and read the Marines'
training manual for a dose of toughness.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, Bradley allowed himself a brief but sharp
self-examination when asked by the hosts of ABC's ``This Week'' why
his campaign theme of racial unity had not won the support of the
majority of black voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that was my own fault in not communicating who I was or
what I believe,'' said the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the intellectual, was personally remote as a
professional basketball player and later as a U.S. senator. As the
campaign got off the ground last fall, his high-brow detachment
appeared to help him with some Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Dull was cool. He was seen as a refreshing departure from Gore
and President Clinton, the national emoter and confessed liar.
Bradley ran ahead of Gore in New York and New Hampshire polls.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gore seemed weighed down by his association with
Clinton and his connections to Democratic campaign fund-raising
scandals. But early on, Bradley never made any direct statements
designed to exploit this.
</P>
<P>
   When the calendar turned to 2000 and Gore started attacking
Bradley's record and policy proposals, Bradley first declined to
engage the battle. He had already set himself up as the knight of
``a new politics'' that shuns attacks and slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Then, heeding the lesson of modern campaigning that no
allegation should go unanswered or unpunished, Bradley changed
gears and got into a tong war with Gore. He portrayed the vice
president as untrustworthy and a closet conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it was too late for Bradley to defend himself and
his complex health insurance proposals, the switch made him look
awkward, if not hypocritical. He was no longer able to claim that
he was running the righteous campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's bid was also flawed because it started without a
built-in base of voters, Pomper said. Bradley ran as a more liberal
alternative to Gore but had not amassed a liberal following during
his Senate years because he was a moderate there, more concerned
with legislative details than broad political strokes, the
professor explained.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Bradley also was up against the political
ties Gore has forged with Democrat-friendly interest groups, such
as the AFL-CIO, during his seven years as vice president. Bradley
disdainfully called this ``entrenched power.'' And the Gore
campaign wielded the power with devastating timing.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley questioned Gore's commitment to abortion rights,
the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League
endorsed the vice president. When Bradley went further than Gore in
pushing new rules for gun control and questioned Gore's record on
the issue, Gore ran a commercial featuring praise from gun-control
advocate James Brady.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by Bradley's surge late last year, Gore moved his
campaign headquarters to Nashville, Tenn., from Washington, D.C.,
sharpened his stage skills and even changed his wardrobe. He was
``a fighter.'' Bradley was the dreamer. And voters in the early
primary states chose active over passive.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who proposed extensive campaign-finance reform, ran
against Gore to change the system. In the end, he ran
unsuccessfully against the system and changed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
