<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BUSH-ANALYSIS-COX     03-07 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush to set sights on Gore
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A year into the quest, and after a few round
trips between inevitable and in trouble, Gov. George W. Bush has
cleared the first hurdle in an effort to accomplish something he
insists is not the goal.
</P>
<P>
   A November win for Bush would complete the bookends around what
his family believes has been a sorry volume in American history:
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Bush has always insisted there is nothing personal
involved in trying to replace the man who ousted his dad.
Privately, he has has made it clear he doesn't think much of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-President George Bush also has steered clear of public
criticism of his successor. But by lunchtime Tuesday, he was on the
phone to his son's campaign to get word of the early exit poll
numbers. On Tuesday, as the voting began, Bush made it clear that
he plans to run a character-counts campaign against an
administration the Bush family believes is sorely lacking in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change my message,'' he said when asked for
his fall strategy. ``Maybe Al Gore feels . . . that he has got to
keep changing message or changing headquarters or changing suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes referred to electing Gore as ``the
equivalent of a third Clinton term.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a riff that began in Fresno, California on Sunday night
after Gore accused Bush of being in the ``pocket'' of special
interests, Bush on Tuesday said he intends to make the ethics of
the Clinton White House a November issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how somebody's memory all of a sudden has
lapses,'' Bush said. ``One of the things I'll do in the course of
the campaign is remind people what's gone on in the administration
for the last seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to end the Clinton-Gore era began quietly, if not
secretly, long before Bush won re-election in November 1998. It was
exactly one year ago yesterday that Bush announced the formation of
the exploratory committee that put the campaign in motion.
</P>
<P>
   It was a candidacy born fully formed with a candidate who
fund-raised his way to prohibitive favorite status. A solid win at
last August's Iowa Straw Poll confirmed his frontrunner status.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John McCain skipped the straw poll and the January Iowa
caucuses won by Bush. As other candidates dropped out, McCain
gained momentum.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 1, in an outcome that shook the Bush camp to its core,
the Texas governor was run over in New Hampshire by McCain's
Straight Talk Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``Test of character,'' Bush said as he flew out of New
Hampshire, angered by the outcome but convinced better days were
ahead. ``We'll just see. Different people, different part of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   That same day, Bush began his first comeback with a speech that
served both as short-term boost and long-term hurdle. Bush steered
hard right by giving a speech at Bob Jones University, a South
Carolina school whose anti-Catholic views became fodder for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won South Carolina big. But the following week, McCain took
Michigan and Arizona. Last week, Bush got it moving in his
direction by winning in North Dakota, Virginia and Washington
(though mail-in absentee votes are still being counted in
Washington).
</P>
<P>
   Bush's bumpy ride included criticism from skeptics who painted
him as a done-nothing lightweight. His stump speeches almost always
included mangled language and the syntax of his father.
</P>
<P>
   (Tuesday, botching a line he has repeated many times in recent
weeks, Bush said, ``If Senator McCain says one thing he ought to do
another.'')
</P>
<P>
   Bush also got branded as a tool of the Christian right and a
too-close buddy of big business. The latter image was hard to
ignore every time Bush came on stage to what might be the
worst-ever entry music chosen for a GOP candidate: ``Taking Care of
Business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush slalomed through the criticism and, almost $60 million
into the effort, now has clinched the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A November loss would be hard for Bush to take, but, at least
for now, he has avoided joining his dad as personification of the
squandered lead.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com or
445-1718.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
