<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COW-PARADE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY ASKED TO PRODUCE HERD OF COWS FOR URBAN SITES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Hawaii, Kans., Fla., Ill., Switzerland, Britain)   By JASON HALL   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Entrepreneur Scott Hamblin may have latched
onto a real cash cow. Hamblin's Resource Factory, a statuary
manufacturer, has received an order to construct 200 fiberglass
cows by April 1 that will eventually be shipped to cities
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The cows are being produced for Cow Parade Holding Corp., a
for-profit company that sponsors art exhibits aimed at making the
cow a vital part of city culture in America.
</P>
<P>
   Hamblin said he may eventually produce up to 900 cows. The first
40 cows were shipped Monday. ``These cows in particular are going
to Manhattan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Resource Factory is one of two companies in the nation
making the cows; the other is in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Hamblin declined to say how much he's paid per bovine. Similar
sculptures cost $2,500 a piece unpainted when they were installed
in Chicago last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hamblin landed the account by word of mouth, through regular
customers at Warner Bros., Six Flags and Disney. Hamblin's company
makes fiberglass sculptures of almost anything, but his biggest
client is the creator of such characters as Bugs Bunny and Daffy
Duck.
</P>
<P>
   Cows on Parade started as an art exhibit in Zurich, Switzerland,
in 1997, and made its big splash last year in Chicago. Coverage of
the cows, displayed all over the city, appeared in newspapers, in
magazines and on television all over the world. Hamblin's cows are
based on molds he made from some of the Chicago cows.
</P>
<P>
   None of the cows Hamblin's team has crafted will be displayed
locally, other than at his shop. They're all being shipped by
tractor-trailer to New York.
</P>
<P>
   There, they will be handed over to artists who will take
liberties with the cows, painting or decorating them as wildly or
conservatively as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   The cows are then sponsored by corporations, with prices of
$7,500 to $350,000, said Daniel Blume, vice president of
Connecticut-based Cow Parade Holding Corp. After expenses, Cow
Parade Holding earns profits from the sponsorships. When the cows
are later auctioned, local charities will receive up to 80 percent
of the proceeds, Blume said.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year's affair in Chicago generated worldwide buzz,
New York City is following with similar efforts this year. Blume
said the cows will be on display in 59 parks in New York from June
15 to July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities are lining up to have cow parades. The list
includes Honolulu, Kansas City and London.
</P>
<P>
   After the cows are paraded, they will be auctioned off in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's auction of about 300 cows in Chicago made about $4
million, said Lorene Barrow, a spokeswoman for Cow Parade Holding
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   New York's parade should generate even more money, because more
cows are being produced _ 500 to 600, Barrow said _ and because
they're being painted by more high-profile artists.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees and the New York Mets will sponsor cows and
have players sign them, and artist Peter Maxx is painting a cow a
day this week, live on NBC's ``Today Show.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jason Hall writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla. The
Herald Tribune is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
