<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-LEVI-NYT &LR;      03-07 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LEVI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARD H. LEVI, 88, ATTORNEY GENERAL UNDER GERALD FORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward H. Levi, who began his association with the University of
Chicago as a 5-year-old in a special kindergarten there and became
the university's president before going on to be a widely admired
attorney general of the United States, died Tuesday at his home in
Chicago. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   A distinguished legal educator, he was called upon to restore
the credibility of the job of attorney general after the turmoil of
the Nixon era.
</P>
<P>
   No one was more a product of the University of Chicago than
Levi. He remained at the university's laboratory school through
grade school and high school, then attended college, graduate
school and law school at the university. He was at various times, a
law professor, dean of the law school, university provost, and
finally the university's president.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who spent most of his life in the shadow of the
University of Chicago, Levi had enormous impact on the university,
the study of law and even the surrounding Hyde Park neighborhood in
which he grew up and which he later helped revitalize. He thrilled
at teaching Chicago's renowned ``great books'' curriculum to
undergraduates, pioneered the pairing of law with other disciplines
like economics and statistics at the law school and was a fierce
recruiter of leading intellectuals in order to maintain the
university as a vibrant agora of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But he secured a wider place in history for his role in
Washington where he demonstrated that the skills he honed and
deployed in academic circles were equally useful at the highest
levels of government.
</P>
<P>
   As the 71st attorney general of the United States, Levi won wide
acclaim for his stewardship of the Justice Department in the
post-Watergate era. He has regularly been cited by political
scientists and lawyers as the model of a modern attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   When he was named to the post in 1975 by President Gerald Ford,
there was confusion about his political affiliations and
philosophy. Some news accounts questioned whether he was best
described as a conservative, liberal, or libertarian. When he left
office two years later, the answer was was no clearer, but the
question seemed mostly irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia of the Supreme Court, who was a senior
official under Levi in the Justice Department, said in an interview
that ``there couldn't have been a tougher job in Washington where
the whole executive branch was in disarray after Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia said that as attorney general, Levi ``brought the
department through its worst years,'' adding ``It was a bad time
not only because of the disgrace of Watergate which had affected
the department most deeply but there were also problems at the
FBI.'' The Federal Bureau of Investigation had been conducting
domestic surveillance operations that were likely unconstitutional
under the code name Cointelpro. Levi forced through regulations
setting limits on what the bureau and the Central Intelligence
Agency could undertake in investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought two qualities to the job,'' Scalia said, ``a rare
intellectuality and a level of integrity such as there could never
be any doubt about his honesty, forthrightness or truthfulness.''
</P>
<P>
   When he left the Department to return to the University of
Chicago, his performance was considered so nonpartisan that he was
warmly praised by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In a January, 25, 1977, speech in the Senate, Kennedy said,
``Mr. Levi entered office under the most difficult and trying
circumstances, yet he leaves a Department once again characterized
by integrity, intellectual honesty and commitment to equal
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Hirsch Levi born in Chicago on June 26, 1911, to Gerson
B. Levi, a rabbi who came to the United States from Scotland and
Elsa Hirsch Gerson. His maternal grandfather, Rabbi Emil G. Hirsch,
was an early member of the University of Chicago faculty and a
leading architect of the Reform branch of Judaism in America.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from college, Levi began studying for a
doctorate in literature at the University of Chicago but dropped
out of the program. Years later he explained that he had been told
in a friendly manner by a professor who admired his family that he
would never be given a position in the humanities department at
Chicago or any leading institution because he was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that incident not ruefully but joyfully, in an essay
written for Newsweek magazine during the nation's bicentennial
celebrations of 1976 to demonstrate how much the country had
changed. He had, after all, become the first dean of a major law
school who was Jewish. When he became the president of the
University of Chicago in 1968, he said he believed he was the first
Jewish president of a major private university that did not, like
Brandeis, have a clear Jewish identity.
</P>
<P>
   Gerhard Casper, the president of Stanford University and a
former colleague of Levi's at the University of Chicago law school,
said that it was Levi who came up with the idea of teaming up with
an economist to teach his course in antitrust law. It was from that
innovation, Casper said, that the notion of tying law to other
forms of study was born. ``This was the beginning of the `law and
economics school' of thought for which Chicago would become
famous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, Levi founded the school's Journal of Law and Economics,
which became a vehicle that helped the University of Chicago to
remain pre-eminent in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Botstein, the president of Bard College, who is a former
student of Levi's, said that he was also a model in furthering the
notion that intellectual arguments should be about ideas, not about
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He resented the personalizing of arguments,'' Botstein said.
``I remember he was asked if he was going to write his memoirs, and
he replied, `if I were to write a book, it would be about ideas,
not about myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   He was also renowned among college and university administrators
for his deft handling of civil disturbances on the Chicago campus
in 1968. Unlike administrators at some other major universities, he
did not call in the police or outside authorities when more than
400 students occupied his office for more than two weeks. He waited
them out and after they were gone, he suspended and dismissed many
of their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   His slim volume, ``An Introduction to Legal Reasoning''
(University of Chicago Press, 1949), has been a perennially
assigned book in courses of jurisprudence at many of the nation's
law schools.
</P>
<P>
   Levi retired from the university in 1984; his wife, Kate
Sulzberger Hecht Levi, said he had suffered from Alzheimer's
disease for the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by three sons, John G.,
a lawyer in Chicago, David F., a federal trial judge in Sacramento,
Calif., and Michael E., a particle physicist in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9737 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLA-AFFIRM-COX     03-07 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-AFFIRM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thousands protest Bush's `One Florida' plan
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ They were grandmothers, roofers, bus drivers,
teachers, students, labor union members. All of them said the door
of opportunity was closing on them with Gov. Jeb Bush's push to end
racial and gender set-asides in state contracting and university
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 11,000 of them _ as estimated by state and local law
enforcement officials _ joined civil rights heavyweights Jesse
Jackson, NAACP president Kwesi Mfume and others in a 1-mile march
Tuesday up a hill on Apalachee Parkway to the Capitol in protest of
Bush's ``One Florida'' plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on you!'' they shouted in unison outside the Capitol,
about the same time Bush delivered his State of the State address
to lawmakers on the first day of Florida's legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of the 20-member Legislative Black Caucus skipped
the speech and marched.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, nearly 600 school bus drivers marked the protest by
taking the day off, leaving thousands of students without
transportation Tuesday. A school official told the Associated Press
that most of the drivers planned to attend the protest.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush argued in his address that the protests were ignoring
the will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of Floridians favor the elimination of
affirmative action programs,'' Bush said in his speech. ``It would
have been politically expedient to simply let these programs be
dismantled, with nothing to replace them.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said now that he's put a plan on the table, he is
``being reminded of the public and private price of taking a stand
on principle.''
</P>
<P>
   In a poll of 689 registered voters sponsored by the by the New
York Times, 44 percent said they support Bush's effort to end some
affirmative action policies through One Florida. Another 40 percent
said they wanted affirmative action policies to remain. The poll
had a margin of error of 4 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Florida, One Term,'' read Jacqueline Brown's homemade
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' said the retired educator, who drove to
Tallahassee from near Daytona Beach with her husband and a friend
early Tuesday morning to protest. ``The nerve of them, trying to do
away with affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying,'' Brown's husband, Harold, said, ``to take us
back to 1963. If those white, conservative Republicans keep it up,
we'd be back to slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has put some of his ideas into action through executive
order. Other parts need legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says the application for minority and female contractors
will be streamlined and outreach programs for minorities enacted.
As for college admissions, One Florida guarantees admission to a
state university of the top 20 percent of each high school
graduating class.
</P>
<P>
   Students in Leon County schools were granted permission to
attend the march, and some took the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's racism and sexism in this society,'' said high school
senior Beth Prentiss. ``It's blatant, it's obvious. If Bush doesn't
get the message we're going to make him listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 buses stretched from the Old Capitol back up
Apalachee Parkway as marchers listened to speakers, who spoke on a
podium framed by 2-story palm trees. Spanish moss swayed from oak
branches overhead.
</P>
<P>
   After waving to the crowd and shaking hands through the windows,
Jackson, Mfume and Martin Luther King III, president of the
Atlanta-based Southern Christian Leadership Conference, along with
other VIPs walked off Old Town Trolley bus No. 983 and strode to
the head of the march on Apalachee Parkway, closed most of the day
to accommodate protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Atlanta activists attending was the Rev. Timothy
McDonald, head of Concerned Black Clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been able to overcome a lot of things and we will be
able to overcome this,'' McDonald said. ``This (Bush proposal) is
the first step towards resegregation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a late winter sun that warmed the day to 80 degrees _ so
hot that some participants were escorted to Red Cross booths
because of dehydration _ Jackson wore a short-sleeve black shirt
and black pants. During his speech on the Capitol grounds, Jackson
started calmly, his voice slowly crescendoing with each passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fighting for privileges, we're fighting for access
to the American Dream for all Americans and leave nobody _ black or
white _ behind,'' Jackson said. ``Affirmative action is based on
need. Say, `Based on need,''' he urged the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on need! Based on need! Based on need!'' the crowd
repeated after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's denial,'' Jackson continued, ``or persistent
discrimination to capital, contracts or health care, gender and
race matters. It affects women's incomes, therefore households'
access to capital. Most poor folks are not black. Most poor folks
are not brown. They're white. They're female, and they're young...
</P>
<P>
   ``Most poor folks are not on welfare, Jeb. They work every day.
They raise other people's children. They work every day. They pick
tomatoes and lettuce. They work every day. They change beds at
hotels. They work every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the march, signs in the crowd mocked all Bushes _ the
Florida governor, his Texas governor brother, George W., the GOP
presidential front-runner, and their father, former President
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   One example: Read My Lips. Damn You!
</P>
<P>
   Another: One term Jeb, No term George W.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it may be Super Tuesday in the nation, it is
super-duper Tuesday in the state of Florida,'' Mfume said, taking
note that the march coincided with presidential primaries and
caucuses in 16 states.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing the Bushes as men of privilege, Jackson declared,
``When you inherit the name, when you inherit legal protection,
when you inherit the wealth, when you inherit skin color, when you
inherit your parents' friends for advantage, you just don't
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami roofing company owner Patrick Burke and his secretary
Carolyn Calhoun drove from South Florida all night to join the
march.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like for him to leave affirmative action alone,'' Burke
said. ``With affirmative action, there's at least a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Calhoun, ``This could be the beginning of something
horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of protesters marched on the Capitol Tuesday, March 7,
2000, against Gov. Jeb Bush's plan to eliminate racial and gender
preferences in university admissions and state contracting
Protesters from around the country chanted 'Shame on Bush' just
before the march, which began as Bush started his State of the
State address to the Florida Legislature and its guests..(AP
Photo/Phil Coale)
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOG / Staff
</P>
