<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SLOVENIA-ART-NYT &LR;      03-07 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOVENIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LJUBLJANA JOURNAL: LIKE SWITZERLAND, BUT WITHOUT THE CUCKOO
CLOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LJUBLJANA, Slovenia _ To Eastern Europe experts who never
confuse this country with Slovakia or Slavonia, it is, in their
words, ``a jewel,'' ``a chocolate box,'' ``Eastern Europe's
best-kept secret,'' or even _ wait for it _ ``the Switzerland of
the former Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who stopped here overnight last June to thank
Slovenia for letting NATO jets fly over on their way to bomb Kosovo
and other parts of Yugoslavia, said at the time that he foresaw ``a
Europe undivided, democratic and at peace for the first time in its
history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Slovenia can lead the way,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But as devotees struggle for the words to praise without
condescending to a country of two million people, economic
statistics tell the story more plainly: on the lists of Eastern
European countries ready to join the European Union, tiny Slovenia
is in the first wave, sometimes ranked at No. 2, behind Hungary but
ahead of the Czech Republic and Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Since it broke away from Yugoslavia in 1991, its gross domestic
product per person has doubled to $10,000, outstripping that of
Hungary and rivaling those of the poorest European Union members,
Greece and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among Eastern Europeans, Slovenes do not need tourist
visas to visit the United States. The standard of living is so high
and unemployment so low that it is assumed that they will go home.
``It's the highest form of compliment the U.S. pays,'' a diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never hear of real poverty here,'' he said. ``There were
people laid off when they did economic shock treatment, but the
growing service industry absorbed them. There are retired people
getting by on pensions, but it's a living wage. There are
subsistence farmers, but they're in valleys where Heidi might have
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Slovenes quickly rebuff comparisons with rivals like
impoverished Romania or even the rest of the former Yugoslavia.
They were at the core of the Austro-Hungarian Empire until it was
broken up after World War I, they say, and generations of their
artists and intellectuals went to the Vienna court, so they judge
themselves by the standards of Austria and northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our misfortune was that we were divorced in 1918,'' said Karl
Lavencic, a Slovenian journalist working in Britain. ``We joined
Yugoslavia, and standards began to deteriorate under communism.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, under Tito's ``self-management'' brand of
communism, Slovenia was allowed to lead the way in running
industries that traded with the West.
</P>
<P>
   When the Eastern bloc fell apart, 80 percent of Slovenia's
export market disappeared, but it recovered, and the country now
does 66 percent of its trade with the European Union. It exports
Renaults, parts for BMW and Ford, pharmaceuticals, furniture,
clothing and tires.
</P>
<P>
   Beaches on the Adriatic, ski runs in the Alps and lots of German
Baroque spires in tidy villages make tourism a growth industry, and
Ljubljana itself has a strange medieval exoticism. Dominated by a
hilltop fortress, it must have more dragons per capita than any
city west of Beijing _ as the city's symbol, there are dragons
guarding bridges, dragons climbing light poles, even dragons on the
manhole covers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the name of its oldest hotel, the Slon, which
claims to date from an inn founded in 1552, means the Elephant. A
government spokesman said it was named for Hannibal's big-guy
cavalry passing through to attack Rome, but that seems doubtful,
since the Carthaginians took the Spanish route. More likely is the
hotel's version: a circus working the Austro-Hungarian gig used to
tether its elephants nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike every other piece of the former Yugoslavia, the country
has no ethnic tensions. The population is 90 percent Slovene, and
the Italian and Hungarian minorities in border areas have their own
seats in Parliament and the right to bilingual education and the
use of their own languages in dealings with government.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenes joke that the shape of the country looks like a chicken
fleeing east, but they actually stood their ground and won a 10-day
war for independence in 1991 against demoralized troops from the
Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought Slovenians would just raise their hands and give
up,'' said Miha Rott, a government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia declared its independence on June 25 that year,
depriving the old Yugoslavia of what had been its borders with
Austria and Italy, and the Yugoslav army attacked on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone who describes the war acknowledges that Slobodan
Milosevic, the Serbian leader, had little interest in the fight
because there were almost no Serbs in Slovenia, and he was
husbanding resources for his plans to seize Serbian-inhabited
portions of Croatia and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs never regarded Slovenia as a part of the world they
would die for,'' Lavrencic said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Slovenia has aggressively pursued entry to NATO and
was almost included in the round of expansion that has already
brought in Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic. One reason that
Slovenia did not make that cut, say diplomats from many NATO
countries, is that NATO was wary of embracing any former Yugoslav
republic while war still raged farther south.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for the European Union requires extensive overhauls
of the legal system and economy, especially in a formerly communist
country, and Slovenia still has changes to make, said Vincent
Piket, counsellor of the organization's delegation here.
</P>
<P>
   The country's banking and insurance are dominated by
government-owned companies that must be merged and sold. The
telephone monopoly must be ended and electricity privatized.
Antitrust laws need strengthening; laws favoring local bids for
government contracts need weakening.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 laws and bylaws matching those of other European
countries must still be passed and legislators taught their
meaning. Some sectors are resisting change: farmers fear
competition and judges resent being given a new body of laws.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``from the point of view of the European Union we're not
a problematic country,'' said Janez Potocnik, head of the country's
negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
   In the toughest areas for other would-be members _ inefficient
small farmers, pollution and corruption _ Slovenia does relatively
well. Though vocal, farmers are only 4 percent of the economy, and
many have second incomes from factory work, guesthouses or hunting.
There is little heavy industry. The justice system is slow but
honest.
</P>
<P>
   And, to the delight of the European Union, nervous about porous
borders even before Joerg Haider's party in Austria made much of
the issue, Slovenia is buying passport scanners, fingerprint
scanners, X-ray machines, night vision goggles and other hardware
needed to tighten its frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   Piket agreed with his counterpart, Potocnik.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental assessment is that they can join the union in
two or three years,'' he said. ``It depends on how fast they do
their homework. If they work as hard as they did last year, they
can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
