<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFURBISHED HOGAN ROOM PROMISES TO BE TREAT FOR FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Construction crews have completed their task outdoors, where an
off-season refurbishment of Colonial Country Club's greens and
bunkers will create subtle differences on selected shots for PGA
Tour participants at the MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   But to the average golf fan, a more eye-catching change is
taking place indoors. Construction is ongoing on the club's
revamped Ben Hogan Room, with a target completion date of April 1.
</P>
<P>
   A popular stop for tournament visitors, the room has been in
transition since the majority of Hogan's mementos were shipped to
the U.S. Golf Association museum in 1998. It was Hogan's desire for
the items, valued in excess of $1 million, to be placed in a museum
setting upon his death.
</P>
<P>
   The decision left Colonial officials in a quandary about the
best way to continue honoring the only five-time champion in
tournament history. They decided to spend roughly $200,000 updating
the room and replicating Hogan's major-championship and Colonial
trophies.
</P>
<P>
   The new display will feature an audio/visual monitor, with a
12-minute highlight clip of Hogan's career. Wood-and-glass cabinets
will hold tributes to Hogan's contributions as a player, club
manufacturer and author of instructional books. Separate displays
will house mementos from his nine major championships and five
Colonial titles.
</P>
<P>
   A locker will be built to replicate the one Hogan kept at Shady
Oaks Country Club until his death in 1997. It will be filled with
clothes Hogan wore in his later years, as well as a set of clubs
manufactured by the Hogan Co. in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights include a granite floor with Hogan's signature
inlaid in gold leaf. A miniature of the bronze statue that
overlooks Colonial's 18th green will sit atop a pedestal listing
his professional golf victories and other major awards.
</P>
<P>
   A separate section will be devoted to Hogan's near-fatal auto
wreck in 1949, as well as his recovery after being told by doctors
that he would never walk again. Hogan went on to add six of his
nine major championships after the wreck, including a stirring
comeback to win the 1950 U.S. Open. A wicker-basket flagstick from
Merion (Pa.) Golf Club, site of the 1950 Open, will be part of the
display.
</P>
<P>
   So will photos donated by Dan Jenkins, the renowned author and
golf writer from Fort Worth. Another Fort Worth resident, Conrad
Bennett, has donated scorecards signed by Hogan from each of the
courses where he won major championships. Family members donated a
silk robe, signed by several prominent actors of the 1950s, that
Hogan received during the filming of ``Follow the Sun'', the 1951
movie based on his life.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Schmuck, former club president and chairman of the Hogan
Room committee, said members are eager to see the finished product.
Currently, the room sits behind locked doors, with an artist's
rendering displayed in the main lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something Colonial needs to have,'' Schmuck said. ``The
golf course is what drives the train at our club. But Ben Hogan was
the engineer who drove the train and put Colonial on the map. His
wins here brought a lot of history and attention to Colonial that
we probably would not have gotten otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Corpening, a longtime Colonial member, said the finished
room will fill a void for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been walking past that room for 40 years and was used to
seeing Ben Hogan's trophies in there,'' Corpening said. ``To see
something else ... seemed wrong. That room is such an integral part
of Colonial. We want to make sure we recreate what we had the best
we can.''
</P>
<P>
   By tournament week, it should qualify as the off-season
renovation project that draws the most ooohs and aaahs from
visitors.
\Nsubheds:CHIP SHOTS \Nsubheds:Investing in the future During the
tournament's annual kickoff dinner, MasterCard Colonial officials
donated $60,000 to the Lindy Miller Foundation for Junior Golf.
Miller, golf director at Mira Vista Country Club, is organizing the
Fort Worth chapter of the First Tee project, an outreach program
founded by the PGA Tour to introduce disadvantaged youngsters to
the game of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Miller hopes to begin construction within the next year on a
nine-hole course and golf academy, specifically tailored to junior
players, at Interstate 30 and Oakland Boulevard. Land for the
project was donated by the city of Fort Worth. Miller plans to
raise the $4 million necessary to fund the project before breaking
ground. Colonial officials also donated $100,000 to the project in
May. \Nsubheds:Early commitments Among the first players to commit
to compete in the 2000 Colonial (May 18-21) was Tom Kite, an Austin
resident in his rookie season on the Senior PGA Tour. Kite, 50,
opted to play in his 27th Colonial rather than take part in the
senior event that week in Kansas City, Mo. Other early commitments
include Mark Calcavecchia, defending champion Olin Browne and past
champions Peter Jacobsen, Keith Clearwater and Ben Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Thomas, Colonial tournament chairman, said officials have
heard from 54 players with plans to compete in the event. Officials
anticipate about 110 participants. \Nsubheds:Furyk moves up David
Duval continues to be Tiger Woods' closest pursuer in the world
golf rankings. But with Sunday's comeback victory at the
Doral-Ryder Open, Jim Furyk has taken over the No. 2 spot in the
``Golfweek''/Sagarin Performance Index.
</P>
<P>
   The world rankings factor players' performances over a two-year
stretch, while the performance index considers only the past 52
weeks. Furyk has moved from No. 5 to No. 2 in the performance index
since Feb. 21, passing Duval (68.38), Davis Love III (68.36) and
Colin Montgomerie (68.45). In a system where the lower score is
better, Furyk (68.28) trails Woods (67.17) by a large margin.
\Nsubheds:INSIDE THE NUMBERS \Nsubheds:Major Milestones Although he
made headlines with his recent six-event winning streak at PGA Tour
events, Tiger Woods said the ``greatest record'' in professional
golf remains Jack Nicklaus' 18 victories in major championships.
Woods, by comparison, has two. The top six players on the list:
Name Major titles Jack Nicklaus 18 Walter Hagen 11 Ben Hogan 9 Gary
Player 9 Sam Snead 8 Tom Watson 8
LPGA GOLDEN MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the LPGA Tour's 50th anniversary, the
Star-Telegram will feature a significant moment in tour history
history each week during the 2000 season. \Nsubheds:Feb. 26, 1978
Nancy Lopez, a 21-year-old rookie, provided a foreshadowing of
things to come by holding off Jo Ann Washam to win the Bent Tree
Classic in Sarasota, Fla. It marked the first of 48 triumphs in a
Hall of Fame career and was the first of Lopez's nine victories in
her rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez ended the 1978 season with a Triple Crown of awards _
Rookie of the Year, Player of the Year and Vare Trophy winner. But
her crowning achievement was a string of five consecutive victories
at midseason, which remains a tour record. That streak could not
have happened, Lopez said, without the confidence gained from
victory No. 1 on a windy day in Florida.
</P>
