<HEADER>
A9750 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-BRAVES-LIGTENBERG     03-07 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-LIGTENBERG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ligtenberg has a good day
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ It might have looked and felt like any other
spring-training day to the mostly 60-something 6,524 Tiger faithful
relaxing in the sun on a breezy afternoon at Marchant Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But to Kerry Ligtenberg, Tuesday was critical. For the first
time in 362 days, Ligtenberg pitched in a baseball game. The result
was one scoreless inning.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreless part was a bonus. The Braves and Ligtenberg's
wife, Sara, breathed a collective sigh of relief when he skipped
off the mound, happy and, more importantly, healthy.
</P>
<P>
   In a spring-training game on March 10 of last year, Ligtenburg
hurt his elbow and ended his season. He had surgery on his elbow in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it,'' Ligtenberg said afterward. ``(It) didn't hurt, so
... .''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg said he got a good night's sleep Monday and wasn't as
nervous as he thought he would be before Tuesday's game. But
listened to some advice from Rudy Seanez, who on Monday
successfully threw his first inning since surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy told me, `The doctors fixed it. You know that the elbow
strong, so don't worry about something happening.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bigger chance of somebody like (Greg) Maddux or
(John) Smoltz or somebody else who hasn't had the surgery but has
pitched a lot more of their elbow blowing out than (mine)
re-blowing out,'' Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got out there, I calmed down a little bit,'' he said.
``It was kind of strange getting back into a game. Now that the
first one is out of the way, I can go have fun the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg threw a dozen pitches _ six balls and six strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors told me not to try to push it today, just to throw
like I was throwing batting practice,'' Ligtenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The third hitter he faced was Juan Gonzalez, the Tigers' new
cleanup hitter who is seeking $148 million to become the
highest-paid player in baseball. Gonzalez came to the plate with a
runner at third and one out, after hitting a two-run homer off
Terry Mulholland his previous time up.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg had been off target with his first two pitches and
gave up a single to Brad Ausmus on his first pitch over the plate.
Ausmus stole second while Ligtenberg dealt with Damion Easley.
Easley flew out to center for Ligtenberg's first out in almost a
year, and Ausmus took third.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have a whole lot on his fastball,'' said Easley, who
saw five Ligtenberg pitches and thought they looked about like any
other pitcher in camp. ``Even if I didn't know who it was or what
happened to him, I'd think, 'Spring training. He's just trying to
get in shape.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg's first pitch to Gonzalez was a ball. His second
Gonzalez was a good one. The Tigers new cleanup hitter swung
tentatively and sent a popup foul down the first base side where
Andres Galarraga was camped.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg then coaxed non-roster player Tilson Brito to hit
another popup in foul territory to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good first time out,'' Bobby Cox said. ``(His
pitches) had a little life on them, but he didn't overdo things.
We're delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg is scheduled to take today off, throw on the side
Thursday and then throw again in a game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to be back,'' Ligtenberg said. ``I'm excited to
get ready for the season. I think this was the first big step, and
we'll see how it goes tomorrow. And the next big step will be
throwing the splitter and trying to come back on shorter days'
rest. I still have a ways to go, but I feel pretty positive about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
