<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9751 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKC-TURNED-PRO-COX     03-07 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TURNED-PRO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks' Glover, 76ers' Jones, getting paid but rarely played
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back when they were high-school stars, which now seems so long
ago, Dion Glover and Jumaine Jones talked a lot about their
promising basketball futures.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it was about the glamour and glitz, the travel and
excitement of the Final Four and later the NBA. And, of course,
they saw themselves rippin' things up, just as they did as
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Never once did they entertain the reality that has been this
season: Seldom-used NBA rookies who look on painfully as their
former college teams struggle without them.
</P>
<P>
   And as March Madness rises toward its climax, it's difficult to
ignore the impact that deciding to leave early for the NBA has had
on both their careers and their respective colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech and Georgia both suffered their worst regular
seasons in years. Barring a stunning reversal in conference
tournaments that begin Thursday, each school's season will be over
that night or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones, a talented, hard-working forward, had stayed beyond
his sophomore year, and scoring guard Glover for his junior season
after missing a year with a major knee injury, the Bulldogs and
Yellow Jackets undoubtedly would have had better seasons and
brighter prospects in the conference tourneys.
</P>
<P>
   It also is possible that Glover's and Jones' NBA values would
have increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about that,'' Jones said recently. ``I do want
Georgia to do well, no question about that. Like everybody else, I
feel tournament time is a great time of year for college
basketball. I mean, I miss it, in a sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers' Jones and the Hawks' Glover find themselves in
similar positions. But instead of being stars, they are rookies who
are financially secure but whose status is far from stable. Neither
has garnered any meaningful moments _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   And so, were they wrong in going to the NBA so early? The
answers vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left college early, so I find it hard to criticize someone
else for leaving early,'' Washington Wizards guard Rod Strickland
said. ``You don't know people's circumstances. It could be a need
for the money to help out the family. People can say what they
want, but when you have a chance to make the kind of money they pay
in the NBA _ and your family needs it _ how can you tell him to
stay in school?''
</P>
<P>
   Although an outsider would look at his limited playing time on a
bad team as a source of regret, the The Glovers say they are
ecstatic about the son's decision, despite his limited playing time
on a poor team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has gone smoothly, to me,'' Glover's father, the
Rev. Franklin Glover, said. ``Dion's been a little anxious, because
he's ready to play. But he's grown to know that it's not about
playing. It's a job. You have to get up everyday, get yourself in
shape, work on the things you need to, watch what you eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a father, when he was making his decision last year, I
always said we had to pray hard about it,'' the Rev. Glover said.
``Schooling is the best thing since water. The money is good, but
an education is best.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Glover decided to leave. ``Sometimes, being young,
you think you can conquer the world,'' Franklin Glover said. ``He
wanted to reach one of his goals and felt he was ready to, and did.
And the way we see it, it's been beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Dion Glover, 21, would not go that far. He's working hard on his
shooting and ballhandling to earn an opportunity from coach Lenny
Wilkens. Going into Tuesday's game at Chicago, Glover had played a
total of 50 minutes in 10 games. He said he would make the same
decision if he had to do it over again, but he's not happy on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting the whole year to show what I can do, that
I'm healthy and that I should be here,'' Glover said Tuesday.
``It's frustrating but very humbling, too. It makes me realize that
I have to work harder and make the coach play me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has played 89 minutes in 19 games, has the same
sentiments in Philadelphia. Coach Larry Brown has praised Jones'
athleticism, fearlessness and commitment to hard work, but it has
been difficult for Jones to find playing time on a team that has
aspirations for the Eastern Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot different from what I expected, because I'm not
playing,'' Jones said. ``So, I have to control the things I can
control. I show up for practice early, work on the things that are
going to make me a better player.'' The 6-foot-7 Jones, also 21,
said he knows that as he sits the bench there's talk that he would
have been better off at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, one of my coaches said I was making a mistake leaving,
so I know people are saying it now,'' Jones said. ``But I
definitely disagree. It's one of the best jobs in America. I have
no regrets. The college game is weaker. Here, you're playing
against the best players in the world, even in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken care of my family,'' he said, ``and I have the
right frame of mind, which is to work hard to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with the money that accompanied going pro. As
the 20th pick in the draft, Glover earns $893,400 this season. Over
three years, he will make more than $3 million. Jones, the 27th
pick of the Hawks who was traded to the Sixers, makes $684,000; he
will earn $2.4 million over three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the money, I've taken care of my mom and family,'' said
Jones, who is from Camilla. ``It's the one thing in going to the
NBA that I felt I had to take advantage of. If someone thinks
taking care of his family and playing in the NBA is a mistake, then
that's his problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover and Jones have been important in each other's lives. As
two of Georgia's top high school players, they became good friends.
They talk regularly on the telephone and have served as sounding
boards for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to Dion everyday,'' Jones said. ``He feels he should be
playing more. But he's going to do like I'm doing -- keep working
hard to help make his time come. He's been my best friend all this
time, and we're kind of keeping each other's spirits up right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover said: ``Jumaine and I have been talking each other
through this. Like me, he's trying to be patient while at the same
time working hard to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Each plans to play in his team's summer league. Jones also plans
to go back to Georgia to work on his degree in sports management.
``No matter what anyone says, my future is bright,'' Jones said.
``I'm going to do what's necessary to get on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows the reason why I haven't played much?'' Glover said.
``Maybe it's not in God's plan. But I know that I'm healthy and,
when it's all said and done, I'll be one of the best to ever play
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
