<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LABONTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labonte finding winning forecasts
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte loves to travel to Atlanta, and it's not only
because of his recent domination in the Winston Cup races at
Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is a dedicated fan of the Weather Channel, headquartered
in Atlanta. Labonte watches the cable station every day, for racing
forecasts and just plain relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Weather Channel, who heard about Labonte's
fascination with weather maps and radar screens, have developed a
friendship with the No. 18 Pontiac driver.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte will be glued to the Weather Channel on the tube this
week, while he also tries to bring the thunder again at Atlanta
Motor Speedway in Sunday's race. He has won three of the past five
events at the 1.54-mile quad-oval, including November's race.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who leads the Winston Cup point standings for the first
time in his career, is considered a favorite in the Cracker Barrel
500 at 1 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no rhyme or reason for my (recent success) at Atlanta
_ I have no idea why,'' Labonte said. ``I'm not sure I want to find
out why, because it might be something that might scare me away
from (doing so well).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked AMS, and that's something I got going for
me,'' he said. ``Another thing is (that crew chief Jimmy Makar)
always comes up with a good setup for the car. Plus, we keep good
notes and fall back on them every time we're at Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather has been a major factor in the last two spring races at
AMS. The No. 18 team, partially due to Labonte's passion for the
Weather Channel, is one of the best on the circuit in being
prepared for weather changes.
</P>
<P>
   When Jim Cantore, an on-air meteorologist for the Weather
Channel, read in a magazine that it was Labonte's favorite
television channel, he contacted the driver's representatives. It
led to an invitation for a special tour of the studios several
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so cool and neat to me,'' Labonte said. ``One thing
about it: I realized that we can all stand still for a little bit,
but the weather is always changing. It was exciting to talk to Jim
and the others. Their lives revolve around the weather, like mine
does with racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Labonte left the building, he was given Weather Channel
clothes and souvenirs. As one of the top Winston Cup drivers,
Labonte rarely walks in public without being recognized. On the way
to the New Hampshire race last year, Labonte and a team member
strolled through the Baltimore airport to change planes. Both were
wearing The Weather Channel shirts and hats.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, rain was pouring, and hurricane warnings had been
posted for much of the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy stopped me and said, `Do you guys work for The
Weather Channel?' '' Labonte said with a laugh. ``I said, `Yeah,
we're hurricane hunters,' and left it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   During races, Labonte still gets the latest weather information.
Mark Cronquist, the head engine-builder for Joe Gibbs Racing, is
stationed at the radar screen located on the side of the NASCAR
trailer. It paid off for the team at Rockingham two weeks ago. The
forecast was for heavy showers, which meant most drivers ran theirs
cars as hard as they could the first half of the race because of
the possible rain.
</P>
<P>
   But Cronquist studied the radar screen and determined that the
rain would hold off for another hour or so. With Cronquist's
opinion, Labonte and Makar decided to save the car for the end of
the race. The strategy worked perfectly, and Labonte had the
strongest car over the final 40 laps to win the Dura-Lube/Kmart
400.
</P>
<P>
   It is why Labonte leads the points standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to make it through (the season),'' Labonte
said. ``There are still 31 races to go that make up this
championship. If we can just keep digging, then, hopefully, it will
pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
