<HEADLINE>
ROLSTON GLAD TO BE WITH BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Brian Rolston has been traded twice this season,
and the second time _ when he was included in the package for Ray
Bourque Monday _ came as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I was traded for Ray Bourque,'' said Rolston, a
27-year-old left winger who comes over to the Bruins from the
Colorado Avalanche. ``There are a lot of things going on here, and,
obviously, he's a Hall of Fame player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray's going to a team that can win the Stanley Cup. If any
player deserves that, it's him. They're a good team. They're going
to have a chance to win it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston came to Colorado last Nov. 3 in a trade with the New
Jersey Devils, who had selected him in the first round of the 1991
NHL draft (11th overall). He isn't familiar with the other players
the Bruins obtained _ defenseman Martin Grenier, who is playing in
the Quebec League, and center Sami Pahlsson, who is in the Swedish
Elite League _ so he can't really assess the trade, which also sent
Dave Andreychuk to Colorado and a first-round pick to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know them at all, they're young prospects,'' said
Rolston, who joins his new teammates here for a game against the
Sabres Wednesday night. ``I haven't been in training camp with
them, but seeing that Bourque and Andreychuk were involved in the
trade, they've got to be good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the speculation about a Bourque trade the past week
in Boston, Rolston and the Avalanche weren't mentioned, which is
why the deal caught him off-guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the way it happens _ if you hear the rumor, it
usually doesn't happen,'' said Rolston, who has 22 points this
season (11 goals, 11 assists), his sixth in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Rolston had a career-high 24 goals for the Devils,
but his production fell off after the first trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely a tough transition for me,'' he said. ``I
haven't put up the points this year that I did last year, although
I just started playing better the last 20 games and feeling a lot
more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to believe I can do that consistently. I had problems
adjusting to Colorado. I didn't have as strong a year as I wanted
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins coach Pat Burns remembers Rolston from his Devils days
and likes what the Bruins are getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a feisty little guy, I know that,'' Burns said. ``He'll
fit in well with this group of players. He's a hard worker. He had
some good times in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston, who is signed through next season, is delighted to be
with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to be here, first and foremost,'' he said. ``This
organization has done nice things in the past few years. I'm
looking forward to playing with them. It's a young team, it's a
very talented hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston, who has outstanding speed, is aware of the defensive
style that Burns loves to play. He saw something like it with the
Devils, who won the Stanley Cup in 1994-95, his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from a defensive hockey team, the Devils, that's
something that was always stressed, something I'm familiar with,''
said Rolston, ``and if that's the style of play, it should be good.
I play both ends of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a Stanley Cup my first year was, obviously, huge. It
was a great experience for me and, hopefully, that experience will
help me down the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
