u w BC-CLINTON-GUNS-1STLD-WR     03-07 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN CONTROL GENERATES TALK BUT LITTLE ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS 12-13th grafs, Under Hyde's ..., to correct his gun show
provisions, expand on NRA's objections; adds quote from White House
spokesman in 6th graf on McQueen meeting; clarifies chronology on
GOP's meeting with Clinton today.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the week since another child was shot to death
in an American school, there has been plenty of maneuvering on gun
control in Washington, but little movement.
</P>
<P>
   That was never more clear than Tuesday when President Clinton,
after meeting with lawmakers in a highly publicized Oval Office
session that was billed by the White House as an effort to break a
months-long impasse on gun legislation, met as well with the mother
of the slain 6-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Clinton urged Congress to shatter the
legislative stalemate and pass far-reaching gun-control provisions
before the first anniversary next month of the shootings at
Columbine High School in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past eight months, the leaders in Congress have done
virtually nothing to complete a final bill,'' Clinton said after
meeting with four key lawmakers, an event the White House labeled
an effort to broker a compromise. ``Congress has kept the American
people waiting long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, the president met with Veronica McQueen, the
mother of Kayla Renee Rolland, the girl shot last week in her
first-grade classroom in Michigan by another 6-year-old who had
brought a pistol to school.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they invited McQueen on Monday when
they heard she would be in town for a day or two to do a television
interview. ``She was in D.C., and we reached out to her for a
private meeting,'' said Jake Siewert, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time their own, largely futile session with the
president was over, the Republicans had learned he would soon be
meeting with McQueen, and they accused the president of wielding
them as an election-year prop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there to be used,'' fumed one senior House Republican
aide.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control promises to be a hot issue in the campaigns for
president and congress alike, and each party is blaming the other
for the delay in resolving the logjam.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation at issue now was passed in differing bills by
the House and the Senate last year, after rancorous debates. But
within each chamber, legislators remain deeply divided on the
provisions, especially those dealing with the regulating of gun
shows, and they have yet to reconcile those differences in
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Clinton signaled a willingness to support some
unspecified version of a compromise proposed by Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., who heads the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hyde's plan, vendors at gun shows would have up to 24
hours to conduct mandatory background checks of prospective gun
buyers. If the check turned up the possibility of a disqualifying
arrest or felony conviction, the vendors would have two additional
days to perform the checks.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association opposes even this compromise,
because gun shows are typically held on weekends only, and many
visitors travel some distance to get there. So the restriction, the
NRA argues, would all but kill the shows.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who heads the Senate Judiciary
Committee, has refused to convene the conference committee of House
and Senate negotiators until gun-control supporters relent on their
demand for a three-day waiting period on all sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put everybody together so people can shout
political epithets at each other,'' Hatch told reporters after the
meeting at the White House Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Republicans of caving in to NRA demands to
keep the conference bottled up. ``We want to lay our cards on the
table; they do not,'' said Julian Epstein, the Democratic staff
director of the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hyde and Hatch, the two ranking Democrats on the
judiciary panels, Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan and Sen.
Patrick Leahy of Vermont, attended the White House meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said he would
back a less sweeping bill that included provisions that enjoyed
broad bipartisan support, like mandatory child-safety trigger locks
on gun sales and a ban on imported large-capacity ammunition clips.
``There are some gun provisions that make good common sense,'' Lott
said.
</P>
<P>
   But White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton would oppose
legislation that failed to close what the president called ``the
gun show loophole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
