u p BC-GORE-NOMINATION-ANALY     03-07 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NOMINATION-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE METHODICALLY PICKED BRADLEY APART 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Note that this is an analysis) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Last September Al Gore's campaign was on the
verge of a nervous breakdown as the candidate suffered from a
series of stumbles on the stump and an inability to escape
President Clinton's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Watching his political dreams slip away, Gore took some drastic
action that included slashing a payroll bloated with high-paid
consultants and moving his headquarters from Washington's lobbyists
row to his native Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   He also pledged to get out of the nation's capital and mingle
more with primary voters, who at that time were increasingly
intrigued by the reformist message of ex-basketball star and former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Today, few question the health of Gore's presidential bid, which
was bolstered by Tuesday's results that virtually ensured his lock
on the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And looking ahead to the November general election, a new NBC/
Wall Street Journal poll shows that Gore has pulled even with
Republican George W. Bush in a general election matchup, wiping out
a double-digit lead the Texas governor once enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's markedly improved situation can be attributed to his own
efforts and to events out of his control, including the campaign of
GOP insurgent John McCain who drew attention away from Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it was not just superficial changes, such as moving
his headquarters to Nashville or swapping business suits for
earth-toned casual wear, that saved Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   They say that during the past six months Gore, who is capable of
boring an audience with his wooden style and technical-talk, has
become a smoother speaker and more adept campaigner, who now makes
an effort to shake hands and kiss babies.
</P>
<P>
   He also revealed a ruthless streak by savaging Bradley's marquee
proposal to provide universal health care coverage, a goal embraced
by many Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gore methodically picked apart the plan, insisting it was so
expensive that it would crowd out spending on other priorities dear
to Democrats such as education, AIDS funding, Medicare and health
care for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Sullivan, chairwoman of the New Hampshire Democratic
Party, credited Gore's tougher style for helping him rebound to
narrowly win the state's first-in-the-nation primary. Bradley never
recovered from that loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``People liked the fact that he said `I've got to change. I've
got to be tougher and I've got to be more like the candidate I was
when I ran for Congress from Tennessee and less like the vice
president,''' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   An aggressive debater, Gore used a series of face-offs with
Bradley to poke holes into his opponent's record and proposals. At
times Gore came across as too slick and prone to relying on
gimmicks, such as when he extended his hand and challenged Bradley
to pull his advertising and to debate him twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   But a key turning point in the race occurred during an Iowa
debate in January when Gore introduced a farmer in the audience and
pointed out that Bradley had voted against flood aid to the state
when he was in the Senate. Bradley did not explain his vote, which
contributed to his big loss to Gore in the state's crucial
caucuses, that kicked off the first test of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Stuart Rothenberg said that one of the
messages of the revitalized Gore campaign was that the candidate
``will do what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   While the analyst said such a combative style worked in a
Democratic primary, it might hurt in a general election by
alienating independent voters who are already turned off by
political posturing and bickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks very much like the typical politician who will do
anything and say anything to win,'' said Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   To beat Bradley the vice president also scrapped his original
plan to concentrate on Bush and spent much of the fall and early
winter stroking key Democratic constituencies _ organized labor,
minorities, abortion rights and gay rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also benefited from the surprisingly competitive
Republican race and the media's fascination with McCain, who
competed with Bradley for independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more difficult balancing acts for Gore has been his
relationship with President Clinton, who is both an asset and a
liability for the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has tried to distance himself from Clinton's
personal scandals by condemning the president's relationship with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and stressing his solid
30-year marriage with his wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Gore takes some credit for the booming economy
of the Clinton years and never fails to mention that he wants to
continue the administration's domestic and foreign policy
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gore is more likely to be haunted by some of his own
questionable campaign finance activities, particularly his visit to
an illegal fund-raiser at a Buddhist Temple during the 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have vowed to keep that controversy alive with
political ads that contain video of Gore at the temple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
