<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-07 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SOUND ADVICE FOR JETS FANS _ GET USED TO IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not only can management threaten to trade Keyshawn Johnson for a
draft choice, it can also actually do it. There might even be some
football justification for doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bill Parcells is just playing with Keyshawn's fertile
mind, trying to make him appreciative of all the good things about
playing for the Jets, whatever they happen to be. However,
contemporary sports economics says Parcells just might deal Johnson
to Baltimore because of the way Keyshawn could clog up the salary
cap if he gets what he thinks he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Keyshawn looks like a franchise player, tall and tough and
resourceful. But he is also a wide receiver, a category of player
often only as good as the man lining up behind the center.
</P>
<P>
   Star receivers are not any more valuable than dominant running
backs or linebackers. This may sound like heresy, but you can bet
this thought has crossed the mind of Parcells. Still, Keyshawn is
the most magnetic player the Jets have.
</P>
<P>
   In the best of worlds, he would remain a target for Jets
quarterbacks for the next decade, a familiar and beloved icon. The
trouble is, Keyshawn has already advertised that he will be
expensive the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   This is the other side of modern free agency. Players leave
teams. Teams leave players. It's a two-way street. In these days of
the pre-emptive strike by management _ get rid of the guy before he
gets too expensive _ there are not going to be very many venerated
locals like Ray Bourque or Dan Marino in the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was traded to Colorado on Monday night after playing 21
years of hockey with the same team. The Boston Ruins, who are not
going anywhere, made it sound as if they did Bourque a huge favor
by dealing him to a team with Stanley Cup pretensions, which, in
hockey, means about two-thirds of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Marino may go to Minnesota, where he could play first-string
quarterback, apparently no longer an option for him after 17 years
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. is the face of the future. Junior had no desire
to be the Tony Gwynn of Seattle: a lovable ancient staying put so
he would not have to go through the trouble of redecorating another
house in another baseball town.
</P>
<P>
   Junior wanted to go home to Cincinnati _ for a while, anyway _
so he forced his way out with a year left in his contract. His old
pal, Alex Rodriguez, might do the same by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't anybody stay in one place anymore?'' as Carole King
once asked.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken, 19 years in Baltimore and counting, is a throwback,
and Patrick Ewing, in his own weird way, is a throwback in New
York, even though he has the most tepid relationship with his
franchise city that you are ever likely to see.
</P>
<P>
   Today's players are mobile, which forces franchises to be
coldblooded in new and creative ways. The housecleaning in Buffalo
at the end of the season was fascinating: Thurman Thomas, Bruce
Smith, Andre Reed, gone.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, a team like the Mets could trade a young Nolan
Ryan for baseball reasons, as ghastly as those reasons turned out
to be. Nowadays, franchises move a player when he even sends out
brain waves that he is speculating about revising his contract.
</P>
<P>
   What can the fans do if the new ownership of the Jets decides to
get Keyshawn before Keyshawn gets it? The fans can look at it this
way: There is no law against wearing their green No. 19 Johnson
jerseys to the games. That still falls under the framework of the
First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Modern sports creates an almost sense of nostalgia. The
stalwarts who thrilled you last season turn out to have just been
passing through. The last 250 Islanders fans in the Nassau Coliseum
still wear their Palffy jerseys. There will be some Olerud jerseys
in Shea this season. There are Messier jerseys in Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson could be next. Why not? He has been the obvious
star of the Jets since he arrived. When they were losing, it was
easy for fans and coaches to dismiss him as a ball hog with a high
opinion of himself, but he has demonstrated his nerve as well as
his touch, and the Jets have built around him.
</P>
<P>
   He has been everything a franchise could want, but now he is
becoming expensive, and maybe even expendable. The fans can only
stop sniveling and pull out that little rectangular piece of
plastic for the season tickets. That is their job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
