<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-2NDT     03-07 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PAKISTAN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: official said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The White House statement further argued that if Clinton had
rebuffed Pakistan, he would strengthen the militant groups that
threaten to send the country into a political and economic collapse
and dishearten advocates of a secular democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Events on the subcontinent _ including the testing of nuclear
weapons by India and Pakistan in 1998 and the sharp deterioration
in their relations _ have made the nature of Clinton's trip more
difficult than when it was first contemplated some years ago as the
celebration of a new American relationship with India.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the White House stressed that the focus of Clinton's
trip, which will start in Bangladesh on March 20, remained on
India, where he will spend five days and visit five cities. The
itinerary in India is geared to spectacular backdrops _ the Taj
Mahal and possibly an elephant ride _ and to emphasizing the new
India of technology and trade.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Clinton may not venture outside the Islamabad
airport, although senior administration officials said arrangements
for the Pakistani visit were only now getting under way.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a State Department official described the tussle over
the visit as a ``fight to the finish'' between security and
anti-terrorist officials, who did not want Clinton to go, and those
who believed it was essential not to write off Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But even those who could see the benefit of Clinton's going to
Islamabad acknowledged there were problems in justifying the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the obstacles the administration had to address was the
unwillingness of the Pakistani government to outlaw Harakat
ul-Mujahedeen, a group the administration accuses of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The severest action Pakistan has taken against the group is to
place under ``house arrest'' one of its leaders, Maulana Masood
Azhar, whom India had released from jail in December as a condition
to end the hijacking of an Indian Airlines jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can spin it so we appear to have passed the test,'' an
administration official said several weeks ago, as talking points
were being composed in favor of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But on the details of Pakistan's progress toward the
administration's goals, a senior administration official who
briefed reporters Tuesday offered a poor scorecard. On democracy,
the official noted that the Constitution and provincial assemblies
remained suspended, politicians remained detained, judges had to
take loyalty oaths, and a ``road map'' to democratic rule was yet
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, the official noted a ``commitment'' by
Musharref to local elections, a lively press, some action against
corruption and the trial of the former prime minister, Sharif,
being conducted with ``due process.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to go ahead with the Pakistan visit received a
mixed reaction here.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview initiated by Lanny Davis, a lobbyist for
Pakistan and formerly a White House special counsel for Clinton,
the Pakistani ambassador, Maleeha Lodhi, said that Clinton's visit
could help ease the Kashmir dispute and slow the arms race between
India and Pakistan. ``He will be received very warmly,'' Lodhi
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a former American ambassador to Pakistan, Robert Oakley,
said that too much energy had been spent on the question of whether
Clinton should go to Pakistan rather than on what would be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Musharref is not one to back down in the face of United States
pressure,'' Oakley said. ``If he's prepared to send a message to
the Indian prime minister through Clinton privately that he's
willing to take credible steps on Kashmir,'' then the visit might
be worthwhile, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
