<SLUG> BC-PHONE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: RECASTING BELLSOUTH AS HIGH-TECH COMMUNICATIONS
PROVIDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BellSouth Corp. is introducing a campaign Thursday meant to
recast the company as a high-technology leader in an effort to
become more competitive against telecommunications and online
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications industry analysts say this is the first time
a regional Bell company has tried to turn its image into that of a
data and digital service provider. The campaign, with a budget
estimated at $35 million to $50 million, is being created by the
BellSouth corporate agency, Merkley Newman Harty in New York, a
unit of Omnicom Group. Merkley Newman won that assignment in
November after a review; previously, BellSouth divided the account
between that agency and the Atlanta office of West Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign, which will extend beyond traditional
advertising to all communications, carries the theme ``connect and
create something.'' ``The tag line is meant to convey that we can
connect people to people, and people to the information they want
when they want it, through e-mail, personal Web pages,
e-business,'' said Alan Blount, assistant vice president for
advertising at BellSouth in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a print ad promoting the service for operating a Web site
shows a fictional Web address, www.prawntoshrimp.com, superimposed
on a catch of shrimp. The text reads, ``Since 1932, gulf prawns,
4th generation shrimper, 1st generation Web business, overnight
shipping, secure transactions, 2nd boat ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   Humorous television commercials also focus on what are portrayed
as the different ways the BellSouth online services improve
customers' lives. One spot shows a 79-year-old man sitting alone on
a bench; the voice-over explains that his wife died in 1993, but
then says he remarried last year after getting e-mail and meeting a
new mate online. Another spot shows a family with three children
gathered for dinner; the father restrains one of them from
answering her telephone as the voice-over says, ``Three pagers,
five e-mail addresses, two Web sites, 160 TV channels, four cell
phones, and just one rule _ not at the dinner table.''
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor advertising conveys the same theme more simply: one
billboard, showing two smiling boys whispering to each other, says
``Chat,'' while ads created for phone kiosks merely say ``Check
voice mail'' or ``Whassssssss uuuuuppp!?''
</P>
<P>
   All ads are a radical departure from BellSouth's previous
corporate campaign, which ran from 1997 to 1999 and featured folksy
ads depicting the town of Chatsford and a BellSouth employee named
Tyler, both fictional.
</P>
<P>
   According to Blount, the new campaign is primarily directed at
adults age 18 to 49. However, William Pate, BellSouth's vice
president for advertising, marketing and public relations, said
some ads, like those created for phone kiosks, are meant for
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That group is the largest cluster since the baby boomers; they
can start and stop trends on a dime,'' he said. ``We've got to
speak to them, build their brand loyalty. We want to make the
connection as early as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The new campaign is a recognition of what's going on in the
marketplace,'' Pate added. ``Our competition is no longer AT&AMP;T,
MCI, Sprint. We now compete with Yahoo, Mindspring, AOL. We knew we
were not getting as much credit as we should for the business
applications we have in e-space. We felt our new brand effort
should be totally focused on these applications, because we were
already known for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, BellSouth's digital and data revenues jumped 33.1
percent, to $2.8 billion, out of a total of $25.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising will appear during NCAA college basketball games and
on cable networks like CNN, E and Oxygen; in daily newspapers in
the Southeast, USA Today and The Wall Street Journal; and in
magazines like Time, Vanity Fair, Inc. and Rolling Stone.
</P>
<P>
   People involved with telecommunications generally applauded
BellSouth's new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kagan, a consultant in Atlanta who advises BellSouth and
other companies, said the branding effort ``makes a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditional phone companies are perceived as stodgy, and
perception is just as important as reality,'' he added. ``The new
strategy lets them compete and thrive in a marketplace that's
become very noisy and confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Asmundson, national communications practice director for
Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP, said it was ``about time'' a regional Bell
company ran a campaign like BellSouth's, because ``they have been
letting newcomers get too much press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And BellSouth has a name that connotes trust, which is crucial
as the world becomes more connected in general'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asmundson said all Bell companies, including BellSouth, would
have to reposition themselves, a task he predicted would be quite
difficult: ``BellSouth's problem is that it is trying to go from
being your father's telephone company to a company that connects
voice and data. Standard budgets won't do it. They'll have to look
at spending more money, because it's harder for them to change the
perception of who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Another issue for BellSouth, said Brian Adamik, chief operating
officer of the Yankee Group, a telecommunications research and
consulting company in Boston, is whether ``consumers will believe
the brand can be extended, whether it's credible in the Internet
economy.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
