<HEADER>
A9773 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AFRICAN-MONEY-ART-$AD     03-07 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-MONEY-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRECIOUS AND POWERFUL ART OF THE AFRICAN COIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They look like swords, hoes, horns and armlets. But
the swords do not cut, the hoes do not weed, the horns do not sound
and the armlets _ some weighing as much as 30 pounds _ must be
unwearable. These copper, iron and gold artifacts are too dull, too
long, too short, too thin or too weighty to function the way they
look as if they should.
</P>
<P>
   But each piece has served its purpose superbly for decades, even
centuries. And today these remarkable, if mystifying, creations
tell us something about how things were bought and sold in Africa,
and probably elsewhere in the world, long before credit cards came
along.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these objects is, in fact, an example of African money.
Each is either a weapon, a farm tool, a musical instrument or a
piece of jewelry _ the things that Africans used for centuries as
barter _ or a symbol created to look like one of these artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, even though historians have not yet resolved all the
questions about where and when this money was made and used, these
powerful forms appeal increasingly to collectors. They buy them as
modernist sculpture and as symbols of life in Africa during the
last millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 15 years, spurred by exhibitions of African masks
and ceremonial sculpture in galleries and museums, collectors have
been acquiring African money. A pioneer collector, William
Greenspon, a New York psychiatrist who became an art dealer and
painter, assembled a large holding of African and other tribal
money and sold it in 1986 to the Chase Manhattan Bank. These
sculptural pieces were then displayed as art in the bank's
executive offices.
</P>
<P>
   Now both kinds of African money, mostly owned by collectors, are
going public in two exhibitions. The smaller but more important
show, ``The Artistry of African Currency,'' opens here Sunday at
the Smithsonian's National Museum of African Art and remains
through July 23. The show, the first of African money in an
American museum, includes 50 artifacts in a variety of metals and
humbler materials: cowrie shells, beads and cloth. They were
produced over the last 200 years in central, western and southern
Africa and used to buy food, medicines, goats or brides.
</P>
<P>
   The larger exhibition, ``Africa's Iron and Copper Currencies,''
is on view in Manhattan this month in the Low Memorial Library at
Columbia University. The 200 items are from the collection of
Philip Gould, an emeritus professor of art history at Sarah
Lawrence College and the show's curator. The people who made the
pieces are identified, but the works are not explained.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, as the brochure for the show in Washington points
out, African metal money was modeled on bartered objects and
retained its intrinsic worth because the metal could be melted down
or recycled into other forms. Gold was reserved for precious
objects, like the show's fifth- and sixth-century coins from the
Aksumite Kingdom in present-day Ethiopia and the huge
crescent-shaped earrings made in the mid-20th century by the Fulani
people of Mali. Dauntingly large as jewelry, the earrings remain
worth their weight in gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scarcity of copper in Africa might have made the raw metal
a medium of exchange on that basis alone,'' said Lydia Puccinelli,
the curator of the show. But the metal's value was increased when
it was transformed into objects like the giant-size anklets made by
the Mbole people of the country now known as Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Other copper works worn as jewelry include the hefty bracelets
cast by the Igbo people of Nigeria to look like twisted rope and
the lethal-looking spherical neck rings made by the Yoruba.
Nigerians also produced the more delicate copper-wire bundles that
look like hanks of hay. From Congo come the arresting X-shaped
ingots called Katanga crosses, named after the place where they
have been made since at least 1400.
</P>
<P>
   Iron, found almost everywhere in Africa, was considered more
valuable if it was refined and forged into distinct shapes. The
most impressive iron pieces are the currency blades _ leaflike
forms, as tall as six feet_ that the Turumbu people of central
Africa modeled after medieval swords.
</P>
<P>
   The Kuba people of Congo continue to use these blades as
symbolic currency in dowries, but in a reverse of practice in the
West, the groom or his family compensates the bride's family for
the loss of her services. The most striking gift of all would have
been a field filled with enormous iron staves.
</P>
<P>
   Kissi pennies, one of the least valuable of African currencies,
are the loveliest of all. The twisted iron rods, 12 to 15 inches in
length, look like long-stemmed anemones by Giacometti.
</P>
<P>
   The Kissi artisans in Liberia called the rods coins with soul:
if a penny was broken, the Kissi people insisted that it not be
circulated again until it was repaired by a blacksmith, who would
restore its soul. These pennies continued to be used throughout
Liberia and Sierra Leone into the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   African money was always an extremely valuable commodity, which
the colonial powers sought to make profitable for themselves. In
the 15th century, the Portuguese took examples of the copper-rod
money used in Angola to Europe to be duplicated. Then, when they
returned to Africa, they used the copies in trading with the
Angolans.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, the British followed suit, copying the Nigerian
iron money that took the form of open ringlets called manillas. The
copies were used in trade in Nigeria well into the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last decade or so, we've come to know an enormous
amount about African money,'' Puccinelli said. ``The interest is
there for all of us to find out a great deal more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
