<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FUDDY-MEERS-THEATER-A     03-07 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUDDY-MEERS-THEATER-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE HUMOR AND THE HOPE IN FRACTURED LIVES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Milton Academy, a boarding school near Boston
where he was a scholarship student, David Lindsay-Abaire got
heavily involved in one of those super-geeky extracurricular
activities that one is apt to look back on later with a mix of
pride and red-faced horror.
</P>
<P>
   It was called ``speech team.'' It required the young man _ known
simply as David Abaire then _ to travel to other high schools and
do combat in such exotic competitions as ``humorous interp,'' in
which the contestants had to memorize every part in a 10-minute
excerpt of a play and perform them all in character before a panel
of judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd go into a classroom, you'd explain what the synopsis was
and then you'd do your piece,'' Lindsay-Abaire recalled recently,
sitting in a Starbucks in Brooklyn Heights and looking suddenly
aghast at having volunteered this biographical tidbit. Scores were
awarded, and the teenager from working-class South Boston did well
enough to enter the nationals in Nashville. ``I think I finished
fourth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who has seen his verbally acrobatic new
comedy, ``Fuddy Meers,'' at the Minetta Lane Theater in Greenwich
Village would understand why the judges might have rewarded him. As
the seemingly nonsensical title suggests, the play is filled with
shards of broken speech uttered by fractured characters who would
have served the author well in the days of humorous interp.
</P>
<P>
   And he is doing well by them these days. Writing in The New York
Times, Ben Brantley called the play ``dark, sweet and thoroughly
engaging'' and likened the playwright to ``a resourceful chef who
turns leftovers into haute cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when ``Fuddy Meers'' opened in November at the Manhattan
Theater Club, before its recent transfer to a commercial Off
Broadway theater, Lindsay-Abaire earned the kind of freshman
notices that might have turned a young writer's head, were he not
so awestruck by the experience. ``I was out of my mind petrified,''
said the 30-year-old playwright, who lives in Brooklyn with his
wife, Chris Lindsay, an actress (and thus the hyphenated last
name). ``Getting a play produced at all was such a huge mountain.
It feels like it has nothing to do with me. It's like winning the
lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   The luck of the draw, though, it really wasn't. Having secured a
spot in a highly selective playwriting program at the Juilliard
School, where he wrote under the tutelage of Marsha Norman and
Christopher Durang from 1996 to 1998, Lindsay-Abaire has been given
every opportunity to succeed at a profession with a terrifying
casualty rate.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has he become an overnight member of the nonprofit
arena _ the Manhattan Theater Club is considering his next play,
``Wonder of the World,'' for its main stage next season _ but he is
also under contract to a major film company, Fox 2000, to come up
with scripts, including one for the actor Hugh Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supporting myself, for the first time, as a playwright,''
Lindsay-Abaire said. ``It's too bad that you have to get a
commercial run for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuddy Meers'' owes a debt to the screwball tradition of
American comedy and to some modern comic writers, like Durang, who
have stretched the form to contemporary contours. The play revolves
around an amnesiac, Claire (J. Smith-Cameron), whose memory is
erased each time she sleeps, and the wild shenanigans of the people
in her life, among them a profane, aphasic mother (Marylouise
Burke), a sullen son (Keith Nobbs) and an ex-convict (John
Christopher Jones) who expresses himself through a sock puppet,
Hinky Binky.
</P>
<P>
   Many silly things happen in the course of ``Fuddy Meers'' _ the
words, significantly, are two of the many that the mother, a stroke
victim, distorts (``funny mirrors''). But at the heart of the play
is a rather poignant examination of Claire's predicament, and the
idea that in the endless cycle of her learning and forgetting,
hope, for those who love her, is a renewable resource.
</P>
<P>
   It was in his own discovery of the romance of amnesia, if you
will, that Lindsay-Abaire first thought he might have a play. ``It
started with this amnesia case I heard of on a news program,'' he
said. ``About a woman who, as soon as she fell asleep, her memory
was gone.'' After scouring books about neurological disorders, he
had what might be called a playwright's epiphany: ``I thought,
`What a convenient device to get out exposition.'''
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear family of ``Fuddy Meers'' is typically
American-neurotic; crazy and yet crazily devoted to one another.
But Lindsay-Abaire insists that in its particulars it is nothing
like the one in which he grew up, a family of five he describes as
``very blue collar.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother is a factory worker and his father, now retired, sold
fruit out of the back of a truck. Both of his parents, he said,
were supportive of his attempts to write, which began at Milton
with some ``terrible, terrible plays'' that he composed as a result
of a school tradition of putting on original shows.
</P>
<P>
   At Sarah Lawrence College, where he majored in theater, he
continued to churn them out, and though his work was produced
there, ``nobody said, `Yes! You're a writer. Come with me.''' After
graduation he moved to New York, where he landed a job in arts
administration at Dance Theater Workshop, continued writing and had
some of his plays produced in Off Off Broadway theaters like the
SoHo Rep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really write plays to entertain myself,'' he said. But he is
also entertained by audacity. When people said they were made
uncomfortable by a stroke victim as a comic figure, he felt
compelled to forge ahead. ``I didn't think, `I want someone to talk
funny,''' he said. ``I wanted characters who were damaged and
viewed the world in skewed, warped ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
