<SLUG> BC-GORE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE GREETS VICTORY IN THE TOWN THAT TURNED HIS CAMPAIGN AROUND
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore, in a triumphant
return Tuesday to his campaign headquarters in the shadow of Music
City's gleaming skyline, couldn't resist a dig at the critics who
had dismissed his move here as a crass political stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that idea to move to Nashville was a gimmick,'' Gore
quipped sarcastically as hundreds of volunteers welcomed him home
to celebrate one of the biggest political triumphs in a career that
began in 1976 with his election to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's decision last October to move his presidential campaign
headquarters from Washington's lobbyist-infested K Street to the
capital of his home state of Tennessee marked the turning point in
a White House bid that had stumbled through most of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In moving to Nashville, Gore was able to streamline an
organization that had grown top-heavy with high-priced consultants
and to energize his campaign with only the most committed workers
and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the process of moving ``from K Street to the K Mart,'' as
he phrased it, he remade himself as a candidate, shedding the
trappings of the vice presidency and his trademark blue suits,
reaching out to voters in open meetings in a casual, more personal
way.
</P>
<P>
   He also trained his political sights on his challenger, former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, and picked apart the Bradley
candidacy with precision. He prevented him from wooing away any of
the core Democratic constituencies _ blacks, Jews, union members
and gays _ while holding together the more conservative ``New
Democratic'' coalition built by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two days of campaigning before the Super Tuesday
primaries, Gore appeared before some of the most loyal Democratic
voters. He met with Jewish leaders and gay activists in New York on
Monday and dropped by a union rally in Nashville on Tuesday before
retiring to a downtown hotel to watch the election returns.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he squeezed in a trip to St. Louis for a rally
Monday night, a final push to sweep even Bradley's native state of
Missouri in the closest thing the United States has ever had to a
national presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking a single vote for granted,'' he told reporters
on Air Force Two en route from St. Louis to Nashville. ``I'm not
looking beyond Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   But in recent days, Gore has stepped up his attacks on Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, who clinched the Republican presidential
nomination Tuesday, in a clear indication of his confidence in
winning the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And he has heaped praise on Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the GOP
challenger who has excited independent voters this year with his
promises to reform the political campaign finance process.
</P>
<P>
   Gore plans to travel Wednesday to Michigan, an important swing
state in the general election and one where McCain defeated Bush in
the GOP primaries on the strength of independent voters who swamped
the political machine of Republican Gov. John Engler, a staunch
Bush backer.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore has also sought to soothe any hard
feelings on the part of Bradley supporters, repeatedly expressing
his admiration for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences between Senator Bradley and myself are nothing
compared to the differences between both of us as Democrats, on the
one hand, and both of the Republicans on the other hand,'' Gore
told an audience over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
