<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-NEWYORK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK REPUBLICANS FAVOR BUSH, BUT INDEPENDENTS SWING TOWARD
McCAIN  
(sw) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among New York voters responding to exit polls,
patterns seen in earlier Republican contests appeared to be holding
on Tuesday, with self-identified Republicans supporting Gov. George
W. Bush, while a wave of independents favored Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The exit poll was taken from a sample of 561 Republican and 707
Democratic voters and conducted by Voter News Service, a consortium
made up of television networks and The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to viewpoints on the heated Republican contest,
political analysts predicted that the Democratic race in New York
was likely to be just an echo of the ringing of former Sen. Bill
Bradley's death knell. A New York Times/CBS poll taken two weeks
ago showed Vice President Al Gore widening his lead to
26-percentage points over Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The New York primary is one of the most important contests on
what has been dubbed ``Super Tuesday.'' At stake are 243 Democratic
delegates and 101 Republican delegates.
</P>
<P>
   In the five weeks preceding Tuesday's contests, upset victories
for McCain in New Hampshire and Michigan have made the Republican
race one of the most closely watched in recent memory. McCain has
painted himself as an establishment outsider, a war hero espousing
campaign reform and denouncing the straight-and-narrow arbiters of
American politics. But in recent contests, Bush has appropriated
that rebel image to some extent and used it to successfully woo
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Tuesday's early exit polls, a third of the registered
Republicans in New York who voted for McCain's delegates identified
themselves as independent, and less than a fifth of Bush's
supporters described themselves that way.
</P>
<P>
   Three-fifths of the voters who preferred Bush were conservative,
and less than a third called themselves moderate, according to the
exit polls. About two-fifths of McCain's supporters described
themselves as conservative, and the same percentage called
themselves moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters were less inclined to favor abortion rights
than those who voted for McCain's delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a third of those who preferred McCain had never voted in
a Republican primary before. Less than 20 percent of Bush's
supporters were new to the Republican primaries, the exit polls
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's supporters named campaign finance and moral values as
the issues that most influenced their vote. Bush's supporters
selected moral values and taxes as the issue with the strongest
influence on their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Half of McCain's supporters said the fact that he ``stands up
for what he believes'' was the quality that mattered most in their
vote decision, followed by strong leader. Almost two-fifths of
Bush's supporters said he ``best represents conservative values,''
and a quarter said he stands up for what he believes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's voter turnout in New York was larger than the usual 20
to 25 percent of registered voters. The warm weather was partly
responsible, as was the highly publicized neck-and-neck race
between Bush and McCain. That heated contest has drawn out a record
number of voters in earlier primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates threw themselves into last-minute campaigning
in New York with full determination. Bush flew to Long Island and
attended a staged panel discussion on breast cancer in an effort to
appeal to women voters. At a Wall Street rally, McCain attacked his
opponent's chief patrons in this state, Gov. George Pataki and
William D. Powers, the New York Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders had joined Bush in lobbying to keep
McCain off the ballot. They pushed for enforcement of obscure
campaign rules that made it more difficult for supporters of
Republican candidates other than Bush to collect nominating
signatures. But McCain won public sympathy, and a federal judge
placed McCain and another candidate, Alan Keyes, on the Republican
ballot in early February. McCain spent nearly $200,000 to get on
the ballot in 19 districts.
</P>
<P>
   But New York was deemed a tough battleground for McCain. In
states with open Republican primaries, McCain has won support from
voters labeling themselves independents or Democrats. In New York,
the Republican primary is closed to voters not affiliated with the
party. And even though New York lacks large numbers supporting a
strong religious right, a faction that helped pushed Bush to
victory in South Carolina, some voters said that McCain's recent
religious criticism swayed them toward his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Catholic and I know darn well that Bush is not
anti-Catholic,'' said Vincent Mauro, a Brooklyn retiree. ``That was
dirty pool. I had mixed feelings about who to vote for but those
comments really bothered me. I decided to stick with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race has failed to inspire the strong feelings
that characterize the Republican contest. While many people regard
Bradley as a lost cause, Gore apparently still has to overcome his
wooden image among some voters. Joyce Liona, for instance, a
registered Democrat in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, said she reluctantly
voted for the vice-president on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to put my faith in something,'' she said. ``Honestly,
I like McCain, and I wish he wasn't a Republican. Gore has no
charisma. I can't even remember sometimes what Gore looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's supporters, Hillary Rodham Clinton, showed up at 7
a.m. at Douglas Grafflin Elementary School in Chappaqua in
Westchester County cast her vote. Clinton, a Democratic candidate
for the U.S. Senate seat from New York, was the 11th person to vote
at the precinct. The school is within two miles of the house that
she and President Clinton recently bought.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City,
who is Mrs. Clinton's Republican opponent in the Senate race,
strode into a high school on Manhattan's Upper East Side and cast
his vote. Giuliani threw his allegiance to Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
