<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ARGENTINA-ECON-ART-2T     03-07 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-ECON-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PRESIDENT INTRODUCES BIG ECONOMIC CHANGES FOR ARGENTINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT24, 25 and 26 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ When President Fernando de la Rua took
office nearly three months ago, the unemployment rate stood at a
stubbornly high 14 percent. Consumer demand remained sluggish.
Shantytowns were spreading. And manufacturers seemed to be jumping
over each other to relocate to Brazil where labor was cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   That bleak picture has not changed much.
</P>
<P>
   But since his Dec. 10 inauguration, De la Rua has shown himself
to be an activist who will put the economy before all other issues.
Whether his actions will be sufficient to repair Argentina's
economy remains a big question, but even his critics say they are
surprised by the vigorous pace of reform from the president, who
dared to suggest that he was a boring fellow in a signature
television advertisement during his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In his first month in office, De la Rua rammed a new budget and
tax package through Congress, slicing this year's fiscal deficit by
more than half and silencing rumors of an impending devaluation.
Then, he reached an unexpectedly generous $7.4 billion loan
agreement with the International Monetary Fund that has allowed the
country to swap bonds for new debt at lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   He succeeded in lowering fuel prices, highway tolls and railroad
freight prices. He ordered raids on tax-evading businesses in order
to raise revenue and relieve law-abiding companies of unfair
competition. He tightened the revenue flow to five provinces that
were virtually bankrupt, forcing them to become more financially
responsible. Declaring a national economic emergency, he has begun
to trim the bloated government bureaucracy. He started by
dismissing one-third of his intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, De la Rua faced down a threatened strike by the
nation's largest labor confederation, opening the way for enactment
of a new labor code designed to reduce the bargaining power of
labor unions and help businesses more easily hire and fire new
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an anxious man,'' De la Rua said in his monotone,
displaying a thin, stern smile during a recent interview at the
Casa Rosada presidential palace. ``I like things done quickly,
without delay. But we are definitely on our way.'' He put
Argentina's economic predicament in simple terms, saying, ``If you
ask me what is my chief concern in a word, that word is
`competitiveness.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reducing business costs and expanding exports are urgent tasks
if South America's second biggest economy _ one with 37 million
consumers that last year had a gross domestic product of $285
billion and $5 billion in imports from the United States _ is to
recoup the high expectations of only a few years ago. The 3 percent
growth rate that most economists expect this year may sound good,
but the economy declined last year by 3 percent in the aftermath of
the Asian and Russian financial crises and the January 1999
Brazilian devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 manufacturing firms have moved to Brazil in recent
months, seeking lower labor costs and offers of tax breaks and
other government subsidies. After Tupperware, Goodyear Tire and
Rubber and Royal Philips Electronics closed factories outside
Buenos Aires _ all decided it was better to supply the Argentine
market from Brazil _ one local business magazine ran the cover
banner headline of ``Bye, Bye Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine auto and auto-parts industries, once seen as an
economic juggernaut that would profit handsomely from a growing
Brazilian market, are barely holding on after suffering a 33
percent loss of production and a 59 percent fall in exports last
year. General Motors, Ford Motor and Fiat are all transferring
production to Brazil, and with negotiations between Buenos Aires
and Brasilia to revamp the MERCOSUR trade union bogged down, big
layoffs are probably inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Two deep recessions in the last five years have dimmed the
memories of the go-go years of the early 1990s. At that time,
Argentina became the favored emerging market of Wall Street
following a series of privatizations and a decision to link the
historically unstable peso one-to-one with the dollar. But the
policy, which was initiated by former President Carlos Saul Menem
to end years of hyperinflation, has tied Argentina to a strong
dollar and rising U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Argentine interest rates, which start at 8 percent,
are totally out of proportion with the country's negative inflation
rate of 2 percent last year. When Brazil devalued its currency by
40 percent just over a year ago, making Argentine exports to Brazil
far more expensive, there was no monetary policy card for Buenos
Aires to play.
</P>
<P>
   What cards the new Argentine leader has played have not received
universal approval. Some economists say De la Rua's move to
increase government revenue by $2.6 billion through higher income
and sales taxes and to eliminate tax loopholes for private health
care, transportation and entertainment may have pleased the IMF,
but will only slow the economy. And once the tax increases begin to
be felt by consumers, the economists say, De la Rua could suffer
losses during a congressional election next year that would hurt
his effectiveness in the last three years of his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still haven't taken into account the distorting tax
structure that costs Argentina competitiveness _ especially the
high taxes on diesel and high payroll taxes,'' said Domingo
Cavallo, the former economy minister who devised the plan to peg
Argentina's currency to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   And few analysts see any progress in the effort by De la Rua to
reinvigorate the MERCOSUR trade union and end a year of disputes
with Brazil over sugar, chickens, textiles, shoes and motor
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, De la Rua and his aides predict that their early
fiscal moves will stimulate bond and stock market rallies and
produce strong growth in the second half of this year. They note
that Standard &AMP; Poor's recently revised its view on the Argentine
economy from ``negative'' to ``stable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people have doubts,'' said Economy Minister Jose Luis
Machinea, the chief architect of De la Rua's economic policies.
``But you can quote me on this: This economy will grow a minimum of
4 percent this year.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The government's optimistic view is based in part on a nascent
boom in high technology and the growing number of local Internet
companies. The complete deregulation of the telecommunications
industry, begun under the previous government, promises to lower
business telephone and computer costs significantly by the end of
the year. Meanwhile, rising agricultural commodity prices and the
strengthening of the Brazilian currency as Brazil's economy expands
should improve Argentine export earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our eyes are focused on growth and whether we will be
competitive or not,'' Machinea said. ``How do you reduce business
costs? You reduce the country risk ratings and interest rates, then
you lower labor expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   And officials continue to voice cautious optimism that they can
fix relations with Brazil. ``If there is a war of subsidies, all
our peoples will lose from the costs of expanding fiscal
deficits,'' said Foreign Minister Adalberto Rodriguez Giavarini.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The crown jewel of the De la Rua economic policy is his labor
reform, which passed the lower house of Congress on Feb. 25. The
legislation would increase the probationary period mandated by law
for new workers to six months from the current 30 days, giving
companies more time to terminate an employee without paying
severance. It would lower the payroll tax rate for new hires to 12
percent from 18 percent. It would eliminate a rule that obliges
companies to retain old contracts if negotiations fail, a reform
that would prohibit union leaders from protecting anachronistic
work rules by refusing to negotiate in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, the new labor code would take away the
power of national union leaders to determine salaries and working
conditions across entire industries, allowing smaller and newer
companies to bargain their own terms rather than having to pay the
same salaries as large, established firms.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the labor code in the Senate, senior De la Rua aides
predict, would give the new administration the momentum to further
reduce business costs by deregulating the health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to be boring before he became president, but now he is
having fun,'' said Eduardo Elsztain, chairman of IRSA and Cresud,
Argentina's largest real estate and farm companies. ``He's making
the right moves.''
</P>
<P>
   But most business leaders, particularly those in the
manufacturing sector who are straining to compete with Brazil, are
skeptical that De la Rua's policies will be sufficient to quickly
return Argentina to the 6 and 7 percent growth rates they had
become accustomed to before last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Ganimian, owner of the Oxigeno shoe company, said he was
happy about De la Rua's labor reforms, and that the expected 10
percent decrease in his labor costs would enable him to add 10
employees to his staff of 80 at a factory outside Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   But Ganimian said that as much as he would like to build a new
factory and double his work force, he felt constrained because of
the competitive disadvantage he continued to suffer in relation to
Brazilian shoe producers who pay their workers one-third the wage
an Argentine shoemaker earns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to expand and export,'' Ganimian added, ``but I can't
put my capital on a roulette wheel.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pablo Piqueras, a director of Casa Pi-Ro SA, a medical supply
company with $20 million in annual sales, said he applauded De la
Rua's early moves but that he and his partners were still giving
serious consideration to closing their plant in the city of La
Plata and dismissing 150 workers. For the first time in its 70-year
history, the company granted a vacation to all of its factory
workers in February and suspended production for three weeks to
reduce an inventory backlog.
</P>
<P>
   Piqueras said it was impossible to compete with the flood of
cheap Korean and Chinese syringes in recent years, and Brazilian
officials were offering a package of tax-breaks and subsidized
loans to relocate to Brazil. ``I'm an Argentine, and I would like
to believe in my county's future,'' he said, ``but if there is no
national policy to save us and we can't compete, its time to
move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
