<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: AIRLINES TRY TO DEAL WITH PASSENGER RAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Fla., Calif.)  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
(bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How serious a threat is air rage?
</P>
<P>
   Federal statistics show that reports of violent or disruptive
passengers _ known as air rage incidents _ have risen sharply in
recent years, but that may just be a consequence of better
reporting. The 1999 OAG Business Travel Lifestyle Survey, polling
thousands of frequent business fliers, found that 40 percent of
them witnessed an incident of ``verbal or physical abuse'' in the
air last year. Two percent said that their flights were diverted
because of an unruly fellow passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even flight attendants acknowledge that some air rage
reports include verbal disputes that in the past airline employees
would have shrugged off instead of literally making federal cases
out of them. But mounting anecdotal evidence suggests that physical
and verbal incidents that would be defined as violent by any
sensible person are in fact increasing.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, safety experts say, those situations can be made
worse by well-meaning fellow passengers who decide to become
involved.
</P>
<P>
   For an example, let's examine what happened two years ago aboard
a US Airways flight from Los Angeles to Baltimore when a handful of
interfering passengers contributed to a melee that left a flight
attendant seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   A passenger, a 200-pound 21-year-old college football player,
began wandering up the aisle, ``blessing'' other passengers by
tapping them on the head with a pillow.
</P>
<P>
   A flight attendant, Renee Sheffer, 34, who had seen just about
everything in 15 years on the job, approached the young man and
gently coaxed him toward an empty seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sit down and shut up!'' a male passenger a few rows back
suddenly shouted, adding some profanities that caused the young man
to become agitated. A few other passengers joined in.
</P>
<P>
   ``His demeanor then became very aggressive,'' Sheffer recalled.
``He said he had to go up to the front of the airplane now and
bless the pilot because now the plane was going to crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a small incident now loomed as a bigger one. ``We had
the situation under control, but then comes the macho man, `I'm
going to deal with this!''' Sheffer said. ``It's just like a fuse
on a bomb. Outside stimuli from the passengers really set him
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffer and another flight attendant ultimately led the man back
to the rear of the plane. But then, she said, ``another macho guy
yelled at us to get the guy in a seat or he would do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The disturbed man wheeled, grabbed her and tossed her into a
bulkhead. A five-minute struggle ensued before the man was
restrained with plastic handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you imagine me at 5-foot-5 and 114 pounds tying up this
200-pound running back, it's kind of amusing in hindsight,''
Sheffer said. Of course, the internal bleeding and the surgery for
knee and shoulder injuries were not so funny, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The assailant was convicted of federal assault charges and given
probation. But Sheffer and her husband, Mike Sheffer, a television
engineer, thought that what she had encountered was just the tip of
a problem the airline industry had ignored for too long.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheffers, who live in Gastonia, N.C., began the Skyrage
Foundation to focus more attention on the safety threat posed by
violent or otherwise disruptive passengers. The last two years,
Sheffer has managed a Web site, www.skyrage.org, that assiduously
archives news reports of violent or disruptive passengers
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheffers were in Los Angeles on Tuesday taking part in a
seminar on violent and disruptive passengers at the annual Aircraft
Cabin Safety Symposium sponsored by the Southern California Safety
Institute. In April, the Air Line Pilots Association will
co-sponsor what it calls the International Aviation Security
Academy in Orlando, Fla. Designed for flight crews and other
aviation professionals, it will be a four-day series of courses on
handling in-cabin safety threats.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffer says he believes that airline passengers in general,
and especially business travelers, also should be giving some
thought to the topic, since the more frequently you fly the more
likely you are to encounter some kind of air rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers have to understand it's a whole different world on
an airplane,'' he said. ``It's not like getting in a taxicab or a
bus. On a plane, when something goes wrong, it can have a domino
effect and a bad situation can snowball into a catastrophic
situation. You're stuck in that aluminum tube, zipping along at 400
miles an hour; there's nowhere to run, nowhere to hide. You can't
call the cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Planes are impossibly crowded, flying is vexing, some passengers
are cranky, and some flight attendants can get snippy. Shrug it off
as the price of getting from here to there in a hurry, Sheffer
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even reasonable people are going to have arguments,'' he said.
``But one thing that passengers and air crews both need to keep in
mind is an aircraft in flight is not the place or the time. Wait
till you're on the ground, because once that door is closed, not
only have you sealed the problem inside the aircraft, you've also
sealed out the resources that can help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      03-07 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: AIRLINES TRY TO DEAL WITH PASSENGER RAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Fla., Calif.)  (duplication warning: also sent with `f' code) 
(bl) 
