<P>
   But Sheffer says he believes that airline passengers in general,
and especially business travelers, also should be giving some
thought to the topic, since the more frequently you fly the more
likely you are to encounter some kind of air rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passengers have to understand it's a whole different world on
an airplane,'' he said. ``It's not like getting in a taxicab or a
bus. On a plane, when something goes wrong, it can have a domino
effect and a bad situation can snowball into a catastrophic
situation. You're stuck in that aluminum tube, zipping along at 400
miles an hour; there's nowhere to run, nowhere to hide. You can't
call the cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Planes are impossibly crowded, flying is vexing, some passengers
are cranky, and some flight attendants can get snippy. Shrug it off
as the price of getting from here to there in a hurry, Sheffer
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even reasonable people are going to have arguments,'' he said.
``But one thing that passengers and air crews both need to keep in
mind is an aircraft in flight is not the place or the time. Wait
till you're on the ground, because once that door is closed, not
only have you sealed the problem inside the aircraft, you've also
sealed out the resources that can help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
