<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: 2 VICTORS, REDEFINED IN DIFFERENT WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With ELN-RDP) 
(jt) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a year of remarkable political tumult, one party ended up
where it started Tuesday, with the nominee it had expected to have,
and the other found its outlook substantially if not decisively
altered.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who began as a seeming shoo-in for the
Democratic presidential nomination, survived a patch so shaky that
even some of his staff members made fun of him. He moved his
headquarters from Washington to Nashville, to more derisive
catcalls, and pulled his ragged operation together with
considerable skill.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in the closest approximation the nation has ever had to
a national primary, he utterly humiliated his rival, former Senator
Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who had looked for a time last year
like the freshest of political faces. Bradley lost on the Atlantic
Coast, on the Pacific coast and in between _ even in Missouri,
where he grew up, and in New York, where he won fame and fortune
playing basketball for the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bravura performance by the vice president, if no longer
surprising in view of the near-collapse of Bradley's campaign in
recent weeks, and it positioned him well for the battle against the
eventual Republican nominee this fall, although perhaps situated
somewhat farther to the left on some key issues than he had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Even on health care, which Bradley had made his signature issue,
most voters said they believed Gore had outlined a batter plan.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas moved much
closer to the presidential nomination, defeating or contending
closely with Senator John McCain of Arizona everywhere but New
England, a region as out of step with the rest of the country in
2000 as the South was a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   What came before Tuesday was mere skirmishing, in the long view.
If not McCain's Appomattox, the Super Tuesday voting seemed likely
to prove his Gettysburg. The wide lead seized by Bush in the
delegate count gave him a commanding position at the campaign's
most significant moment.
</P>
<P>
   Now the governor can look forward with confidence to a day, next
Tuesday, when his own state as well as Florida, where his brother,
Jeb, is the governor, choose their delegates. As they were in
Tuesday's Republican primary and caucus voting in 13 states, the
numbers at stake will be significant: Texas is the nation's
second-largest state and Florida is the fourth-largest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also began the campaign as a heavy favorite. But he
suffered serious setbacks in New Hampshire and Michigan as McCain
mounted an unexpectedly potent insurgency, and he veered sharply to
the right in South Carolina in a successful effort to head off the
Arizonan.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Bush, who had originally presented himself as a
candidate who could appeal to all voters, regardless of party,
found himself redefined as a Republican partisan with little
backing among Democrats, independents and moderate Republicans _
without whom he would have little chance in November.
</P>
<P>
   Again in Tuesday's balloting, Republicans voted heavily for Bush
while Democrats and independents voted for McCain. The pattern was
much the same as in each test since New Hampshire: who won in many
states depended heavily on the proportion of independents and
Democrats in the electorate. The more there were (as in
Massachusetts) the better McCain did; the fewer there were (as in
Ohio), the worse.
</P>
<P>
   If, as now seems highly likely, he moves on to win the
nomination, Bush will have to find a way to remedy this problem. He
has tried hard since South Carolina, without success; his senior
advisers are already deep in discussions about fresh notions of how
to renew his appeal to voters in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, most politicians believe, emerged from the campaign a
weaker candidate than he began it, scuffed by McCain's attacks, and
with a party badly split between conservatives and moderates. Gore
emerged as a stronger, more vivid campaigner, with a relatively
united party.
</P>
<P>
   One hopeful sign for Bush came among Roman Catholics. McCain
sharply criticized leaders of the Republican right in a speech in
Virginia late last month, hoping, aides said, that Catholics and
others in northern states who resent Christian conservatives would
rally to him. But according to exit polls in Missouri and Ohio, in
each of which Catholics accounted for a quarter of the electorate,
Bush received half their votes or more.
</P>
<P>
   Gore kept intact a political pattern that went largely unnoticed
in the weeks when his reputation waned, then waxed once more. No
sitting vice president since World War II who sought the
presidential nomination has failed to gain it, except for Alben W.
Barkley of Kentucky, Harry Truman's number 2, who attracted little
support in 1952, largely, it was said, because of his age. He was
then 74.
</P>
<P>
   Although he will no doubt be considered the favorite at first,
especially considering the blood-letting that has taken place in
the Republican primaries for the third campaign running, Gore faces
problems of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Like his mentor, President Clinton, he has put tremendous effort
into courting the voters of California, and he has built a strong
following there. But in Tuesday's so-called beauty contest in the
Golden State, there was a small note of warning.
</P>
<P>
   He and Bradley together polled considerably fewer votes than
Bush and McCain together. That may have resulted in part from the
fact that the Republican campaign was the more gripping one, but it
also suggested that Gore has work to do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
