<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WOMEN-MENTOR-NYT &LR;      03-07 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MENTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THEY SAY, A GOOD MENTOR IS HARD TO FIND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DYLAN LOEB McCLAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a clash of management styles, and Tami Sue Keller did not
know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Keller had been put in charge of strategic planning for natural
gas transmission and storage for Consumers Energy in Jackson, Mich.
A Type A personality, she was bubbling with ideas for shaking her
department up. But first she had to sell the innovations to her
fellow managers.
</P>
<P>
   That would be no easy task, but she knew one man could make it
happen: her boss, who has been around the industry and commanded
her colleagues' instant respect. The problem was, he was a Type B
personality who favored a low-key, deliberative approach that would
surely delay the changes she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   So Keller, 33, turned to her mentor, a scholarly looking older
man with more than 20 years in the energy business. She turned to
her father, Gerald A. Abood, 55, a senior director at the Wisconsin
Electric Power Co. in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   His advice was straightforward. ``He told me to lay out the
benefits and the needs and the consequences of not taking an action
_ and to create a feedback loop to the boss after you have
established what needs to be done,'' she said. The advice paid off,
and the two began setting goals and working together to achieve
them.
</P>
<P>
   Every young manager needs a mentor. Despite a mountain of
management tomes out there _ more than 6,400 at last count,
according to R.R. Bowker's Books in Print _ a landmark study of
mentoring in the Harvard Business Review in 1979 established that
nothing beats the human touch for learning how to navigate the
shoals of workplace politics.
</P>
<P>
   But for women, relative newcomers to the ranks of the nation's
19 million managers, it is not always easy to find an in-house
tutor. ``Unfortunately, because the people at the top are still
usually white men, they tend to mentor other white men,'' said
Jennifer Allyn, director of research and advisory services for
Catalyst, a nonprofit research organization in New York that works
to advance women in business. She cited a recent Catalyst survey in
which 47 percent of minority women and 29 percent of white women
said lack of a mentor was a major barrier to advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have tried to fill the void. Six years ago,
Procter &AMP; Gamble created a program called Mentor-Up that pairs
young women with older managers. A New York-based company called
Women Unlimited provides mentoring and educational services to
women who are managers.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, finding a mentor remains a largely ad hoc process. For
many women, the surest bet is to tap the expertise of older men who
would never dream of giving them the brushoff: their fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Allyn's father, John S. Wilcha, is chief executive of Old London
Foods, in the Bronx, and she definitely considers him a mentor. ``I
wasn't particularly interested in his career when I was growing
up,'' she said. ``But then I got this job at Catalyst, and suddenly
I had a lot more questions for him at the dinner table.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller's father, Abood, who oversees a staff of 55, has been
answering questions for a long time. When he and his wife divorced
in 1977, he took custody of their four daughters, then ages 6 to
11. Much like Lewis E. Platt, the former chief executive of Hewlett
Packard who raised his two daughters after his wife died, Abood
quickly gained an appreciation of what girls, and women, are
capable of.
</P>
<P>
   ``They demonstrated to me a potential second to none,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Abood was learning from his daughters, they were learning
from him. ``A lot of the skills that I feel are necessary in
management are skills that my dad used in raising our family,''
Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, he insisted that all four girls push
themselves to the limit, but he also recognized that each had
different limits. ``For those of us who got straight As, he would
expect nothing less,'' she said. ``But one of my sisters got Bs and
he would expect nothing else of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Abood said he learned that lesson in the military. He did two
tours of duty in the Vietnam War, rising to staff sergeant in the
Marine Corps, and later spent 16 years in the National Guard. ``You
don't get to pick and choose'' if you are a military officer, he
said. ``So you learn to evaluate and identify each person's
potential and then to develop it. I tried to apply this to my
daughters and teach them this.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller, who joined Consumers Energy when she was 19, said that
she did not intend to go to work for a power company, but that it
was easier because of her father. ``There's a lot of comfort that I
have a mentor outside the company who understands the environment
in which I work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Abood's influence extended to his other daughters as well. All
have ended up in positions that require management expertise. They
are Lori Ann Poirier, 32, the nursing supervisor of two hospitals
and a nursing home in Lansing, Mich.; Madonna Alice Boyd, 29, a
real estate agent in Beaver Dam, Wis., and Natasha Elizabeth
Schmidt, 28, who runs a hog farm with her husband in Fox Lake, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Keller who has most leaned on her father for
management guidance. When she first became a manager, she said, the
youngest person on her team was nine years older than she was, and
she didn't know any of the members all that well. Her father told
her not to worry; he had been around long enough to know that age
and appearance do not matter that much in the dynamics of corporate
power. What really count are self-assurance and decisiveness, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to ignore the perceptions,'' Keller recalled. ``He
said a leader isn't always a person who knows it all or has all the
answers. It's how you get people involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, Keller said she was having problems with a
colleague, an older man who knew a great deal about older
technologies. She said he felt threatened by her. Her father told
her to try to see the situation through his eyes and find a way to
make him feel wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to consult him on his expertise,'' Keller said. ``I
showed him that I respected him. Then he started to do the same
with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
