<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST THE SOOTHSAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The chants finally came, arguably a month overdue,
and ironically not even at a Los Angeles Lakers home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``M-V-P.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid Shaquille O'Neal's 61-point extravaganza Monday, a chorus
of Clippers ticket-holders at Staples Center grasped what Laker
fans haven't yet. Amazingly, not a single ``MVP'' yelp has been
audible at a Lakers home game, in the same arena.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign will be hard to stop now and it's a pleasant
sight to the man who predicted O'Neal's MVP season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille, I'm so happy for him and just proud of what he's
accomplished,'' Lakers executive Jerry West said recently, before
O'Neal's latest demolition job. ``His hard work and dedication have
paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   And how. O'Neal's career high against the Clippers raised his
scoring average to 28.2 points, second in the NBA. He's also second
in rebounding (14.3 per game), first in field-goal percentage
(.565), third in blocks (3.32) and first in double-doubles (50).
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before training camp started, I'm not a prediction-
maker, but I just felt in my mind this was going to be one of those
watershed years for him,'' West said. ``As he goes forward in his
career, this is something our fans will have an opportunity to
witness firsthand for a number of years going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is also among the league's top five in playing time, at
39.9 minutes per game, in part because coach Phil Jackson has
little faith in his backup centers. But the long minutes don't faze
West, a onetime teammate of Wilt Chamberlain, who averaged 45.8
minutes per game over his 14-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not leading the league in minutes played,'' West said of
O'Neal. ``He !ital!should play 40 minutes a game, period. Good
players should play 40 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to have times when you can rest him, but the fact
remains, he's prospered playing the way he's playing, and the
amount of minutes he's playing. You'd like to be two-deep
everywhere, and I think sometimes when I look at our situation,
we'd like to see development of a backup player in his position
that Phil has confidence in.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Down time: After playing five games in seven days, the Lakers
are taking a breather. A Thursday trip to Golden State is the only
game on the calendar between now and Sunday, and Jackson gave his
players Tuesday off.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking forward to (the down time); I'm not looking
forward to it,'' Jackson said. ``There's not much I can do to them,
although I'd like to. But they'll have a day off and then we'll
resume and go hard.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Dribbles: O'Neal's 61-point, 23-rebound line was the first
60-20 game in the NBA since Chamberlain had 66 points and 27
rebounds Feb. 7, 1969, in a 121-117 overtime loss at Phoenix. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Milestone check: If the Lakers win their 17th in a row Thursday,
their streak will be tied for the sixth longest in NBA history. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   They might not get to 33 the NBA record set by the 1971-72
Lakers but the second-longest streak (20, by the 1970-71 Milwaukee
Bucks) is in reach. After the Warriors, the Lakers are at home
against Sacramento, then on the road at Denver and Washington for
potential wins 19 and 20. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Despite the off day, the Lakers (50-11) were set to be the first
team to clinch a playoff berth. All they needed was a Denver loss
at Indiana on Tuesday, or a victory over the Warriors on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
