<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS, ENERGIZED IF PUZZLED, FLOCK TO THE POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ELN-NEWYORK) 
(lh) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With predictions that turnout would be heavier than
usual for a primary, New York voters, energized by a highly
competitive presidential campaign, headed to the polls Tuesday,
even though they were sometimes still puzzled about their choices.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in particular stepped into the booth with more than
a little uncertainty. In some cases this arose from the confusing
ballot, but it was also because of the tough campaigning of Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who were
virtually tied in opinion polls heading into the primary. And a few
voters were surprised that they could not cross party lines to
vote, as was the case in a few other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Democrats were very disappointed that they could not
vote for a Republican,'' said Al Krooler, a polling inspector in
Mount Kisco. ``We had to convince some of them that once you go in
the booth you have to vote for somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Election and party officials in several areas said they believed
turnout would be heavier than normal _ for a primary, 20 to 25
percent of registered voters _ but it was impossible to tell early
in the evening if those predictions would come true. Much of the
balloting was expected to take place in the hours right before the
polls closed at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs people were eager to vote. In Putnam County,
Robert J. Bennett, the Democratic commissioner of the Board of
Elections, said voters started calling the board early in the
morning demanding to know why the polls would not open until noon,
the normal hour in most upstate New York counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the number of phone calls we received, it indicates to me
that there is a heck of a lot of interest in these races,'' Bennett
said.
</P>
<P>
   The polls opened at 6 a.m. in New York City, on Long Island and
in Westchester, Rockland, Orange and Erie counties; in the rest of
the state, not enough people typically vote in primaries to warrant
longer hours, said Lee Daghlian, a spokesman for the state
elections board.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters said the political brawl between McCain and Bush had
ignited their interest. William F. Milford, a farmer in the Suffolk
County community of Southold, said his misgivings about Bush led
him to vote in a primary for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't trust Bush,'' he said. ``I don't agree with
everything McCain says, but I trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another first-time primary voter, Darrin Smith of Eastchester,
said that after reading and hearing so much about the campaign he
would have felt guilty sitting it out. ``I had to do something with
this information,'' said Smith, an accountant who went with Bush
because of his record on education in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some voters found the ballots baffling. In the Republican
primary, the names of delegates for the candidates were printed in
larger type than the names of the candidates themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Norman A. Ernst Jr., of Garden City, who said he voted for
McCain, linked the small print to the failed effort by the state's
Republican Party leaders to keep the senator off the ballot. ``It's
upsetting to me when the Republicans espouse very democratic
principles, and here they are trying to keep McCain off the ballot,
and there being this confusion on the ballot,'' he said. ``The name
was very tiny.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been an expectation in the McCain camp that New York
Republicans, who are considered moderate, would flock to him, but
in North Castle, a woodsy suburban town in central Westchester
County, a different phenomenon was evident: Republicans _ at least
two of them _ for Gore. Richard and Virginia Weir, lifelong
Republicans, said they were repelled from their own party when both
Bush and McCain began using religion as an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very religious people, and that was a real turnoff,''
Virginia Weir said. ``McCain came across as nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush, they said, he shared few traits with his father,
for whom they had voted enthusiastically. Looking ahead to
November, each said, the only reasonable candidate left was the
likely Democratic nominee, Vice President Al Gore. ``I do believe
I'm going to vote for him,'' Virginia Weir said. ``There just isn't
anybody out there who has the old-fashioned qualities we like.
They're all dead now.'' In the meantime, the Weirs said, they were
so frustrated they split their votes Tuesday between Bush and
McCain delegates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
