<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG)     03-07 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM TOP SCORER TO PURE PASSER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ He was always a great jumper in high school, and
by the time he was a junior at Palmdale High, Markus Carr could
already dunk a basketball, even though he stood just a tad over
6-feet.
</P>
<P>
   Then, four years ago, before his senior season, Carr made the
biggest leap of his life. Unlike many of the players before him,
Carr committed to a four-year school.
</P>
<P>
   He was a kid with skinny legs who weighed maybe 170 pounds
soaking wet. Playing in an area not known for great basketball he
leaped at the chance to sign with Cal State Northridge. Carr was
confident he made the right choice, even as the local junior
college coach asked him to change his mind and stay in the Antelope
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of people before me go to (Antelope Valley
College),'' Carr said. ``I didn't want to do the same thing. I
wanted to try something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at him now. Carr, a sophomore, has blossomed into one of
the top guards on the West Coast. He leads the Big Sky Conference
in assists, averaging 7.3 per game, which also ranks him in the top
10 in the country.
</P>
<P>
   When CSUN (18-9) plays Weber State (18-9) tonight in the first
round of the conference tournament, Carr will take the court as a
first-team all-conference selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Carr)'s elevating his game,'' said CSUN teammate Carl Holmes,
who broke in with Carr in 1997. ``He's a solid point guard. He
scores when he needs to, but his No. 1 priority is getting his
teammates the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr, now 6-1 and 180 pounds, improves every game. He's a little
cocky and he never hesitates to throw a no-look pass. He's been
known to throw an alley-oop pass, too. From halfcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flashiness is just an instinct,'' Carr said. ``It comes
with the package.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr bounces when he walks. There's a rhythm there. It seems
like James Brown's ``Super Bad'' is always playing in Carr's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of being a dreamer,'' he said. ``(Growing up) I did
a lot of dreaming of what I wanted to do on the court, in front of
a large crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Antelope Valley wasn't known for producing players
who could fit nicely into a pickup game on Venice Beach. In
back-to-back years, though, three players brought the playground to
the Golden League.
</P>
<P>
   One was Highland's John Burrell, who averaged 30 points per game
as a senior. After a two-year standout career at Antelope Valley
College, Burrell is at CSUN by way of Nevada. He's sitting out this
season because of NCAA transfer rules. Another was Tony Walker, a
two-sport star at Antelope Valley who went to Utah State to play
football.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Carr, the least-known of the three.
</P>
<P>
   Like Burrell, Carr was a scorer, averaging 18 points as a junior
and 20 as a senior. But Burrell led his team to a Golden League
title. Walker was a football hero, which counts for everything in
the AV.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Carr) shot the ball anytime he wanted,'' said Kevin Miller,
Carr's backcourt teammate in high school. ``He had the green light,
every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr said nobody saw the passes he made in practice. No one knew
his ability to do anything other than make baskets. When he got to
CSUN, he even doubted himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (my teammates) first saw me, I don't think they thought I
could handle it at the D-I level,'' Carr said. ``I was really small
and really skinny. I seemed like another average player that might
not be able to step up to this competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markus was probably the best freshman of all of us who came
in,'' he said. ``We knew that right off the bat. He was very
athletic, as small as he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee in
September of 1997 and missed what would have been his freshman
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The injury) was a blessing in disguise, really,'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Carr redshirted and he got bigger and stronger
through physical therapy. He also had a chance to observe CSUN
coach Bobby Braswell.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I sat out that year, I got to see what (Braswell) really
wanted the point guard to do and how he wanted the point guard to
run the team,'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he came back from the injury, Carr had less jumping
ability but a better understanding of the college game. He started
23 of the Matadors' 29 games and he led the team in assists with
127.
</P>
<P>
   Carr has completely changed himself as a player from when he was
at Palmdale. He's averaging 8.4 points this season, up from 6.2
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to college, I realized that around me were a lot of
scorers,'' Carr said. ``I knew I could be the person to get them
the ball to score. Once you get to college, especially at the D-I
level, everybody was a scorer or they were the best on their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has to get them the ball. I just figured out a way .
. . to get them the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr has found his way and his friend Miller said everybody in
Palmdale knows how he is doing at CSUN: ``You see his name in the
papers all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But trips home during the school year are infrequent for Carr,
who says he last went back at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go see (my) family,'' he said. ``I'll go out there for the
summer and run up in the hills. Most of the people from my time
left. They've got new people they look up to in high school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
