<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERISIGN-NETWORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERISIGN TO ACQUIRE NETWORK SOLUTIONS IN STOCK SWAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the costliest acquisition of an Internet
company to date, VeriSign Inc., a producer of online security
software, agreed to acquire Network Solutions Inc., the
Virginia-based company that maintains the master list of Internet
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   VeriSign valued the deal, a stock swap, at $21 billion, although
a drop in its share price took it down to $17 billion _ still a
high premium for a company with 1999 earnings of $26.9 million on
sales of $220.8 million. The deal rivals Lucent Technologies Inc.'s
$20 billion acquisition of Ascend Communications Inc. in January
1999 as the biggest high-tech acquisition ever. The major
difference is that Ascend had $1.6 billion in sales in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the price was all the more astonishing because
Network Solutions no longer enjoys a monopoly in the registration
of domain names, as Internet addresses are known, and will see
growing competition in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The merger also constrains VeriSign's ability to form
partnerships or strategic alliances with a generation of companies
that now compete with Network Solutions in registering domain
names, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns drove VeriSign shares down $47.4375 to close at
$200, in Nasdaq trading. Network Solutions shares soared, closing
at $407.3906, up $46.7656, to make it the biggest gainer on the
Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of these two companies makes sense,'' said
Charles Rutstein, an analyst with Forrester Research. ``The
cross-selling and up-selling opportunities are evident to most
observers.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``What's a bit confusing is why VeriSign needed to
own this company as opposed to being a marketing partner. The two
have done business together before. At the end of the day, you have
to wonder whether $21 billion was too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, VeriSign, whose software keeps sensitive
information safe when people buy and sell things on the Internet,
will issue 2.15 shares of VeriSign common stock for each share of
Network Solutions stock, as constituted before a 2-for-1 split of
Network Solutions stock on March 10. Verisign had earnings of $4
million on revenues of $84.8 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said that by combining they would be able to offer
services including domain registration, global directory listings,
basic Web site creation and secure processing of online
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton Sclavos, VeriSign's president and chief executive,
called Network Solutions ``one of the most undervalued assets on
the Internet by any of the standard metrics _ number of customers,
type of business model, revenue growth, profitability, cash flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said there were regulatory issues and competitive
pressures that made the outcome of the merger difficult to predict.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Commerce Department created Internet Corp. for
Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann, to end Network Solutions'
monopoly and open up the registration of Internet addresses to
competition. Tuesday, at an Icann meeting in Cairo, people were
caught off guard by the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real eye-opener,'' said Ken Stubbs, who runs a
nonprofit group that now competes with Network Solutions. But he
said he was not concerned about its impact on his group. ``I think
I'll register more names tomorrow than today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1979, Network Solutions pioneered the registering of
Web addresses ending in .com, .net, .org and .edu. It is the
world's leading registrar with more than 8.1 million domain
registrations. It also offers so-called registry services, meaning
that it maintains the InterNIC database, the telephone directory of
the Internet. Network Solutions' registry customers include all the
new competing companies that register domains ending in .com, .net
and .org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
