<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCSORLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS CHARGE MCSORLEY WITH ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When suspended defenseman Marty McSorley stopped by the Bruins'
dressing room Monday afternoon, he had a terrible feeling that he
would be facing criminal charges in Vancouver in connection with
the stick-swinging incident Feb. 21 that gave the Canucks' Donald
Brashear a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   His dread turned out to be well-founded, as a Canadian court
ruled Tuesday that McSorley must appear in court April 4 to face
one count of assault with a weapon. If convicted, McSorley faces a
maximum sentence of 18 months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' McSorley said during an interview on ESPN.
``I'm disappointed it's going to court, because I don't know if
anybody really knows right now how much I've already lost.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley, who has aspirations to coach once his playing career
is over, realizes his reputation has been tarnished and his future
employment in the NHL has been jeopardized. If he wants to return
to playing, the 36-year-old defenseman must petition to be
reinstated and meet with commissioner Gary Bettman in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley's suspension, which covers the final 23 games of the
season, is the longest in NHL history for an on-ice incident. It
will cost him an estimated $72,000 in salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in contact with a very good lawyer in Vancouver and
we were trying to not have it go to court,'' said McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Gaul, a spokesman for the British Columbia criminal
justice branch, said the decision to charge McSorley was made after
a prosecutor's review and a police investigation.
</P>
<P>
   An NHL representative said the league wasn't happy with the
decision but will cooperate with Canadian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the league dealt with the matter quickly,
decisively, and appropriately _ and did not feel that any further
action was either warranted or necessary,'' said Bill Daly, the
NHL's chief legal officer.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning moments of a 5-2 loss in Vancouver, McSorley
struck Brashear in the right temple and knocked him to the ice,
causing a Grade 3 concussion, the most serious type. McSorley and
Brashear had fought earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had absolutely no intention of hurting Donald Brashear with
my hockey stick,'' said McSorley. ``I wanted a confrontation with
Donald Brasher, no different than I've done on so many other
nights. It just went badly.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time law enforcement agencies have
responded to on-ice violence in the NHL. Who can forget the Wayne
Maki-Ted Green incident? After a stick-swinging duel in a September
1969 preseason game, they were taken to court. Boston's Green, who
suffered a fractured skull, and Maki, who was not injured, were
acquitted of assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Dave Forbes of the Bruins stood trial, accused of using
excessive force against Henry Boucha of the Minnesota North Stars
in another stick attack. The trial ended in a hung jury and the
prosecution did not seek a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent incident involved Minnesota's Dino Ciccarelli,
who was sentenced to one day in jail and fined $1,000 in 1988 for
striking Luke Richardson several times in the head with his stick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
