u p BC-BUSH-NOMINATION-HNS &LR;      03-07 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NOMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TURNING INTO `A BETTER CANDIDATE' AFTER BRUISING PRIMARY
BATTLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush, almost assured of the Republican
presidential nomination after Tuesday's primaries, is emerging from
his brutal nominating battle by taking the attitude that any
illness that does not kill you will only make you stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primaries can be very healthy. It's made me a better
candidate,'' the Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's fight with GOP rival John McCain may have left his
candidacy so unhealthy that it would be considered terminal if his
general election Democratic opponent was anyone other than Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wounds are deep,'' said University of Virginia political
scientist Larry Sabato, but ``as many weaknesses that have been
revealed about George W. Bush, he's still 50-50 because Al Gore is
an exceptionally unexceptional candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato said Bush's primary campaign exploded the idea that he is
a candidate who can appeal to crossover independent and primary
voters. Sabato said Bush's moderate credentials have been tainted
by his appeal to Southern fundamentalists to the degree that it now
looks unlikely Bush could carry any northeastern states in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's extremely lucky that his opponent is Al Gore. Gore has
the same problem that Bush does: zero appeal to independents or
voters of the other party,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   This status is a far cry from where Bush was coming out of the
Iowa caucuses in January.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was viewed as a centrist whose re-election victory as Texas
governor in 1998 had proven he could attract independents and
Democrats. He had raised more than $70 million, a record in
presidential money-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But in underestimating McCain in New Hampshire, Bush allowed the
Arizona senator to score an upset victory that suddenly made him a
competitive opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The loss burst the bubble on Bush as the inevitable nominee and
eventual president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign replied by embracing religious conservatives to
win South Carolina. That primary gave Bush's candidacy an extremist
tint. And McCain's subsequent use of Bush's speech at Bob Jones
University harmed Bush's plan to make northeastern Catholics a part
of his winning general election coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, McCain had become what Bush was supposed to be, the
candidate who was attracting independent and Democratic voters. But
Bush outpaced McCain by winning with core Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has pushed himself out of the center and that will give
Gore an opportunity to play on the theme that he is too extreme,''
said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Center for the People and
the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Kohut said that even though some voters may consider Bush a
centrist, they now view him ``as a moderate in the grip of the
extreme right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign also was harmed by the view that it had been
profligate in spending almost all of the money it had raised.
</P>
<P>
   The original campaign funding plan had been promoted that Bush
would have enough money to win the nomination. He would then have
money left over to campaign against Gore from March until his
campaign receives federal funds after the Republican National
Convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   Bush finance chairman Don Evans said there always had been two
plans, and one was that there would be a competitive primary race
through March.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said a series of six events in coming weeks will raise
somewhere between $5 million and $10 million for Bush. He noted
that President Clinton had $18 million in the bank March 1, 1996,
for his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main point is we'll be competitive,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Tuesday kept downplaying the idea that the Super Tuesday
primaries would make him the presumptive nominee. But he also
promoted the idea that he can heal his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primaries are tough because we are arguing among a political
family, but there is going to be ample time to heal wounds that
exist,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he goes into the general election with an excited
Republican base vote. He said he has no plans to change his message
because his programs for tax cuts and education reform cross party
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change my message. Maybe Al Gore feels like
that's the way he needs to campaign. He keeps changing message,
changing headquarters or changing suits,'' Bush said, chiding
Gore's campaign overhaul that occurred late last year. ``I'm going
to say the same thing during the course of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also said he believes he faces a stiff challenge this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough campaign, given the way this
administration has conducted themselves over the past seven years.
It's the politics of personal destruction,'' Bush said. ``It's an
administration that if you don't agree with them on an issue,
they'd much rather fight than debate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
