<HEADLINE>
ALL-BIG 12 HONORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
All Big 12 The Star-Telegram's All-Big 12 men's basketball team, as
selected by staff writer Mike Jones:
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIRST TEAM
</P>
<P>
   Player of the Year Marcus Fizer, Iowa State, F, 6-8, Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: 22.8 points, 7.6 rebounds and shot 60.7 percent from
the field.
</P>
<P>
   The facts: Emerged this season as the most dominant player in
the conference during the team's February stretch run to its first
conference title in 55 years, outdistancing three other Player of
the Year candidates. Was at his best in ISU's biggest games.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaal Tinsley, Iowa State, G, 6-3, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: 10.1 points, 6.6 assists
</P>
<P>
   The facts: Helped transform the Cyclones from also-rans to
conference champions with his penetration on offense and sticky
defense. Recorded a triple-double (points, rebounds, assists)
against Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Mason, Oklahoma State, G-F, 6-6, Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: 18.1 points, 6.8 rebounds
</P>
<P>
   The facts: Ended his career No. 5 on OSU's scoring list, No. 8
in rebounding. He was fifth in steals and 3-pointers and No. 6 in
blocked shots. Made a school-record 98 consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Najera, Oklahoma, F, 6-8, Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: 18.5 points, 9.5 rebounds
</P>
<P>
   The facts: The heart and soul of the Sooners, Najera epitomized
the hard-working, blue-collar ethic of OU's team. He finished
fourth in the Big 12 in scoring, second in rebounding and fifth in
steals.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mihm, Texas, C, 7-0, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Key stats: 17.8 points, 10.4 rebounds
</P>
<P>
   The facts: The conference's most marked man, who despite between
doubled- and sometimes tripled-teamed, nevertheless led the league
with 17 double-doubles (scoring and rebounding). SECOND TEAM Player
Team Pos. Yr. Key Stat Rayford Young Texas Tech G Sr 17.9 ppg Ivan
Wagner Texas G Sr 9.7 ppg Jaquay Walls Colorado G Sr 17.4 pgg Gabe
Muoneke Texas F Sr 13.6 ppg Brian Montonati Oklahoma State F Sr 7.4
rebounds
</P>
<P>
   COACH OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Larry Eustachy, Iowa State
</P>
<P>
   The facts: In his second season in the conference, he realized
the promise predicted for him and established himself in a
conference known for having some of the most respected coaches in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   FRESHMAN OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Bernard King, Texas A&AMP;M
</P>
<P>
   Key stat: 17.3 points, 4.1 assists
</P>
<P>
   The facts: The only freshman in Division I who averaged at least
15 points, four assists and four rebounds a game, and he did it
despite being a defensive focus in a conference with a number of
good defensive teams.
</P>
<P>
   NEWCOMER OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Kimani Ffriend, Nebraska
</P>
<P>
   Key stat: Blocked 83 shots
</P>
<P>
   The facts: Averaged 12.2 points and 8.9 rebounds in a season
that is usually one of transition for junior college transfers.
</P>
