<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MCCAIN08-COX     03-07 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delegate math is a sobering equation
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ John McCain has spent the past week
preaching the ``politics of addition, not the politics of
division.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was talking about bringing new blood into the Republican
Party, a key part of his improbable run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But as he awaited the verdict in coast-to-coast voting in 13
states Tuesday, McCain confronted a sobering problem of political
math.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, would McCain have any way of denying George W. Bush
the 1,034 Republican delegates needed to win the presidential
nomination?
</P>
<P>
   The answer will play a decisive role in whether McCain continues
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On top of Bush's bounty Tuesday, Bush's home state of Texas and
five other Southern states with 340 delegates hold primaries next
Tuesday. Florida, where Bush's brother Jeb is governor, is one of
the states voting next week.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has lost all three Southern states that have voted so
far, Georgia, South Carolina and Virginia, and McCain aides have
conceded that Bush will have a good day next week.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are pointing to Illinois, which has a March 21
primary open to all voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain issued a statement early Tuesday night as he watched
election results with his wife, Cindy, from Los Angeles. Early
projections showed McCain winning Vermont, and he anticipated
strong results in Massachusetts and several other Eastern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the polls begin to close on the East Coast, Cindy and I
want to express our tremendous gratitude for the great support my
campaign received at the polls today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is too early to officially comment on all the
results, it is clear we have done very well on the East Coast and I
am deeply grateful for the strong support our campaign is receiving
throughout the state of New York and the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am optimistic that this trend of support will continue on
the West Coast, and I look forward to all the results as they
continue to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Straight Talk Express, McCain's campaign bus, sat silent
most of Tuesday, while the candidate was closeted in his hotel
suite with much of his family.
</P>
<P>
   His only campaign activity was a round of early morning radio
interviews that began with Don Imus' program and included stations
in San Diego and San Francisco. McCain awoke at 4:30 a.m. PST to
chat with Imus, a McCain supporter.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's public comments provided mixed signals about the future
of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how proud I am to have sparked the kind of
prairie fire out there that is getting people involved,'' he said
on radio station KGO in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The same wistfulness about what he has done over the past few
months also was evident in McCain's last campaign appearance in
California.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood in the soothing sunshine in San Diego's Old Town on
Monday afternoon, McCain talked about his stops at factory gates,
his town hall meetings, his enthusiastic receptions on college
campuses, ``the people we've known and the relationships we've
had.''
</P>
<P>
   While McCain and his aides insisted he would soldier on, the
candidate is scheduled to go today to his Arizona retreat near
Sedona for a day of rest and consultation with his senior staff and
family.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign schedule is supposed to resume Thursday with a stop
in Grand Junction, Colo., before Friday's primaries in Colorado,
Utah and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Murphy, a media consultant, said the campaign has spent
$200,000 to buy time on Colorado television stations this week.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate himself continued to stress the theme of inclusion
that has dominated his rhetoric since he branded religious
conservative leaders Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell
``agents of intolerance'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the speech was to attract moderate Republican,
independent and Democratic voters who object to the political
influence of Christian conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you reach beyond your party,'' McCain said on KGO in
San Francisco, ``you are condemned to minority status.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was appealing to non-Republicans who are allowed to vote
for Republican candidates in California and nine other states. In
California, McCain was hoping to win the overall vote, while Bush
held a wide lead among Republicans. Only GOP votes would count in
awarding the state's 162 delegates to the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   McCain again lashed out at Bush for not doing anything to stop a
$2.5 million anti-McCain ad campaign that is being run by a Texan
with ties to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain called the ad, which attacks his environmental record and
praises Bush's, ``a violation of everything I've been fighting for
in campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has denied any connection to the ad, which would be
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   In response, McCain has attacked Bush as a candidate who is
willing to do and say anything to win.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts fault McCain for reacting so forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been angry and whiny,'' said Larry Sabato, a political
science professor at the University of Virginia. ``Whether he
realizes it or not, he is proving some of the criticisms of some of
his most ardent opponents to be accurate. He does have a temper and
he's just not a good sport. ... Voters expect a strong leader who
can take criticism. They want someone with elephant skin because
they know that's what the presidency demands.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McCain talked about the topsy-turvy nature of the
2000 Republican campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every model that there's been so far in this primary has not
been true,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But on the biggest political day of the year so far, McCain
showed that he still retained his ability to tease those around
him.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Cindy, complained that she dined on cashews Monday
night while McCain's senior staff ate at one of Los Angeles' best
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had honey-roasted peanuts, too,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
