<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE TAKES CLASS ACT TO AVALANCHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While the struggling Bruins were working out in the
suburbs Tuesday before leaving for Buffalo, their former captain,
Ray Bourque, was on a private jet alongside Dave Andreychuk on the
way to join the Colorado Avalanche in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, who was traded Monday after nearly 21 seasons in the
Black and Gold, had asked to be dealt to Detroit or Philadelphia so
he could stay close to his family, with his first choice being the
Flyers. However, Bruins management felt the Avalanche offered the
best package (Brian Rolston, Martin Grenier, Sami Pahlsson, and a
first-round pick in 2000 or 2001).
</P>
<P>
   This hockey season in Boston has been bizarre from the get-go,
and Tuesday's strange sequence of events was typical of just how
odd and unfortunate things have gotten.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque held a poignant, dignified, and emotional news
conference at Logan International Airport a little after 8 a.m., in
which he bid a tearful farewell to the city he loves and the only
one he's known in his professional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 10 years, I haven't been close to competing for a Cup,''
said Bourque. ``The other reason, another big reason I wanted to
go, is I think I need to challenge myself at this point in time to
really find out what I've got left as a hockey player.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that, however, Bruins president/general manager
Harry Sinden was pointing the management howitzers at coach Pat
Burns during an interview on WEEI radio.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Sinden felt compelled to travel to New
Jersey to put to rest rumors that Burns was about to be fired.
Tuesday, Sinden said Burns's future would be addressed after the
season, and he clearly criticized the coach when asked by radio
hosts John Dennis and Gerry Callahan whether Burns could have done
anything differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury factor didn't occur on this team until we were
already in very, very bad shape on the ice,'' Sinden said. ``Up to
the point where (Jason) Allison went down. In October, it was our
10th game before we won and we didn't have any injuries then. It
was not the reason we went into (the tailspin). We just lost our
way completely, and had we not had any injuries to Allison and
(Anson) Carter, I still have my doubts if we would've come out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the club's lack of success shocked him, though he
conceded that Byron Dafoe's holdout hurt his ability to pick up
where he left off last year. In a staggering turn, though, he all
but blamed Burns's failings for Bourque's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget, we were winning one game in every 15 while he
was playing and everybody else was playing,'' said Sinden. ``I
would've thought we would've been able to win two in every 15. It
seemed to me that it was an absolutely ridiculous record . . . for
a team that everybody thought perhaps could contend and that
Raymond Bourque would say, `I don't want to go anywhere. I want to
stay with this team.' It's one thing to drop a little bit and not
live up to expectations, but to totally, totally fail . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shocking to me that this group of players could go in
that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise, given those comments, that Burns was subdued
after practice and called for a truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the mudslinging stops,'' said Burns. ``I've had
enough of that. I'm so tired of it _ who's at fault, what happened,
this guy, that guy . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``We have five weeks of hockey left. I want to have fun with
this group. I want to win some games. Our record sucks right now.
We have to find a way to win some games and change some things.
It's just become so heavy on everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get through these five weeks and try to win as
many games as we can and maybe help some players along. Decisions
will be made, the evaluation period will all happen over the summer
or after the season. Let's just leave it up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   As that situation simmers, the day brought even more negativity
as defenseman Marty McSorley was formally charged in Vancouver with
assault for his stick attack on Donald Brashear Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The only positive note on the day was seeing the classy Bourque
leave with a chance to win something. He was disappointed, though,
not to be going to Philadelphia, a point reiterated by his longtime
agent and friend, Steve Freyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it abundantly clear where he wanted to go and he
wanted to stay close because of family,'' said Freyer. ``So he's
not happy about going to Colorado. It's real rough on the kids. He
probably could've traded him to Hawaii but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Bourque, there is no NHL team in Hawaii, but
given the circumstances, he said he was happy to be going to a
talented, contending team. He said his motivation for leaving
Boston was partly not having been in the finals for a decade and
also not having an accurate gauge on his own talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been satisfied with how I've been playing this
year,'' said Bourque, ``and I think a challenge like a Stanley Cup
run will bring the best out of me and I sure hope it does. That
will answer a lot of my questions with regard to if I'm going to
play next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque already has a couple of friends on the Avalanche _
former Bruin Dave Reid and goalie Patrick Roy. The only bad thing
about the situation is how far away he'll be from his wife, Chris,
and three kids. In terms of hockey, though, he's far more
optimistic than he was here, where he was asked to do too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about it,'' he said. ``For 39, playing 30 minutes
some nights or being asked to do a lot of things that a few years
ago were a lot easier, today is a lot tougher. Some things I
couldn't do as well as I would've liked. I think going to Colorado
to go out and play my game, I think it's going to be a lot better
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad that isn't the case here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
