<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-MCLAREN-BO     03-07 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MCLAREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' LEADERSHIP ROLE GOES TO MCLAREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was no formal ceremony to mark the passing of the
torch from Ray Bourque to Kyle McLaren, the new minister of defense
for the Bruins. There was a two-minute phone conversation Monday
night between Bourque and McLaren, not long after Bourque had been
dealt to the Colorado Avalanche to pursue his Stanley Cup dreams.
</P>
<P>
   That will have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he told me, `Remember what I taught you over the
last couple of years,' '' said McLaren. ``He believes in me. He's
one guy who really believes in what I can do. I know I have a fan
in him that will watch me through the years. To have the respect of
Ray Bourque and what he taught me, I'm never going to forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first game ever was in the Boston Garden. I started in that
game, the last game ever there. Those memories will last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Tuesday was warm and springlike outside, it was cold and
gloomy inside the suburban Bruins practice rink on the first day of
the post-Bourque era. One fan expressed the darkness in his soul
planting a sign at the entrance to the Ristuccia Center that said,
``Jeremy Jacobs and Harry Sinden: You suck!'' It was quickly taken
down.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange day in Bruins history. The most recognizable
figure on the ice was the coach, Pat Burns. There was no presence,
no centerpiece. It was as if the Eiffel Tower had been removed from
Paris, Big Ben ripped out of London.
</P>
<P>
   What remained was, well, the future _ which had swiftly, perhaps
too swiftly, turned into the present.
</P>
<P>
   Will the spotlight fall on McLaren now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's my team,'' he said. ``The younger guys are
definitely now in the forefront. We still have guys around that
have done a great job over the years like Rob DiMaio and Don
Sweeney and Steve Heinze. Those are the veteran guys right now. The
young guys are now having to wise up and mature a little sooner
than expected because we didn't expect Ray to leave this early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not seeing him is strange. It's tough for everyone. Twenty-one
years he's been here. When he's around, he's brightened up so many
guys' lives. Some guys are still shocked it happened. I'm sure it's
not going to settle in for a while, but it has to settle in because
we have to play hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   In five years, the 23-year-old McLaren has not yet reached
All-Star level. He has soaked in the wisdom of Bourque, but the
other part, the biggest part, must come from McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at his points and you can look at his production,
but what he did off the ice is what impressed me,'' said McLaren.
``Family came first to him. No matter what. This is the only time
where I see him going for something and maybe moving away from his
family for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Now McLaren will be expected to handle himself on and off the
ice with the same class, even though he is no Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be pressure there for someone to come
in and fill his shoes,'' said McLaren. ``If people are expecting me
to do it, give them 80-90 points a year, I'd only be kidding myself
to put that kind of pressure on myself. I just have to play the
best I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking to be the captain of the team or the main
focal point because there are a lot of guys in here who can do the
job, too. Ray was an All-Star here and he'll be that wherever he
goes. You can't just build a team around one guy; it has to be
around a bunch of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   As amazing as it seems, McLaren is third on the team in
seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's strange,'' he said. ``Ray's gone and we can't cry about
it. We're certainly sad to see him go, but we have a lot of guys
with five or less years in the league. We need those guys to pick
it up and play stronger. We have to worry about winning those
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the need to move on, McLaren thinks some things are
sacred. One of them is the ``C'' that Bourque wore for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very surprised if there was a captain for a while,''
said McLaren. ``One of the most respected captains in our league
just left our team. I think it's out of respect that nobody should
wear it, nobody should sit in his stalls here or the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should wear the `C' today and really I don't think
anyone should wear it for the rest of the season and maybe next
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
