<SLUG> BC-ELN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING FIGHT, GORE DROPPED BOY-SCOUT IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ It was a slap at an already wounded man: The night
before Tuesday's primaries, Al Gore made a quick stop to Bill
Bradley's home state, Missouri, asking for votes he almost
certainly didn't need to dominate the contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to fight for YOU!'' Gore screamed at the St. Louis
crowd in the guttural roar he has employed frequently in the past
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has fought very hard for Al Gore since Bradley first
proved to be a serious challenge to the vice president last fall.
The vice president made over his campaign, moving its headquarters
from Washington, D.C., to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   He lined up the backing of the Democratic establishment, which,
by publicly embracing Gore, embarrassed Bradley at ostensibly open
Democratic Party events.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president quickly crushed Bradley's efforts to chip
away at the front-runner's support. When Bradley raised questions
about Gore's record on abortion rights, Gore wrangled the
endorsement of the country's biggest abortion-rights group, the
National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley decided to make an all-out effort to win Washington
state's primary last week _ a contest that awarded no delegates _
Gore determined to crush him there, and did, depriving Bradley of
even a public relations boost.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Gore's boy-scout public image. When it appeared that
Bradley might have a chance to capture the Democratic nomination,
the vice president, the man teased for being stiff and boring,
battled like a gladiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a two-fisted fighter,'' said Stephen Hess, an analyst
with the Brookings Institution. ``If he needs to slug it out, he'll
slug it out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the backdrop of Gore's speedy comeback was a campaign
tailored to appeal to different Democratic constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Before liberal New York and Massachusetts voters, Gore voiced an
impassioned commitment to ``a woman's right to choose,'' and said
that in his boyhood household, he was taught that ``women were
equal, if not more so.''
</P>
<P>
   Those references were deleted from an address Gore gave late
last month to Hasidic Jews in a New Square, N.Y., synagogue. To an
all-male audience _ the few women permitted in the building were
seated in a high balcony _ Gore talked about the strong US economy
during the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   The comments about the booming economy were themselves softened
in venues such as Cudahy, Calif., and Buffalo, where the local
economies are struggling. There, Gore talked about helping those
``who have been left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke phrases in Spanish in front of Latino audiences, and
joked before raucous Buffalonians that ``you must all have had your
Flutie Flakes today,'' referring to the cereal named after Buffalo
Bills hero Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   The message appeared to work. But while the people at Gore's
rallies pledged their votes, they often lacked strong enthusiasm
for the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the most experience,'' said 71-year-old Julian Van of
Cudahy with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as exciting as Bill Clinton. He doesn't bring the
same kind of excitement,'' said Doris O'Meara, 64, of Malden. But
``I would never vote Republican,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's supporters note that the vice president has become more
charged up in his speeches, and, with his knit shirts and casual
slacks, less formal. There is plenty of time, they say, for Gore to
create a groundswell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president transitioned from being vice president to
being the candidate for president,'' said Andrew J. Cuomo,
secretary of Housing and Urban Development and an active Gore
campaigner. ``It's early yet. When we get closer to'' the general
election ``you will see the energy for Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fair to say that in the early fall, late summer, you
could see people were kind of undecided about Al Gore,'' said
Dennis Rivera, president of the high-profile Local 1199 union in
New York, representing health care workers. ``But there has been a
dramatic transformation since then of his campaign style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
