<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley campaign at crossroads with `no specific plan'
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Democrat Bill Bradley planned to rest at his New
Jersey home today after watching returns from Super Tuesday's
primary voting at a New York hotel Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley greeted voters on their way to the polls early Tuesday
morning, but spent a largely quiet day in his hotel room with
senior aides and a few close supporters.
</P>
<P>
   With more than one-third of the Democratic delegates up for
grabs, the former New Jersey senator said Tuesday that he had to
win several states to remain viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come what may, he's not dropping out this evening,'' said a
subdued Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman and a former member of his
Senate staff, speaking to reporters at the Sheraton New York Hotel
and Towers.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign made tentative plans to campaign in Florida on
Thursday, but virtually the entire Bradley campaign advance team
was in New York preparing the Sheraton ballroom for what could be
Bradley's last party of the 2000 primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas Lynch, a Bradley supporter from Connecticut,
dropped by the ballroom early to see if he could catch a glimpse of
Bradley, but he encountered Secret Service agents who were still
securing the ballroom. Lynch said he voted for Bradley but was
preparing for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' said Lynch, who recalled watching Bradley play
tournament basketball games at Madison Square Garden while Bradley
was at Princeton. ``He should have had a little of McCain's blood
in him. ... He didn't have the fire. He just didn't go after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's Super Tuesday party was just 20 blocks from Madison
Square Garden, where Bradley played basketball for the New York
Knicks and where they won two NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   At the Penn South polling place, just two blocks from the
Garden, Irving Pakewitz said he remembered Bradley's glory days
well. ``I thought he was an exceptional figure.'' But Pakewitz said
he voted for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was quixotic, him trying for the nomination,''
said Pakewitz. ``I didn't see that he brought something startling
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris Benjamin, 50, a board of education employee, also said he
remembered Bradley fondly. He said he voted for Bradley even though
he suspected the candidate would lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping the polls are wrong,'' Benjamin said. ``It's tough
to run against an incumbent vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley appeared in good spirits as he greeted voters at a
polling place on Manhattan's Upper East Side early Tuesday morning.
Bradley was greeted by seven male staff members, including Hauser,
who stripped to the waist and chanted Bradley's name. In
alternating blue and red paint, the line of staff members spelled
B-R-A-D-L-E-Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful!'' Bradley said, giving each staff member a
high-five.
</P>
<P>
   On the Upper West Side, Louis Gonzalez Jr. was so excited after
shaking Bradley's hand that he changed his plans and went straight
in to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just voted for you,'' said Gonzalez, returning to shake
Bradley's hand again. ``I just voted for you. I pulled the_ the_
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley brightened and said, ``Let me shake the hand that pulled
the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   To reporters, Bradley predicted ``a couple'' of wins Tuesday, a
hope that he clung to all week. ``We're far from the end,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move for a candidate after such an important round
of primary voting, Hauser said Bradley would grant no media
interviews after he spoke to supporters Tuesday night. Hauser said
Bradley also would not appear on any television news shows today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no specific plan,'' Hauser said. ``I assume he'll
talk to people.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
