<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SCHWAB </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Schwab Alters IPO Pipeline for Investors  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Just as investors are clamoring louder than ever to get into
initial public stock offerings, Charles Schwab Corp. has cut off
the tap.
<P>
   Investors love IPOs _ especially those of hot technology
companies _ because these days stock often rise dramatically on the
first day of trading. Last week, for example, in one of the year's
most widely watched IPOs, shares of Palm, which makes a popular
digital organizer, closed at $95.06, up $57.06 from its issue price
of $38 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, the nation's largest online brokerage, offered 88 such
deals to qualified customers in 1999, reinforcing its position as a
leading provider of IPOs to individual investors. By contrast, so
far this year Schwab's IPO total has been zero.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the hiatus is a direct result of Schwab's push to
grab more IPO shares for its clients.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Schwab began selling IPO shares more than two
years ago when it inked agreements with several investment banks
that managed public stock offerings, including Hambrecht &AMP; Quist
and Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, dissatisfied with the tiny number of shares those
firms were setting aside for its customers, Schwab let the pacts
expire. Instead, it helped set up a new investment bank, Epoch
Partners, in cooperation with two brokerage rivals, Ameritrade and
TD Waterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with no deals flowing from its former partners and San
Francisco's Epoch still gearing up, Schwab is going through a tough
transition, denying its customers while promising them that better
times lie just ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we're going to have a much bigger supply (of IPO
shares) than we had before, and my sense is that it is very soon to
come,'' said Daniel Leemon, Schwab's chief strategy officer.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schwab is slowly getting back into the IPO game,
temporarily getting shares through its Epoch partner Ameritrade,
which is helping arrange several transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming IPOs include Digitas, a Boston Internet consulting
firm; and iPass, a Redwood City Web software company. Through
Ameritrade, Schwab has already sold shares of Red Hat in a
follow-up offering for the software company that had its IPO last
year.
</P>
<P>
   With deals still scarce, IPO-hungry Schwab customers are
steamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable. These guys were saying, `We're going to
have more and more IPOs,''' griped Bob Hink of Berkeley, a Schwab
IPO customer for more than two years. ``I don't even bother to look
at the site anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab took the risk of angering customers because its former
investment banking partners were doling out IPO shares with an
eyedropper, reserving the biggest allocations for their traditional
customers among big institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab typically got 1 or 2 percent or less of total IPO shares
for sale, people familiar with the matter said. In turn, that meant
Schwab disappointed most customers who wanted to get into IPOs,
because demand for shares greatly outstripped the brokerage's
supply.
</P>
<P>
   As a part-owner of Epoch, Schwab expects to get a much bigger
share of future offerings. ``Epoch should give us anywhere from
double to quadruple what we were getting before,'' said Leemon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to get access to IPO shares, rival brokers are
following similar strategies of helping to organize or forming
alliances with startup, Internet-based investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the beneficiaries of the trend are in San Francisco.
E-Offering has the backing of Menlo Park's E-Trade Group, the No. 2
online broker. And WR Hambrecht recently signed a deal to provide
IPO shares to the discount brokerage arm of Fidelity Investments,
the giant mutual fund company.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman &LR; sfgate.com.
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
