<HEADLINE>
AT ART MUSEUMS, LEARNING CAN BE FUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH HEILMAN BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Three o'clock on a sunny Sunday afternoon and my
7-year-old twins, faces contorted, were hopping before a display
case of classic Maya pottery. ``Like this, Mom?'' Alexander
wondered, as he tried to imitate the victory dance of a Maya lord,
Bird Jaguar, depicted on a clay plate.
</P>
<P>
   To my delight, William and Alexander were in the pre-Columbian
galleries of the Denver Art Museum, learning about an ancient
people, how they lived and what they created. My sons were proving
that art museums are no longer fussy, austere vaults for fine art
and cultivated adults.
</P>
<P>
   At the Denver Art Museum, art is an educational adventure. This
museum leads a pack of art museums that are inventively and
aggressively seeking to educate those who enter their once hallowed
halls.
</P>
<P>
   With a wealth of activities competing for children's time, art
museums can no longer afford to intimidate. How can a museum of
fine art lure children, their future audience, away from computers
that talk back, videogames, laser tag, ski slopes and soccer
fields? A classroom lecture or curator tour clearly cannot match
up. Just as classroom teaching techniques are evolving, museum
education programs are becoming more interactive and engaging.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Denver, families are not just shunted to some basement
filled with linoleum tables, glue, tissue paper and crayons.
Families with strollers and sometimes squealing children can be
found in once hushed galleries of Chinese porcelain or clay
Peruvian pots.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Melora McDermott-Lewis, a museum educator here, started
a ``family backpack'' program that has been emulated in art museums
across the country. Nylon backpacks in vivid colors can be checked
out free on Saturdays, Sundays and during school breaks, just as my
boys did in their Mayan gallery visit.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, museum directors would have been pleased to see a
noisy family hike right back out of the museum. Today, this art
museum is happy to send backpackers to an upstairs gallery where
they unpack puzzles, mirrors, crayons, scissors, silver and gold
packets and squeeze bottles filled with a scent held dear to the
Mayans _ chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Children and adults piece together puzzles that mimic designs on
an intricate Navajo blanket or color their own paper versions of a
flashy headdress. In the process, the museum teaches its young
visitors the significance of design, form, iconography and, from
its own selfish view, that its galleries can be comfortable places
for learning.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's dean of education, Patterson B. Williams, said that
since the ``plain brown wrapper versions of galleries and
installations of 30 years ago, there has literally been a
revolution in exhibition design, lighting, seating and interactive
educational programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams added, ``Our galleries are now places where people can
linger, hang around and actually do something, make something in
front of the works of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, art museums are setting aside millions of
dollars to educate not just their biggest audience, so-called
novice adults who know little about art, but also a new, previously
ignored audience: families with the kind of scrambling,
touch-everything toddlers and kinetically charged children that
museum directors used to prefer to see on playgrounds. The 1999
Association of Art Museum Directors Survey says that the nation's
top two art museums for education spending, the National Gallery of
Art in Washington and the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York,
spent $5.8 million and and $5.7 million, respectively. The Denver
Art Museum was 24th on the list, spending $768,240.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the Denver museum opened a new, livelier variation
of the old dusty, instructional basement, a Just for Fun Center on
its lower level. At five play stations, each featuring a world
culture from one of the museum's collections, children are
encouraged to explore, touch, erect and create the designs or
concepts presented in the upstairs galleries.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, 6-year-old Jade, in a burgundy velveteen
jumper, was flipping clamshells with the dexterity of a card shark.
She was playing a Japanese shell game similar to the card game
Memory, but the interiors of the white shells were embossed with
herons, dogs and delicate designs from the upstairs Japanese
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there are many adults who want to do something
with their kids that is `worthwhile,''' Williams said. ``We fit the
bill there. We are more worthwhile than Waterworld or an amusement
park. But we won't attract kids or their families during their
leisure time if all we are is worthwhile. We have to be worthwhile
and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time in history when we can talk on the phone while
driving, and carry our overscheduled agendas in the palms of our
hands, it is refreshing to see that art museums teach young and old
the value of taking time to contemplate the grace and novelty
around us.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott-Lewis said she knew the museum was doing something
right when a 6-year-old girl selected its galleries over Chuck E.
Cheese for her birthday celebration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
