<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-INTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Intel Joins PC Giveaway  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The folks who design and manufacture the brains inside most PCs
will soon get a chance to take one home _ with all the fixings _
for free.
<P>
   Intel Corp. yesterday became the latest company to announce
plans to provide home PCs plus Internet access for its employees.
Ford started a similar program last month, and since then, both
Delta and American airlines have boarded the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's offer, however, is the sweetest yet. While the other
companies require employees to make monthly co-payments for
Internet service, the Santa Clara chipmaker's program includes
unlimited Internet access _ via high-speed cable or DSL connections
where available _ at no charge to its workers. If employees face
extra taxes on the new perk _ as they might in some locations _ the
company even plans to cover that cost.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is also upping the ante in terms of hardware. The PCs it
will offer will feature a 667-megahertz Pentium III processor, 128
megabytes of memory, 32 megabytes of video RAM and a 20-gigabyte
hard drive. They'll come with a 17-inch monitor, a printer, a
bundle of ``productivity software'' and a video-conferencing camera
_ not to mention the employee's choice of one computer-connected
toy from the new Intel Play line.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that have previously announced similar programs have
offered much more modest configurations. Delta even plans to charge
employees for a printer. Intel will charge only those of its
staffers who want a notebook PC instead a desktop model or a
flat-panel LCD screen instead of a conventional monitor.
</P>
<P>
   All regular full-time and part-time Intel employees _
currently, &LR; about 70,000 people in all _ will be eligible for the
program. About 8,000 of them work in the Bay Area, with another
40,000 or so located elsewhere in the United States. The rest are
scattered around the world, chiefly in Israel, Ireland, Malaysia,
the Philippines, China and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who leave the company will get to keep the hardware,
though they'll lose the free Internet service. Workers who stay
will be offered new machines about every three years, spokesman
Chuck Mulloy said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ford's free-PC initiative that inspired Intel, according
to Mulloy. ``When our HR folks read about it, some of them asked
`That's a neat idea _ why can't we do that?''' he said. ``The
answer is we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel is now soliciting bids from companies to supply the
hardware and the Internet service, he said. Employees should begin
receiving their systems in July, and the roll-out should be
complete by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ford and Delta contracted with PeoplePC, a San Francisco
company that offers consumers PCs and Internet access for $25 per
month, to manage their home-PC programs. American Airlines has not
yet disclosed who will service its employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy said Intel has no data about how many of its workers
already have PCs at home. For those who do, Intel will set up a
program to facilitate donations _ of either the old system or the
new one _ to schools or nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
