r f BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      03-07 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   How Much VC You Need And How to Get It 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: Can you offer any tips on how to figure how much venture capital
you need, how to get it and what to give up for it?
<P>
   &QL; 
A: We took your three tough questions to the ``Alley to the
Valley'' conference in San Francisco earlier this week, where 28
e-commerce companies from New York's flourishing ``Silicon Alley''
made pitches to Silicon Valley financiers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third such conference and vividly illustrates that
good ideas and money flow easily across state lines. New York City
has more than 3,800 software and information technology companies,
up nearly 50 percent in two years, and most have tapped venture
capital companies around the country.
</P>
<P>
   David Gray, CEO of Wizeup.com, a New York company marketing
electronic versions of college textbooks via the Web, says it is
essential to ``know your market and do thorough financial
analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   In his case, that meant studying the college textbook market,
finding books used in classes with at least 150 students and
verifying that a minimum of 35 percent of them would switch to
digital versions if given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching your company takes as much energy and enthusiasm as
running for elected office although you need to go beyond sound
bites and not just bad-mouth your competitors. Gray, who visited a
lot of venture and angel investor forums, was initially turned down
by about 20 potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear `no' a lot, especially in the venture capital
community,'' Gray recalls. ``You have to be able to handle
rejection. At the end of the day, you have to believe in yourself
and your vision. And every day, you have to be willing to scratch,
claw and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   After his early difficulties attracting investors, Gray narrowed
his focus and went after investors who understood his company's
mission and might be interested in partnering with him.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first $500,000 seed capital in mid-1998 from a
Michigan holding company with a publishing arm. Then, last June, he
got $2 million in second-round financing from Enigma Systems, a
Boston company that produces online manuals for jet engine
manufacturers and was interested in expanding its market through a
strategic partnership with Wizeup.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gray is searching for $12 million and has lined up some VC
investors. He also hired a consultant with a good track record as a
financial matchmaker so that he can spend most of his time building
his company. Gray is paying the consultant both cash and stock in
Wizeup.
</P>
<P>
   There is no magic formula on how much ownership to give up for
how much money. ``You have to give up enough to make the investor
feel the risk does not outweigh the potential reward,'' Gray
advises. ``Private equity investors often look for a 10-times
return on their investment over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Millard, head of investment banking for Prudential
Securities Inc., suggests, ``It's always better to own a smaller
percentage of a very large pie than 100 percent of nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other financiers also believe it is often best to ``give
up some valuation'' to find the right partner. That means joining
forces with those who have great contacts and credibility and who
you will enjoy working with even if it means getting less money or
retaining a smaller ownership stake.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond having a brilliant idea, Millard said it is essential
that entrepreneurs explain very clearly just how they are going to
be profitable. That requires careful analysis of the size of the
market and how much money, how many people and how long it will
take to capture a specific part of it.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get in the door of a VC firm, Millard suggests
asking yourself two key questions: Are you the right person to do
the knocking? Are their flaws in your business plan?
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Ellman, a partner of former American Express CEO James
Robinson at RRE Ventures in New York, advises raising ``as much as
it takes to get you to the next significant valuation event.''
</P>
<P>
   That might mean $500,000 to $2 million in seed capital from
angel investors to turn a business plan into a ``beta'' test
program and proving the concept with a couple of customers.
</P>
<P>
   In the next round, when venture capital investors might put in
$5 million to $15 million to build the company, Ellman said
entrepreneurs must typically part with a 20 percent to 33 percent
stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
   He recommends contacting potential financiers through a source
they already know and taking money from those who can be most
helpful to you.
</P>
<P>
   Your financial partners should understand your market, have
experience building companies similar to yours and help you create
strategic alliances. Also make sure the personal chemistry is
correct since you'll be spending a lot of time together.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of sources of information on VCs and startups.
Ellman's favorites include Red Herring, Upside, Business 2.0,
Industry Standard and AlleyCat News, which sponsored this week's
``Alley to the Valley'' conference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
