374.47 points on investors' fears that rising oil prices combined
with higher interest rates may do significant damage to corporate
profits. The fall began when Procter &AMP; Gamble, one of the nation's
biggest and best-known companies and one of the 30 stocks in the
Dow, said that its earnings in the current quarter would come in
well below the levels expected by Wall Street analysts. By Gretchen
Morgenson and Kenneth N. Gilpin. (The story has moved in ``f'' news
file.) 1,300 words.
