<P>
   CLINTON-PAKISTAN (Washington) _ Arguing that important national
security interests would be jeopardized if President Clinton stayed
away, the White House announces that he will visit Pakistan ``for a
few hours'' at the end of his lengthier trip to India later this
month. The decision is based on the need to urge the Pakistani
military government to work toward resolving the heightened
conflict with India over Kashmir and to clamp down on terrorism,
officials said. By Jane Perlez. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT13.
</P>
<P>
   SEe also PAKISTAN-U.S.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MEDIA (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ The South African
Human Rights Commission holds a hearing on racism in the media;
some see this as part of a government effort to pressure the press
into more favorable coverage. By Rachel Swarns. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-UNREST (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Dozens of people were
wounded in shootings and grenade attacks in the divided town of
Mitrovica, among them French peacekeepers and both ethnic Albanian
and Serb civilians. What began as a street brawl escalated into a
number of retaliatory attacks between ethnic Serbs and Albanians,
catching the peacekeepers in the middle. By Carlotta Gall. (The
story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-DRESDNER (Frankfurt, Germany) _ In a move that could
lead to one of the biggest job reductions yet in Europe, Deutsche
Bank AG plans to acquire a big German domestic rival, Dresdner Bank
AG, in a deal potentially worth more than $30 billion. By Edmund L.
Andrews. (The story has moved in ``f'' news file.) 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-GERMANY (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Capitulating to demands from
the United States, Germany withdraws its candidate for managing
director of the IMF but proposes someone who may not be much more
popular. By Edmund L. Andrews. (The story has moved in ``f'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   FAA-CONGRESS (Washington) _ House and Senate negotiators agree
on a three-year plan that would increase spending on air traffic
control and on aid to airports by 30 percent and would let local
airport authorities increase departure taxes to pay for additional
improvements. By Matthew L. Wald. (The story has moved in ``w''
news file.)
</P>
