<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEM-MAIN08-COX     03-07 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-MAIN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE TAKES COMMAND OF DEMOCRATIC RACE
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore took command of the
Democratic presidential race Tuesday, apparently sweeping to
lopsided victories in states from coast to coast and forcing Bill
Bradley to assess whether to continue his challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Gore immediately pivoted to a general election strategy,
planning trips in the coming days that target the independent
voters that were attracted to GOP upstart John McCain and Hispanic
voters that are crucial to a general election victory in key
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is full tonight,'' Gore declared in a victory speech
that not only rallied Democrats but urged independents to ``join us
now.''
</P>
<P>
   He also saluted Bradley, calling him a ``good man,'' adding,
``Anybody who has heard Bill Bradley throughout this campaign has
come away from the experience moved and touched by the strength of
his commitment to healing the divisions in our country, especially
divisions based on race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore won every core Democratic constituency in what is likely to
be his last face-to-face contest with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gathered in New York to await the final results of the voting,
Bradley supporters grumbled about ``entrenched power'' supporting
the vice president. But according to network television polls, Gore
also won African Americans, Jews, Hispanics, gays, labor and women,
all key elements of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's support came almost exclusively from anti-Clinton
Democrats, not a large constituency in a party that, despite the
impeachment of President Clinton, has presided over the longest
economic expansion in history.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's victories in the largest primary voting of the year
reflected a remarkable comeback from the days last summer when his
campaign was viewed as weak and ineffective in the face of a
surprisingly strong challenge from Bradley and the popularity of
the relatively unknown George W. Bush, the GOP front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   But a disciplined and energetic Gore powered past Bradley on
Tuesday. And in a poll published Tuesday by the Wall Street
Journal, Gore erased the double digit lead Bush had on him last
summer. The latest Wall Street Journal poll shows the two in a
46-46 percent tie with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his family joined hundreds of fellow Tennesseans at a
downtown Nashville hotel to celebrate one of the biggest victories
of his 24-year career in politics, one that brings him a step
closer to the nomination he first sought in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Gore registered convincing margins of victory in New York,
Georgia and Ohio, three of the most important states in the
so-called Super Tuesday primary. He also rolled up victories in
Connecticut, Massachusetts, Maryland, Vermont, Maine and Missouri,
Bradley's native state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, polls showed him leading in California, the largest
of the 15 states that held Democratic primaries Tuesday and the one
state critical to his strategy for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley absorbed Tuesday's crushing returns in a hotel room in
New York City, the place where he once reigned as one of the
nation's greatest basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   Glum supporters, including some of Bradley's former NBA
teammates from his days with the New York Knicks, gathered at the
Sheraton New York Hotel and Towers to offer their support to the
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's spokesman, Eric Hauser, said the campaign would issue
a statement Wednesday announcing the candidate's schedule for
Thursday and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate himself planned to spend Wednesday at home in New
Jersey, and was declining all media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Before the election returns came in, Bradley had clung to slim
hopes that a handful of victories in the New England could sustain
his candidacy and perhaps give him enough life to continue on to
the March 14 primary balloting.
</P>
<P>
   But it became clear early in the evening that those hopes would
be dashed. The vice president carried all the New England states
handily. Bradley even lost in his native Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley launched his uphill campaign against Gore in December
1998. Others considered the race, but calculated that a sitting
vice president would be too difficult to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley scored early success in the fund-raising arena, raising
almost as much money as Gore and threatening the vice president
with positive poll numbers in New Hampshire, site of the nation's
first primary.
</P>
<P>
   Pledging to be a candidate of ``big ideas,'' Bradley ran on a
plan to provide health insurance to the nation's poor, enact
stricter gun control and replace the campaign finance laws with a
system of public financing.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley invested heavily in Iowa and lost. The defeat,
coupled with Sen. John McCain's maverick appeal, contributed to
Bradley's loss in New Hampshire. From then on, Bradley found it
difficult to regain his footing in a national media environment
where all the focus was on McCain and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of this is that we had an extraordinarily hard
task in front of us,'' said Anita Dunn, Bradley's communications
director. ``We knew it would not be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett's e-mail address is kenf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
