<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9825 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BLUEPLANET-BLUEPLANET     03-07 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUEPLANET-BLUEPLANET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Independent Game Developers Look for the Perfect Pitch  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Daniel Lucas usually gets his phone calls returned because of one
word: Tetris.
<P>
   For the past three years his company, Blue Planet Software, has
made or licensed a half-dozen video-console and PC games based on
the addictive, falling-block puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to original titles, executives at the San
Francisco firm fight a battle not unlike an independent filmmaker
trying to woo a major studio. They cajole, beg, wheedle _ whatever
you want to call it _ the large publishers who actually distribute
and market most game titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parallels between our business and the movie business are
striking,'' said Lucas, Blue Planet's vice president of
development. ``There's a million ideas out there, but you try to
pitch one, and no one wants to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Planet has already shown its latest work-in-progress,
code-named Genesis, to liaisons _ who often act as gatekeepers _ at
three or four publishers. At this week's Game Developers Conference
in San Jose, the company will pitch the game to a couple of
publishers' marketing and sales teams in the hopes of working out a
deal by this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is a chance for developers _ about 10,000 strong
this year _ to network with one another, check out the newest in
hardware and software and rub elbows with some of the biggest names
in the business including Sony, Sega and Electronic Arts.
</P>
<P>
   A less well-known facet of the conference, but one important to
the tiniest developers, is the second annual Independent Games
Festival. Much like the film industry's Sundance Film Festival, the
festival is designed specifically to help small shops gain the
attention of a publisher _ an increasingly difficult task as
publishers consolidate and the cost of games skyrockets.
</P>
<P>
   With consumers expected to spend an estimated $7 billion this
year on computer and video games _ more than on movie tickets _ the
industry is ramping up for an unprecedented period of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But one important link within the chain won't necessarily share
in the bounty.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party game developers, the small companies that originate
ideas, must land a contract with a deep-pocketed publisher _ like
Redwood City's Electronic Arts _ to cover the multimillion-dollar
expense of actually getting the game to market.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas small firms brainstorm an idea, draw conceptuals and
construct a rough version of a game, most often it's the publisher
who picks up the tab for creating the final version, plus
advertising, manufacturing, packaging and distribution _ costs that
can run into the millions.
</P>
<P>
   The outside developer usually gets its costs covered and
royalties from game sales. But only about 100 of the roughly 1,500
games that premiered last year were profitable. And only a handful
reached the stratospheric sales _ 800,000 or 1 million units _ to
land them on mainstream magazine covers.
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, it's no wonder publishers want to make
sure the next title they scoop up from an external developer has at
least a chance of becoming the next Tomb Raider, the popular
Indiana Jones-like game starring the buxom Lara Croft.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to get the ball rolling, a small developer usually
has to create a workable version of the game to show a publisher.
Such a prototype can be a costly and time-consuming proposition _
especially when the newest PCs and consoles require more work and
larger teams to take advantage of their cutting-edge capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible to survive in today's market on your
own,'' said Ben Rinaldi, senior editor at GameWeek Magazine. An
independent developer needs ``not just the funding but the
technology and experience that comes from being part of a bigger
corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   Seed, a third-person adventure game from San Mateo's Human Soft,
is among nine titles vying for prizes and publicity at the
Independent Games Festival. Human Soft, which incorporates a unique
feature _ real-time shadows _ into Seed's plot, was a finalist last
year as well.
</P>
<P>
   But with little experience developing for consoles, Human Soft
has had a hard time landing a publisher. Consoles like Sega's
Dreamcast and Sony's PlayStation are commanding more and more of
the game market. And although Human Soft has had eight titles
published for the PC, it hasn't had a major hit.
</P>
<P>
   Rinaldi says an external developer typically faces three
scenarios: if successful, it's mostly likely purchased or it signs
a long-term contract with a big publisher. If unsuccessful, often
it folds.
</P>
<P>
   Any of those options can be a hard pill to swallow for a small
game outfit _ usually a band of independent-minded artists and
programmers who relish work outside a corporate structure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most would jump at the chance to sign a lucrative deal
with the Activisions or Sonys of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, San Rafael developer Andrew Leker sold his strategy
game Resurrection to Japan's Sega and got a job further developing
the game at the U.S. headquarters of the maker of Sonic the
Hedgehog.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' he said. ``I don't have to spend 30 to 40
percent of my time trying to market my game to publishers. And I
don't have to sweat getting paid.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't any hard figures on the number of small game
developers out there _ mainly because so many are two- or
three-person operations in basements across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But it's safe to say that even if they forge a publishing deal
and remain independent, many won't recoup more than their costs
after 18 months of grueling hours completing a title _ setting them
up for another hardscrabble fight to fund another game.
</P>
<P>
   Developers' royalties, or a piece of the game's sales, vary
considerably and depend on the platform, how much work the
developer does, and whether they own the license to the game. Blue
Planet's Lucas says it ranges between 10 and 30 percent. But often
those royalties don't kick in until after the publisher has made
back its costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more common actually not to make a profit,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Some insiders draw parallels between the gaming and recording
industries. Publishers or record labels fork over the big bucks to
fund a project; but they also reap the most rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Arts spokesman Jeff Brown admits commercial potential
is among the top factors when considering an outside game. But
there are other criteria: the team behind the title, their track
record and the potential for multiplayer or online gaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also at a point in this industry when the demographics
are getting much broader to include women and older people, so
we're looking for titles that will help us continue that trend,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   When independent firms dream, it's often of one of the
industry's best-known Cinderella stories: Cyan Inc. The four-person
Washington firm, known mainly for edu-tainment titles, created
Myst, one of the first adult-oriented adventure games, in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Infused with groundbreaking graphics and a ``submersive''
environment, Myst catapulted Cyan and its publisher, Broderbund,
into the limelight and inspired a whole generation of indie
developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was a milestone in the industry,'' said Michael
Arrington, director of software research at Jon Peddie Associates,
a Mill Valley firm that tracks digital media. ``It was the first
big indie game and it established how (developers and publishers)
worked together.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyan, run by brothers Robyn and Rand Miller, forged a deal with
Novato's Broderbund (now a unit of toy giant Mattel) to publish
Myst for the PC and Macintosh. Since it was released in November
1993, it has become the most popular PC title of all time, selling
about 7 million units and raking in $146 million.
</P>
<P>
   But even Myst had its doubters in the beginning. Cyan shopped
the title around for about a year before it signed on with
Broderbund. Cyan officials say several publishers turned it down
largely because the market for such a plot-driven game hadn't been
proven.
</P>
<P>
   In Myst, and its successor Riven, the player must determine _
through a series of fantasy-world puzzles _ which of two brothers
is the good guy and which is the bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were presenting a game heavily centered on a story, and
that took a little bit of time for publishers to grapple with,''
said Chris Brandkamp, Cyan's vice president of licensing and
development.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Planet would be ecstatic if Genesis attracts a fraction of
Myst's audience.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the company estimates it has spent three or four months
and about $150,000 on the strategy game, which pits city against
country. It needs another year to 18 months and several million
dollars to finalize it _ which is why the company needs to find a
well-funded publisher.
</P>
<P>
   In Genesis, players plant ``seeds'' _ gray representing city and
green representing country _ in a particular area. The player who
first controls 50 percent of a zone _ either with skyscrapers or
forests, wins. Blue Planet officials are optimistic that they'll
find a publisher in coming months and subsequently reduce their
financial reliance on the Tetris franchise, which accounts for more
than 90 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   But they know what failure tastes like.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months ago, Blue Planet scrapped a fantasy, role-playing
game called Black Onyx after searching for a publisher for about a
year. Sketches of medieval-style weapons, costumes and characters
still cover a few walls at the company's Geary Street headquarters.
Ironically, those offices housed a now-defunct game company called
Velocity before Blue Planet moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas guesses that Blue Planet sank a year, and hundreds of
thousands of dollars, into Black Onyx.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he understands why publishers are so picky. In a previous
life, he reviewed game pitches for Alameda's Microprose, now a
Hasbro brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get hundreds of pitches a year ... it's really hard,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at kzito &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
