<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-MCCAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN CONTINUES ON HIS OWN UNIQUE MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the beginning, it was much simpler,
stripped-down, fun.
</P>
<P>
   All over New Hampshire, people knew what Senator John McCain
stood for, and it wasn't about ideology or policy or legislation.
Voters said the same thing over and over again. He is honest. He is
brave. He has integrity. He has my vote.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform? Very important, they all said. But more
important that he has the guts to take it on.
</P>
<P>
   More than a hundred town hall meetings in New Hampshire and
McCain had shaken hands and given that rigid two-thumbs-up to a
huge swath of the state's voters. They had seen him for themselves,
squeezed his shoulder, gotten the wink.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, there have been vast tracts of ground to
cover, and McCain hasn't been able to get to as many people as he
would like to make them his. Forced to rely on less old-fashioned
politics -- on television, where money counts for more, and where
he can be stiff and awkward, more distant from the crowds from whom
he draws his energy and focus, he has struggled.
</P>
<P>
   That glorious night in New Hampshire, McCain so awed by his own
achievement that he was almost subdued, seems long ago now, indeed.
Back then, it seemed his media strategist was right when he said
``inevitability died in the snows of New Hampshire tonight.'' Now
the snow has melted and after five weeks of tumultous campaigning,
things seem much the same as they were before his campaign took
off.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful symbols and inside jokes were born in the months
leading up to his spectacular New Hampshire victory, and they
helped sustain the campaign in the states beyond.
</P>
<P>
   There was the bus, of course. In the last month, awe-struck fans
started climbing aboard it at rallies to snap pictures by his red
swivel seat, though McCain was nowhere near it. A state trooper
pulled it over in South Carolina, jeopardizing his job because he
thought the senator might be on board, and he wanted to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   The one-liners had traveled almost as many miles as the Straight
Talk Express. The ``I want Republicans, Democrats, Libertarians,
Vegetarians'' line pawned a legion of wiseacre signs at rallies.
Ones that said ``Vegetarians for John McCain'' appeared first. By
Tuesday, the vegetarians were joined by Ukranians, Hippies,
Omnivores and Carnivores.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has taken great pleasure in pointing them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way, `Soccer Moms for McCain,' McCain said at a rally
in San Diego Monday. ``Up in Santa Clara this morning we had
`Carnivores for McCain.' In Cleveland we had `Ukranians for
McCain.' I'm telling ya,'' he said, laughing, ``We are assembling a
coalition never seen before in the history of American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, has been McCain's greatest strength, and one of
his biggest weaknesses. Texas Governor George W. Bush has tried to
make the Senator's broad appeal his liability. McCain's relative
weakness among Republican voters in most states has vindicated the
governor. And, then another funny sign appeared, saying something
that in an ordinary campaign, should have been a given:
``Republicans for McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   In the waning days of his campaign before Tuesday's primaries,
McCain, the kind of man who absorbs a blow and barrels forward, was
unusally reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back, I wish I hadn't done so many things, but I'm
glad I did so many other things. Come on, you can't complain and
you can't explain. If you do, you diminish what you tried to do.
I'm happy. I'm the three percent guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He did allow that there have been other mistakes. Maybe the
joking comment about Robertson and Falwell being evil. Maybe his
comment to a California newspaper saying he would be unlikely to
repeal Roe v Wade.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much would it have to do with my flip remark about evil?''
he ventured. ``How much would it have to do with my statements to
the San Francisco Chronicle? How much has to do with all the
idiotic things I've said in this campaign?''
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't going to let those things drive him crazy. He
hadn't gotten this far, in his life and in this campaign, by
dwelling on things. He had battles to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, with two friends of Bush buying $2.5 million worth
of advertising to criticize McCain's environmental record, the
senator seemed to be seething at times, his usually clenched jaw
grinding away as he answered reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain took something from that latest onslaught: a new
focus, he said. See? he told audiences everywhere he went. Those
advertisments are exactly why he wants campaign finance reform.
McCain said Bush had handed his signature issue back to him.
</P>
<P>
   It was not quite the noble, anti-establishment message that had
so inspired New Hampshire's voters, but McCain seemed pleased at
least to be able to speak to his signature issue.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides, who over the weekend seemed angry and dejected at
the advertising that may have been their death knell, were at peace
Tuesday. They were proud of what they had done, and, before the
final results came in, were looking forward to primaries in
Colorado, Illinois and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be prouder of what John and the campaign
accomplished today and in the future'' political director John
Weaver said. ``We struck a chord with the American people. There's
a hunger in the country for someone like him.''
</P>
<P>
   If McCain, whose comments on Bush have grown ever more venomous
this week does not seem like the kind of man who will easily go
back to the bosom of the establishment and stand beside Bush if he
is the nominee, he is also not the kind of man to dwell on his
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   On his bus in central California last week, while he was in the
throes of several controversies, and on hold with a radio
interviewer about to grill him for a long time about his views on
abortion, McCain was surrounded by reporters, heads down, furiously
scribbling in their notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plum trees!'' he said to them, pointing out the window as the
rows of blossom-covered trees rushed by. ``You're missing a lot of
plum trees out there, and they're all blossoming. Millions of
'em.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
