<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SUPER-ANALYSIS08-COX     03-07 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-ANALYSIS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mavericks have left their mark
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the beefs the experts had with so many states
voting early was that it would overshadow the early primaries and
settle the party nominations before there could really be a race.
That didn't come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   This year's early contests, punctuated by the Republican
primaries in New Hampshire and South Carolina, produced a
nomination race that was sharp-elbowed and intense, if it was short
and a mismatch, moneywise. While the Democratic race hasn't been as
scintillating, it still was a spirited competition in which Vice
President Al Gore _ outspent by his challenger, former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley _ was forced to step up his game to ensure what
could have been a perfunctory endorsement by his party.
</P>
<P>
   The other complaint about the front-loaded primary system was
that it would give the nation two nominees very early, guaranteeing
a long general election campaign with enough time for both
candidates to get in a lot of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   At least part of that prediction fell into place Tuesday night,
as the two front-runners piled on big victories that made their
nominations inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has not been entirely clear about how long he will go on,
but it's safe to say that the longest general election campaign in
memory has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Outright regional bias might be a thing of the past like, say,
bans on interracial dating. But some voters who have had their fill
of Bill Clinton and a host of Southern Republicans in Congress do
express a preference for a non-Southerner, for a change.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to get the South entirely out of the political
equation. This will be a race between the Southerner gone north _
the son of Tennessee raised in a Washington hotel _ vs. the
Northerner come South _ a Connecticut senator's grandson brought up
in the oil patch.
</P>
<P>
   These are two candidates who both express a passionate interest
in education issues and how to launch a nation of students into the
coming century. Yet the educational institution that has been the
focal point of the most heated debate in the nominating process has
been a Bible college in upstate South Carolina with the prosaic
name of Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   More has been said in presidential debates this year about
whether the Confederate flag should fly over Southern statehouses
than whether the nation should launch a Mars exploration effort in
the next decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   Racism and religious intolerance are still burning issues, and
Bob Jones U. and the Confederate battle flag are still powerful
symbols. Yet at some point, voters elsewhere in the country are
bound to wonder when the preoccupations of this campaign year catch
up with what concerns them most directly.
</P>
<P>
   This past week has seen some spectacular milestones in
moderation. There was the Rev. Jerry Falwell on television Sunday,
declaring he didn't think Bill Clinton was a murderer and never had
thought so. There was the president of BJU, announcing there really
wasn't anything in the Bible that prohibited interracial dating,
and the ban was a bother, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   These may seem like small things, but no one dreamed they would
see the like before McCain made the religious right, which had
already targeted him, an issue. Small social progress was not
accompanied by success at the polls, and McCain on Tuesday met the
fate of a maverick in a party that has come to see itself as the
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   But the issues McCain set in motion in the Republican primaries
are likely to roll through this long general election campaign.
McCain promised he would beat Gore like a drum, but in the vice
president's rhetoric over the next few months he may hear the
echoes of his own campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
