u a BC-DARTMOUTH-CHEATING-BO     03-07 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARTMOUTH-CHEATING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARTMOUTH STUDENTS SUPPORTED IN ENTRAPMENT CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teaching assistants in the class of Rex Dwyer, Dartmouth
College's embattled visiting computer science professor, Tuesday
backed students in charging him with entrapping them in one of the
Ivy League's worst cheating scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer, a North Carolina State College professor on sabbatical,
has accused 78 students in his introductory computer science class
of cheating on a homework assignment by downloading answers he
placed on an unsecured Web site. Students, however, believe Dwyer
put them there so students would find them, essentially setting
them up for a fall because the class was consistently disrespectful
to him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the college begins hearing the alleged cheating cases
this week, Dwyer's main teaching assistant and students who graded
tests and other assignments in the class describe the professor as
disorganized, vengeful, and out to get the unruly students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very angry at the class, and at the time he appeared to
take quite a bit of pride in catching everyone,'' wrote David
Wagner, the lead teaching assistant in the class of 178 students,
in an e-mail to The Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview before attending the first student hearings
Tuesday, Dwyer defended both his teaching methods and the integrity
of his accusations against the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been personally very painful to me,'' Dwyer said. ``I
guess I wanted to get away from here at the end of the semester.
But I certainly didn't want to find out everyone was cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues at North Carolina State also vouched for Dwyer's
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be really surprised if he tried to entrap the kids,''
said Alan L. Tharp, chair of the computer science department at
North Carolina State in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cousins, director of the North Carolina State's office of
student conduct, said he has only heard praise for Dwyer's
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any concerns with professor Dwyer's ability to do
the right thing,'' Cousins said.
</P>
<P>
   At Dartmouth, where Dwyer taught two courses as a visiting
professor this term, administrators said they would reserve
judgment on the scandal until after the accused students are given
a fair hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But in e-mails and telephone conversations, four of Dwyer's 12
assistants said the cheating charges are unfair and they're
relieved the professor resigned from teaching two computer science
courses at Dartmouth. The other eight assistants did not respond to
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, the lead teaching assistant, said he initially got along
well with Dwyer, who presided over a class where students felt free
to pass around pornographic magazines, read newspapers during
class, and jeer at him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in early February, Wagner's opinion of Dwyer changed, he
said. Before the professor disclosed to the class that some
students stole the solution to homework assignment No. 4 off an
unencrypted Web site, he told the teaching assistants that he had
uncovered cheating in the class and threatened them with
disciplinary action if they didn't keep the secret, Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, this was, in part, getting back at the class for
their ongoing unruliness and lack of respect towards him,'' Wagner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Wagner went public with his concerns to the campus
newspaper, he said Dwyer sought revenge, e-mailing prominent
faculty members, including the teaching assistant's advisor,
telling them Wagner's performance in the classroom was poor.
</P>
<P>
   But other assistants backed Wagner and questioned Dwyer's
motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, students should not have done some of the things they
did,'' said Richard M. Adams Jr., an undergraduate teaching
assistant, ``but the fact that he left the information public,
didn't specifically outlaw such actions, coupled with the fact that
the class was so poorly taught'' was ``ridiculous'' and seemed to
invite students to cheat.
</P>
<P>
   Lubna Ammar, another undergraduate who helped Dwyer by grading
assignments, agreed that something was very askew in Computer
Science 4. ``I think the point is he left it up on the Web site,''
she said. ``It's like leaving the answers on the board during a
test. And this wasn't even a test; it was a homework.''
</P>
<P>
   To Sam Desai, another teaching assistant, it's simple: the
professor was striking back at disrespectful students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I completely agree with the students,'' he said. ``The
animosity just reached that point. So he set them up.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dwyer, who resorted to ringing a Tibetan prayer bell to get
the rowdy class's attention, the accusations of entrapment on top
of what he says was blatant cheating on the students' part adds
insult to injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very disheartening, and not anything I wanted to be
involved in,'' said Dwyer, adding that he has been sent threatening
e-mails by Dartmouth students. ``It's the last thing I wanted out
of my sabbatacial. There's not an academic who would want to deal
with this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm not the most popular guy on campus, and most of
the students I see don't acknowledge me. I was a sort of nonentity
before and a nonentity now.''
</P>
<P>
   While he agreed that the assignment may have been above his
students' education level, he rejects the idea that it was an
excuse for for many of them to take answers off the class' Web
site, which he left unprotected for two days after showing it to
students in class.
</P>
<P>
   He said two hours after class on February 2, at least 20
students had already downloaded the answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many just decided they wanted to cheat and not do any work,''
Dwyer said. ``And that's what's most offensive about this. These
were not students who ran into trouble. They just decided they
didn't want to do the assignment, they wanted to steal it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
