u f BC-MICROSOFT-TRADEGROUP-     03-07 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRADEGROUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT QUITS TRADE GROUP AFTER DISPUTE OVER ANTITRUST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. quit the nation's oldest and largest software
industry trade association Tuesday after a long-running dispute
over the group's support for the government in the Microsoft
antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   The Software and Information Industry Association, formerly
known as the Software Publishers Association, filed a
friend-of-the-court brief in February on behalf of the Justice
Department, arguing that Microsoft had a monopoly in personal
computer operating systems and used it to expand its market power.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the trade group Tuesday, Robert Herbold,
Microsoft's chief operating officer, said he was resigning because
the company believed that the software trade association had become
totally focused on the antitrust issue and that its efforts on
other policy issues have ``regrettably withered away.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbold noted that the ``SPA and SIIA management have worked
directly against Microsoft on competition issues.'' But, he said,
``As long as the organization was also accomplishing at least some
other useful goals for the industry as a whole, we thought it made
sense for Microsoft to remain a member, despite this area of
disagreement.'' Herbold, a member of the association's board, added
that Microsoft had come to believe that was no longer true.
</P>
<P>
   In a fiery reply, Ken Wasch, the group's president, said that by
quitting, ``Microsoft has again proven that their tactics resemble
that of a schoolyard bully.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade group's board voted two years ago to support the
government in the antitrust case, Wasch said its relationship with
Microsoft had been ``a difficult one, much like the U.S.
relationship with China.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter of resignation, Herbold said the group was
increasingly ineffective and that its membership was ``sagging.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasch replied that the Software and Information Industry
Association was ``thriving.'' Microsoft paid membership fees of
$125,000 a year. The trade group's annual budget is about $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's stock jumped more than 5 percent at one point
Tuesday after a Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. analyst, Rick Sherlund,
released a research memo suggesting that settlement talks with the
government in the antitrust case ``may be heating up.'' The stock
price fell back to $92.875, an increase of 2.48 percent, by the
close of the regular trading day.
</P>
<P>
   The shadow of the antitrust suit has pushed Microsoft's share
price down 25 percent from its 52-week high in recent weeks despite
the introduction of its Windows 2000 operating system in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TEACHER-SHORTAGE-4     03-07 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-SHORTAGE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PLAN AIMS TO DRAW MORE TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Senate's Republican leaders proposed a plan
Tuesday to ease the looming teacher shortage in New York state that
seeks to provide salary bonuses, scholarships and other financial
incentives to draw teachers to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is similar to one that Gov. George Pataki, a
Republican, proposed earlier this year. It received a warm
reception from the Democratic leaders of the Assembly, increasing
the likelihood that it will pass in one form or another during the
current legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the Senate plan calls for providing cash grants to
college students who agree to teach for four years in public
schools that are facing a particularly severe shortage of teachers.
That program would provide each of those students $3,400 annually
for four years to help them repay college loans or to supplement
their income.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan also calls for creating a tuition assistance
program to help the state's 11,500 uncertified teachers cover the
costs of college courses they must complete to become fully
licensed teachers. That program would provide uncertified teachers
up to $2,000 each to complete their required course work.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the two initiatives would cost the state about
$25 million a year, and would help it attract more than 50,000 new
teachers into the public school system over the next 10 years,
according to Senate officials.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal comes as New York City faces the worst teacher
shortage in its history. The city's public school system is
expected to lose more than half of its 78,000 teachers over the
next five years as an unusually high number of them, 54,000, reach
age 55 and become eligible for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Bruno, the Republican majority leader, urged adoption of
the measure, saying the state stands to lose many of its most
experienced teachers. ``We all recognize that there is a crisis in
New York with the teacher shortage,'' he said. ``What we're talking
about is bringing teachers back into the system.''
</P>
<P>
   New York is not the only state grappling with a potential
shortage of teachers. From Massachusetts to Texas to California,
officials are offering a host of financial incentives to woo
prospective teachers into the public schools and to keep good ones
from fleeing to other states or professions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate proposal received tempered support from the
governor's office. ``We are pleased the Senate's plan reflects the
governor's priorities,'' said Charles Deister, a spokesman for
Pataki. ``But as for the details of their plan, we'll have to take
a look at it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the plan drew greater enthusiasm among Democratic leaders of
the Assembly, who said they intended to release their own plan to
address the teacher shortage. ``The speaker is committed to
education,'' said Patricia Lynch, a spokeswoman for Sheldon Silver,
the Assembly speaker. ``Obviously, teacher recruitment and
retention is an important component of any plan that addresses
education in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key provision of the Senate plan would eliminate the
penalties that many retired teachers now face if they return to
work. Under current state law, retirees lose $1 of their pension
benefits for every $1 they earn beyond $17,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate proposal would allow retired teachers to return to
the schools without giving up any of their retirement benefits, at
no cost to the state. The legislation is intended to deal with a
longstanding policy that critics say discourages teachers from
continuing to work after they reach normal retirement age and begin
drawing pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan also calls for providing an annual bonus of
$10,000 to experienced teachers who agree to teach in
low-performing schools. To qualify for the bonus, a teacher must be
certified under a series of national standards that are more
rigorous than the state's standards. Republican Senate leaders said
the purpose of the program was to ensure that relatively new
teachers in those schools had experienced colleagues to advise
them. That program is expected to cost the state $10 million a year
and benefit about 1,000 teachers annually.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan would also give teachers five years to earn the
master's degree needed in New York to complete certification
requirements. If approved, the measure would effectively scrap a
proposal by state education officials to reduce to two years the
time teachers are given to earn the degree. Leaders in the Senate
contend that the education officials' proposal would aggravate the
teacher shortage in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan embraces a key element in Pataki's proposal:
encouraging college students to perform volunteer work in the
state's struggling inner-city schools, like tutoring children
enrolled in summer programs. In return, the college students would
earn college credits.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan drew praise from the powerful teachers' union,
New York State United Teachers, a group with considerable political
clout in the Capitol, as well as from Richard P. Mills, the state's
commissioner of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate proposal would be an important step in helping
bring teachers to the areas of the state that need them the most,''
Mills said. ``The proposal has come at a good time to support
higher standards and improve student achievement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
