<HEADER>
A9833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-ELN-NEWENGLAND-BOS &LR;      03-07 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE FAVORS MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 ENGLAND-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY AND TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts can start printing the bumper stickers:
``Don't blame us, we voted for McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever willing to ignore national trends, Massachusetts primary
voters reaffirmed their political independence Tuesday, giving
Arizona Senator John McCain his biggest margin of victory on a day
of big losses from coast to coast to his Republican rival, Texas
Governor George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the McCain stronghold of New England _ where, until
recently, he seemed poised for a sweep of all five states holding
primaries _ Bush made late inroads, in Rhode Island and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore's nationwide rout
of former Senator Bill Bradley extended throughout New England.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said McCain's strength in Massachusetts and
its neighboring states reflects an independent streak in the region
that rewards anti-establishment candidates such as the Arizona
senator, who called for sweeping campaign finance reform and
denounced pork-barrel spending.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly the case in Massachusetts, the only state
won by Democratic presidential nominee George McGovern in 1972 _ a
tidbit of political history that spawned ``Don't blame me, I voted
for McGovern'' bumper stickers as Watergate unfolded and President
Nixon's administration crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more voters register as independents than Democrats and
Republicans combined in the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts has a lot of intellectual pride,'' said John
Berg, a professor of government at Suffolk University. ``It's a
state where people haven't felt comfortable at all about following
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's failure to sweep New England, said others, was a
sign of how far his once-rocketing campaign has fallen since his
Feb. 1 upset victory over Bush in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for McCain to have made that argument to fight on, he
needed that New England sweep,'' said Lou DiNatale, a political
analyst at the University of Massachusetts' McCormack Institute for
Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Berg said that despite the natural inclination of New England's
independent voters to back McCain, the Arizonan's campaign had lost
its way in recent weeks and enthusiasm dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People following the campaign have been getting more and more
of a sense over the last couple of weeks that it was really all
over already,'' Berg said. ``People like underdogs _ they don't
like losers.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Bradley was also a victim of perceptions that his
campaign was a lost cause and was doubly damaged by McCain's
appeals to the independents Bradley had once hoped to enlist.
</P>
<P>
   Berg said that among independents, who were able to vote for
either Democrats or Republicans in every New England state except
Connecticut, ``only one or the other of the insurgent candidates
can do well. . . . McCain probably took most of those votes from
Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the excitment over McCain, most polling stations in
Massachusetts were quiet.
</P>
<P>
   At the Talbot School in Weymouth, for example, there were no
signs, no lines, no volunteers outside during late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Voters tried to change their enrollment status on the spot to
vote for McCain, not knowing that they had missed the deadline to
do so by many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confused,'' said one voter who declined to give her
name. ``I didn't know you had to go fill out a card first.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustrated woman left without casting a ballot for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the rest of New England voted.
</P>
<P>
   --Maine. Bush did not visit the state once to campaign. But no
matter. This is where the Bush family spends its summers, in
Kennebunkport, and it was the only New England state that chose the
Texas governor over McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Maine voters are independents, the primary allows
only party members to cast ballots, which also helped Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 14 GOP delegates are apportioned according to vote,
unless a candidate gets more than 50 percent and would then win all
the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won the state and its 23 Democratic delegates.??chart has
14
</P>
<P>
   --Connecticut. This state was logistically and historically
stacked against McCain, but voted for the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   Only party members are allowed to vote in the winner-take all
primary, which means independents, making up 40 percent of the
electorate, could not cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also faced Governor John G. Rowland's support for Bush
and his opponent's Connecticut family legacy. The ?? and both he
and his son graduated from Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain won the state's 25 GOP delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore easily claimed the state's 54 Democratic delegates.
</P>
<P>
   --Rhode Island. This overwhelmingly Democratic state also chose
Gore and McCain, who was helped by the Ocean State's primary rules
allowing independents to vote. The state delivered 22 Democratic
delegates and 14 Republican ones, winner take all.
</P>
<P>
   --Vermont. The free-spirited state with strict campaign-finance
laws was fertile ground for McCain, who swept its 12
winner-take-all GOP delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore never visited the state, he was likely helped by
his environmental reputation in defeating Bradley. Gore won 15
Democratic delegates in Vermont's open primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
