<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9835 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-GOODEN-HNS     03-07 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-GOODEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
WINTER HAVEN, Fla. _ It becomes more and more evident with each
passing day that Scott Elarton likely won't be ready to pitch when
the regular season begins.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker will make the final call,
and at this point he's not ready to completely rule out the
24-year-old righthander, who underwent rotator-cuff surgery during
the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear that Elarton, who hasn't appeared in any of the
Astros' five exhibition games, is behind the rest of the team's
pitchers, which is exactly what the club expected when spring
training began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give it another week, but we've already played
a week of games, and I'm not going to cut his preparation short,''
Hunsicker said. ``We're rapidly getting to the point where it would
be difficult for him to make up time. Next week, we'll probably
have a better feel for where we are with Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't cut short the time it takes for someone to get into
shape. We've got to get him to the point where he can begin getting
into game shape. I'm certainly not going to be shortsighted there
and worry about racing the calendar for a couple of weeks or
whatever it turns out to be just to try to get him ready (to start
the season on time). It's not the team you start with; it's the
team you finish with.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Astros, there is a doctor in the house. He's
not the kind who can speed up Elarton's progress, but the kind who
can help patch up a rotation that probably will start the season
without two of its main contributors from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Doc Gooden is not Elarton, nor is he Mike Hampton, whom the
Astros traded to the Mets over the winter. In fact, Gooden isn't
even the same pitcher he was when he last pitched in the National
League in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But if his first two outings of the spring are any indication,
Gooden just might have the cure for what most expect will ail the
Astros in 2000. Exhibiting the type of precision and attention to
detail one might expect from a doctor, Gooden has been pretty close
to perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, the 35-year-old righthander has been flawless,
retiring each of the 12 batters he has faced, including six in a
row Tuesday against his former teammates, the Cleveland Indians.
Some nifty defensive work has probably saved Gooden a couple of
hits, but so far he has accomplished what he set out to do this
spring: get ahead in the count, throw strikes and locate his
pitches consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Having pitched in the big leagues for 15 seasons, Gooden isn't
about to get overly excited about two spring outings, but he has
been pleased with his performance nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to throw strikes and to be aggressive,'' Gooden
said. ``It's like I've been saying all along: I'm not the same kind
of pitcher I was years ago when I could fall behind in the count
and everyone knew what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I have to get ahead in the count and be more of a
complete pitcher. Today was probably the best I've located the ball
the whole while. I feel good about where I am at this stage. I just
want to get stronger and stronger each time out.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Gooden once threw only a rising four-seam fastball, he
now has a sinking two-seamer, which theoretically induces more
ground balls. Seven of his 12 outs this spring have come on ground
balls, a pattern that figures to serve him well at Enron Field,
where the modest dimensions down the lines could spell trouble for
fly-ball pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bako, who was Gooden's batterymate Tuesday, is almost in
awe of the former Cy Young Award winner. When the Indians visited
the Astrodome last season, Bako anonymously had a ball sent to the
visitor's clubhouse for Gooden to sign. Now, he's catching the
icon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little hard to believe,'' Bako said. ``It really is a
pleasure to catch him. He's located the ball really well, his
fastball has been sharp, and his slider was sharp today. He's just
gotten better each time in the two weeks since I first caught him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be the first to admit he's not the Doc of old. He was the
dominant pitcher of his time. All he needed to throw back then was
a fastball and curveball. Everyone knew he was coming right at
them, and they still couldn't hit him. Now, he knows he can't blow
people away anymore. He's more of a complete pitcher, and he
probably takes more pride in that.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this spring, the thing Gooden is most proud of is also
the thing that has the Astros' brass most encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's throwing a lot of strikes,'' pitching coach Vern Ruhle
said. ``He's been doing that all spring, even in the intrasquad
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hunsicker: ``If there has been one culprit for him over the
last few years, it's been that he's walked too many batters and he
pitched behind in the count. I think improving that was one of his
goals for the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good goal to work toward, and so far he's done a
great job. When we first got him, we talked to him about the
importance of pitching ahead in the count. To his credit, he's
really worked on it, and so far we've seen some results.''
</P>
<P>
   And as a result of that, Gooden no doubt is making it easier for
the Astros to resist any temptation there might be to push Elarton
any harder than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
