<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, MARCH 8
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-UNESCO-REFORM-NYT (moved on Saturday, March 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, March 4,
about Koichiro Matsuura, the new director general of Unesco,
misstated the tenure of his predecessor, Federico Mayor Zaragoza.
Mayor served two six-year terms, not one two-year term.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-PAPER-USE-NYT (moved on Sunday, March 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, March 5,
about companies that print and deliver paper copies of documents
created remotely by customers misidentified one company and
misstated its Internet address. The company is Sedona Systems, not
Sidona. Its address is www.reprint.com, not reprints.com.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MACHINES-HUMANS-NYT (moved on Friday, March 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, March 3,
about opposing approaches to the relationship of flight computers
and autopilots to their human operators omitted part of a
quotation. The comment, from Nadine P. Sarter, a specialist in
cognitive engineering at Ohio State University who advocates more
generic research into issues involving all machines, should have
read: ``We are chasing technology. It is developing so quickly that
by the time we get around to studying one thing, the next thing is
on the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT (moved on Monday, Feb. 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Feb. 7,
about the effect of cold medications on blood pressure
misidentified ingredients in CoricidinHBP. It does not contain
decongestants.
</P>
