<SLUG> BC-ELN-DEMOCRATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ROLLS OVER BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was Al Gore coast to coast, as the vice
president defeated former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley in every
one of the 15 states holding Democratic primaries and caucuses
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And in a good omen for his prospects in November's general
election, Gore was also on track to best Texas Governor George W.
Bush in California's ``beauty contest,'' a mini-general election in
the nation's largest state, where voters could pick from candidates
in either party.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's clean sweep almost certainly means the end of the
Democratic nomination fight, which Bradley's challenge made a
spirited, sometimes snarling, substantive and close-run affair,
right up to the New Hampshire primary, which Gore narrowly won. In
the five-weeks since, Bradley's national support steadily slipped
away, taking with it his dream of remaking Democratic politics in
his sober, insurgent's image.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Gore will meet with his campaign chairman, Tony
Coehlo, and his chief strategist, Carter Eskew, to make decisions
about his general election strategy. In recent days, he has already
begun focusing his attention on Bush, criticizing him for opposing
trigger safety locks on guns, campaign finance reform, and
attacking his health care record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Gore's apparent clamp on the nomination, he plans a
heavy travel schedule to Texas, Florida, Louisiana and other states
holding primaries on March 14, as well as Illinois, with a primary
a week later. Wednesday he leaves for Michigan, where Democrats
will elect delegates in a caucus on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For the vice president, the results marked an impressive
turnaround from his early days in New Hampshire where he initially
struggled to confront a strong challenge from Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is really the comeback kid now,'' said Darrell M. West, a
political science professor at Brown University. ``He has turned
around what was a dismal situation in October and emerged in very
good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gore revamped his campaign, moved his headquarters to
Nashville and transformed his own persona on the stump, Bradley
often seemed tactically overmatched. Gore attacked Bradley's image
as a reformer and sought to turn the former senator's campaign
centerpiece, a health care plan to give insurance to all Americans,
against him. In their first debate at Dartmouth College, Bradley
responded to Gore's criticism mildly, saying, ``We each have our
own experts, and I dispute the cost figure that Al has used.''
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, Bradley was similarly passive during another debate
when Gore asked him to explain why he voted against a flood-relief
amendment that would have helped Chris Peterson, a farmer in the
audience with 300 of his 400 acres of land under water at the time.
Bradley said he wanted to talk about the future, not the past He
didn't defend his record on flood relief, which was not nearly as
stark as Gore made it appear. More telling still, he never spoke to
Peterson's own plight at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the values of the process is you learn whether they
have what it takes, and we learned that Bradley did not,'' said
Thomas E. Mann, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution.
``Gore demonstrated you've got to be tough in this business, and
he's certainly that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall and into the early winter, Bradley was leading Gore in
the polls in New Hampshire and Massachusetts, as well as in New
York, where he played professional basketball for the New York
Knicks for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Gore bested Bradley in Massachusetts, in New York,
and even in Bradley home state of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has yet to win a contest in the 2000 election, beginning
with losses in Iowa and New Hampshire. When he left the Granite
State, a four-point loser to Gore, Bradley still hoped he could
revive his chances and win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're smarter and better prepared and ready and eager to
continue the fight,'' Bradley said at the time. He described the
race as a fight for new politics, big dreams, and a different
philosophy of leadership _ his.
</P>
<P>
   But John McCain's 19-point New Hampshire victory over Bush meant
that the Arizona senator had grabbed the spotlight. With no
Democratic primaries for five weeks, voters were watching the
Republicans do battle in South Carolina, Michigan, and elsewhere,
rather than listening to Bradley hold forth.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley tried to take back the momentum in advance of Super
Tuesday by concentrating his time in Washington State, which held
an open primary with no Democratic delegates on Feb. 29. But the
longer Bradley stayed in Washington, the more he dropped in the
polls. Gore won there, as well.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has insisted during the past week that he is ``not
taking a single vote for granted,'' he also has been laying the
groundwork for a general election campaign. Gore, who once
relentlessly criticized Bradley, switched his target to the
Republican contenders, especially Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus is moving more and more to the Republicans,'' said
Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane. The two leading Republican
candidates want to make ``a right wing U-turn'' in economic policy,
and ``it's hard not to address that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From California to Massachusetts, Gore has accused Bush and
McCain of being ``two peas in a pod,'' with ``right-wing'' agendas
against abortion rights and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, they're afraid to do anything that isn't
blessed in advance by the NRA,'' Gore said in a TV interview late
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been harsher toward Bush, singling him out for speaking
at Bob Jones University, which until recently banned interracial
dating, and denouncing the Texas governor for refusing to back a
ban on ``soft money.'' Soft money is loosely regulated, unlimited
cash raised for voter education or party building, and is not
supposed to be spent on behalf of a specific candidate or campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president frequently mentions that he and McCain agree
on issues such as campaign finance reform and the need to ``stand
up to special interests.'' The tactic has allowed him to draw a
comparison between himself and McCain, without completely
alienating McCain's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, hasn't had a nice thing to say about Bush yet.
And he is unlikely to start now.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming days, Gore will focus his message on the booming
economy, urging voters to continue the policies of the Clinton-Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a critical question in the general election: who
will keep the economic prosperity going?'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is also expected to talk extensively about
Bush's record in Texas, which he likes to note ranks second to last
for children's health insurance, last for women's health insurance,
and first for pollutants and carcinogens released to the air and
soil. One study Gore cites, by the Children's Rights Council,
ranked Texas as the 48th worst place to raise a child.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
