<SLUG> BC-STATESTREET-GLOBAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE STREET INVESTMENT ARM UPS PAY TO SLOW DEFECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After eight employees jumped ship last summer to join a
higher-paying rival, State Street Global Advisors had to look in
the mirror _ and open its wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The $667 billion investment arm of Boston's State Street Corp.
confirmed it reviewed the compensation of about 500 employees in
the wake of the Deutsche Bank defections. And it has awarded large
raises to a ``significant number'' of those people in a bid to keep
them from hopping to local mutual fund companies or Wall Street
firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exercise for us that was probably long overdue,''
said Marc Simons, chief operating officer at State Street Global.
``It gave us a chance to make sure our folks were competitively
compensated and meeting their long-term goals.''
</P>
<P>
   State Street wouldn't say how big the raises were, but employees
say they ranged from 5 percent to 40 percent. Simons said the
increases came in the form of cash, bonus, and stock, depending on
the employee and the job description. In all, he said, the pay
hikes will add several million dollars to the group's wage budget.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after five years of massive returns in the stock
market that have fueled fast growth at State Street and other
investment shops. Employees increasingly expect to share in their
employers' riches, whether it's at a downtown financial firm or a
high-flying dot-com start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Thomson, an executive recruiter at Pendleton James
Associates in Boston, said candidates for top investment posts no
longer ask just about salary, bonus, and stock options. They want
to know, ``What's the walk-away?'' he said, or how much the hiring
company will pay to make good on deferred compensation and stock
left on the table with the former employer.
</P>
<P>
   Simons said State Street is not looking to match the kind of
eye-popping pay being offered in a frothy market. One of the
executives who left for Deutsche Bank had boasted he was signing on
for $9 million, a sum Simons called ``really off the end of the
curve.''
</P>
<P>
   But the company does want to be able to attract and keep talent
by making sure it's in the top 50 percent of the pay range among
its peers. Said Simons, ``Money has clearly become more of a
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, the recruiter, observed that traditionally ``investment
management firms that are attached to banks have lower-paid
investment managers.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a hot-button issue for State Street Global, whose chief,
Nicholas Lopardo, has labored to create an investment culture quite
separate from the parent company's banking tradition. His pay has,
in some years, exceeded that of his boss, Marshall Carter, chief
executive of the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   State Street Corp. recently sold its small but profitable bank
division to focus on its core business of keeping records on $6
trillion for mutual funds and pensions. But the company has yet to
entirely shed that banker image with investors.
</P>
<P>
   If State Street Global did, by its own admission, fall behind on
the wage front, Simons said it was partly because turnover has been
light in recent years. The company was lulled into believing its
culture helped keep people, even in a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, it was a harsh wake-up call when Deutsche Bank
lured away a fund manager, a quantitative strategies chief, the
head of emerging markets, two analysts, and four salesmen _ all in
one swoop early last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time that's ever happened to us,'' Simons said.
``We recognize that the marketplace has become very competitive,
and that our assets travel up and down the elevator every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
