<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-REPUBLICAN-PRIMARIES-     03-07 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICAN-PRIMARIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUSH BLITZES McCAIN ON SUPER TUESDAY  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     (EDS: CORRECTS Rhode Island outcome; new material throughout)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George Bush effectively ended the challenge of Sen.
John
</P>
<P>
   McCain for the Republican presidential nomination Tuesday,
setting the
</P>
<P>
   stage for Bush to court McCain and his supporters to join a GOP
crusade to reclaim the White House in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush harnessed hard-hitting campaign ads and a lavishly financed
nationwide campaign organization to score victories in most of the
13 states with GOP contests, according to Voter News Service exit
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The voter interviews showed Bush beating McCain in California,
Ohio, Georgia, Maryland, Missouri and Maine with a close race in
New York. Bush was running ahead of McCain, as well, in the popular
vote contest in California in which non-Republicans could cast
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Bush swept key winner-take-all delegate contests, including
California, as well as the majority of the GOP delegates in other
states that award delegates on a district-by-district basis, the
exit polls showed. Karl Rove, his campaign manager, said Bush would
pick up as many as 450 of the 613 delegates chosen on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   CNN delegate projections at 9 p.m. EST gave Bush a total of 397
delegates and McCain with 193. A Republican candidate needs 1,034
delegates to secure the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, whose fiery populism sustained an uphill challenge for
the last six weeks, captured only Vermont, Connecticut,
Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   The 63-year-old former Navy pilot and Vietnam prisoner of war
failed to make inroads among the bedrock Republican voters that he
needed in order to sweep large numbers of delegates in the
district-by-district duels, particularly in Ohio where he was
banking that two campaign stops on Monday would turn the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, son of former President George H.W. Bush, made it clear
that his most pressing task in the days ahead will be to court
McCain as well as the centrist Republicans, independents and
Democrats who rallied to McCain in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush extended an olive branch to McCain even before the results
were in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if there's any personal issues between me and my
opponents, we'll sit down and talk,''' Bush said. ``I'm confident
we can heal any wounds that may exist between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a prepared statement, Bush referred to McCain and
said, ``We have our disagreements but I respect him and his
commitment to reform. Republicans and conservatives across America
have said they want me to lead the Republican party to victory in
November _ and I am ready and eager to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove signaled that Bush wasn't interested in pressuring McCain
to withdraw in his own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not up to us to urge him out of the race,'' Rove said.
``What would be appropriate for us to do is to indicate that Gov.
Bush is ready to heal and unify the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary schedule moves into Bush territory next Tuesday,
with contests in six key southern and southwestern states,
including Texas, where Bush is governor, and Florida where his
brother, Jeb Bush, is chief executive. The six states offer 341
delegates _ enough to give Bush a mathematical lock on the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said the race will only be over ``when we get to 1,034
delegates and we're the only candidate left,'' adding: ``It's going
to be apparent, particularly after next week, that Bush has got
unstoppable momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would stay in the race only if he believed he
still had a chance to turn things around and win the nomination.
McCain said last weekend that he would withdraw from a failing race
rather than have his ``megaphone turn into a kazoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran senator struck a wistful tone before the results
were in. ``I can't tell you how proud I am to have sparked this
kind of prairie fire out there that got people involved,'' McCain
said told a radio call-in program early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's hard-hitting populist bid, featuring attacks on Bush,
``the establishment,'' the White House, Congress and special
interests, attracted legions of first-time voters, once-alienated
young voters, independents and Democrats to the GOP banner.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's candidacy ignited historic turnouts in New Hampshire
and Michigan, where he won early momentum, as well as in South
Carolina where he lost.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross Baker, a political science professor at Rutgers
University, said excitement does not translate into nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a credible early favorite _ and you have the
fortitude to stay on in the face of early disappointments _ you're
going to win the nomination,'' Baker said. ``Ultimately the
favorites designated by the party graybeards walk away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster based in Atlanta who is not
working for any presidential campaign, said McCain could not hope
to win the GOP nomination ``without Republican votes,''' adding:
``Establishment matters, and money matters _ especially in a war of
attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, which had the support of Republican leaders _
including 29 governors, 38 senators and 175 House members _ carried
out 2 million get-out-the-vote telephone calls in nine states in
the final two days of the Super Tuesday campaign, mailed 2 million
pieces of campaign literature and distributed 69,000 yard signs,
according to Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Baker and Ayres said Bush had been strengthened for the
fall campaign by being forced to grapple with McCain's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has become ``a far superior candidate, far more aggressive,
far more
</P>
<P>
   unscripted, far more willing to take chances,'' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920 or at
</P>
<P>
   the e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2144EST &QL; 
