<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-GORE-ART-3RDTAKE-     03-07 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-GORE-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHVILLE , Tenn.: Boston television.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We faced a serious financial decision, and that was whether to
go up in Boston or not,'' this adviser said. ``Unless you
communicate through the Boston media, you won't reach a big chunk
of New Hampshire voters. We knew it would cost more and be less
efficient, but if you don't do it, you're cooked.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign was also monitoring another topic that no one
wanted to be caught discussing in public. That was Bradley's heart
palpitations, a seemingly minor problem that could have mushroomed
into a larger one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bradley people say that if he hadn't had the heart thing,
he would have won New Hampshire,'' a Gore adviser said. ``Well, if
we were trailing, we might have run a different kind of campaign,''
he said, not suggesting they would have used Bradley's heart
condition against him but that as long as Bradley supporters were
engaging in hypotheticals, this adviser would too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no lack of will to win over here,'' he said, in a
clear shot across the bow at Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
leading Republican candidate. ``If we had found ourselves in a
situation where we were short a vote, we probably would have tried
a different route.''
</P>
<P>
   What would they have done? ``We would have drawn much stronger
contrasts than we did,'' said this adviser. ``We would have brought
up that Bradley wants people to work until they're 70 when they
retire. We didn't unload all our firepower.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Zukin, a public policy professor at Rutgers University,
said that Gore prevailed for both tactical reasons but also larger
reasons that he had little control over. ``Bradley was running
against the longest economic expansion in history,'' he said. ``How
do you call for fundamental change during good economic times? No
one has ever done it successfully.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
