<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9844 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NY     03-07 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SOARS BEYOND BRADLEY; BUSH HOLDS OFF MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT1, 18, 33, 3, 10, 11, 16, 19 _ have been sent
to NYT photo clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore crushed Bill Bradley from ocean to ocean
Tuesday in a powerful display that assured him the Democratic
presidential nomination, while Gov. George W. Bush took a huge
stride toward capturing the Republican nomination, piling up far
more delegates than Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's victories were particularly impressive because he was
supported by every demographic group in the 16 states with
Democratic contests, and, significantly, by women, who backed him
in some states by margins of more than 2-to-1, according to results
or surveys of voters leaving the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In several states Gore held a margin of 3-to-1 or better. Gore
also racked up a double-digit margin in New York, a victory made
even sweeter by the memory of his dismal performance in the 1988
presidential primary, where he won a paltry 10 percent and quit the
race.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican verdict Tuesday was less overwhelming. Bush
prevailed in the Midwest powerhouses of Ohio and Missouri and in
the only southern state voting Tuesday, Georgia. McCain captured
Massachusetts and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the most sought-after electoral prize of all,
Bush was comfortably ahead of McCain in the votes of registered
Republicans, the exit polls showed. That is crucial because the
winner of the Republican vote captures all of California's 162
delegates. It was not clear which of the four contenders would
prevail in that state's popular vote, which is not binding but
could be a telling measure of a candidates' potency in November.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the other huge electoral trove, with 101 delegates,
Bush and McCain were battling in what exit polls showed was a tight
contest. The vote was also tight in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the votes were counted, both Gore and Bush were
looking toward the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm privileged to win the nomination, I'm going to need you
more than ever going forward to the general election,'' the vice
president told labor supporters Tuesday, ``because there's an awful
lot at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Gore has been concentrating his assaults on Bush, while
the Texas governor has softened his conservative oratory in recent
days, positioning himself for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The voting Tuesday was tantamount to a national primary. Never
before have so many states, in every region, held contests on the
same day. Roughly a third of the delegates to the parties' national
conventions were up for grabs. The Democrat needs 2,170 delegates
to get the party's nomination; The Republican needs 1,034.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side the primaries capped the most contentious
nomination battle in decades, a week-by-week electoral see-saw in
which Bush would win one round, only to be humbled by McCain in the
next. Bush entered Tuesday's voting with more victories and more
delegates. But no one could safely bet what would happen Tuesday
because in the entire yearlong run-up to the primaries, Bush had
been widely viewed as the front-runner, only to see his prospects
grow far more precarious after McCain trounced him in the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race was far less climactic Tuesday because while
Bradley emerged as a threat last fall _ polls at one point had him
beating Gore in New Hampshire _ that spurt of popularity never
translated to the voting booth. Bradley, a former senator from New
Jersey, was shut out by Gore in every contest before Tuesday.
Bradley's campaign had so sputtered that even before the voting
Tuesday, many of his most prominent supporters said it would take a
miracle for him to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has so fizzled that even on his signature issue, health
care, voters were more likely to say that the vice president had
the preferable plan. The enormity of Gore's triumph allows him to
move more quickly to patch up relations with Bradley's backers.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, patching up with McCain and his supporters could prove
more difficult. The polls of voters Tuesday, conducted by a
consortium of the television networks and the Associated Press,
found that Bush and McCain continued to draw from far different
bases of support. Republicans backed Bush overwhelmingly while
independents and Democrats, in states where they could vote for a
Republican, favored McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The victors in each state depended largely on the proportion of
independents and Republicans in the electorate. In Ohio, for
example, more than seven in 10 voters described themselves as
Republicans and seven in 10 of them voted for Bush. By contrast, in
Massachusetts, nearly six in 10 of the voters described themselves
as independents, and seven in 10 of them backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence that either candidate had cut into the
other's constituency. Those who described themselves as
conservatives, and those who want abortion to be illegal, voted for
Bush; those calling themselves moderates or liberals, as well as
those who favor abortion rights, favored McCain.
</P>
<P>
   While the days leading up to Tuesday's primaries have been
dominated by McCain's repudiation of religious right leaders and
Bush's apology for his much-ridiculed appearance at Bob Jones
University _ an institution that is viewed as anti-Catholic _ there
was no sign in the exit polls that those episodes significantly
affected the voting. Bush held his own among Catholics, although he
did not do as well with them as with other groups.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain's attacks on the religious right appeared to be a
mistaken gambit _ or one that did not yield him new support among
more moderate voters. In New York and Ohio, people who said
McCain's criticisms mattered backed Bush; those who said they did
not matter backed McCain. In New York, six in 10 voters said
McCain's outspoken comments did not affect their vote; in Ohio,
nearly half said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robertson, the television evangelist who was harshly
attacked by McCain, said Tuesday night that he had been
``absolutely dumbfounded when Senator McCain had come to my home
town and launched that barrage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to destroy his campaign, and I didn't know
why he did it,'' he said in an interview with the Fox News Channel.
``To attack 25, 30 percent of your base just isn't smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he was opposed to a Bush-McCain ticket. Asked
whether he thought such an alliance were out of the question, he
replied, ``I really think so. That kind of anger, the concept that
there are people who are agents of evil, that kind of thing isn't
civility in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case throughout the contest, voters said they
were more concerned about candidates' morals than about issues.
While McCain was widely seen as someone who stands up for his
beliefs and tells people the truth, Bush was seen as having high
moral values.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio and Missouri, two pivotal battlegrounds in the fall,
Bush did extraordinarily well. In those states, Bush won the
backing of men and women, the young and old, voters who are
educated and those who are not, and Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, where a quarter of the Republican electorate is
Catholic, Bush drew half their vote and McCain took just under
half. In Missouri, where Catholics account for a quarter of the
vote, more than half favored Bush and less than four in 10 backed
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's nationwide sweep was especially welcome for him since his
campaign has endured its share of traumas. While Gore has been
elected to two terms as vice president and served in the House and
Senate from Tennessee for 16 years, he was not prepared for
Bradley's sudden emergence last year. That led him to dramatically
retool his campaign from top to bottom, shifting his campaign
headquarters from Washington to Nashville, distancing himself from
President Clinton and significantly loosening up his style on the
stump.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was unrelenting in finding holes in Bradley's
record and in his proposals _ and put Bradley on the defensive for
several weeks before the former senator responded.
</P>
<P>
   The voters Tuesday gave Bradley high marks for saying what was
on his mind regardless of the political price he might pay; they
viewed Gore as more of a panderer.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bradley had little backing anywhere among any
demographic group and failed to leave his mark in any significant
way.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Republicans, Democrats said they were more
concerned with a candidate's standing on the issues than his
personal qualities. In a sign that the Clinton impeachment hearings
may still loom, Clinton was seen as doing a good job by more than
eight in 10 of the Democrats who voted. But only one in four rated
him favorably as a person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
