<HEADLINE>
CSUN WOMEN: NO SLOW START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Any local landscaping company would be lucky to
hire the Cal State Northridge women's basketball players. They've
got a lot of experience in digging out.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Matadors were down by 11 (34-23) at halftime at
Weber State and they came back to win. Two days later, they trailed
by nine (36-27) at Sacramento State and won that game, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both must-wins for us,'' CSUN coach Frozena Jerro
said. ``Unfortunately, we got into the habit of digging ourselves a
hole in the first half. The good thing is we were able to battle
back and come out with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Second-seeded CSUN (17-9) opens the women's Big Sky tournament
Thursday in Missoula, Mont. Northridge faces the highest-seeded
semifinal winner from today's games.
</P>
<P>
   Jerro isn't looking for another slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a season-long thing,'' she said. ``We've had
different starting lineups, but it's just a matter of us coming in
focused and ready to go. . . . I'm sure the adrenaline is going to
be flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Inside-outside: Not many 6-foot-9 forwards take as many
3-point shots as CSUN's Andre Larry, who's tossed it up 61 times
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Larry, a senior who enters the Big Sky tournament second on the
Matadors in scoring (13 points per game), has made 19. His shooting
percentage (31 percent) is next-to-last on the team, and Larry is
just 3 for 15 in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm in a little bit of a slump, but I can't get out
of it by stopping (shooting),'' Larry said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry could be more effective inside, though. An example:
Saturday he missed a wide-open 3-pointer against Sacramento State.
CSUN got the offensive rebound and Larry went inside and scored
while being fouled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, I was a guard,'' he said. ``That was just my
thing, just to shoot 3-pointers. Shooting 3's was the first thing I
liked to do. As tall as I am, it's something that a lot of people
can't (defend). I've still got a little guard in me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Primed: Last year the CSUN men went to the Big Sky tournament
with a gimpy Jeff Parris (injured back) a disgruntled Greg Minor
(he quit the team but came back) and a vanished Rico Harris (quit
with Minor and didn't return).
</P>
<P>
   Northridge boarded a plane Tuesday with no injuries and no
dissension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, thank God, we're in good shape,'' CSUN coach Bobby
Braswell said. ``Last year we had injuries, we had defections, we
had all kinds of things. This feels like the first time we've had
our whole team solid and locked in.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quotable: ``Everybody feels like they can win the tournament
and make it to the NCAAs. That's the only way any team in our
conference is going to be there, by winning this tournament. So
you're going to have six hungry teams.'' _ Braswell
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
