<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: OFFICER'S ROLE IN LOUIMA CASE STILL HARD TO DEFINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story was previously skedded as NY-LOUIMA) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles Schwarz has been held up to the public eye as
a Janus figure, a man with two irreconcilable faces.
</P>
<P>
   To the federal prosecutors who convinced a jury last year that
he was guilty of helping to torture Abner Louima and then won
another conviction against him this week for covering up his role
in the attack, Schwarz is a poster boy for police misconduct _ a
cop who not only willingly joined in one of the most horrendous
assaults in the New York Police Department's history, but who then
ensnared his colleagues in a web of self-serving lies to try to get
himself off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   But to his lawyers, his family, and even the other officers
convicted in the notorious 1997 assault and its cover-up, Schwarz
is an entirely different man. His partisans and colleagues say he
is the victim of an overly zealous federal government _ an innocent
and honest patrolman who was railroaded by a vengeful team of
prosecutors willing to forgo the truth in order to win their case.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, 34, is being held in a cell at the Metropolitan
Correctional Center in Brooklyn, under lock and key 23 hours a day,
facing a possible life sentence on the assault conviction and five
years for the coverup conviction. His lawyer, Ronald Fischetti, has
promised to overturn both verdicts, but after two juries ruled
against him, the chances of a successful appeal seem dim.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is possible that the truth about Schwarz and his
role in the attack, in which Louima was sodomized with a broken
broomstick in the bathroom of a Brooklyn station house, lies
somewhere between the extremes portrayed by prosecutors and by his
supporters. The jurors in both trials were granted anonymity by the
court, so it is impossible to say exactly what they believed about
him. And after two trials, more than 100 pieces of evidence and
untold hours of courtroom arguments, many New Yorkers may be left
with a frustrating sense that the truth _ cold and hard and clean _
remains elusive.
</P>
<P>
   There was a ``Rashomon''-like quality to both trials, as each
person who spoke about what happened on Aug. 9, 1997, came up with
a different version of events. Not only did the accounts of several
witnesses blatantly contradict one another, but there was a gnawing
feeling that no one could offer a complete version, from beginning
to end.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Schwarz loudly proclaimed his innocence _ as
many accused men do _ and he took the stand in his second trial to
present his alibi to the jury: that he was not inside the 70th
Precinct station house at all during the time of the attack, but
instead was outside searching his squad car after a night out on
patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the murkiness of the Schwarz case lies with the nature
of the jury system in which 12 ordinary people undertake the tough
task of coming to a conclusion about extraordinary events. But part
of the problem also lies with the general nature of the evidence
introduced at the two Louima trials.
</P>
<P>
   In the first trial, the case against Schwarz was based on the
accounts of Louima himself and of two officers who said they had
seen Schwarz leading Louima toward the bathroom where the attack
took place _ but not into it.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Detective Eric Turetzky, testified to seeing
Schwarz take the prisoner, handcuffed with his pants and underwear
around his knees, from the front desk of the station house down a
hallway that leads to the bathroom. The second officer, Mark
Schofield, recounted seeing Schwarz leading Louima toward the
hallway but not down it.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Louima testified that the officer who pinned him
down during the assault was the same one who had driven the patrol
car that carried him from the streets of Flatbush to the station
house that night. Although police records show that Schwarz was the
driver _ and Schwarz, in fact, testified at his second trial that
he was driving _ Louima gave confusing accounts of the driver's
identity under cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   In the second trial, which concerned a conspiracy to lie about
the assault, the government based its case on phone records showing
a blizzard of calls among Schwarz and his co-defendants, Thomas
Bruder and Thomas Wiese, as well as testimony that the three
officers met with union officials four days after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   While the government offered no tapes of the phone calls or
witnesses who concretely said that a plot to obstruct justice was
discussed at the meeting, they argued that the timing and
circumstances of both the calls and the get-together suggested that
the officers were joining forces to get their stories straight.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also argued that Bruder and Wiese tailored their
false accounts to conform each time a new development arose in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The government argued, for example, that on Aug. 15 _ six days
after the attack _ Bruder told Internal Affairs investigators that
Justin A. Volpe, who eventually pleaded guilty to the attack,
marched Louima to the bathroom alone. But on Aug. 18 _ just three
days later _ Bruder changed his story, the government said, and now
related that Wiese and Volpe had escorted the prisoner toward the
bathroom door.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution said that change, mirrored by a similar
alteration in Wiese's story, was made because the conspirators now
had to account for two officers in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   In large degree, an assessment of what exactly happened that
night must depend on how one views the testimony of Volpe, the only
person who everyone agrees was there. When he took the stand in the
second trial, he testified _ as expected _ that Schwarz was not in
the bathroom at all and was never involved in the attack. But
within moments Volpe plunged the courtroom into a new round of
chaos when he said that Wiese, who claims he walked in only after
the attack, was, in fact, in the room the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, there would seem to be little reason to
disbelieve the testimony of Volpe, a man who pleaded guilty in open
court last May, who is already serving a 30-year prison term for
his crime, who apparently has nothing more to lose. ``It has
nothing to do with friendship,'' Volpe said of his testimony on the
stand three weeks ago. ``It just has to do with doing what's right
in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to federal prosecutors, Volpe's motives were far
more sinister: they included a desire to seek a lower sentence and
an abiding hatred for Wiese. Indeed, Volpe is expected to file
papers appealing his sentence Wednesday morning and might stand to
gain by having appeared contrite and helpful on the witness stand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
