<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-RESTAURANT-CREDITS-NY     03-07 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-CREDITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARRING THE CHEF, THE SOUS-CHEF ... AND THE DISHWASHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time when chefs were anonymous. No one
knew their names. If a restaurant was named Chez Louis, chances
were that Louis was not the guy behind the stove. He was the owner.
When anyone dared to ask Henri Soule, the owner of Le Pavillon, who
was responsible for the greatness of his restaurant, he had a very
simple answer: ``Le Pavillon,'' he would say, ``c'est moi.''
</P>
<P>
   I found myself thinking about those far-off days while studying
the menu at Thalia recently. Down at the bottom, the name of the
chef, Michael Otsuka, is printed. Next to him are listed his
sous-chefs, Bill McDaniel and Robert Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Sous-chefs?
</P>
<P>
   The United States has often been called a credit society. It's
true in two senses. Americans love credit cards. They love credit _
the recognition of accomplishment, near-accomplishment,
well-intended lack of accomplishment or merely showing up. In a
success-ethic democracy, it just doesn't feel right unless
everybody wins and trophies are handed out all around.
</P>
<P>
   After a long historical lag, restaurants are catching up to the
rest of the culture. The chefs were the first to step forward and
demand recognition, not as skilled technicians, but as artists.
It's been trickle-down ever since. In recent years, pastry chefs
have been rewarded with credit on menus and, often, menus of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Now the No. 2s _ the sous-chefs, or the chefs de cuisine _ seem
to be restive. At Picholine, Terrance Brennan, the chef and owner,
gives the nod to his chef de cuisine, Peter Dalleda. At Icon, the
menu credits the executive chef, Paul Sale; the sous-chef, Eric
Woods; and Michael Trenk, the manager. Oceana and Molyvos thank
everyone, adding ``and staff'' to the chef's name. That would seem
to be the limit.
</P>
<P>
   But no. New ground has been broken at Chicama, the restaurant at
ABC Carpet &AMP; Home. The menu lists 77 names, from Douglas Rodriguez,
the executive chef, down to Jesus Pedroza, food runner, and Mano
Garcia, coffee maker. I see no end to this. Before long, menus will
look like Playbill, or orchestra programs, with a roll call of
everyone involved in the production from the chef down to the
coat-check attendant. Diners who should be spending precious
minutes studying the appetizers will give in to the irresistible
urge to scan the names, looking for ones that sound funny. Morale,
presumably, will rise to unprecedented heights.
</P>
<P>
   Do we really want to know? Of course not. But if it makes their
mothers proud, why quibble?  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
