<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON MAYOR SEEKS STATE'S HELP IN MEETING SMOG STANDARDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mayor Lee Brown joined local business leaders Tuesday
in asking state lawmakers to approve economic incentives to help
the Houston region meet its federal smog-reduction mandate.
</P>
<P>
   They also appealed for the state's help in persuading U.S.
officials to crack down on emission sources solely under federal
jurisdiction _ things like airplanes, locomotives and ships _ that
contribute to Houston's air pollution problem.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's office, meanwhile, released a letter he has sent to the
two leading candidates for the Republican and Democratic
presidential nominations, soliciting their views on how they think
the federal government can help the Houston area clean up its air.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and business leaders were among those testifying
before two legislative committees meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   At the same meeting, a leader of Texas' environmental commission
indicated his discomfort about two highly controversial programs
his agency is considering mandating for the Houston area _
restrictions on when people can use their vehicles and when
construction equipment can be operated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, some way, we've got to find a way out of that,'' said
Jeff Saitas, executive director of the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission. ``We've got to replace them with something
more acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and the Greater Houston Partnership, the area's leading
business organization, provided an assortment of recommendations at
the hearing for alternative ways to help reduce smog levels.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC is working on a plan, which it must submit for federal
approval by the end of the year, to bring ground-level ozone below
the federal health standard by 2007, a deadline set in the 1990
Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone, smog's main ingredient and a respiratory irritant, forms
in sunlight in reactions of pollutants emitted by industries,
vehicles and many other sources.
</P>
<P>
   TNRCC studies indicate that meeting the ozone standard will
require major reductions in one key group of pollutants, nitrogen
oxides, by all types of emission sources. Agency officials say they
intend to order the biggest reductions at major industries
</P>
<P>
   Brown warned that this goal of a 90 percent nitrogen oxide
reduction by area plants could halt industrial growth in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the state of Texas to establish a set of tax and
financial incentives to facilitate the needed technological
innovations as well as the installation of pollution-control
equipment by the industrial sector,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Frels, an attorney who chairs the partnership's
Environment Advisory Committee, supported the plea for economic
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility, he said, is to expand a constitutional
amendment, which was adopted in 1993 to provide a property tax
exemption for pollution-control facilities, to encourage both
businesses and home-owners to invest in smog-abatement equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Among other recommendations, Frels urged lawmakers to consider
delaying the opening of public schools in this area, perhaps until
after Labor Day, as another ozone-reducing action.
</P>
<P>
   Heat fosters the atmospheric chemical reactions that yield
ozone, and more violations of the ozone standard are traditionally
recorded in August than in any other month, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Houston surpassed Los Angeles last year to become the city with
the nation's worst smog. The city earned the distinction by
recording 44 days in which the ozone level exceeded federal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
