A9852 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-CHOPRA-SFCHRON &LR;      03-07 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHOPRA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS DEEPAK CHOPRA TOO CEREBRAL FOR `TODAY'? 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   California author and spiritual guru Deepak Chopra says an NBC
producer told him he was too brainy for the ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmic bummer, because Chopra flew all the way to New York two
weeks ago to promote his new book, ``How to Know God,'' on
``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   His bad ``Today'' experience catapulted Chopra into a fit of
deep meditation and self-examination. He has recovered and resumed
his book tour.
</P>
<P>
   Chopra's live interview, scheduled for February 22, was bumped
for an interview with jilted TV groom Rick Rockwell _ or Rock
Rickwell, as he'd be known in porn films _ of ``Who Wants to Marry
a Multi-Millionaire'' notoriety. This was network TV; commerce
before God.
</P>
<P>
   So Katie Couric interviewed Chopra on tape instead. Chopra
figured it would air the next day. He was wrong. He says that after
the interview, a ``Today'' producer deemed Chopra too cerebral for
the show's viewers.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that Chopra lost Couric during the ``restful
awareness response'' part of the interview. But we might never
know; as of Tuesday, when Couric was busy reporting on her own
colonoscopy to screen for cancer, the Chopra segment still hadn't
been broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' spokeswoman Allison Gollust said this week that
there's nothing unusual about shelving an author interview in favor
of timely news. Gollust said the interview still might air, and she
denied that anyone associated with the program told Chopra that he
was too smart for the show.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what Chopra heard because he said, in a subsequent
e-mail to friends and followers, that the incident led him into an
exploration of the ``seven biological responses'' he outlines in
his book.
</P>
<P>
   He would wonder, eventually, what Jesus, Buddha, Mohammed, Lao
Tsu, Moses and other figures would do ``in such a situation.''
Meaning, presumably, if they'd been bumped by the ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Chopra says he first found himself in the throes of the
``fight/flight response,'' grumpy and wanting to confront his
``Today'' show oppressors.
</P>
<P>
   But few gurus _ the late Ayatollah Khomeini excepted _ can stew
for long. Chopra says he ``quickly moved into a `reactive
response,' with my ego wanting to assert control and seeking to
demonstrate how they were wrong and I was right. I stayed in the
reactive response all evening.''
</P>
<P>
   That could take a bite out of anyone's trip to the Big Apple.
Chopra says he woke up the next morning, went into meditation and
experienced the ``restful awareness response,'' a state of centered
awareness that ushered him into a fourth, ``intuitive response''
stage.
</P>
<P>
   He asked himself, ``What was the deeper significance of this
episode? The answer was immediate and obvious. The mainstream media
is stuck in an old paradigm while the world is moving into a new
one.''
</P>
<P>
   This makes sense. ``Today'' was stuck in an old paradigm. It
booked Rockwell after ``Good Morning America'' had already beaten
it to Darva Conger.
</P>
<P>
   Pondering old paradigms nudged Chopra into the ``creative
response'' stage, in which he realized that a whole new company
could ``develop a multimedia approach that will nurture people in
an evolutionary manner that acknowledges and supports their
relationship with the larger web of life.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure, but I think that's curtains for ``WWF
Smackdown!,'' and possibly for the entire UPN schedule. No, wait,
``Moesha'' stays.
</P>
<P>
   Chopra was reaching fever pitch. He leapt into the ``visionary
response'' stage, in which ``it became obvious to me that if we
could reach critical mass with a nurturing and evolutionary
message, the world would never be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Much less the ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' Chopra says, ``I had a taste of the `sacred
response' through the experience of reverence and gratitude for a
God that makes things happen just as they are supposed to, and for
providing me the opportunity to witness how my reality changes in
different states of awareness. I felt love and appreciation for
everyone engaged in this little drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Me too, especially for Conger. If she hadn't dumped Rockwell,
and ``Today'' hadn't bumped Chopra to get Rockwell on the show, I
might not have had a Wednesday column.
</P>
<P>
   Not that that's a (set ital)bad(end ital) thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
