<SLUG> BC-NY-REGENTS-EDUC-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS GETTING JUMP ON REGENTS EXAM REQUIREMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four years ago, the New York State Board of Regents
adopted a policy to require all graduating public high school
students to pass high-stakes Regents exams in English, math,
science, global studies and American history and government by
2004.
</P>
<P>
   But some students are not waiting that long.
</P>
<P>
   Though English is the only exam that is required for a diploma
this year, a majority of students across the state have already
taken and passed exams in the other four subjects, the state
education commissioner, Richard P. Mills, said Tuesday at an Albany
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Some students are fulfilling their graduation requirements.
Others are just seeking a bright credential for their high school
transcript, because they will graduate before the new standards are
fully in effect. And still others are being prodded to take the
test by teachers who themselves are gathering experience for the
more rigorous teaching that will be required under the new
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the new data shows that the world of tougher standards
has already arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, flanked by Carl T. Hayden, the chancellor of the Board of
Regents, contended that the results signaled that students could
meet the state's tough new standards, despite warnings by critics
that moving to high-stakes testing would be calamitous. The
findings, released as part of the state's annual school report
cards, outline and compare school performance from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students are doing far better than many predicted two years
ago,'' Mills said. ``Many are doing well on tests they don't have
to pass this year. Others need extra help, and they must get that
help.'
</P>
<P>
   The reality on the ground may be more subtle than that, however.
</P>
<P>
   Myron Liebrader, principal of Grover Cleveland High School in
Ridgewood, Queens, said that some students at his school were
rushing to complete the examinations before the passing score rose.
During a four-year transition period, the Regents lowered the
minimum passing grade for the exams to 55 out of 100, from 65. But
a 65 grade for each test will eventually be required.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an increased number of kids taking the Regents, but
we've always encouraged our kids to take them,'' Liebrader said.
``It looks better when a kid applies to college to have a Regents
diploma. It all adds up.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics said Tuesday that students were not doing better and
that whole swaths of students were not represented in the results,
especially in New York City, because they had been held back, had
dropped out or had left the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this realistically reflects what's happening,''
said Norma Gluck, a former Regent who helped pave the way for the
new standards but has recently asked the board to postpone the plan
for two years, contending that students should not be required to
meet a single, uniform standard. ``It just seems to me there are a
lot of young people who are not included.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City has traditionally lagged behind schools elsewhere
in the state, and it did so again on the results released Tuesday.
Statewide, 83 percent of high school students have taken the global
studies test and 71 percent have passed. In New York City, 68
percent have taken the global studies test and 50 percent have
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the city's high school students have taken the
English Regents, but only 69 percent have passed compared with 80
percent statewide, the statistics show. The results are somewhat
better for New York City's seniors. In this year's graduating
class, 88 percent of the students have passed the test.
</P>
<P>
   This year's graduating class is the first to be required to pass
the stricter new English Regents exam. Some students took the exam
in January, but the results for that test have not been released.
Seniors will have two more chances to pass the English test.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 99 out of every 100 students have taken the math
Regents and 72 percent have passed, news that Mills trumpeted. But
he was disheartened by New York City's performance. Eighty-seven
percent of the city's high school students took the math exam, but
only 47 percent passed. The performance dovetails with findings by
City Comptroller Alan Hevesi, who released a report showing that
more students were taking the math Regents, but more were failing.
</P>
<P>
   Next year's seniors will be required to pass the math exam to
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said that one reason for the large number of failures in
math in New York City was that students were not being adequately
prepared in the middle grades, with students performing poorly on
the new statewide eighth grade math test. Another reason, he said,
is that New York City has 10,000 uncertified teachers throughout
the system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The pattern was pretty much the same in American history and in
biology, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-three percent of all high school students throughout the
state took the American history and government exam and 64 percent
passed. Fifty-eight percent of New York City's high school students
took the exam and 44 percent passed. In biology, 64 percent of all
high school students took the exam last year and 55 percent passed.
The graduation requirement in science can be met using any Regents
examination in science. Because most New York City students opt to
use tests other than biology, like earth science, comparison
figures were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Though performance varies regionally, Mills said he was pleased
that students were being encouraged to take Regents courses and
pass the exams long before they were required. Most students, it
appears, are taking the exams just after or during the course.
</P>
<P>
   Regents math is offered in the ninth and 10th grades. Global
studies is offered in the 10th grade and American history is
offered in the 11th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said he planned to work with Harold O. Levy, the interim
schools chancellor, on trying to increase state aid and improve
teacher recruitment to help students better prepare for the Regents
exams. Report cards released Tuesday showed a significant increase
in the dropout rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until this system can provide students with a longer
instructional program and more certified teachers, our school
report cards will continue to paint a disappointing portrait,''
Levy said in a prepared statement. ``Too many of our students read
below grade level, fail Regents exams and need to spend more than
four years in high school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
