<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dow Industrials Drop 3.7 Percent on Worries About Profits
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged 374.47 points, or 3.7
percent, to 9,796.03, on investor fears that rising oil prices
combined with higher interest rates may do significant damage to
corporate profits. Broader market averages fared a bit better. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index lost 2.6 percent of its value,
and the Nasdaq composite index lost 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The decline began when Procter &AMP; Gamble said that its earnings
in the current quarter would come in well below Wall Street
expectations. Adding to investor anxiety, oil prices soared to
$34.10 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Germany Has New IMF Candidate
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to opposition from the United States and a cool reaction
from many other countries, Germany withdrew its candidate for
managing director of the International Monetary Fund, Caio
Koch-Weser, but proposed someone who may not be much more popular,
Horst Koehler, head of the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and the World Bank should be radically overhauled
because they often do more harm than good in the developing world,
a congressional panel will recommend.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom Backs Off Qwest
</P>
<P>
   Spooked by Qwest Communications' apparently ironclad deal to
acquire U S West, Deutsche Telekom of Germany has essentially ended
negotiations to acquire either company, executives close to the
talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Quits Software Group
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft quit the nation's largest software industry trade
association after a long-running dispute over the group's support
for the government in the Microsoft antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   VeriSign to Buy Network Solutions
</P>
<P>
   VeriSign, which makes online security software, agreed to buy
Network Solutions, which maintains the master list of Internet
addresses, in a $21 billion stock swap, although a drop in share
price reduced it to $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign to Halt Money Laundering
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department plans to roll out its heavily promoted
anti-money laundering program today as part of the White House's
effort to combat international financial crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Search for a Good Mentor
</P>
<P>
   When Tami Sue Keller was put in charge of strategic planning for
Consumers Energy, a natural gas transmission and storage concern,
she needed advice on selling her innovations to her fellow
managers. So she turned to her mentor, Gerald A. Abood, who is a
senior director at Wisconsin Electric Power _ and her father. Every
young manager needs a mentor, but for women, it is not always easy
to find an in-house tutor.
</P>
<P>
   Rail Merger Runs Into Opposition
</P>
<P>
   A plan to unite two national freight railroads _ one in the
United States and the other in Canada _ to form the biggest network
of tracks and trains in North American history ran into opposition
from shippers, competing railroads and members of Congress who told
regulators that the merger would cripple service and dampen
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico Credit Rating Is Upgraded
</P>
<P>
   In a surprisingly broad endorsement of Mexico's economic
strength and financial management, Moody's Investors Service raised
the country's credit rating to investment grade for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   4th-Quarter Productivity Up 6.4 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Worker productivity in the fourth quarter of last year grew at a
revised annual rate of 6.4 percent, the fastest pace in seven
years, and labor costs fell for the second consecutive quarter, the
Labor Department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
