<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9856 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-BOOKS-GEFFEN-REVIEW-S     03-07 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GEFFEN-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING DAVID GEFFEN'S RUTHLESS RISE TO THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID WIEGAND  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Press reports on the eve of Tuesday's release of Tom King's
controversial biography of entertainment mogul David Geffen have
the book's subject raging against the tome and ruing the day he
ever granted King interviews for ``The Operator.''
</P>
<P>
   But readers of King's detailed portrait of Hollywood's premier
manipulator may actually wonder if Geffen's fury isn't a brilliant
ploy to draw attention to himself by helping the book's sales.
After all, who wants to read a biography whose subject actually
approved of it? If Geffen really hates the book, it must be filled
with dirt. And it is.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Operator'' is as much a composite portrait of the
``New Hollywood'' of its subtitle as it is of the 57-year-old
partner in DreamWorks SKG, whose hardscrabble Brooklyn childhood
convinced him that the best revenge wasn't only living well, but
getting revenge itself. Monstrous though King often makes Geffen
out to be, he is clearly not alone in the moral tar pits of the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Geffen is seen here repeatedly bullying, outmaneuvering
and crushing men who are in his way as he scampers nimbly upward
from the William Morris Agency mailroom, into the lower echelon of
the TV industry, then into the recording and film industries.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also clear that Geffen is merely one master of a very
popular game in Hollywood. Not only do his competitors employ
similar tactics, but many of them also find themselves admiring and
even working with Geffen again after he's ground them into the
dirt. His idols, like Atlantic Records' Ahmet Ertegun, and enemies,
like super-agent Michael Ovitz and Columbia Records' Clive Davis,
all play tough in the high-stakes entertainment business.
</P>
<P>
   Though it sounds like a line from a bad film, King reports that
while taking his first limo ride to bury his 57-year-old father,
18-year-old David remarked: ``You know ... nobody knows that we're
not rich ... We could be rich riding in this limousine.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Oliver Twist has evolved into Citizen Kane.
From the music business, Geffen made a preliminary stab at films
and fell on his face. But with the money and power amassed by
buying and selling record labels, he took the plunge into films
again and scored big-time with hits such as ``Risky Business'' and
``Interview With the Vampire.'' He saw the century out as a partner
with Steven Spielberg and Jeffrey Katzenberg in DreamWorks, an
entertainment hydra involved in film, television and music.
</P>
<P>
   King, an entertainment industry reporter for the Wall Street
Journal, packs his fat biography with detailed descriptions of how
Geffen amassed a fortune estimated at $2.7 billion. We find
ourselves repeatedly aghast at Geffen's amoral compulsiveness.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he wanted to renegotiate Geffen Records' deal with
parent company Warner Bros. Records. He knew that his old friend Mo
Ostin was tough to bargain with. So he engineered the end of their
friendship. That would, and did, leave him free to negotiate with
Warner's Steve Ross, who rarely denied his protege Geffen anything.
Geffen destroyed the friendship by taking Ostin's wife to lunch and
telling her that her husband didn't really care about her.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Geffen exercised his skills for the sake of hollow
vengeance alone. While producing the girl-meets-girl sports film
``Personal Best,'' Geffen clashed so violently with director Robert
Towne that he exacted vindication ``in a move so Machiavellian that
it could have fit into a scene in Towne's script for `Chinatown.'''
As the film neared completion, Geffen threatened to pull out unless
Towne signed a contract for two more films. That may sound like an
olive branch, but according to King, Geffen knew that the two films
would never be made and that Towne's career would be ruined because
he would be obligated to Geffen until they were.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there is a strong undercurrent of sadness beneath
Geffen's complex surface. We see it in his struggles with his
sexuality, which drew him to relationships with women such as Cher
and Marlo Thomas as he tried to deny his homosexuality. He
eventually came out in grand style at an event honoring him for his
AIDS donations.
</P>
<P>
   There are times, mostly in recent years, that Geffen has shown
generosity on the same level as his monomania. He abruptly ended
feuds with ex-colleagues like agent Sue Mengers when they've been
in trouble, and he's a tireless contributor to AIDS and other
charities.
</P>
<P>
   There is a telling moment in ``The Operator'' when Geffen, as
the producer of ``Risky Business,'' fought director Paul Brickman's
plan to have the young entrepreneur played by Tom Cruise lose
everything because of his manipulative ways. Geffen insisted on a
happy ending in which the character gets into Princeton and walks
into a figuratively golden sunset. The new ending, King writes, was
a mirror of how Geffen saw his own life story: ``If you maneuver
enough, you can get away with anything, and winning is easy. It
does not matter if you tell the truth, cheat on a test, or step on
people on your way to the top. It only matters if you win.''
</P>
<P>
   After a shaky start, DreamWorks seems to be fairly stable now.
Geffen's still making millions and squiring pretty young men half
his age around town. And, by the way, Mo Ostin, the man whose
friendship Geffen intentionally destroyed? Geffen hired him five
years ago to head DreamWorks' music division.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual, King writes, in the New Hollywood: ``People he
tangled with returned time and again for more. Alternately
exasperating and exhilarating, some people found Geffen to be like
an intoxicating drug. The high was indescribable, despite the fact
that it would likely be followed by a wicked hangover.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooray for the New Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE OPERATOR: David Geffen Builds, Buys, and Sells the New &LR; 
 &UR; Hollywood &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Tom King &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Random House; 671 pages; $25.95. &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
