<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HUMAN-CANNONBALL-ART-     03-07 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMAN-CANNONBALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND YOU THINK YOUR COMMUTE IS TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT42 and 43 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Circus history is littered with the bodies of its daredevils,
some lying not far from their equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Zazel, the first known human cannonball, died in 1919 in London
when she missed the net. Elvin Bale, doing the stunt at a Hong Kong
amusement park in 1987, was paralyzed when, because of an error
involving his test sandbag _ it had been left out in the rain,
rendering it considerably heavier than Bale _ he overshot the air
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Bale had his accident, as it happened, about the time that Jon
Weiss, Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey's current human
cannonball, as well as a longtime clown, was learning his craft.
</P>
<P>
   Did Bale's accident cause Weiss to reconsider?
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly did,'' says Weiss, 37, a warm, broad-shouldered
man with a surprisingly sunny disposition. ``You start questioning
yourself, `Is this the right job for me?' But I didn't want to miss
out on the opportunity. Clowning, you reach a certain level, but
specialty acts, especially daredevil acts, you have longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   Career concerns, very commendable, Weiss. And yet there must be
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notoriety, you know what I mean? It's the  &UR; cannon &LR;  act. How
many people you know are shot out of a cannon?''
</P>
<P>
   What does it take to be a human cannonball like Weiss, who lives
in Port Jefferson, N.Y., and can be seen with the circus this month
at the Nassau Coliseum in Uniondale, N.Y., and Madison Square
Garden in Manhattan? Knee pads, a back brace, an ability to roll
nicely into the net in a somersault, landing on your shoulders,
which are precariously close to your neck. Also you should allow
for at least two and a half hours after eating before being shot
100 feet across the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, however, does not perform only the cannonball. He also
balances things on his chin: a chair, a ladder, and finally,
terrifyingly, an active buzz saw.
</P>
<P>
   Care to tell us about the first time you tried this, Weiss? It's
not a stunt that seems to allow a large margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sure, that's an interesting story. Kenneth Feld,'' the
circus' producer, ``and Tim Holst,'' vice president for talent,
``came to me and asked if I could balance a running chain saw. They
wanted something thrilling. I bought the chain saw, but I never
tried it. When you rev up a chain saw it's got a lot of torque.
They kept asking me, `Did you do it yet?' So one day, in Tim's
office, I said, `OK, I'm going to balance it right now.' It was
pretty wild. The top of the saw is three inches from the ceiling,
the room is filling up with smoke. I just psyched myself up and did
it. From then on, I let my hands go longer and longer away. I don't
like to practice outside the show. If I'm gonna get hurt at all,
I'd rather do it for a paying audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a moment, now, and try to balance your pen on your nose.
Come on, it's New York, no one will even notice. Jon Weiss can do
it, from months of practice as a child in his room. Growing up in
Selden on Long Island, both Jon and his older brother were sent
often to their room by their father, who had a small trucking
company. Jon's older brother passed the time by doing magic tricks,
escaped from home at 18, and is now a professional magician in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' father was a tough guy?
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, whose parents divorced when he was 12, stares out into
the empty arena where an hour earlier people were screaming for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father,'' he says. A long pause. ``It was one of those
things.'' He laughs without humor. ``You know.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invited him to see what I do. When I got shot out of the
cannon, he just sat there like this.'' Weiss puts his chin in his
hand, does bored. ``Not interested. So, you know, what's the point?
My mother was the supportive one.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we need Ringmaster Freud, of the thrilling, chilling, Circus
of the Unconscious, to announce what happens when Dad is an
impossible room to play? Is that not he, in his top hat, shouting,
``A lifelong search for applause, dots vaht happens!'' As for the
cannon thing, don't even think of going there.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, anyway, finds the attention he craves at Centereach High,
balancing cafeteria tables on his chin. He also finds love, with a
classmate, Laura Litts. On an outing to Six Flags, Weiss invites
Litts to join him on the roller coaster, and though she hates the
roller coaster, she accepts. When he graduates from Ringling's
Clown College and is offered a job, she goes with him. The
showgirls teach Litts to dance and she, too, becomes a performer.
</P>
<P>
   They marry in 1986, just before a 1:30 performance, in the
center ring at Madison Square Garden. The bridesmaids are
elephants, the ring bearer  &UR; is &LR;  a bear, Weiss arrives in a clown
car. Describing his wife coming toward him under a 40-foot canopy
of white balloons, in a white feathered headpiece, he becomes
teary.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are three little Weisses, the latest, Max, born a week
ago Monday. Beaming, Weiss brings out the pictures. His wife, the
month before her delivery, had to stay at home on Long Island,
Weiss recalls, so he drove from Richmond, Va., where the circus was
playing, every weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The daredevil can balance a buzz saw on his chin, he can be shot
from a cannon. But being separated from his wife for a month would
have been too much stress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
