<HEADLINE>
MURPHY AND IRISH LOOKING FOR MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Notre Dame might not have the best team in the Big
East tournament this week, but it will have the player honored as
the best in the conference. He is Troy Murphy, the sophomore
forward from New Jersey, who will lead the Fighting Irish against
Rutgers Wednesday night in what promises to be the most interesting
matchup of four first-round games at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was named conference player of the year Tuesday night
before a banquet at the Grand Hyatt Hotel in Manhattan. The coach
of the year was Jim Boeheim of Syracuse, the rookie of the year was
Troy Bell of Boston College and the defensive player of the year
was Etan Thomas of Syracuse. Two players tied for the most improved
player: Ricardo Greer of Pittsburgh and Shaheen Holloway of Seton
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 21.2 points and 10.2 rebounds per game, Murphy led the
resurgent Irish to a record of 17-13 over all and 8-8 in the
conference under Matt Doherty, their rookie coach.
</P>
<P>
   Despite significant victories over Connecticut (twice), St.
John's and Ohio State, the Irish were only .500 in league play, and
they lost to Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame _ along with Seton Hall and Villanova _ are
considered to be teams that need good showings in this tournament
to qualify for the 64-team National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have exceeded all expectations this year, but one more
thing we want to accomplish this year is to play in the NCAA,''
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The three top seeded teams _ Syracuse, Miami and St. John's _
are expected to be selected by the NCAA, and all have byes
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, the defending Big East and NCAA champion, which
should also make the NCAA field, opens against Boston College
Wednesday afternoon. In other games Wednesday, West Virginia plays
Georgetown, Seton Hall plays Providence and Villanova plays
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In Notre Dame's only game against Rutgers, Murphy fouled out,
something he did only one other time. The Scarlet Knights played
him rough and beat the Irish 76-51.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to play any team that you lost to by a lot of
points,'' Murphy said. ``It's nice to get a chance. I'll be better
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the inconsistency of Notre Dame's season,
Murphy replied: ``We're young, and we don't have the maturity yet
to handle big wins. After we beat a UConn or something or St.
John's, we lose to a team in the lesser half of our league.
Hopefully, as we get older, we get better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being chosen as most valuable player in the conference,
Murphy called it ``a great honor. With all the great players in
this conference, I'm lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall (19-8, 10-6) enters the tournament with a better
record than Notre Dame. But the Pirates lost their last four league
games and played a weaker schedule overall. Their coach, Tommy
Amaker, said that a week off following a season-ending loss to St.
John's is a mixed blessing because his players needed to get
``healthy, rested and better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing contradicts the other two,'' Amaker said. ``We
try to get them to remember why we were good and not that the
bottom is falling out because we lost a few.''
</P>
<P>
   As for NCAA tournament speculation, Amaker said: ``It surrounds
us. Everybody talks about it. Our mood will greatly improve when we
win. We're a fragile team. We've got to get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   For Villanova (18-11, 8-8), aa victory over Pittsburgh in
Wednesday's 9:30 p.m. finale would send the Wildcats against St.
John's in the last game of the quarterfinals Thursday night. The
Notre Dame-Rutgers winner plays Miami. The Seton Hall-Providence
winner plays either Connecticut or Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Should Notre Dame get by both Rutgers and Miami, the Irish could
face St. John's in a semifinal on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley, the point guard of the Red Storm, is the only
other sophomore with Murphy on the all-conference team. Recalling
Notre Dame's 73-60 victory over the Red Storm on Jan. 29, Barkley
said: ``You would never think we'd go down to Notre Dame and lose
to Notre Dame. But any team on any given night can beat anybody. I
consider Notre Dame a Cinderella team. I think they'll be in the
NCAA tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, under Coach John McLeod, Notre Dame finished with a
14-16 record, 8-10 in the league. The Irish have not been in the
NCAA tournament for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're kind of having a year like we had last year,''
Barkley said. ``They're doing real well. They are on the rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Barkley and Murphy are coy about a major decision that will
come soon. Should they remain in college or declare for the
professional draft?
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said he has not decided, and Murphy said: ``I don't
know. I'll sit down and talk to coach at the end of the season, and
we will decide from there.'' But, as he accepted his award last
night, Murphy addressed his coach and said ``I just look forward to
next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
