<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-DRESDNER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN BANK IN TALKS TO BUY RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS lede graf to supply attribution; subs 3rd graf for
rewriting) (sw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In a move that could lead to one of the
biggest job reductions yet in Europe, Deutsche Bank AG plans to
acquire a big German domestic rival, Dresdner Bank AG, people close
to the deal said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank is already the largest bank in Europe in terms of
assets and the world's second largest behind the pending
combination of three big Japanese banks. If a deal to purchase
Dresdner Bank goes through, Deutsche Bank would become a far bigger
No. 2, with more than $1.2 trillion in assets, about twice the size
of Citigroup, the largest bank in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said on Tuesday that if the deal _ potentially worth
more than $30 billion _ is completed, the two German banks would
eventually eliminate 1,000 to 2,000 branches in Germany and, over
time, cut tens of thousands of jobs. The two banks have combined
work forces of 120,000 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the deal said the ultimate goal is a fundamental
overhaul of the banks that have been the hub of this country's
postwar economy.
</P>
<P>
   A ``new Deutsche Bank,'' they said, would largely retreat from
the basic business of serving retail customers at local branches.
The combined branch network of both banks would be spun off as a
separate company. Though Deutsche Bank might still own a majority
stake, it would concentrate on serving wealthy individuals and
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Dresdner and Deutsche would only say on Tuesday that
they are in ``advanced'' talks about a collaboration and would hold
a news conference on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the deal said it is to be structured as a
three-way agreement between the two banks and the biggest European
insurer, Allianz of Munich.
</P>
<P>
   All three institutions hold stakes in each other, as well as
many other German companies, and have been at the center of a web
of cross-holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The people close to the talks said that under a proposed
agreement, Allianz would take a significant stake in the new branch
network.
</P>
<P>
   One purpose of the deal would be to guarantee Allianz a
distribution channel for its insurance and investment products. At
the moment, Allianz distributes many of its products through
Dresdner Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Allianz would also like to acquire Deutsche Bank's huge mutual
fund business, known as DWS. People close the talks said this may
also become part of the agreement, because Dresdner Bank has its
own mutual fund business and antitrust regulators in Germany or at
the European Commission in Brussels may demand that one of the two
businesses be sold.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, according to one executive, a combined company would
become what Deutsche Bank's top executives have long wanted: a bank
focused on serving the wealthy and the corporate.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted jubilantly to the prospect of a merger. Shares
of Deutsche Bank rose nearly 8 percent on Tuesday to 94 euros, or
$90.01. Dresdner soared 21 percent, to 57.20 euros, or $54.77.
Allianz shares gained 12.9 percent, to 383.30 euros, or $367.05.
</P>
<P>
   Though German banking executives have speculated about mergers
for years, the prospect of a deal between Deutsche Bank and
Dresdner Bank caught many analysts by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The two held extensive negotiations last year about merging
their retail networks, but Dresdner Bank's chief executive, Bernard
Walter, broke off the talks in September.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank's chief executive, Rolf-Ernst Breuer, has been
restlessly restructuring his company from the time he took over the
top post three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer engineered Deutsche Bank's $10 billion acquisition of the
Bankers Trust Corp. last year, a move that gave Deutsche Bank a
much bigger presence in the United States and strengthened its
position in investment banking and transaction services.
</P>
<P>
   Under Breuer, Deutsche Bank has realized its biggest profits
from trading in bonds and derivative securities like options and
futures.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in large part to those businesses, Deutsche Bank's net
income rose 50 percent in 1999, to 2.6 billion euros. Dresdner's
profit rose 13 percent, to 1.1 billion euros.
</P>
<P>
   But their retail banking businesses have consistently kept
overall profitability below those of American and British financial
institution. Deutsche Bank's return on equity, a commonly used
measure of bank performance, was roughly 9.9 percent last year, and
Dresdner Bank's even lower. By comparison, Citigroup's return on
equity was around 14 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
