<SLUG> BC-ELN-BRADLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TIDE AGAINST HIM, UNDERDOG TURNS TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Refusing to surrender, but aware of the mighty odds
he faced, Bill Bradley has made the painful psychological
adjustment of addressing his presidential campaign in the past
tense here.
</P>
<P>
   New York is where he won fame as a professional basketball
player for the New York Knicks. Across the Hudson River is his home
in New Jersey, which he represented in the US Senate for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   So it was Bradley's poignant choice to spend his last 48 hours
here, awaiting the Super Tuesday results, hoping that New Yorkers
would confound the polls. And as he traveled the city streets, he
took stock of the accomplishments _ and failures _ of his
presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I am most proud of is we put some issues on the
agenda that weren't there before, in terms of health care, in terms
of gun control, in terms of making sure people understand how
important campaign finance reform is in this country,'' Bradley
said on CBS's ``Early Show'' on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the Democratic Party has moved in the direction
that I've pushed it over the last year,'' said Bradley. ``I'm
pleased about that. But, of course, having the party move in a
direction is not the same as leading the party as the candidate, or
as president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   At a noontime rally in Westchester County on Monday, Bradley's
wife, Ernestine, told the crowd, ``It has been a wonderful
experience.'' Then she caught herself and made the correction: ``It
continues to be a wonderful experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband grew poetic. Quoting Eleanor Roosevelt, Bradley told
the crowd to cling to hope because ``the future belongs to those
who believe in the beauty of their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you share my dream,'' Bradley said, ``help me make it our
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   From suburban Westchester, Bradley traveled to Brooklyn, and
then ended his last full day of campaigning with a rally at dusk in
Bryant Park in midtown Manhattan. When the speeches were over, he
lingered long after the crowd had drifted away, chatting with the
well-wishers who remained, as if to savor the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The young, tired members of his staff, many of whom had come to
New York from the campaign headquarters in New Jersey, hugged one
another and took souvenir group photographs at what they knew might
be the last Bradley 2000 rally.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was up early Tuesday, greeting New Yorkers at a bagel
shop, a subway stop, and a polling booth, and telling the mob of
photographers and reporters that ``I think there will be some
surprises today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll win a couple and then we'll move on,'' Bradley said.
``We're far from the end.''
</P>
<P>
   At one stop, Bradley was met by seven male staffers with
B-R-A-D-L-E-Y spelled out in paint on their bare chests. He told
them they looked ``beautiful!''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign began in obscurity last spring, then soared
in excitement and expectation when the polls showed that many
Democrats were tired of the Clinton-Gore scandals and receptive to
a fresh face.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley's cerebral approach to the campaign trail
intrigued many independents, he failed to thrill or clinch the
loyalties of enough wavering Democrats, said Mark Green, a top
Democratic official here.
</P>
<P>
   Vice president Al Gore, the choice of the party establishment,
launched attacks on his rival, questioning Bradley's fortitude and
challenging him in debate. When Bradley suffered a series of minor
heart problems, the sizzle seemed to drain from his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of organized labor and the Democratic faithful,
Gore trounced Bradley in Iowa, and beat him more narrowly in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance at a Bronx high school on Monday, Bradley was
asked why he chose this year to run. He gave the students his
reasons for not running in 1988 or 1992, and acknowledged that time
may have passed him by.
</P>
<P>
   He had once been a famous basketball player, Bradley told the
high school students, but that was long ago, in the days ``before
you were born.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
