<HEADLINE>
FOCUS SHIFTS TO SHORTSTOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Brian Dohn  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
entered spring training wanting to make sure the catching
situation, especially Todd Hundley, was fine.
</P>
<P>
   No problem there, so his next agenda item was to chart the
progress of Mark Grudzielanek in the transition from shortstop to
second base. Again, no drama.
</P>
<P>
   Next on Johnson's list: shortstop. While Alex Cora is the
favorite, Johnson isn't ready to declare Cora the winner of the
four-man battle that includes Juan Castro, Kevin Elster and Jose
Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortstop, that one has been a C-plus,'' Johnson said.
``They've showed me a little nervousness. That's going to get more
of my focus, more of my attention because it's so critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he hasn't focused on the shortstops yet because the
position is so muddled. The Dodgers have 12 middle infielders in
camp. That number will change with the first round of cuts today
and give the contenders a chance to play more innings.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is what type of shortstop best fits this
club. Cora seems the safe bet because he's strong defensively and
showed last season he could hit _ he batted .308 in Triple-A
Albuquerque _ but a sliding scale could be in effect for the
Dodgers' needs.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is superb defensively, but his offense is lacking even at
the minor-league level. Vizcaino is a proven veteran, but his
ability to play anywhere in the infield works against him. Elster
is a wild card, mainly because he played for Johnson during his
Mets days and he provides power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's wait until we find out what type of offensive club we're
going to be,'' Johnson said. ``Right now, we're just trying to get
something going here, and it's slow going. Guys are having trouble
getting going.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Workin' the weights: Right-hander Darren Dreifort's last two
seasons ended with him watching the last few weeks instead of
pitching. Both years it was due to problems with his right
shoulder. Though Dreifort said he could have pitched through it in
1999, he took steps during the offseason to prevent it from being
an issue again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started doing a little bit more, weights-wise,'' Dreifort
said. ``More back work, more back-of-the-shoulder work, lat work.
Stuff like that, maybe strengthen everything around the shoulder
more. I'm anxious to show myself. It's as important to me as it is
to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Tix on sale Friday: Tickets for individual home games,
including the opener against Ken Griffey Jr. and the Cincinnati
Reds, go on sale at 8:30 a.m. Friday at the Dodger Stadium
advance-ticket windows. Tickets can also be purchased by calling
(323) 224-1-HIT.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Scott Boras, the agent for third baseman
Adrian Beltre, and Bob Daly, managing general partner and CEO of
the Dodgers, are supposed to meet today in hopes of working out a
three-year contract that would put an end to a four-month battle
for free agency. If the sides agree on a deal, the players
association will drop the grievance filed on Beltre's behalf. . . .
Lefty Onan Masaoka (sprained left ankle) could be ready to pitch
Thursday and right-hander Mike Fetters (quadricep) is hoping to
return by the weekend. . . . Right-hander Robinson Checo is
expected to arrive in camp today, and when he arrives he'll be
greeted by a trip to minor-league camp instead of big-league camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
