r p BC-BUSH08-COX     03-07 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush supporters buoyed by victories on Tuesday
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As news of George W. Bush's sweeping primary
victories rolled in Tuesday night, several hundred Bush supporters
at the Four Seasons Hotel in downtown Austin celebrated a day they
always expected would come _ if perhaps a little earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Tuesday triumphs virtually assured his nomination as the
Republican candidate for president after a surprisingly strong
challenge from Arizona Sen. John McCain. McCain's victories in New
Hampshire, Arizona and Michigan delayed what looked to be a
coronation last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Johnson, a member of the Austin Republican Women's Club,
was one of the early arrivals. Wearing the group's traditional red,
she sold Bush for President pins that looked like sheriff's badges
for $15 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   She was beaming as the primary results rolled in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to live at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue,'' she
said. ``I don't know of any president who's won without California.
It's in the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   California wasn't among the state's Bush had won by early
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Munday, another club member, said that if Bush hadn't
wrapped up the nomination with his Tuesday night victories, he'd
certainly come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week from tonight is what? Texas and Florida,'' she said,
dragging out the names of the Bush-friendly states in a sing-songy
drawl. Bush's brother Jeb is the governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Munday stood with a thickening crowd outside the
ballroom of the Four Seasons, waiting to be ushered in for the
victory celebration. Outside the hotel, two-dozen satellite trucks
filled the eastern portion of the parking lot, ready to beam news
of Bush's victories around the globe. Reporters, photographers and
cameramen from across America and the world packed into the
ballroom to await Bush's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:45 p.m., Bush strategist Karl Rove strolled through the
lobby outside the ballroom on his way to the first of many
television interviews. Even at that early hour, he was grinning.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd outside the ballroom grew, people jockeyed for
position in front of the four large television sets broadcasting
CNN's coverage of the primary results. Cheers went up when the
screen flashed a graphic showing a Bush victory, with the biggest
cheers reserved for the largest states.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, the televisions showed the scene in the ballroom
next door, which at that point was filled only with reporters and
Bush staff members. Bush volunteers handed out stickers and
campaign literature as the guests came downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Butchko said she'd been waiting for Tuesday night for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's always an anxiety when you see the bumps along
the way, but in my opinion it's made him a much stronger candidate
and solidified his base,'' Butchko said of McCain's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Masset, a Republican consultant based in Austin, dispensed
his political wisdom to a circle of Bush supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly never had a doubt,'' Masset said of Bush's apparent
clinching of the nomination on Tuesday night _ although he admitted
that he had thought the night would come sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of those at the Four Seasons, Masset said McCain's
challenge had only strengthened Bush for a battle with Gore, the
likely Democratic nominee, in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all vetting George something fierce,'' he said. ``It's
far better to learn now. Everyone's a lot stronger for this
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Those inside the Four Seasons were giddy at Bush's big
victories. But on the street outside the hotel, several dozen
protestors were less sanguine about the brightening prospects of a
second Bush presidency. Shouting into a stiff wind, they decried
Bush's support for the death penalty, chanting ``Stop Bush's
killing machine!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically just all anti-Bush, and anti-death penalty,''
said Molly Moore, a student at Austin Community College whose lip
ring and black T-shirt stood in stark contrast to the well-dressed
crowd inside. ``We just want to alert everybody that he's not as
good as he's making himself out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
