<HEADER>
A9882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LOUIMA-VERDICT-N     03-07 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LOUIMA-VERDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A VERDICT ON A COVER-UP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 8:
</P>
<P>
   The conviction of three New York City police officers, Charles
Schwarz, Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder, for conspiracy to obstruct
justice in the torture of Abner Louima concludes the government's
second trial of individuals involved in this vicious crime. A third
trial, of two other officers, Rolando Aleman and Francisco Rosario,
who are charged with lying to federal investigators about the
attack, will begin at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution charged that Schwarz, Wiese and Bruder conspired
to cover up Schwarz's role in the attack. To some observers the
case is troubling because Justin Volpe, the officer who admitted to
ramming a stick into Louima's rectum in a Brooklyn station house
bathroom, says that Schwarz was not in the bathroom and did not
participate in the attack. The defense argued that there could be
no conspiracy to hide Schwarz's involvement since he was not
involved.
</P>
<P>
   But the crime of conspiracy to obstruct justice does not require
a finding that the underlying crime was carried out. It is illegal,
even for a person innocent of the underlying crime, to conspire to
create a false alibi or hinder an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a federal jury convicted Schwarz last June of
helping to hold down Louima while Volpe assaulted him. Volpe
pleaded guilty to the attack during that trial, and has been
sentenced to 30 years in prison. At that trial, Volpe was not
called to testify on Schwarz's behalf. Schwarz maintains he is
innocent, and he is appealing the earlier verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution in this second trial presented evidence of
dozens of phone calls among the three defendants soon after the
assault, and evidence of a meeting they had with a police union
representative to discuss the investigation. The prosecutors argued
that the defendants tailored their accounts to investigators to
protect Schwarz. The most riveting testimony came from Volpe, who
testified that Schwarz was never in the bathroom. But the jury
clearly did not see Volpe's words as proof of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, having lied about his crime initially, has little
credibility. There are serious questions about his motives for
exonerating Schwarz and for placing Wiese in the bathroom during
the assault instead. There was also testimony from two other
officers that they saw Schwarz escort Louima toward the bathroom,
though Schwarz testified that he was outside the station house
searching his patrol car during the assault.
</P>
<P>
   All three defendants are expected to appeal Monday's verdict.
The torture of Louima has brought enormous shame to the Police
Department. Prosecuting the cover-up is as important as punishing
the brutality itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
