<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ELN-PRIMARIES-NY     03-07 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ELN-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SUPER TUESDAY PRIMARIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 8:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on early returns and exit polls, Vice President Al Gore
won a sweeping nationwide victory in the ``Super Tuesday''
primaries, sealing his capture of the Democratic presidential
nomination. Gov. George W. Bush also appeared to be headed toward
capturing most of the delegates at stake, based on exit surveys in
California and vote tabulations elsewhere. Sen. John McCain's
victories in New England may persuade him to continue his
candidacy, but he will face long odds. Bush is expected to shift
his focus now to the general election, but the tough primary
contests have left him looking more battered than anyone could have
predicted when he began as a pre-emptive favorite. Recent polls
show him even with Gore, instead of leading the vice president as
he was a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate, Gore has scored one of the most impressive
recoveries in many years. He started out only six months ago
struggling to overcome his image s an awkward figure running a
costly, uninspired campaign based on the idea of entitlement. When
Democrats started moving toward Bill Bradley as a fresher
candidate, Gore junked his campaign plan, threw off the smothering
cloak of supposed inevitability and starting fighting for the
nomination. He emerged from his clashes with Bradley with a sharper
debating style, though still lacking the kind of emotional
connection with voters that seemed to come so easily to McCain on
the Republican side. Gore's unbroken string of primary victories
has made him no less reviled by Republicans, but many of them admit
that he will be a tough competitor in November.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Gore was able to use the primaries as a warm-up, they
have been a battle for survival for Bush and McCain. Bush, in
particular, endured unexpected questions about his knowledge,
experience and debating skills. But the most ominous sign for the
Republicans, if Bush gets the nomination, may be the ideological
repositioning forced upon him by McCain. After stepping onto the
national political stage as a new-style Republican moderate, Bush
was forced to embrace the agenda of the party's cultural
conservatives in order to counter McCain's reform candidacy. Now
when he tries to move back to the center, Bush will find Gore
camped out there, if the two meet in the general election. McCain's
victories in the primaries in Massachusetts, Connecticut and
Vermont were another sign of Bush's continuing difficulties in
areas with moderate voting patterns.
</P>
<P>
   But if Bush's lead in the exit polls in California holds up, his
supporters will have ample reason for optimism about his potential
in the mega-states. Next Tuesday will bring primaries in Texas,
Florida and other friendly Sun Belt states. As Tuesday's win in
Georgia attests, Bush has a strong regional base and deep campaign
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed there has been a lot of talk in recent weeks about
``firewalls'' in various states known to be reliable Bush
strongholds, ready to prevent a stampede to McCain. In the end,
however, the governor's main firewall has been money _ his own and
the large sums put up by his rich Texas friends to pay for attack
ads at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not McCain continues after Super Tuesday, he clearly
fell far short of the scenario his team envisioned following the
New Hampshire victory on Feb. 1. It was then that his spokesmen
talked openly of igniting one state after another with McCain's
heroic story and his crusade for reform. When he was attacked
unfairly by the religious right in South Carolina, McCain returned
the fire. But his decision to counterattack now looks like a costly
tactical mistake that damaged the aura of his campaign and revived
old worries about his temperament. Even Republicans friendly to him
were unsettled by the ferocious tone of his attack on Christian
conservative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to say what McCain's future will be this year.
Even if he drops out of the race, he will probably continue to
speak out and espouse his appeal for moderation and especially for
campaign finance reform, demanding that the party listen as the
price for vigorously supporting the nominee. Whatever happens,
McCain has opened a historically significant debate among
Republicans over the fundamental purpose and direction of their
party. That debate must continue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
