A9887 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PRAIRIE-FIRE08-COX     03-07 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAIRIE-FIRE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prairie fires replenish and restore
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Early settlers to the West called them
``necklaces,'' long, thin lines of dancing light stretching from
horizon to horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon was caused by the leading edge of immense prairie
grass fires, touched off by lightning and often consuming millions
of acres of the tall prairie grass that once covered the West.
</P>
<P>
   Prairie fires were not uncommon in Ohio, either. American
Indians as far back as 10,000 years ago, as their societies became
more agricultural based, set fire to prairies, showing a knowledge
of land management.
</P>
<P>
   Fires help replenish and restore prairies.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the warm, dry weather, Five Rivers
MetroParks managers set fire to the big prairie at Possum Creek on
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying cans of diesel fuel and gasoline, David Nolin and Mary
Klunk of Five Rivers MetroParks lit a backfire on the downwind side
of the 50-acre prairie to contain the main blaze. Other park
workers kept the fire in check with water hoses.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to the other side, with a steady southwest wind at her
back, Klunk then ignited the main fire. In a flash, a string of
fire swept across the dry grass field, sending a surge of smoke
into the sky and turning the ground black.
</P>
<P>
   Klunk, who is a land stewardship specialist, directs prairie
burns every two or three years on some portion of MetroParks' 300
acres of prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Left unattended, prairies in Ohio can become choked with vining,
cool-weather plants such as fescue and start turning into tree
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burning gets rid of some of the woody plants,'' Klunk
said. ``Also the blackened ground warms up quicker, which releases
nutrients and allows the seeds to germinate sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   The prairie, which contains Indian grass, big bluestem, prairie
cord grass and little blue stem, will have grown back by late May,
Klunk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plant diversity is one of our main goals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The park workers conduct the burn with great caution, but not
without some fun.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the job touches some deep childhood wish to set a
really big fire, Klunk said, ``Oh, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
