u a BC-TEENS-KILLED08-COX     03-07 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-KILLED08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio man gets 4 life terms for killings
 &HT;    By Lisa Perry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIDNEY, Ohio _ In a plea agreement to avoid a possible death
sentence, a man who his lawyer said believed ``Satan was more
powerful than God'' admitted Tuesday to the murders of three
teen-age girls and a Bible studies teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Michael Hensley entered the pleas in Shelby County
Common Pleas Court. The three-judge panel then sentenced the
30-year-old to four consecutive life terms, plus 80 years, without
the possibility of parole for the July 8 deaths of the three teens
_ Sherry Kimbler, 16; Kimbler's cousin, Tosha Barrett, 16;
14-year-old Amy Mikesell; and Brett Wildermuth, Hensley's
37-year-old Bible studies teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The shackled Hensley sobbed and wiped tears from his cheeks when
sentenced. The victims' families, who packed the courtroom, were in
tears for most of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say I'm sorry to all the victims' families. I'm
sorry for taking your daughters' lives. I am so sorry. It haunts me
all the time, that they won't get their licenses or go to
Homecoming, or get married. Sheila (Wildermuth's wife), I am so
sorry for what I did to Brett,'' Hensley said through his sobs.
``Please forgive me. Please forgive me for what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley also pleaded guilty to three counts of attempted
aggravated murder, and three counts of kidnapping. In exchange for
the plea, Shelby County Prosecutor Jim Stevenson said he would not
seek the death penalty out of deference to the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just wanted closure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley's lawyer, Kort Gatterdam, said prior to sentencing that
testimony would have shown that Hensley had a mental defect that
made him unable to understand ``the criminality of his conduct.''
Hensley also was addicted to exposing himself and believed that
members of an imaginary satanic cult were trying to harm him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hensley) began to create a cult,'' Gatterdam said. ``Not a
real cult, but something to cover up that he was a very sick
individual who needed help. He could not beat his addiction. ... He
continued to pay people so he could expose himself to them. ... He
was possessed by the thought that Satan was more powerful than
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Police were called to Hensley's Sidney home July 8, moments
after Veronica Eagy, 22, crawled out of the house's basement. Eagy
had been shot numerous times, but survived. Wildermuth was shot
inside his home outside Sidney 20 minutes after police began
searching Hensley's home. Mikesell and Kimbler were both stabbed
and beaten; Barrett was beaten and shot in the chest at close range
with a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson said Hensley killed the teens to cover up activities
with the girls in which criminal charges could have been filed. He
did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
