<HEADER>
A9889 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-MUSIC-$     03-07 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-MUSIC-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AUSTRIA, POLITICS WAVES THE BATON 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., March 12) 
(jt) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diplomatic relations are one thing. The really important
business of Austria is music, and while the hills are sure to be
alive this summer, they do not look entirely well.
</P>
<P>
   As is so often the case, the venerable Salzburg Festival
promises to be the center of attention among European music
festivals, but the reasons extend well beyond the usual sheer
quality and variety of its presentations. A noisy dispute about the
nature of the programming erupted last year between Gerard Mortier,
the festival's innovative artistic director, and a traditionalist
rear guard including Thomas Klestil, the nation's president.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that appears mild compared with the potential storm
brewing this year around the inclusion of Joerg Haider's right-wing
Freedom Party in the national governing coalition. Haider, who
stepped down as leader of the party on Feb. 28, and his
sympathizers are widely thought to be soft on Nazism if not kindly
disposed toward it, and the 14 other European Union nations have
downgraded diplomatic relations with Austria. Now, musicians from
around the world are reconsidering their activities in that
country.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, events in Salzburg and elsewhere are subject to
change. The pianist Andras Schiff, who is scheduled to participate
in the Vienna Festival this summer, though not in Salzburg until
next year, has said that as long as Haider and the Freedom Party
remain in power, he intends to cancel his appearances in Austria
one by one. As proof of his intentions, he canceled a performance
at the Austrian Embassy in Washington during his recent triumphal
American tour, citing his intense distress, as an Austrian citizen
and a European Jew, at political events back home.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier, whose successor, Peter Ruzicka, has already been named
for next year, has called for a boycott of another national
showcase, the annual New Year's concerts of the Vienna
Philharmonic. In addition, he has threatened to oust the Austrian
conductor Nikolaus Harnoncourt, a recent mainstay of the Salzburg
Festival, if he accepts an invitation to become involved with those
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   What is promised in Salzburg, at any rate, is a handsome array
of operas on stage and in concert, radiating outward from a
familiar core of Mozart (``Cosi Fan Tutte,'' ``Don Giovanni'' and
``Idomeneo'') and Wagner (``Tristan und Isolde''). Other staged
works are all in French: Gluck's ``Iphigenie en Tauride,''
Berlioz's ``Troyens'' and Offenbach's ``Belle Helene.'' Even the
new opera by Kaija Saariaho, a Finnish composer with whom New York
Philharmonic audiences made a happy acquaintance last year,
``L'Amour de Loin,'' will be in French, with Peter Sellars
directing.
</P>
<P>
   The concert presentations, on the other hand, range from the
French of Cherubini's ``Medee'' to the Russian of Tchaikovsky's
``Queen of Spades'' and Rimsky-Korsakov's ``Invisible City of
Kitezh,'' and the Danish of Carl Nielsen's ``Saul and David.''
</P>
<P>
   A game of musical podiums involving the conductors of some of
those works has already taken place, with Claudio Abbado
withdrawing and Lorin Maazel and Valery Gergiev taking on new
assignments: more a matter of musical shenanigans as usual,
presumably, than of world politics. Among the star singers
scheduled to appear are Renee Fleming in ``Don Giovanni'' and Ben
Heppner and Waltraud Meier in ``Tristan.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna Festival, too, explores fascinating operatic byways,
with Monteverdi's ``Incoronazione di Poppea'' and Schumann's
``Genoveva.'' In the present climate, this festival's opening
event, on May 12, in which ``2,000 musicians send their greetings
from Vienna to the world to celebrate the year 2000,'' as a
prospectus puts it, sounds loaded in every sense.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna Philharmonic, meanwhile, a fixture in both of those
festivals, strikes an altogether different note on May 7, with a
long-planned and perhaps now increasingly meaningful memorial
concert at a former concentration camp in Mauthausen, Austria. Sir
Simon Rattle conducts the orchestra in Beethoven's Ninth Symphony
as ``an affirmation of humanity at a site of horror,'' in the words
of Clemens Hellsberg, the Philharmonic's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   A final uncertainty for Austria, whatever the administrators and
artists decide, is audiences. How eager will foreigners be to
travel to Austria and to patronize such events? Other festivals
around Europe could hardly be blamed for sensing an opportunity
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Zurich Festival, for example, was intended as a rival to
Salzburg when it was founded four years ago. And Switzerland in
general must be relieved that the shadowy activities of its banks
during and after World War II have been crowded from the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   In Zurich, Franz Welser-Moest will conduct a potted history of
Germanic opera: Mozart's ``Zauberfloete,'' Berg's ``Wozzeck'' and
``Lulu,'' and Strauss' ``Arabella.'' And Cecilia Bartoli will sing
two soprano parts in Haydn's ``Anima del Filosofo.''
</P>
<P>
   A commemoration of the 250th anniversary of Bach's death
involves a variety of specialists, including Harnoncourt, John
Eliot Gardiner and Reinhard Goebel. And Wolfgang Sawallisch leads
the Tonhalle Orchestra in Brahms' ``German Requiem'' on his way to
Salzburg, to conduct the Vienna Philharmonic in Schumann's Requiem.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucerne Festival, too, offers glittering attractions. Schiff
plays all the major keyboard works of Bach, a series he began last
month at Lincoln Center and completes in the fall at Carnegie Hall.
In what amounts to a royal flush of European orchestras, Abbado
conducts the Berlin Philharmonic, Zubin Mehta the Vienna
Philharmonic and Riccardo Chailly the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra
of Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the musical hills of Austria and Switzerland, the
Munich Opera Festival celebrates a composer who wrote no operas,
Bach, with a performance of his ``St. John Passion'' and with the
jazz fusion pianist Uri Caine playing the ``Goldberg'' Variations.
Not surprisingly, composers who did write operas are also amply
represented: Handel, Mozart, Strauss and Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   But for full immersion in Wagner, the Bayreuth Festival, founded
by the composer, remains the place to go. A new production of ``Der
Ring des Nibelungen,'' directed and designed by Juergen Flimm and
Erich Wonder, and conducted by Giuseppe Sinopoli, gives New Yorkers
the option of a second opinion after the Met's ``Ring'' revival in
the spring. In addition, Christoph Eschenbach conducts
``Parsifal,'' Christian Thielemann ``Die Meistersinger von
Nuernberg'' and Antonio Pappano ``Lohengrin.''
</P>
<P>
   In other climes, there are attractions aplenty in
Aix-en-Provence, France (with intensive activities by the
contemporary specialist Pierre Boulez and the Baroque specialist
William Christie); in St. Petersburg, Russia (with Valery Gergiev
conducting Prokofiev's ``Fiery Angel,'' ``War and Peace'' and
``Semyon Kotko'' at the White Nights Festival); and in
Glyndebourne, England (with Janacek's ``Jenufa,'' Britten's ``Peter
Grimes'' and Stravinsky's ``Rake's Progress'' blended with Mozart).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, listeners who wish to turn their backs squarely on
Austria might look to a new opera festival at the Roman Theater in
Caesarea, Israel. With forces from the New Israeli Opera, Strauss'
``Elektra'' will have what is said to be its first staging in
Israel, alongside Puccini's ``Tosca'' and a concert featuring
Jessye Norman. To be sure, it's not quite Salzburg, but then, for
good or ill, what else is?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
