<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9890 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHYALAMAN-FILMS-2TAKE     03-07 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHYALAMAN-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIRECTOR WITH A SENSE OF WHERE HE'S GOING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   Jamie Malanowski's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the film ``Boiler Room.''  
 (af)  
 By JAMIE MALANOWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Call it vision, or perspective, or intuition.
Call it the residue of a boy's imagination (``From when I was about
7 to about 13, I had weird feelings, and people had to stay with me
because I felt uneasy about the room or the house I was in.'')
Ascribe it to a sensitivity earned from a youth in schools as the
only Indian among Americans, the only Hindu among Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Attribute it to the eye that is trained when a 10-year-old is
given a movie camera, which he uses to make 45 short films before
age 15. Whatever the reason, it should seem appropriate that M.
Night Shyamalan _ M., for Manoj; Night, a name he adopted at 17
(``romantic, mysterious, poetic''); Shyamalan (pronounced
SHA-ma-lan) _ would come up with ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's a thriller about a boy, Cole, who sees things
that no one else can see (dead people, as it happens), and it
features an alarming secret, numerous clues to which have been
sitting in plain sight. Shyamalan has a way of seeing things other
people do not see, and recognizing things others are slow to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about knowing that Bruce Willis could play the subtle
and subdued psychiatrist Malcolm Crowe because of the way he played
John McClane, the can-do cop in ``Die Hard.'' He says he sensed
that Haley Joel Osment, 11, whose astonishing performance has won
him a best supporting actor nomination, could handle the part of
the emotionally fraught, hypercompassionate Cole because he showed
up at his audition wearing a suit.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about casting Toni Collette, the actress whose
performance as Lynn, Cole's mother, earned her a best supporting
actress nomination: how she came in with her head shaved wearing,
as he puts it, ``this bag,'' and how he ended up just flat-out
telling the studio he wanted her and denying he had an audition
tape to send them, because ``with the way she looked it would be
difficult for them to get her, to think of her as a Philadelphia
mom, kind of sexy but kind of tired, but in an endearing way.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could they see all that I saw in her?''
</P>
<P>
   How does anyone? Barry Mendel, one of the producers of ``The
Sixth Sense,'' remembers the day he saw the rough cut of the
picture. ``Afterwards, Night said: `I think we did it. I think
we'll get a best picture nomination.' I thought we'd done a good
job, but he was way ahead of the rest of us.'' Young Osment recalls
that during filming Shyamalan, a basketball fan, shot hoops to
relax, and that ``one day he made 20 foul shots in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Osment adds the kicker: ``With his eyes closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Successful pro quarterbacks will often refer to the point in
their careers when the game ``slows down'' and they can see the
momentarily available gaps in the defense. Hockey mavens talk about
Wayne Gretzky's extraordinary vision, how he could see who would be
open for a pass before anyone else would even look. These athletes
do not feel they are seeing anything extraordinary; these patterns
are just what they see, and that, of course, is what is
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Shyamalan is in possession of something similar. He is
only 29, and ``The Sixth Sense'' is only the third picture he has
directed. Yet in that film he has managed to combine artistry and
commercial appeal ($600 million worldwide, and counting) to make a
genre film with a genuine emotional touch, a suspense film with a
genuinely surprising ending. It has earned six Oscar nominations,
including best picture, and two _ best screenplay and best director
_ for him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everything is instantly visible to Shyamalan.
``The big challenge in writing the screenplay was to not make this
story the familiar, unimportant, popcorn-type pabulum,'' he says,
sitting in the production offices of his next movie,
``Unbreakable,'' in a vacant, fairly dilapidated, ivy-overrun
museum on the edge of the University of Pennsylvania campus. ``It
took a lot of drafts until I got even a moment that I thought was
truthful, and it wasn't until the sixth draft that I thought of the
ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the film's popularity means that more than a few
readers know the ending, nothing will be revealed here, except to
say that Shyamalan found it challenging to preserve the secret in
the story. ``It was really restricting, because the character
couldn't do a lot of things,'' he says. ``But it was exciting, too.
</P>
<P>
   I had to make dialogue scenes feel like movement. Take that
early scene between the psychiatrist and Cole, when he has Cole
move forward if he says something right, and step back if he was
wrong. I needed the movie to have a sense of physicality to it, so
you wouldn't notice how passive he was being. And it had to be on
the edge of eerie but not confusing. You couldn't have people
saying, `What the hell's wrong with him?'''
</P>
<P>
   Excited as he was by the screenplay, Mendel was even more
impressed by how confident, even daring, the relatively
inexperienced Shyamalan was as a director. (His two earlier efforts
_ the independent productions ``Praying With Anger,'' a
semi-autobiographical film about an Indian-American visiting India
in which he starred, and ``Wide Awake,'' about a boy's search for
God _ created little stir.)
</P>
<P>
   Mendel points to the scene in which the mother and the boy are
having dinner and discussing a bumblebee pendant that keeps showing
up in his room. ``The safe way to handle that scene would be to
shoot it a couple of times and cut them together,'' Mendel says.
``But Night shot it all in one shot, with no coverage, meaning
there's no way to edit it or shorten it or finesse mistakes. And
Night just said, `I promise you it won't be boring, I promise you
we won't need to cut, I promise you it will work.' I kept wishing
he'd shoot close-ups, but he was totally confident, with a kind of
boldness that's scary in one so young. And he was totally right.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one lesson Shyamalan, a New York University film school
graduate, took from ``The Sixth Sense'' was to have
(italics)more(end italics) confidence in himself. ``I learned that
when I get the feeling that something's wrong,'' he says, ``that I
shouldn't ignore it and just keep pushing through and pushing
through, and not listen to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He talks about a scene he wrote, in which Cole and Lynn are in a
car: ``Cole sees a pregnant woman, and he screams, `Watch out!' and
the car hits the woman, and the woman goes through the windshield,
and Lynn hits the brakes and almost causes an accident. And then he
opens his eyes, and the windshield's fine, it was just one of his
visions. The scene was really exciting, almost a pure action scene,
but I knew it would ruin the pace. But then I also thought the
audience would love it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He ended up shooting the scene, at great cost and difficulty,
but it did not get into the film. ``And I knew from the beginning
it shouldn't have!'' Shyamalan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when you're doing something at the highest level,
you understand the flow of things without knowing why. Now I grasp
that. I wrote one of those scenes for `Unbreakable.' I thought it
was great, and I added more, and more, and more, but then I
realized, `This is that scene!' And I pulled it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbreakable,'' which will begin shooting next month, is about
a man who has survived a train wreck. (A lot of Shyamalan's
projects explore death, one exception being the screenplay he wrote
for ``Stuart Little.'' Doesn't he have a nice romantic comedy
floating within? ``I have them. I have a great idea for a comedy
with Jim Carrey that would kill. But I just can't bring myself to
do them. They just don't feel resonant enough. They just don't have
enough weight.'')
</P>
<P>
   Disney paid Shyamalan $5 million for the screenplay, a record
amount for a screenplay written on spec, and paid him another $5
million to direct. Again he wrote the screenplay with Bruce Willis
in mind but without any commitment, and again Willis will star
(reportedly he signed onto ``Unbreakable'' practically overnight
and told Shyamalan that ``it would be an honor'' to appear in the
movie.)
</P>
<P>
   I'm always surprised about how closely we think about our
characters,'' Shyamalan says. ``There's a trust thing that's
happening that's working both ways. In `The Sixth Sense,' in the
Vincent scene'' _ an early scene in which Malcolm Crowe is
confronted by a former patient _ ``I wrote it with Vincent having
the gun out and aiming it at Bruce the whole scene. And Bruce said:
`You know, I'm known for having guns pointed at me. Let's not make
this a gun scene. Let's make this about Malcolm talking to a
disturbed patient.' And he was absolutely right. The gun didn't
appear until Malcolm was shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Shyamalan is handsome, trim, friendly, neatly and plainly
dressed, a dedicated family man who has made up his mind to live
and work in Philadelphia, where he grew up, the son of two
physicians. He lives in the suburbs with Bhavna, his wife of seven
years, and their two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not willing to give up a normal life plan in order to make
movies,'' he says calmly. (His hometown has reciprocated his ardor.
At a Sixers game he attended recently his face was shown on the
Jumbotron, and the crowd cheered. ``It was sweet,'' he says,
``definitely.'')
</P>
<P>
   He is very matter of fact about his accomplishments; if there is
no self-effacing humor or self-doubt or astonishment, neither is
there any bragging. He does not refer to himself in the third
person, but seems able to see himself that way, almost as a
character. He says that if his first two films had not been
failures, his current success would have been ``meaningless; it
wouldn't have been a good experience to have.''
</P>
<P>
   He likens himself to an athlete who ``went from `I wish I could
play' to being on the team, to coming off the bench, to being a
star, to being an all-star, all in one season, and it was a weird
feeling, because I never got to feel those middle things.'' He
describes his experience as ``an interesting arc.'' He speaks about
having to give up moviemaking, or about the possibility of hitting
a dry period, almost clinically, like the fiction writer he is,
clicking off possible fates a character could meet in Act II.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mendel, Shyamalan is not much of a cinema
historian. Among the directors he admires are Peter Weir, Cameron
Crowe, Alfred Hitchcock and the Wachowski Brothers. (``Whatever you
think of `The Matrix,' every shot is there because of the passion
they have! You can see they argued it out!'') Not surprisingly, at
the top of the list is Steven Spielberg, who has made the kind of
large-themed movies with wide audience appeal that Shyamalan
envisions himself directing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in things coming together right,'' says Shyamalan, a
man used to seeing things others do not. ``It's not altogether a
coincidence that as a kid I saw `Jaws' and `E.T.' and dreamed about
making movies, and that in the room where I write I have three
posters _ `Jaws,' `E.T.' and `Jurassic Park.' And now the poster
for `The Sixth Sense' is there, and actually, when I sit down to
write now, in the image of `Jaws,' in the black, you see `The Sixth
Sense' reflected. It's not like I sat there, lining up the
reflection _ it just happened! And he was 28 when he made `Jaws,'
the same age I was when I made `Sixth Sense.' Maybe life has
orchestrated itself that way, or if it's destiny or what. But right
now I see things coming together, and everything is in balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
