<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-CITY-BALLET-$ADV12     03-07 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CITY-BALLET-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN NOTHING BUT NEW MASTERPIECES WILL SUFFICE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While waiting for the next Balanchine to fill the
original Balanchine's shoes, the trick is to preserve his legacy
and breathe fresh air into the company he founded.
</P>
<P>
   One solution, as the New York City Ballet demonstrated this
winter, is to present an exuberantly danced season, introduce young
and gifted dancers, and realize that there is no second Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it would be helpful to accept the idea, 17 years
after George Balanchine's death, that his kind of genius comes
along only once every 100 years and to stop measuring other
choreographers in the company by his standard.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, do what he and Lincoln Kirstein did as founders and
directors of the City Ballet: encourage talent from within the
ranks to create ballets, and invite guest choreographers. Remember
also that all the premieres once staged for City Ballet by
Frederick Ashton, Antony Tudor, William Dollar, Lew Christensen,
Todd Bolender, Ruthanna Boris, John Taras and Birgit Cullberg, to
list a few established names, have long vanished from City Ballet's
repertory.
</P>
<P>
   These works may not have been masterpieces, but they were worth
doing, and some were considered hits. None had to undergo the
scrutiny that every premiere does today.
</P>
<P>
   If masterpieces were not required or expected, this was possibly
because Balanchine and Jerome Robbins, the company's two founding
choreographers, provided the balance. They created the occasional
masterpieces that still exist at City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   But now a young choreographer's premiere suffers precisely
because it is surrounded by masterpieces. Even established
choreographers are asked to meet some impossible standard when they
step into City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   It was nonetheless a capital idea for Peter Martins, the
company's artistic director, to invite Twyla Tharp to create a
premiere, ``The Beethoven Seventh,'' for the recently concluded
season. Inevitably, there would be disappointment among viewers who
expect Tharp to clown around forever as she did in 1976 with ``Push
Comes to Shove,'' created for Mikhail Baryshnikov and American
Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``The Beethoven Seventh,'' set to the composer's Seventh
Symphony, is the best of Tharp's works in the classical idiom. It
breaks down ballet conventions and extends City Ballet's dancers in
new directions.
</P>
<P>
   One sees them in a fresh light, looking more uninhibited but
still performing with the strong classical technique that allows
Tharp to try out difficult and speedy combinations of steps. In
short, a serious ballet and a step forward for Tharp.
</P>
<P>
   Her Beethoven, however, is not everyone's Beethoven. He is used
more as a challenge than a springboard. Not for Tharp the logic of
following a composer's structure when she can build her own
structures and mesh them into the music's rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   There is no point in inviting an experimentalist like Tharp into
the City Ballet and then assuming she will choreograph like
Balanchine or Robbins. That is not her background. Although she
collaborated with Robbins on her only other work for City Ballet
(``Brahms/Handel,'' 1984), she is not necessarily familiar with key
works in the company. She has never seen ``The Cage,'' one of
Robbins' most famous ballets.
</P>
<P>
   Tharp comes out of modern dance and the fact that her own early,
spiraling idiom has been largely replaced in the last 25 years by
ballet's academic vocabulary does not alter her approach to music.
Like many modern dancers, she is apt to choreograph to no music and
then add it later; or she will substitute music in performance that
was not used initially in rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   Even Roland Petit, following Jean Cocteau's directions,
choreographed to jazz and then used Bach's Passacaglia in his
landmark ballet, ``Le Jeune Homme et La Mort.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that surprising to learn that the central duet in
``The Beethoven Seventh,'' danced so magnificently by Nikolaj Hubbe
and Wendy Whelan, began in the studio to music from a couple of
Beethoven sonatas rather than the symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Yet paradoxically, the choreography's fit to the symphony's
second movement is striking. Anyone can hear its dirgelike sound
and Tharp extends these rhythms into her own dramatic image of
irretrievable loss. Hubbe, limping to the staggered chords, has a
whirlwind encounter with Whelan, whose technical brilliance
deliberately contrasts with his weighted heroic postures. When she
is carried off by a cortege of men, not once but twice, Hubbe's
body breaks down in isolated movements, a study in disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, the ballet is a pure-dance work, an experiment
with the ballet vocabulary. It is not, as in the past, an example
of Tharp's inability to accept this idiom as a given. Here is a
Neo-Classical ballet with a difference.
</P>
<P>
   True, Tharp's obsession with counterpoint brings in too many
crisscrossing lines in the opening ensemble, led by the mercurial
Tom Gold and the noble Peter Boal, partnering Jenifer Ringer. This
raw outburst excites with its refusal to be neat or packaged or to
keep the dancing in one place. Entire groups nest on one side of
the stage rather than yield to conventional symmetrical design.
</P>
<P>
   Tharp is hardly the first to see Beethoven's symphony as a
bridge between the Classical and Romantic eras. Boal embodies the
first principle in the initial movement and Damian Woetzel, with
Miranda Weese, embodies the more emotional aspect in his fabulous
Pan-like creature. He leads the third movement into the jubilant
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Within the context of repertory, ``The Beethoven Seventh'' is
more than just another addition. And it is not just another Tharp
ballet. Unlike many of the works she has staged for Ballet Theater
or her modern-dance troupe, this one has nobody in sneakers. Nor
are there contrasts between classical dancers and modern dancers.
</P>
<P>
   There are simply no modern dancers in City Ballet. Those who
have never liked the company are those who have never been
interested in the steps of the academic idiom for their own sake.
Kirstein, just 10 years ago, still promoted the company as the
``fortress of the traditional classic dance.'' Tharp did not storm
the gates this time around. She walked right in and felt at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
