<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9893 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-COX     03-07 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court issues guidance on abortion law
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Further defining how a state law governing
abortion for minors will be applied, the Texas Supreme Court on
Tuesday set standards for lower courts to use when deciding whether
it would not be in the child's best interest to notify parents that
their daughter is seeking an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature passed the Parental Notification Act last year
to require physicians who perform abortions to notify the parents
if a minor daughter seeks one. But the law also gave minors the
right to apply to a state district judge to get an abortion without
parental notification.
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-2 ruling written by Justice Craig Enoch, the court said a
district judge must consider at least four factors in deciding
whether, as the law puts it, ``notification would not be in (her)
best interests'': her emotional or physical needs; the possibility
of emotional or physical danger to the minor; the stability of her
home and whether notification ``would cause serious and lasting
harm to the family structure''; and the effect of notification on
the girl's relationship with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling did not identify the minor, ``Jane Doe 2,'' or where
the case originated.
</P>
<P>
   But a dissent by Justice Nathan Hecht, joined by Justice Greg
Abbott, said she was 16 years old, lived with both parents, was a
junior in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Doe 1 was the unidentified minor in the court's first
ruling on Feb. 25 that outlined how judges should decide whether a
girl was mature and sufficiently informed to get an abortion
without telling her parents.
</P>
<P>
   A trial judge and appeals court had turned down Jane Doe 2's
application. The Supreme Court told the judge to reconsider in
lights of its rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
