<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-WEST-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRENCH-RUSSIAN TEAM TELLS A FORGOTTEN STORY OF THE COLD WAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The end of the Cold War was definitely bad news for
those novelists and screenwriters who were counting on the ``evil
empire'' to provide them with plots for life. Yet, while the KGB
may no longer be a credible adversary, the old Soviet Union has not
been exhausted as a font of good stories. In fact, thanks to the
collapse of Communism, it is now possible to see many human dramas
long obscured by the glare of the ideological struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The French director Regis Wargnier's new movie, ``East-West,''
nominated for best foreign language film in this year's Oscars,
recounts one such drama. When it was released in France last
summer, some critics described it as anti-Communist. Yet, in a
sense, it is no more anti-Communist than ``Indochine,'' Wargnier's
prize-winning 1991 film about the struggle against French
colonialism, was pro-Communist. Both films are love stories in
which love is tested by _ and eventually triumphs over _ politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have made this movie in any place or any country where
there had been a totalitarian regime,'' the 51-year-old Wargnier
said of ``East-West,'' which opens in the United States on March
31. ``I was most interested in the human relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   It no doubt helps that the political context of the movie is
relatively unfamiliar. After World War II, thousands of Russian
exiles living in France were wooed back to the Soviet Union in the
name of reconstructing the motherland. Once they arrived by boat or
train, often accompanied by French spouses, most were forever cut
off from the West. Some were assigned work, but others, suspected
of being spies, were sent to labor camps. Only a handful managed to
escape.
</P>
<P>
   Wargnier first learned of these returnees and their dismal fate
in the mid-1980s. Then, a decade later, while researching another
film in Kazakhstan, he met some French-speaking Russians who
explained that they were brought up in France and returned to the
Soviet Union with their parents in the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all said the same thing,'' he recalled in an interview in
his Montmartre apartment, ``the very dramatic conditions of their
arrival, people being separated, some being sent to camps, others
sent into `exile' in Kazakhstan because it was difficult to leave
there. Some were also `saved' because they were useful to the
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Wargnier mentioned these dramatic stories to the Russian movie
director Sergei Bodrov (``Prisoner of the Mountains'') and the idea
of a film was born. Wargnier brought in the French writer Louis
Gardel, while Bodrov invited the Russian author Roustam Ibraguimbek
to join their screenwriting team. Their script was filmed in
Ukraine and Bulgaria over 12 weeks in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a true story, but it could have been,'' Wargnier
said. ``Everything is real except our characters. But there were
people whose experiences were very similar.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie opens aboard a ship carrying scores of returning
Russian exiles, among them Aleksei Golovine, a Russian doctor
played by Oleg Menchikov; his French wife, Marie, played by
Sandrine Bonnaire, and their young son, Serioja. Their optimism
disappears as soon as they land in Odessa and their passports are
seized. Allocated a single room in a communal apartment in Kiev,
they immediately recognize they have made a mistake. Marie demands
to return to Paris; Aleksei already knows this is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Marie, though, does not give up, ignoring Aleksei's warning that
she is putting the entire family at risk. She sees her first chance
to escape when a famous French actress, Gabrielle Develay
(Catherine Deneuve), arrives in Kiev with a French theater troupe.
Marie appeals to Develay for help, but Aleksei steps between them.
With her marriage increasingly strained, Marie turns her attention
to a 17-year-old neighbor, Sacha, played by Sergei Bodrov Jr., the
son of the director. Sacha is a champion swimmer who also dreams of
freedom. Friendship grows into love and, when Sacha escapes, he
pledges to rescue her. Instead, the KGB discovers her collusion and
jails her. Aleksei, however, does not abandon her.
</P>
<P>
   Wargnier credits his Russian co-writers for what he believes is
the authenticity of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have done the film without them,'' he said. ``It's
their lives. It's their blood. When I suggested that Aleksei and
Marie would live in a big building outside Moscow, they said, no,
those apartment blocs were built later. When I had Marie taking a
train on her own, they said, no, she'd be arrested within two
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shooting the film in Ukraine and Bulgaria presented different
challenges. It helped, for instance, that Kiev today still looks
much as it did in the 1950s, so no new sets had to be built. On the
other hand, Ukrainian and Bulgarian film crews had little
experience with new movie equipment. Further, Bonnaire noted, the
psychological scars left by Communism have not fully healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still very distrustful,'' she said in a telephone
interview. ``They are people who have been silent for long years,
so it is not easy for themselves to learn how to express themselves
overnight. It was also delicate for them because we were telling
their story. At times, we all felt a bit like exiles, like the
characters in the film, wondering if we would ever get out.''
</P>
<P>
   A different kind of cultural gap became apparent when Menchikov
arrived to work on the movie. A major star in Russia thanks to his
leading roles in ``Prisoner of the Mountains'' and in Nikita
Mikhalkov's ``Burnt by the Sun'' and ``Barber of Siberia,'' he
showed no interest in mixing with other members of the cast or
crew. He also refused to rehearse, even though he speaks no French
and learned his French-speaking role phonetically. Bonnaire grew
alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oleg is unapproachable,'' she said. ``When he's not on the
set, you never know where he is. And yes, he is very mysterious.
Perhaps he protects himself by isolating himself. I was scared.
Would he speak French? How would we get across that Marie and
Aleksei had been living together for 10 years when we had hardly
spoken? Yet, on camera, he spoke French and was present,
emotionally present. Off camera I had no contact with him, but on
camera he was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnaire was also working for the first time with Deneuve,
herself no beginner in appearing mysterious, although the younger
actress had nothing but praise for Deneuve's openness towards her.
Wargnier was no less grateful that Deneuve was willing to accept
the small part of Gabrielle Develay. Her only condition, he said,
was ``if I like the script, I'll be with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with French stars like Deneuve and Bonnaire on
board, ``East-West'' received mixed reviews when it was released
here. But Wargnier, no favorite of art house audiences in France,
was not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if I didn't sign the film with my name, the
reviews would have been different,'' he said. ``But some critics
just say, `Oh, it's another film by this guy, it's going to be a
kind of bloody epic, an old-fashioned melodrama.' It's not. It's
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he conceded, the film may have been chosen as France's
candidate for a foreign language Academy Award this year because it
is something of an epic. After all, he said, over the last 15
years, only three French films have been nominated for an Academy
Award. Of these, he added with a slightly triumphant smile, only
``Indochine'' has won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
