<SLUG> BC-ELN-NEW-ENGLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND GIVES MCCAIN SOME HOPE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ While the news looked grim for Sen. John
McCain in much of the country, in New England things looked much
brighter Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He defeated Gov. George W. Bush in Massachusetts and Vermont and
was running well against him in Connecticut. But Bush was ahead in
Maine, where the Bush family owns a summer home.
</P>
<P>
   A strong showing in the region, with its 102 collective
delegates, was crucial to McCain's hopes of keeping his
presidential campaign alive, especially in light of his projected
losses in most of the other states holding primaries Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But despite McCain's victories in New England, Tuesday's
primaries also showed his enduring inability to capture votes from
registered Republicans. In Massachusetts, for example, where polls
of voters showed McCain garnering six out of every 10 votes,
two-thirds of the voters who cast ballots for McCain were Democrats
or independents who supported him. In Vermont, Democrats and
independents carried McCain, who won by capturing just 45 percent
of registered Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did well in Connecticut, home to a historically moderate
and independent electorate, despite significant efforts by Gov.
John G. Rowland and every Republican lawmaker in the state, all of
whom had publicly endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very intelligent, capable man,'' said Hope Whitehead,
78, a retired history teacher, after she voted for McCain at the
Davis Middle School in Guilford. ``He has our interests at heart.
He wants to make big changes in the government, which is why the
Republican Party is not behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, thousands of Connecticut voters throughout the
state switched their party affiliations to register as Republicans
in time for Tuesday's primary. Polls of voters also suggested
McCain won a majority of the state's large number of Catholic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   They also showed he drew much support in both Connecticut and
Massachusetts from former Democrats and Liberals who recently
switched to the Republican Party. McCain received fewer than half
of the votes from registered Republicans in both states.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, McCain won the state's 12 delegates by nearly a
2-to-1 margin over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Anchoring McCain's showing in New England was Massachusetts,
where he outpaced Bush by about a 2-to-1 margin overall, and
received the support of a strong majority of Catholic voters. But,
just as he did in Michigan and New Hampshire, McCain's
Massachusetts victory was because of an outpouring of Democrats and
independents which, combined, accounted for about two-thirds of the
ballots cast for him.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts said the number of
non-Republicans who supported McCain bodes well for Bush in the
fall. ``I think it shows dissatisfaction with the Democratic
candidates,'' said -Cellucci, who noted that the presidential
primary showed the largest turnout in state history.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republican voters said they were upset with the McCain
campaign and said it had become increasingly negative, especially
in the last few weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
