<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-BRADLEY-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY DECLARES HIS FIGHT A VICTORY FOR IDEALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT44 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Declaring a proud victory for idealism even as he
conceded total defeat in Tuesday's primaries, former Sen. Bill
Bradley told supporters Tuesday night that his long insurgent
campaign had ``shaped the national debate'' and returned ``core
Democratic values'' to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remember the fact that we did not succeed in winning
tonight's primaries makes that cause no less just, the fight no
less honorable, the goal no less reachable,'' Bradley told several
hundred tearful supporters at the Sheraton Hotel in midtown
Manhattan. ``Some have called our goals unrealistic. I call them
common sense. I call them democratic. I call them American. And I'm
going to work for them until we win. And we will win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley told the crowd that he had called Vice President Gore to
congratulate him just minutes after 9 p.m., when the polls had
closed in New York and most other eastern states. By that time, it
was clear that Bradley was well behind in all of the 16 states that
held primaries and caucuses Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bradley said he would spend Wednesday resting at his
home in Montclair, N.J., as well as calling friends to talk about
his future. They said he was likely to hold a news conference on
Thursday somewhere in New Jersey to announce his withdrawal from
the race.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley did not mention talk of quitting Tuesday night,
though he spoke of his campaign in the past tense. Instead, he
spoke with soaring oratory about how his campaign had succeeded in
bringing young and idealistic people back into politics, in forcing
a national debate on things like campaign finance reform, universal
health care and child poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave voice to the voiceless,'' he said. ``When no one was
talking about the 13 children who die every day from gun violence,
we heard their cries. When no one was talking about the nearly 14
million children who still are in poverty in this country, we said
America can't remain America if they remain poor in a time of
plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as he often has during this campaign, he referred to
Robert F. Kennedy, saying, ``34 year ago in South Africa, Robert
Kennedy said, `Few will have the greatness to bend history, but
each of us can work to change a small portion of the events, and in
the total of all these acts will be written the history of this
generation.'' I believe history will write that we tried to change
politics, to restore trust and to defeat the politics of
expediency.''
</P>
<P>
   There is already talk among some of Bradley's staunchest
supporters about laying the groundwork for a Bradley campaign in
2004. ``There should be some time for mourning, but then it will be
time to go back to work,'' said a friend and adviser to Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   But close aides to Bradley said he had given absolutely no
thought to mounting another campaign in four years, and none would
hazard a guess about his intentions. ``I was wrong about his
running this time, so I'm not one to prognosticate,'' said Anita
Dunn, his communications director.
</P>
<P>
   They also declined to speculate on whether Bradley would be
willing to take a position in a Gore administration. Bradley has
already ruled out being Gore's running mate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bradley's supporters began filtering into the narrow ballroom
before 8 p.m. and, despite the rhythm 'n' blues band, the red,
white and blue balloons and the free-flowing wine, most were
already wearing long faces. The news reports all day had been
unrelentingly bad, and even before the polls had closed, they were
prepared to hear their candidate concede.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was so prepared for bad news that when CNN projected
Gore the winner in New York at precisely the moment the polls close
at 9 p.m., there was not so much as a murmur or a groan from the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Many people said they were first-time political volunteers who
had been drawn into the campaign by Bradley's idealism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good seeds planted an nurtured don't always come up when you
expect them to,'' said Chris Hansen-Nelson, 45, of Manhattan. ``But
they come up eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   At another corner of the room, Stuart Kolbert, a 62-year-old
real estate broker from Westchester, and Ed Gerstein, a 52-year-old
accountant from Brooklyn, were reminiscing like old college
roommates about their volunteer days for Bradley in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really did something good this country,'' Kolbert said. ``I
have to believe we elevated the process.'' He added, ``Tomorrow I'm
going to be depressed. I'm depressed now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
