<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9897 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-FLA-LOOKAHEAD-COX     03-07 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LOOKAHEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida voters lament lack of impact
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ If you feel a little like the kid who was told he
could play later and then suddenly the game was over, don't feel
bad, you're not alone. Millions of Florida voters found out Tuesday
that the game of presidential nominations has once again ended
early.
</P>
<P>
   While that is good news for Texas Gov. George Bush and Vice
President Al Gore, even some of their biggest Sunshine State
supporters wish next Tuesday's primary could be as important as
tiny New Hampshire's.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Floridians haven't paid for the privilege of an
exciting primary. So far, more than $8 million of Florida cash has
been given to the presidential candidates. But with the party
nominations all but formalized Tuesday night, the nation's fourth
largest state finds itself with no say in the country's politics
until the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we have to change,'' said GOP state chairman
Al Cardenas, who supports Bush. ``We can't continue to have a
primary system where states like ours do not get to participate.''
</P>
<P>
   There was hope as recently as two weeks ago that Floridians
would share the excitement. Arizona Sen. John McCain looked as if
he might drag out the primary season and former New Jersey Sen.
Bill Bradley held out hope that he might have a few surprises up
his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking it one step at a time,'' said an ever hopeful
Natalie Zellner, Bradley's Florida state director, even as Tuesday
night's dismal results were becoming known. ``I'm trying to sound
hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Bradley's campaign fizzled, McCain appeared in recent
weeks to have an outside shot of thwarting Bush's march to the
nomination. McCain's Florida campaign chairman, Bob Milligan, the
state comptroller and a retired Marine general, suggested that
large numbers of volunteers were ready to move out in force here
once McCain gave the word.
</P>
<P>
   Their strategy relied on the idea that if McCain could not win
the entire state, he could win a chunk of the 80 delegates, which
are divided by congressional district, by winning two or three
districts, particularly around Pensacola and Tampa Bay, that have a
strong military presence. One thing McCain could not depend on was
Democrats and independents. Unlike Michigan and New Hampshire,
where McCain won because of help from those groups, Florida has a
closed primary meaning you must vote according to your party
registration.
</P>
<P>
   McCain would also be going up against the formidable political
machine of Gov. Jeb Bush, the younger brother of the Texas
governor. Months ago, Jeb Bush dispatched senior aides to Coral
Gables to open a campaign headquarters and organize all 67
counties. They have been operating phone banks and mailing campaign
brochures to likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Jillian Inmon, a political veteran, the Florida
headquarters was filled with volunteers and paid staff last night
as they continued to prepare for Tuesday's election determined to
make sure that Democrats will be impressed by Bush's prowess here.
</P>
<P>
   And for Florida voters that is good news. Both Democrats and
Republicans expect Florida to be a key battleground state in the
November election. For Jeb Bush, a loss here would be humiliating
and he will do everything he can to make sure his brother defeats
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, emboldened by President's Clinton victory here in
1996, believe that they can be competitive. Clinton and Gore have
made frequent visits to the state in recent months. Whether Florida
will remain in play will most likely be determined by campaign
polling in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to lose this state,'' says Inmon. ``There is
no way we are going to let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, so far neither Bush nor Gore has made plans to come
here before Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   briancrowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
