<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-WITNESSES-COX     03-07 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-WITNESSES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More witnesses are emerging in case of Buckhead stabbings
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A grant of immunity to a Houston woman riding with Ray Lewis the
night of the Buckhead murders may prompt a string of new witnesses
to surface in the case.
</P>
<P>
   One of the potential witnesses emerged Tuesday and is conferring
with a lawyer about speaking to authorities. The man, a law student
from Texas, was one of several individuals identified by Jessica
Robertson as being among the passengers in the stretch limousine
with Lewis on the night of the slayings, said Atlanta lawyer Dwight
Thomas, the law student's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, also a passenger, was given immunity by prosecutors
last week. Her statement broke an investigative logjam in the case,
Thomas said. He said Robertson's statement was the first time
authorities had spoken to a passenger in the limousine, apart from
initial comments Lewis made to police. Police have obtained
statements from the limousine's driver. Thomas said there were 13
people riding in the limousine that night and that Robertson gave
several of the names to District Attorney Paul Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few people from the vehicle have surfaced, but they
have surfaced with counsel,'' said Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said his client, whom he would not name, ``witnessed
quite a bit'' and that he would confer with the man this weekend
before allowing him to talk to prosecutors. He may seek immunity
for his client, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the witnesses are retaining lawyers because they
fear being charged in connection with the deaths of Jacinth Baker,
21, and Richard Lollar, 24, both of Decatur. The two were stabbed
to death near a Buckhead nightclub the night of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a star NFL linebacker for the Baltimore Ravens, is
charged with murder. He is out of jail on bail and under a
court-supervised curfew in Maryland. Also charged with the murders
are two other passengers: Reginald Oakley, 31, of Baltimore, and
Joseph Sweeting, 34, of Miami. They are jailed in Atlanta awaiting
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone they can put in that limousine has the potential for a
criminal charge _ obstruction of justice, a party to the crime,''
said Thomas. ``These people can be squeezed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said his client has long been a friend of Robertson, who
is also known as Jaye Roberts, but the law student barely knows
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution Tuesday obtained the
affidavit for the warrant police used to search Lewis' home in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit relies heavily on statements that Duane Fassett,
Lewis' longtime limousine driver, gave authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett said that he ``routinely picks 'Shorty' and 'Derby' up
at Raymond Lewis' residence ... on Sundays when there is a home
game for the Baltimore Ravens.'' Oakley is known as ``Derby'' and
Sweeting as ``Shorty.'' Fassett also said Oakley and Sweeting
``would be at the Foxcreek Court address (Lewis' home) without
Raymond Lewis Jr. being present.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was vague in statements to police about the occupants of
the limousine, calling them ``club people'' and only naming A.J.
Johnson and Kwame King. A.J. Johnson was an alias used by Oakley.
Lewis told police he'd only met him the night of the party.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit also stated Lewis was ``observed in a physical
altercation with one of the victims'' and that a ``substantial
amount of blood'' was found in the limousine's passenger
compartment.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit appears to go further than what Fassett told
police in a taped interview. In the interview, Fassett did not
describe a physical altercation with a victim but said he saw Lewis
throw a punch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
