<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-SUPER-NEWYORK08-COX     03-07 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-NEWYORK08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain loss in New York could silence campaign
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Arizona Sen. John McCain's hopes for New York were
dashed in what could be his greatest political defeat as early
projections awarded this key state to Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush's additional wins in the major swing state of Ohio, as
well as Maine, the governor robbed McCain of the Northeast sweep
his camp was counting on. A New York victory would have allowed
McCain to march on, his strategists surmised.
</P>
<P>
   Even without New York, Bush knew enough late Tuesday to look
toward November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, in the other party, Al Gore is celebrating victory as
well,'' Bush said in Austin, Texas, even before hearing of New
York. ``I congratulate him and look forward to the contest. He is
the candidate of the status quo in Washington, D.C., and he has a
tough case to make in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's primary is really 31 separate contests held in each
of the state's congressional districts. Delegate, not candidate,
names appear most prominently on the ballot, arguably giving Bush
an edge since he enjoyed the backing of party leaders from Gov.
George Pataki and state GOP Chairman William Powers on down.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials dropped their efforts to keep McCain off the
state ballot after Bush's sobering New Hampshire loss raised
concerns of a backlash in this state. But that didn't stop McCain
from dubbing Pataki and Powers ``Comrade Pataki'' and ``Comrade
Powers.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bush have sparred over a Bush campaign ad featuring
Geri Barish, a breast cancer survivor and activist who criticizes
McCain for failing to vote for federal funding that included money
for some breast cancer research programs. The issue is a potent one
on Long Island where activists say rates of the disease are
unusually high and where more moderate Republicans who could help
McCain are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, tried to distance himself from a campaign waged
by backer Sam Wyly, a wealthy Texan who spent $2.5 million on TV
ads in New York, California and Ohio attacking McCain and touting
Bush's environmental record. Bush said he knew nothing about the
ads.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush sent a letter to Cardinal John O'Connor
expressing regret for not speaking out about his objection to Bob
Jones University's anti-Catholic philosophy. Bush kicked off his
South Carolina primary bid with a speech at the evangelical
university in February.
</P>
<P>
   That speech and the timing of the letter changed Republican Joe
Artino's mind about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week before the New York primary, he writes a letter to the
cardinal apologizing. I felt he only did that because he was
looking for the Catholic vote,'' said Artino, a Catholic. ``I
didn't like that at all. So, I said maybe McCain is the better
person for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
