<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALAMP-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA AMPLIFIER DENIES CLAIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; CAMARILLO, Calif. _ California Amplifier Inc. isn't waiting for
a court date to defend itself from a lawsuit by a competitor
alleging patent infringement.
</P>
<P>
   The Camarillo-based company issued a statement Tuesday saying
allegations contained in a federal lawsuit filed by Orland Park,
Ill.-based Andrew Corp. are without merit.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cal Amp officials have seen a copy of the complaint,
they have not yet been formally served with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very disappointed that Andrew Corp. did not contact us
prior to filing this complaint,'' chief executive officer Fred
Sturm said in a statement. ``We firmly believe that if we had been
given the opportunity to clarify the design characteristics of our
transceiver products, Andrew Corp. would have had significant
relevant information to consider before filing this infringement
claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Corp. spokesman John Byrne declined to comment beyond
confirming the existence of the lawsuit, which was filed in U.S.
District Court for the Eastern District of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Andrew purchased Conifer Corp., which, like
California Amplifier, makes multichannel multipoint distribution
service products, including microwave amplifiers.
</P>
<P>
   They enable cable television signals to be transmitted via
microwave. The technology is also called wireless cable.
</P>
<P>
   The service eliminates the need for much of the wiring a cable
connection requires but is limited by geography because microwaves
travel in a straight line and cannot pass through mountains or
heavy vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Caliornia Amplifier closed at $43.75 Tuesday, up 25
cents, and shares of Andrew Corp were up 13 cents to close at
$29.75.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
