<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9904 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WR     03-07 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADD RESOLVE, TOUCH OF OPRAH, BRADLEY'S MISTAKES, AND, VOILA, A
RESURGENT GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs to insert Gore comments and color in new 3rd, 4th and
5th grafs)  
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT 1, 18, 33 _ have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 &HT;    (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ For someone who was embalmed just last fall
by a New York tabloid as ``Dead Veep Walking,'' it was a stunning
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years after he embarrassed himself with an ill-conceived
and inept presidential campaign and only a few months after he was
nearly written off as a loser, Vice President Al Gore has revived
his fortunes, sweeping aside an opponent who sneaked up on him last
fall and nearly stole his political future.
</P>
<P>
   He was nearly giddy here Tuesday in acknowledging his triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is full tonight, and I want to thank all of you who
are here and all those across America who have stood with us and
helped to bring us this moment,'' Mr. Gore said in a speech after
the voting in the Super Tuesday primaries. ``This is your victory,
too.'' Gore and his wife, Tipper, watched the returns in a hotel
suite here. Shortly after 9 p.m. East Coast time, Gore took the
stage at the hotel ballroom here where he claimed his last Senate
title in 1984. While he did not technically declare victory because
the polls had yet to close on the West Coast, he said he had
received ``a very gracious'' telephone call from his only rival,
former Senator Bill Bradley. His conciliatory tone toward Bradley
belied the heat of the campaign and the scare that Bradley had
given him. He did not reveal the contents of the conversation, even
to his aides, because he rushed to the ballroom right after he hung
up.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is fond of saying that competition from his lone rival,
former Sen. Bill Bradley, has been good for him, that the challenge
by Bradley forced him to become a better candidate. Bradley ``was a
blessing in disguise,'' Gore said recently, invoking Winston
Churchill as he hinted in a trenchant aside just how nervous he had
once been: ``Some disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that Bradley did spur Gore into a wholesale overhaul
of his candidacy, prompting an extraordinary political resurrection
of the vice president after Labor Day, when a poll by The Boston
Globe showed Bradley neck and neck with him in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But the building blocks that helped Gore survive that period
actually were put in place long ago. As Bill Clinton's vice
president, he devoted himself to raising money and doing political
favors _ and collecting iou's from local and state politicians
across the country. And in 1999 he called those chits in, racking
up endorsements from county sheriffs to the president of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   So formidable was the political infrastructure Gore assembled
that by last year he had scared off any challengers. Most notable
among them was Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, who decided that the
Democrats had a better chance of recapturing the House than keeping
the White House after eight years of Bill Clinton and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   So confident was the Gore team that when Bradley loped into the
picture from left field, it paid him little mind. After all, Gore
had locked up most of the so-called superdelegates, the elected
officials and party leaders who will pick the nominee at the
party's August convention. He had built a floor through which he
could not fall. And he was campaigning at a time of peace and
nearly unprecedented prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But then, perhaps feeling too secure, he lapsed into an
imperious Rose Garden strategy that nearly led to his ruin.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles have been well-documented, as has his very public
makeover, in which he abandoned the podium in favor of the
Oprah-style town meeting used with such great success by his
mentor, Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to bring an end to Gore Inc.,'' one Gore adviser
recalled recently, referring to the sprawling, complacent, almost
corporate entity that the sterile campaign had become. ``It wasn't
just a building on K Street; it was a psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   What secured his victory, however, were certain strategic
decisions and a newfound discipline in the candidate and in his
campaign to adhere to those decisions. As he was developing a
warmer and fuzzier public image, his campaign was developing a
sharper edge. That sharpness sometimes overtook the candidate in
his debates with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore deftly forced Bradley into a more negative campaign than
Bradley had vowed to run. All the while, the vice president was
nailing down the support of core constituents, relentlessly
painting a worrisome picture of Bradley and resolving not to stray
from his message of the day _ even to the point of laughing in
recent days about his universal answer, no matter the question: ``I
am not taking a single vote for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The central decision was basically to keep the gas on and not
let up,'' one top Gore strategist said. ``That was the guiding
principle, to stay disciplined, focused, on message, and campaign
like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the history of the Gore campaign is written, it may
focus less on Gore's successful stratagems (and there were many)
and more on Bradley's missteps (and there were many). Even as
Bradley loomed as a potentially serious threat, he mystified Gore
operatives for his inability to build on his assets, and he made
blunders that in retrospect seem naive.
</P>
<P>
   One telling moment went almost unremarked by the Gore campaign
at the time. It was back on Dec. 16, when Bradley shared a stage in
Claremont, N.H., with Sen. John McCain, a Republican, to highlight
their disgust with the campaign finance system. At the time, it
looked like a coup for Bradley: lasso the maverick Republican, make
a name for yourself as a new breed of politician, and build some
excitement among independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, that ``summit of the underdogs,'' as Bradley and
McCain termed it, hurt Bradley more than it helped him. In the eyes
of the Gore campaign, at least retrospectively, it validated the
scrappier McCain as the true insurgent and seemed to give Bradley's
stamp of approval for independent-leaning Democrats to vote for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-FETUS-KAN &LR;      03-07 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FETUS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FROM KC AREA SUMMONED TO TESTIFY ABOUT FETAL-TISSUE
TRANSACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A pathologist and a medical technician from Lee's
Summit, Mo., who worked at clinics that perform abortions have been
subpoenaed to testify before a U.S. House committee investigating
whether fetal tissue was sold at excessive prices for medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   The men worked with two companies that did fetal-tissue removal
at various places in the country, including the clinic of Planned
Parenthood of Kansas and Mid-Missouri in Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The companies leased facilities for the tissue work. Planned
Parenthood is not accused of breaking the law but has been drawn
into what could be a highly charged congressional inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law allows fetal tissue to be donated for research, but
the House committee will focus on whether fees charged to cover
costs of tissue removal and transportation are unreasonable and in
violation of the law. Stronger laws are being advocated in
resolutions in the House and in the Senate, where members of the
Judiciary Committee also talked last month of calling for witnesses
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is clearly a for-profit, market-driven sale of body
parts,'' said Steve Schmidt, spokesman for the House Commerce
Committee. Its Health and Environment Subcommittee will conduct the
hearing Thursday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to testimony about the sale of fetal parts, the
committee is expected to hear graphic description of organs being
removed from fetuses. Some Democrats are trying to close the
hearing, but Republicans are resisting that, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents acknowledge that fetal-tissue research is
valuable in finding treatments for certain diseases, but they said
it could increase abortions by making women feel less guilty about
having one.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has subpoenaed pathologist Miles Jones and medical
technician Dean Alberty, both of Lee's Summit. Jones has given no
indication he will appear, Schmidt said. Alberty intends to appear
if his expenses are paid, said his lawyer, David Stout of Kansas
City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had an agreement to work at the Planned Parenthood clinic
for 10 weeks in 1998 and has worked at clinics in several other
states. He has a businesses called Opening Lines, which puts out a
brochure listing fetal-organ prices, such at $999 for a brain and
$150 for a liver.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has not returned phone and e-mail messages from The Kansas
City Star. No one answered the door at his house on recent visit by
a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight the ABC News program ``20//20'' is scheduled to show a
hidden-camera interview conducted by an ABC producer, pretending to
be a potential investor, meeting with Jones over dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty worked for Opening Lines and for the Georgia-based
Anatomic Gift Foundation as a technician when the company leased
space at Planned Parenthood's clinic in Overland Park several years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty has not returned phone calls seeking comment. Anatomic
Gifts sued him after he left its employment, alleging he violated
an agreement to keep details of his work confidential. In his
response to the lawsuit, Alberty said he witnessed illegal tissue
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bardsley, president of Anatomic Gift, said Tuesday that the
company did nothing illegal or unethical and that Alberty was
working as a spy for an anti-abortion organization that was
investigating fetal-tissue research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything to hide, and we abide by the law,''
said Bardsley, who agreed to testify voluntarily to the
subcommittee. The company, however, got out of the fetal-tissue
business Jan. 1 because it detracted from its other work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alberty told the ``20//20'' reporter that he was so disturbed by
the practice of fetal-tissue extraction that he accepted money from
an anti-abortion group to work under cover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9906 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WR     03-07 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHVILLE, Tenn.: for McCain.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When Bradley stood with McCain, he provided a letter of
transit for independent voters to go with McCain,'' one Gore
confidant said. ``It didn't matter that McCain was pro-life or
pro-gun,'' he said. ``People saw him as legitimized.''
</P>
<P>
   Such blunders, over time, created an opening for the vice
president after months of self-inflicted wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``His failures reinvigorated the Gore campaign,'' said Leon E.
Panetta, a former White House chief of staff for Clinton and a
close observer of the Gore candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Gore campaign was lining up with all the core
Democratic constituencies that vote in primaries. These efforts
were led by Donna Brazile, the campaign manager, who has extensive
experience in working with the party's core groups, like
influential blacks, women and gays. The rest of the Gore team was
also clicking into place, with Tony Coelho, the campaign chairman,
Carter Eskew, the message man, Bob Shrum, the media strategist, and
Michael Whouley, the top field marshal, on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign averted a potential disaster by persuading
organized labor to endorse Gore, which it did on Oct. 12. The
AFL-CIO could have remained neutral and nearly did. Only after
intense lobbying by Gore officials, with an assist from Clinton,
did the unions, though not unanimously, bestow their prized backing
and its promise of election-day manpower on the vice president. It
helped restore a sense of strength that had slipped through Gore's
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before, Gore had signaled a new aggressiveness. In
twin speeches to the Democratic National Committee, Bradley made a
lofty appeal to the party's highest instincts, while Gore, aiming
his message less at suburban moderates and more at the party's
base, said he would roll up his sleeves and fight for the
traditional values the party advocated.
</P>
<P>
   This was followed by a similarly disparate appearance at the
Jefferson-Jackson Day Dinner in Des Moines, where again Bradley
aimed for the ideal and Gore came across as more practical. Gore,
still the self-anointed underdog, pressed Bradley to agree to
debates. Bradley demurred, a pose that he would often adopt, to his
detriment, in the face of Gore's confrontational style.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Gore's campaign anthem of ``Stay and Fight''
emerged. He had accused Bradley of quitting the Senate (he retired
after a third term), while Gore decided to ``stay and fight'' the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Grisolano, a direct-mail consultant in Iowa and a Gore
supporter, proposed that Gore expand this phrase into a theme. By
the night of the dinner, 1,000 signs had been printed up with the
slogan, and over time it evolved into a full-fledged battle cry
that Gore now gives full throat to at the end of nearly every
speech: ``I am a fighter! I want to fight for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Panetta said: ``The crucial thing is that Al Gore came out of
this thing looking like a fighter. Bradley didn't. He wasn't
willing to fight back. And in not fighting back, he let Gore look
like the stronger candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fighter persona emerged just as Bradley was putting his
health-care proposal forward, and it offered Gore a chance to go
after something substantive.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore team believed health care would be a central concern of
voters but there was some question about what approach to take
since the Clinton administration's own proposal for universal
coverage had failed so drastically in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   One top Gore adviser described the internal debate: ``There was
a very active debate in the campaign between those who wanted a
more sweeping health-care proposal _ those who frankly had lived
with the ghost of Harris Wofford and Bob Kerrey, who had ridden it
with incredible political power and momentum _ and those on the
policy staff who said we should be more incremental.'' The adviser
said Gore had decided to put the brakes on a more ambitious
health-care proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, Gore ripped into Bradley's proposal as a
half-baked plan that would cost too much and provide woefully
inadequate coverage. His main charge was that Bradley's goal of
universal coverage _ which Gore adopted as his own _ was worthy but
that the approach should be step by step, not in one fell swoop.
</P>
<P>
   From this, Gore extracted a larger message about his candidacy _
that he was a political realist and would be a careful steward of
the prosperity while Bradley was a dreamer with an academic
approach to problems that would end up hurting people and ruining
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were up against a Clinton/Gore-style campaign,'' said Lee
Miringhoff, director of the Marist Institute poll in New York.
``They target, hit, morph their positions very closely to yours and
poke a hole or two in them and then bore away _ and you have to be
up at the same speed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore honed his skills in debate practice with his friend Tom
Downey, a former congressman from Long Island, standing in for
Bradley. More than one observer said that Downey was sharper
playing Bradley than Mr. Bradley was in the actual debates. ``Gore
and Downey are friends, too, and that added to the competition
between them,'' said one who watched.
</P>
<P>
   The race in Iowa was effectively over on Jan. 8, when in a
debate, Gore questioned Bradley's commitment to helping flood
victims in Iowa and Bradley did not address the matter. New
Hampshire, where Gore had been on television for most of October
with no counter-advertising from Bradley, fell into line shortly
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That month that we had to ourselves really helped us to get
back in the race,'' said one strategist. He said that when Bradley
did buy air time, he did so in Boston, and the Gore campaign could
see Bradley gaining ground among voters who watched Boston
television.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
