<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING THE SMALL INVESTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ One of the questions most frequently asked
when Americans are frustrated by their inability to make government
more responsive concerns how they can ``make a difference,'' as
they usually put it.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nadler began mulling how to improve the system a few
years back, and his ruminations resulted in the American
Shareholders Association, which is nearing its first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler is best known in Kansas City as editor in chief of K.C.
Jones Monthly, a journal of conservative commentary, and as a
regular panelist on KCPT's ``Ruckus'' program. His epiphany
occurred, he relates, when, as a small investor reaping the rewards
of a rising stock market, he came to realize he was a small part of
a history-making epoch. His next step was an attempt to determine
just how large the working-class capital-ownership phenomenon had
become.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler's research led him to write a monograph titled ``The Rise
of Worker Capitalism,'' which late last year was published as a
Cato Institute policy analysis. What Nadler discovered along the
way was the emergence of what he characterizes as ``the first mass
class of worker-stockholders in history.'' These are wage earners,
he says, who derive a substantial portion of their income from
investments.
</P>
<P>
   What was perhaps most surprising about Nadler's research was how
it showed this development transcending age, sex, race, wealth and
occupation. During the first half of the '90s, stockholding
increased significantly for virtually all demographic groups. His
study revealed, for instance, that of all those owning stocks or
stock mutual funds, half had incomes under $50,000, and the
ownership increase has been especially steep for families with
incomes under $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the increasing capital ownership comes from expanded
opportunities. Companies offering 401(k) plans tripled during the
'90s, and mutual fund holdings of private pension plans increased
15-fold from 1990 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While there are several powerful organizations representing
America's capitalists, Nadler believed there still was a need for a
lobby for the little guy. From this belief emerged the American
Shareholders Association. Nadler, who serves as executive director,
established his association as an affiliate of Americans for Tax
Reform, a strong advocate of taxpayer rights.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far it's not a mass movement. Nadler estimates current
membership at some 5,000, with about half the U.S. congressional
districts represented. In the early going he is recruiting people
interested in doing grass-roots lobbying. A big part of that effort
this year is attempting to get congressional candidates to respond
to the association's questionnaire on legislation affecting
investors.
</P>
<P>
   They survey attitudes toward capital gains tax rates, Internet
taxation, taxation of retirement investments and estate taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Will Nadler's association evolve into a behemoth resembling an
AARP for individual investors? It's an interesting thing to
contemplate, Nadler concedes, but the priority is to create a
organizational foundation on which to build.
</P>
<P>
   If he's successful, those who want to ``make a difference'' will
have increasing opportunities to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
