<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WR     03-07 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADD RESOLVE, TOUCH OF OPRAH, BRADLEY'S MISTAKES, AND, VOILA, A
RESURGENT GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs to insert Gore comments and color in new 3rd, 4th and
5th grafs)  
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT 1, 18, 33, 45, 46 _ have been sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 &HT;    (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ For someone who was embalmed just last fall
by a New York tabloid as ``Dead Veep Walking,'' it was a stunning
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years after he embarrassed himself with an ill-conceived
and inept presidential campaign and only a few months after he was
nearly written off as a loser, Vice President Al Gore has revived
his fortunes, sweeping aside an opponent who sneaked up on him last
fall and nearly stole his political future.
</P>
<P>
   He was nearly giddy here Tuesday in acknowledging his triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is full tonight, and I want to thank all of you who
are here and all those across America who have stood with us and
helped to bring us this moment,'' Mr. Gore said in a speech after
the voting in the Super Tuesday primaries. ``This is your victory,
too.'' Gore and his wife, Tipper, watched the returns in a hotel
suite here. Shortly after 9 p.m. East Coast time, Gore took the
stage at the hotel ballroom here where he claimed his last Senate
title in 1984. While he did not technically declare victory because
the polls had yet to close on the West Coast, he said he had
received ``a very gracious'' telephone call from his only rival,
former Senator Bill Bradley. His conciliatory tone toward Bradley
belied the heat of the campaign and the scare that Bradley had
given him. He did not reveal the contents of the conversation, even
to his aides, because he rushed to the ballroom right after he hung
up.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is fond of saying that competition from his lone rival,
former Sen. Bill Bradley, has been good for him, that the challenge
by Bradley forced him to become a better candidate. Bradley ``was a
blessing in disguise,'' Gore said recently, invoking Winston
Churchill as he hinted in a trenchant aside just how nervous he had
once been: ``Some disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that Bradley did spur Gore into a wholesale overhaul
of his candidacy, prompting an extraordinary political resurrection
of the vice president after Labor Day, when a poll by The Boston
Globe showed Bradley neck and neck with him in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But the building blocks that helped Gore survive that period
actually were put in place long ago. As Bill Clinton's vice
president, he devoted himself to raising money and doing political
favors _ and collecting iou's from local and state politicians
across the country. And in 1999 he called those chits in, racking
up endorsements from county sheriffs to the president of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   So formidable was the political infrastructure Gore assembled
that by last year he had scared off any challengers. Most notable
among them was Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, who decided that the
Democrats had a better chance of recapturing the House than keeping
the White House after eight years of Bill Clinton and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   So confident was the Gore team that when Bradley loped into the
picture from left field, it paid him little mind. After all, Gore
had locked up most of the so-called superdelegates, the elected
officials and party leaders who will pick the nominee at the
party's August convention. He had built a floor through which he
could not fall. And he was campaigning at a time of peace and
nearly unprecedented prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But then, perhaps feeling too secure, he lapsed into an
imperious Rose Garden strategy that nearly led to his ruin.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles have been well-documented, as has his very public
makeover, in which he abandoned the podium in favor of the
Oprah-style town meeting used with such great success by his
mentor, Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to bring an end to Gore Inc.,'' one Gore adviser
recalled recently, referring to the sprawling, complacent, almost
corporate entity that the sterile campaign had become. ``It wasn't
just a building on K Street; it was a psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   What secured his victory, however, were certain strategic
decisions and a newfound discipline in the candidate and in his
campaign to adhere to those decisions. As he was developing a
warmer and fuzzier public image, his campaign was developing a
sharper edge. That sharpness sometimes overtook the candidate in
his debates with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore deftly forced Bradley into a more negative campaign than
Bradley had vowed to run. All the while, the vice president was
nailing down the support of core constituents, relentlessly
painting a worrisome picture of Bradley and resolving not to stray
from his message of the day _ even to the point of laughing in
recent days about his universal answer, no matter the question: ``I
am not taking a single vote for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The central decision was basically to keep the gas on and not
let up,'' one top Gore strategist said. ``That was the guiding
principle, to stay disciplined, focused, on message, and campaign
like hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the history of the Gore campaign is written, it may
focus less on Gore's successful stratagems (and there were many)
and more on Bradley's missteps (and there were many). Even as
Bradley loomed as a potentially serious threat, he mystified Gore
operatives for his inability to build on his assets, and he made
blunders that in retrospect seem naive.
</P>
<P>
   One telling moment went almost unremarked by the Gore campaign
at the time. It was back on Dec. 16, when Bradley shared a stage in
Claremont, N.H., with Sen. John McCain, a Republican, to highlight
their disgust with the campaign finance system. At the time, it
looked like a coup for Bradley: lasso the maverick Republican, make
a name for yourself as a new breed of politician, and build some
excitement among independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, that ``summit of the underdogs,'' as Bradley and
McCain termed it, hurt Bradley more than it helped him. In the eyes
of the Gore campaign, at least retrospectively, it validated the
scrappier McCain as the true insurgent and seemed to give Bradley's
stamp of approval for independent-leaning Democrats to vote for
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
