<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9911 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WR     03-07 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-GORE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHVILLE, Tenn.: for McCain.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``When Bradley stood with McCain, he provided a letter of
transit for independent voters to go with McCain,'' one Gore
confidant said. ``It didn't matter that McCain was pro-life or
pro-gun,'' he said. ``People saw him as legitimized.''
</P>
<P>
   Such blunders, over time, created an opening for the vice
president after months of self-inflicted wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``His failures reinvigorated the Gore campaign,'' said Leon E.
Panetta, a former White House chief of staff for Clinton and a
close observer of the Gore candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Gore campaign was lining up with all the core
Democratic constituencies that vote in primaries. These efforts
were led by Donna Brazile, the campaign manager, who has extensive
experience in working with the party's core groups, like
influential blacks, women and gays. The rest of the Gore team was
also clicking into place, with Tony Coelho, the campaign chairman,
Carter Eskew, the message man, Bob Shrum, the media strategist, and
Michael Whouley, the top field marshal, on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign averted a potential disaster by persuading
organized labor to endorse Gore, which it did on Oct. 12. The
AFL-CIO could have remained neutral and nearly did. Only after
intense lobbying by Gore officials, with an assist from Clinton,
did the unions, though not unanimously, bestow their prized backing
and its promise of election-day manpower on the vice president. It
helped restore a sense of strength that had slipped through Gore's
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before, Gore had signaled a new aggressiveness. In
twin speeches to the Democratic National Committee, Bradley made a
lofty appeal to the party's highest instincts, while Gore, aiming
his message less at suburban moderates and more at the party's
base, said he would roll up his sleeves and fight for the
traditional values the party advocated.
</P>
<P>
   This was followed by a similarly disparate appearance at the
Jefferson-Jackson Day Dinner in Des Moines, where again Bradley
aimed for the ideal and Gore came across as more practical. Gore,
still the self-anointed underdog, pressed Bradley to agree to
debates. Bradley demurred, a pose that he would often adopt, to his
detriment, in the face of Gore's confrontational style.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Gore's campaign anthem of ``Stay and Fight''
emerged. He had accused Bradley of quitting the Senate (he retired
after a third term), while Gore decided to ``stay and fight'' the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Grisolano, a direct-mail consultant in Iowa and a Gore
supporter, proposed that Gore expand this phrase into a theme. By
the night of the dinner, 1,000 signs had been printed up with the
slogan, and over time it evolved into a full-fledged battle cry
that Gore now gives full throat to at the end of nearly every
speech: ``I am a fighter! I want to fight for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Panetta said: ``The crucial thing is that Al Gore came out of
this thing looking like a fighter. Bradley didn't. He wasn't
willing to fight back. And in not fighting back, he let Gore look
like the stronger candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fighter persona emerged just as Bradley was putting his
health-care proposal forward, and it offered Gore a chance to go
after something substantive.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore team believed health care would be a central concern of
voters but there was some question about what approach to take
since the Clinton administration's own proposal for universal
coverage had failed so drastically in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   One top Gore adviser described the internal debate: ``There was
a very active debate in the campaign between those who wanted a
more sweeping health-care proposal _ those who frankly had lived
with the ghost of Harris Wofford and Bob Kerrey, who had ridden it
with incredible political power and momentum _ and those on the
policy staff who said we should be more incremental.'' The adviser
said Gore had decided to put the brakes on a more ambitious
health-care proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, Gore ripped into Bradley's proposal as a
half-baked plan that would cost too much and provide woefully
inadequate coverage. His main charge was that Bradley's goal of
universal coverage _ which Gore adopted as his own _ was worthy but
that the approach should be step by step, not in one fell swoop.
</P>
<P>
   From this, Gore extracted a larger message about his candidacy _
that he was a political realist and would be a careful steward of
the prosperity while Bradley was a dreamer with an academic
approach to problems that would end up hurting people and ruining
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were up against a Clinton/Gore-style campaign,'' said Lee
Miringhoff, director of the Marist Institute poll in New York.
``They target, hit, morph their positions very closely to yours and
poke a hole or two in them and then bore away _ and you have to be
up at the same speed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore honed his skills in debate practice with his friend Tom
Downey, a former congressman from Long Island, standing in for
Bradley. More than one observer said that Downey was sharper
playing Bradley than Mr. Bradley was in the actual debates. ``Gore
and Downey are friends, too, and that added to the competition
between them,'' said one who watched.
</P>
<P>
   The race in Iowa was effectively over on Jan. 8, when in a
debate, Gore questioned Bradley's commitment to helping flood
victims in Iowa and Bradley did not address the matter. New
Hampshire, where Gore had been on television for most of October
with no counter-advertising from Bradley, fell into line shortly
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That month that we had to ourselves really helped us to get
back in the race,'' said one strategist. He said that when Bradley
did buy air time, he did so in Boston, and the Gore campaign could
see Bradley gaining ground among voters who watched Boston
television.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
