<SLUG> BC-EXIT-POLLS-METHOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE POLL WAS CONDUCTED
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Several election stories have referred to polls of voters
today; this story can accompany any of them.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Election Day polls were based on questionnaires completed by
voters leaving voting stations in six states Tuesday. The poll was
conducted by Voter News Service, an organization created by ABC
News, CBS News, CNN, Fox News, NBC News, and The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   In each state, the results were based on 500 to 800 Republican
primary voters, and 350 to 700 Democratic primary voters, in
randomly selected precincts throughout California, Connecticut,
Massachusetts, Missouri, New York and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, in 19 cases out of 20, the results from such polls
should differ by no more than plus or minus 5 to 7 percentage
points from what would have been obtained by seeking to interview
all primary voters who turned out in each of the six states
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Results based on smaller subgroups have a larger potential
sampling error. In addition to sampling error, the practical
difficulties of conducting any survey of voter opinion on Election
Day, like the reluctance of some voters to take time to fill out a
questionnaire, may introduce other sources of error into the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Helmut Norpoth of the State University of New York at
Stony Brook is assisting The Times in its Election Day polling
analysis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
