<HEADLINE>
ROCKER REPORTER VISITS ANGELS CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Jeff Pearlman, the Sports Illustrated reporter
whose interview and subsequent article on Braves pitcher John
Rocker caused such a stir, was in Angels camp Tuesday working on a
story.
</P>
<P>
   Pearlman said he has been surprised at the uproar the story
caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't expecting it at all,'' Pearlman said. ``I thought
maybe it would be a note on the wire. I guess I was naive. It's
kind of silly the proportion it's grown to. This is the first time
I've ever experienced anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearlman has remained relatively anonymous considering the
attention his story received. However, his phone rang off the hook
when the magazine first hit the newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day it came out, I got about 50 different requests for TV
and radio interviews,'' he said. ``It was a little overwhelming.
But it hasn't changed my life. It gave me a little bit of
recognition, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sales down: Angels season-ticket sales are down 20 percent
from last season, despite the club's promotional offer to draw fans
back after last season's last-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   The club is offering a money-back guarantee if, at the end of
April (after 16 home games), the buyer is not satisfied with the
team's performance. Fans can get a refund for the remaining games.
</P>
<P>
   The offer was made available when season-ticket renewal packages
went out but is available to all fans. The Angels sales department
said there is no way of quantifying the effect on sales the
promotion has had.
</P>
<P>
   __ Woeful Washburn: Pitcher Jarrod Washburn had another poor
performance in Tuesday's 5-3 loss to the Mariners. Competing for a
spot in the starting rotation, he gave up three runs and five hits
in 2 innings. He allowed two runs in two innings in his first
spring start last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't throw strikes,'' said Washburn, who walked four.
``I'm not very locked in to the strike zone. I have to try to get
used to throwing again. There's a lot of work to do in all areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn knows what's at stake for him personally _ a starting
spot in the majors or a trip to Triple-A Edmonton, but he's trying
not to think about the importance of each outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the world I want more than to make the team
out of spring training,'' he said. ``I don't want to go back to the
minor leagues again. But I can't put pressure on myself, because
that will put strain on myself mentally. Mentally I have to be
strong so I can pitch like I can.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Results are in: The Angels announced their all-time team in
celebration of their 40th season. The voting was done by fans on
the team's Web site, Angelsbaseball.com.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the voting: Manager _ Jim Fregosi; catcher _ Bob
Boone; first base _ Rod Carew; second base _ Bobby Grich; third
base _ Doug DeCinces; shortstop _ Fregosi; left field _ Brian
Downing; center field _ Jim Edmonds; right field _ Reggie Jackson;
DH _ Don Baylor; right-handed starters _ Nolan Ryan, Mike Witt;
left-handed starters _ Frank Tanana, Chuck Finley; reliever _ Troy
Percival. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
