<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC PROCESSING CHANGES NAME, ADDS FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Electronic Processing Inc., a publicly owned developer of
bankruptcy software, is jumping feetfirst into the burgeoning
business-to-business e-commerce market.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City, Kan.-based company on Tuesday announced an
agreement to acquire the assets of Phitech Inc., a San Francisco
developer of products that route data over the Internet and private
networks, for $6.25 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a bold one for Electronic Processing, which has
changed its name to EPIQ Systems Inc. to reflect its leap into the
advanced-technology market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this will catapult EPIQ into a new era of growth,''
said Christopher Olofson, the company's president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street greeted the announcement favorably. Shares in EPIQ
rose 20 percent Tuesday to 12 on a volume of 41,600 shares, nearly
four times its daily average.
</P>
<P>
   The company will continue to produce software for Chapter 7 and
Chapter 13 bankruptcy trustees, its main line of business. The
software allows trustees to manage many bankruptcy cases
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Phitech produces a software tool called Data Express, which
enables corporate customers to secure, format and automatically
route data using different Web-based protocols. The company
reported $2.1 million in revenue last year, a 60 percent increase
from 1998, mostly from Data Express licensing, maintenance and
other fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Internet economy develops, there's a real need for
high-quality infrastructure to get from point A to point B,''
Olofson said. ``Four out of the five largest banking companies have
adopted this technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Phitech is working on a new, Java-based product, jDX, for
release later this year. Olofson said jDX would enable EPIQ to
double revenue from Phitech's business annually for at least the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy software, however, will remain EPIQ's core business.
In November, the company purchased the assets of a competitor, DCI
Chapter 7 Solutions Inc., for $10 million. More recently, EPIQ
established a toehold in the back yard of another competitor, Chase
Manhattan Bank, when it acquired two major accounts in New York.
Chase markets a rival Chapter 7 software.
</P>
<P>
   Most of EPIQ's current revenue derives from a marketing
arrangement with Bank of America under which it licenses its
Chapter 7 software to trustees who, in turn, deposit cash proceeds
from asset sales with the bank. EPIQ gets a percentage of those
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The company also gets licensing fees from Chapter 13 trustees
and monthly fees based on the number of cases the trustees manage.
</P>
<P>
   For its third quarter, which ended Sept. 30, EPIQ's net income
increased 58 percent to $605,100, or 13 cents a share, on revenue
of $3.1 million. For nine months, net income increased 64 percent
to $1.49 million, or 31 cents a share, on revenue of $11 million.
The company's fourth-quarter and yearly results have been delayed
by the DCI purchase.
</P>
<P>
   EPIQ, which has about 100 employees, was founded in 1964 by
Kansas City, Kan., lawyer Claude Rice. The company went through
several ownership changes before being acquired by an investment
group led by Olofson's father, Tom Olofson, in 1988. Tom Olofson, a
former executive with Marion Laboratories Inc., is the company's
chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   EPIQ went public three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Phitech, which has about 20 employees, was founded 15 years ago
by Hinda Gilbert, its president and chief executive. Gilbert will
become vice president and general manager of EPIQ in San Francisco
after completion of the asset sale, which is expected within two
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
