<HEADLINE>
GAS LEAK CUTS USC'S PRACTICE SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's basketball practice Tuesday was canceled
after less than an hour because of a gas leak in the physical
education building that caused several campus buildings to be
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a gas leak in the North Gym and it killed our
whole practice,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans had practiced for nearly an hour when Los Angeles
City Fire Dept. personnel arrived on campus and forced the P.E.
building to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   __ NIT breakdown: Forward Brian Scalabrine was asked if he would
be disappointed if the Trojans won their final two regular-season
games, and did not make the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't happen,'' Scalabrine said. ``If it does, I don't
know. It won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Trojans (14-14, 7-9) are no sure bet for the postseason
tournament, even if they sweep the Washington schools this weekend.
Consider some of the Western teams that could be trying to squeeze
into the 32-team field if they don't make it into the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Arizona State (17-11) and Cal (16-12) from the Pac-10,
there's New Mexico State (20-8), Fresno State (21-9), SMU (21-7),
Long Beach State (23-4), San Francisco (19-8), New Mexico (17-12),
Colorado State (18-11) and Wyoming (18-11).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll go to the NIT. I'm excited about going to the
NIT,'' Scalabrine said. ``I know it's not the NCAA, but we put
ourself in this situation. Sam (Clancy) got hurt and we didn't get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Trojans were not happy about the prospect of being
bypassed by the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be upset,'' Clancy said. ``I'd be a little disappointed. I
think if we win both games, we should get in. I don't know how the
NIT does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added guard Jeff Trepagnier: ``Yeah, I think we'd be a little
disappointed. We're already disappointed to miss the NCAAs. So we'd
be disappointed if don't get to the NIT.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Health check: Scalabrine (strained hip) did not practice
Monday or Tuesday but said he would be ready for Thursday's game
against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting therapy three or four times a day,'' Scalabrine
said. ``It's not tight or sore, but I can't control it completely.
I should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy has also missed both practices but will return today. He
has been resting after coming back from the broken right foot he
suffered on Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some soreness, but the swelling has gone down,'' Clancy
said. ``It feels fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier's swollen right eye is OK and he has practiced all
week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Most improved: Bibby was asked which player benefited most
from Clancy's six-week absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kostas (Charissis) has really grown and made giant,
giant steps,'' Bibby said of the 6-foot-11 freshman. ``That really
helps us going into next year. And he'll grow into being our
starting center.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Not on final cut: Scalabrine, who was among 11 players added
for consideration for the Wooden Award, did not make the final cut
of 10 players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
