<SLUG> BC-BOX-SUBPOENA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRICT ATTORNEY SUBPOENAS FIGHT CARD FROM THE GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for additions; adds byline, and final 10 grafs are new.)  
(lh) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Manhattan district attorney's office has
subpoenaed the records of the New York State Athletic Commission
for the Feb. 26 boxing show at Madison Square Garden, according to
Scott Trent, a spokesman for the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Trent said he did not know why the district attorney's office
was interested in the commission's records from the fight, but all
of the records were turned over without a challenge from the
commission. The district attorney's office would not comment on why
it wanted the records.
</P>
<P>
   The card, which was headlined by a bout between Oscar De La Hoya
and Derrell Coley, was noteworthy because of the enormous amount of
weight gained by Arturo Gatti in the 28 hours between the weigh-in
on Friday afternoon and the time he stepped into the ring against
Joey Gamache on Saturday night. Gatti weighed in at 141 pounds. But
on the night of the fight he weighed 160 pounds, according to an
unofficial weigh-in conducted by Home Box Office, which broadcasted
the bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti knocked out Gamache in the second round, and, according to
Gamache's manager, Johnny Bos, the fighter suffered a severe
concussion. He was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   The records turned over to the district attorney's office show
the official weights of the bout to be 141 pounds for Gatti and
140-3/4 pounds for Gamache. Bos said he believes Gatti was
overweight at the weigh-in. He suspects that Gatti was close to 148
or 150 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bos protested the day of the weigh-in by saying that Gatti was
overweight, because when Gatti got on the scale, which was already
set at the prescribed weight of 141 pounds, the needle went right
to the top of the scale. Gatti waved his arms in the air and the
needle bounced. Tony Russo, the executive director of the New York
commission, announced his weight at 141 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started yelling and screaming,'' Bos said. ``Russo told me
to shut up and stop stirring up a stink.''
</P>
<P>
   Bos did not ask the commission to make Gatti get back on the
scale. Trent said that Gatti would have had to climb back on the
scale if Bos had insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The needle also banged the top of the scale when De La Hoya
climbed on, which enraged Coley and his trainer, Leonard Langley.
Coley kept screaming: ``He's over. He's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Wynne, vice president of sports properties at Madison
Square Garden, said he had no reason to doubt the accuracy of the
scale.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti, a former 135-pound world champion who boxed as a junior
lightweight (130 pounds) as recently as three years ago, is
legendary for his enormous weight gains between the weigh-in and
the fight. Before a bout against Reyes Munoz on Aug. 17, Gatti
weighed 139 pounds at the weigh-in and stepped into the ring at 160
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gatti has found a way to put on 19 pounds of muscle
overnight then more power to him,'' Bos said. ``That's a gift I
don't think anybody's ever had. But I don't think he made weight.
And he came into the ring looking faster and quicker than I've ever
seen him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a winnable fight for Joey. If you look at the Arturo
Gatti, outside of the fight against Reyes Munoz, he has never had
the kind of power he showed against Joey.''
</P>
<P>
   Bos said that Gamache was still being treated for the severe
concussion he received in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the fight, I thought he was all right in the dressing
room,'' Bos said. ``They sent him to the hospital, and I'm glad
they did. When he got there he was throwing up. It was serious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
