<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ELN-NEWYORK-1STLD-WRI     03-07 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-NEWYORK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-395(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 IN NEW YORK, GORE WINS BIG AND BUSH-McCAIN RACE IS TIGHT  
 (subs for updating and rewriting throughout)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Adding to his string of victories across the country,
Vice President Al Gore soundly trounced former Sen. Bill Bradley in
the  &UR;  &LR; Democratic primary in New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But in the closely watched Republican primary, the outcome was
too close to call Tuesday evening. Gov. George W. Bush and Sen.
John McCain were running neck-and-neck in early vote tallies.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic race, exit polls showed Gore with a commanding
lead of 66 percent of the vote over Bradley's 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, exit polls in New York showed Bush and
McCain running within several percentage points of each other.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls were conducted by Voter News Service, a
consortium made up of television networks and The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The New York primary was one of the most important contests on
what has been dubbed ``Super Tuesday,'' in which millions of voters
in 16 states swarmed to the ballot boxes to dictate the loyalties
of convention delegates. At stake in New York were 243 Democratic
delegates and 101 Republican delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Although analysts had predicted that Gore would easily beat
Bradley in New York, opinion polls had forecast a tight race
between the two major Republican candidates. Winning a majority of
New York delegates was seen as crucial to McCain's chances of
staying a viable contender.
</P>
<P>
   Among New York voters responding to early exit polls, Republican
party loyalists were supporting Bush, while Republicans who saw
themselves as independents favored McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In the five weeks preceding Tuesday's contests, upset victories
for McCain in New Hampshire and Michigan made the Republican race
one of the most closely watched in recent memory. McCain painted
himself as an establishment outsider, a war hero espousing campaign
reform and denouncing the straight-and-narrow arbiters of American
politics. But in recent contests, Bush appropriated that rebel
image to some extent and used it to successfully woo voters.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Based on early exit polls, a third of the registered Republicans
in New York who voted for McCain identified themselves as
independent, while less than a fifth of Bush's supporters described
themselves that way.
</P>
<P>
   Three-fifths of the voters who sided with Bush labeled
themselves conservative, and less than a third were moderate,
according to those polls. About two-fifths of McCain's supporters
described themselves as conservative, and the same percentage
called themselves moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters were less inclined to favor abortion rights
than those who voted for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a third of those who preferred McCain had never voted in
a Republican primary before. By contrast, less than a fifth of
Bush's supporters had never voted in a Republican primary, the exit
polls indicated.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's supporters named campaign finance and moral values as
the issues that most influenced their vote. Bush's supporters chose
moral values and taxes as the issues with the strongest influence
on their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Half of McCain's supporters said the fact that he ``stands up
for what he believes'' was the quality that mattered most in their
vote decision, followed by the fact that they perceive him as a
strong leader. Almost two-fifths of Bush's supporters said he
``best represents conservative values,'' and a quarter said he
stands up for what he believes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's voter turnout in New York was larger than the usual
turnout of 20 to 25 percent of registered voters. The warm weather
was partly responsible, as was the highly publicized neck-and-neck
national race between Bush and McCain. That heated contest
attracted a record number of voters in primaries earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates threw themselves into last-minute campaigning
in New York with full determination. Bush flew to Long Island and
attended a staged panel discussion on breast cancer in an effort to
appeal to women voters. At a Wall Street rally, McCain attacked his
opponent's chief patrons in this state, Gov. George E. Pataki and
William D. Powers, the New York Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders had joined Bush in lobbying to keep
McCain off the ballot. They pushed for enforcement of obscure
campaign rules that made it more difficult for supporters of
Republican candidates other than Bush to collect nominating
signatures. But McCain won public sympathy, and a federal judge
placed McCain and another candidate, Alan Keyes, on the Republican
ballot in early February. McCain spent nearly $200,000 to get on
the ballot in 19 districts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But New York was still deemed a tough battleground for McCain.
In states with open Republican primaries, McCain won support from
voters labeling themselves independents or Democrats. In New York,
the Republican primary was closed to voters not affiliated with the
party. And even though New York lacks large numbers of people
supporting a strong religious right _ a faction that helped Bush to
victory in South Carolina _ some voters said that McCain's recent
religious criticism swayed them toward his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Catholic and I know darn well that Bush is not
anti-Catholic,'' said Vincent Mauro, a Brooklyn retiree. ``That was
dirty pool. I had mixed feelings about who to vote for, but those
comments really bothered me. I decided to stick with Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to their views of the heated Republican contest,
political analysts predicted that the Democratic race in New York
was likely to be just another echo of Bradley's clamorous death
knell. His supporters here were puzzled by the candidate's intense
campaign focus on Washington state, especially since New York was
seen as a possible victory for the former senator and basketball
star. But a New York Times/CBS poll taken two weeks ago showed Gore
widening his lead to 26-percentage points over Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race failed to inspire the strong feelings that
characterized the Republican contest. While many people regarded
Bradley as a lost cause, Gore apparently still has to overcome his
wooden image among some voters. Joyce Liona, a registered Democrat
in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, said she reluctantly voted for Gore on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to put my faith in something,'' she said. ``Honestly,
I like McCain, and I wish he wasn't a Republican. Gore has no
charisma. I can't even remember sometimes what Gore looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's supporters, Hillary Rodham Clinton, showed up at 7
a.m. at Douglas Grafflin Elementary School in Chappaqua to cast her
vote. Mrs. Clinton, a Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate seat
from New York, was the 11th person to vote at the precinct. The
school is within two miles of the house that she and President
Clinton recently bought.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's
Republican opponent in the Senate race, strode confidently into a
high school on the Upper East Side of Manhattan and cast his vote
for Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
