<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRIZZLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARD PUTS THE BITE BACK IN THE KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He did not erupt for 20 points or wow the masses with
open-court flair. Charlie Ward merely did what he does best for the
Knicks: help them win.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever funk had engulfed the Knicks, Ward helped to erase it
with a superlative performance at point guard Tuesday night. He
moved the ball around the perimeter quickly. He stepped in front of
larger men on defense, often slamming to the hardwood in hopes of
drawing an offensive foul. He snatched rebounds with malice.
</P>
<P>
   When Madison Square Garden had emptied, the Knicks had run the
Vancouver Grizzlies off the floor in a 111-86 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, returning to the lineup after missing nine games, was the
elixir, despite his modest line of seven rebounds, six assists and
5 points.
</P>
<P>
   He led a fuel-injected offense that made 62.1 percent of its
shots from the field, a season-high. Ward not only helped the
Knicks end a two-game skid, but also showed how easy the game can
be when you persevere and don't take a struggling opponent lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell, Patrick Ewing and Allan Houston were in
perfect rhythm, combining for 65 points.
</P>
<P>
   John Wallace added 13 points off the bench as the Knicks moved
to within a half-game of Miami in the Atlantic Division.
</P>
<P>
   Shareef Abdur-Rahim's 18 points led Vancouver, which never led
and fell behind by 20 several times in the second half en route to
the blowout loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks entered the game having lost three of their last four
games, including two straight to Atlanta and Utah. They look tired
and disinterested against the Jazz on Sunday at the Garden, never
making a game of it until late in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But they were re-invigorated Tuesday night. Whether it was Ward
or the lackluster competition, the Knicks started quickly. They
opened the game with a 13-0 run. Ward had four rebounds and two
assists in the opening 4 minutes 30 seconds, sacrificing his
6-foot-1 frame as he lunged for loose balls. He found Larry Johnson
in a maze of bodies for a dunk on the fast break _ a Knick rarity
for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ward returned after missing the past nine games with a fractured
right pinkie. The Knicks averaged 7 fewer points without their
starting point guard. In 10 games overall without Ward, the Knicks
are 5-5. Beyond the numbers and the record, the Knicks miss Ward's
grit and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Houston have brought the ball upcourt decently in
Jeff Van Gundy's big-backcourt offense. But it's not the same. Ward
had a presence about him, eyeing Vancouver's young point guard,
Mike Bibby, as he directed the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Through three quarters, Ward contributed 6 points and six
assists. He also provided the intangibles that make the Knicks'
offense purr for more than one possession. In the second quarter,
four of the five Knicks on the floor touched the ball before they
scored inside.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was able to create scoring opportunities without
worrying about being a playmaker, Houston was freed of his
ballhandling duties and Ewing had all the space he wanted to make
things happen in the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks traveled to Washington after the game to make up a
contest that was postponed due to bad weather. In the second game
of back-to-back series this season, the Knicks are an abysmal 3-10.
The Wizards should be ripe. Wednesday night's marks their third
game in a row, the most any team in the NBA will play consecutively
this season.
</P>
<P>
   With Ward back in the fold and Marcus Camby projected to return
from injury in the next week, the Knicks seem to be closer to being
at full strength.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
