<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOBSTER-BOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BID TO TAKE FEE FROM MOBSTER ON BOOK FAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for addition; adds byline and 5 grafs to end of story.)  
(lh) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state appellate court Tuesday rejected the efforts
of the New York state Crime Victims Board to seize book and movie
profits from Salvatore Gravano, the Mafia informer known as Sammy
the Bull.
</P>
<P>
   The board sued Gravano in 1997, seeking to collect $250,000 he
said he received for assisting the author Peter Maas with
``Underboss,'' a best-selling book that gave details of Gravano's
career as a killer and racketeer who rose to the No. 2 position in
the Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano, who defected from the mob and testified against the
Gambino family boss, John Gotti, and other organized crime figures,
once said he might earn as much as $1 million from his tale.
</P>
<P>
   The suit _ which also named Maas, two divisions of HarperCollins
Publishers, the ICM talent agency and the 20th Century Fox Film
Corp. _ was filed under the state's so-called Son of Sam law. That
law allows crime victims and their relatives to sue criminals for
profits they earn from telling their tales.
</P>
<P>
   But a Supreme Court judge dismissed the case in 1998, saying
that the law did not apply to Gravano because, although he admitted
to killing 19 people and pleaded guilty to racketeering, he was
convicted of federal, not state, crimes. Further, the court found
that the board was not in itself a victim and did not have the
authority to bring the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The decision Tuesday, by the First Department of the Appellate
Division, upheld the lower court's ruling. Larry H. Krantz, one of
Gravano's lawyers, said, ``We believe that the Appellate Division
was correct in affirming the trial court.''
</P>
<P>
   Krantz said he had not talked with Gravano, who is being held on
drug charges in Arizona, and did not know his reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Quartararo, a spokeswoman for the board, said the
members were disappointed and reviewing the decision. ``We will
continue to fight to ensure victims are compensated, and criminals
can't benefit from the crimes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gravano faces several federal lawsuits seeking to seize his
earnings from the ``Underboss'' story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-07-00 2308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0453 </DOCNO>
