u a BC-NY-CHEM-LEAK-NYT &LR;      03-07 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHEM-LEAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARELESS POLLUTER OR VICTIM OF HYSTERIA? CHEMICAL LEAKS SPLIT
VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRIMAN, N.Y. _ At first glance, this seems an unlikely place
to be troubled by chemical leaks, school evacuations and
denunciations of one of its oldest employers. A placid suburban
village nestled in the unspoiled Ramapo Mountains of Orange County,
Harriman spreads out like a fief beneath the century-old hilltop
estate of its namesake, the railroad and finance tycoon Edward H.
Harriman.
</P>
<P>
   But the area has been gripped in recent weeks by widespread
anger at a local chemical manufacturer _ or, if one listens to the
other side, by an almost Salemlike hysteria. State officials have
halted production of the company's primary product, pyridine, and
though all 105 of its employees continue to report for work, some
fear for their jobs. The local police say they and the FBI are
investigating threats sent by e-mail to a critic of the company,
and the air is rife with conspiracy theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just won't die,'' said Harriman's mayor, Charles Gayser,
who is frequently stopped by residents who want to sound off on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The furor began on Oct. 26, when Nepera Inc., which has operated
its single factory here since 1957, accidentally leaked a small
amount of gaseous residue from its production of pyridine, an
ingredient in agrochemicals, pharmaceuticals and anti-dandruff
shampoo. School officials, alerted by the authorities, sent 4,000
students home early from three schools a mile from the factory;
some complained of nausea, dizziness, skin rashes or asthmalike
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Pyridine is a known eye, nose and respiratory irritant,
according to the state Department of Health, and can induce
dizziness, although little is known about its long-term health
effects on humans. The company, which was subsequently cited by the
state Department of Environmental Conservation for violating air
pollution regulations, voluntarily stopped pyridine production for
nine days while it repaired faulty equipment that caused the leak.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, on Nov. 19, schools were dismissed
early and the pyridine operation was temporarily shut down again
after odors were detected inside the plant.
</P>
<P>
   And in February, the DEC says, there were two more residue
leaks, although schools were not evacuated: one on Feb. 22 and
another two days later.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the agency's commissioner, John P. Cahill,
ordered Nepera (pronounced ne-PARE-a) to halt manufacturing
immediately, pending completion of a long list of safety measures.
It was only the third such emergency closing in 20 years by the
agency, which takes such action when it sees ``an imminent danger''
to residents or the environment.
</P>
<P>
   But Cahill had to issue his directive twice before Nepera
complied _ the result of either a miscommunication, as Nepera
officials say, or of company arrogance, as its critics say.
Whatever the case, the lingering image of a business defying
authority has many residents on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting alarmed,'' said Michelle Miscioscia, who
has three children in schools that have been affected.
</P>
<P>
   Miscioscia was among about 400 people who crowded an elementary
school auditorium on Feb. 28 for the monthly meeting of the
Community Advisory Panel, which discusses and recommends safety
policies for Nepera _ normally drawing little public attention.
</P>
<P>
   Many called for the factory's overhaul or outright closing. A
handful of Nepera employees who defended their company were
heckled, and more than a dozen local police officers and state
troopers ringed the room in case words spilled over into something
more.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie O'Brien, a mother of three school-age boys, made a
tearful plea to the advisory panel and representatives of the DEC
and the State Department of Health to close Nepera for good. ``I
would like to know they're not going to operate anymore,'' she said
later. ``They're careless.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said youngsters were playing at the bus stop near her
house on the morning of the latest incident when a familiar odor
permeated the air. ``All the children ended up in the nurse's
office with the same symptoms: nausea, dizziness, headaches,'' she
said. She has felt the effects, too, she said. ``You feel like
you're coming down with something, but you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   The smell of pyridine, a sweet odor that can be nauseating at
higher concentrations, has drifted periodically over the Harriman
area since Nepera's inception. Many in the village say odors were
more common in the 1960s and '70s than today, and they do not
remember widespread claims of adverse physical effects.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a series of airborne leaks and school evacuations led
to a consent agreement between the environmental conservation
department and the company, which installed sophisticated
monitoring equipment on its property to detect chemical emissions.
The company has also removed from its property contaminated soil
and water and drums of hazardous waste, some of which was deposited
by a previous chemical manufacturer. It has also submitted plans
for long-term monitoring of ground and surface water.
</P>
<P>
   Nepera, which is owned by Cambrex, of East Rutherford, N.J.,
also produces niacinamide, an ingredient in enriched foods and pet
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely safe plant,'' said John Van Hulle, the
president of Nepera. ``We're aware of odor issues and certainly
want to work with the community to reduce these in every way
possible. The discussion needs to move from the extremes and into
the middle. We make a lot of good things here. Shutting the plant
down does nobody any good.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
