u a BC-NY-CHEM-LEAK-2NDTAKE-     03-07 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHEM-LEAK-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HARRIMAN, N.Y.: any good.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the most recent leak, the DEC has allowed Nepera to resume
all operations except production of pyridine, after it agreed to
several measures, including the posting of a DEC monitor at the
plant and the retaining of an engineering firm to review
operations. The company is in talks with the DEC over when it can
resume making pyridine; the agency is expected to fine the company.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, employees who used to run the superheated
reactors that make pyridine now busy themselves with cleanup
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset, because it's my livelihood and because it's a
responsible company,'' said Pete Gallagher, a senior chemical
process operator and 27-year Nepera employee. ``We'd never operate
any process in an unsafe manner. We run it. We'd be the first ones
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Kanterman, a Nepera customer service representative for
two years, said she was angry at her community and the
environmental conservation department. ``I'd like the community to
be more open-minded and allow us to educate them,'' she said. ``If
something smells in the area, you can't assume it's Nepera. Kids
are being prodded by their teachers and parents'' to blame the
company for unfamiliar odors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hysteria,'' said Dolly Mancino Kirk, a shipping
supervisor who has worked at Nepera for 23 years and has heard
colleagues wondering if layoffs are around the corner. She said the
company's major mistake had been its failure to better inform
residents about the plant and its products.
</P>
<P>
   Gayser, the mayor, said the company, which is due in local court
March 15 to answer for violations of the village's air-quality
ordinances, had cooperated in investigations into leaks and
traditionally provided support to local sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a chemical company, they're doing the best they can,'' he
said. ``But I take it very seriously when people bring me their
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The schools superintendent, Terrence Olivo, said he believed
that some of his students were genuinely affected by exposure to
pyridine, while a larger percentage suffered a psychosomatic
reaction triggered by the first group. A third group, he said,
played along in hopes of getting time off from school.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the schools' first tactic for dealing with
announced leaks is to close windows and doors, which eventually
leads to stuffy classrooms and, some maintain, the true cause of
headaches and other ailments laid at Nepera's door.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Olivo said the district was interviewing law firms for a
possible suit against Nepera for disrupting the schools. ``There
have to be changes,'' he said. ``Our goal is for Nepera not to
restart without the reasonable certainty that there will be no
emissions.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 22 the Zoning Board of Appeals in the town of Woodbury,
of which Harriman is a part, will consider renewal of Nepera's
special operating permit, something that Jay M. Gubernick, a town
supervisor who is not a member of the board, said he would oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that Nepera hasn't served the public
safety and welfare,'' Gubernick said. ``If they can't live with us,
then they shouldn't live here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nestor Pozzo, who works in a cafe just outside Harriman,
said that he lived for more than 20 years without ill effect in the
path of the prevailing wind that blows over Nepera. After a decade
away, he moved back to the same area.
</P>
<P>
   The odor that was so prevalent in the 1970s was much reduced, he
said. He has never experienced any of the symptoms claimed by some
of Nepera's opponents. Asked to explain the commotion, he said,
``It doesn't take much to agitate the masses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
