<HEADER>
A0008 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-TUBBS-TCU-TEX     03-07 1635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TUBBS-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE STRUGGLES THIS SEASON, TUBBS WOULD LIKE TO STAY AT TCU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU hired Billy Tubbs in 1994 to resuscitate
its basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great hire at the time,'' former TCU athletic director Frank
Windegger said recently. ``We got a name coach, and he's done a
tremendous amount for the program.''
</P>
<P>
   In the three years before this season, Tubbs led his team to at
least 21 victories and postseason play. In doing so, he fulfilled
the mandate of Provost William Koehler, TCU's executive
administrator to the athletic department, and Windegger, who asked
Tubbs to give the Horned Frogs instant credibility and a national
profile.
</P>
<P>
   But, starting with an incident that embarrassed school officials
before last season concerning a scholarship promised to a local
high school star, and a perceived slide in his team's on-court
performance this season, the shine on the most-successful coach in
school history has dulled. So much so that sources close to the
athletic department say the 64-year-old Tubbs might not coach at
TCU beyond next season. A buyout of his contract is possible, the
sources say, if his team struggles again next season or if Tubbs
further clashes with the school's power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Factors fueling speculation about Tubbs' future include:
</P>
<P>
   TCU's failure to extend his contract after last season, as was
routinely the case under Windegger;
</P>
<P>
   a strained relationship with athletic director Eric Hyman that
soured when Tubbs reneged on a scholarship commitment to former
Crowley High School standout Brian Brookhart before last season;
</P>
<P>
   and a home-attendance drop of more than 20 percent this season.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs admits his sixth season has been his most disappointing at
TCU. This week's suspension of forward Myron Anthony, once thought
by Tubbs to be a fix for his team's early-season problems, is
indicative of the Frogs' up-and-down 17-13 season heading into
Western Athletic Conference tournament play tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said his program has merely hit a ``hiccup.'' Hyman,
diplomatically, calls it a ``speed bump.''
</P>
<P>
   The discontent of both parties goes deeper than this season's
record, however.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Tubbs say he would be agreeable to a buyout of
the final two years of his contract. The same sources said Tubbs
talked to Lamar University, his alma mater and one of his first
coaching stops, about its head-coaching job after last season.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said, ``I want to coach as long as they want me, and as
long as I think I'm doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyman refused to address Tubbs' contract situation and said
discussions on his performance would wait until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to make things better and improve, and you want to
be up-front with the coach and let him know that,'' Hyman said.
``With every program here we discuss how we can make things
better.''
The first hiccup
</P>
<P>
   Hyman began his first full academic year as TCU's athletic
director in the fall of 1998. The school year had barely started
when he was left to deal with a major public-relations
embarrassment concerning the case of Brian Brookhart.
</P>
<P>
   Brookhart, a lifelong TCU fan, had signed a national letter of
intent with the school in November 1997, his senior season.
However, when Brookhart arrived on campus the following August, a
TCU assistant coach told him it would be best for him to first play
junior-college basketball instead of coming to TCU.
</P>
<P>
   The Brookhart family took issue with the suggestion. Eventually
Brookhart, disillusioned with his treatment by the basketball
staff, decided to transfer. Chancellor Michael Ferrari said at the
time: ``I was disappointed how this particular instance was
handled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way we do things around here, especially
coaches,'' said a prominent booster. ``That's not TCU.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tubbs was hired from Oklahoma in 1994, Koehler and
Windegger provided him with a comfortable support system. A close
associate of Tubbs said the coach wants to run his program with the
autonomy he was given by Windegger but has been held more
accountable under Hyman. Under Windegger, Tubbs received contract
extensions after each season, in essence leaving Tubbs with a
four-year contract when Windegger retired two years ago. Hyman
didn't extend Tubbs' contract after the Frogs finished 21-11 last
season, which included advancing to the third round of the National
Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs turned a team that had won 13 games combined the previous
two seasons before his arrival into a competitive team his first
season, then built on that success to start a run of three
consecutive postseason appearances.
</P>
<P>
   This year's team, however, probably needs to win at least one
game in this week's WAC tournament to be considered for an NIT bid.
The Frogs have been inconsistent, losing five home games, their
most in a season under Tubbs, and five games by at least 10 points,
including 33- and 21-point losses to WAC champion Tulsa. Though TCU
has beaten 21-7 SMU twice, the Frogs rank 84th in the latest
CollegeRPI.com ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said the expectations he helped create with three
consecutive 20-victory seasons have made him a target of his past
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've raised the bar at TCU,'' Tubbs said. ``Twenty-win
seasons and legitimate expectations for a conference championship,
that's what people expect. And that's what I expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is like a little hiccup. Like my financial adviser
tells me after a drop in earnings, look back at '94, the same thing
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Koehler: ``Every time a team doesn't win 20, people want to
fire the coach, but that would get awfully expensive. Eight to 10
years ago, if we'd won 13 games, people would be ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's eight or 10 years ago.
Greater expectations
</P>
<P>
   The recent success of the TCU's football team (back-to-back bowl
victories), ironically, has taken some of the spotlight off the
basketball program. When TCU officials hired Dennis Franchione they
were determined to get a football coach to fulfill's Hyman's goal
of having a ``nationally prominent'' program to match what Tubbs
appeared to be building in basketball, a program that helped TCU
get an invitation to Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman wants both programs to be competitive on a national scope
heading into C-USA, an acknowledged step up from the WAC, in the
2001-2002 school year.
</P>
<P>
   Fan interest in the basketball program, however, dropped
dramatically this season. After averaging slightly more than 5,900
fans for home games in the 1997-98 and 1998-99 seasons, TCU
averaged 4,536 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Season-ticket holders are not coming to games,'' Hyman said.
``I'd like to get in a situation where we sell out every game, and
that's in the realm of possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Koehler said: ``We have to put a product on the floor that Fort
Worth and the surrounding areas can relate to. We're Fort Worth's
team. We've got to have a product that's exciting and people can
personally invest in without fear of disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, TCU hit its pinnacle under Tubbs, fielding a Top
25 team that swept through WAC play 14-0 and earned an NCAA
Tournament bid. Since then, Tubbs has had difficulty replacing
standouts such as Lee Nailon, Malcolm Johnson, Mike Jones and
Prince Fowler.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman prefers TCU's recruiting philosophy in all programs focus
on Fort Worth-Dallas area talent. Tubbs, however, has relied
primarily on transfers and has had little success signing and
keeping area players. Only two of the players on the current roster
are from Fort Worth-Dallas. One, J.R. Jones of Brewer High School,
is a walk-on. The other, Colin Boddicker of Duncanville,
transferred to TCU from Holy Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The booster is critical of Tubbs' recruitment of junior-college
players _ ``they're just hired guns'' _ and said TCU can't build a
competitive Conference USA program relying primarily on transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Junior guard Ryan Carroll, one of only four current scholarship
players who didn't transfer to TCU, said the team has struggled to
find the right chemistry all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never really jelled as a unit,'' Carroll said. ``This team
is more talented and deeper , but we didn't have enough guys in the
system. A lot of learning has to be done in practice, and it took
some time for guys to get adjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tubbs: ``I accept full responsibility. I try to stay in
touch with the fact that I'm an optimistic person, but I'm not so
optimistic that I'm out of touch with reality. I would like people
to be supportive of our program, but would I expect them to be
happy with this year? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, but at least we've changed the attitude
around here. TCU expects to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said he doesn't need to coach anymore, but the competitive
fire still burns. He would like to coach at least five more
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a point in time where I just want to be good and I want
the program to be good,'' Tubbs said. ``Today, I don't feel any
different than when I came to TCU. If I would have stayed at
Oklahoma, I would have quit coaching by now. I was in a rut. Coming
here energized me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs certainly isn't talking about slowing down. He has high
expectations for next season. He said the recruiting class coming
in could be TCU's best in some time. Plus, the addition of transfer
guard Greedy Daniels to a team that returns everyone except forward
Marquise Gainous should put the Frogs in the running for the WAC
title in their final season in the league, Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   He is proud of the fact that whenever he leaves, the TCU
program, much like Oklahoma and Lamar, will be left in better shape
that what he inherited.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is when.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
