<HEADLINE>
PERISHO LOCKED IN BATTLE TO MAKE ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Matt Perisho has two opportunities to
make the club. He can beat out Mark Clark and become the fifth
starter, or he can earn a spot as a left-handed reliever.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't hurt his chances for either job yesterday, pitching
two hitless innings in the Rangers' 3-1 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays. He only allowed one base runner, on a one-out walk to Dave
Martinez in the fourth inning. He struck out Greg Vaughn and Vinny
Castilla to open the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw strikes and got people out,'' manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho is looking forward to a springlong battle with Clark,
who shut out the Devil Rays for three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to bring out the competitor in both players,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho was 15-7 with a 4.61 earned-run average in 27 starts at
Triple-A Oklahoma City last season, and he had a 2.61 ERA in four
appearances with the Rangers in September.
</P>
<P>
   He is out of options, and likely would be claimed if the Rangers
tried to get him through waivers to return him to the minors. That,
along with left-handed reliever Mike Venafro's finger injury, makes
Perisho a good bet to make the club in some role.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easier, though, if he could be certain of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could be like 130 other guys where they say, `Here's
your job, here's what you need to do, now let's go get ready for
the season,' '' he said.
Wetteland not a concern
</P>
<P>
   When outfielder Rusty Greer and reliever John Wetteland suffered
injuries in an intrasquad game Thursday, both were expected to miss
three to four days.
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who had inflammation around his right ankle, was back in
the lineup Monday. He took the day off yesterday as scheduled and
isn't expected to have any lingering problems.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who strained his right calf muscle, was back on a
mound to throw on the side Sunday but has yet to make his
exhibition debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure when he'll be ready to throw in a game,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, though, has yet to raise a warning flag like the
ankle injury he had last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not serious,'' Oates said. ``I've been told it's just a
strain. If John can get ready last year, he can get ready any time.
He didn't pitch at all last spring, and he had a pretty good year.
He's already got his arm strength up there fastball-wise, so it
won't take him that long to get ready to pitch.''
Base-running blunder
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton was successful on a steal of third with no one out
in the first inning Monday. He tried it again yesterday, this time
in the wrong situation and without success.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton was thrown out at third with two outs and Rafael
Palmeiro up in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we're having spring training,'' Oates said. ``He
knows he made a mistake, and we talked about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he gives everyone on the team a green light on the
bases this early in the spring in order to learn who gets one
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get a lot of knowledge about who knows how and when to
go,'' he said.
Alicea solid
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Luis Alicea displayed his power Monday, hitting
two home runs. He displayed his bat control yesterday, flicking it
out to make contact that led to a infield single with Royce Clayton
running in fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea, who is expected to take over for Mark McLemore as the
regular second baseman, is hitting .300 and has made all the plays
in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything that I did not expect,'' Oates said.
``He's a good baseball player; he knows how the game is supposed to
be played. I'm not sure he's a 140-game type guy, but when he's
rested and healthy he can do a lot of things well.''
More Mateo
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ruben Mateo again displayed the ability to handle
the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo's one-out, fourth-inning sacrifice fly with the bases
loaded scored Royce Clayton. Mateo delivered the sacrifice fly
despite a two-strike count against right-hander Chad Ogea.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's two times in a row he's been able to get the ball to
the outfield'' with a runner at third and less than two outs,
Johnny Oates said. \Nname:_ Johnny Paul
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Third-base coach Jerry Narron was hit by a Ruben Mateo foul ball
for the second time this spring. He also was nailed in the
exhibition opener.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler's grand slam against the Boston Red Sox on Monday
was the first by a Ranger in spring training since Shawn Gallagher
hit one against the Detroit Tigers on March 13, 1999. Kapler played
for the Tigers that day, and went deep twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have had two two-homer games this spring, one by
Alicea and one by Tom Evans in the exhibition opener Friday against
the Minnesota Twins. Before this year, the last two-homer spring
game was by Dean Palmer on March 4, 1997.
nn
</P>
