<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CANCELS GAME AT HAWAII
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texas officials, citing concerns about
rising travel costs and the possible wear and tear on athletes
during a possible 14-game season, have canceled the team's Sept. 2
football game at Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director DeLoss Dodds made the announcement yesterday,
meaning the Longhorns' season opener will be Sept. 9 in Austin
against Louisiana-Lafayette. Under terms of the agreement, Texas
officials must pay Hawaii a $100,000 cancellation fee if the
Rainbow Warriors cannot find ``an opponent of similar stature'' to
replace Texas on their 2000 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dodds said school officials expected to lose $175,000
going to Hawaii because of rising fuel costs that made the trip
``fiscally irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Texas coach Mack Brown expressed concerns about
playing a 14-game schedule if the Longhorns reaches the Big 12
title game and earned a bowl invitation.
</P>
<P>
   By dropping Hawaii, the Longhorns now have 11 regular-season
games and would play a maximum of 13 games next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry this didn't work out and for any inconvenience it
causes Hawaii,'' Dodds said yesterday in a prepared statement. ``We
looked at this from every angle. ... The bottom line is we have to
do what is in the best interests of our program.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his team lost its final three games to end last season
with a 9-5 record, Brown has been lobbying to avoid the chance of
playing another 14-game season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we got a little tired at the end of the season last
year, and the schedule played a part,'' Brown said. ``We played 14
games ... and our guys just wore out.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
