<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK MAKE BID FOR FIFTH SPOT IN RANGERS' ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Questions regarding the health of
right-hander Mark Clark can be put to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Only one question requires an answer this spring. Will Clark be
part of the Rangers' rotation by Opening Day?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go out there and pitch the way I'm capable, I don't see
any reason why I won't be the fifth starter,'' Clark said after
pitching three scoreless innings during the Rangers' 3-1 loss
yesterday to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Clark or left-hander Matt Perisho likely will join left-handers
Kenny Rogers and Darren Oliver and right-handers Rick Helling and
Esteban Loaiza in the Rangers' rotation. The odd-man-out likely
will become the staff's long reliever. Perisho replaced Clark
yesterday and also pitched impressively, with two innings of no-hit
relief that included strikeouts of Greg Vaughn and Vinny Castilla.
</P>
<P>
   Only one batter reached safely against Clark during his
economical, 33-pitch appearance against a Devil Rays lineup that
included power hitters Jose Canseco, Fred McGriff, Vaughn and
Castilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better now than I felt at any time last year,'' Clark
said, ``and I think they're seeing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not see that last year in his debut with the
organization after signing a two-year, $9 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Clark went 3-7 with an 8.60 earned-run average in 15 starts
before being placed on the disabled list June 20 with a tear of the
ulnar collateral ligament in his right elbow. Clark never returned
from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to prove that I can pitch,'' said Clark, who did
not allow a well-hit ball to any of the nine batters he faced
yesterday. ``They know I can pitch. I've got to show them that I'm
healthy, and I'm doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Gerald Williams had the only hit against Clark, a
first-inning infield single. Clark struck out McGriff and second
baseman Miguel Cairo and threw first-pitch strikes to seven of nine
batters.
</P>
<P>
   Credit that to Clark's sinking, two-seam fastball, the
foundation of his arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of my pitches come off that pitch,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The injury prevented Clark from extending his right arm during
his delivery, and that robbed him of velocity and movement.
Opponents hit .329 against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been throwing the ball well,'' bullpen coach Larry Hardy
said. ``He's getting through the ball, and his fastball has
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark does not relish the idea of pitching in relief and
informed general manager Doug Melvin of that this winter in a
cordial conversation. Clark also informed Melvin of his desire to
be traded if relegated to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good,'' Clark said of the conversation. ``I just
expressed my thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's performance, though, will determine his role and future
with the Rangers. The organization also has an option on his
contract for the 2001 season worth $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, would it be nice to have him come out of the chute and
pitch like he can,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``He had a pretty
good year in '98. He was hurt in '99. We didn't see Mark Clark last
year.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
