<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS WAITING ON WORD FROM MITCHELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Could the Cowboys lose a free-agent prospect to
lowly Cincinnati?
</P>
<P>
   That appears more possible as Baltimore Ravens quarterback Scott
Mitchell didn't contact the Cowboys yesterday, a day after they
offered him a contract to replace Jason Garrett as Troy Aikman's
backup.
</P>
<P>
   A deal with the Bengals has not been completed, but Mitchell's
agent, Tony Agnone, asked the team to send a contract to the
quarterback via overnight delivery, the ``Dayton Daily News''
reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Agnone could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys offensive coordinator Jack Reilly, whose close
relationship with Mitchell from the University of Utah was the
impetus for the Cowboys' interest, said the quarterback believes he
would have a better chance of playing next season as a backup to
Akili Smith in Cincinnati than as a backup to Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys don't get Mitchell, they could turn to Mike
Quinn, the team's No. 3 quarterback last season, as the primary
backup or to a moderately priced veteran free-agent quarterback,
such as Shane Matthews, Billy Joe Hobert and Paul Justin.
nn
</P>
