<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK AIMS FOR 200TH VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock is one regular-season
victory shy of No. 200. If he gets it tonight against the Vancouver
Canucks, he will be the fourth-fastest coach in NHL history to
reach 200 victories. In 355 games, Hitchcock is 199-114-42. Don
Cherry did it in 341 games, Toe Blake did it in 345, and Tommy Ivan
did it in 353. Mike Keenan is fourth, notching 200 victories in 357
games.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, in his fourth full season as the Stars' coach, has a
.620 winning percentage, the second highest among active NHL
coaches. Detroit coach Scotty Bowman is first at .653. Hitchcock
became the Stars' winningest coach with his 175th victory on Dec. 1
at Montreal.
Fernandez in net
</P>
<P>
   It's tough enough being a backup goalie and going day to day not
knowing the next time you'll play. It's worse when your most-recent
game was a 5-2 loss to Nashville. Manny Fernandez returns to the
net tonight having plenty of time to mull that Feb. 21 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try it all over again,'' Fernandez said. ``I don't play
much, so I'll get back to the basics. I just want to win the games.
We've got to get the two points from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Belfour has taken the past two days of practice off. He's
using the extra time to work out at Dr Pepper StarCenter and at his
home gym, Ken Hitchcock said.
Penalty killer
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner has become a penalty killer out of
necessity. With penalty-killing regulars Blake Sloan and Guy
Carbonneau out with injuries for at least two weeks, Langenbrunner
has emerged as Ken Hitchcock's choice to play on the special-teams
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it; it keeps you in the flow of the game,''
Langenbrunner said. ``We tend to play a lot of pressure, so you get
to keep moving, and I like that. We try to get after them and try
to make them make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said defenseman Darryl Sydor will likely be pulled up
as forward more often on the penalty-killing unit while Sloan and
Carbonneau are out.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
