<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE TAKES COMMAND OF DEMOCRATIC RACE
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects last word of 9th graf to ``Gore.''
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Vice President Al Gore took command of the
Democratic presidential race Tuesday, sweeping to lopsided
victories in states from coast to coast and forcing Bill Bradley to
assess whether to continue his challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a victory address at a posh downtown Nashville hotel,
immediately pivoted to a general election strategy with an appeal
to the independent voters that were attracted to GOP upstart John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Join us now,'' he said in touting the economic prosperity of
the last seven years and presenting the Democratic Party as
``mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is full tonight,'' Gore declared to the hundreds of
supporters who celebrated his victory with food, drinks and country
music.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to heal any wounds from the surprisingly bitter battle
with Bradley, Gore called his challenger a ``good man.'' He added,
``Anybody who has heard Bill Bradley throughout this campaign has
come away from the experience moved and touched by the strength of
his commitment to healing the divisions in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   A subdued but relaxed Bradley spoke to supporters in an
appearance shortly after the polls closed in New York. Surrounded
by longtime friends and campaign staff at a New York hotel, Bradley
hinted that the losses would force him to withdraw from the race,
but vowed to continue the fight for a ``new kind of politics in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He won; I lost,'' Bradley said. ``On one level I agree with
Vince Lombardi when he said winning isn't everything, it's the only
thing. Tomorrow, I'll consult with supporters around the country
and get their thoughts and advice and I'll make my plans known
shortly.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign chairman Doug Berman shook his head ``no'' when asked
if the the speech left any doubt that Bradley planned to exit the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley had long contended that he was up against
``entrenched power'' in his campaign against Gore, he lost every
core Democratic constituency in what is likely to be his last
face-to-face contest with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   According to network television polls, Gore won African
Americans, Jews, Hispanics, gays, labor and women, all key elements
of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's support came almost exclusively from anti-Clinton
Democrats, not a large constituency in a party that, despite the
impeachment of President Clinton, has presided over the longest
economic expansion in history.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's victories in the largest primary voting of the year
reflected a remarkable comeback from the days last summer when his
campaign was viewed as weak and ineffective in the face of a
surprisingly strong challenge from Bradley and the popularity of
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the GOP front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   But a disciplined and energetic Gore powered past Bradley on
Tuesday. And in a poll published Tuesday by the Wall Street
Journal, Gore erased the double digit lead Bush had on him last
summer. The latest poll shows the two in a 46-46 percent tie.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his family joined fellow Tennesseans at a hotel near
the Vanderbilt University campus to celebrate one of the biggest
victories of his 24-year career in politics, one that brings him a
step closer to the nomination he first sought in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Gore registered convincing margins of victory in California, New
York, Georgia and Ohio, the most important states in the so-called
Super Tuesday primary. He also rolled up victories in Connecticut,
Massachusetts, Maryland, Vermont, Maine, Rhode Island and Missouri,
Bradley's native state.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley launched his uphill campaign against Gore in December
1998. Others considered the race, but calculated that a sitting
vice president would be too difficult to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley scored early success in the fund-raising arena, raising
almost as much money as Gore and threatening the vice president
with positive poll numbers in New Hampshire, site of the nation's
first primary.
</P>
<P>
   Pledging to be a candidate of ``big ideas,'' Bradley ran on a
plan to provide health insurance to the nation's poor, enact
stricter gun control and replace the campaign finance laws with a
system of public financing.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley invested heavily in Iowa and lost. The defeat,
coupled with McCain's maverick appeal, contributed to Bradley's
loss in New Hampshire. From then on, Bradley found it difficult to
regain his footing in a national media environment where all the
focus was on McCain and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of this is that we had an extraordinarily hard
task in front of us,'' said Anita Dunn, Bradley's communications
director. ``We knew it would not be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett's e-mail address is kenf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
