<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMY-AWARDS-DOCUMENTARIES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOOST FOR DOCUMENATRIES THAT AIM HIGH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has become almost as much of an Oscar ritual as overwrought
production numbers and fashion gaffes: a documentary that has
entranced both critics and audiences is inexplicably omitted when
the nominations in that category are announced. Over the years, the
roster of distinguished non-nominees has included ``Shoah,'' ``28
Up,'' ``Roger and Me,'' ``The Thin Blue Line,'' ``Brother's
Keeper,'' ``Crumb'' and ``Hoop Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The snubbing of acclaimed pictures like these proved so
embarrassing to the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
that its leaders began tinkering with the selection process half a
dozen years ago. But the complaints persisted.
</P>
<P>
   For this year's awards, academy officials went much further.
They set in motion a process that led to a complete overhaul of the
documentary selection process. This time, according to some of
their harshest critics, they appear to have gotten it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new system seems to be working very well,'' said Betsy A.
McLane, the executive director of the International Documentary
Association, a nonprofit organization that represents 2,500
documentary filmmakers. ``I haven't talked to anyone who doesn't
feel this is an improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to past years, when popularity at the box office
seemed to disqualify a documentary from academy consideration, this
year's five nominees include one film that found an unusually large
audience for a work of nonfiction: ``Buena Vista Social Club,''
about a group of forgotten musicians from prerevolutionary Cuba.
The other nominees include some well-regarded pictures, two of
which also focus on musicians.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, academy officials acknowledge, the choice of
nominees in the documentary category was skewed by rules that
required every member of the screening committee to watch every
eligible film in a theater, subjecting them to a marathon of as
many as 65 films in the space of two months.
</P>
<P>
   Since few people working in Hollywood have that much disposable
time, many of the committee's volunteers were retired people, not
even necessarily documentary filmmakers, who often had little
appreciation for innovative work or for complex, unsentimental
approaches to social themes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve James' ``Hoop Dreams,'' for example, which traced the
lives of two Chicago youths who dreamed of becoming basketball
stars, was regarded by many critics as one of the best films of
1994, documentary or dramatic. But the academy screening committee
did not share that enthusiasm, said Jean Rouverol Butler, an
actress and screenwriter, now 83, who was a member for more than 15
years. ``I don't think `Hoop Dreams' was that popular,'' she said.
``People felt it was self-indulgent, in terms of being an hour too
long and running well past what it had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler said the committee rejected ``The Thin Blue Line,'' the
much-praised 1988 film by Errol Morris that helped bring about the
release of a death row inmate, on the ground that some scenes were
re-enacted. ``People were quite bitter against it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reform the screening process, the academy tried
to reduce the workload, including barring films that had been seen
at festivals but not in theaters. But this year, it took a much
bigger step by asking some leading documentary filmmakers to come
up with completely new procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schwartzman, the producer of the 1981 Oscar-winning
documentary ``Genocide,'' was named chairman of a 12-member
documentary executive committee consisting of a number of
well-known filmmakers, including Morris, Michael Apted (``28 Up'')
and Barbara Kopple, who received Academy Awards for the 1976
``Harlan County U.S.A.'' and the 1990 ``American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We put them into a room,'' said Bruce Davis, the executive
director of the academy, ``and we said, `You need to work out a
system, and do it better than we've been doing it in the past.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The system they devised worked like this: about 130 academy
members across the country who are associated with the nonfiction
genre were asked to help come up with a short list of 12 films,
culled from 55 entries. About 80 people responded, many more than
expected, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a departure for the academy's leadership, which has
generally frowned on the use of videotapes in the selection
process, they were encouraged to see the entries on their VCRs. The
volunteers were divided into four groups so that no one had to
watch more than 14 cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   After the results of the first round of voting were announced,
in early January, the process was opened to the entire academy
membership of 5,607. To join the voting at this point, members had
to see all 12 films in a screening room in Los Angeles, San
Francisco or New York. About 140 people participated, Davis said.
(Before the remaining academy members vote in the best documentary
category, they must see all five nominees.)
</P>
<P>
   Sinofsky, the co-director of ``Brother's Keeper,'' said he was
thrilled that so many documentary filmmakers had taken part in the
initial selection. ``They are opening it up from the myopic view of
what a nonfiction film is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five nominees, the heavy favorite is ``Buena Vista Social
Club,'' directed by Wim Wenders. The film has already picked up
awards from the New York Film Critics Circle, the Los Angeles Film
Critics Association and the National Society of Film Critics.
</P>
<P>
   The other nominated films with musical themes are ``Genghis
Blues,'' produced by Roko and Adrian Belic, which follows a blind
San Francisco blues singer and guitarist who becomes enamored of
the Central Asian vocal technique called throat-singing; and
``Speaking in Strings,'' Paola di Florio's portrait of the
Italian-born violinist Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Cohn, a two-time Oscar winner, is represented by ``One
Day in September,'' an account of the 1972 massacre of Israeli
Olympic athletes, produced with Kevin McDonald. Rounding out the
nominees is ``On the Ropes,'' a film by Nanette Burstein and Brett
Morgen that looks at the role of the Bed-Stuy Boxing Center in
Brooklyn in the lives of three aspiring prizefighters.
</P>
<P>
   (A film by Morris, ``Death: The Rise and Fall of Fred A.
Leuchter Jr.,'' which was a runner-up for several critics' awards,
made the first cut but was eliminated in the second round.)
</P>
<P>
   The response to the new system has been positive, Davis said.
``It is very exhilarating to walk into a roomful of documentarians
and have them all smiling at you,'' he said. ``It's a nice
change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
