<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0088 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-REPUBLICAN-PRIMARIES-     03-07 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBLICAN-PRIMARIES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BUSH BLITZES McCAIN ON SUPER TUESDAY  
 &HT;     (Eds: Updates with delegate figures, early returns in New York,
McCain quote)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush effectively ended the challenge of
Sen. John
</P>
<P>
   McCain for the Republican presidential nomination Tuesday,
setting the
</P>
<P>
   stage for Bush to reach out to McCain and his supporters to join
a GOP crusade to reclaim the White House in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain pledged late Tuesday that his ``crusade'' would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush harnessed hard-hitting campaign ads and a lavishly financed
nationwide campaign organization to sweep most of the 13 states
with GOP contests.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial returns and television network projections showed
Bush beating McCain in California, New York, Ohio, Georgia,
Maryland, Missouri and Maine. Bush dashed McCain's last hopes for a
symbolic victory by capturing the popular vote contest in
California in which non-Republicans cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls showed that Bush dominated key winner-take-all
delegate contests, including California, as well as the majority of
the GOP delegates in states that award delegates on a
district-by-district basis.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's campaign manager, said the Texan would pick up
as many as 450 of the 613 delegates chosen on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   CNN delegate projections at 11 p.m. EST showed Bush winning 245
delegates from the Super Tuesday contests, not including the 162
delegates at stake in California. The projections showed McCain
picking up 108. Including his anticipated victory in California,
Bush has won 622 delegates and McCain 213 since the 2000 contest
began in Iowa in January. A Republican candidate needs 1,034
delegates to secure the presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, whose fiery populism sustained an uphill challenge for
the last six weeks, captured Vermont, Connecticut, Massachusetts
and Rhode Island. He did not sweep New England and New York, as he
said he needed to do to sustain his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the 63-year-old former Navy pilot and Vietnam prisoner
of war make inroads among the bedrock Republican voters who he
needed in order to garner large numbers of delegates in the
district-by-district duels in states such as New York and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, son of former President George H.W. Bush, made it clear
that his most pressing task in the days ahead will be to court
McCain, and the centrist Republicans, independents and Democrats
who rallied to McCain, in hopes of ending the GOP fratricide that
imperils his chances in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bush paid homage to McCain, echoing the Arizonan's message of
reform and publicly praising him. ``We have our disagreements but I
respect him and his commitment to reform,'' Bush said in remarks
prepared for his victory celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, savoring the likely end of his GOP primary struggle,
shifted his attention to Vice President Al Gore, ``the candidate of
the status quo'' who must be defeated because ``America must not
give Clinton-Gore a third term.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign manager signaled that the victor would await
McCain's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not up to us to urge him out of the race,'' Rove said.
``What would be appropriate for us to do is to indicate that
Governor Bush is ready to heal and unify the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove said Bush would only claim victory ``when we get to 1,034
delegates and we're the only candidate left.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary schedule moves into Bush territory next Tuesday,
with contests in six key southern and southwestern states,
including Texas, where he is governor, and Florida where his
brother, Jeb Bush, is chief executive. The six states offer 341
delegates _ enough to give Bush a mathematical lock on the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would stay in the race only if he believed he
still had a chance to turn things around and win the nomination.
McCain said last weekend that he would withdraw from a failing race
rather than have his ``megaphone turn into a kazoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran senator struck a wistful tone before the results
were in. ``I can't tell you how proud I am to have sparked this
kind of prairie fire out there that got people involved,'' McCain
said told a radio call-in program early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's hard-hitting populist bid, featuring attacks on Bush,
``the establishment,'' the White House, Congress and special
interests, attracted legions of first-time voters, once-alienated
young voters, independents and Democrats to the GOP banner.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's candidacy ignited historic turnouts in New Hampshire
and Michigan, where he won early momentum, as well as in South
Carolina where he lost.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross Baker, a political science professor at Rutgers
University, said excitement does not translate into nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a credible early favorite _ and you have the
fortitude to stay on in the face of early disappointments _ you're
going to win the nomination,'' Baker said. ``Ultimately the
favorites designated by the party graybeards walk away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster based in Atlanta who is not
working for any presidential campaign, said McCain could not hope
to win the GOP nomination ``without Republican votes,'' adding:
``Establishment matters, and money matters _ especially in a war of
attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, which had the support of Republican leaders _
including 29 governors, 38 senators and 175 House members _ carried
out 2 million get-out-the-vote telephone calls in nine states in
the final two days of the Super Tuesday campaign, mailed 2 million
pieces of campaign literature and distributed 69,000 yard signs,
according to Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Baker and Ayres said Bush had been strengthened for the
fall campaign by being forced to grapple with McCain's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has become ``a far superior candidate, far more aggressive,
far more
</P>
<P>
   unscripted, far more willing to take chances,'' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at
202-298-6920 or at
</P>
<P>
   the e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com and dan &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
