<SLUG> BC-ACADEMY-AWARDS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIMBING MT. OSCAR: SO MANY MOVIES, SO LITTLE TIME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics) March 7, 2000. Days remaining: 19. Best film nominees
seen: 5 of 5 (excellent). Best actor and actress nominees seen: 16
of 20 (very .good.). Films of best director nominees seen: 5 of 5
(excellent). Best screenplay nominees seen: 9 of 10 (v.g.).
Calories consumed in process: 6,400, mostly three-ounce boxes of
Milk Duds (unfortunate).(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year I'm really going to do it. When Billy Crystal bounds
onto the stage of the Los Angeles Shrine Auditorium on March 26, I
will have seen every single film and performance nominated for an
Academy Award in every major category, so help me God. Even if I
have to go to a movie about an old man driving a lawn mower across
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   I am not alone in this quest. There are many of us, the
Oscar-dependent, who view the annual awards presentation as not
just a reason to stay home and watch movie actresses try to
outshine one another in borrowed dresses but as a crucial filmgoing
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, of course, is to see as many of the nominated movies
and performances as possible _ at the very least, to see more of
them than your friends have. And some people actually don't
understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Oscar parties are a factor. Whether you are the host or a
guest, it's very satisfying to be the person in front of the
television set who knows the most about the nominees. And if
there's a party prize for the greatest number of accurate
predictions (or if you're making predictions in the office pool),
it certainly doesn't hurt to have checked out the nominees
firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't the whole story. Anyway, since when does knowing
who (italics)should(end italics) win give you any insight into who
(italics)will(end italics) win? Those crazy Oscar voters chose
``Chariots of Fire'' as best picture over ``Reds'' for 1981. They
picked ``Forrest Gump'' over ``Pulp Fiction'' for 1994.
</P>
<P>
   And even when you try to think like them and forecast a victory
for a sentimental favorite, they'll fool you every time. I was
almost as surprised as Lauren Bacall was three years ago when
Juliette Binoche's name was read as the supporting actress winner
for ``The English Patient.'' ( Bacall was expected to win for
having played Barbra Streisand's gloriously egocentric mother in
``The Mirror Has Two Faces.'')
</P>
<P>
   What this multiplex-to-multiplex quest is really about is
informed opinion. Yes, there are moviegoers who will be willing to
insist that Michael Clarke Duncan should be named best supporting
actor for playing the gentle giant of a death row prisoner in ``The
Green Mile'' without having seen Tom Cruise as the slightly
deranged sex guru in ``Magnolia'' and vice versa. Well, that's OK
for some people, for some humdrum people, but no serious Oscar
devotee would make such rash judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Real Oscar devotees start making their mental lists early, at
least by November and December, when most of the likely award
contenders are released. Those of us who saw ``American Beauty''
back in September were smart; it ended up with eight nominations.
Seeing ``The Sixth Sense'' was a lucky break. Who knew back in
August that this Bruce Willis ghost movie with the nifty surprise
ending would rack up six Oscar nominations including _ excuse me _
best picture? Not that it isn't a lot of fun, but come on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Ripley,'' on the other hand, was a miscalculation
on my part. I really liked it, but it yielded fewer major
nominations than I had thought: only Jude Law for supporting actor
and Anthony Minghella for adapted screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Golden Globe Awards narrow things down
considerably. Then, when the actual Academy Award nominations are
announced, it's time to get serious. I happened to be in Los
Angeles and awake on Feb. 15, when this year's were read aloud on
television, and a friend and I saw ``Boys Don't Cry'' that night.
</P>
<P>
   This was, of course, to evaluate Hilary Swank's gender-bending
performance as Brandon Teena. I had waited in case her Golden Globe
victory had been a fluke. (The Screen Actors Guild Awards are
Sunday night; I'm hoping for no surprises.)
</P>
<P>
   The best actress award is going to be a tough one to call,
because I missed Janet McTeer in ``Tumbleweeds'' in November, and
Fine Line doesn't plan to rerelease it in New York. I have a
feeling I'm missing something important, because McTeer was amazing
in ``A Doll's House'' on Broadway three years ago. Rumor has it
there are several great performances in not-so-great movies this
year. Do I really want to see ``Music of the Heart,'' for instance,
about a depressed single mom who becomes an inspiring violin
teacher in East Harlem? I know Meryl Streep can do anything, but
I'm imagining some misguided combination of ``Dangerous Minds'' and
`` Holland's Opus.''
</P>
<P>
   This Oscar madness has one positive side effect. It helps me
focus and prioritize my moviegoing. There are always more good
movies than there are free afternoons or evenings to see them in,
and for a couple of months it's a little easier to choose. So
``Wonder Boys'' will have to wait, as will a lot of Broadway
theatergoing.
</P>
<P>
   There will be time to catch up later. Meanwhile I am definitely
going to see Richard Farnsworth in ``The Straight Story'' (the
aforementioned old man on a lawn mower). Its reviews have been
enthusiastically positive, and there's a 7:30 at the Village East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
