<HEADLINE>
BUSH WINS MISSOURI GOP PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With the vanguard of the state's Republican
Party in his corner, George W. Bush thumped John McCain in
Missouri's GOP presidential primary Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With 71 percent of the state's 4,017 precincts reporting, Bush
led 59-35 percent with former Ambassador Alan Keyes getting 6
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, Bush won by about the same margins. In
Jackson County, he was up 57-35 percent over McCain with all
precincts reporting.
</P>
<P>
   With 100 percent of the precincts reporting in Clay County, Bush
won 54-39 percent. In Platte and Cass counties with all votes
counted, Bush won with 52-41 percent and 58-34 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a better victory than we could have hoped for,'' said
Catherine Hanaway, Bush's Missouri executive director. ``We think
that bodes very well for November.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was strong in St. Louis where he was buoyed by the
efforts of relatives, including his uncle, Bucky Bush, who lives in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls showed that Bush's support from conservative
Republicans easily offset crossover voting by Democrats and
independents, the force that propelled McCain to victory in other
states.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case in most state primaries, Bush was the clear
choice of GOP voters. Six in 10 voters in the GOP primary
identified themselves as Republicans. Among them, seven in 10
favored Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain pulled in more independents than Gore, his numbers
were nowhere near the two-thirds of independents he attracted in
other recent primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed Bush was not severely damaged by his speech at
Bob Jones University, a South Carolina college whose leaders have
espoused some anti-Catholic views. A quarter of Republican voters
were Catholic, and a majority of the Catholics favored Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The bitterness of the GOP race seemed to work against McCain.
Nearly half of all voters said McCain's attacks on Bush were
unfair; only about one-third said that of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Final visits by both candidates were of little use, the poll
showed. Seven in 10 Republican voters had made up their minds at
least a week before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Former Missouri GOP chairman Woody Cozad said McCain's recent
denunciation of conservative religious leaders Jerry Falwell and
Pat Robertson as ``forces of evil'' backfired on McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's divisive, and everybody in the party agrees they don't
want that this year,'' Cozad said.
</P>
<P>
   One voter McCain lost because of his comments was state Rep. Roy
Holand, a Springfield Republican. Heading into last week, Holand
said he was undecided between McCain and Bush. But that changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To pop off like this is surprising and disappointing,'' Holand
said. ``If John McCain feels that conservative Republicans are that
bad, then that includes me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush worked for his Missouri victory. Although he spent the bulk
of his time in California and New York, states that offered far
more delegates Tuesday, the Texan stopped in St. Louis and
Springfield last week and visited Kansas City on Feb. 22. He also
spent thousands of dollars on television advertising focused on
specific regions, but not the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking to the next president,'' he said in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bush volunteers made more than 200,000 telephone calls during
the last 10 days, an effort that made the difference, Hanaway said.
</P>
<P>
   With little time to organize here, McCain ran a
seat-of-the-pants campaign based exclusively on volunteers. He made
only one stop in the state _ a hastily arranged event last week in
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCain campaign simply didn't have the resources I would
have liked seen devoted to Missouri,'' said David Steelman,
McCain's Missouri chairman. ``We were outspent 10 to 1, maybe 20 to
1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
