<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AFRO-CARIBBEAN-MUSIC-     03-07 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRO-CARIBBEAN-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING A STOCKPILE OF SALSA'S HISTORY INTO A SHOWPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Part of it hangs on the walls of a cramped corridor
in an East Harlem school, identified by tiny paper labels,
yellowing and brittle. A portion is squeezed into a shelf under an
assemblage of broken appliances. Another piece of it is encased in
bubble wrap, lining the bottom of a deep closet.
</P>
<P>
   But even in its current undignified setting, the Raices Latin
Music Collection is considered one of the most important archives
of Afro-Caribbean music in America today. It has about 15,000
items, including a marimba made to order for Tito Puente, Machito's
original orchestral arrangements, rare photos of Mongo Santamaria
performing with Dizzy Gillespie, posters promoting concerts, rare
magazines, hand-scrawled sheet music, slides, rare 78 rpm
recordings and oral histories with the music's pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, Raices, which means roots, tells the story of
how Latin traditions and American jazz converged into the brassy
percussive sound of salsa. Its story, archivists and music
historians say, is just waiting to be told.
</P>
<P>
   Its fans hope Raices will soon be drawn out of the dusty closets
and arid filing cabinets where it has been stored since 1978 at the
Boys Harbor's Conservatory for the Performing Arts, a music school
for children at 104th Street and Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone, a government-financed
local development corporation, voted in January to give Boys Harbor
a $450,000 grant to help the conservatory preserve the collection
and transform it from a private archive to a public institution,
although the grant is still awaiting final approval from the city.
</P>
<P>
   That financing follows a 1998 zone grant of $125,000, which
allowed the Harbor to hire an appraiser to assess the collection.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has also helped the cause by naming the
collection an ``American treasure,'' a designation by the Save
America's Treasures program that will help it receive recognition
and financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Rodriguez, director of the Boys Harbor Conservatory, and
Louis Bauzo, director of its Latin percussion program, have long
been frustrated that the collection is now seen only by scholars
who make appointments to rummage through it. They have great
visions for a museum that they hope will eventually house the
material.
</P>
<P>
   For now, that museum is only a dream. The empowerment zone money
is only a small portion of the $36 million the Harbor must raise
either to renovate a building somewhere in East Harlem or to build
anew and have money left over for an endowment.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first. The grant will enable Boys Harbor to
appoint Gladys Pena Acosta, a former curator for the city's Art
Commission, director and curator of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very, very detailed work,'' she said, ``and
the first step is to take it out of the closets and put it in a
situation where it's going to be safeguarded. It's an incredible
opportunity to come in and rescue these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry C. Lane, president and chief executive of the Upper
Manhattan Empowerment Zone, said the support was part of an effort
to promote ``heritage tourism,'' which he said is the growth sector
of the tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
   The collection and the hoped-for museum, Lane said, ``would be a
destination on upper Museum Mile,'' along with El Museo del Barrio,
the Museum of the City of New York and the Schomburg Center for
Research in Black Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Raices' collection may not be well known, but it was not for
lack of effort. Nina Olson, who has been the fund-raiser and
publicist for Raices for nine years, has written at least 50
requests for grants and financing, most of them rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've ever read that someone is interested in Latin music,
believe me they've gotten a letter,'' she said. ``Avon, Coors,
Philip Morris, Herb Alpert, Rums of Puerto Rico, Bacardi Rum,
there's quite a list. I'm hoping now that somehow the declaration
of an American treasure and support I've gotten from the
empowerment zone will give it a kind of validity somehow that's
more inviting to funders.''
</P>
<P>
   A scholar who has plumbed the Raices collection said that there
is nothing else like it in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Raices gets a lot of support, it may be the foundation of
what would become the recognized national archive of East Coast
Latino music,'' said the scholar, Juan Flores, a professor of black
and Puerto Rican studies at Hunter College and a professor of
sociology at the City University of New York Graduate Center.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, he added, the collection puts to rest the
notion that America's craze for Latin music began when Ry Cooder
visited Havana to resurrect the Buena Vista Social Club.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a surge in the popularity of Afro-Caribbean music
nationwide, spurred in part by the growing Hispanic population and
in part by the rise of a handful of mainstream music stars who have
Latin roots, like Marc Anthony and Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Although some would argue that these artists have little
connection to the Latin jazz pioneers like Machito, Mario Bauza or
Noro Morales, their popularity promotes an interest in the music's
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundations of salsa are unarguably in Cuba and the
capital of modern salsa is New York,'' wrote Sue Steward in her new
book, ``Musica!'' (Chronicle Books, 1999). The American Latin tinge
was born and raised in el Barrio, the South Bronx, Harlem and parts
of Brooklyn when Cuban, Dominican and Puerto Rican artists and
black jazz musicians mingled.
</P>
<P>
   The fusion began in the early 1920s when streams of immigrants
from Puerto Rico and a smaller group of immigrants from Cuba
arrived in Spanish Harlem, many toting instruments from their
homelands.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bauza, the Cuban clarinetist and trumpeter who played in the Cab
Calloway orchestra with Gillespie in the 1930s, pulled together the
Afro-Cuban and American jazz traditions in 1940, when he became
musical director for Machito's Afro-Cuban orchestra. The brassy
power of this new swing music, Latin jazz, created the first major
mambo craze in America.
</P>
<P>
   The new music gained its greatest popularity during the
``Palladium age'' in the 1950s, when people of all ethnic groups
began to frequent the Palladium and other clubs to see performances
by artists like Machito, Puente, Tito Rodriguez, Beny More and Joe
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But it took years for the sound to get its modern-day name. At
some point in the early 1970s (scholars argue over the date), Fania
Records, an influential New York company known as the ``Latin
Motown,'' began to market Puerto Rican music infused with other
cultural elements as salsa, the Spanish word for sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Rodriguez and Bauzo began collecting salsa's artifacts
more than 20 years ago. Bauzo, an avowed pack rat, said it was a
silent process at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would bring things in and he would store it,'' Bauzo said,
smiling at Rodriguez across a small rehearsal room on the
conservatory's fifth floor.
</P>
<P>
   Then the items started to pile up.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 5,000 Latin music LPs, many of which are
original pressings, including the entire personal collection of Al
Santiago, a renowned Latin record producer, 200 78s and 75 45s.
</P>
<P>
   The records are stacked haphazardly in a closet on the fifth
floor. Many have lost their sleeves or jackets and are marred by
scratches and dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Items from the personal collection of Puente, the ``King of
Mambo,'' are scattered about the conservatory in rehearsal rooms,
classrooms and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Raices has 200 videos, including a tape of the last concert
Puente and the vocalist Santos Colon performed together, and rare
copies of Machito's orchestra performing in the 1940s. The first
conga drum of the composer and vocalist Miguelito Valdez, who was
sometimes called `` Babalu,'' is kept in a former utility closet.
Other instruments, badly in need of repair, hang by strings from
classroom ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Cardboard boxes are overflowing with tapes of interviews with 35
prominent Latin musicians, like the pianist and band leader Eddie
Palmieri, the percussionist Ray Barreto and Bauza, who was credited
by the jazz historian John Storm Roberts with creating the New York
Latin sound.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 photographs are beginning to discolor and crack in
their glass frames in the hallway. The rest of 10,000-piece photo
archive, including shots of Latin musicians, orchestras and
ensembles from the 1920s to the present, is either in plastic wrap
in closets or crammed into stuffed file drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Black loose-leaf binders bulge with all but three issues of
Latin New York magazine, the primary chronicler of the scene from
1970 to 1985. This is a more comprehensive set than that owned by
the New York Public Library, according to an appraisal completed
last year by Archival Music Collections, a Brooklyn company.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Carp, an archivist and librarian at the Milken Archive
of American Jewish Music in Manhattan, said that Raices is probably
the only archive of its kind that is not privately owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other archive that deals with the performing arts
in the Afro-Caribbean field,'' he said, ``and unfortunately I can
say that with some certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that much of its existing collection is
collecting dust, Raices' keepers are still looking for more
treasures. They fear that at any moment someone in New York could
be tossing a potentially vital piece for the collection into the
trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much is still out there,'' Rodriguez said. ``More than with
any other type of music, so much has been lost. As a people, there
was never the notion to save anything about this culture. The music
was developed, used, given to the band, the band would rehearse it
and toss the sheet music. All the old arrangers never made copies,
the musicians certainly didn't make copies. Even when people did
keep it, the next generation wasn't interested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
