<SLUG> BC-KC-MODEMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CAPTURES DEMOCRATIC PRIMARY IN MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Reinforced by the backing of Missouri's
Democratic elite and talk of the seemingly inevitable demise of his
opponent, Vice President Al Gore captured the Missouri presidential
primary Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who was a star athlete
and scholar at high school in Crystal City, Mo., failed to turn his
fading native son status into victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that most people in the party really see Gore as the
person who can lead us to victory,'' said Jackson County Executive
Katheryn Shields, a supporter of the vice president. ``They think
he can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, Gore won 64 percent of the vote to 34 percent for
Bradley, a one-time professional basketball player, with 71 percent
of the precincts reporting. The precise delegate split won't be
determined until the party works through a series of meetings that
wind up in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   In Jackson, Clay, Platte and Cass counties, Gore was beating
Bradley by nearly 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that lacking significant differences on policy _
Bradley and Gore want tougher gun control, broader health-care
coverage and an end to racial profiling _ voters saw little reason
to bank on an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Missouri was an afterthought in the most decisive
day to date in the presidential campaign. Missouri promises just 92
Democratic delegates (including 17 chosen without regard to the
popular vote) while Ohio, New York and California held 170, 294 and
434, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a great incentive for people to turn out here,''
said Woody Overton, who ran then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton's
Missouri campaign in 1992. ``Missouri's just not a player on Super
Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley made a strategic move by challenging Gore in Iowa's
caucuses, where overcoming the might of organized labor and the
endorsement of Sen. Tom Harkin proved too difficult, Overton said.
And, he said, perceptions began to build that Bradley couldn't
overcome the political clout of the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then when he lost in the New Hampshire primary it only got
worse,'' Overton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley supporters meeting at Kansas City's Union Station as the
results trickled in took some solace in their candidate's forcing
issues such as racial justice into the campaign. They blamed the
primary losses on timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley was on fire a few months ago and he was the star of
the media,'' said Mary Ellen Miller, a former labor union
president. ``Then McCain got hot and the media ended up paying all
the attention to the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Reginald Bassa, a University of Missouri-Kansas City professor,
said he hopes Bradley stays in the race even if his chances of the
nomination have badly faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to raise the issues that determine what people talk
about in the campaign,'' Bassa said.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polling conducted by The Associated Press and Voter News
Service also found many independents forsaking the Democratic
primary to support McCain in the GOP contest.
</P>
<P>
   Of those voters in the Democratic primaries who chose Gore,
about eight in 10 approved of the job President Clinton has done.
But the Democratic voters were nearly evenly split on their opinion
of Clinton as a person.
</P>
<P>
   Gore dominated Bradley in virtually every subgroup. Bradley was
slightly favored by Missouri Democrats with post-graduate degrees,
but that group made up only about a quarter of all voters. Among
those with college degrees, the vote was about evenly split.
</P>
<P>
   Nine in 10 Democrats favor Gore over Bush, but only seven in 10
favor Gore over McCain. In fact, eight in 10 Democrats had an
unfavorable opinion of Bush. A majority of Democrats had a
favorable opinion of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   State Auditor and Gore backer Claire McCaskill said the results
in Missouri mimic the change in the national Democratic race. Where
polls late last year showed Gore in trouble, he has since rebounded
in popularity and a newly assertive and flexible campaign style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on,'' she said, ``before Gore started asserting himself
as a distinct personality, I would have said it would be a
barn-burner in Missouri.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
