<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0098 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BOB-DYLAN-MUSIC-ART-2     03-07 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOB-DYLAN-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGING DYLAN'S WORDS TO A DIFFERENT TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12)  
 (af)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bob Dylan was an acerbic young folk singer warning that the
times were a-changin', one change he probably did not envision was
that he would become a darling of the high-art world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet last fall, nearly 40 years after he made his first records,
Dylan was declared one of the greatest artists of the 20th century
by Andrew Motion, the British poet laureate. And now the composer
John Corigliano, commissioned to write a song cycle for the soprano
Sylvia McNair's Carnegie Hall recital on Wednesday evening, has
produced `` Tambourine Man: Seven Poems of Bob Dylan,'' a 35-minute
song cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano, a composer known for his accessibly melodic style,
has not merely spiffed up Dylan's music with a high-toned crossover
accompaniment. He insists, in fact, however implausibly, that he
has never heard Dylan's music. Rather, he selected a group of
lyrics from a collection of Dylan's work and treated them as he
would anyone else's poetry: he set them as he felt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I may have heard them in the background and not
focused on them,'' said Corigliano, 62, who was in his 20s in the
1960s when Dylan came to prominence and when Joan Baez, Peter, Paul
and Mary, the Byrds and Manfred Mann recorded hit versions of his
songs. ``That was when I was getting my skills in the contemporary
orchestral repertory. I was listening to late Stravinsky and
Penderecki. I knew show music. I knew Rodgers and Hammerstein. But
I didn't really listen to much rock music. I heard the Beatles, who
were fascinating because of what they were doing musically, and I'm
not saying I wouldn't have found Dylan fascinating had I turned my
attention to him. But I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Corigliano maintains that this gap in his musical experience
allowed him to encounter Dylan's lyrics uninfluenced by the
songwriter's own ideas. Once he decided to write the cycle, he went
out of his way to avoid Dylan's music. When McNair started to sing
``Blowin' in the Wind'' for him at one point, he made her stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dylan first heard about this project, his response was,
`Well, this is how they go; it's done,''' said Corigliano, who did
not speak to Dylan directly but negotiated for permission to use
the lyrics through Dylan's manager, Jeff Rosen. ``And the way I put
it was, `Wouldn't you be curious to see what someone with no
musical preconceptions, who comes from a completely different world
from yours, would do with poetry of yours that he finds moving and
beautiful?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not like what I've done. I'm not sure he will. But if
the poetry is good, it can stand it, just as a poem by Goethe can
stand different settings by Schumann, Brahms or Wolf. And I think
it (italics)is(end italics) good, otherwise I wouldn't have set
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why Dylan agreed to the project is unknown. He did not
respond to a question faxed through his publicity agent, and Rosen
refused to comment. But Corigliano and McNair jumped through a few
hoops to obtain Dylan's permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of collecting of credentials about a year
ago,'' McNair said recently. ``We had to list the Grammys we had
each won, and all the cities in the United States and Europe where
the songs would be performed. We had to prove we were the real
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A difference between Goethe and Dylan, of course, is that Goethe
wrote his poetry as poetry, with little concern about whether it
would be set to music. Dylan's songs were written as songs, and
their words are fitted closely to their melodies. Corigliano
rejects this distinction as too narrow.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, maybe Dylan bought Corigliano's Goethe argument. Or
maybe he was just curious.
</P>
<P>
   What he will hear, if he listens to the cycle, is the difference
between his directness and Corigliano's artfulness. In place of the
simple, flowing melody that listeners associate with ``Blowin' in
the Wind,'' for example, Corigliano has written a highly chromatic
setting, marked ``solemn'' in the score, and mostly in the lopsided
meter of five beats to the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clothes Line,'' originally in a blues form edged with Dylan's
wry humor, is now a complex structure in which the time signature
changes almost every bar, and the dialogue within the song has been
marked ``him'' and ``her'' and set in corresponding ranges.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is music for virtuoso performers. The vocal line has leaps of
a 12th (an octave and a half) in either direction. The pianist
(Martin Katz, at McNair's recital) has a tough job, too. He is
asked to create overtone effects to suggest bells in ``Chimes of
Freedom'' and to play a brisk accompaniment for `` Tambourine Man''
in which the right hand plays in the key of F sharp and the left in
the key of C.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the score, a few weeks ago,'' McNair said, ``I
thought, `Why me?' There are some very, very difficult things in
this song cycle. There are huge melodic leaps, which I always find
difficult. And keeping track of the meter changes _ there are
places where the meter changes 6, 8, 10 times per page. I've had to
learn to sing a tritone as easily as a whole step, and a minor
ninth as easily as an octave. But your ears get used to it, and it
becomes simpler after a while. And as a musician, I'm in awe of the
architecture of this piece.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carnegie Hall invited Corigliano to write a song cycle for
McNair, he did not have any text ideas in mind. In fact, when the
New York Philharmonic commissioned him around the same time to
write a work for the ``Messages for the Millennium'' series it was
to present last November, he wrote the wordless ``Vocalise,'' in
which McNair was also the soloist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange,'' he said. ``I'll be reading poems I like, and
one word or phrase will seem clumsy or unsettable, and will ruin it
for me. So I've not been able to set many poets.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's one request here was that Corigliano set works by an
American poet, and on a whim, he bought a book of Dylan's work, It
was a surprise to McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up with the idea of setting Dylan on his own,'' she
said. ``Originally, we were going to bat ideas about texts back and
forth, and we did that a bit. Then the next thing I knew, he had a
big book of Dylan's lyrics and was trying to get permission to set
some of them. I thought that was great. I'm realizing _ finally, in
my early 40s _ that Bob Dylan has been one of the great thinkers of
my lifetime. I read these poems over and over, and I am
fascinated.''
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano, who typically works out a structural plan for his
compositions before he begins writing the music, originally chose
more than a dozen lyrics, then narrowed them to seven that fell
into what he considered a logical order: `` Tambourine Man'' is a
prelude of sorts, and ``Clothes Line'' struck him as a charmingly
innocent foil for the more worldly wise ``Blowin' in the Wind.''
``Masters of War'' and ``All Along the Watchtower'' represent
political fury and an apocalyptic view of the future, after which
``Chimes of Freedom'' and ``Forever Young'' offer a brighter vision
and a closing benediction.
</P>
<P>
   Corigliano sent his final revisions to McNair only three weeks
ago, and he is about to take a break before transforming his String
Quartet into his Second Symphony, for the Boston Symphony
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, between this and `Vocalise,' I've spent the last
year and a half writing for Sylvia,'' he said. ``Sylvia, Sylvia,
Sylvia.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he should write her an encore. After all, there is an
excerpt from Shakespeare's ``Two Gentlemen of Verona,'' famous as a
Schubert song, ``An Silvia'' (``Who Is Sylvia?''), that is surely
due for a new setting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
