<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL GORE AS BRADLEY TAKES BEATING FROM COAST TO COAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore swept the Super Tuesday primaries,
crushing rival Bill Bradley from Maine to California and forcing
him to begin planning an exit from the race for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   If Bradley withdraws, a prospect his aides did not dismiss late
Tuesday, Gore will emerge as the first candidate since World War II
to win a contested Democratic presidential nomination without
losing a single state primary.
</P>
<P>
   Turning his attention late Tuesday to the November general
election, Gore began trying to unify the Democratic Party,
appealing to liberals and independents who supported Bradley's
insurgent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody who has heard Bill Bradley throughout his
campaign has come away from the experience moved and touched by the
strength of his commitment to healing the divisions in our
country,'' said the vice president, who vigorously attacked the
former New Jersey senator in campaign debates and television
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to reach out to all who believe that this is a time for
great progress, for great reforms, for an America of tolerance and
high ideals,'' Gore said at a victory rally in Nashville, Tenn.
``We need to build on our record of prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the polls closed in the East, Bradley aides put his
campaign on hold and said the former New Jersey senator would
announce Thursday whether his campaign will continue.
</P>
<P>
   When he appeared at New York's Sheraton Hotel to concede the
Super Tuesday primaries, Bradley all but conceded that he would
pull out and only spoke of his campaign in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe history will write that we tried to change politics,
to restore trust and to defeat the politics of expediency,''
Bradley said. ``We shaped the national debate. We brought core
Democratic issues to the fore. We gave voice to the voiceless.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has yet to win a primary contest against Gore, set
Tuesday as the day he would have to break through and win in at
least two states. Short of that, he said, continuing to challenge
Gore would be futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be dropping out this evening,'' said Eric Hauser,
Bradley's campaign spokesman. He added that the campaign early
Wednesday ``will put out a paper and announcement explaining what
we plan to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst news of the evening for Bradley was his weak
showing in New York, where he spent five of the past six days
campaigning. Exit polls showed Bradley, a former player on the New
York Knicks basketball team and a former senator from neighboring
New Jersey, trailing Gore 2-1 in the Empire State.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns also showed Gore winning by wide margins in
Georgia, Vermont, Ohio, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Maryland,
Maine, Rhode Island and Missouri, the state where Bradley was born
and raised.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls not only show Gore overwhelming Bradley in other
Super Tuesday states, the surveys by Voter News Service found the
vice president to be the favorite of key Democratic constituencies;
black and Hispanic voters by an 8-1 margin, labor households by
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found the vice president, who was backed by most
organized labor groups, running stronger than Bradley among the
party's liberals and conservatives. Among women, Gore was backed in
some states by more than 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   In more good news for the vice president, a Wall Street Journal
poll showed him tied with likely Republican nominee George W. Bush
with 46 percent apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore could effectively clinch the Democratic nomination
if Bradley withdraws, the vice president will be short of the 2,170
delegates needed to officially claim the party's nomination until
at least next Tuesday, by which time another 13 states, including
Texas, will have held presidential primaries or caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday's primaries, Gore had won 1,005 delegates to
280 for Bradley, according to unofficial counts. At stake Tuesday
were 1,315 delegates, which will be awarded based on the
candidates' proportional share of the states' primary results.
</P>
<P>
   In the general election, Gore will face a Republican opponent
scarred by the GOP's roughest primary campaign since 1976, when
President Ford fended off conservative insurgent Ronald Reagan in a
fight that went all the way to the party's nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Tuesday's cross-country primaries, Gore had been
looking beyond the primaries, no longer criticizing Bradley,
instead beginning his attacks on Bush and Arizona Sen. John McCain,
the only other Republican with a chance for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   With Bradley's challenge from the political left unable to shake
Gore's image as a centrist, he is expected to have a slight edge on
issues important to voters. On subjects such as gun control, health
care or Social Security, polls show that a majority of Americans
favor the approach taken by Gore and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore comes out of these primaries as very much someone who
represents the mainstream values of the American people,'' said Bob
Schrum, a consultant with the Gore campaign. ``By contrast, Bush is
a different candidate than he was six or seven months ago. He had
to move to the right if he was to get the Republican nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   As he turns toward the fall campaign, Gore is expected to wrap
himself in the mantel of a de facto incumbent, which carries with
it two key advantages _ a world at peace and a country with
unparalleled economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore carries several weaknesses into the
general election, even without a foreign-policy crisis or an
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are expected to remind voters of his involvement in
the Democratic Party's 1996 fund-raising scandals. One of his
allies, Maria Hsia, last week was convicted for 1996 campaign
finance violations.
</P>
<P>
   Voters can expect to see Republican-financed campaign ads
showing Gore enthusiastically praising President Clinton on the day
he was impeached.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Alan Bernstein and Bennett Roth contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
