<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000307.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0101 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-ASSESS-2NDLD-WRIT     03-07 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-ASSESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 VICTORS, REDEFINED IN DIFFERENT WAYS  
 (EDS: TIGHTENS LEAD, MOVING SOME ANALYTICAL MATTER TO 2ND GRAF; 8TH
AND 9TH GRAFS INJECTS ASSESSMENT OF MCCAIN'S POSITION)
</HEADLINE>
   (jt) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a year of remarkable political tumult, both parties ended
up back where they began Tuesday, with the presumptive presidential
nominees they had expected all along.
</P>
<P>
   But there were important differences. Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, most politicians believe, emerged from the campaign a weaker
candidate than he began it, scuffed by the attacks of his rival,
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, and with a party dangerously split
between conservatives and moderates. He has yet to prove he can
appeal to voters in the vital electoral center.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, on the other hand, emerged as a
stronger, more vivid campaigner, and stands at the head of a much
more united party.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Bush assured himself of the nomination
by defeating or contending closely with McCain everywhere except
New England, a region as out of step with the rest of the country
in 2000 as the South was a half-century ago. And even in New
England, McCain had to yield Maine, where the Bush family has spent
summers for generations.
</P>
<P>
   After the closest approximation the nation has ever had to a
national primary, Gore and Bush both made a victory speeches
looking to the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   What came before Tuesday was mere skirmishing. If not quite
McCain's Appomattox, the Super Tuesday voting seemed certain to
prove his Gettysburg. The extremely wide lead seized by Bush in the
delegate count gave him a commanding position at the campaign's
most significant moment.
</P>
<P>
   Now the governor can look forward with confidence to a day, next
Tuesday, when his own state as well as Florida, where his brother,
Jeb, is the governor, choose their delegates. As they were in
Tuesday's Republican primary and caucus voting in 13 states, the
numbers at stake will be significant: Texas is the nation's
second-largest state and Florida is the fourth-largest.
</P>
<P>
   As for McCain, he headed for his retreat at Sedona, north of
Phoenix, with the weight of self-interest seemingly favoring a
withdrawal. If he stays in the race for another week, facing long
odds, he might do little except win a reputation as a
party-wrecker. If he pulls out, he could accelerate the healing
process and enhance his chances of trying again four years from now
if Bush were defeated. McCain will be 68 in August, 2004.
</P>
<P>
   One of McCain's few backers in Congress, Sen. Chuck Hagel of
Nebraska, said McCain had failed to get the ``rocket boost'' he
needed and would make a decision in a day or two on what to do
next. Hagel said his colleague ``won't put the party or country
through any high drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush began the campaign as a heavy favorite. But he suffered
serious setbacks in New Hampshire and Michigan as McCain, running
as an outsider, mounted an unexpectedly potent insurgency, and he
veered sharply to the right in South Carolina in a successful
effort to head off the Arizonan.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Bush, who had originally presented himself as a
candidate who could appeal to all voters, regardless of party,
found himself redefined as a Republican partisan with little
backing among Democrats, independents and moderate Republicans,
without some of whom he would have scant chance in November.
</P>
<P>
   Again in Tuesday's balloting, Republicans voted heavily for Bush
while Democrats and independents voted for McCain. The pattern was
much the same as in each test since New Hampshire: who won in many
states depended heavily on the proportion of independents and
Democrats in the electorate. The more there were (as in
Massachusetts) the better McCain did; the fewer there were (as in
Ohio), the worse.
</P>
<P>
   If, as now seems highly likely, he moves on to win the
nomination, Bush will have to find a way to remedy this problem. He
has tried hard since South Carolina, without success; his senior
advisers are already deep in discussions about fresh notions of how
to renew his appeal to voters in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who also began as a seeming shoo-in for the Democratic
presidential nomination, survived a patch so shaky that even some
of his staff members made fun of him. He moved his headquarters
from Washington to Nashville, to more derisive catcalls, and pulled
his ragged operation together with considerable skill.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he utterly humiliated his rival, former Senator Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, who had looked for a time last year like the
freshest of political faces. Bradley lost on the Atlantic Coast, on
the Pacific coast and in between _ even in Missouri, where he grew
up, and in New York, where he won fame and fortune playing
basketball for the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bravura performance by the vice president, if no longer
surprising in view of the near-collapse of Bradley's campaign in
recent weeks, and it positioned him well for the battle against the
eventual Republican nominee this fall, although perhaps situated
somewhat farther to the left on some key issues than he had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Even on health care, which Bradley had made his signature issue,
most voters said they thought Gore had outlined a batter plan.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, the vice president praised Bradley in a bid
to create greater party unity. After praising the former senator's
``commitment to healing the divisions in our country, especially
divisions based on race,'' Gore said in Nashville: ``He believes in
this healing, heart and soul. I share his commitment to it. I have
learned from his passion for it. Tonight I salute Senator Bill
Bradley and Ernestine Bradley, his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made a similar appeal.
</P>
<P>
   One hopeful sign for Bush came among Catholics. McCain sharply
criticized leaders of the Republican right in a speech in Virginia
late last month, hoping, according to aides, that Catholics and
others in northern states who resent Christian conservatives would
rally to him. But according to exit polls in Missouri and Ohio, in
each of which Catholics accounted for a quarter of the electorate,
Bush received half their votes or more.
</P>
<P>
   Gore kept intact a political pattern that went largely unnoticed
in the weeks when his reputation waned, then waxed once more. No
sitting vice president since World War II who sought the
presidential nomination has failed to gain it, except for Alben W.
Barkley of Kentucky, Harry Truman's number two, who attracted
little support in 1952, largely, it was said, because of his age.
He was then 74.
</P>
<P>
   Although he will no doubt be considered the favorite at first,
especially considering the blood-letting that has taken place in
the Republican primaries for the third campaign running, Gore faces
problems of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Like his mentor, President Clinton, he has put tremendous effort
into courting the voters of California, and he has built a strong
following there. But in Tuesday's so-called beauty contest in the
Golden State, there was a small note of warning.
</P>
<P>
   He and Bradley together polled considerably fewer votes than
Bush and McCain together. That may have resulted in part from the
fact that the Republican campaign was the more gripping one, but it
also suggested that Gore has work to do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
