<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-07 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0103 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ARTISTS-TIME-BOXES-AR     03-07 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISTS-TIME-BOXES-ART-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLOWING A LONG-INTERRED PAST OUT OF ITS CONTAINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12)  
 (af)  
 Ann Wilson Lloyd's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the British artist Cornelia Parker.  
 By ANN WILSON LLOYD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ In a stage-worthy scene, the artists Richard
Artschwager, Daniel Buren, Sol LeWitt and Robert Ryman met here
recently to reveal the secret contents of four steel boxes they
individually filled and sealed 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   These artists' time boxes, and the dramatic opening held at the
Rose Art Museum at Brandeis University on Feb. 24, are both part of
a quarter-century-long collaborative project initiated by another
artist, Stephen Antonakos. The boxes, their contents and a neon
installation by Antonakos will be displayed here through Sunday as
part of the museum's millennium celebration.
</P>
<P>
   None of this started out nearly as portentous as it turned out
to be. Antonakos was not thinking about the millennium in the early
'70s, nor did he foresee that museums everywhere would be looking
for special programs to mark the momentous turn of the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five years just seemed like a nice round number, and
2000, well, that was too far away to ever come,'' he says. But when
Joseph Ketner, the director of the Brandeis museum, heard about the
boxes from Antonakos, he thought opening them would be a perfect
salute to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The time-box project began when Antonakos, who is perhaps best
known for his meditative architectural spaces and neon
installations, began several series of ``package'' projects in
1971, all of them involving other people. On a fellowship in
Fresno, Calif., and feeling lonely for his New York City circle of
friends, he wrote to them requesting that they send him something,
anything, in a package.
</P>
<P>
   He received 87 parcels. A year later, he displayed them _ large,
small, variously shaped, but all still unwrapped _ in the gallery
at Fresno State College, where he was in residence.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he admits he never intended to open the packages, and he
still does not, even though this frustrated many of the senders.
The parcels, too, are on display at the Rose, looking a bit
battered but still very tantalizing: an array of brown paper
packages tied up with string, tape, stickers, etc., bearing fading
return names like Art Works on T.V./Don Judd, Richard Tuttle, Rudy
Burckhardt, Dorothea Rockburne, Hans Haacke and Ray Johnson.
There's even one from Christo.
</P>
<P>
   Once Antonakos realized the emotional response a simple unopened
package could provoke, he also realized that their small,
mysterious, dark interiors were the inverse of the light-filled
spaces he created in his larger works. He decided to follow the
project with a return mailing, wrapping and sending his own
packages and pledging the recipients to honor his instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Some packages were marked to be opened on certain dates (which
have come and gone in some cases), others were to be opened upon
the death of Antonakos, still others were never to be opened.
</P>
<P>
   Antonakos says some things he sent were sketch books, or
collages, usually enclosed with a copy of that day's New York
Times. The contents are less important to him, though, than the
tension of waiting _ a mixture of anticipation and potential
disappointment _ along with the implied presence of the sender that
an unopened package can quietly emit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have displayed them for years on their wall,'' he
says. ``They tell me of their anxiety as the opening time comes.
Will they like what's inside? Will they like the way it looked
unopened better?''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a way to cap his package projects, Antonakos found
four simple steel boxes, each about the size of an average
television, and had an idea. He approached four close friends,
Artschwager, Buren, LeWitt and Ryman, with a proposition: a
contractual agreement whereby each would fill a box, seal it, swear
to secrecy regarding its contents and agree to open it with him in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Artschwager said that when he received Antonakos' 1974 proposal,
he was inclined to think it might be tempting providence. ``I was
sure I'd never live to see its conclusion, that it would be a total
waste of time,'' he says. Did he remember what he had put inside?
``No. I forgot about the box entirely. At my age, I've dropped a
few things along the way _'' a wry smile ``_ it's the best kind of
security.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The use of time as an artistic dimension sprang from the late
'60s and early '70s when conceptualism was fresh. ``Time was one of
the many conceptual toys that came to the surface when Stephen,
some of the other people here and I were kicking around back
then,'' Artschwager said. ``It was kind of a cooperative venture.''
</P>
<P>
   Time has played its own tricks on the artists. Just before the
opening, LeWitt also said that he never thought he would see this
day, and that he had forgotten what he put in his box. ``I hope
it's not embarrassing,'' he said. ``Twenty-five years was too long
to imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the French artist Daniel Buren, who flew in
from Paris to attend, said: ``I have a fresh memory of filling the
box. I am excited about it. I even wrote a letter in mid-1999 to
ask: `What's happening with our box? We are close to the
anniversary date.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even though in 1974 Antonakos had envisioned the opening to be a
private gathering of his friends, he was quite happy to share it
with a sold-out crowd of more than 250 people who came to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Following a piano concert by the composer Terry Riley, Ryman's
box was opened first. He was the only one to alter the box itself,
crisscrossing it with now-yellow masking tape that recalled the
texture of his variously white canvases. He explained: ``I wanted
there to be something on the outside as well as the inside, so the
box itself would be seen as a thing _ and also to keep anyone from
peeking.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside his box was a square wrapped in brown linen; inside the
linen was a small, framed glass palette, dominated by a swirl of
white paint. It was signed by Ryman and dated 1961.
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt's box was next. At first its white-painted interior
looked empty; then a tiny, one-inch white cube was discovered.
``The cube opens,'' said Antonakos, ``and there's a note inside the
lid.'' LeWitt asked what it said. `` `A line, not straight, corner
to corner, Sol LeWitt, Oct. 14, 1974,''' Antonakos read aloud.
``This must be Sol's smallest work.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside Artschwager's box lay a nest of four skillfully made
plywood boxes, the lids of which required a rather tedious
unscrewing to reveal, finally, that the last and smallest box
contained nothing. These foreshadowed, perhaps, the artist's recent
series of packing-crate sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   It was Buren's box, though, that held the most poignant
surprise. In keeping with the spirit of the project, he had given
his box to yet another artist, Chris D'Arcangelo, who had been
Antonakos' studio assistant at the time.
</P>
<P>
   D'Arcangelo, who died in the early 1980s, had, in turn, paid
homage to Buren by painting the inside of the box with two wide red
stripes (narrower, though, than Buren's standard stripe of 8.7
centimeters or 3.4 inches). A letter inside the box from Buren,
dated June 1975, explained this exchange, and ended with this
salutation from the past: ``Best regards to you from New York and
... 25 years ago!''
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing that the contents of the boxes turned out to be
consistent with the work these four artists have gone on to
produce, Ketner said he had come to realize the contents were less
important than the time and space between the creation of the boxes
and the opening. ``It was the mystery, the wonder, the
anticipation, the waiting for discovery and all that preceded that
was the crux of the project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Antonakos was just relieved that the waiting was over. ``It was
a tremendous responsibility, constantly wondering how this project
would end,'' he said. ``When you're young you only think about how
things will begin; you never think about how they will end. I'm
very happy, very gratified this has ended so beautifully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
