 McCAIN TOPS BUSH IN 4 OF 5 NEW ENGLAND STATES  
 (Eds.: Subs to include unofficial results, new quotes, other
revisions throughout)  
 (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ While the news looked grim Tuesday night for
Sen. John McCain in much of the country, he defeated Gov. George W.
Bush in 4 of 5 New England states holding primaries. The exception
was Maine, where the Bush family owns a summer home.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won the Republican primaries in Massachusetts, Vermont,
Connecticut and Rhode Island, picking up a total of 88 delegates in
the region, according to unofficial results. Bush won Maine's 14
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   A strong showing in New England was crucial to McCain's hopes of
keeping his presidential hopes alive, especially in light of his
projected losses in most states holding primaries Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But despite these victories, Tuesday's primaries also showed
McCain's enduring inability to capture votes from registered
Republicans. In three of his four victories _ in Massachusetts,
Vermont and Rhode Island _ he won big, by margins of 25 points or
more. But exit polls showed two-thirds of the voters who cast
ballots for McCain in Massachusetts, for example, were Democrats or
independents who changed registration to support him. Democrats and
independents also carried McCain in Vermont, where he captured just
45 percent of registered Republicans, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's narrow victory in Connecticut, home to a historically
moderate and independent electorate, came despite significant
efforts by Gov. John G. Rowland and every Republican lawmaker in
the state on behalf of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very intelligent, capable man. He has our interests at
heart,'' said Hope Whitehead, 78, a retired history teacher, after
she voted for McCain at the Davis Middle School in Guilford. ``He
wants to make big changes in the government, which is why the
Republican Party is not behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other McCain voters said they voted for him as a form of
protesting against Bush. ``I don't trust Bush, I don't like the way
he looks,'' said Fran, an Avon resident who did not want her last
name published. ``He strikes me as very arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he was disappointed in Bush's showing, but he
shrugged off its significance in the national campaign. ``I don't
mind losing a battle if we win the war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was able to do well in Connecticut by appealing to
voters' desire for political reform and on the strength of his
image as a maverick. In recent weeks, thousands of Connecticut
voters throughout the state switched their party affiliations to
register as Republicans in time for Tuesday's primary. Exit polling
also suggested McCain won a majority of the state's large number of
Catholic voters.
</P>
<P>
   They also showed he drew much support in both Connecticut and
Massachusetts from former Democrats and Liberals who recently
switched to the Republican Party. McCain received less than half of
the votes from registered Republicans in both states.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts said the turnout of
non-Republicans for McCain bodes well for Bush in the fall. ``I
think it shows dissatisfaction with the Democratic candidates,''
said Cellucci, who noted that the presidential primary showed the
largest turnout in state history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
