<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CARBONNEAU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' GUY CARBONNEAU OUT 2-3 WEEKS WITH WRIST FRACTURE 
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Stars center Guy Carbonneau has scored only two goals
since Jan. 20, but he has been indirectly responsible for many,
many more.
</P>
<P>
   Who do you think freed up Mike Modano to score or assist on 30
goals in the past 20 games?
</P>
<P>
   ``With the injuries we had this year, it was evident that we
needed me playing against the best lines and leave Mo a little bit
more free to do whatever he wants,'' Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano had almost all the responsibility for checking the other
teams' top lines until Carbonneau volunteered. Now, someone else
will have to. At least, for two to three weeks. Carbonneau is
expected to miss at least that long with a hairline fracture of his
right wrist suffered Sunday against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The injury couldn't have been worse for the Stars if it had been
to Modano himself.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said players such as Carbonneau, who
play ``16-17 minutes a night and it's all five on five and killing
penalties...those players, I find as a coach, are more difficult to
replace than sometimes your skill players.''
</P>
<P>
   The task of trying do so will now fall to Aaron Gavey, Kirk
Muller and 20-year-old Roman Lyashenko, who Hitchcock said is being
groomed to one day take over the shutdown role.
</P>
<P>
   A trade for another defensive forward seems unlikely. The Stars
need scoring, and general manager Bob Gainey said Carbonneau's
injury wouldn't make the Stars rethink their strategy as the March
14 trading deadline approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our info on Guy Carbonneau's injury is clearly that
he'll be back long before the playoffs and be ready to play,''
Gainey said. ``I think the number-one need for our team is that we
get healthy before the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau said he'll be in a cast for two to three weeks at
which point X-rays will be taken to make sure the fracture is
healing properly. He'll then be suited for a playing cast that
he'll have to wear the rest of the season. He will likely need
surgery in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to hurt, especially this time of year,'' Modano
said. ``This is the time of year Carbo thrives on as a player. This
is the part of the year that runs through his veins probably more
than any player on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau is one of ``those players.'' At 39, he's the oldest
player in the NHL, but his stats don't show it. He has played in 62
of the Stars' 66 games this season, doing all of the little things
and a few of the big ones that win hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest one probably is assuming the responsibility that
once fell to Modano of not allowing the Joe Sakics, Steve Yzermans
and Eric Lindros of the NHL to score. He has been good, too,
posting a plus-9 rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing against the best lines all my career, but I
didn't have to score 30, 40, 50 goals,'' Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano did, which is why Carbonneau said he talked to Hitchcock
earlier this season. The Stars weren't scoring. He said he'd handle
the shutdown role. Modano would have more time to score.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 42 games, Modano had 16 goals and 19 assists. In
the past 20, he has 15 goals and 15 assists. Only Calgary's Jarome
Iginla has more points in the recent span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it's a lot easier out there than the first three or
four months were,'' Modano said. ``It was a real struggle mentally
and physically to play and to get motivated and get into the flow
of the year. But of late, I haven't found it very difficult to
play. Mentally and physically, this is the best I've felt in a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Carbonneau with a big, fat assist on that, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars desperately needed scoring. All he did was free up
their best scorer to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I want it,'' Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Two to three more weeks, and the Stars will be more than happy
to give it back to him.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
