</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-BUSH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRONOUNCED MOVE FROM RIGHT TO CENTER ACCOMPANIES BUSH'S PRIMARY
SUCCESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: This is an added starter on Page One) 
 (ART ADV: NYT Photo (NU)48 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES and B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nearly five weeks ago, when Gov. George W.
Bush's grip on the Republican presidential nomination looked
tenuous, he indulged in the most controversial symbolism of his
campaign and appeared at Bob Jones University, a conservative
Christian school in South Carolina that still barred interracial
dating.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night, as the Texas governor basked in several key
victories that put him in what he clearly felt was a very different
position, he turned that symbolism inside out. He chose to be
introduced at his celebration here by a black female educator from
Houston, Phyllis C. Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   More than any exit poll or tally of delegates, that change in
signals illustrated what really happened to Bush and his advisers
Tuesday. They pivoted from flattering the right to courting the
center, from nurturing their most reliable sources of electoral
strength to cultivating new supporters, from traditional tactics to
bolder plans.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they began their general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That shift was also reflected in Bush's speech. It not only
anticipated the nomination, relegating the Republican primary
contest to the past tense, but also sought to woo the independent
and moderate voters who liked Sen. John McCain and to allay any
concerns or speculation that McCain might have been a stronger foe
for Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans must expand our prosperity, and extend it to those
who still struggle,'' Bush said, sounding the centrist theme of
compassionate conservatism that was sometimes lost in his bitter
struggle against McCain. ``We must be a strong nation _ that also
cares for the weak and forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a party of principle,'' Bush added. ``We must also be a
party of inclusion a party with a generous heart and an open
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also signaled that he was ready to take on Gore _ and that
he had already hammered out many of the battle lines for that
engagement _ by repeatedly mentioning the vice president and
unreservedly attacking the record of ``the Clinton-Gore
administration.'' That phrase, used like a mantra, tethered Gore
tightly to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is celebrating victory as well,'' Bush told hundreds
of cheering supporters at the Four Seasons hotel here. ``I
congratulate him and look forward to the contest. He is the
candidate of the status quo in Washington, D.C., and he has a tough
case to make in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will remind Al Gore that Americans do not want a White House
where there is no controlling legal authority,'' Bush said, showing
at least one of the cards he planned to play. ``I will repair the
broken bonds of trust between Americans and their government.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, his advisers and his supporters, Tuesday night was
more than a sweet vindication of their tireless predictions that
the governor would win the nomination decisively and early, despite
the surprising potency of McCain's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chance to turn their attention in the direction they
had always wanted to: toward November and Gore. Although there had
been something akin to a superstition in the Bush campaign about
talking too extensively about the general election before the
primaries were won, aides were suddenly willing to talk Tuesday
about the need to widen the campaign's circle of advisers, bring
new allies onboard, plot the details of the convention in August
and coordinate efforts more closely with the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   They re-evaluated Bush's upcoming travel schedule in the context
of what would be most helpful for the general election, not what
was necessary to secure the nomination, and the details of that
schedule betrayed no sense of urgency. Bush planned to spend most
of the next four days at home in Austin, off the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials said that their firmer purchase on the
nomination would allow them, between now and the end of April, to
begin folding more fundraisers into Bush's plans. One aide said
that the campaign would raise another $5 million to $10 million
between now and the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   But, most important of all, Tuesday's results meant that Bush
could focus on the themes he would need and the weapons he would
use to prevail in November, campaign officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In various television interviews Tuesday night, Bush
acknowledged that reaching out to the independents and the
moderates who were courted so successfully by McCain was perhaps
the Bush campaign's first and most important order of business. Ms.
Hunter's presence was a clear indication of that.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush simultaneously sought to turn questions about any
repositioning he would have to do into critiques of Gore, and those
critiques demonstrated how Bush planned to go after Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change my message,'' he said at a midday news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some candidates, maybe Al Gore, feels like that's the
way to campaign _ you've got to keep changing message or changing
headquarters or changing suits.''
</P>
<P>
   In his victory speech, Bush identified several issues that he
clearly felt he could address more forcefully and persuasively than
Gore, including strengthening the military, cutting taxes and
improving public education.
</P>
<P>
   But even more obvious, in both Bush's speech and his earlier
news conference, was that he planned to put character and ethics at
the forefront of his general election campaign, to tie Gore to the
moral lapses of Clinton and to invoke the vice president's widely
criticized actions in the course of raising funds for Clinton's
1996 reelection campaign. Bush's senior advisers confirmed this
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years is a long time, and eight years is enough,'' Bush
told supporters, who frequently broke into the chant, ``No more
Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready, and I believe our country is ready, to return
exiled honor to the White House,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
