<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROSCOST HAS TOBACCO FUND PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Speaker of the House Jeff Groscost on Tuesday, March 7,
unveiled a plan to spend Arizona's $3.1 billion tobacco settlement
on schools, teacher pay raises and fighting disease.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by House leadership, the plan would pay for a $1,000
salary boost for teachers, raise $600 million to help fix
dilapidated schools through the Students FIRST program and set up
programs to help people quit smoking and fight cancer and
Alzheimer's disease. It would also repay the state's ``rainy day''
fund for construction of the state hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The plan seems to contradict Gov. Jane Hull's wishes to focus
the tobacco money on health care, specifically mental health,
helping the uninsured, and children's health programs. Hull also is
exploring a plan to sell the settlement risk in exchange for $1
billion up front. The money would be invested and interest would be
used to solve health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Brenda Burns also favors putting the money into
a trust, but has also added education to health care as a major
issue to address.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Groscost said that his plan could
accommodate Hull's wishes, and that he is willing to explore
securing a portion of the bond money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a conflicting proposal,'' Groscost spokesman Paul
Senseman said Tuesday, March 7. ``We still believe we can pull
together a consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is working on a tobacco plan to counteract two
initiatives on the Nov. 7 ballot that would restrict the money to
only health-related programs such as insurance for the working poor
and preventative care for children. &QL; 
 &QL; 
House Republicans on Tuesday unveiled a plan to spend Arizona's
$3.1 billion tobacco settlement on schools, teacher pay raises and
fighting disease.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
