<HEADER>
A0117 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-ROBERT-TROUT-ART-2     03-07 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ROBERT-TROUT-ART-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEL ANCHORMAN CAN'T ESCAPE THE MICROPHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 12)  
 (af)  
 By CHARLES STRUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Trout came out of a cold drizzle and into a
nearly deserted midtown restaurant the other day, ordered a bowl of
risotto and a glass of red wine and began to chat amiably, almost
shyly, about broadcasting, cab driving and Warren G. Harding. Trout
is 90, and while osteoporosis has bent his back and skewed his
sense of balance, he is still the very model of the suave, modern
anchorman. And still very much in demand.
</P>
<P>
   After living in Madrid for two decades, he ``pitched up in New
York about four years ago,'' said his friend Peter Jennings, the
ABC newsman, and took a small apartment in the West 50s. The move
came after the death of his wife, Kit, by all accounts a vivacious
woman whom he adored during a marriage of almost 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   And while he maintains the Madrid residence _ he plans to go
back next month _ he was coy about why he would be hanging around
during a New York winter when Spain beckoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm crazy,'' he said, suppressing a smile.
</P>
<P>
   He was indisputably dapper in a three-piece herringbone suit
from his London tailor, Anderson &AMP; Sheppard. (``Ed Murrow took me
there when I got to London during the war.'') The thin, trademark
mustache he grew in the 1930s to make himself look older is still
there, though gray. But the voice _ the rolling baritone, with its
sense of droll self-deprecation _ is undiminished in strength or
clarity.
</P>
<P>
   It is vintage Trout, worrying to this day that he could be
accused of mumbling. In the hands of a less elegant broadcaster,
such drollness can be a fumbled card trick. Conveyed by the
famously unassuming Trout, it is a moment of intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   As millennium fervor ignited an interest in the past, Trout
returned more and more to the microphone he never really abandoned,
in a career that appears to have no retirement clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure whether I'm retired or not,'' he said. ``I guess
I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he and his reporting have been rediscovered through the
abiding interest of the news business in marking anniversaries:
coronations (King George VI, 1937), presidential nominating
conventions (all but one between 1936 and 1996) and wars. As
Jennings said: ``I can never overcome my sense of awe that he has
seen nearly a third of America's political history.''
</P>
<P>
   On the air again, notably on public radio, Trout is still
reporting the news _ not the breaking news of the day but extended,
scripted commentary on the news that broke during his watch decades
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Typical is a recent essay for National Public Radio's ``All
Things Considered,'' in which Trout, who has rarely been at a loss
for words, wryly acknowledged that sometimes he did not have all
the answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could reach into an archive somewhere and retrieve
the dramatic moment when I interrupted an evening's entertainment
to announce the onset of McCarthyism,'' he intoned in a preamble on
the red scare. ``It would seem that a moment of such consequence
should exist. But I'm afraid that those of us who pursued
politicians with intent to commit journalism missed this story
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching back a half century to Wheeling, W.Va., and to a
largely unnoticed speech, Trout tried to account for the rise of an
obscure first-term senator named Joseph R. McCarthy. It was in
Wheeling, in February 1950, that McCarthy sounded one of his
earliest unsubstantiated alarms about a government teeming with
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw a word of copy about McCarthy or Wheeling that
week, nor would I have expected to,'' Trout said. ``McCarthy's name
rarely made news.''
</P>
<P>
   Trout is perhaps best known for his many years at CBS, which in
the 1930s and '40s fielded the unparalleled team of broadcast
reporters that admirers would come to call Murrow's Boys, for the
network's chief European correspondent, Edward R. Murrow.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The names are still familiar to generations of listeners and
viewers: William L. Shirer, Eric Sevareid, Howard K. Smith, Richard
C. Hottelet, Winston Burdette, Charles Collingwood and Robert
Trout.
</P>
<P>
   Murrow and, later, Walter Cronkite would become synonymous with
the CBS brand, but Trout, a master of extemporaneous commentary, is
often acknowledged as having paved the way. Most broadcasters
credit him with creating and perfecting the role of anchorman at a
time when CBS itself was inventing the business of broadcast news.
</P>
<P>
   The moment came in March 1938, when the network produced its
first ``World News Roundup,'' with Trout in New York introducing
live reports from Paris, Rome, Berlin and Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Trout moved briefly to NBC in the late '40s, then returned to
CBS. He began reporting for ABC in the late 1970s. In the last
decade, he has collaborated frequently with John McDonough, a
writer, independent producer and news archivist in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had acquired a set of transcription recordings covering the
first 36 hours of broadcast D-Day coverage, the first eight or nine
hours of which were anchored by Bob,'' McDonough said. ``It was a
masterpiece of broadcasting, utterly contemporary in style and
tone, and the first time an emergency had taken over the air
totally.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, McDonough produced four hourlong documentaries, ``When
Conventions Were Conventions, With Robert Trout,'' for Public Radio
International. The programs caught the attention of another Trout
admirer, Art Silverman, senior producer of ``All Things
Considered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard them at home,'' Silverman said, ``and I got in touch
with John and said, `Is there anything you can do for
(italics)us(end italics?'''
</P>
<P>
   As a political reporter, Trout had a distinct home-field
advantage, having grown up in Washington, where his father owned a
shoe store. His political indoctrination came unusually early. At
age 7, he attended Woodrow Wilson's second inaugural in March 1917.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the attraction for me was the parade,'' he said.
``The big feature was always the remnants of the Civil War. They
had a float with the Blue and Gray shaking hands. Everything was
horse-drawn.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1920s, Trout had graduated from Central High School
(``I got G's, for good. I was lazy''), worked one summer on the
liner President Roosevelt between New York and Bremerhaven and
earned rent money by driving a cab and jerking soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this vague, romantic idea that I wanted to be a
writer,'' he said. ``I thought getting experience was the way to
get material.'' Which is why Trout answered an ad in The Washington
Evening Star for a piano player (although he could not play) at
WJSV, a small radio station just across the Potomac in Alexandria,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   After a few false starts and more taxi driving, Trout went on
the air, officially, in October 1931. The following year, the
fledgling Columbia Broadcasting System, in search of a Washington
license, acquired WJSV _ and Robert Trout.
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, he and Franklin D. Roosevelt attended their first
presidential inaugural. FDR sat in an open car heading toward the
Capitol; Trout stood on the roof of the Willard Hotel describing
the pageantry.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the assignment, Trout was reminded of an earlier
inaugural, that of Warren G. Harding, whose presidency ended with
his sudden death in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Harding was the first president who went to the
Capitol for the ceremony in an automobile,'' he said. ``From then
on, it was all downhill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
